<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BRAVES-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 0609 &HT;    Braves score 6 in bottom of 9th to beat Red Sox
 &HT;    By I.J. Rosenberg
 &HT;    c. 1998 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA _ Even Leo Mazzone, a man never at a loss for words,
couldn't explain this one. The Braves pitching coach, with a
toothbrush jammed between his teeth, just shrugged and smiled.
</P>
<P>
   Oh, what a ninth inning Monday night at Turner Field.
</P>
<P>
   For a team that has written a book this decade on comebacks,
there have been few better than this one, the Braves scoring six
runs in the final frame to knock out the Boston Red Sox 7-6 before
44,018.
</P>
<P>
   And the Braves needed just one out to do their damage, most of
it coming against who has been the hottest reliever in baseball and
against a team that has been one of the American League's best. The
winning run came across when Andruw Jones drove a ball into left to
score Gerald Williams.
</P>
<P>
   And who said interleague play wasn't going to be fun.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's phenomenal,'' said Braves third baseman Chipper Jones.
``This has to be our No. 1 comeback.''
</P>
<P>
   Added a giddy general manager John Schuerholz, ``That's
incredible, it's really exciting.''
</P>
<P>
   It's was such a great comeback that even the Elias Sports Bureau
said they need a day to research it to find out whether it is the
biggest deficit the Braves have ever overcome in the ninth to win a
game.
</P>
<P>
   But this game was lost, the Braves down 6-1 going into the ninth
as it appeared Tom Glavine would lose for the first time in a month
and Red Sox starter Derek Lowe would win his first game of the
season.
</P>
<P>
   But as Braves manager Bobby Cox pointed out, ``Everything that
didn't fall in all night seemed to fall in in one inning.``
</P>
<P>
   The ninth started with Tom Gordon walking to the mound. He has a
major-league-leading 19 saves, had allowed just four runs all
season. But he made a big mistake when he opened the inning by
walking pinch hitter Ozzie Guillen and Walt Weiss. Keith Lockhart
then singled in the first run, Chipper Jones following with another
RBI hit. Gordon was lifted for John Wasdin and Andres Galarraga
launched a ball to left-center to score two on a double. Still, no
outs and up came Ryan Klesko, who tied the game on a hit to left,
his second RBI-single of the night to the opposite field. Then Javy
Lopez moved Williams, who had come in to run for Klesko, to second
on a bunt. Michael Tucker was intentionally walked and on came
Andruw Jones for the game-winner.
</P>
<P>
   ``They weren't going to let Michael Tucker beat them,'' said the
center fielder. ``We never give up.''
</P>
<P>
   Meanwhile, the other clubhouse was numb, the Braves stinging a
team that has so many Atlanta and Georgia Tech connections.
</P>
<P>
   Said Red Sox manager Jimy Williams, ``It's a nine-inning game.
They're good.''
</P>
<P>
   Added Cox, ``How do you figure out this game sometimes?''
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
