<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-NY-SCHOOL-DONATION-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
COSMETICS EXECUTIVES PLEDGE $1 MILLION TO A BRONX HIGH SCHOOL 
</HEADLINE>
  (mk) 
 By JACQUES STEINBERG   
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ The competition among New York City's elite public
high schools has always been fierce, especially when academic
bragging rights have been on the line. But lately, the jousting has
moved from the classroom into the fund-raising arena.
</P>
<P>
   Less than three months after alumni pledged to create a $10
million endowment for Brooklyn Technical High School, Leonard and
Ronald Lauder said Monday that they would donate as much as $1
million to a campaign seeking to raise $10 million on behalf of
their alma mater, the Bronx High School of Science. Leonard Lauder,
chairman and chief executive of Estee Lauder Cos., the cosmetics
concern, is a 1950 graduate of the school; his brother Ronald,
chairman of Estee Lauder International and a former U.S. ambassador
to Austria, graduated in 1961.
</P>
<P>
   Only one other public school in the United States, Walnut Hills
High School in Cincinnati, is believed to have set a more ambitious
target _ $12 million for a new science center.
</P>
<P>
   At Bronx Science, alumni leaders said, the investment income
from the endowment _ potentially hundreds of thousands of dollars a
year _ would be used to upgrade computer equipment and
laboratories, provide supplemental course materials and renovate
antiquated classrooms.
</P>
<P>
   But the president of the endowment fund, Milton Kopelman, a
former principal of Bronx Science, said the group also hoped to use
the money to hire teachers to reduce class sizes.
</P>
<P>
   That could set up a showdown with Schools Chancellor Rudy Crew.
</P>
<P>
   Last fall, Crew spurned the efforts of parents at a Greenwich
Village elementary school to raise $46,000 to hire an additional
fourth-grade teacher so that all fourth-grade classes would be
smaller. While Crew has said that he has no quarrel with parents or
outsiders spending money on fringe items _ like computers or
teacher training _ he said that class size must be determined by
the school system's budget.
</P>
<P>
   A spokeswoman for Crew, Chiara Coletti, quoted the chancellor as
saying he was ``touched and deeply grateful'' to the Lauders. Asked
if she expected the class-size reduction issue to be a source of
friction, Ms. Coletti said that the chancellor was not familiar
with the details of the gift but had ``complete faith'' that the
alumni ``will choose to use the endowment in the most equitable and
creative way.''
</P>
<P>
   For the 60-year-old high school in the northwest Bronx _ which,
like its rivals Brooklyn Tech and Stuyvesant High School, admits
students using a stiff entrance examination _ word of the Lauders'
donation has already lit a fire under other alumni: Since a
kick-off event for the endowment on May 28, Kopelman said, other
graduates have contributed $400,000 to match the Lauders' pledge.
(The endowment will receive the full $1 million from the Lauders,
Kopelman said, once $1 million in matching donations have been
pledged.)
</P>
<P>
   In an interview, Leonard Lauder said he hoped the money would
influence others.
</P>
<P>
   ``Any time you raise the bar of excellence,'' he said, ``it
brings everyone else along with it. If it weren't for the Bronx
Sciences, the Brooklyn Techs, the Stuyvesants and the Hunters over
the years, the New York City school system and indeed the entire
New York State Regents system wouldn't have the high standards they
have today.''
</P>
<P>
   Moreover, Lauder estimated that his family and its companies had
probably contributed upwards of $1 million, ``quietly,'' to the
system as a whole over the last 15 years.
</P>
<P>
   But at a time when countless other city public schools are
suffering from decades of fiscal neglect, the Lauders' largesse, as
well as the fund-raising efforts at Brooklyn Tech and elsewhere,
raise lingering questions about equity throughout a school system
of 1,100 schools.
</P>
<P>
   ``Most schools don't have a monied alumni and don't have monied
parents,'' said Noreen Connell, the executive director of the
Educational Priorities Panel, a coalition of 25 civic organizations
that monitors city school spending.
</P>
<P>
   Such gifts, Ms. Connell added, also continue to blur the lines
between public and private education, tempting school systems to
shift resources away from the most richly endowed schools,
confident that the private sector will fill the gap.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't begrudge them trying to help out plugging holes in the
city budget,'' she said, noting that just five years ago Bronx
Science was so starved for money that its students were playing
violins without backs.
</P>
<P>
   ``But the sad thing is,'' Ms. Connell added, ``that the more
parents and alumni fill in the gaps, the more the city assumes the
funding is there and the city doesn't have to provide the money.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
