<SLUG> BC-CT-PHONE-MERGER-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
PHONE MERGER SHOULD INCLUDE RATE CUT, CONNECTICUT OFFICIAL SAYS 
</HEADLINE>
  (mk) 
 By JONATHAN RABINOVITZ   
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW BRITAIN, Conn. _ The merger between Connecticut's primary
telephone company and a Texas-based telecommunications giant should
not be approved unless it includes a substantial rate reduction,
Attorney General Richard Blumenthal said Monday.
</P>
<P>
   The $4.4 billion deal that would allow SBC Communications of San
Antonio to acquire Southern New England Telecommunications Corp. of
New Haven was announced in January, but hearings by the state
Department of Public Utility Control on whether to allow the deal
to go forward started Monday.
</P>
<P>
   If the sale is completed, it would introduce a new player into
the state's efforts to deregulate the local telephone market, which
has been an SNET monopoly for at least 70 years.
</P>
<P>
   ``Much has been said that this is a good deal, but the question
is, a good deal for whom?'' Blumenthal said Monday morning, adding
later that he did not oppose the merger, but simply wanted
consumers to get their fair share.
</P>
<P>
   Although the two companies have said the deal would improve each
company's financial prospects, they have declined to include any
rate reduction for consumers.
</P>
<P>
   Blumenthal estimated that SBC would gain $220 million in savings
and added revenues from the merger, and that half of that should go
back to consumers in rate reductions that would reduce a typical
monthly bill by about $4.
</P>
<P>
   But Edward Whitacre Jr., SBC's chief executive, told The New
Haven Register last week that such a rate reduction would be a
``financial disaster'' for his company. ``We would not do the deal
under those terms,'' Whitacre said.
</P>
<P>
   At the hearing Monday, executives from SBC and SNET said that
SNET was already losing money on its local telephone service and
that Blumenthal's figures were wrong. A rate cut, they added, would
discourage new companies from entering the deregulated local
telephone market.
</P>
<P>
   And the companies' officials also charged that state law did not
permit the Department of Public Utility Control to order a rate
reduction as part of a merger approval. The department will make a
ruling later this year, and federal regulators are also reviewing
the merger.
</P>
<P>
   Yet when SBC acquired Pacific Telesis Group of San Francisco
last year, it agreed to refund $214 million to consumers, in return
for approval of the merger by California regulators. Selim Bingol,
a SBC spokesman, said that Connecticut's rules do not allow state
regulators to make the same deal, a point Blumenthal disputed.
</P>
<P>
   Others suggested that SBC's position may come from its desire to
limit the cost of another business deal _ the $62-billion purchase
of the Midwestern phone company, Ameritech. That deal must still be
approved by Illinois regulators, who may be influenced by how
Connecticut addresses the issue.
</P>
<P>
   ``This can easily become a situation where a certain political
dynamic takes over,'' said Eli Noam, director of Columbia
University's Institute for Tele-Information. ``If Connecticut rolls
back rates, other state regulators will be asked, `How come you
didn't do the same?' You create a dynamic where it is hard for any
commission to do less.''
</P>
<P>
   SBC, one of the eight ``Baby Bells'' created by the breakup of
AT&AMP;T, has about 34 million customers in California, Texas, Nevada
and other states, but no customer base for local telephone service
in the Northeast. SNET has about 2.2 million customers in
Connecticut.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
