<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BBN-DODNOTE-LADN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
CANDIOTTI RETURNS AS VISITOR
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By MATT McHALE  
 c.1998 Los Angeles Daily News  
<TEXT>
<P>
   LOS ANGELES _ After six seasons with the Los Angeles Dodgers,
knuckleballer Tom Candiotti returned to Dodger Stadium for the
first time Monday as a member of the Oakland Athletics.
</P>
<P>
   Candiotti, 4-7 with a 5.20 ERA for the last-place A's, was
warmly greeted by executive vice president Fred Claire, who had
offered Candiotti a spot in the Dodgers bullpen for this season but
couldn't guarantee a place in the starting rotation.
</P>
<P>
   ``I had lots of fun here, playing every night in front of
150,000 people,'' Candiotti said. ``But I like where I am. When I
got here (1992), Darryl Strawberry and Eric Davis had bad years and
we finished last. But Eric Karros got his start that year and then
it was (Mike) Piazza, (Raul) Mondesi and all the Rookies of the
Year.
</P>
<P>
   ``That's what we're getting started in Oakland.''
</P>
<P>
   Candiotti said National League fans might not know much about
right fielder Ben Grieve, shortstop Miguel Tejada or injured center
fielder Jason McDonald, but they will.
</P>
<P>
   ``They aren't household names,'' Candiotti said. ``But they come
to play every night.''
</P>
<P>
   Candiotti, 40, wishes he could say the same. He left Sunday's
start against Arizona after one inning because of back spasms.
Candiotti underwent treatment Monday and said he expects to make
his next start.
</P>
<P>
   __ McMichael arrives: Reliever Greg McMichael, part of last
Thursday's Hideo Nomo trade with the Mets, joined the club Monday.
The day of the trade, McMichael returned to his home in Atlanta,
where wife Jennifer went into premature labor. She was not due
until August. Doctors corrected the situation.
</P>
<P>
   To make room for McMichael on the roster, the Dodgers optioned
reliever Eric Weaver to Triple-A Albuquerque. Weaver pitched four
innings and allowed one run in two appearances.
</P>
<P>
   Dave Mlicki, the other member of the Mets to join the Dodgers,
reported Friday and started Saturday's game. Despite a poor showing
against Seattle, Mlicki is expected to start Friday's series opener
against Colorado at Dodger Stadium.
</P>
<P>
   __ Luke claimed: First baseman/outfielder Matt Luke was claimed
off waivers by the Cleveland Indians. Luke, who didn't look to get
much playing time after the Dodgers acquired Jim Eisenreich, was
designated for assignment May 29. The Dodgers had seven days to
trade Luke, who batted .286 with three homers and 11 RBI in 33
games. When that didn't happen, he was placed on waivers.
</P>
<P>
   __ Quick hits: Third baseman Bobby Bonilla returned to the
lineup after missing two games with the flu. He struck out swinging
his first two at-bats.... Scott Spiezio's first-inning single
extended his hitting streak to 17 games, two short of the American
League-season high set by Detroit's Damion Easley.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
