<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-NY-ANTHEM-COLUMN-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
COLUMN: A CITY IN SEARCH OF AN ANTHEM 
</HEADLINE>
  (mk) 
 By CLYDE HABERMAN   
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ Let's start by spreading the news, which is not
really that new.
</P>
<P>
   Soon after Frank Sinatra died last month, the City Council
speaker, Peter Vallone, introduced a bill to make the singer's
version of ``New York, New York'' the city's official song. Mayor
Edward Koch did the same thing in a 1985 proclamation, but Council
action would give this anthem the weight of law.
</P>
<P>
   In case you've been stranded on a remote island for two decades,
we're talking about the 1977 composition by John Kander and Fred
Ebb, the one that an aging Sinatra croaked into a signature song
heard everywhere from night clubs to ballparks. Steve Ross, the
cabaret singer, who has dozens of New York songs in his repertoire,
calls the opening notes _ da da da-de-dum _ ``probably the most
famous vamp of any popular song in the world.''
</P>
<P>
   ``The music primes the pump,'' he said at a cafe on the Upper
West Side. ``It sets up this little buzz that all foreigners say
happens when they hit the airport here.''
</P>
<P>
   But even though Ross considered it a splendid number _ king of
the hill, top of the heap, if you will _ he also entertained a
question about whether this city could do better for itself.
</P>
<P>
   Listen to the lyrics. The fellow in the song isn't even a New
Yorker. He is an out-of-towner whose ``little town blues are
melting away'' only because he is about to go to New York ``and
make a brand new start of it.'' His focus is on wanting to ``wake
up in a city that doesn't sleep,'' to find he's king of the hill
and all that. ``If I can make it there, I'll make it anywhere.''
</P>
<P>
   Bully for him. But why should New York's anthem be about the
ambitions of a self-absorbed arriviste? Shouldn't it be about the
wonders of the city itself, maybe with lyrics that reflect New York
sophistication and not just ``We're No. 1'' chest-thumping?
</P>
<P>
   A strong candidate, Ross agreed, would be ``N.Y.C.,'' from the
musical ``Annie.'' Besides having a great title, worthy of a
column, this paean to the city has a topical fillip, given recent
mayoral battles:
</P>
<P>
   ``N.Y.C., what is it about you? You're big, you're loud, you're
tough. N.Y.C., I go years without you, then I can't get enough.
Enough of cabdrivers answering back in language far from pure.
Enough of frankfurters answering back.'' And so on, down to the
fade-out: ``You snap, you fizz, the best there is is you, is
N.Y.C.''
</P>
<P>
   ``That ain't bad,'' Ross said. Ditto for a clever number that he
favors: Cole Porter's ``I Happen to Like New York,'' which moves to
the finger-snap pace of a New York self-confident enough to
acknowledge its own imperfections.
</P>
<P>
   ``I happen to like New York,'' it begins. ``I happen to like
this town. I like the city air. I like to drink of it. The more I
know New York, the more I think of it. I like the sight and the
sound and even the stink of it.'' Definitely, a contender.
</P>
<P>
   Other New York songs are marvelous, though perhaps problematic
as anthems. ``Autumn in New York'' speaks lovingly of ``glittering
crowds and shimmering clouds in canyons of steel.'' But an
underlying melancholy makes it unsuitable, Ross said.
</P>
<P>
   Another obvious candidate is ``New York, New York (It's a
Helluva Town),'' where the Bronx is up and the Battery's down.
``But it's too jazzy,'' the singer said. ``It's not simple and
straightforward enough for a good anthem.''
</P>
<P>
   In that vein, he finds Billy Joel's ``New York State of Mind''
too discursive. The venerable ``Sidewalks of New York'' is dated.
Rodgers and Hart's ``Give It Back to the Indians'' is witty but
negative. And an array of tunes lose out because of their narrow
geographical focus, including songs you may love the melody of:
``42nd Street,'' ``Manhattan,'' ``Take the A Train,'' ``Lullaby of
Broadway'' and ``The 59th Street Bridge Song.''
</P>
<P>
   When you get down to it, Ross said, the Kander and Ebb number
may be about as good it gets. By now, it is known by everyone,
everywhere. ``If all else fails and I'm losing an audience,'' he
said, ``if I start that song, I can get it back.''
</P>
<P>
   He added: ``It may not say the ultimate thing that needs to be
said about New York. But people do seem to view New York as a
testing ground, and you have that in those powerful last words: `If
I can make it there, I'll make it anywhere.'''
</P>
<P>
   Perhaps the only other strong candidate happened to come from
outside the cafe where he was sitting. There it was, the true New
York anthem, ever present: a car alarm.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
