<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BKL-WNBASIDE-LADN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
ABL NEEDS TV CONTRACT
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By MICHAEL ROSENTHAL  
 c.1998 Los Angeles Daily News  
<TEXT>
<P>
   LOS ANGELES _ Although it might appear the WNBA has all the
advantages to becoming the only women's professional basketball
league, the ABL isn't willing to give up. It was started by a group
of investors and runs its affairs its way and is confident its
demise is not in sight.
</P>
<P>
   Many believe the ABL has an edge in talent, although even ABL
officials admit the WNBA landed the majority of the top college
players who graduated in the spring.
</P>
<P>
   The ABL, however, pays better. Which means its players don't
have as much of a need to play overseas to complement their
incomes, as many WNBA players do. Also, the ABL boasts about its
winter schedule _ it plays basketball when basketball should be
played. The WNBA operates during the summer.
</P>
<P>
   Not long ago, girls were given access to the high school gym
only when the boys weren't using it, a situation some might compare
to the NBA-WNBA setup.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't want to see women settle for playing in the summer,''
Long Beach Stingrays center/forward Cass Aure said. ``We fought for
equal opportunity. I don't think we should sell out. I'm not saying
the WNBA sold out. But if it comes down to one league, I don't want
to see it played in the summer.
</P>
<P>
   ``That's going backward. We've come too far.''
</P>
<P>
   The question is how far will they go?
</P>
<P>
   Among the challenges the ABL faces in its attempt to survive is
hanging onto its stars and landing a serious TV package. The league
already lost 1996-97 Most Valuable Player Nikki McCray, who jumped
to the WNBA. And star Dawn Staley of the Philadelphia Rage is
considering a move when her contract expires in August, which could
be damaging to a league that can't absorb too many punches.
</P>
<P>
   Will others follow suit?
</P>
<P>
   A lot could depend on television. Gary Cavalli, the ABL's
co-founder, admits that bringing his product to more people is the
top priority. Last season, 24 games were broadcast on Fox Sports
Net, 13 games on BET. Many were delayed.
</P>
<P>
   Cavalli is looking for a deal or deals to widen dramatically the
league's audience, possibly with coverage on both free and cable TV
like the WNBA, which is on NBC, ESPN and Lifetime. He said he's
negotiating with ``five different networks'' but wouldn't reveal
them. He said he expects to make an announcement by next month.
</P>
<P>
   The result of the talks could determine the fate of the league.
</P>
<P>
   ``I wonder about some of the ABL sponsors, how long they'll
stick with it once their contracts expire,'' said Sharon Barbano,
president of the Women's Sports Marketing Group. ``... That's why,
unless (the ABL) gets a major TV package, I don't think they can
survive. The sponsors aren't going to hang in there.''
</P>
<P>
   The response of ABL officials?
</P>
<P>
   If they'd listen to doubters from the beginning, they said, they
wouldn't be making plans for third season.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think the same people who believe only one league can
survive are the same people who didn't believe women's basketball
could take off in the first place,'' said Bill McGillis, general
manager of the Stingrays.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-06-09-98 0037EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
