<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FBN-COWBOYS-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
GAILEY'S GOAL IN 1998: NO VANILLA IN COWBOYS 
</HEADLINE>
  (mk) 
 By THOMAS GEORGE   
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   DALLAS _ Chan Gailey came seemingly from nowhere, an offensive
coordinator from the Pittsburgh Steelers who had quietly but
efficiently done his job. A man of strong character and stout
religious background who in his football travels had never left a
place where his return would not be welcomed. An offensive guru, an
imaginative, cutting-edge offensive mind, a 46-year-old Georgian
who in his football travels had been a special teams coach, a
defensive coordinator, an offensive coordinator and a head coach.
</P>
<P>
   And now Gailey has been told to take this job and shove this
team, this franchise, back where it believes it belongs.
</P>
<P>
   Gailey got the Dallas head coaching job that appeared to be
Terry Donahue's, the former UCLA coach, the job that Sherman Lewis
from Green Bay seemed suited for, the job that several others
appeared in line for miles before him. The task of taking the
Dallas Cowboys star and polishing it and making it shine once
again.
</P>
<P>
   He is head coach of a team that is removed from its startling
success in this decade: Three Super Bowl championships, five
consecutive National Conference East division titles and a six-year
playoff run. All of that came to a draining, spinning, reeling halt
last season when the Cowboys finished 6-10, lost its last five
games, missed the playoffs and, in many circles, became the brunt
of cruel jokes throughout the league and beyond for its mishaps in
character off the field as much as for its demise on it.
</P>
<P>
   Jerry Jones, the Cowboy owner, met Gailey last February at the
scouting combine in Indianapolis on a Sunday afternoon and by
Thursday afternoon they were talking money and contracts and how to
fix what was broken in Dallas.
</P>
<P>
   ``When I first met him,'' Jones said, ``I sat up straight. By
the time I finished talking with him, I was on the edge of my
seat.''
</P>
<P>
   Gailey fit. He could redesign the Cowboys predictable offense.
He could work with quarterback Troy Aikman. He had head coaching
experience. And he could, in his prescience alone, offer a sort of
moral character and fiber from the top that the Dallas players,
especially the young ones, certainly needed.
</P>
<P>
   So, when the cowboys conducted minicamp here last week, Gailey
started the makeover firsthand with the entire week.
</P>
<P>
   ``From afar, I saw a team that looked like it was having
problems,'' Gailey said of the Cowboys, now his Cowboys. ``And that
is as far as I went with it because I was having enough problems of
my own getting the Pittsburgh offense where we wanted it to be
instead of spending time judging someone else. When someone is at
the top, you want to bring them down, knock them down to your
level. That is the nature of pro football and the nature of some
people's lives.''
</P>
<P>
   Gailey grew up in Americus, Ga., the hometown of Dan Reeves, the
former Cowboy player and assistant coach who is now coach and
general manager of the Atlanta Falcons. It was Reeves who gave
Gailey his start as a pro coach when he hired him to tutor special
teams for the Denver Broncos in 1986.
</P>
<P>
   ``The Cowboys were bigger than life to me as a kid,'' Gailey
said. ``A team involved in so many championships. A team that had
Dan, who was one of our own. You can't perceive on the outside just
how strong the history is here, how much pride they have and how
much responsibility goes with being a Dallas Cowboy. And it's not
just a local thing. This is a worldwide entity.''
</P>
<P>
   And it is one that Gailey must fix to survive as boss.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm going to be the person that I am,'' Gailey said. ``Naive?
If I'm naive, I'm naive. I'm going to do what is right. I'm going
to treat people the way they want to be treated. It used to be that
drawing the line with a player was easy but it gets harder today to
find that line. I'm worried about that guy and his family and his
friends and his grandchildren down the road. My responsibility,
totally? No. But I am partially responsible for all of that being
his head coach. I am responsible, too, for winning.''
</P>
<P>
   In Pittsburgh the last two seasons, Gailey led an offense that
finished ranked No. 2 in the NFL in rushing in 1996 in and No. 1 in
'97. Pittsburgh scored 44 touchdowns last year, fourth most in the
league, and its 19 rushing touchdowns was third best.
</P>
<P>
   Look for the Cowboys offense to be dripping with creativity.
Gailey will use the shotgun formation, four and five receiver sets,
the option, reverses, and several gadget plays. He will take a
whirl with an offense that has looked stale.
</P>
<P>
   Erik Williams, the Dallas star offensive tackle, said of Gailey:
``It's going to be a different offense with him. When I look back
at our Super Bowl teams, those were talented clubs that were so
much better than other teams. We kept it simple. We don't have that
kind of talent now. So, we need variety in the offense and he's got
it. Coach is a killing-you-softly kind of guy. He's real soft
rather than being real loud but he's killing you all of the time.
Both ways can work. We've got young guys looking to be led. Certain
people do not lead you in the right direction all of the time. With
him, he is going to lead you the right way and we need that.''
</P>
<P>
   Aikman added: ``The worst is behind us. Chan presents us with a
fresh new start. Usually when you get a new head coach you tend to
be in a rebuilding mode. This football team is not going to be like
that. We expect great things.
</P>
<P>
   Thus, Gailey enters in Dallas and his players say all are off on
the right foot. Change can be good, they say. Gailey wants his team
to prepare, to be strong in the running game, to be swift on
defense, with the entire success of this upcoming season, his first
season, depending on the health of the offensive line, he said. He
views himself like a movie director. Here is the script, the parts,
the scene. Now, what must I do to choreograph this show?
</P>
<P>
   ``I was not hired to be a robot,'' Gailey said. ``They hired me
to bring something to the table. I'll give it a whirl. Especially
when things look a little stale.'' &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-06-09-98 0040EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
