<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-JENKINS-JACKSON-SFCRON </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
THE INNER GAME OF AN ODDBALL COACH 
</HEADLINE>
  By BRUCE JENKINS 
 c.1998 San Francisco Chronicle  
<TEXT>
<P>
   CHICAGO _ Phil Jackson's body enters a room in stages. It could
be an elbow coming through first, or a knee or a shoulder or a
chin, depending on the undulations of the moment. He's from the
Ministry of Silly Walks. The body appears to have been built with
an Erector Set or in some secret laboratory, where they were just
about to start over when someone said, ``Wait, keep this model.
It's funny.''
</P>
<P>
   Phil's a little different upstairs, too.
</P>
<P>
   You can't capsulize the man in a single phrase, because he's had
too many lives: church-goer, rebel, flower child, power forward,
Zen philosopher. Just now he's presiding over the most fascinating
cast of NBA champions since the eclectic Warriors of 1975.
</P>
<P>
   But maybe this sums him up, at least for the moment: Dennis
Rodman missed practice Monday, and nobody even blinked.
</P>
<P>
   It's almost a given now that Rodman will bypass important team
functions _ practices, community appearances, even actual games _
to follow his muse. Of course he missed the shoot-around. Of course
he went to Vegas. Of course he was working out on a treadmill in
some Delta Center hallway when Jackson wanted him in the game last
Friday. You bet he goes shopping for wedding gowns and fancies the
company of transvestites. Aren't all the really great rebounders
like that?
</P>
<P>
   With Jackson, you really start to wonder. Make no mistake, he's
steamed over Rodman's assaults on team unity. But Jackson's
patience, and the way it all seems to work out for Chicago in the
end, is nothing short of remarkable.
</P>
<P>
   ``You think about the rope he gives Rodman, and I'm not sure any
other coach would do that,'' said Jack Ramsay, the astute former
coach and current ESPN analyst. ``I couldn't do it. My thing was
`same rules for everybody.' I can't imagine one of my players not
being on the bench during a game! (laughter) But Phil's strength is
his great touch with his players. Whatever happens with Dennis,
Phil doesn't let it gnaw at his soul. Somehow he sees a bigger
picture.''
</P>
<P>
   Because of that, the Bulls' players see it, too. Their motto
isn't ``Three-Peat'' or any tribute to the wondrous Jordan. It's
``Oh, Well _ That's Just Dennis.''
</P>
<P>
   And by the way, Rodman got every key rebound, passed expertly
within the triangle offense and pulled a head-trip number on Karl
Malone.
</P>
<P>
   There's an angry faction out there, ridiculing Jackson, calling
for Rodman's banishment and claiming that a barbershop quartet
could win the NBA title with Jordan. The fact is, the Bulls need
all of their mysterious little pieces to function. They need Rodman
under the boards. They need Jackson to dismiss every transgression
with a simple fine. And they need the players to get on Jackson's
wavelength.
</P>
<P>
   ``What do we feel about Dennis missing practice today?
Nothing,'' said Steve Kerr. ``We're used to it. Phil handled it the
right way, leave it at that.''
</P>
<P>
   The same question went to Luc Longley. ``We're all tired of it,
to be honest,'' he said. ``It's just a shame these things should
happen during a championship series. But with Dennis, we know what
we've got. We're not gonna quit on him now. We stick by him.''
</P>
<P>
   And that comes strictly from the fine touch of Jackson, the most
erudite, eccentric, well-rounded and downright interesting NBA
coach in memory.
</P>
<P>
   You think about guys like Rick Adelman, Del Harris, the esteemed
Pat Riley _ hell, almost anyone in this business: All forthright
fellows, but pretty much on the same road for life. Plenty of
coaching, with a side of seminars, followed by two clinics and a
film session. They've all lived a single life, maybe two on the
outside, to Jackson's dozen.
</P>
<P>
   He grew up in a wilds-of-Montana environment so stifled, his
parents wouldn't let him go to movies, watch TV, listen to rock 'n'
roll, or even read, if it wasn't the Bible or a schoolbook. His
family's life revolved entirely around the church. Young Phil hung
with it for several years, absorbed the best of it all, then
flipped his life's record to the ``B'' side. Over there he found
exotic Eastern religions, sultry ports of call, alternative
lifestyles, the questioning of authority, a hint of weed, and as he
once revealed in a biography, the occasional tab of acid.
</P>
<P>
   And he always played hoops. They laughed at his body, the odd
shoulders and sharp bones and funny angles, but he had a deep and
thorough understanding of the game. In a small but undeniable way,
he was a little like Rodman: thoroughly unconventional, both on the
court and off, but a master of hard work and the game's subtleties.
Old film clips show Jackson playing for the Knicks in the early
'70s, an incomprehensible vision alongside ``Clyde'' Frazier,
``Black Jesus'' Monroe, ``Fall Back, Baby'' Barnett and future U.S.
Senator Bill Bradley. But they loved him on that team. And he loved
the life. He saw it a little differently than anyone else, but he
was born to elbow his way inside, toss that bag of bones skyward
and grab a rebound from Paul Silas.
</P>
<P>
   When they first interviewed him in Chicago, for an assistant's
job, Jackson showed up in a Panama hat with a macaw's feather. He
tried to explain the look to Stan Albeck, then the Bulls' GM, ``but
his eyes glazed over very early in the interview,'' Jackson said.
``I didn't get the job.''
</P>
<P>
   In time, Jackson mastered the art of diplomacy. He became a man
comfortable in two distinct worlds. ``He's like lubricating oil,''
his wife, June, once said. ``He keeps everything moving.''
</P>
<P>
   And without Phil Jackson, Michael Jordan simply cannot continue
playing in the NBA. Jordan has bought into it all: the curious body
language, the honey-smooth speaking voice, the Zen-Buddhist
teachings, the utter calm under stress.
</P>
<P>
   ``No matter what I've attained,'' said Jordan, ``Phil can still
motivate me, still criticize me, still coach me as he would any
other player on our team. I have a high regard for someone not
caught up in my mystique.''
</P>
<P>
   Everything else is just speculation now, the tedious and
long-running rumors about Bulls management breaking up the team.
Everyone thinks it's over. They're calling it ``the last dance''
and shooting home videos to save the memories. But when it's all
over, and the Bulls are just another topic for summer afternoons in
the rocking chair, Jordan won't be the only one with a mystique.
Save one of those plaques for Phil Jackson.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; (For use by clients of the New York Times News Service) &QL;  &LR;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
