</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BKN-FINALS-SFCHRON </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
BATTERED JAZZ SKIP PRACTICE 
</HEADLINE>
   By DAVID STEELE  
 c.1998 San Francisco Chronicle  
<TEXT>
<P>
   CHICAGO _ The day after the worst beating in the history of the
NBA Finals, the Utah Jazz decided not to practice.
</P>
<P>
   So did Dennis Rodman.
</P>
<P>
   They apparently reached their conclusions from different
directions. The Bulls gave no explanation for Rodman's absence and
did not indicate how they would discipline him.
</P>
<P>
   Coach Phil Jackson told reporters that Rodman had called him and
said he had overslept _ but later in the day, the power forward
showed up at The Palace of Auburn Hills, near Detroit, at a pro
wrestling match. He declined to talk to a reporter at the match,
staying in a luxury box at The Palace and cavorting with, among
others, wrestlers Hulk Hogan and Bret Hart.
</P>
<P>
   The Jazz, meanwhile, passed on a workout in favor of a film
session at the United Center dedicated to dissecting Sunday's 96-54
Bulls victory.
</P>
<P>
   ``We put a couple of tables back there in the training room,''
said coach Jerry Sloan, ``so guys could lay back and rest for a
while while we watched film, in case somebody gets sick.''
</P>
<P>
   Sloan was joking, but the goal of the day was to eject the
residue of Game 3 from their systems. Desperately needing a Game 4
victory to tie the series 2-2 and secure a trip back to Salt Lake
City _ but forced to endure two days of introspection and public
scrutiny until the next game _ the Jazz have a difficult task
ahead. They gave the appearance of a team with a firm grasp of what
they faced and a clear mental outlook. They were still angry but
made a show of not sounding beaten.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think we'll come back and play,'' Sloan said. ``I've always
felt like when we've had disappointing times we've always come back
and played pretty hard ... I think we'll play hard, but the
important thing is, I think you have to play intelligently. I don't
think we did that all the time.''
</P>
<P>
   Added John Stockton, ``The sun came up, today's another day, and
we just go back to the drawing board and try to start playing well
again ... So that one's behind us.''
</P>
<P>
   The Jazz do have reason for hope. Seven teams before them had
lost a Finals game by 33 points or more, and three of them went on
to win the series and the title: the Lakers over the 76ers in '82,
the Celtics over the Lakers in '84 and the Lakers over Boston in
1985. Plus, the Bulls crushed the Blazers by 33 in the opener of
the 1992 Finals, only to lose Game 2 in Chicago.
</P>
<P>
   Apparently, though, the Jazz cannot count on their opponent
being rattled by another Rodman no-show. The reaction to Rodman's
absence from the morning practice was utter nonchalance. ``We don't
worry about that. The only ones who make a big deal about it are
you guys, the media,'' said the Bulls' Ron Harper.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think something happened between the game (Sunday) and this
morning,'' Jackson said, making it clear the absence was not
excused. ``He called at practice about 15 minutes ago and he said
he got up late, his alarm clock didn't work and he didn't think
he'd be here in time for the press.''
</P>
<P>
   The NBA fined Rodman $10,000 for not showing up at the mandatory
media session.
</P>
<P>
   ``It is the wrong time of the season to take the focus away from
what we are trying to accomplish,'' said Chicago's Scottie Pippen.
``But we've always let Dennis have his way.''
</P>
<P>
   The Bulls had their way with the Jazz on Sunday, and when they
return to practice Tuesday, the Jazz will concentrate on solving
the Bulls' trapping defense, which completely negated their
precision pick-and-roll offense. The Jazz reacted so slowly to the
Bulls' defense, Sloan said, that they were being beaten to their
appointed spots by their defenders. Throw in the numerous missed
layups (particularly by center Greg Ostertag) and missed open
jumpers (everyone except Karl Malone), and the result is a
record-setting disaster.
</P>
<P>
   The Bulls, meanwhile, are on guard to avoid complacency and
overconfidence after the Game 3 rout. Michael Jordan said he
remembered the scenario from 1992: ``We've had experience to be in
that situation before. We are very aware of the circumstances, and
I don't think that we are going to come out overconfident.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think we are going to come out looking at the adjustments
that are made to go into Game 4, and be prepared to apply our
aggressive defense once again and offensively play a lot better.''
</P>
<P>
   In fact, the Bulls focused their film session on the first eight
minutes of the game, when the Jazz and Malone seemed on the verge
of taking control. ``We stunk the first period,'' Harper said, ``so
we know we didn't play a great ballgame. Whatever adjustments (the
Jazz) are going to make, we're going to have to make, too.''
</P>
<P>
   And Sloan said the adjustments need to be more than tactical
ones. ``You don't motivate players. They have to motivate
themselves,'' he said of his role as coach. ``I've always had that
philosophy, and I think that's the most overused word in sports.
... That comes from within yourself. That's the bottom line.''
</P>
<P>
   &UR; (For use by clients of the New York Times News Service) &QL;  &LR;
</P>
