<DOCNO> NYT19980609.0018 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-06-09 00:57 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A0279 &Cx1f; ttd-z
r s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-SOC-WORLDCUP_SFCHRON &LR;      06-09 1043
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-SOC-WORLDCUP </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
CONFIDENT AMERICAN FACE UPHILL BATTLE TO BE WORLD-BEATERS  
 BY DAN GIESIN 
</HEADLINE>
 _ SFCHRON   c.1998 San Francisco Chronicle  
<TEXT>
<P>
   Moments before embarking for France and the World Cup last
Thursday, Steve Sampson talked the talk of underdogs everywhere.
</P>
<P>
   ``This team,'' the coach said of the U.S. National squad,
``truly believes in themselves and believes that they can beat
Germany, Iran and Yugoslavia. ... The players really feel they will
do something terrific.''
</P>
<P>
   Getting to the second round would just about fill the bill.
</P>
<P>
   In a World Cup grouping that does the United States no favors _
in the 1994 tournament, the team had a relatively easy first-round
draw, home-crowd advantage and a ``wild-card'' pass into the round
of 16 _ the Americans face an uphill battle. Even the president of
the U.S. Soccer Federation, Alan Rothenberg, is on record as saying
this team has little chance of repeating the glory of '94.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think the goal is to make the second round,'' Rothenberg was
quoted recently in the Washington Post. ``Realistically, I don't
expect to achieve that goal.''
</P>
<P>
   Sampson, whose greatest asset perhaps is his unflappability,
said Rothenberg has a point but politely added that maybe his boss
is mistaken.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't think Mr. Rothenberg was stating anything different
than what many people are saying; that Germany and Yugoslavia are
expected to advance out of our group,'' Sampson said. ``But I think
this U.S. team can surprise some people. Our best soccer is yet to
come.''
</P>
<P>
   That's been Sampson's mantra ever since the Americans qualified
for their unprecedented third straight Cup finals in November. He
truly believes that his squad _ comprised of, in roughly equal
parts, experience, youth and talent _ will show the world that
Americans can compete successfully on the international stage.
</P>
<P>
   ``We have gone from a team that was conservative and
inexperienced (in '94) to one that imposes its (playing) style on
other teams,'' he said of a team that has gone 9-3-5 since
September and has outscored opponents 23-11 during that stretch.
``It's hard to say how far we'll go in France, but anything's
possible. We have enough talent to get results. ... I'm a firm
believer of this team doing something special. When it is faced
with a tough opponent, this team always steps up.''
</P>
<P>
   Just ask Brazil, which saw Kasey Keller, one of the best goalies
in the world, deny its stars shot after shot in the Americans'
stunning 1-0 upset of the defending world champs in February. Or
how about Austria, a Cup finals qualifier that was taken apart 3-0
by the Americans two months ago in Vienna.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think we're definitely a team that every team in the world
knows that even if they play their best game against us, they can
lose,'' midfielder Tab Ramos said.
</P>
<P>
   On the other hand you can talk to Holland and Belgium, two more
Cup qualifiers that easily dissected and exposed the U.S. team four
days apart in Europe in late February. Or how about Macedonia,
which did not qualify for the Cup but nonetheless shut down the
Americans in a scoreless draw three weeks ago in San Jose.
</P>
<P>
   ``This team at times is so perplexing,'' Sampson said. ``It can
play so very well and at other times play to the level of a poor
team.''
</P>
<P>
   The key to the Americans' chances lies in the midfield, and so
far this year the team has performed remarkably well under
Sampson's 3-6-1 configuration, which was installed for the Austria
match for the first time (the team is 2-0-2 with that alignment).
</P>
<P>
   Brian Maisonneuve, a World Cup rookie who is known for his
tenacious defensive play, and Claudio Reyna, the elegant, veteran
playmaker, constitute the ``spine'' of the midfield corps, and much
of the U.S. team's play will be dictated by these two players.
</P>
<P>
   But no matter how well the team defends and sets up the attack,
it is not going to go very far if it can't score. And the forwards'
recent inability to put the ball in the back of the net has been a
worrisome problem. Eric Wynalda, who will most likely shoulder the
responsibility of being the lone striker in the 3-6-1, has scored
just one goal in international play this year (10 matches); Brian
McBride, who has shown great potential at times, missed four
excellent scoring chances against Macedonia, and Roy Wegerle is
starting to show fatigue in his 34-year-old legs.
</P>
<P>
   Still, Sampson is not panicking _ yet.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm confident in these individuals,'' he said. ``We have
created dozens of great opportunities. It's just a matter of being
a little more precise, a little more composed in front of the goal.
I'm not going to concern myself too much with that (inability to
score). I would be more concerned if we weren't creating
opportunities.''
</P>
<P>
   That, perhaps, best sums up Sampson's philosophy _ play the game
well and things will fall into place.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think it's more important for us to play well than to get to
the second round,'' he said. ``We're playing more sophisticatedly,
more intelligently, and we're taking more risks. We've made great
strides. But our greatest failure would be if we lose in bad style.
</P>
<P>
   ``I want us to play better. It's not good enough to me just to
get results (wins or draws); I want to do it in style. ... Against
Germany and Yugoslavia, we must prove we can hold the ball under
pressure and create goal-scoring opportunities. Then we will have
shown we have improved.''
</P>
<P>
   Wynalda, about to partake in his third World Cup, thinks the
team is just about there.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're playing some of the best soccer that we've ever
played,'' said the player who has scored more international goals
(32) than any other American man. ``We are ranked No. 11in the
world ... and now it's time to respond. This team knows how to
compete at the highest level, and we need to instill confidence in
the (American) public that `We won't let you down.' We're not the
underdog anymore; we're expected to win. We're capable of doing
something very special.''
</P>
<P>
   Added defender and team captain Thomas Dooley: ``Anything can
happen in soccer. We hope to have a surprise for someone over
there.''
</P>
<P>
   A trip to the second round would be pleasant enough.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; (For use by clients of the New York Times News Service) &QL;  &LR;
</P>
