A0281 &Cx1f; ttd-z
r s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-SOC-WYNALDA-SFCHRON &LR;      06-09 0581
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-SOC-WYNALDA-SFCHRON </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
WYNALDA HAS THE SKILLS TO MAKE HIS POINTS 
</HEADLINE>
   By DAN GIESIN  
 c.1998 San Francisco Chronicle  
<TEXT>
<P>
   In the world's eye, there are two Eric Wynaldas.
</P>
<P>
   One is the brash, young punk who threw a vicious elbow at Czech
midfielder Lubomir Moravcik in a first-round match in the 1990
World Cup and earned instant notoriety _ and lasting infamy _ as
the first U.S. player to be ejected from a World Cup match.
</P>
<P>
   The other is the skillful veteran whose spectacular,
pressure-filled 28-yard free kick arced above and around the Swiss
defensive wall and into the net to secure a 1-1 draw in the
Americans' Cup-opening game in 1994.
</P>
<P>
   Who's it gonna be this time?
</P>
<P>
   ``I want to make a statement in this World Cup,'' Wynalda said.
``This is the World Cup that I have the experience to handle the
pressure. I have the experience where it counts to make this the
World Cup where I play my best soccer, to help my country the best
I can.''
</P>
<P>
   Until recently, that job was to just put the ball in the net _
he has a team-record 32 goals in 100 international matches (to put
that number into perspective, retired Bruce Murray is No. 2 on the
all-time list with 21 goals in 93 games).
</P>
<P>
   But leg and groin injuries over the past year and a half have
limited his effectiveness, and he has scored just once in his past
10 games wearing the U.S. colors.
</P>
<P>
   Although Wynalda doesn't mind setting up others to score goals
(``Sometimes the game plays into my hand that I need to be an
assist guy,'' he said), it's out there on the point where he would
love to show the world his skills. And his coach, Steve Sampson,
believes the time is ripe.
</P>
<P>
   ``Eric Wynalda wants to make a statement in this World Cup,''
Sampson said. ``And I expect him to be prepared, mentally and
physically, to do so in France.''
</P>
<P>
   But Sampson has installed a new on-field look for his team,
switching from the traditional four defenders-four midfielders-two
forwards alignment to a 3-6-1 configuration, and that means only
one player is the go-to guy.
</P>
<P>
   Unfortunately for Wynalda, there are three candidates for the
job _ himself, Brian McBride and Roy Wegerle. If anybody other than
Sampson knows who that man will be next Monday, when the U.S. team
opens World Cup play against Germany, they aren't talking.
</P>
<P>
   ``We all bring different things to the table,'' Wynalda said.
``Roy can hold the ball well, and he has the legs to open up and
stretch the defense. I'm the same way, but on the wings. Brian's
main attribute is what he does in the air. The starting forward job
is up for grabs, and each of us is working hard to get it.''
</P>
<P>
   No one more than Wynalda. Regarded sometimes as recalcitrant and
hard to work with (just ask erstwhile Clash coach Laurie Calloway,
whose battles with his forward were well known), Wynalda said
that's baloney, that he is just too intense and focused in his
playing style and attitude toward the game to accept anything less.
</P>
<P>
   ``I've been labeled as a bad boy, and I don't think that's
necessarily true,'' he said. ``I'm a very competitive player, and
pretty fierce on the field, and that can be misconstrued. If you
play against me, you might say that. But if you meet me off the
field, you wouldn't say that.''
</P>
<P>
   Which persona Eric Wynalda takes on in France remains to be
seen. But he already has an idea.
</P>
<P>
   ``I know,'' he said authoritatively, ``what's expected of me.''
</P>
<P>
   &UR; (For use by clients of the New York Times News Service) &QL;  &LR;
</P>
</TEXT>
