<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-NIGERIA-OPPOSITION-1STLD-WRITETHRU-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
NIGERIAN OPPOSITION LEADERS CALL FOR MILITARY TO STEP ASIDE
</HEADLINE>
  
 (Subs for updating, re-editing throughout)   (sw) 
 By ELAINE SCIOLINO   
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ After the death of Nigeria's military ruler, Gen.
Sani Abacha, the daughter of Moshood Abiola, the opposition leader
who was imprisoned after being elected president in 1993, called on
Monday for the military to step aside and for her father's
immediate release.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's the end of an era, and I hope, the end of military
rule,'' said Hafsat Abiola, his 23-year-old Harvard-educated
daughter who has worked with other opposition figures to protest
military rule in Nigeria.
</P>
<P>
   But Ms. Abiola, who works for the Special Olympics and lives in
suburban Maryland with 5 of her 18 siblings, said she is concerned
about her father's welfare.
</P>
<P>
   ``Abacha wanted to use my father as a hostage, to keep him close
by so that if he was ever attacked he'd attack my Dad,'' she said
in a telephone interview.
</P>
<P>
   Asked whether she thought her father should take over the reins
of power in Nigeria now that Abacha is dead, she replied, ``I just
want my father released. I am very concerned about his safety.''
</P>
<P>
   Other Nigerian opposition leaders called for Abiola to be
installed as president of a transitional government in Nigeria.
</P>
<P>
   Wole Soyinka, the exiled Nigerian playwright, told reporters in
Jerusalem on Monday, ``There's only one choice for Nigeria _ that's
a democratic option. And the structure is there. The
president-elect is waiting.''
</P>
<P>
   Soyinka added that the general's death presented an opportunity
for the military to step aside.
</P>
<P>
   ``The people were sick of military dictatorship,'' he said. ``So
it's up to the military to recognize this _ and up to the
international community to say that we're sick and tired of the
degeneration of a potentially great society.''
</P>
<P>
   Until that happens, other countries should increase diplomatic
pressure and economic sanctions on the military government, Soyinka
said.
</P>
<P>
   Soyinka, who won the Nobel prize for literature in 1986, fled
Nigeria in 1994. He was charged in absentia with treason last March
in connection with bomb attacks aimed mostly at the military, which
left two people dead and about 60 people wounded.
</P>
<P>
   The view that it was time for the military to step aside was
echoed by the son of Ken Saro-Wiwa, a human rights activist and
writer who was executed by the Nigerian government. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   ``This is an opportunity for the opposition and an opportunity
for democracy to be restored to Nigeria, though how that actually
happens is anybody's guess,'' Ken Wiwa told Britain's Channel Four
television news.  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   ``One hopes that democracy will have a chance to establish
itself,'' said Wiwa, whose father was hanged in 1995 with eight
others.
</P>
<P>
   But he said it was unclear whether Abiola was well enough to
assume power.
</P>
<P>
   ``We are really not sure how healthy and fit Moshood Abiola
is.'' Wiwa said. ``Reports say he himself is close to death.''
</P>
<P>
   Ms. Abiola said that she was not ready to embrace the call of
other opposition leaders like Soyinka for her father to assume the
leadership of the country.
</P>
<P>
   ``We know he is not doing very well and have to attend to his
medical needs first,'' she said. She said that he suffered from
high blood pressure, a pinched nerve and had trouble moving his
left leg.
</P>
<P>
   The family has not seen her father in well over a year. When
they saw him in January 1995, ``he had been tussled, beaten around
and looked very disheveled,'' she said.
</P>
<P>
   But Ms. Abiola said that her father was the only person who can
bring democracy to Nigeria.
</P>
<P>
   ``The only person who can move the country beyond the point
where it is peaceful and democratic is my father,'' Ms. Abiola
said. ``He is the only person chosen by the people to do so.''
</P>
<P>
   Abiola has been in jail since mid-1994, after he was charged
with treason by a federal high court in Abuja for declaring himself
president. He was chosen by popular vote in election that was
annulled by the military.
</P>
<P>
   One of his three wives, Kudirat Abiola, Ms. Abiola's mother, was
killed two years ago while working to free her husband from prison,
in what her daughter called a political execution.
</P>
<P>
   Ms. Abiola, who has spent nearly a third of her life in the
United States, said she was ready to go home if she could feel safe
again. ``I want to be able to welcome my father back to our
house,'' she said.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
