<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BANK09-AZR </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
BANK MERGER LIKELY TO BE MOST PAINFUL IN ARIZONA 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by N.Y. Times News Service clients)  
 BY CATHERINE REAGOR and CRAIG ANDERSON  
 c.1998 The Arizona Republic  
<TEXT>
<P>
   The impact of the proposed $34 billion merger of Wells Fargo and
Norwest banks is likely to be felt the most in Arizona, where the
two banks have the greatest overlap.
</P>
<P>
   San Francisco-based Wells Fargo and Minneapolis-based Norwest
said Monday they plan to combine operations and form the nation's
seventh-largest bank. It will have almost $191 billion in assets,
more than 90,000 employees, about 20 million customers and 5,777
financial-services outlets worldwide. The companies hope to have
the deal settled by this fall.
</P>
<P>
   Wells Fargo is the third-largest bank in Arizona and Norwest is
fourth. After the merger, the new bank could be the second-largest
in the state. It will keep the Wells Fargo name. The overlap
resulting from the merger is likely to lead to branch closures and
layoffs.
</P>
<P>
   ``The landscape of Arizona banking is definitely changing. We'll
just have to see how it works out for the consumer,'' said Marilyn
Seymann, president of M One Inc., a Phoenix bank consulting firm.
</P>
<P>
   Two years ago, Wells Fargo undertook an $11.3 billion takeover
of First Interstate Bank, based in Los Angeles. Wells Fargo is
still digesting that deal.
</P>
<P>
   Wells Fargo closed hundreds of branches and eliminated 7,000
jobs. It also lost customer deposits, bounced good checks and
incorrectly withdrew money from some accounts and deposited it in
others.
</P>
<P>
   Paul Hazen, chairman of Wells Fargo, said he expects the merger
with Norwest to go much more smoothly than with First Interstate
because the partners will spend three years integrating their
operations, paying special attention to the computer systems.
</P>
<P>
   ``Customers usually take a back seat in these megamergers,''
Seymann said. ``The concern is more for the shareholders.''
</P>
<P>
   One Phoenix Norwest customer, who had heard about the problems
with Wells Fargo's buyout of First Interstate, is concerned.
</P>
<P>
   When asked about the deal in front of her Norwest branch at 22nd
Street and Camelback Road on Monday, Debbie Mortensen, a 10-year
Norwest customer, said, ``Oh, no. I've heard a lot of bad things
about Wells Fargo.'' She doesn't know if she will remain a customer
after the merger.
</P>
<P>
   Not all customers were disappointed, though. Braxton Glass, who
has been a Wells Fargo customer since it bought out First
Interstate, initially was apprehensive.
</P>
<P>
   But, he was pleasantly surprised with Wells Fargo because of its
Internet banking, which he said has made his life easier.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think it (Wells Fargo) is an improvement over First
Interstate,'' Glass said.
</P>
<P>
   The two banks have totally different operating styles.
</P>
<P>
   Norwest is known as a community bank with a very local approach
that revolves around traditional branches. It has just begun to
expand into Internet and grocery store banking.
</P>
<P>
   Wells Fargo was an early leader in grocery store and Internet
banking, moving its focus away from traditional branch banking. It
is also known for having a tough corporate culture.
</P>
<P>
   Jon Campbell, president and chief executive of Norwest's Arizona
Bank, said the company's customer service culture will be part of
the new bank's strategy.
</P>
<P>
   Kathleen Lucier, Wells Fargo's Arizona senior executive, said
the merger will give customers more products and a bigger network
of branches and automated teller machines (ATMs).
</P>
<P>
   The merger may be painful in Arizona. Branches are likely to
close or be sold to competitors and employees are likely to lose
jobs. Wells Fargo and Norwest will have to divest some assets
because both are so large. That means some customer deposits could
be sold to other banks. Regulators will determine in the next few
months how much the banks have to shed.
</P>
<P>
   No details on job losses or branch closings were available
Monday. Wells Fargo has 245 branches and 4,800 employees in
Arizona; Norwest has 85 branches and 2,500 employees.
</P>
<P>
   Although overlap between the two banks is great in Arizona, it
is relatively small nationally.
</P>
<P>
   ``This merger will be small in terms of staff reductions
compared to others,'' said Richard Kovacevich, chairman and chief
executive of Norwest, who will become chief executive and president
of the new bank. Hazen will remain chairman.
</P>
<P>
   Wells Fargo and Norwest expect to save at least $650 million
annually by their third year of operating together.
</P>
<P>
   The new Wells Fargo will be the No. 1 bank in the West for
financial services and No. 1 in the country for mortgages, Internet
services and agricultural lending. It will be No. 2 in small
business lending nationwide and No. 3 for total ATMs. &QL; 
(Catherine Reagor can be reached at 444-8040 or at
catherine.reagor(at)pni.com.) &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
