<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-06-09 01:07 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A0289 &Cx1f; ttc-z
r s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-SOC-KRIKOR-COLUMN-LAD     06-09 0924
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-SOC-KRIKOR-COLUMN-LADN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
SOCCER AWARENESS BRINGS STATE OF BLISS
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By DOUG KRIKORIAN  
 c.1998 Long Beach Press-Telegram  
<TEXT>
<P>
   There was a time in my thrilling life when I blithely would have
ignored the World Cup, dismissing it with a haughty disdain formed
by being weaned in the good U.S. of A. on football, baseball,
basketball and boxing.
</P>
<P>
   Soccer?
</P>
<P>
   Please!
</P>
<P>
   I'd give it roughly the same keen attention I would give, say,
to an audio-visual film on suppositories if I somehow found myself
stuck at a pharmaceutical convention.
</P>
<P>
   It's not that I detested soccer. It was even worse than that. I
was totally indifferent to it. I never watched it, read about it,
talked about it, or thought about it. To me, it was just this weird
sport in which a bunch of guys ran crazily around a field for
tiresomely long periods, kicking a ball back and forth when they
weren't kicking one another's shins for no discernible reason.
</P>
<P>
   All I ever knew about the sport is that its most famous
personality, Pele, matched Muhammad Ali in retirement
announcements.
</P>
<P>
   But such feelings began to change slightly back in 1994 when I
attended several World Cup games at the Rose Bowl, including the
championship match that wound up a scoreless tie between Italy and
Brazil.
</P>
<P>
   Although I understood only the barest rudiments of soccer which
I guess is still the case since I still don't understand how Brazil
wound up victorious against Italy in that farcical overtime
penalty-kick ritual I was impressed with the fans' passionate
devotion, the players' intense competitiveness and the games'
unrelenting drama.
</P>
<P>
   Still, I'm sure I would have continued my lifetime habit of
totally ignoring this far less violent version of American football
except for a most lethal incident I wound up marrying a Brit.
</P>
<P>
   And, if this decision weren't stunning enough to those friends
who couldn't envision a long-time bachelor tied down in connubial
bliss, I actually exchanged vows with a Geordie, an appellation
given to those with strange accents even to other Brits who hail
from the Newcastle area in the north of England.
</P>
<P>
   I had not the faintest idea until I started spending a lot of
time in that vicinity that those who lived there were absolute
soccer zealots, crazed souls who cherished the sport with a fierce
fervor.
</P>
<P>
   I mean, if you think the good burghers in Indiana are stuck on
basketball, their devotion is laughably mild compared to the
fanatical attachment Geordies have for soccer.
</P>
<P>
   The people in that region follow it like a Wall Street broker
does the Dow Jones. I don't care where you go around there
Newcastle, Hartlepool, Middlesborough, Sunderland, etc. they're
rabidly discussing soccer.
</P>
<P>
   And so, your venerable correspondent was forced by marital
obligations to at least have a superficial knowledge of the sport,
if for no other reason than to avoid the social embarrassment at
family gatherings of being an American sportswriter who couldn't
tell you the difference between George Harrison and George Best.
</P>
<P>
   And thus, with a slight twinge of embarrassment, I have a
confession to make I've actually been following the goings-on of
soccer in recent years.
</P>
<P>
   Honestly.
</P>
<P>
   Oh, don't get the wrong impression.
</P>
<P>
   I'm not yet an aficionado of the most popular athletic activity
on the planet.
</P>
<P>
   But I will be intrigued by what unfolds during the next month at
the World Cup proceedings in France because, well, because, well,
because, well, I'm a henpecked husband who feels compelled to give
the impression to my European better half that my sporting
interests extend beyond the boundaries of this country.
</P>
<P>
   I have no idea who will emerge victorious at the 105,000-seat
Saint-Denis in Paris in the championship game on July 12, but I
will brazenly predict right now it will be either Brazil, or
Germany, or Italy, or Argentina, or Uruguay,
</P>
<P>
   or England.
</P>
<P>
   After all, these are the only countries besides Uruguay that
have been able to win the World Cup since its inception in 1930.
</P>
<P>
   Actually, my newfound knowledge of soccer extends even beyond
such trivia!
</P>
<P>
   I know, for instance, that the French organizing committee has
been savagely criticized by the world press for its ticket
apportioning policy, that Brazil is supposed to have a new Pele in
Ronaldo, that Argentina is supposed to have a new Maradona in Ariel
Ortega, that the traditionally dangerous Germany team has too many
guys past 30 to be a serious threat, that the traditionally erratic
England team has too many guys under 30 without enough talent to be
a serious threat, that always-strong Italy has a 23-year-old
superstar goal scorer in Alessandro Del Piero, and that the French
police better be ready for the feared English hooligans.
</P>
<P>
   All I know about the Americans is that they're supposed to be
better I swear I hear such a spiel every four years and that they
probably will lose their opener Monday against Germany and that
they face Iran on June 21 and Yugoslavia on June 25 in the first
round of the competition.
</P>
<P>
   I also know that England figures to breeze in its opener Monday
in Marseilles against Tunisia and that the Brits' best player, Alan
Shearer, lives less than eight miles from where my wife's parents
live, and that I better root for England to ensure continued
household harmony.
</P>
<P>
   Who ever thought that matrimonial imperatives could turn a
soccer-ignorant sportswriter into an observer of the game, albeit
one who still doesn't understand it?
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
