<SLUG> BC-astros </SLUG>
 lede-HNS  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
Astros rough up old friend, top Tigers
<TEXT>
<P>
   First-place tie in NL Central retained as Jones victimized for
five ninth-inning runs
</P>
<P>
   &UR; By JOSEPH DUARTE &LR;  &QL; 
 &UR; c. 1998, Houston Chronicle &LR;  &QL; 
DETROIT _ Earlier this week, Detroit closer Todd Jones called his
bitterness toward the Astros a ``dead'' issue.
</P>
<P>
   Nonetheless, Jones stepped to the mound in the ideal situation
Monday night: bottom of the ninth, one-run game and the chance to
once-and-for-all prove his former employer wrong.
</P>
<P>
   The outcome wasn't exactly what he had in mind.
</P>
<P>
   Jones, who began his career in the Houston organization before
being traded to the Tigers in 1996, surrendered five runs in the
ninth inning as the Astros rallied for a 9-5 victory before a crowd
of 11,767 at Tiger Stadium.
</P>
<P>
   Carl Everett, who went 2-for-5 with four RBIs, put the finishing
touches on the Astros' third straight victory with a two-run double
in the ninth as the Astros kept pace with the Chicago Cubs atop the
National League Central.
</P>
<P>
   Of the former Astros traded in the nine-player swap with Detroit
in 1996, Jones has been the most vocal in expressing his
displeasure with the Houston front office.
</P>
<P>
   ``I just wasn't very good tonight,'' said Jones, who pitched for
the Astros from 1993-96. ``They got me. I'm sure there is a lot of
satisfaction in that clubhouse. Stuff like this defines you. I'll
just go out and do my job if the same situation arises tomorrow.''
</P>
<P>
   The come-from-behind victory was the Astros' third this season
in their last at-bat. And it came against Jones, who had allowed
runs in only four of 22 relief appearances this season and had
converted nine of 10 previous save opportunities.
</P>
<P>
   There was little he could do right against the Astros, who
overcame a 5-3 deficit with six runs over the final three innings.
That the decisive rally came off Jones (0-2) was no big deal to the
Astros.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think there is something extra in this series because so
many guys for the Tigers have been with us and vice versa, yet I
don't think anybody in our locker room is going to say it sure was
nice to beat Todd Jones,'' said Astros manager Larry Dierker.
``They're saying it's nice to be even with the Cubs. We're not
thinking about any of that stuff. We're just trying to win games
and stay in first place.''
</P>
<P>
   The Astros actually began their comeback in the seventh when
Craig Biggio, who had three hits in the game, scored on a passed
ball to cut the Tigers' lead to 5-4.
</P>
<P>
   Two innings later, Biggio delivered a one-out single through the
hole at shortstop and stole second before Bill Spiers walked. Derek
Bell pushed across the tying run with a double to right field.
</P>
<P>
   Jones intentionally walked Jeff Bagwell, and Moises Alou put the
Astros on top 6-5 with a sacrifice fly to center field, scoring
Spiers. Everett, who also hit his third home run of the season in
the fourth inning, cleared the bases with a two-run double and
scored on the play when Detroit catcher Paul Bako's throw to third
sailed into left field.
</P>
<P>
   ``I love being up at the plate with the bases loaded,'' said
Everett, so excited that he must have forgotten there were only two
on when he batted in the ninth. ``The pressure is all on the
pitcher. He made a mistake, and I took advantage of it.''
</P>
<P>
   The Astros overcame a shaky outing by righthander Sean Bergman,
whose 4-inning stint was his shortest in more than a month. Bergman
allowed four runs and six hits and walked three while struggling to
find his control. He had gone at least six innings in his previous
five starts.
</P>
<P>
   ``I was fighting with myself to find location,'' Bergman said.
``Going 4 innings was definitely not what I wanted to do. I wanted
to go out and pitch seven or eight innings.''
</P>
<P>
   Astros relievers Mike Magnante, Doug Henry and Billy Wagner
combined to hold the Tigers to one run and three hits over the
final 4 innings. Henry (4-2) picked up the victory with 1 innings
of scoreless relief.
</P>
<P>
   ``That was big. After the last three outings I've had, it's nice
to go out and pitch like I needed to,'' Henry said. ``One thing the
bullpen always needs to remember is that in a close game, this team
can erupt for four or five runs at any time. We have to keep it
close and not let the lead get any farther away.''
</P>
<P>
   When the Astros needed a big inning, they got it. Dierker, who
saw his team collect 14 hits for the night, noted the Astros'
patience at the plate against Jones in the ninth, which forced the
righthander to work deep into the count on several occasions.
</P>
<P>
   ``Our guys are tough,'' Dierker said. ``If you look at the
statistics, the one thing that's sort of a hidden asset is our
selectiveness at the plate. We have a lot of hitters that make
pitchers work.''
</P>
<P>
   The Astros were doing a lot of work of their own early on as
holding a lead became a chore. There were four lead changes during
the first four innings before the Tigers took a 5-3 lead in the
sixth.
</P>
<P>
   Houston took a 3-2 lead off Detroit rookie righthander Seth
Greisinger in the fourth when Alou singled and Everett sent a line
drive into the left-field stands for his third home run of the
season.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
