</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-HKN-NHLCOL-LADN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
VIEWERS TUNE OUT STANLEY CUP
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By JARRE FEES  
 c.1998 Los Angeles Daily News  
<TEXT>
<P>
   In a presidential election year, it would be fitting that the
Washington Capitals made the Stanley Cup Finals.
</P>
<P>
   But there is no presidential election. There's only a
presidential scandal. So maybe it's appropriate for Ron Wilson, the
coach of the U.S. Olympic team, which had scandals of its own in
Nagano, to be coaching the team that somehow stumbled into the NHL
championship round.
</P>
<P>
   And just as with the Clinton scandals, a lot of people are
already bored.
</P>
<P>
   Fox's weekend NHL playoff ratings through May 31 clocked in at
1.8, down 14 percent from last year. But last year there was a
reason to watch. Fans saw Detroit and Philadelphia in the final
series. Before that, it was Eric Lindros and the Flyers taking on
Wayne Gretzky, Mark Messier and the New York Rangers in the Eastern
Conference finals.
</P>
<P>
   This year it was Washington vs. Buffalo, and ESPN's numbers were
down 23 percent through May 27, from 1.3 to 1.0. And ESPN2's 24 NHL
playoff telecasts averaged a pathetic 0.5 nationally.
</P>
<P>
   On Sunday May 31, the Detroit-Dallas game on Fox posted national
ratings of 2.2 with a 6 share, meaning just six percent of people
who had their televisions on were watching the hockey playoffs.
This was better than NBC did with the French Open (1.9 rating with
a 5 share) but not as good as what ABC did with the PGA Memorial
Tournament (3.0 with an 8 share).
</P>
<P>
   Those Sunday ratings were for the same time slot: 11 a.m. to 2
p.m. PST. Compared to everything else that weekend, Fox's NHL
number is only slightly better than what CBS got for pro bowling on
May 30 from 2-3 p.m. PST (a 1.8 rating with a 5 share).
</P>
<P>
   Wilson might have unwittingly summed up the ratings problem when
he talked about the Capitals' postseason pairings.
</P>
<P>
   ``No disrespect to the teams that we played, but we had a draw
that you dream about before the season,'' Wilson said. ``We didn't
have to face Philadelphia, New Jersey or Pittsburgh, the three
teams that really have given the Caps trouble over the years. I
think that helped.''
</P>
<P>
   It certainly helped the Capitals, but what's good for the Caps
might have poisoned the playoff ratings.
</P>
<P>
   The Flyers, Devils and Penguins were the top three seeded teams
in the Eastern Conference. More important for the ratings, Philly
and Pittsburgh lay respective claim to Eric Lindros and Jaromir
Jagr, two good reasons to watch the playoffs. But the fourth-seeded
Capitals faced Boston, Ottawa and Buffalo. And aside from curious
fans who tuned in to see if Buffalo's Dominik Hasek could win this
year's version of hockey's triple crown (an Olympic gold medal, the
Hart trophy for MVP and a Stanley Cup), nobody cared.
</P>
<P>
   And now it's the accidental playoff team vs. the defending
Stanley Cup champions. There's interest in Detroit, where buildings
and statues are draped in red and white. And there's interest from
die-hard fans nationwide, those of us who can't quit no matter how
bad it gets.
</P>
<P>
   But new fans have flown, shooed away by high ticket prices, a
too-rapid expansion resulting in mediocre teams and the NHL's
decision to broadcast February's Olympic games long after most
would-be fans were asleep.
</P>
<P>
   The NHL is investing in new league-sponsored rinks nationwide to
attract new fans to the game, but that investment won't pay off for
years. Television won't attract new fans; they must first be
introduced to a live game.
</P>
<P>
   In an ESPN interview during intermission at a Caps-Sabres game
last week, new Caps fan President Clinton said, ``No offense to
ESPN, but this is the greatest game live.''
</P>
<P>
   Any hockey fan could've told him that. Is anyone telling the
NHL?
</P>
<P>
   __ Sore loser?: Dallas Stars defenseman Sergei Zubov was
arrested Sunday morning and charged with assaulting his wife,
according to police in Coppell, Texas.
</P>
<P>
   Zubov, 27, was charged with aggravated assault and family
violence, a second-degree felony. If convicted, he faces between
two and 20 years in prison and a $10,000 fine. The alleged assault
occurred the day after the Stars were eliminated in the Western
Conference finals by Detroit.
</P>
<P>
   Police went to Zubov's house after someone called 911 and then
hung up at 3:05 a.m. on Sunday. An initial investigation indicated
Zubov had brandished a kitchen knife during the assault. Police
wouldn't say if Zubov's wife, Irina, was injured.
</P>
<P>
   Zubov was the NHL's third-leading scorer among defensemen this
season with 10 goals and 47 assists in 73 games. He had four goals
and five assists in 17 playoff games, behind only Mike Modano in
team scoring.
</P>
<P>
   Zubov was released Sunday morning after posting a $5,000 bond.
</P>
<P>
   __ Goalie quiz: Who was Dallas goaltender Ed Belfour's backup in
Chicago during the 1991-92 season? (Answer: Dominik Hasek.)
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-06-09-98 0113EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
