<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BBA-RANGERS-TEX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
CEDENO LEADS RANGERS TO VICTORY
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By JOHNNY PAUL 
c.1998 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   DENVER _ Reserve infielder Domingo Cedeno became a casualty of
overexposure during 1997.
</P>
<P>
   Injuries to second baseman Mark McLemore and infielder Bill
Ripken and the unacceptable performance of shortstop Benji Gil
forced Cedeno into a role not suited best for him.
</P>
<P>
   ``He's not a guy you want to play 140 games,'' Texas Rangers
manager Johnny Oates said. ``Now, he's just one of the guys.''
</P>
<P>
   Cedeno, succeeding in his role as ``one of the guys,'' can
emerge as ``the'' guy on occasion. That occurred during the
Rangers' 3-1 victory Monday night against the Colorado Rockies at
Coors Field.
</P>
<P>
   Cedeno, going 3-for-4, drove in all of the Rangers' runs and hit
what proved to be the game-winning, eighth-inning home run off
Rockies right-hander Pedro Astacio (4-8).
</P>
<P>
   Cedeno, who turned on a first-pitch fastball from Astacio, sent
it 398 feet and deposited it into the right-field stands.
</P>
<P>
   ``Mingy was the offensive and defensive star of the game,''
Oates said.
</P>
<P>
   Cedeno's offensive performance would be all the firepower needed
by right-hander Aaron Sele (9-3), who joined Atlanta's Greg Maddux
as the major leagues' only nine-game winners.
</P>
<P>
   Sele, who recorded six strikeouts in eight innings, refused to
let the reputation of Coors Field become his opponent.
</P>
<P>
   ``I didn't change the way I pitch,'' said Sele, who allowed only
one run on five singles and four walks. ``You really have to stay
aggressive. You just have to keep the ball down and move it in and
out. I seemed to miss down more than I missed up.''
</P>
<P>
   Rangers closer John Wetteland, who last year failed to protect
two three-run leads at Coors Field, found himself in a little
trouble after allowing a one-out, ninth-inning single to right
fielder Dante Bichette.
</P>
<P>
   First baseman Todd Helton, the next batter, worked the count
full, but Wetteland retired the rookie on strikes with a 3-2
fastball and induced a game-ending line drive from pinch-hitter
Jeff Reed for the final out.
</P>
<P>
   Cedeno, who gave Wetteland an extra run to work with after his
ninth-inning single scored first baseman Will Clark with the
Rangers' final run, can seemingly do no wrong right now.
</P>
<P>
   Cedeno, making his seventh consecutive start since shortstop
Kevin Elster sustained an injury to his left shoulder eight days
ago on the artificial turf of Tampa Bay's Tropicana Field, is
hitting .407 (11-for-27) with two home runs and eight runs batted
in during that stretch.
</P>
<P>
   Cedeno would be Astacio's primary antagonist.
</P>
<P>
   Astacio entered this appearance 4-7 with a 7.26 earned-run
average, but the struggling right-hander experienced his best
performance this season in his previous start Wednesday against the
Arizona Diamondbacks.
</P>
<P>
   Astacio did not figure in the decision, but he allowed only two
runs on six hits and one walk and recorded a season-best nine
strikeouts in 72/3 innings.
</P>
<P>
   The Rangers witnessed a similar display from Astacio, who
surrendered only one hit _ a double by none other than Sele _
during the first four innings.
</P>
<P>
   The Rangers finally tagged Astacio for a run in the fifth inning
to tie the score, but wasted their opportunity for a bigger inning.
Catcher Ivan Rodriguez began the inning with a double to
left-center field and scored on the ensuing bloop single by Cedeno.
Third baseman Fernando Tatis drew a walk, which brought Sele to the
plate.
</P>
<P>
   The Rockies expected the attempted sacrifice bunt and defensed
it with the ``wheel,'' where both the first and third basemen
charge down the lines to field the bunt and the middle infielders
cover first and third base.
</P>
<P>
   Sele bunted the ball to Astacio, who wheeled and delivered an
accurate throw to shortstop Neifi Perez to retire Cedeno at third
base. Astacio then retired center fielder Tom Goodwin on strikes
for his fifth strikeout through five innings, and induced an
inning-ending ground ball from second baseman Luis Alicea.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
