<HEADLINE>
ARMY IS REDESIGNING DIVISION, AIDE SAYS 
</HEADLINE>
  (sw) 
 By DAVID STOUT   
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ Without the Soviet Union to plan a war against, the
Army has redesigned its basic combat division and will announce its
new makeup on Tuesday, a congressional aide said on Monday night.
</P>
<P>
   The aide, speaking on the condition that he not be named, said
the Army had decided on a modest makeover, not a wholesale
retooling as some military experts had hoped.
</P>
<P>
   Instead of the old troop strength of 18,000, the new division
will have just under 16,000 men, the aide said. The new division
will have fewer tanks and fewer Bradley Fighting Vehicles to carry
troops, but it will have more surveillance equipment and more
intelligence officers.
</P>
<P>
   The Washington Post, which reported on the Army's forthcoming
announcement in Tuesday's issues, quoted an Army colonel as saying,
``In doing this redesign, we conducted probably the most intense
and thorough look that the Army has ever gone through.''
</P>
<P>
   Despite the Army's position that the retooled division will be a
far better fighting force for the brushfire wars and rogue despots
the United States now has to worry about, some lawmakers are sure
to greet the announcement with skepticism, the congressional aide
said tonight.
</P>
<P>
   ``The Army missed an opportunity to transform its force
structure and gain some efficiencies,'' said the aide, who has
followed military affairs for years.
</P>
<P>
   Asked what the new Army division should look like, he replied,
``smaller, more mobile, more lethal _ less logistically intense.''
By that last phrase, he said he meant even fewer heavy vehicles
carrying heavy artillery. The Army's redesign of its division,
which is the building block for combat, has been under way for
several years.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-06-09-98 0121EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
