<SLUG> BC-BKN-NBA </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
JAZZ FIGHTING TO REGAIN A LITTLE RESPECT
</HEADLINE>
 FINALS-TEX (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By RICHIE WHITT 
c.1998 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   CHICAGO _ A week ago, the Utah Jazz was fighting for an NBA
Championship.
</P>
<P>
   Now _ in the wake of Sunday's humiliating loss to the Chicago
Bulls _ the Jazz is suddenly fighting for respect.
</P>
<P>
   ``The sun came up and today's another day,'' Jazz point guard
John Stockton said Monday. ``That game's behind us and we're headed
back to the drawing board.''
</P>
<P>
   Despite the 96-54 loss in Game 3 in which the Jazz set records
for worst margin of defeat and fewest points in a game, there is
not only precedence _ but a trend _ to suggest the Jazz can bounce
back in tomorrow night's Game 4 at the United Center. Consider: The
previous four teams to lose a Finals game by at least 33 points
regrouped to win the next game, including the Portland Trail
Blazers against the Bulls in 1992.
</P>
<P>
   ``I am pretty sure that they want to redeem themselves,''
Michael Jordan said of the Jazz. ``It was a very embarrassing
moment for them. We expect a great effort from them, so this is no
time to start feeling smug about ourselves.''
</P>
<P>
   Feeling smug, disinterested or hung over, Bulls forward Dennis
Rodman epitomized Chicago's comfort level by choosing not to attend
Monday's practice. The Jazz, meanwhile, used the day to begin the
chore of turning psychological baggage into motivation.
</P>
<P>
   ``It was nothing to lose sleep over,'' Jazz center Greg Ostertag
said. ``We had a bad game and we got our butts kicked. Doesn't mean
the series is over.''
</P>
<P>
   Jazz coach Jerry Sloan said jokingly: ``We watched the film and
it was very exciting. Like watching cartoons.''
</P>
<P>
   With the Bulls smelling blood only two wins from their sixth
title in eight years, the Jazz must find a way to win one of the
next two games and send the series back to Salt Lake City. No team
has ever swept the three middle games of the 2-3-2 format, but
neither has a team rallied from 2-1 down in the past 13 years.
Moreover, no team has ever come back from 3-1 down to win the
Finals.
</P>
<P>
   ``We can't worry about all that stuff,'' Karl Malone said. ``The
way we played, we just need to worry about the way we come out. If
we play the same, we'll get killed again.''
</P>
<P>
   Problem is, unlike the versatile and interchangeable Bulls, the
Jazz is not quick to make major adjustments. The Jazz base its
chances on Malone, the pick-and-roll and a deep bench. After the
Game 2 loss, for example, Sloan's only move was to insert Ostertag
at center for Greg Foster.
</P>
<P>
   Sloan realizes, however, his team must find a way to combat and
attack Chicago's aggressive defense, which has used Scottie Pippen
as a floating free safety to keep Utah from setting up the
pick-and-roll.
</P>
<P>
   ``With the defense they're playing,'' Sloan said, ``they've kind
of got us in a trick box.''
</P>
<P>
   To avoid going back to Utah in a wooden box, the Jazz will try
using revenge and history to regroup.
</P>
<P>
   Players and coaches didn't like the way Chicago's reserves ran
up the score in Sunday's fourth quarter, shooting _ and making _
four 3-pointers after the lead had swelled to 34.
</P>
<P>
   ``Yeah, they were having fun,'' Malone said. ``But over here on
our side, our coach would have a fit if we did that.''
</P>
<P>
   The Jazz also has experience in rallying from a lopsided defeat.
The Jazz shot 28 percent and scored a then-playoff record 62 points
in a 21-point loss to the San Antonio Spurs in Game 3 of the
Western Conference semifinals on May 9. The next night, Malone made
his first eight shots and scored 35 points as Utah won by 11 to
take a 3-1 series lead.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's only 2-1,'' Malone reminded. ``It was a bad game, but
it's gone. And it only counts as one. I expect us to be ready for
the next game.''
</P>
<P>
   Recent NBA Finals history also likes Utah's chances. In '92,
Portland dropped Game 1 by 33, only to recover and win Game 2 by 11
in overtime. The '82 Lakers, '84 Celtics and '85 Lakers all lost
games by at least 33 before rallying to win the next game in the
series.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
