<SLUG> BC-BKN-FINALS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
RODMAN FOLLOWS STERLING EFFORT BY FAILING TO SHOW FOR PRACTICE
</HEADLINE>
 NOTES-TEX (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By RICHIE WHITT 
c.1998 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   CHICAGO _ Dennis Rodman turned Karl Malone into a no-show Sunday
night. Monday, Rodman become one himself.
</P>
<P>
   On the heels of shutting down the Utah Jazz's leading scorer
over the final 39 minutes of Chicago's 96-54 victory, Rodman missed
Chicago's practice at the United Center.
</P>
<P>
   ``He's not here,'' Bulls coach Phil Jackson said. ``I think
something happened between the game last night and this morning. He
called at practice and said he got up late, his alarm clock didn't
work or something.''
</P>
<P>
   While the Bulls scratch their heads in frustration over the
timing of Rodman's absence, they admit they are by now used to it.
So much so, in fact, that Jackson said Rodman likely wouldn't be
fined or punished.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't think punishment is necessary,'' Jackson said. ``He
just says `Fine, punish me. I don't care.' There's some dysfunction
there, but he's a very functional player.''
</P>
<P>
   Said teammate Scottie Pippen, ``We are used to it. He'll show up
\Rtoday\S with some lame excuse. But we've always let Dennis have
his way.''
</P>
<P>
   That philosophy, however, is reaching all-time leniency during
the Finals.
</P>
<P>
   Rodman _ sporting a hairdo featuring black-and-Rodzilla-green
splotches _ routinely shows up for games an hour before tipoff
despite a mandatory 90-minute reporting time for other players.
During pregame introductions and the first minutes of the game,
Rodman remains in the locker room, staying loose until Jackson nods
for a security guard to summon him into the game. And after Game 1
of the Finals, Rodman jetted to Las Vegas for a night of partying
and gambling with Jackson's consent.
</P>
<P>
   ``Dennis is going to be Dennis,'' Michael Jordan said. ``We just
need him to be ready and focused when the game arrives.''
</P>
<P>
   So far, he has done that. Guarded by Rodman, Malone went 0-of-4
in the second half of Game 2 and missed three of five shots in the
final 39 minutes of Game 3 after a 6-of-6 start.
</P>
<P>
   ``He's doing a great job,'' Jackson said of Rodman. ``He's
really kind of disrupting Karl's flow and that's as key for us as
anything else.'' RUNNING OF THE BULLS
</P>
<P>
   Maybe Malone will get reserve Jud Buechler's name correct after
the Bulls' reserve made two fourth-quarter 3-pointers in Game 3.
Malone has been calling Buechler ``Jed'' the entire series.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't know,'' Buechler said, ``I'm just glad he's trying to
talk about me at all.'' ALL THAT JAZZ
</P>
<P>
   The ironic part of coach Jerry Sloan's lifestyle change in the
wake of wife Bobbye's battle against breast cancer? Instead of
staying out ruining his health by drinking and smoking cigarettes,
Sloan now accompanies his wife out to clog his arteries by eating
nachos and ice cream. JORDAN WATCH
</P>
<P>
   Jordan continues to take a wait-and-see approach toward coming
back next season. He will, however, play in Texas at least one more
time. Jordan and teammate Ron Harper are committed to playing in a
charity game June 22 at Southwest Texas State in San Marcos. The
game, organized by 10-year veteran NFL receiver Eric Martin, also
is scheduled to include Mavericks Michael Finley, Robert Pack and
Erick Strickland. INSIDE THE NUMBERS
</P>
<P>
   People on the waiting list for Bulls' season tickets: 23,000.
</P>
<P>
   Karl Malone's times to score more than 23 points in nine Finals
games against Chicago: 1.
</P>
<P>
   Utah's turnovers in Game 3: 26, another Finals record. THE
FINALS SCENE
</P>
<P>
   Pearl Jam lead singer Eddie Vedder performed the national anthem
before Game 3. Movie critic Gene Siskel and controversial talk-show
host Jerry Springer were spotted in court-side seats. ... The
Mavericks will be spared playing in Mexico City next season. That
duty will belong to the Spurs and Clippers. The Mavericks lost to
the Rockets before a sellout of more than 20,000 in Mexico City in
December. ... The Bulls claim Jazz fans threw coins at them as they
left the floor at halftime of Game 2. After their Game 3 implosion,
the Jazz would welcome any sort of change. ... Buzz around Chicago
is not only about the Bulls, but also the rise of 6-foot-10 German
Dirk Nowitzki in the June 24 draft. Nowitzki, only 19, has scouts
salivating with his point-guard skills and power forward body. Most
commonly heard rumor: The Mavericks, owners of the sixth pick, are
touting Saint Louis guard Larry Hughes as a smokescreen in order to
get their hands on Nowitzki. He is considered the best German
prospect since Detlef Schrempf, but isn't he also the only one
since Schrempf? HE SAID IT
</P>
<P>
   ``They could suit up Helen Keller and win at this point. They're
that good.'' _ Nets All-Star forward Jayson Williams on the Bulls.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
