<SLUG> BC-ADVERTISING-NOTES-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
DECISIONS REACHED IN ACCOUNT REVIEWS 
</HEADLINE>
  (sw) 
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   Three advertisers have named agencies to handle accounts.
</P>
<P>
   AMF Bowling Inc. in Richmond chose Richards Group in Dallas for
its account, with billings of about $10 million to $15 million. The
account had been handled by Mumford Marketing in Richmond, which
will continue to handle promotional projects. A monthlong review
had been narrowed to Richards and Carmichael Lynch in Minneapolis,
a unit of the Interpublic Group of Companies.
</P>
<P>
   Wyndham Resorts in Dallas, part of Wyndham Hotels and Resorts,
selected Harris Drury Cohen in Fort Lauderdale, Fla., as the first
agency to handle its account. Billings were estimated at $10
million. The two-month review had been narrowed to Harris Drury and
three other finalists: Richards Group, which continues to handle
the Wyndham Hotels account; Yesawich, Pepperdine &AMP; Brown in
Orlando, Fla., and the Zimmerman Agency in Tallahassee, Fla.
</P>
<P>
   The Andrew Jergens Co. in Cincinnati, a unit of the Kao Corp.,
decided to keep Bozell Worldwide in New York, part of True North
Communications, as the creative agency for Curel moisturizing
lotion. Though billings were not disclosed, trade publications
estimated them at $10 million. Jergens bought Curel last month from
Bausch &AMP; Lomb, which had used Bozell to handle the brand's creative
duties since 1994.
</P>
<P>
   Top executives at Siegel &AMP; Gale, the corporate identity company
in New York, have agreed to buy the company from Saatchi &AMP; Saatchi
PLC for $33.8 million in cash.
</P>
<P>
   ``After 13 successful years as part of the Saatchi &AMP; Saatchi
group of companies, now is the right time for Siegel &AMP; Gale to
become independent again,'' said Alan Siegel, chairman and chief
executive at Siegel &AMP; Gale, which has 275 employees and revenue of
$33.6 million from clients like AT&AMP;T, American Express and IBM.
Siegel, 59, will continue in his posts. Scott Lerman, 39, managing
director, becomes president, succeeding Kenneth Morris, 53, who
will leave to become chairman and chief executive at Lightbulb
Press, a publishing company in New York.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
