<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BKN-VECSEY-SPI </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
BULLS BUILDING CASE FOR ANOTHER TITLE 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By LAURA VECSEY  
 c.1998 Seattle Post-Intelligencer  
<TEXT>
<P>
   SEATTLE _ Michael Jordan and his Bulls don't get it.
</P>
<P>
   Blowing out the Jazz like that. Making a mockery out of the
hardest-working, most efficient squad in the NBA.
</P>
<P>
   All of that Jud Buechler, Randy Brown and Bill Wennington
romping and running up the score in the fourth quarter of the
Bulls' crushing 96-54 victory in Game 3 at the United Center.
</P>
<P>
   All with Jordan and Scottie Pippen on the bench, giggling.
</P>
<P>
   What the Bulls did to the Jazz Sunday makes you think the Bulls
don't understand: The world was ready for their fall.
</P>
<P>
   In fact, Jordan, Pippen and coach Phil Jackson totally seasoned
us for that. All year, the mainstays in the five-time champion
Bulls have bullhorned a single message: ``We're done. It's over.''
</P>
<P>
   Cite whatever factor you want. There were so many signaling the
end.
</P>
<P>
   The Dennis Rodman Insanity Scenario. The Pippen ``Trade Me''
Impasse. The Jackson ``I Won't Be Back'' Action. The Jordan Bet
Hedging, since if Jackson's not back, forget about the greatest
player in the galaxy doing his caped crusader routine any longer in
the Windy City.
</P>
<P>
   Underlying all the soap opera sub-plots is the power struggle by
Bulls owner Jerry Reinsdorf and general manager Jerry Krause
seeking to glom control and glory of a franchise that is all thanks
to the uniqueness of Jordan and Co.
</P>
<P>
   But what if this is the time and place for the tune of doom to
change? What if the tone of these Finals was set by the Bulls' Game
2 win in Salt Lake City and then amplified by the Game 3 whipping?
</P>
<P>
   If the Bulls are champs again, especially with such ease as a
42-point slaughter like Sunday, maybe there is wiggle room for
another shot at it all. Maybe it won't be impossible to sign up
Jordan, Pippen and Jackson for another tour of championship duty.
</P>
<P>
   Reinsdorf is now apparently putting the onus on Jackson about
whether he will be part of another Bulls' run.
</P>
<P>
   ``Phil (Jackson) has done a great job for us, and if he changes
his mind and wants to come back, I'll be open to discussing it with
him, absolutely,'' are Reinsdorf's reported latest words on the
subject.
</P>
<P>
   So, if Jackson is willing to eat his words about not coming
back; or, if there's an NBA season after the impending July 1
lockout; or, if Reinsdorf is willing to fire Krause _ all big
``ifs'' _ the door is open for a Bulls Reunion.
</P>
<P>
   Frankly, the possibility of another Bulls title defense is more
than any of us expected. We have been so thoroughly prepared for
something else.
</P>
<P>
   No disrespect to Sir Air, but psychologically, emotionally,
intestinally we have expected that this would be the dynasty's
faltering last dance.
</P>
<P>
   Heading into the NBA Finals, the magnitude of Jordan's persona
outside of the NBA became the main topic of the free world. Forget
the sports pages, much bigger guns were sent to chronicle The
Jordan Effect in two separate publications.
</P>
<P>
   In its latest issue, Fortune Magazine reports that Jordan is
nothing less than a $10 billion man if you account for his total
trickle-down effect.
</P>
<P>
   The June 1 issue of the New Yorker, meanwhile, provided a
masterpiece essay by Harvard sociologist Henry Louis Gates, Jr.,
describing how Jordan has blown to smithereens the standard of
product branding, thus making himself the biggest marketing force
ever witnessed.
</P>
<P>
   Not only that, Gates provided some of the most compelling quotes
from Jordan, especially in regard to Jordan's disgust with
Reinsdorf and Krause and their unending need to seize the power and
the glory for the Bulls that Jordan created.
</P>
<P>
   After signing his $30-million-plus contract for this season,
Jordan made this damning statement about Reinsdorf:
</P>
<P>
   ``We shook hands, but one comment struck me as we left and I
lost total respect for him when he said it: `At some point in time,
I know I'm going to regret what we just did,''' Jordan was quoted
as saying.
</P>
<P>
   ``And I'm saying (to myself) all these years where you knew I
was underpaid and you've been making money and your organization
has moved from a $15 million business when you bought it to $200
million _ all those years have just gone down the drain because you
have for once finally paid me my value. And you regret that! That
hit me so deep inside _ that sense of greed, of disrespect for
me.''
</P>
<P>
   Such articles and comments seem like compelling evidence that
Jordan the marketing and cultural phenomenon no longer needs to be
the greatest NBA player who ever lived. He won't stand for the
Bulls brass disrespecting him.
</P>
<P>
   But after watching the overwhelming Bulls, especially in Games 2
and 3, you get a different sense of things to come.
</P>
<P>
   Indeed, Jordan does need to play hoops. He needs to win. It is
his ultimate reward. That's why he was giggling with Pippen during
the fourth quarter when his Bulls were blowing away what everyone
expected to be the Bulls' stiffest competition.
</P>
<P>
   Here's betting that barring a season-long lockout in 1998-99,
Jordan and the Bulls run again. They have grown to love the misery
of their twisted club dynamics. In fact, with such wins as 96-54
over the Jazz, you could say Jordan and his Bulls thrive on their
over-dramatized adversity.
</P>
<P>
   Laura Vecsey is a P-I columnist.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
