A0331 &Cx1f; tth-z
u s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-BBA-MARINERS-SPRINGER     06-09 0683
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BBA-MARINERS-SPRINGER-SPI </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
M'S ADDICTED TO SPRINGER SHOW 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By DAN RALEY  
 c.1998 Seattle Post-Intelligencer  
<TEXT>
<P>
   SEATTLE _ It is midnight on a weekday in Seattle. Do you know
where your All-Star center fielder is?
</P>
<P>
   Unless there's extra innings or nine extra-long innings to be
played, Ken Griffey Jr. insists he's easy to find.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm in bed watching `The Jerry Springer Show' on Channel 10,''
he says with a smirk. ``I watch it every night.''
</P>
<P>
   In a season chalk full of inconsistency, of bullpen blowups and
endless fielding errors, Jerry Springer remains the lone constant
and a rallying cry for the Mariners. Most players are devoted fans,
treating the bawdy trash-talking, fist-swinging talk show as a
daily, or late-night, ritual.
</P>
<P>
   On the road, watching a mid-afternoon Springer episode is nearly
as important in terms of pregame preparation as taking batting
practice. Mesmerized Seattle players often are joined in front of a
clubhouse television by coaches, trainers and clubhouse personnel.
</P>
<P>
   ``Jerry's on,'' second baseman Joey Cora announces, emerging
from the training room in Kansas City, imploring teammates to
gather around him. ``Wives battle mistresses'' soon flashes on the
screen.
</P>
<P>
   ``Jer-ry, Jer-ry, Jer-ry,'' third baseman Russ Davis chants
quietly while seated in the club's Kingdome dugout and broached
about the subject. The Springer show that day is centered around a
man who claims to have married his pet horse.
</P>
<P>
   Cora has suggested that the next time the Mariners are in
Chicago, where the show is taped, the players obtain tickets and
become part of the studio audience. Griffey asks why stop there? We
could be disfunctional guests as well as anyone, he maintains.
</P>
<P>
   Upon hearing of the Mariners' allegiance to the show, Springer
spokeswoman Linda Shafran says the talk-show host is flattered.
Springer is a big sports fan whose favorite team is a Mariner
rival, the New York Yankees. Pictures of Mickey Mantle and Yogi
Berra hang in his office wall. His following cuts a wide swath
through professional sports.
</P>
<P>
   Springer has met members of the Houston Rockets, unabashed
viewers. He has learned that the Los Angeles Lakers, most notably
Shaquille O'Neal, share a deep affection for his show. Anaheim
Angels players showed up in The Windy City for a recent taping.
</P>
<P>
   ``We love hearing the Mariners are huge fans,'' Shafron said.
``Right back at them.''
</P>
<P>
   Unfortunately, the show will be on summer hiatus when the
Mariners return to Chicago in mid-August, preventing a studio
visit.
</P>
<P>
   Their television fix will have to do for now. It fills a
definite void in the otherwise mundane existence of today's
millionaire ballplayer.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's interesting,'' Davis said. ``When there's nothing else on
TV and you can't sleep, it's good entertainment _ people up there
making fools of themselves.''
</P>
<P>
   Said first baseman David Segui: ``I think most athletes like to
watch it and see people air their dirty laundry. You can give a
good ass-whipping without getting thrown in jail. I'm definitely
fascinated by the bizarre things in the world.''
</P>
<P>
   But no more than Cora. The diminutive infielder appears to be
the Mariners' biggest Springer fan. When two people start to tangle
on the screen, he becomes the most animated watcher, leaping from
his seat on the clubhouse couch in excited fashion, gesturing
approvingly at the crass and unusual. He has informed teammates he
would like to be a guest bouncer for Jerry Springer.
</P>
<P>
   Quizzed about this by an outsider, Cora isn't quite so
forthcoming. With his Vanderbilt University background, it's
possible he has a cerebral image to protect.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't like it,'' he says of the show. ``I don't watch it.
It's (expletive).''
</P>
<P>
   Griffey, however, has nothing to hide. He isn't afraid to admit
he owns six copies of Springer's ``Too Hot For TV'' video. He
routinely watches the nightly Channel 10 offerings. His wife joins
him. Jer-ry, Jer-ry, Jer-ry.
</P>
<P>
   ``Jerry's fun,'' Griffey says. ``What else is there to do late
at night?''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
