<HEADER>
A0332 &Cx1f; tth-z
u s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-BBA-MARINERS-SPI &LR;      06-09 0842
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BBA-MARINERS-SPI </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
MARINERS FALL INTO LAST PLACE 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By JIM STREET  
 c.1998 Seattle Post-Intelligencer  
<TEXT>
<P>
   SAN FRANCISCO _ In a game where inches mattered and breaks meant
even more, the Mariners on Monday night tumbled into a place they
hadn't visited in nearly three years _ the American League West
basement.
</P>
<P>
   Not even a well-pitched game from Randy Johnson, who struck out
at least 10 batters for the 88th time in his career, and Joey
Cora's four hits could save the Mariners. Just-misses and a
controversial call by the first base umpire helped settle the
surging San Francisco Giants' 4-3 victory before 34,166 fans at
3Com Park.
</P>
<P>
   The Giants won their 10th straight. The Mariners have lost seven
of eight and dropped into last place for the first time since July
16, 1995.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're scuffling and we need all the breaks we can get,''
manager Lou Piniella said.
</P>
<P>
   They could have used a break _ or accurate call _ in the ninth
inning.
</P>
<P>
   Cora led off the inning with a grounder to Rich Aurilia at deep
shortstop. He clearly beat the throw to first base, but first-base
umpire Sam Holbrook called Cora out.
</P>
<P>
   ``The replays showed it wasn't really that close,'' Piniella
said.
</P>
<P>
   Cora jumped up and down, got in the umpire's face, and was
ejected. Piniella rushed onto the field from the dugout, slammed
his cap to the ground, kicked the dirt (he might also have kicked
Holbrook) and was ejected.
</P>
<P>
   ``When you get the leadoff guy on base in the ninth, you have a
chance,'' Piniella said.
</P>
<P>
   Giants reliever Rich Rodriguez used the break to begin a
three-up, three-down ninth to register his first save of the
season, ending it by striking out Ken Griffey Jr.
</P>
<P>
   ``We lost the (expletive) game,'' said Cora, whose ejection was
the second of his career in 1,036 regular-season games. ``He called
me out and that was it.''
</P>
<P>
   The Mariners, who erased two-thirds of a three-run deficit in
the seventh inning on Alex Rodriguez's one-out, two-run single, put
the tying run on third in the eight inning when Glenallen Hill
doubled and advanced on Russ Davis' infield out. But Edgar
Martinez, pinch-hitting for Johnson, grounded out.
</P>
<P>
   Johnson never got another chance to bat or pitch, departing with
his fifth loss in 10 decisions despite allowing six hits, walking
three and striking out 10.
</P>
<P>
   ``I hadn't faced him since '92 and he looked the same to me,''
said Giants first baseman Charlie Hayes. ``He threw me one fastball
and I grounded out. He threw me nothing but sliders after that and
they were all good ones.''
</P>
<P>
   Hayes struck out twice.
</P>
<P>
   ``If they (Mariners) don't want him, we'll take him and I don't
care if he can't hit,'' Hayes said.
</P>
<P>
   The only shaky inning Johnson pitched was decisive.
</P>
<P>
   Johnson retired the first six batters he faced, striking out
two, but Rich Aurilia's fifth homer of the season ignited a
three-run Giants rally that was given a boost when Davis made
another error.
</P>
<P>
   Davis, who has a team-leading 15 errors, couldn't handle Brian
Johnson's hot grounder immediately after Aurilia's homer. Two outs
later, Bill Mueller singled, Barry Bonds walked and Jeff Kent
slapped a two-run double to right-center.
</P>
<P>
   Griffey, shading Kent to right, attempted a diving catch, but
the ball ticked off his glove and rolled toward right fielder Rob
Ducey.
</P>
<P>
   ``Junior made a helluva effort,'' Piniella said.
</P>
<P>
   San Francisco tacked on another run in the fifth inning, taking
advantage of another ball that had just enough room to elude a
Mariner glove.
</P>
<P>
   Ex-Mariner Alex Diaz singled, Mueller walked and Bonds hit a
run-scoring single between first baseman Jeff Huson and Cora.
</P>
<P>
   The seeing-eye single drove in Diaz for the eventual deciding
run.
</P>
<P>
   Johnson retired the next three batters to escape further damage,
but it would prove to be too big of a deficit.
</P>
<P>
   Seattle opened the 10-game road trip with two of its best
hitters in the dugout.
</P>
<P>
   David Segui missed his second straight start because of badly
bruised right foot and Martinez didn't start for two reasons: the
designated hitter rule isn't used in National League ballparks and
Martinez hasn't played in the field for more than a year.
</P>
<P>
   Piniella figured Martinez might be a defensive liability,
especially when Johnson attempted pickoff throws, so he started
Huson at first base.
</P>
<P>
   The Mariners scored first, grabbing a 1-0 lead in the second
inning when Ducey led off with a double past Hayes and Davis
delivered a one-out double to left.
</P>
<P>
   After Johnson struck out, Cora hit the second of his four
consecutive singles. But a dandy defensive play by Kent saved a
run. Kent, running to his right, dove and smothered the ball before
it could scoot into center field.
</P>
<P>
   Davis had to stop at third and went no further.
</P>
<P>
   Danny Darwin escaped the inning by retiring Huson on a fly to
Bonds in left field. The Mariners would put runners on third base
in the third and second base in the fifth, and third again in the
eighth but failed to get any of them home.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-06-09-98 0232EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
