<DOCNO> NYT19980609.0047 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-06-09 02:57 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A0345 &Cx1f; ttd-z
r s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-BBO-GIANTS-SFCHRON &LR;      06-09 0764
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BBO-GIANTS-SFCHRON </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
GIANTS MASTER BIG UNIT 
BY HENRY SCHULMAN
</HEADLINE>
   c.1998 San Francisco Chronicle  
    SAN FRANCISCO _ Nothing was cheap about the nine-game winning
streak the Giants brought into interleague play Monday night,
except the salaries of most of the pitchers they beat. Willie
Blair, Omar Daal, Jeff Suppan, Eddie Priest, Scott Winchester,
Brett Tomko, Kent Bottenfield, Sean Lowe and Kent Mercker are fine
athletes all, but they are not Randy Johnson.
<TEXT>
<P>
   But Randy Johnson is Randy Johnson, and Monday night the Giants
beat him as well. Anyone who still thought this run of victories
was a product of weak competition, even after the sweep in St.
Louis, must think again.
</P>
<P>
   The streak is 10 after a 4-3 victory over the Seattle Mariners,
who dropped into the AL West cellar. A vocal crowd of 34,166
witnessed the Giants triumph for the 16th time in their past 19
games at home.
</P>
<P>
   Some say Johnson (5-5, 5.34 ERA) is not the pitcher he once was.
Giants manager Dusty Baker begs to differ.
</P>
<P>
   ``He looked like Randy Johnson to me,'' Baker said. ``He made
pitches when he needed to make them. That was a big two-out,
bases-loaded double by Jeff Kent. If he hadn't hit that, we might
still be playing. Randy Johnson looked fine to me. I'm sure a lot
of people would take Randy Johnson old, new, whatever.''
</P>
<P>
   Kent's double on an 0-2 pitch in the third inning capped a
three-run rally off Johnson, who struck out 10 in seven innings.
That gave the Giants a 3-1 lead.
</P>
<P>
   Given how hard Johnson throws, Kent must be saluted for his
ability to stay aggressive with two strikes and drive that pitch
into right-center. Ken Griffey Jr. dived for the ball, but it
deflected off his glove. It is common to swing defensively on an
0-2 pitch. Kent laughed when asked why he didn't.
</P>
<P>
   ``I've got quite a few strikeouts. I don't think I'm very
defensive,'' he said. ``I swing the bat. When you've got a guy
throwing 95 mph, it's hard to be defensive. You've got to be
aggressive. If you become defensive as a hitter against Randy
Johnson, you'll lose.''
</P>
<P>
   Johnson lost in part because Mariners third baseman Russ Davis
committed his team-leading 15th error, on a bouncer by Brian
Johnson after Rich Aurilia tied the game 1-1 with a homer leading
off the third.
</P>
<P>
   Two outs later, Bill Mueller singled, Barry Bonds walked to load
the bases, and Kent hit his double. Bonds singled home another run
in the fifth inning, and the Giants withstood a two-run single by
Alex Rodriguez in the seventh off Steve Reed.
</P>
<P>
   Rich Rodriguez earned his first save, getting Griffey (0-for-5)
to whiff at a low, outside slider to end the game. The winner was
Danny Darwin (6-3), the Middle-Aged Unit, who more than held his
own against the Big Unit for 61/3 innings with his typical
underpowering stuff that leaves hitters mumbling, ``How'd he do
that?''
</P>
<P>
   Darwin retired Griffey twice on popups, once on a long fly to
right and once on a grounder to second. The latter came with the
Giants leading 4-1, two Mariners on and nobody out in the seventh.
</P>
<P>
   Baker then summoned Reed, and Darwin got a huge ovation as he
strode to the dugout before Alex Rodriguez hit his two-run single.
</P>
<P>
   ``They're big swingers, a great fastball-hitting team,'' said
Rich Rodriguez, who got the save opportunity because Baker insisted
on resting an overworked Robb Nen. ``We talked in the meeting
before the game about keeping them off-balance, mixing up location.
It's one thing to say it, it's another to do it.''
</P>
<P>
   Before the left-hander retired Griffey to end the game, the fans
got to see quite an explosion of anger from the Mariners.
</P>
<P>
   Second baseman Joey Cora led off the ninth with a grounder deep
into the hole at short. Aurilia's throw seemed very late, and Cora
thought he had his fifth hit. When vacation-replacement umpire Sam
Holbrook called Cora out, the diminutive Mariner went bonkers.
</P>
<P>
   Holbrook ejected Cora, who had to be restrained, and the ump
quickly thumbed a charging Mariners manager Lou Piniella as well.
But that was as explosive as Seattle got.
</P>
<P>
   Fans who came to see Griffey hit homers should have been there
for batting practice, when he popped three into the upper deck.
Randy Johnson hit a homer in batting practice, too, drawing cheers
from the crowd, but his three at-bats in the game were different
matter. He threw his bat into the dirt chasing strike three in the
third inning, managed a grounder to second in the fourth and forgot
to run when he hit a comebacker to Darwin in the sixth.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; (For use by clients of the New York Times News Service) &QL;  &LR;
</P>
</TEXT>
