<HEADER>
A0353 &Cx1f; ttd-z
r s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-BBO-A'S-SFCHRON &LR;      06-09 0614
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BBO-A'S-SFCHRON </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
STEIN BESTS MARTINEZ, TAMES L.A. 
BY STEVE KETTMANN
</HEADLINE>
   c.1998 San Francisco Chronicle  
<TEXT>
<P>
   LOS ANGELES _ Until recently, towering right-hander Blake Stein
seemed all too likely to end up as part of one of the great
thwap-to-the-head baseball trivia questions of all time.
</P>
<P>
   ``Can you name  &LR; one  &LR; of the three pitchers sent to Oakland in
the 1997 Mark McGwire trade with the Cardinals?''
</P>
<P>
   The way Stein pitched Monday night in the A's 7-3 win, the
Dodgers aren't going to forget his name any time soon. Stein, 24,
struck out a career-high 10, missed a complete game by two outs,
and thoroughly outclassed no less a pitcher than Ramon Martinez,
ending Martinez's five-game winning streak.
</P>
<P>
   ``You've got to give credit to that guy Stein,'' Martinez (7-3)
said. ``He pitched a great game.''
</P>
<P>
   Eric Karros nailed a fastball that Stein (2-3) left where he
shouldn't have in the ninth for a two-run homer. That forced
manager Art Howe to send in Billy Taylor for the last two outs. And
Paul Konerko hit a solo shot in the fifth, too. But none of that
mattered. The A's won for the fourth time in five games and hopped
past the Mariners to claim sole possession of third place in the AL
West.
</P>
<P>
   Stein was in command once Charles Johnson, considered the best
defensive catcher in the National League, muffed a potential double
play at the plate in the first inning. Johnson let Martinez's throw
on Mike Blowers' comebacker get past him, two runs scored on the
play, and the A's were off and running to a four-run rally.
</P>
<P>
   ``I should have had it,'' Johnson said. ``I thought I had it,
but when I went to squeeze it I lost it. It was the type of play
where I should have got Ramon out of the jam. It really could have
changed the outcome of the game.''
</P>
<P>
   The A's (27-34) keep saying they're going to stop letting
themselves down and put a hot streak together, and after a game
like this, it's easy to believe them.
</P>
<P>
   Jason Giambi blasted a three-run homer in the seventh to put the
A's in potential-rout mode. Miguel Tejada banged out two hits and
roamed the infield like a 21-year-old who knows he's in charge. Ben
Grieve cranked two doubles and a single. And old-reliable Matt
Stairs missed a sign in the seventh and laid down his first
sacrifice bunt in an A's uniform to put runners at second and
third.
</P>
<P>
   ``I knew he was kind of confused, the way he kept looking down
to third base,'' Howe said. ``He got them over, so I wasn't too
upset.''
</P>
<P>
   Stein had a lead before he ever took the mound, looking a lot
taller than 6-foot-7, and he was smarter than your average rookie
in doing something with it. He worked a one-two-three first, helped
by Blowers' excellent play on Gary Sheffield's scorcher down the
line; struck out Raul Mondesi and Bobby Bonilla back-to-back in the
second; and struck out the side in the third, finishing off the
trick by getting leadoff man Eric Young with a nasty breaking ball.
</P>
<P>
   ``Something kicked in,'' Howe said. ``He had extra hop on his
fastball. It's got to give you a boost, knowing you're throwing the
ball by some of the best hitters in baseball.''
</P>
<P>
   Bonilla probably summed up the mood of the night best in the
fifth after he struck out for the second time. Stein floated a
breaking ball past him for his seventh strikeout, and Bonilla
didn't even uncork himself from his all-out swing before he stared
out at the mound with a ``Who IS this guy?'' look.
</P>
<P>
   ``He really took it to us,'' Young said. ``Even if we had a
scouting report, he was coming at us with two pitches, a fastball
and a slider. He did a good job moving them in and out.''
</P>
<P>
   &UR; (For use by clients of the New York Times News Service) &QL;  &LR;
</P>
