<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-06-09 11:18 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A0621 &Cx1f; tad-z
r l &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-AIR-HUNNICUTT10-COX     06-09 0938
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-AIR-HUNNICUTT10-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;    
 &HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Georgian plots course for aviation policy
 &HT;    By Scott Thurston
 &HT;    c. 1998 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA _ Charles Hunnicutt had an uncommon interest in politics
and international affairs while growing up in the West Georgia city
of LaGrange.
</P>
<P>
   ``There was a civics teacher, Louise Evans, and some others who
really kind of opened my eyes to a broader world,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   That early interest led Hunnicutt to a globe-trotting career
that now finds him as the top U.S. official on aviation policy.
</P>
<P>
   Hunnicutt's title is assistant U.S. transportation secretary for
aviation and international affairs. His job is to negotiate complex
bilateral treaties between the United States and foreign
governments. These pacts dictate where the world's airlines can
fly, and they influence consumer travel options and economic
development on a global scale.
</P>
<P>
   He also plays a key -- and potentially controversial -- role in
formulating the government's stance on domestic competition and the
burgeoning issue of airline alliances.
</P>
<P>
   Hunnicutt, a University of Georgia law school graduate, was back
in his home state last week to mark a treaty success. He joined his
boss, Transportation Secretary Rodney Slater, at a kickoff ceremony
for Delta Air Lines' new nonstop flights between Atlanta and Tokyo.
The flights are a product of a revised U.S.-Japan air pact hammered
out last winter after years of inertia.
</P>
<P>
   Hunnicutt, 47, oversees a staff of negotiators but personally
handles some talks, such as those that led to the U.S.-Japan deal.
Treaty negotiation demands the tact of a diplomat, the toughness of
a trial lawyer and the savvy of a business executive, he said.
</P>
<P>
   ``It takes a lot of skills, and in some cases those of a poker
player,'' said Hunnicutt, whose drawl betrays his Georgia roots.
</P>
<P>
   Hunnicutt got the job in 1996. Air treaty revisions that open
new routes have been a DOT priority under the Clinton
administration. Hunnicutt points to 31 ``open skies'' pacts between
the United States and foreign countries, compared with one before
the effort began, as evidence of the push to remove protectionist
barriers to air service.
</P>
<P>
   Some in the airline industry say that number is misleading,
since most of the open skies pacts involve small countries that
were essentially open anyway. Of more importance, they say, are a
few liberalized treaties, such as the one with Japan, which stop
short of open skies but allow new service in key markets. A similar
treaty revision with France is behind Air France's plans to start
Atlanta-Paris flights June 19.
</P>
<P>
   On the other hand, the United States has yet to land the biggest
prize, a new deal that would open more routes to Great Britain.
</P>
<P>
   ``The interests in these treaties are so diverse and the stakes
so valuable that it takes a lot of work to get the stars aligned so
that governments will move,'' said Hunnicutt.
</P>
<P>
   Hunnicutt's office recently proposed new rules for domestic
competition. They are aimed at preventing airlines from driving
discount carriers out of business by selling too many seats below
cost on competing routes, a practice known as predatory pricing.
</P>
<P>
   ``Has it occurred? Yes,'' said Hunnicutt. But the DOT has never
taken formal action against an airline, and Hunnicutt said the
rules would give it the tools to identify and punish such behavior.
</P>
<P>
   Critics at major airlines complain the rules amount to
``re-regulation'' that will distort the marketplace and hurt
consumers by restricting the ability of big carriers to match
discounters' fares.
</P>
<P>
   ``That's a straw man,'' said Hunnicutt. ``The point of these
rules is to apply the competitive principles that were always
intended under deregulation.''
</P>
<P>
   Hunnicutt also will play a key role in DOT decisions on three
pending alliances among the six biggest U.S. carriers:
Northwest-Continental, United-Delta and American-US Airways. The
airlines claim the deals will enable them to broaden their route
offerings by selling seats on each others' flights. Critics say
they diminish competition.
</P>
<P>
   The DOT could block any of the deals if it deems them
anti-competitive. ``These deals vary in scope and the way they work
and we'll look at each one,'' said Hunnicutt. ``We're not going to
rush to judgment.''
</P>
<P>
   Hunnicutt got his first dose of politics while at LaGrange High
School, when he went to Washington as a page for his congressman.
He later got a bachelor's degree from American University, then
returned to Georgia to get his law degree.
</P>
<P>
   At UGA Hunnicutt had another academic mentor, former Secretary
of State Dean Rusk, who ran the international law program. ``He was
a major influence,'' Hunnicutt said of Rusk, who also hailed from
rural Georgia.
</P>
<P>
   Hunnicutt studied at the Hague Academy of International Law in
Brussels, Belgium, working part-time for the state of Georgia as a
trade representative. He then worked for President Jimmy Carter's
transition team, the Commerce Department and the International
Trade Commission.
</P>
<P>
   Hunnicutt then worked at a Washington law firm and in 1995 spent
a year in Ukraine, helping the fledgling country establish its
government, before joining the DOT.
</P>
<P>
   As Delta's Tokyo nonstop prepared to leave Hartsfield last week,
Hunnicutt said it was doubly satisfying to see the fruits of his
labors being realized in his home state.
</P>
<P>
   ``Personally, you're always pleased to see your native region
benefit,'' he said, ``but professionally you have to hold the
national interest paramount.''
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
