<DATE_TIME> 1998-06-09 11:18 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A0623 &Cx1f; tad-z
r l &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-GOETHE-TOWELS10-COX     06-09 0801
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-GOETHE-TOWELS10-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Mop it up with a lyric poem paper towel
 &HT;    By Cynthia Mitchell
 &HT;    c. 1998 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA _ Maybe it's a birthday thing. A psychic rumbling from
the grave to keep us from forgetting the wise words of Johann
Wolfgang Van Goethe.
</P>
<P>
   Next year is, after all, the 250th birthday of the lyric poet,
Germany's own Shakespeare.
</P>
<P>
   How else to explain why Georgia-Pacific finds itself awash in
free publicity for a design on its Sparkle paper towels that
features a boiled-down phrase from Goethe's ``Wilhelm Meister's
Travels'': ``Nothing is worth more than this day.''
</P>
<P>
   The coast-to-coast coverage -- more than two dozen stories in as
many newspapers -- started in mid-April, with a story in The
Washington Post.
</P>
<P>
   ``Is this a great country or what?'' Linton Weeks mused in the
resulting Style section-front article. ``Only in America -- where
you can get 8 percent of the daily iron you need from a 5 1/4-ounce
box of Oreos -- will you find a thought from one of the massive
minds of Western civ on a tossable towel.''
</P>
<P>
   Since then, the towels have soaked up a lot of time for Jill
Mattos and Ken Haldin, the two Georgia-Pacific execs Weeks quoted.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm having more fallout from this story than I've ever had,''
said Haldin, the company's PR chief. ``It just keeps on
snowballing, or, er,'' he adds with a grin, ``unrolling.''
</P>
<P>
   Says Mattos, the brand's marketing manager, with a laugh: ``I
hate to say I'm too busy to take these calls and talk to my
consumers, but I'm too busy to take these calls and talk to my
consumers!''
</P>
<P>
   Regrettably, she can't tell either consumers or reporters much
of what they really want to know. Seems the Goethe towels aren't
tracked separately with their own bar code. The Goethe rolls are
lumped in with nine other patterns in something called the
``Designer Case Pack.'' And even then, she can't be sure Goethe
made it into the box; it depends on what the mill was running that
day.
</P>
<P>
   In other words, good luck finding it.
</P>
<P>
   The above also means she can't track how well the Goethe design
is selling -- though she will hear from grocers if they're backing
up on the shelves.
</P>
<P>
   So how about who came up with the idea? Does she know if it was
some frustrated German lit major, whose life was changed by reading
``Faust,'' Goethe's famous poem about the title character's pact to
sell his soul to the devil?
</P>
<P>
   The best she can do is this: It was somebody at one of four
design firms she tapped two years to come up with new patterns. Out
of the hundreds submitted, 80 were picked to test on consumers in
Tampa and Baltimore, with 10 emerging as ``the winners.''
</P>
<P>
   Up in New Haven, Conn., Yale's Beinecke Rare Book and Manuscript
Library is absorbed with the towels as well. It is home to the
world's third-largest collection of Goethe's work -- the largest
outside of Germany.
</P>
<P>
   Christa Sammons curates the German literature collection, which
includes the largest Goethe collection outside of Washington. After
hearing about The Washington Post story, she got Haldin to send her
three rolls.
</P>
<P>
   They won't be for the library's bathroom, she says, but for the
``special collection'' of what literary scholars call ``reception
history.'' Or more plainly, stuff -- any stuff -- with Goethe on
it.
</P>
<P>
   The towels, Sammons thinks, are the first U.S. stuff with bona
fide, attributed Goethe on it since World War I.
</P>
<P>
   Before the war made anything German politically incorrect,
Sammons said, most Americans not only knew his works but how to
pronounce his name correctly. (It's Gher-tuh)
</P>
<P>
   But since then, he hasn't exactly been a pop culture icon.
</P>
<P>
   Hence her excitement. And, since seeing the towels herself, her
relief.
</P>
<P>
   Because Sammons is where the buck stops when anybody in the
United States wants to know if it was Goethe who said thus and so
and where he said it.
</P>
<P>
   ``When I read the story, I thought `Oh my God! Every towel has a
different one and people will be calling me night and day to find
out where he said it,''' she said. ``Thank heavens there's only
one, and I found it already!''
</P>
<P>
   Actually, under the right conditions, Sammons would love to see
Goethe maxims spilled all over a roll of Sparkle towels -- a
special Goethe's birthday edition, a 250-sheet roll, each with a
different Goethe saying, one for every year since he was born.
</P>
<P>
   ``Not only that, but he could have Kafka towels, Rilke towels.
I'll be his consultant! He can pay me to pick out the phrases!''
she suggests.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think they better get the presses going at the paper towel
factory because next year's gonna be a big year!''
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By The Atlanta Journal-Constitution
</P>
<P>
   AP-NY-06-05-98 2232E
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
