<SLUG> BC-MCCARTY-COLUMN10-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Teenie-Beanies instill the great-American value of . . .
consuming?
 &HT;    By Mary McCarty
 &HT;    c. 1998 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   DAYTON, Ohio _ ``They're absolutely free,'' the fifth-grader
tells his friend. ``Every kid at school has them.''
</P>
<P>
   He displays his Coca-Cola card, the proud trophy acquired after
calling an 800 number and waiting patiently on hold for a
half-hour.
</P>
<P>
   Meanwhile, Teenie-Beanie Babies have invaded McDonald's
restaurants all over America. ``People called into Traffic Reports
that the McDonald's stations were all backed up,'' said Brian
Bruchey, an assistant program director for WMMX radio. The
Associated Press reported some Happy Meal purchasers throwing away
their food.
</P>
<P>
   None of this is news, exactly, so why was I feeling so
uncomfortable? With all these kids clutching pseudo-credit cards,
and parents scavenging Beanie Babies, I couldn't help worrying what
we're teaching our kids. We don't always succeed in instilling the
three R's, but every child in America is getting an excellent
education in how to be a consumer.
</P>
<P>
   In my basement, and in the basement of nearly every parent I
know, lie buckets of once-coveted, rarely touched McDonald's toys.
It would take a stout-hearted parent indeed to resist the
persistent pleas of kids who can say ``McDonald's'' before they can
pronounce their own names.
</P>
<P>
   My friend, Amy, is an unusually sensible parent, but even she
fell into the trap. The family is moving to Hawaii, and Amy
conducted a toy purge recently with her 7-year-old son. She found a
bin stuffed with about 60 Happy Meal toys, from Toy Story to
Anastasia. ``I can't think of any of those toys that survived the
cut,'' she said.
</P>
<P>
   Forget, for the moment, what these billions of discarded toys
might be doing to the environment. Think about a less tangible
erosion: the reflex for mindless consuming we're creating in our
kids. Can't you just see them when they're adults, and dining at
The Pine Club or Lller-blading and popcorn-popping. The tease goes
like this: ``Mass consumption. Instant gratification. Ahhh, summer
is here.''
</P>
<P>
   The Teenie-Beanie Babies are touted as collectors' items, and
books such as Beanie Mania and magazines such as Beanie World
compare current and projected market values. (They're counting on
us to forget that Cabbage Patch dolls, now readily available at
garage sales everywhere, were once touted as collectors' items,
too.)
</P>
<P>
   But suppose someday the Beanie Babies turn out to be a wise
financial investment. Are they worth the price? How much do we
ultimately pay if we encourage our kids to get in the habit of
consuming?
</P>
<P>
   Think of that fifth-grader telling his buddy, ``They're
absolutely free.''
</P>
<P>
   There's dad standing nearby, stifling his impulse to laugh,
stifling an even stronger impulse to say, ``Take it from me, kid.
There's nothing in life that's absolutely free.''
</P>
<P>
   Mary McCarty writes for the Dayton Daily News
</P>
<P>
   Mary McCarty: e-mail her at mary_mccartycoxore to the clinical
appearance of melanoma, the potential beneficial impact from
sunscreens would not have been seen yet,'' Siegle said. Until
``more definitive research can be done,'' he recommended using
sunscreens and avoiding long exposure to the sun, especially
between 10 a.m. and 4 p.m. 1
</P>
<P>
   E WEB SITE for information about skin cancer prevention from
Ohio State's Arthur G. James Cancer Hospital and Research Institute
is www.jamesline.com, or call, toll-free, (800) 293-5066.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
