A0631 &Cx1f; tad-z
r l &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-MELANOMA-SIDE10-COX     06-09 0203
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-MELANOMA-SIDE10-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    SIDEBAR: Early detection of skin cancer saves lives.
 &HT;    Staff
 &HT;    c. 1998 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   The five-year survival rate is 95 percent for malignant melanoma
that is removed before it spreads, the American Cancer Society
said. And for less serious basal cell and squamous cell skin
cancers, ``cure is highly likely if detected and treated early.''
</P>
<P>
   People should beware of any change in skin growths, especially a
change in size or color of a mole or other darkly pigmented spot.
</P>
<P>
   Basal and squamous cell cancers often appear as either a pale,
waxlike, pearly nodule or a red, scaly, sharply outlined patch.
</P>
<P>
   The cancer society recommends this ``ABCD'' list to remember the
warning signs of melanoma:
</P>
<P>
   E A is for asymmetry, where one half of a mole does not match
the other half.
</P>
<P>
   E B is for border irregularity, where edges are ragged, notched
or blurred.
</P>
<P>
   E C is for color, where pigmentation is not consistent or is
intensely black.
</P>
<P>
   E D is for diameter greater than 6 millimeters, roughly a
quarter of an inch.
</P>
<P>
   Story by the staff of the Dayton Daily News
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
