<DOCNO> NYT19980609.0073 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-06-09 11:20 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A0632 &Cx1f; tad-z
r l &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-MELANOMA-VACCINE10-CO     06-09 1333
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-MELANOMA-VACCINE10-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;    
 &HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    By Kevin Lamb
 &HT;    c. 1998 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   He found out his cancer was back on the day after he found out
his wife was pregnant.
</P>
<P>
   Rob Fairburn's malignant melanoma had branched out from the
original mole on his right shoulder to the lymph nodes under his
arm. The lymph nodes were cut out quickly, but there still was a 70
percent chance the cancer would pop up somewhere else by two years.
Fairburn, then 30, had less than a 50 percent chance of turning 35.
</P>
<P>
   Within days, Fairburn and his wife were in their Union home
learning about the country's major cancer hospitals, from southern
California to North Carolina. ``Everything was such a mess. You're
like, 'What's going on? What is there?' ,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Well, said Dr. Rob Finley, there was this experimental vaccine
he was researching right in Dayton, at Franciscan Medical Center.
It was just a small trial, with only enough money for five
patients. Experiments don't always work out either, so Finley
couldn't promise that Fairburn would live longer or even better if
he used this vaccine instead of conventional treatments. But he had
room for one more patient.
</P>
<P>
   ``I was in the right place at the right time,'' Fairburn said
recently, three years later. ``If we'd have had to go out of state,
we'd have probably gone bankrupt. I don't know if we even could
have done it.''
</P>
<P>
   Things change quickly
</P>
<P>
   The search for a melanoma vaccine is a microscopic detective
story that shows how fast things change in the treatment of this
deadliest form of skin cancer. The vaccine Fairburn used still
isn't available to the general public, and Finley's research team
already has moved two generations ahead in the laboratory.
Meanwhile, evidence mounts that vaccines could be not only more
effective, but cheaper and with fewer toxic side effects than other
treatments for malignant melanoma.
</P>
<P>
   The theory behind all vaccines is to stimulate the immune
system, which ordi purpose of this vaccine, said Currier, is ``to
make the cancer cells stand out'' as intruders.
</P>
<P>
   Scientists do that by combining melanoma cells with substances
they know the immune system will recognize. When those altered
melanoma cells are injected back into the body, they hope the
immune system knows to go after all those other melanoma cells that
have assembled in the body, much the way a hunting dog knows what
to chase after it has sniffed the right scent.
</P>
<P>
   The question that researchers are racing to answer is: What's
the best way to alter those melanoma cells?
</P>
<P>
   Franciscan is among several research sites exploring vaccines
against malignant melanoma, the fastest-growing cancer in the
United States after doubling its rate among whites from 1973 to
1991. The journal Nature Medicine reported in March on vaccines
tested in New York and Germany that shrank tumors in nearly half of
melanoma patients.
</P>
<P>
   By next fall, the Franciscan team expects to be ``one of few
places in the country, and the fiherapy late last month, naming it
for the former Dayton Foundation president and the first patient to
use their vaccine. Now, as they continue with other vaccine
research, they're awaiting the anticipated two to six months for
approval by the Food and Drug Administration.
</P>
<P>
   Finley was treating Cash's melanoma in 1994 when Cash brought
him an article about melanoma vaccine research in Philadelphia.
Within months, Finley and his collaborating scientist, Dr. Emilio
Barbera-Guillem, were investigating similar vaccines in Dayton.
``Unfortunately,'' said Finley, ``it was too late for Jim.''
</P>
<P>
   Fairburn arrived in April 1995, three months after Cash's first
vaccine and 10 months after the mole on his shoulder had been
removed. He had noticed the mole about six months before he had his
doctor check it. ``I ignored it,'' he said, ``and paid the price.''
Now the cancer had traveled, or metastasized.
</P>
<P>
   To explain how Fairburn's vaccine worked, Finley talked about
poison ivy.
</P>
<P>
   Some people can roll around in poison ivy without any
consequences. Others will be itching for days if they just brush
against it. The difference is that people who get bad reactions
have a chemical in their skin that binds with a chemical in the
poison ivy.
</P>
<P>
   ``That chemical (in the plant) is a hapten,'' Finley said.
``It's a small molecule that causes the body's immune system to
react more.''
</P>
<P>
   If haptens stimulate the immune system, and melanoma cells
thrive because they escape the immune system's notice, then it made
sense to find out if the immune system would attack cancer cells
that were bonded with haptens.
</P>
<P>
   Came at good time
</P>
<P>
   Fairburn walked into Finley's office just in time to help test
that premise. The vaccine consisted of a patient's own irradiated
cancer cells blended with a common hapten.
</P>
<P>
   ``When I started this vaccine, the only thing I wanted was to
see my son born,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   There would be some torture involved. The scars from 24 vaccine
injections still make his left arm look and feel ``like craters on
the moon,'' he said. And even before the injections began, he
underwent about a month of painful injections of substances to
stimulate his immune system.
</P>
<P>
   ``One day it felt like a hot poker went right up to my brain,''
Fairburn said. That was a good sign, actually. The worse Fairburn
hurt, the more aggressively his immune system was reacting. When
doctors started the vaccine regimen of three injections a month for
eight months, ``they said my body reacted pretty well to that,
too.''
</P>
<P>
   The cancer was gone, and it stayed gone. ``But you're never out
of the woods,'' Fairburn said. Cash died Nov. 25, 1995, the same
day Fairburn's son, Tyler, was born and before his last injections.
Two others from the trial group also died, one of unrelated causes.
He wondered: If the vaccine didn't save them, could it save him?
</P>
<P>
   ``But my faith pulled me through,'' he said. That, and his wife
of nine years, Debbie. ``To watch another person go through this
has got to be very difficult,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   The worst times were the weeks before his battery of tests every
spring and fall. ``You get the anxiety, the what-ifs,'' Fairburn
said. ``I get very short with people then. I'm better off left
alone.
</P>
<P>
   ``You just don't want to hear 'We're sorry.' But that day could
come. You've just got to accept that. You're not in control. You've
got to accept that every day you have free of cancer is a gift.''
</P>
<P>
   Alarming signs
</P>
<P>
   At a regular three-month checkup in April 1997 Finley noticed
the lymph nodes in Fairburn's groin were bigger than they should
be. They weren't necessarily cancerous, but Fairburn remembered how
Cash's cancer had traveled down his right side to his right hip.
Now these enlarged lymph nodes were on Fairburn's right side, the
same side where his cancer had already appeared twice.
</P>
<P>
   ``You're on the bubble waiting,'' Fairburn said _ first for the
CT and MRI scans, then for the surgery to remove the lymph nodes,
then for the biopsy reports. He spent some nights tossing and
turning, some days sweating and snapping at people. ``You just hold
on,'' he said, ``and hope for the best.''
</P>
<P>
   E Coming Monday: Rob Fairburn learns if the vaccine has helped.
1
</P>
<P>
   E CONTACT Kevin Lamb at 225-2129 or by e-mail at
kevin_lambcoxohio.com
</P>
<P>
   More information available
</P>
<P>
   E VACCINES: For information about participating in clinical
trials for melanoma vaccines, consult a physician who belongs to
the Dayton Clinical Oncology Program.
</P>
<P>
   E WEB SITES and phone numbers for information and prevention
programs about skin cancer: www.cancer.org and (800) 227-2345 for
the American Cancer Society www.aad.org for the American Academy of
Dermatology (800) 422 6237 for the National Cancer Institute
www.cdc.gov/nccdphp/dcpc/nscpep for the U.S. Centers for Disease
Control and Prevention.
</P>
<P>
   Kevin Lamb writes for the Dayton Daily News.
</P>
