<SLUG> BC-NEWSSTAND10-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;    
 &HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Lewinsky exercises her libido
 &HT;    BY Don O'Briant
 &HT;    c. 1998 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   In a photographic coup, Vanity Fair ($3.50) features Nancy and
Ronald Reagan in the first portrait of the former president and
first lady in six years. But the more interesting pictures are the
ones of Monica Lewinsky at Malibu, Calif. The six-page layout by
celebrity photographer Herb Ritts was one of William Ginsburg's
last publicity stunts before being replaced as Lewinsky's lawyer.
</P>
<P>
   Time ($2.95), which ran one of Ritts' photos of the former White
House intern posing a la Sally Rand behind a raft of pink feathers,
reports that Lewinsky's new legal team, Jacob Stein and Plato
Cacheris, will not court the media as frenetically as Ginsburg did.
Ginsburg says he agreed to the Vanity Fair shoot because special
prosecutor Kenneth Starr had ``imprisoned'' Lewinsky's libido.
</P>
<P>
   Apparently Ritts was able to rectify this. In the photos,
Lewinsky does not look or act like a young woman facing an
indictment. She frolics on a grassy dune in blue jeans and a red
and white checked shirt, poses in a sophisticated black dress and
then hides seductively behind pink plumage.
</P>
<P>
   OUT OF THE MOUTHS OF BABES: In a fascinating cover story, U.S.
News &AMP; World Report ($2.95) reveals that infants learn to tune in
to their native language by the time they are 10 months old. Two
recent studies show that the size of toddlers' vocabularies depends
on how much their mothers talk to them. At 20 months, children of
talkative mothers had 131 more words in their vocabularies than
children whose mothers were less loquacious. By age 2, the gap had
more than doubled to 295 words.
</P>
<P>
   JOGGING OUR MEMORIES: Do you find yourself forgetting your car
keys more often? Don't worry. Newsweek's ($2.95) cover story on
memory says forgetfulness is America's latest health obsession.
Aging baby boomers are ingesting everything from Ginkgo bilboa to
estrogen to boost their brain power.
</P>
<P>
   THE RIGHT PRESCRIPTION: Skip New York's ($2.95) cover story on
the best doctors in New York City (good information, but only if
you're planning on getting sick in the Big Apple), but be sure to
read Garrison Keillor's witty essay on choosing the perfect M.D.
His advice: Never choose a doctor who uses his first initial or a
cardiologist who leaves religious tracts around the waiting room.
``I eliminate doctors whose first name is the same as any of the
dumbest people I went to high school with. ... And I avoid doctors
in solo practice at an address whose house number ends with a
fraction.''
</P>
<P>
   CLOSE SHAVE: Reading about shaving usually is as fascinating as
watching someone shave, but James Surowiecki's article on ``The
Billion-Dollar Blade'' in The New Yorker ($3) is an exception.
Surowiecki goes into the Gillette laboratories to describe the
development of the Mach 3, a triple-blade razor with an edge twice
as hard as steel. Gilette, which spent $50 million in a seven-year
research project, predicts the blade will revolutionize shaving.
</P>
<P>
   THE KING OF ROCK? Dave Matthews looks like Forrest Gump and his
band features a violin. So how did he become one of rock's hottest
stars? Spin ($2.99) profiles the unlikely superstar, whose group
sold out the 78,000-capacity Giants Stadium in 90 minutes.
</P>
<P>
   X MARKS THE SPOT: In case you want to see the movie ``The
X-Files: Fight the Future,'' and you've never watched the
television series, Entertainment Weekly ($2.50) offers a beginner's
guide to the conspiracies, the agents and the cigarette smoking
man.
</P>
<P>
   GONE FISHING: You'll never look at a deviled crab the same way
after reading Michael Finkel's man-against-nature adventure saga in
P.O.V. ($2.95). Crab fishing is the deadliest job in America, says
Finkel, who ventured into the Bering Sea in January. ``Each winter,
a snow-crabber faces about a 1 percent chance of not returning
home. That's 75 times the death rate for firefighters; 110 times
the death rate for members of the armed forces.''
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
