<HEADER>
A0634 &Cx1f; tad-z
r l &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-TEXAS-BUGS10-COX     06-09 0561
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-TEXAS-BUGS10-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;    
 &HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Dry spring has helped Central Texas in battle with some bugs.
 &HT;    By Julie J. Everitt
 &HT;    c. 1998 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   WACO, Texas _ An unseasonably dry spring has squelched what
could have been a horrendous year for bugs, giving residents a
break from the normal battles fought with tiny critters in Central
Texas.
</P>
<P>
   The latest rainfall, however, could change that.
</P>
<P>
   ``We haven't had many calls about anything,'' said Doug Andrews,
McLennan County extension agent. ``The biggest problems we have
seen of late has been the grasshopper population.''
</P>
<P>
   Much of the insect population is down this year, particularly
mosquitoes, Andrews said.
</P>
<P>
   But grasshoppers, he said, thrive in dry weather conditions,
feeding off grass and anything else green.
</P>
<P>
   ``They're very destructive,'' Andrews said. ``A swarm ... can
destroy a lot of tonnage of forage(NO)cq(RO).''
</P>
<P>
   The latest moisture dousing parched Central Texas in the past
few days, however, could mean the demise of much of the grasshopper
population, he said. But it does bode well for other insects
needing wet conditions to reproduce.
</P>
<P>
   Andrews said rain stimulates the growth of a fungus that
destroys grasshopper eggs, limiting reproduction of the insect.
</P>
<P>
   But rain, on the other hand, also causes many other types of
bugs to thrive, meaning more mosquitoes and fleas may be on the
way, he said.
</P>
<P>
   Local veterinarians are already reporting massive flea problems
this year.
</P>
<P>
   ``Terrible, terrible,'' said Lisa Holub, a veterinary technician
at the Heart of Texas Veterinary Hospital. ``This is one of the
worst (flea) situations we've had so far.''
</P>
<P>
   Charles Anderson of the Anderson Veterinary Hospital agreed.
``As a matter of fact, we had a couple of dogs brought in today
that were (bleeding) because the fleas were so bad,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   The warm winter failed to kill much of the flea population,
Holub said, already creating unsavory conditions for pet owners.
And the latest addition of moisture to the area certainly won't
help matters.
</P>
<P>
   ``Once you get the moisture and the warmth, they just go
berserk,'' she said.
</P>
<P>
   Keeping fleas under control takes work, veterinarians say.
</P>
<P>
   They advise using a preventive medicine, such Frontline spray or
Advantage topical solution to treat fleas directly on the pets. In
addition, homes should be fogged or bombed with a treatment
containing a growth regulator to kill adult fleas and eggs.
</P>
<P>
   Finally, the yard should be sprayed for fleas, not just once but
as many times as it takes to eliminate any flea problem.
</P>
<P>
   ``That's all you can do,'' said Holub, reminding pet owners to
keep pets on preventive heartworm medication to eliminate the risk
of heartworm transmitted by mosquitoes.
</P>
<P>
   Rain or shine, however, roaches seem to be the only bug that
thrives regardless.
</P>
<P>
   If there isn't much moisture outside, roaches will move indoors,
Andrews said. If there isn't much food outside, they again will
move indoors.
</P>
<P>
   ``What you or I need to live, they need it, too,'' Andrews said.
</P>
<P>
   But eliminating the accessibility of the roaches' needs _ such
as keeping food covered _ may force them to move somewhere else.
</P>
<P>
   ``They will move and be in areas where their needs are met,''
Andrews said.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
