<P>
   TEEPEN-COLUMN _ Partisanship aside for a moment, anyone with
even vestigial twitches of fairness has to be relieved that
California voters last week put the kibosh to a referendum that
would have forced unions to get written permission from their
members to spend dues money on politics. (Teepen, Cox News Service)
MOVED MONDAY.
</P>
<P>
   KLEINBERG-COLUMN _ The 54th anniversary of D-Day passed Saturday
without mention in my local newspaper, or on any of the local and
national TV news shows I saw. Four years after much of the Western
world commemorated the 50th anniversary of the momentous 1944
Allied invasion of Nazi-held Europe, the significance of it seems
no longer worthy of a line of observance, or a flash of film.
Howard Kleinberg is a former editor of the Miami News. (Kleinberg,
Cox News Service) MOVED MONDAY.
</P>
<P>
   MURRAY-COLUMN _ There comes a time when a man has to consider
his conduct, as judged by community mores. So it is for me, now
that I have a young grandson. Which is why I'm across the river,
shooting pool with my Cousin Bubba. I want to be ready and able to
teach my grandson what a man's gotta know to be a man. (Murray, Cox
News Service) MOVED MONDAY.
</P>
<P>
   MCCARTY-COLUMN _ Teenie-Beanie Babies have invaded McDonald's
restaurants all over America. None of this is news, exactly, so why
was I feeling so uncomfortable? With all these kids clutching
pseudo-credit cards, and parents scavenging Beanie Babies, I
couldn't help worrying what we're teaching our kids. We don't
always succeed in instilling the three R's, but every child in
America is getting an excellent education in how to be a consumer.
(McCarty, Dayton Daily News) MOVED.
</P>
<P>
   SCHUETT-COLUMN _ Three days left and already I've begun to eat
things I don't even like - two jelly donuts from a box in the
teacher's lounge - just because they're there. I guess maybe thats
how teachers measure stress - days, hours, and all the jelly donuts
they can eat. (Schuett, Cox News Service) MOVED.
</P>
