<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19980609.0078 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-06-09 11:22 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A0637 &Cx1f; tad-z
r k &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-SCHUETT-COLUMN10-COX     06-09 0630
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-SCHUETT-COLUMN10-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    COLUMN: School's about finished and so am I
 &HT;    By Elizabeth Schuett
 &HT;    c. 1998 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   GIBSONBURG, Ohio. _ ``Three more days,'' I chant under my breath
as I head down the hall. It's my end-of-the-school-year mantra.
</P>
<P>
   As I round the corner, I glance at the clock. It's 7:30. Good.
I'm early. But not quite early enough. Patty is already there, a
shoulder to my door and obviously trying to decide whether to
giggle or bawl.
</P>
<P>
   ``What's wrong?''
</P>
<P>
   ``My shoe's on the roof.''
</P>
<P>
   ``You're kidding.''
</P>
<P>
   ``It is,'' she begins to wail, ``REALLY!'' I look down and sure
enough, she's wearing two white socks and one Nike.
</P>
<P>
   ``Can you tell me how your shoe got on the roof?'' I really
don't want to know but I have to ask before I call out the
custodian.
</P>
<P>
   ``Ben did it,'' she rasps in between sobs. ``My mom's going to
kill me.'' I assure her we'll get her shoe back before the buses
run this afternoon, but in the meantime, I need some facts.
</P>
<P>
   ``How'd Ben get your shoe off?'' I envision arm-wrestling or
worse.
</P>
<P>
   ``I threw it at him.''
</P>
<P>
   ``You took off your shoe and threw it at Ben?'' I give her my
wickedest one-eyebrow-raised look, she sobs and nods. I ask why.
</P>
<P>
   ``He called me a name.'' She waits and then asks: ``Wanna
hear?''
</P>
<P>
   I say I don't but that doesn't fit her plan.
</P>
<P>
   ``'Toad breath'! That's what he called me.''
</P>
<P>
   ``Patty,'' I remind her, ``name-calling is seldom based on fact,
but rather on an inadequate vocabulary.'' I'm not helping. She
wails on while I head for the office to report a shoe on the roof.
Before I can make it, though, an anxious-looking Dan overtakes me.
</P>
<P>
   ``Ms. Schuett!''
</P>
<P>
   ``Wha-at?''
</P>
<P>
   ``Roger has his head buried in his parka and he won't come
out.''
</P>
<P>
   ``He'll come out when the movie starts.''
</P>
<P>
   ``No, he won't. He says he's never coming out. What if he
suffocates?'' I assure Dan that Roger is not going to stop
breathing just because he has his head stuffed in his coat, but Dan
insists.
</P>
<P>
   ``Okay, where is he?''
</P>
<P>
   ``In your room.''
</P>
<P>
   Dan's right. There's a headless, oversize Indians jacket with
feet at Roger's desk.
</P>
<P>
   ``Roger, take off the parka and tell me what's wrong.'' The
parka shakes. ``You can't go around like this all day.'' He mumbles
he can because there's nothing in the student handbook that says he
can't. I warn him I'm going to check when I go to the office for
help with Patty's shoe.
</P>
<P>
   He mutters something and I leave.
</P>
<P>
   Halfway down the hall, Tommy catches up with me. ``Ms. Schuett!
Ms. Schuett! Kenny needs you RIGHT now.'' I wheel and head back to
209. Kenny meets me at the door clutching a box.
</P>
<P>
   ``Where do I put the ice cream bars?''
</P>
<P>
   ``The what?''
</P>
<P>
   ``Ice cream bars for the movie. I told the kids in 4th period
I'd bring em.''
</P>
<P>
   ``Kenny, it's 70 degrees in here. How do you propose we keep
this stuff from melting?'' He shrugs. Patty hollers for her shoe,
and Dan wants to know why Roger isn't coming out of his coat.
</P>
<P>
   Since they never covered this stuff at teacher school, I decide
to wing it.
</P>
<P>
   ``Kenny, hand out the ice-cream.'' He gapes.
</P>
<P>
   ``Now?''
</P>
<P>
   ``The way I see it, we eat it now or you wind up wearing it.
Take your pick.'' He catches on and rips the box open.
</P>
<P>
   Now, where was I? Oh, right. Patty's shoe and Roger's
hibernation. And it's not even 8 o'clock.
</P>
<P>
   Three days left and already I've begun to eat things I don't
even like _ two jelly donuts from a box in the teacher's lounge _
just because they're there. I guess maybe that's how teachers
measure stress _ days, hours, and all the jelly donuts they can
eat.
</P>
<P>
   Elizabeth Schuett is a teacher and writer in Gibsonburg, Ohio.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
