 &HT;    COX NEWS SERVICE WEDNESDAY FEATURES BUDGET
 &HT;    c. 1998 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   These feature stories for release Wednesday, June 10, 1998, are
moving today to clients of the New York Times News Service.
</P>
<P>
   Separate budgets move daily with spot news, sports, business and
commentary.
</P>
<P>
   Stories are moving in the category they're listed under. Stories
moving to duplicate categories are marked. All stories have moved
except those with an ETA.
</P>
<P>
   If you have questions or need a resend, please call CoxNet, the
Cox News Service, at 404-526-5456.
</P>
<P>
   ENTERTAINMENT/ARTS (e category)
</P>
<P>
   TV-SURFER _ ``PrimeTime Live'' profiles Faye Yager (but doesn't
talk to her). Connie Chung, whose still-broiling recent run-in with
Yager's lawyer has been well-publicized, reports. (Atlanta
Journal-Constitution) ETA: 8 p.m. ET.
</P>
<P>
   MINI-REVIEWS _ Capsule reviews of recently released movies. The
Apostle to Woo. Moves in four parts. (Hamilton/Murray/Ringel,
Atlanta Journal-Constitution) MOVED.
</P>
<P>
   NEWSSTAND _ In a fascinating cover story, U.S. News &AMP; World
Report ($2.95) reveals that infants learn to tune in to their
native language by the time they are 10 months old. Newsweek's
($2.95) cover story on memory says forgetfulness is America's
latest health obsession. Reading about shaving usually is as
fascinating as watching someone shave, but James Surowiecki's
article on ``The Billion-Dollar Blade'' in The New Yorker ($3) is
an exception. And more reviews of this week's magazine offerings.
(O'Briant, Atlanta Journal-Constitution) MOVED.
</P>
<P>
   LIFESTYLE (l category)
</P>
<P>
   GETAWAY-MEMPHIS _ MEMPHIS, Tenn. _ You could eat every meal here
in a famous barbecue joint and convince yourself the four food
groups consist entirely of pork. But do try to tear yourself away
from pit heaven (if not for your own sake, at least for your
cardiologist's) and sample at least one of this city's finer dining
establishments. (Kessler, Atlanta Journal-Constitution)
</P>
<P>
   GETAWAY-PERU _ Visit to the Ancestors of the Incas Wonders
exhibit at The Pyramid. (Kessler, Atlanta Journal-Constitution).
</P>
<P>
   GETAWAY-TIPS _ If you go to Memphis. ETA: 8 p.m. on all.
</P>
<P>
   GOETHE-TOWELS _ ATLANTA _ Maybe it's a birthday thing. A psychic
rumbling from the grave to keep us from forgetting the wise words
of Johann Wolfgang Van Goethe. Next year is, after all, the 250th
birthday of the lyric poet, Germany's own Shakespeare. How else to
explain why Georgia-Pacific finds itself awash in free publicity
for a design on its Sparkle paper towels that features a
boiled-down phrase from Goethe's ``Wilhelm Meister's Travels'':
``Nothing is worth more than this day.'' (Mitchell, Atlanta
Journal-Constitution) MOVED.
</P>
<P>
   AIR-HUNNICUTT _ ATLANTA _ Charles Hunnicutt had an uncommon
interest in politics and international affairs while growing up in
the West Georgia city of LaGrange. That early interest led
Hunnicutt to a globe-trotting career that now finds him as the top
U.S. official on aviation policy. Hunnicutt's title is assistant
U.S. transportation secretary for aviation and international
affairs. His job is to negotiate complex bilateral treaties between
the United States and foreign governments. (Thurston, Atlanta
Journal-Constitution) MOVED.
</P>
<P>
   CYBERSCENE _ ATLANTA _ The Internet is truly a wonderful and
mysterious place. Besides offering information on how to do
anything from bake a cake to get rid of fleas, it's also the
world's biggest source of both free and inexpensive computer
programs. (Husted, Atlanta Journal-Constitution) MOVED.
</P>
<P>
   MACNEWS _ ATLANTA _ A program called Consultant is the best new
personal information manager to hit the Mac market in years -- and
it's a heck of a good deal, too. For about $50, you get a calendar
and electronic card file largely the equal of programs costing
twice as much. And, in some cases, it's easier to use and more
attractive. (Haddad, Atlanta Journal-Constitution) MOVED.
</P>
<P>
   JUSTFORFUN _ ATLANTA _ Canon's Digital Printer CD-200, which
ships next month, claims to be the industry's first color printer
to accept and print images directly from a digital camera's Compact
Flash card. (Davis, Atlanta Journal-Constitution) MOVED.
</P>
<P>
   TECHTOOLS _ ATLANTA _ I'm writing this on my new 400-MHz
computer, and I'm not having as much fun as you might think. I have
come to dread new computers. Used to be, getting a computer was the
most exciting thing in the world. I was like a kid at Christmas.
Now I'm like Scrooge. It's more work than it's worth. (Warner,
Atlanta Journal-Constitution) MOVED.
</P>
<P>
   SCIENCE/MEDICINE
</P>
<P>
   MELANOMA-VACCINE _ The search for a melanoma vaccine is a
microscopic detective story that shows how fast things change in
the treatment of this deadliest form of skin cancer. Evidence
mounts that vaccines could be not only more effective, but cheaper
and with fewer toxic side effects than other treatments for
malignant melanoma. (Lamb, Dayton Daily News) MOVED.
</P>
<P>
   WITH
</P>
<P>
   MELANOMA-PROTECTION _ Don't throw away your sunscreen, beg
dermatologists who worry that people have been confused by accounts
of a recent research report indicating sunscreens do not lower the
risk of malignant melanoma. (Lamb, Dayton Daily News) MOVED.
</P>
<P>
   WITH
</P>
<P>
   MELANOMA-SIDEBAR _ Melanoma facts. (Staff, Dayton Daily News)
MOVED.
</P>
<P>
   BOXING-FITNESS _ Boxing and its close cousin, kickboxing, have
become the wunderworkouts of choice for the Hollywood A-list, both
on- and off-screen, from Jodie Foster to Ally McBeal. Fitness
boxing is becoming increasingly popular outside Hollywood, too.
Unlike regular boxing, fitness boxing and kickboxing involve no
actual sparring _ except with a heavy bag. But the workout is
incredibly demanding; devotees say it's the toughest exercise
they've ever tried. (Kim, Atlanta Journal-Constitution) ETA: 8 p.m.
</P>
<P>
   MONSTERS _ As sci-fi and monster movies increasingly depict kids
at risk _ and spin off toys that appeal to very young kids _
parents need to arm their kids with two weapons: common sense and
sleep. Atlanta psychologist Stephen Garber, author of ``Monsters
Under the Bed and Other Childhood Fears,'' says kids under 8 or 9
really can't distinguish reality and fantasy. (Lore, Atlanta
Journal-Constitution) ETA: 8 p.m.
</P>
<P>
   TEXAS-BUGS _ WACO, Texas _ An unseasonably dry spring has
squelched what could have been a horrendous year for bugs, giving
residents a break from the normal battles fought with tiny critters
in Central Texas. The latest rainfall, however, could change that.
Much of the insect population is down this year, particularly
mosquitoes. (Everitt, Waco Tribune-Herald) MOVED.
</P>
