<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-06-09 12:20 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A0694 &Cx1f; ttx-z
r p &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-GOP-TEXAS-TEX     06-09 0886
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-GOP-TEXAS-TEX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
THOUSANDS TO GATHER FOR STATE REPUBLICAN CONVENTION IN FORT WORTH
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By MAX B. BAKER 
c.1998 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   FORT WORTH, Texas _ Texas Republicans, giddy with the
possibility of Gov. George W. Bush leading a statewide sweep in
November, will stream into Fort Worth this week for the biggest
political convention in the country.
</P>
<P>
   As many as 14,000 delegates and alternates _ more than the
number attending the Republican National Convention _ are eligible
to attend the three-day event that starts Thursday.
</P>
<P>
   With their eyes fixed on maintaining control of the Texas Senate
and taking over the Texas House for the first time in more than 120
years, Republican activists are optimistic about their chances to
become the state's majority party.
</P>
<P>
   ``This should be a history-making year for the Republican
Party,'' said Mark Sanders, a GOP consultant in Austin. ``It is a
very balanced ticket statewide with individuals who bring their own
strengths to each race.''
</P>
<P>
   State Sen. Jane Nelson, chairwoman of the Texas convention, said
that she is proud of the growth of the party since she was elected
in 1993.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's our year. November is going to be the month the
Republican Party assumes majority party status in this state,''
Nelson said. ``It is so exciting to see the energy in the
Republican Party.''
</P>
<P>
   Lurking not too far below the surface, however, is a division
between social conservatives and the more moderate party members
who have financially supported the GOP for years. Because of the
differences, the convention at times may resemble an unruly
fundamentalist tent revival.
</P>
<P>
   Elected officials fret that the party's sometimes strident
political message and image will scare away the independent voters
needed to win elections. There also is a concern that the GOP is
becoming an exclusive club.
</P>
<P>
   ``The people who elect the party apparatus are not the same
people who elect officials'' to public office, said Rep. Todd
Smith, a freshman Republican House member from Euless who has
butted heads with the GOP's conservative wing.
</P>
<P>
   ``You get into all these stupid fights over what is a
conservative, and there is no single, accepted definition of that
term and people tend to use it for their own purposes,'' Smith
said.
</P>
<P>
   Up to 16,000 GOP activists and family members are expected to
flock to the Fort Worth Convention Center starting Thursday. The
general sessions will be held Friday and Saturday.
</P>
<P>
   So many conventioneers are coming to town that the city's
outdated convention center is bursting at the seams, with some of
the party's caucuses, dinners and receptions scheduled to be held
in nearby hotels, officials said.
</P>
<P>
   ``We have every hotel room booked in Fort Worth and beyond,''
said Nelson, who is from Flower Mound but represents several North
Texas counties. She has helped to coordinate this year's
convention, which will cost about $500,000.
</P>
<P>
   The Texas Christian Coalition is sponsoring a dinner with
Arkansas Gov. Mike Huckabee scheduled to be the keynote speaker.
The new national chairman of the Christian Coalition, Randy Tate,
is also scheduled to appear.
</P>
<P>
   One of the few open convention events is a communitywide,
patriotic rally on Friday in General Worth Square, just north of
the convention center. It will honor Texas veterans.
</P>
<P>
   The theme of the 1998 GOP convention is ``Changing the Course of
Texas History.'' Although Texas is trending toward becoming a
Republican state, Democrats still control the state House and
several statewide offices.
</P>
<P>
   The Texas Republican Party is almost bubbly this year over its
prospects in November. With polls showing him far ahead of
Democratic foe Garry Mauro, Bush is expected to be the first
governor in history to win consecutive four-year terms.
</P>
<P>
   Right behind him is a ticket that party officials said mirrors
the makeup of Texas. Lieutenant governor candidate Rick Perry, land
commissioner nominee Tony Garza and state comptroller hopeful
Carole Keeton Rylander are candidates with something to offer to
every constituency, party activists said.
</P>
<P>
   After wresting control of the state Senate from the Democrats in
1996, there are high hopes among party loyalists that the GOP will
be able to maintain its grip on the Senate while electing eight
additional members to take control of the statehouse.
</P>
<P>
   Despite the prospect of squabbling between conservatives and
moderates, state party Chairwoman Susan Weddington said that,
unlike during previous conventions, there aren't likely to be any
major fights over platform planks and policies.
</P>
<P>
   State Rep. Kim Brimer, who defeated a Democrat to win his
Arlington district in 1989, said delegates can disagree but they
must remember that they represent the party, and should not offend
undecided voters.
</P>
<P>
   ``The most tantamount thing I do is represent my district. I won
it from a Democrat. I can't be a cookie-cutter Republican,'' said
Brimer, who is supportive of Texas House Speaker Pete Laney, a
Democrat.
</P>
<P>
   Even Bush pushes a bipartisan message on the campaign trail.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm not supporting any Democrats, but I'm willing to have
Democrats support me,'' Bush said.
</P>
<P>
   _
</P>
<P>
   (Visit the Star-Telegram's online services on the World Wide
Web: www.star-telegram.com)
</P>
</TEXT>
