<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-06-09 12:29 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A0711 &Cx1f; ttj-z
u e &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-NIGHTINGALES-PREVIEW-     06-09 1169
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-NIGHTINGALES-PREVIEW-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
RAW POWER DRIVES TENNESSEE WILLIAMS PLAY `NOT ABOUT NIGHTINGALES' 

</HEADLINE>
  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  (Eds.: U.S. premiere of play is Wednesday) 
 
By EVERETT EVANS 
c.1998 Houston Chronicle 
<TEXT>
<P>
   HOUSTON _ Tennessee Williams considered ``Not About
Nightingales'' unique among his works.
</P>
<P>
   ``I have never written anything since then that could compete
with it in violence and horror,'' the playwright wrote, recalling
his early, unproduced play about prison atrocities.
</P>
<P>
   That sentence intrigued Vanessa Redgrave when she read it in the
preface to Williams' 1957 success, ``Orpheus Descending.'' Redgrave
starred in the 1989 London production of ``Orpheus,'' while her
background reading launched her search for the earlier ``lost''
play.
</P>
<P>
   ``I knew this subject had impassioned and outraged Tennessee
when he read news stories about it,'' Redgrave said. ``Because of
that paragraph in his preface to `Orpheus Descending,' I knew he
still felt strongly about it, even years later. Given the writer he
was, I just expected a play from him on this topic would be
terrific.''
</P>
<P>
   The result of Redgrave's fascination is the world premiere of
``Not About Nightingales,'' which stirred considerable excitement
when it opened in March at London's Royal National Theater of Great
Britain. A collaboration among the National, Redgrave's Moving
Theater and Houston's Alley Theater, the production will have its
U.S. premiere Wednesday at the Aerial Theater in Bayou Place in
Houston.
</P>
<P>
   To characterize ``Not About Nightingales'' as the dramatic event
of the year requires no hyperbole whatsoever. Just consider the
facts. Here is the long-overdue premiere of a previously unseen
work by the legendary creator of ``The Glass Menagerie,'' ``A
Streetcar Named Desire,'' ``Cat on a Hot Tin Roof'' and other
modern classics _ the man many regard as America's greatest
playwright. In ``Nightingales,'' playgoers will find a work
atypical of the writer _ essentially political rather than personal
in nature. Yet they also will find early expression of themes that
recur throughout Williams' oeuvre.
</P>
<P>
   The director is Trevor Nunn, the National's new artistic
director, formerly in the same position with the Royal Shakespeare
Company and one of the world's most-renowned theater artists. His
credits including ``Nicholas Nickleby'' and ``Les Miserables''
(both co-directed with John Caird), ``Arcadia,'' ``Cats,''
``Aspects of Love'' and ``Sunset Boulevard.''
</P>
<P>
   Williams (1911-83) wrote ``Not About Nightingales'' in 1938, at
age 27 _ seven years before his breakthrough to fame with the 1945
Broadway premiere of ``The Glass Menagerie,'' which announced his
arrival as a mature dramatist. Yet ``Nightingales'' is not the work
of a beginner. Rather, it is the culmination of several years of
apprentice playwriting, much in the socially conscious,
Depression-era vein of Clifford Odets' ``Waiting for Lefty'' and
``Awake and Sing.''
</P>
<P>
   As early as 1935, Williams had ``his Cairo! Shanghai! Bombay!''
produced by an amateur group. In 1937, a St. Louis amateur troupe
called the Mummers staged his ``Candles to the Sun,'' about a
miners' strike, and, later that year, his next proletarian drama,
``Fugitive Kind,'' set in a waterfront flophouse.
</P>
<P>
   The inspiration for ``Nightingales'' came in September 1938,
when Williams read a newspaper account of events at a prison in
Holmesburg, Pa. Convicts on a hunger strike were locked in a
steam-heated cell called ``the Klondike,'' and four were roasted
alive.
</P>
<P>
   The outraged writer began his play, shaping it as a titanic
power struggle between Butch O'Fallon, the convict who leads the
hunger strike, and Boss Whalen, the sadistic warden. Caught up in
that struggle are Canary Jim, a sensitive prison trustee due for
parole, and Eva Crane, the warden's new stenographer, who is
attracted to Jim but must fend off the warden's advances.
</P>
<P>
   Significantly, ``Nightingales'' was the first play Williams
signed with his ``nom de plume'' ``Tennessee,'' rather than his
birth name of Thomas Lanier Williams. He included it in a package
of works entered in a contest held by New York's famed Group
Theater. Though Williams did not win the playwriting prize, which
would have guaranteed production, his promise was acknowledged with
a $100 prize for a set of one-acts (but no nod for
``Nightingales''). Nightingales went unproduced.
</P>
<P>
   Scholars knew of ``Nightingales'' and the other early Williams
works, which are mentioned in passing in biographies. Yet no one
capable of launching a production took up the cause, until
Redgrave.
</P>
<P>
   Shortly after Vanessa and brother Corin Redgrave founded their
Moving Theater in 1993, Maria St. Just, executor of Williams'
estate, located a copy of the manuscript and gave it to Vanessa.
After some research at the University of Texas, other materials
would be used to shape an edition for the play's world premier in
London.
</P>
<P>
   Redgrave considers ``Nightingales'' important in our
understanding of Williams.
</P>
<P>
   ``First of all, this is the work of a young guy _ about 26 when
he started it. We have to realize that at this point, he'd only
worked with small troupes, limited in their resources and
experience. He didn't know the great international movements, the
innovations of (directors) Erwin Piscator and Max Reinhardt. What's
extraordinary is that ... he wrote a trailblazing work unlimited by
the common wisdom as to what you can do onstage. He disregarded the
rules. That's the only way great drama is written.''
</P>
<P>
   Nunn believes the play went unproduced for ``relatively
undramatic'' reasons. Because it was based on a real-life case
(still wending its way through the judicial system when Williams
wrote it) and because of the accusatory nature of the writing,
producers likely would have considered its presentation impossible
at the time. There were other controversial aspects, including an
openly gay character called the Queen.
</P>
<P>
   By the early '40s, Williams put the script aside and moved on to
other projects: the play ``Battle of Angels,'' which would be his
first Broadway-bound production, but would close in Boston in 1941;
and ``Portrait of a Girl in Glass,'' the short story that
ultimately would evolve into ``The Glass Menagerie.''
</P>
<P>
   Corin Redgrave was impressed with ``Nightingales''' ``sheer
skill and grasp and daring'' upon his first reading of the script
in early 1996.
</P>
<P>
   ``Most of all, I was impressed with the subject. Though it's not
an uncommon theme, it's certainly not something I'd expected of
Williams.''
</P>
<P>
   Despite talk of ``Nightingales''' prospects for New York or
London's West End, Nunn said nothing is definite beyond the Houston
engagement.
</P>
<P>
   ``All things are possible,'' Nunn said. ``It would be wonderful
if someone would come forward and say they want to take the play to
New York. We need a producer who wants to do it. We're waiting with
baited breath and increasing anxiety. We love the play.''
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
XXXX END OF STORY &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
