<SLUG> BC-YIP-COLUMN-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
FEES DIMINISHING PROGRAMS' ALLURE 

</HEADLINE>
  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  By PAMELA YIP 
c.1998 Houston Chronicle 
<TEXT>
<P>
   Direct investment programs, which allow small investors to buy
stock directly from a company for little or no fees, have been a
popular option.
</P>
<P>
   But the programs, which include dividend reinvestment plans or
``DRIPs,'' have lost some of their shine because many companies
have started charging when they've added features or created a new
program.
</P>
<P>
   ``In truth, there are companies that may no longer be
appropriate for those who want to contribute small amounts of money
on a regular basis,'' said Vita Nelson, publisher of The Moneypaper
in Mamaroneck, N.Y., a publication that tracks direct investment
plans. ``They impose fees for cash investments and for reinvesting
dividends.''
</P>
<P>
   Charles Carlson, editor of the DRIP Investor in Hammond, Ind., a
newsletter that focuses on dividend reinvestment plans, said there
are generally three types of fees:
</P>
<P>
   _ A one-time enrollment fee, ranging from $5 to $15. ``When you
start to get north of $10, it starts to get a little excessive,''
Carlson said.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; _  &LR; Fees of $1 to $10 for each purchase, depending on the size
of your investment &UR; . &LR;  ``When you start to get above $5 per
purchase, that starts to get a little aggressive,'' Carlson said.
</P>
<P>
   _ A fee to reinvest dividends. A company may charge a percentage
of the amount reinvested, up to a set total. Carlson said the
amounts range from 50 cents to $5 per reinvestment.
</P>
<P>
   ``That's a detestable fee based on principle,'' he said. ``If I
am willing to be a committed investor to the company, they're going
to charge me a fee? To me, that seems ludicrous.''
</P>
<P>
   As plans add costs, they are also offering added services.
</P>
<P>
   ``A lot of the companies have bells and whistles in the plans,''
Carlson said.
</P>
<P>
   Those extras include allowing purchases using automatic
deductions from bank accounts, earmarking funds to go directly to
an Individual Retirement Account, allowing investors to borrow
against the value of their DRIP shares, and buying and selling
stocks on a daily basis instead of only on a set date.
</P>
<P>
   That goes beyond the services offered by DRIPs in the past,
Carlson said.
</P>
<P>
   Fees anger Nelson, who did something about it.
</P>
<P>
   The Moneypaper recently yanked General Electric Co. from its MP
63, an index of companies offering direct investment plans, because
GE started charging a fee of ``at least'' $3 per cash investment.
</P>
<P>
   ``On a typical $50 investment, the new `no-load' plan would
deduct over $3 or more than 6 percent of the investor's funds,
which is excessive by any standards, so it's poison to the small
investor,'' Nelson said. ``We view such heavy charges as a betrayal
of the shareholders who have long supported this company.''
</P>
<P>
   Officials of General Electric said the fee is necessary to pay
for the program's operating costs.
</P>
<P>
   The new direct stock purchase plan, which took effect this
month, is an enhancement of the dividend reinvestment plan, said
Tony Zehnder, GE spokesman.
</P>
<P>
   There is a $7.50 fee to enroll in the plan and a $3 fee for each
additional stock purchase, he said.
</P>
<P>
   ``The fees are for purchases,'' Zehnder said. ``There is no fee
for having the dividends reinvested.''
</P>
<P>
   The push for fees is coming from transfer agents, typically
banks that maintain records of stock owners. Most fees by companies
with DRIPs are used to pay transfer agents, Carlson said.
</P>
<P>
   ``Transfer agents are pushing a fee agenda in order to have more
companies do this in order to generate income for themselves,'' he
said. ``These programs are very important to transfer agents.''
</P>
<P>
   The fees also steer away investors who are not likely to invest
a significant amount of money.
</P>
<P>
   ``For some companies, the fees represent a hurdle rate for a
committed investor,'' Carlson said. ``Fees help defray the cost of
operating the plan and they filter out some of the investors who
are tire-kicking and are apt to stay in the plans shorter than the
long-term investor.''
</P>
<P>
   All this doesn't mean that you ought to write off all direct
investment plans.
</P>
<P>
   ``Don't get the impression that most plans are no longer viable
for the small investor,'' Nelson said. ``That is not true. Most
plans have not changed. Most plans do not charge fees.''
</P>
<P>
   But it is increasingly important to consider the fees before
investing in a dividend reinvestment plan, Carlson said.
</P>
<P>
   ``People need to evaluate what is the fee compared with other
companies of comparable quality,'' he said. ``How does the fee
compare to what my other options are in the non-DRIP world?''
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &QL; 
Pamela Yip can receive electronic mail via the Internet. Address
your comments and questions to pamela.yip(at)chron.com, or call
(713) 220-2000 and enter access code 1003. &QL; 
 &QL; 
XXXX END OF STORY &QL;
</P>
