<SLUG> BC-TRULY-COLUMN-TEX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
REMEMBER, WE ARE FREE _ AND LET'S KEEP IT THAT WAY
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By PAT TRULY 
c.1998 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   Gee, I got back to work a week ago, having been on the road, and
durned if all heck hadn't broken loose during my absence.
</P>
<P>
   House Speaker Newt Gingrich, taking his direction from the Pat
Robertson wing of the Republican Party, was busily undermining 20
years of U.S. support for peace in the Middle East.
</P>
<P>
   The Western Athletic Conference discovered that it was
unworkable after all. I suspect that the crowning blow was the
proposal to add the Universities of Beirut and Greenland to the
far-flung league.
</P>
<P>
   Another wacked-out kid had shot up another school, killing other
kids.
</P>
<P>
   And then Barry Goldwater died.
</P>
<P>
   I had not been a Goldwater admirer back in the 1960s (in my
heart, I doubted he was right about some things), but I came to
appreciate his love of personal liberty later on. Indeed, by
accident I even had a treasured exchange of letters with him in
1993.
</P>
<P>
   I had wondered, in a column, if Goldwater might not later have
regretted his ``extremism in defense of liberty is no vice''
statement at the 1964 Republican convention, considering that so
many people took it as a defense of extremism in general. The
column was carried in an Arizona newspaper and brought to the
former senator's attention. So he wrote to me (addressing me as
``Miss Truly'') to thank me for ``bringing the statement to the
attention of this generation,'' to say that he thought it had been
borrowed from one of the old Greeks and to add that he remained
proud of what he said and would say the same thing again.
</P>
<P>
   I responded to thank him for his letter and to point out that I
was actually a ``hairy-legged, balding, middle-aged Mister'' and
not a ``Miss.'' He seemed to find this amusing and wrote again to
say he was sorry for the mistake.
</P>
<P>
   Two things stood out about this exchange of notes: First, his
letters obviously were from him, and not boilerplated by some
secretary. Second, Barry Goldwater was not a man to change his mind
or harbor regrets about his straightforward conservative
principles.
</P>
<P>
   He had been ill this year, and making few public pronouncements,
but I have to wonder what Goldwater must have thought about some of
the ``conservative'' stuff going on in the America of Randy Tate,
James Dobson and Ken Starr.
</P>
<P>
   It ill serves Goldwater to give him credit for the current wave
of conservatism, which often seems based less on his view of
freedom than it is on a call for state control over the private
lives and morals of citizens.
</P>
<P>
   Driving around this country, you become aware of just how free a
people we are. Oh, we are asked to observe speed limits and other
laws enacted for our safety and for the public health and
well-being. But ours is still a land where a great measure of
diversity and even personal eccentricity is tolerated. Individual
initiative is still treasured. Look at the businesses starting up.
Anyone, literally, can do it. Look at all the thriving churches.
Listen to the free speech being expressed. Hark to the political
discourse (if you can find it lurking someplace behind the
name-calling).
</P>
<P>
   We are free, folks. We have liberties that others can only dream
about. People who keep saying Microsoft is being sued for being
successful miss the point. Microsoft is being sued because others
have to have the same chance Microsoft had. America is still about
opportunity.
</P>
<P>
   It is the Big-Brother-like brand of government intrusion upon
the individual (supported by a lot of folks who are uncomfortable
with the Bill of Rights) that Goldwater decried and I find
offensive. I may not agree with the way that give-everybody-a-gun
advocates read the Second Amendment, but I'd rather leave it at
that than risk losing stuff like free speech and separation of
church and state and protection from unreasonable searches. To me,
it is unthinkable that conservatives would want to change a word in
the Bill of Rights.
</P>
<P>
   There are twin related threats to such an American vision of
responsible freedom. Self-serving religio-patriotism (the kind that
wants to mix country and theology and impose them on others) is
one, and our national love affair with victimization is the other.
We seem to revel in considering ourselves victims of racism,
victims of the Supreme Court, victims of government, victims of big
business, victims of death rays from outer space, victims of
teachers unions, victims of sexism, victims of the United Nations,
victims of affirmative action, victims of technology, you name it.
</P>
<P>
   Americans _ conservative, liberal or whatever _ can do better
than that.
</P>
<P>
   (Pat Truly is a columnist and editorial writer for the Fort
Worth Star-Telegram. You can call him at (817) 390-7751. Visit the
Star-Telegram's online services on the World Wide Web:
www.star-telegram.com)
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-06-09-98 1235EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
