<HEADLINE>
JURORS RECONSIDER CONVICTION OF TEXAS BAR OWNER 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By MELISSA PRENTICE  
 c.1998 San Antonio Express-News  
<TEXT>
<P>
   SAN ANTONIO _ Minutes after Joe Kennedy was sentenced in May to
probation for raping a female employee of his downtown Irish pub,
five jurors told him they had made the wrong decision.
</P>
<P>
   ``They said, `We want to make this right. We know you are
innocent,''' the former bar owner said Monday. ``I'm glad they are
going with their consciences.''
</P>
<P>
   District Judge Sid Harle will decide Friday if the jurors can
testify as part of a motion for a new trial.
</P>
<P>
   Defense attorney Catherine Babbitt asked for a new trial after
the five jurors from Kennedy's trial signed sworn statements saying
they were uncomfortable about voting to convict Kennedy.
</P>
<P>
   Babbitt has until Friday to provide the judge with court
decisions supporting a juror's right to testify about what happened
in closed-door jury deliberations.
</P>
<P>
   Jurors deliberated more than 14 hours over two days before
convicting Kennedy of sexual assault on May 18. It took only
minutes for jurors to agree to sentence Kennedy to five years
probation and six months in jail.
</P>
<P>
   If convicted at a second trial, he could face up to life in
prison.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm willing to take the chance of a long prison term,''
Kennedy said Monday. ``I did not commit this crime and I will prove
my innocence in court.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-06-09-98 1252EDT &QL; 
