<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-AUTHOR-MITCHARD-SPI </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
AUTHOR'S CHALLENGE NOW IS FOR SECOND NOVEL 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By JOHN MARSHALL  
 c.1998 Seattle Post-Intelligencer  
<TEXT>
<P>
   The first time Oprah Winfrey called Jacquelyn Mitchard, the talk
show host was merely a fan wanting to share how much she enjoyed
the writer's first novel, ``The Deep End of the Ocean.'' But
Winfrey also made it clear that she wouldn't be having Mitchard on
her show because she had learned that discussing fiction on
television was ratings suicide.
</P>
<P>
   The next time Winfrey called Mitchard, which was just three
weeks later, the talk show host confessed she just could not get
the book out of her mind, had bought copies as gifts for all of her
producers and had instructed them to find a way to make fiction
somehow work on television. What they came up with _ and what they
wanted Mitchard to appear on as the first guest _ was something
they were going to call Oprah's Book Club.
</P>
<P>
   ``I thought then,'' Mitchard recalled recently in Seattle,
``that if there never got to be a second Oprah Winfrey book, at
least my book got to be the first Oprah Winfrey book. I also
thought it could do something to enhance sales.''
</P>
<P>
   ``The Deep End of the Ocean'' became an instant publishing
legend. Within hours of its Winfrey anointing, the list of people
requesting a copy in the New York Public Library grew to 4,000. And
within 10 days, the crush of demand prompted publisher Viking to
rush 800,000 copies into print. Nine months later, there are 3
million copies of ``The Deep End of the Ocean'' in print, with a
film version starring Michelle Pfeiffer and Whoopi Goldberg
scheduled for fall release.
</P>
<P>
   Few writers would dare let themselves dream dreams as grand as
what happened to Mitchard and her heart-searing novel about a
family's worst nightmare _ the sudden disappearance of a child in a
busy moment of distraction in a public place and the period of
family turmoil afterward, amid the lingering guilt and grief.
</P>
<P>
   For the author herself, the huge success of ``The Deep End of
the Ocean'' also set up a daunting challenge _ what she would do
for a second novel to fulfill her $500,000, two-book contract with
her publisher. Second acts for writers with first-time success are
often as daunting as they are for athletes and other public
figures; there is widespread belief in a curse called the
``sophomore jinx.''
</P>
<P>
   Life had already dealt Mitchard far more daunting challenges,
including caring for her newspaper editor husband in his losing
battle with colon cancer until his death in 1993, then raising
their four children on her own in Madison, Wis., as she attempted
to expand her writing from her newspaper journalism to a first
novel. But her difficult struggles _ at one time the single
mother's checking account dwindled down to $86 _ only seemed to
further deepen her rock-solid Midwestern level-headedness.
</P>
<P>
   So this was Mitchard's mind-set as she approached her second
novel: ``It's a devil's bargain. Whatever I write can't sell better
than my first book did; there has to be a shortfall. . . .
</P>
<P>
   ``But I wanted to avoid writing another family drama. I wanted
to do a different kind of story because at the least _ at the very
least _ I didn't want people to be able to say I did the same book
twice. . . . And it was also important for me to have it over with,
that dreaded second novel. I wasn't going to fuss around for six
years and have someone then say I hadn't lived up to the promise of
my first novel.''
</P>
<P>
   Once again, Mitchard _ who is no woo-woo spiritualist _ had the
essence of her novel's plot come to her in a dream. It is set in
San Antonio, Texas, where Mitchard had recently adopted a
2-year-old, and it centered on a 14-year-old girl's first love for
a charismatic prison inmate.
</P>
<P>
   Mitchard's ``The Most Wanted'' (Viking, 407 pages, $24.95) is an
unabashed women's tale of life changes wrought by love and romance,
with both the 14-year-old woman-child and her rescuer-mentor, a
40-year-old public-assistance attorney, narrating their heartening
stories in alternating chapters. It is a character-driven novel
where leisurely pace and small pleasures gradually give way to a
powerful sense of gathering doom, although the doom never quite
dims the expectation that the heroines' selflessness will be
rewarded and love will triumph.
</P>
<P>
   As the 45-year-old author emphasized, ``My goal with this book
wasn't lofty. I just wanted to write a love story that was poignant
and dangerous and sexy and one that didn't make you hate yourself
in the morning for having read it. I really think that topics like
romantic love deserve better treatment in books. After all, who in
the hell doesn't get involved in romantic love in their lives _
we're all thinking about it all the time.''
</P>
<P>
   Mitchard _ who jokes about having ``dated more dentists than any
woman in America'' _ created a love interest in ``The Most Wanted''
that had her friends and even the author herself salivating.
Charley Wilder is a carpenter by trade but more of an artisan, a
soft-spoken and caring younger man of unassuming strength who
listens, really listens, to women.
</P>
<P>
   ``I made up this guy and kept e-mailing my friends who all
agreed how cool he was,'' Mitchard recalled. ``We all kept saying,
`If only Charley was a real human being, instead of a made-up
character.'''
</P>
<P>
   Then into Mitchard's life _ or actually into a tiling job in
Mitchard's bathroom _ stepped Chris Sornberger three months ago.
This carpenter and artisan did not look exactly as Charley Wilder
does in the book, but almost everything else about him seemed to
fit with Mitchard's descriptions, right down to how he slept at
home not in a bed but rather in a Yucatan hammock (edited out of
the book).
</P>
<P>
   This was life imitating art beyond all reason. Or as Mitchard
put it: ``If there is a dimension of life that you might call
destiny, it was like a big rubber hammer hitting me over the
head.''
</P>
<P>
   So Mitchard told Sornberger, who is 12 years younger, that
perhaps he ought to read ``The Most Wanted'' before they got
involved any further. And that did not deter him in the slightest.
The two were married only a month after their initial meeting on a
bathroom remodeling.
</P>
<P>
   So now it's farewell to all those stories that once dubbed
Mitchard, as she recalled with a smile, ``the little widow who
could.''
</P>
<P>
   But Mitchard and her remarkable success will continue to serve
as testament to what true grit and high energy and profound
graciousness can reap, even after personal tragedy.
</P>
<P>
   ``The difference between me and somebody who would not try to
live a larger life after a disaster is that I was too afraid of
withering from boredom to not take the risk,'' Mitchard emphasized.
``And once you say, `I'm willing to walk the walk no matter where
it takes me,' then you can do it.
</P>
<P>
   ``But you also have to be willing to do whatever it takes, which
is often a hell of a lot more than you think you can do. But that
turned out to be healthy for me _ it forced me back on reserves I
might not have known I had. I didn't want to live a life where
people think isn't she brave. I'd much rather have people think I'm
goofy _ and I wanted children not to grow up and be timid either.
</P>
<P>
   ``I am a most ordinary person. I am medium everything, even a
medium talent. But I will push that as far as I possibly can.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
