<HEADLINE>
THERE'S NOTHING LIKE BEING A KID IN SUMMER 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By JON HAHN  
 c.1998 Seattle Post-Intelligencer  
<TEXT>
<P>
   Do you remember when May turned to June turned to Summer and you
were still trapped behind a school desk while the sounds and smells
of summer seemed to say: Six times seven is 42 and it doesn't make
any difference because in exactly two more weeks we'll be outta
here and riding our bikes all day and climbing trees and checking
out whose garden will offer up the best filched tomatoes(?)
</P>
<P>
   It was anticipation. It was knowing that out there, just beyond
the schoolyard, there were days when you actually woke up early and
made your bed and wolfed down breakfast and ran out the door to do
maybe absolutely nothing.
</P>
<P>
   ``And what are you going to do today?
</P>
<P>
   ``Oh, nothing . . .''
</P>
<P>
   It was a time when being farmed-out was every kid's dream, going
to the grandparents' farm or the aunt and uncle's farm or the
neighbor's family farm, where there were real cows and horses and
pigs and real milk and helping with chores you wouldn't be caught
dead doing at home.
</P>
<P>
   Summer was not having to come home from school and change into
play clothes because summer meant you didn't even have to put shoes
on if you didn't want to, and getting dirty was part of summer's
territory.
</P>
<P>
   But on the leading edge of summer, we sat listless at our school
desks and passed notes about Albert having to go to the dreaded
Summer School because he couldn't remember six times seven is 42.
And kids from St. Bartholomew's School would ride their bikes by
our open school windows and taunt us with the fact that Catholic
school kids got out two weeks earlier and being Catholic sounded
like a pretty good deal because they got out of school early and
didn't face the prospect of losing several weeks of summer at a
distinctly Protestant invention called Vacation Bible School
because Catholic kids seemed to get their religion pounded up their
noses every day of the year anyway and they even took communion
long before the rest of us even had to start learning about Martin
Luther and the grace of God, which didn't seem to make much of an
impression when you were a kid on the leading edge of summer.
</P>
<P>
   June _ actually, right after the Memorial Day parade _ was when
``Girls Baseball'' started night games at the not-so-elegant
stadium with wooden bleacher bench seats. These Girls of Summer had
been Rosie the Riveters during The Big One, and had filled-in the
very-minor league demand for local baseball games. Entire families
went for loose-change admission prices and watched teams like the
Olympia Queens take on the Rockolas while nighthawks circled above
us and occasional balls were knocked over the wood fence into the
leftover Victory Gardens surrounding the ballpark.
</P>
<P>
   Summer from the front end was the sound of the Milwaukee Road
and the Chicago and North Western trains blowing their whistles as
they crossed one another's rights-of-way, and the not-so-distant
chance of crouching on a wooden overpass with your country cousin,
waiting for the chance to drop stones down the locomotive smoke
stack and coming home with soot all over you.
</P>
<P>
   In June, there were games at night because you were allowed to
stay out long after the street lights went on, and your grandmother
would let you use an old quart Mason jar for catching fireflies,
which some kids called lightning bugs. And you could sleep on the
screened porch and hear the adults across the street laughing and
drinking as their swing creaked back and forth, and it wouldn't be
long until you also could hear the night sounds from the annual
carnival that ran a whole week in the Sears, Roebuck parking lot.
</P>
<P>
   Whole summers of ``doing nothing'' were jammed with unending
marbles games and top-spinning contests and inner-tube gun wars and
loud clackety-clackety races down the blocks of WPA sidewalks on
steel roller-skate wheels nailed to wooden crates still smelling of
oranges and celery.
</P>
<P>
   But in the early part of June, before we could chant ``School's
out! School's out! Someone left the monkeys out!'' we were still
trapped behind those desks, gazing out the open windows like
animals in those almost-real enclosures at the zoo where you had to
hold your sister's hand so she didn't get kidnapped by rumored
unsavories who could blend in with the crowds, which is why your
mother could never actually point out someone who was liable to be
a kidnapper.
</P>
<P>
   And in June, it wasn't kidnappers snatching us away; it was the
sounds and smells of summer coming through the classroom window,
the butterfly zigzagging from one blossom to another on the catalpa
trees ringing the schoolyard.
</P>
<P>
   And the alleged fact that six times seven is 42 was as
unfathomable as the Catechism because when you're young and it's
June, what's really important is knowing what time the Good Humor
guy comes down your street.
</P>
<P>
   STILL HERE: Reports of My Demise, or possible retirement, are
drastically premature. Last week's column must have read like a
swan song to some, but you shall not be that lucky. Hahn is alive
and well and hopes to be gainfully employed at the P-I for years to
come, for which at least his creditors and the family dog remain
thankful.
</P>
<P>
   Jon Hahn is a staff columnist for the P-I. He can be reached at
206-448-8317 or e-mail him at jonhahn(at)seattle-pi.com
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-06-09-98 1315EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
