<SLUG> BC-DIRECTOR-FITZGERALD-SPI </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
MOVIE ABOUT OUT-OF-THE-CLOSET TRAVAILS REFLECTS CANADIAN DIRECTOR'S
LIFE 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By PAULA NECHAK  
 c.1998 Seattle Post-Intelligencer  
<TEXT>
<P>
   SEATTLE _ Imagine you're a youth who left home and didn't return
for 10 years because your family ostracized you for being gay.
</P>
<P>
   Imagine you've come up with the idea to make a movie about it.
It's wildly anarchic and chronicles a teenage boy's suicide, a
father's alcoholism, a mother's disappearance and a daughter's
wedding that will reunite the clan in a weekend of trauma and
truth.
</P>
<P>
   Then toss in the fact that it's told in flashbacks, set in a
remote Nova Scotia home and uses a lush, overripe garden as a messy
metaphor.
</P>
<P>
   And add that its cast mostly consists of unknown actors from
Canadian theater and TV, with the most familiar face that of New
Zealand actress Kerry Fox (``An Angel at My Table,'' ``Shallow
Grave,'' ``Welcome to Sarajevo''), who plays foul-mouthed sister
Rosemary.
</P>
<P>
   Does it stand a chance at the box office? If you said no, think
again.
</P>
<P>
   ``The Hanging Garden,'' which is 29-year-old Thom Fitzgerald's
first feature film after working in the theater, has been one of
Canada's biggest domestic hits of all time.
</P>
<P>
   The movie won prizes at the Toronto Film Festival and won for
best screenplay at the Canadian Genie Awards _ the equivalent of
America's Oscars _ beating Atom Egoyan's critically praised ``The
Sweet Hereafter.''
</P>
<P>
   ``I couldn't be happier,'' confesses Fitzgerald, on a visit to
Seattle for screenings of ``The Hanging Garden'' at the Seattle
International Film Festival. His dark, non-literal comedy has just
opened in New York and is set to be released in Seattle on July 3.
</P>
<P>
   Fitzgerald says his script evolved from a very literal place,
then ``worked backward,'' diverging from real life. It took three
shaky years for the story to make it from the first draft to the
screen.
</P>
<P>
   ``My desire to write it came from feeling far away from my
family. But the root of the story is the idea of the teenage
William killing himself. I certainly never tried to hang myself in
a garden. I'd never do that. But the feelings William has over
losing hope, well, I did experience that as a teenager.''
</P>
<P>
   But his teen angst didn't result only from his being gay,
Fitzgerald says. ``I would venture to guess more teens than not
feel a complete loss of power. They're close to adulthood but they
can't make a blessed decision. After awhile, that weighs pretty
heavily.''
</P>
<P>
   Although a decade has passed, Fitzgerald says he still struggles
with the idea that he's ``out of the closet'' to his family. ``My
mother, when I was 18, through her sobs, made me swear not to tell
the rest of the household,'' he laughs. ``It's hard when you can't
talk to family about your friends, love life or even your work.
That repression certainly pushed me to make the film in the first
place.''
</P>
<P>
   ``The Hanging Garden'' is full of mystery and allusion. The
director says that it has something to do with his ``objections to
movies and everything else being so very literal these days.''
</P>
<P>
   The gay subtext and lack of name actors could have become an
obstacle to getting financing for the movie.
</P>
<P>
   ``It hurt,'' he admits, ``but not much. The non-literal aspect
gave people more pause.''
</P>
<P>
   ``As far as casting a name, I thought I'd start at the top and
since I know Andrew Macdonald's mother (Macdonald produced
``Shallow Grave`` and ``Trainspotting''), I thought perhaps he'd
give Kerry Fox the script since they worked together on `Shallow
Grave.' They're great friends and I would never have been able to
get it into her hands had I sent it to her agent at ICM. I'm sure
they would have thrown it in the trash.''
</P>
<P>
   He recalls, ``I met her in London and not only is she a great
actress, she's an even nicer human being. She agreed to do it and
the next day I met with Channel 4 Films (one of the producers).
Luckily they realized they not only had a script with Kerry Fox
attached but it helped that one of the programming executives was a
lesbian and had a huge crush on her.''
</P>
<P>
   With Egoyan, David Cronenberg, Patricia Rozema and now
Fitzgerald making Canada a significant contributor to the
iconoclastic art-film world, does the director think his country
has a particularly distinct sensibility?
</P>
<P>
   ``I hear all the time how Canadian films are dark and often
cross the lines of good taste. It's true of Egoyan and Cronenberg's
films and other things like Lynne Stopkewich's `Kissed,' as well as
my movie. But there are all these other films out there. There's an
entire population of filmmakers who closely emulate what American
moviemakers do, but on a smaller scale.''
</P>
<P>
   And are Canadians more tolerant of small, gay, art films? After
all, in the past few years the Canadian film industry has praised
and given awards to such movies as ``Lilies'' and ``When Night Is
Falling.''
</P>
<P>
   Fitzgerald notes that ``the Oscars, by contrast, still reward
commercial success. You rarely have a film win prizes that doesn't
do big business.''
</P>
<P>
   ``In Canada, it's different because one doesn't necessarily
expect a good film to make money. After all, 2 percent of Canadian
box office dollars are spent to see Canadian films. That's a low
ratio compared to what we shell out to see American movies.''
</P>
<P>
   He's recently completed a second film, even though he calls
directing ``a nightmare, a horror, because there are all these
people lined up waiting to ask questions.''
</P>
<P>
   ``I didn't have any answers for any of them but it was all stuff
a director needs to know. Making movies is very different from the
theater where there are more actors than crew,'' he says.
</P>
<P>
   He acknowledges that the whole process got easier the second
time behind the camera.
</P>
<P>
   ``What made `The Hanging Garden' so hard is that everything I
said and tried to do was up for discussion. It wasn't trusted, but
judged, because it was my first film. On my second film, nothing I
said was ever questioned and I think they thought I was smarter
than I actually am.''
</P>
<P>
   He adds, with a laugh, ``I hope there will be a middle ground.
I'll have a sophomore flop and then things can finally get back to
normal.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-06-09-98 1316EDT &QL; 
