<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BARNICLE-COLUMN-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
HERE'S A GREAT ATHLETE WHO MOVES COUCHES FOR SPENDING MONEY
</HEADLINE>
  (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By MIKE BARNICLE 
c.1998 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   One of the country's greatest athletes was on the third floor of
a gray Victorian on Dana Street in Cambridge yesterday lugging
boxes of books out to a purple moving truck parked at the curb. A
week earlier, Jamie Koven, a 25-year-old graduate of Brown
University, stood on a platform near Lyon, France, as a band played
the Star Spangled Banner while he was presented with the World
Championship medal for single-scull rowing.
</P>
<P>
   ``Thirty countries participated,'' Koven was saying in between
trips to the top floor. ``Twenty-four guys competed to see who
would represent the United States. Only one got to represent our
country.''
</P>
<P>
   ``You?'' he was asked.
</P>
<P>
   ``Me,'' he said humbly. ``It was really neat. I beat a German
guy who had won Olympic gold medals in 1992 and 1996. Third place
went to a British guy who had one Olympic gold and one bronze. It
was nice.''
</P>
<P>
   Koven is from Green Village in New Jersey. He attended St.
Paul's in Concord, N.H., prior to Brown, where he majored in
mechanical engineering. He is a big, strong kid _ 6-foot-4, 200
pounds _ who is out on the Charles River at dawn and again at dusk,
practicing, when he is not lugging beds, books, and pianos for
Larry O'Toole, who owns Gentle Giant Movers.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is tremendous for keeping in shape,'' Koven declared,
drenched from the aerobics of running between house and truck.
``It's great cross-training.''
</P>
<P>
   ``I would be willing to bet that the men Jamie beat returned to
their countries with huge headlines,'' O'Toole said. ``And here we
have, literally, one of the world's finest athletes and nobody
knows it because his sport isn't accorded any attention here.''
</P>
<P>
   On Sunday, the Bulls played the Jazz for the basketball
championship of the globe. The NBA features Michael Jordan, the
most famous athlete in the whole universe. But it also features a
cast of felons and perverts like Dennis Rodman who get millions to
perform with no requirement to behave. Koven _ in a single day _
works harder than a Rodman or a Shaquille O'Neal do in a week and
he symbolizes the pride of athleticism far better than many who are
displayed daily on television.
</P>
<P>
   But Koven's is a solitary enterprise: One man in one boat on a
flat surface of water racing against a current as well as the
others out there alongside him. It is an old sport, a purely
amateur enterprise played out a long way from the celebrity that
accrues to those who play our big games.
</P>
<P>
   Monday, Koven worked with O'Toole, John Brokars, a rower from
Northeastern, Greg Young of the University of New Hampshire team,
and Rob Hellman from Cornell. Here we had one sport's own version
of Michael Jordan _ Koven _ tilting a daybed down three flights of
narrow stairs.
</P>
<P>
   He is a wonderfully gifted amateur athlete trying to make enough
money to compete in the World Cup tournament in Europe this summer.
He has a couple of corporate sponsors to help pay the tab, but
moves couches for spending money.
</P>
<P>
   ``I have to fund the trip myself,'' Koven pointed out. ``The
World Cup takes place across seven weeks. That's a lot of money so
I'm always looking for sponsors. It starts next week in Brussels,
moves to the Henley Regatta in England July 4, and the last race is
in Lucerne, Switzerland.''
</P>
<P>
   ``An athlete of Jamie's stature would get great coverage in
those other countries,'' O'Toole stated. ``Here, we don't even
cover rowing in the newspapers or on TV. It's too bad because Jamie
is a wonderful example of what is possible when you combine skill
with dedication and hard work.''
</P>
<P>
   Professional hockey players disgraced the country and themselves
during the Olympics. Basketball, baseball, and football have thrown
their titles open to the highest bidder and richest owners. And, in
Cambridge yesterday, one of America's best was moving furniture
through a muggy morning in order to earn money to represent the
United States with pride, integrity, and the kind of character
missing among so many whom we foolishly regard as role models
simply because they happen to play a more popular sport.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
