<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BUSTAMANTE-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
FORMER CONGRESSMAN BEGINS PROBATION 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By JACQUE CROUSE  
 c.1998 San Antonio Express-News  
<TEXT>
<P>
   SAN ANTONIO _ A Hispanic rights organization is asking President
Clinton to pardon a former U.S. congressman who was booted from
office and later imprisoned on federal racketeering and bribery
charges.
</P>
<P>
   Former Rep. Albert G. Bustamante, D-Texas, concluded his prison
sentence Monday for the 1993 conviction, but must serve two years
of probation.
</P>
<P>
   Mario Obledo, president of the California Coalition of Hispanic
Organizations, has urged the president to pardon the former Texas
lawmaker, according to a letter Bustamante shared Monday.
</P>
<P>
   Obledo could not be reached for comment.
</P>
<P>
   The letter says Bustamante was found guilty of ``sham'' charges
and asked for a pardon.
</P>
<P>
   ``A pardon is not what is important to me,'' Bustamante said.
``I and my family have gone through it all. But what I want to get
across, for people to understand, is how they (prosecutors) have
really misused the power Congress gave them, especially with the
racketeering law.
</P>
<P>
   ``They haven't been able to convince a lot of people that I did
something wrong, that I'm a crook, and that's what hurts them,'' he
said.
</P>
<P>
   Bustamante, a Democrat who served four terms in Congress, was
defeated in 1992 by Henry Bonilla, a Republican who still
represents the South Texas district.
</P>
<P>
   Bustamante, 63, was convicted by a federal jury in 1993 on
charges of accepting $340,000 in bribes while in office, including
payments from a food-service company that was seeking to win a
contract with the Air Force. He entered the federal prison in El
Paso on May 22, 1995, and served 35 months of a 42-month sentence.
</P>
<P>
   He returned to a San Antonio half-way house in February, but was
soon released to home confinement. Bustamante wore an ankle
bracelet for electronic monitoring.
</P>
<P>
   ``So, now I begin another chapter of this,'' he said of the
probation. ``I will be able to move around, relax a little, go out
with family and friends. And I want to look at the future.''
</P>
<P>
   Bustamante may move about more freely, but cannot travel out of
south central and west Texas without having restrictions lifted and
he must report to a federal probation officer once a month.
</P>
<P>
   Bustamante is manager of a commercial shopping center in San
Antonio. He said he also has been asked to work helping open trade
markets for goods from Mexico.
</P>
<P>
   Bustamante said about a year ago he would not accept a pardon if
one was offered to him. But throughout his trial and federal prison
term, the former congressman steadfastly proclaimed his innocence.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
