<HEADLINE>
ARTHUR DOVE MAY HAVE CREATED THE FIRST ABSTRACT PAINTING
</HEADLINE>
  (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By CHRISTINE TEMIN  
 c.1998 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   ``ARTHUR DOVE: A RETROSPECTIVE''
</P>
<P>
   Traveling show organized by Debra Bricker Balken, in
collaboration with William C. Agee and Elizabeth Hutton Turner. At:
Addison Gallery of American Art, Phillips Academy, Andover, through
July 12.
</P>
<P>
   ANDOVER, Mass. _ A scholarly debate rages over whether it was
the American Arthur Dove or the Russian Wassily Kandinsky who made
the first abstract painting. Check out the splendid Dove show at
the Addison Gallery and you may decide, who cares? The selection of
over 80 paintings, drawings, pastels, and assemblages is both
ravishing and revolutionary. It demonstrates Dove's greatness _
whether he was ``first'' in a field that is not, after all, a race.
</P>
<P>
   Dove was championed early on by Alfred Stieglitz, the pionering
photographer and dealer who first showed Dove's work at his 291
Gallery in New York in 1910, and then in his subsequent galleries
from 1925 to 1946, the year Dove died. But despite the reputation
he gained as one of America's foremost modernists, and despite the
patronage of collector Duncan Phillips _ which is why the Phillips
Collection in Washington, D.C., is so rich with Doves _ the artist
remained on the edge financially.
</P>
<P>
   His career predated the age of the art star. He lived on a
cramped boat for seven long winters in the '20s, then in derelict
farmhouses in upstate New York, finally in an abandoned post office
on Long Island. His death coincided with the dawn of Abstract
Expressionism. Debra Bricker Balken, the curator who spent five
years organizing the Dove show, says Dove's late paintings directly
influenced Abstract Expressionists including Mark Rothko and
Barnett Newman. But the debt hasn't been acknowledged. The dislike
of the notoriously narrow-minded critic Clement Greenberg for
artists in Stieglitz's circle helped push Dove aside for decades,
until a 1973 retrospective at the Whitney Museum in New York. There
hasn't been another major Dove show until the current one.
</P>
<P>
   Dove's geographical isolation meant he didn't engage in the art
socializing that might have boosted his career, Balken contends. In
matters of style, too, he charted his own course instead of signing
onto one of the early 20th century's many ``isms.'' That, too,
helped push him into a corner.
</P>
<P>
   His painting is an idiosyncratic response to nature at its
broadest and most basic, his signature image a sun with concentric
halos, radiating outward. You bask in these paintings. The first
one you encounter at the Addison is the 1935 ``October.'' The
seasons, the weather, the time of day, all play important parts in
Dove's work. ``October'' is a scroll-like horizontal filled with
rounded, rollicking forms leaning against each other as if drunk.
They're abstractions of trees, but they have anthropomorphic
qualities as well: A couple of them have notches you might read as
chattering mouths. Dove has layered one color over another here,
creating luscious effects. This is a painting you might want to
eat.
</P>
<P>
   The earliest work in the show, the 1909 ``Still-Life Against
Flowered Wallpaper,'' reflects Dove's absorption of Cezanne and
other French painters during a 15-month sojourn in France. The
change from 1909 to the abstractions of 1910-11 is swift and
definitive. In these small nonrepresentational works he gives birth
to a new style, and while there are affinities and influences, the
style is recognizably his. The palette temporarily dims, as if with
the seriousness of the effort.
</P>
<P>
   In the teens and early 1920s, he worked out the vocabulary of
shapes he'd draw on throughout his career _ zigzags, rays, circles
that close as tight as a fist and then explode into halo after halo
of carefully graded color. He experimented with metallic paints
that make his surfaces sparkle. He painted on sheets of metal, as
in the 1927 ``Something in Brown, Carmine and Blue,'' which looks
like an oil slick. He tried out assemblage, as in the 1925 ``Goin'
Fishin,''' a boxy construction with real strips of bamboo arranged
in the fan formations he also liked to paint.
</P>
<P>
   And he made achingly lovely works, like the 1923 ``After the
Storm, Silver and Green (Vault Sky),'' in which a pale moon, sliced
in half by the top edge of the picture, shoots arcing rays of light
down onto the water. There's a mystic, magnetic communication
between moon and sea here, the waves straining skyward. The work
also offers a prime example of Dove's curved and angled
brushstrokes. It's hard to think of another painter who used the
direction of brushwork to such expressive effect. Here, the strokes
that create the light cascade like fireworks or a weeping willow.
</P>
<P>
   Around 1927, Dove started painting with the radio on. Some works
are titled after what he heard, songs by Gershwin or Irving Berlin,
for instance. In these musical paintings, Dove captured the
Zeitgeist of the jazz age. The 1927 ``George Gershwin _ I'll Build
a Stairway to Paradise'' perfectly conveys that song's ebullient
staccato rhythm through horizontal jabs of black paint that curve
their way upward: This staircase is a spiral. The Gershwin
painting, with its musical repetitions and variations, illustrates
one of Dove's guiding principles: If you like a shape or color,
stick with it, repeat it, play with it.
</P>
<P>
   As a colorist, Dove had few peers among his contemporaries; he
created harmony in hues both tender and robust. In the exquisite
1929 ``Fog Horns,'' a trio of rounded forms in muted violets,
centered with black, aim right at you, the echoing bands suggesting
sound. By skillfully manipulating the overlapping colors, he
achieved translucent, watercolor effects in oil.
</P>
<P>
   He was also a master in manipulating scale. In the 1930 ``Silver
Tanks and Moon,'' a canyon plunges between the two towering forms;
a tiny moon presides over the scene. This painting makes a good
comparison with a Georgia O'Keeffe, the 1928 ``Wave Night,'' in
another room at the Addison. The O'Keeffe, like so many of the
Doves, features dramatic contrasts of scale, careful gradations of
color, halos, and the tiniest speck of a moon.
</P>
<P>
   By the late 1930s, Dove's paintings exhibited an almost
worshipful attitude toward the sun and moon, illustrated at the
Addison by a lineup of seven exultant paintings of orbs, all
radiant, expansive, and weightless. They're all big _ his work
ballooned along with his confidence _ except for the 1937 ``Golden
Sun,'' which features a minute yellow circle shooting rays down on
a diagonal, to warm the earth below. This little icon was once
owned by O'Keeffe, who carried it with her, wherever she went,
until her death.
</P>
<P>
   Around 1940, something happened to Dove's painting. It became
flatter, more factual, and abstract. Even in paintings that still
refer to nature, like the blazing 1941 ``Indian Summer,'' there is
a jigsaw puzzle look. Gone is the misty evanescence. Gone, too, is
some of the enchantment that had been called up by an artist
communing so directly with the natural world.
</P>
<P>
   The Addison is a fine venue for this show, which opened at the
Phillips Collection, then went to the Whitney Museum, and, after
Andover, travels to the Los Angeles County Museum of Art. Given
this itinerary of major museums, you wonder why the show didn't go
to the Museum of Fine Arts, which, thanks to the late collector
William H. Lane, has excellent Doves, several on loan to the
Addison now.
</P>
<P>
   The Addison's relatively small size makes it easy to take in the
Dove show and then to cruise through nearby galleries to put Dove
in context. The comparison with O'Keeffe is a natural. The two were
contemporaries, and both were in Stieglitz's circle, although
O'Keeffe, who married Stieglitz, was of course closer. But there
are also more adventurous comparisons to be made. The Addison's
``Toilers of the Sea,'' a brooding little moonlit seascape by the
idiosyncratic, turn-of-the-century artist Albert Pinkham Ryder, is,
like Dove's paintings, simplified, shape-conscious and, above all,
invested with an almost supernatural force. It's spellbinding. The
Doves even bear comparison with the Addison's Winslow Homers,
especially the 1904 ``Kissing the Moon.'' And while it's a stretch,
you can even compare Dove with the Addison's 1974 Brice Marden
painting, ``Third Figure,'' a vertical row of three canvases in
deepening shades of gray-blue. It's the same gray-blue, similarly
graded, that Dove uses. The Addison exhibition does what a great
solo show should: After you see it, you tend to look at everything
else through the prism of that one artist's achievement. In Dove's
case, that's a pleasure. His painting is ecstatic.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
