<SLUG> BC-BOOKS-NEW-AZR </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
NEW AND NOTABLE BOOKS 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by N.Y. Times News Service clients)  
 By ANNE STEPHENSON  
 c.1998 The Arizona Republic  
<TEXT>
<P>
   (UNDATED) _ A survey of recently published books:
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &UR; FAMILY MAN &QL; 
 &UR; Calvin Trillin (FSG, $20)
</P>
<P>
   Here is the only advice you'll get from Trillin about parenting:
``Try to get one that doesn't spit up. Otherwise, you're on your
own.'' Trillin seemed vaguely uncomfortable writing about his
father, Abe, in a previous book, ``Messages From My Father.'' Here,
he's back on familiar ground with Alice and their two daughters.
Much of this, in fact, is made up of old stories, reminiscences of
when the girls were in diapers (they long since have removed them
and moved on), or later, when he and Alice used vital parts of
their Sunday newspaper to line the guinea pig's cage. There are new
reflections on old columns, on the differences between men and
women, on his well-documented passions for Halloween and a good
meal, and on other preoccupations of a self-described ``fifties guy
at heart.'' The voice is familiar, funny and oddly sweet in this
age of familial dysfunction, and his wife and girls are still good
subjects. ``It does seem unfair,'' he admitted to Alice, ``but we
all have to construct our little stories with the tools available
to us.'' &QL; 
 &QL; 
 &UR; THE MUHAMMAD ALI READER &QL; 
 &UR; Edited by Gerald Early (Ecco, $26)
</P>
<P>
   ``His eyes were wise and canny, like Ray Robinson's,'' Murray
Kempton wrote as he watched Cassius Clay after his astonishing
victory over Sonny Liston in 1964. Clay looked at the journalists
who had laughed at him before the fight and said, ``I told you. I
just played with him. I whipped him so bad and wasn't that good.
And look at me: I'm still pretty.'' Was that what drew so many
writers to him? The brash, poetry-spouting man who would drive up
to a schoolyard at recess and shout, ``Come here, all you beautiful
Black children!'' (The difference between him and the Pied Piper,
Clay explained to Gordon Parks, was that the piper didn't have a
Cadillac.) Here is a splendid collection of writings about Muhammad
Ali by the likes of Irwin Shaw, Jimmy Cannon, Norman Mailer, Pete
Hamill, Roger Kahn, Garry Wills, Hunter Thompson, Joyce Carol Oates
and Gay Talese. There's also an excerpt from Ali's 1975 interview
with ``Playboy,'' in which he talks about how he would like to be
remembered _ as a man who never looked down on those who looked up
to him, as a man who wouldn't hurt his people's dignity by doing
anything that would embarrass them, as a great boxer who became a
preacher and a champion of his people. And then, he added, ``I
wouldn't even mind if folks forgot how pretty I was.'' &QL; 
 &QL; 
 &UR; RANTING AGAIN &QL; 
 &UR; Dennis Miller (Doubleday, $21.95)
</P>
<P>
   We went through this in search of something to laugh at, and
came up dry. It's an awful book. Here's Miller on abortion: ``This
is (begin itals) the (end itals) big debate. And I'm talking bigger
than who was the better Darrin on ``Bewitched.'' On motherhood: ``A
63-year-old woman has had a baby last year. You know what the first
clue was she was pregnant? She missed her Jurassic Period.'' On
smoking: ``If you're saying you didn't know cigarettes were bad for
you, you're lying through that hole in your trachea.'' Are you
smiling yet? This material came from Miller's HBO show ``Dennis
Miller Live.'' It should have stayed there. &QL; 
 &QL; 
 &UR; TITAN &QL; 
 &UR; Ron Chernow (Random House, $30)
</P>
<P>
   Chernow won the National Book Award for ``The House of Morgan,''
and his new book, an epic biography of John D. Rockefeller Sr.,
already is being hailed as one of the best of the year. Son of a
con man who deserted his wife and five children, Rockefeller was
raised by his mother as a strict Baptist. Her prudent nature (and
philanthropy, despite her difficult circumstances) and his father's
daring combined to make Rockefeller the man he became _ one,
Chernow writes, who ``flouted government and rode roughshod over
competitors'' and incarnated the capitalist revolution that
followed the Civil War and transformed American life. What sets
this biography apart from others is Chernow's use of a 1,700-page
transcript of interviews conducted with Rockefeller from 1917 to
1920 by a newspaperman who intended to write an authorized
biography. That book never materialized. In the transcript, Chernow
found Rockefeller to be ``analytic, articulate, even fiery; he was
also quite funny, with a dry Midwestern wit.'' The result is a
splendid portrait of both a superb businessman and a complex human
being. &QL; 
 &QL; 
 &UR; THE BOOK OF POLITICAL LISTS &QL; 
 &UR; (Villard, $14.95)
</P>
<P>
   You will be shocked to know that only nine of our nation's
presidents had facial hair and that only one of them was a
Democrat. That five presidents were fat (William Howard Taft had a
body-mass index of 42.3, with 30 as the threshold of obesity), and
13 were/are (Bill Clinton is one) overweight. That George
Washington, Herbert Hoover, Abraham Lincoln, Ulysses S. Grant and
John Quincy Adams had asteroids named after them. That John F.
Kennedy is on a list of ``Presidents Who Had Mistresses'' even
though John F. Kennedy Jr. is editor of ``George'' magazine, which
put these lists together. We thought they wrote books like this
only about baseball. We were wrong. Here is a collection of what
can only be called the minutiae of politics, intensely trivial
facts that only a junkie could love. Our favorite list offers H.L.
Mencken's thoughts on democracy, which he called ``the theory that
two thieves will steal less than one.'' &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
