<HEADER>
A0864 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u e &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-BOOK-HOPE-BOS &LR;      06-09 0766
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BOOK-HOPE-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
YOUNGSTER FROM D.C. GHETTO FINDS SUCCESS AGAINST ALL ODDS
</HEADLINE>
  (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By DANIEL GOLDEN  
 c.1998 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   A HOPE IN THE UNSEEN &QC; 
An American Odysey from the Inner City to the Ivy League &QC; 
By Ron Suskind &QC; 
Broadway, 372 pp., $25 &QC; 
 &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Of 52 promising minority teenagers chosen for a science and
engineering program at the Massachusetts Institute of Technology in
the summer of 1994, 51 had the advantage of coming from solid
backgrounds and schools. The exception was Cedric Jennings, a drug
dealer's son determined to study his way out of a Washington, D.C.,
ghetto.
</P>
<P>
   After struggling to keep up with his classmates that summer,
Jennings was told he was not ``MIT material.'' But the next year,
he became the first student in a decade from his gang-ravaged high
school to be admitted to the Ivy League: Brown University. There,
he is holding his own, academically and socially, with upper-class
whites bred for elite educations.
</P>
<P>
   In a country stratified more than ever by race and class,
Jennings is an increasingly rare exemplar of upward mobility. His
achievement demonstrates the continuing vitality of _ and the
enormous barriers to _ the American dream.
</P>
<P>
   Ron Suskind, better known in these parts for a controversial
Wall Street Journal piece suggesting that cocaine use caused the
death of Boston Celtics captain Reggie Lewis, first told Jennings's
story in a Pulitzer Prize-winning Journal series. Now, he brings it
up to date in ``A Hope in the Unseen,'' an absorbing, painstakingly
reported book that illuminates the lives and emotions of Jennings
and his parents and friends. One of the best of a recent spate of
accounts about black America by white journalists, it should be
required reading in college education and sociology courses.
</P>
<P>
   Shrewdly, Suskind avoids pontificating about Jennings's
experience; there's no need. Every detail proclaims the odds
against his protagonist. Violence and naysayers _ Jennings calls
them ``dreambusters'' _ are so pervasive at his high school that he
doesn't show up at an assembly to accept an award for fear that
resentful peers will insult or beat him.
</P>
<P>
   &UR;  &LR; Less than 10 percent of his peers in the senior class at
Ballou High School were accepted by any college; fewer can afford
to go. &UR;  &LR; One classmate, as talented as Jennings, witnesses a murder.
Afraid of retaliation, he seeks popularity by becoming the class
clown. His grades slip, and he ends up working in a mailroom.
</P>
<P>
   Jennings's father has two college degrees, but wastes his
intelligence and charm shuttling between prison and barbershops,
where he sells haircuts and heroin. And the Rolls-Royce-driving
minister at the Pentecostal church where Jennings and his
strong-willed mother turn for consolation and support inveighs
against the temptation of godless academe.
</P>
<P>
   Whenever Jennings competes against students from beyond the
ghetto _ on the SATS, at MIT, and Brown _ he's hindered by a lack
of information they take for granted. He's listened to every
hip-hop CD, but he's never heard of Freud or Churchill.
</P>
<P>
   Rather than relying on dialogue, Suskind unfolds the story
through the characters' minds. This technique, which he calls
``internal voice,'' speeds up the narrative, but at times begs
credulity. How does Suskind know, for example, what a friend of
Jennings was thinking just before she dozed off in church?
</P>
<P>
   The second half of the book, covering Jennings's freshman year
at Brown, does lag occasionally. Jennings took most of his courses
pass-fail, removing much of the suspense over his academic
performance. And he's not the only neatnik ever to be afflicted
with a messy roommate.
</P>
<P>
   In addition, Suskind's chronicle suffers from one unavoidable
problem: his own contribution to Jennings's rise. The Journal
series earned Jennings audiences with Supreme Court Justice
Clarence Thomas and a Boston benefactor began sending him $200 a
week, which may have distorted his value as a case study.
</P>
<P>
   But it wasn't Suskind who got Jennings into MIT or Brown. It was
Jennings's own perseverance, and his resistance to the temptations
of drugs and defeatism, that qualified him for affirmative action
``enrichment'' programs that too often benefit those already
relatively enriched.
</P>
<P>
   As one MIT administrator ruminates, ``It would take two years of
tutoring, not six weeks, to bring some of the inner cities'
brightest up to the level where they might be accepted to MIT.
Their similarity to the polished suburb-bred minority kids goes
little more than skin deep.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
