<SLUG> BC-PRIEST-RESIGNATION-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
PRIEST INVOLVED IN WRESTLING MATCH WITH BOY RESIGNS 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By ELIZABETH FERNANDEZ  
 c.1998 San Francisco Examiner  
<TEXT>
<P>
   SAN FRANCISCO _ A Catholic priest who admitted having a
nighttime wrestling match with a teen-age boy who worked in the
rectory announced in the church bulletin that he was resigning.
</P>
<P>
   The Rev. James Aylward, pastor of St. Catherine of Siena
Catholic Church in Burlingame, attributed the resignation to
``personal and administrative pressures'' and to two successful
battles with cancer.
</P>
<P>
   ``I felt that I ought now to turn over the reins of running the
parish to someone with both a greater heart for administration and
a greater talent for bringing together the disparate elements of
the parish,'' Aylward, 60, said in the resignation announcement.
</P>
<P>
   The San Mateo district attorney's office investigated the
incident but concluded there was not enough evidence to file
charges. The archdiocese conducted an investigation and said the
pastor's behavior was inappropriate but not sexual.
</P>
<P>
   Aylward publicly apologized for his ``foolishness and
imprudence'' and said he had begun therapy with ``a mental health
professional'' for ``the benefit of his evaluation.''
</P>
<P>
   The Rev. John Conley, who also worked at the church, reported
the wrestling incident to church and civil authorities, and was
later put on administrative leave.
</P>
<P>
   Conley said he was being unfairly punished for his revelations.
The archdiocese, however, said Conley was disciplined for previous
transgressions and for insubordinate and disrespectful behavior
toward his bishop during the process of reporting the wrestling
incident.
</P>
<P>
   Conley remains on administrative leave without assignment.
</P>
<P>
   Aylward, who was ordained in 1964 and holds a doctorate in
music, was appointed to St. Catherine's in 1996. During his tenure,
he won the admiration and respect of many parishioners, but also
caused dissension among others who disagreed with his pastoral
style.
</P>
<P>
   Aylward was unavailable for comment, his lawyer said.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
