<DATE_TIME> 1998-06-09 14:28 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A0877 &Cx1f; tad-z
u i &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-MEXICO-GUERILLAS-COX &UR;      06-09 1186
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-MEXICO-GUERILLAS-COX </SLUG>
    
 &HT;     SURPRISE GUN BATTLE A REMINDER GUERRILLA GROUPS FIND FERTILE
GROUND AMONG MEXICO'S INDIANS
 &HT;     NOTE: El Charco is about 105 miles south of Acapulco.
 &HT;     By SUSAN FERRISS 
 &HT;     c.1998 Cox News Service  
<TEXT>
<P>
   EL CHARCO, Mexico _ After most of the soldiers had retreated and
the blood was almost dry, a small group of Mexican villagers crept
back into this remote mountain village at dusk Monday to observe
the remains of carnage.
</P>
<P>
   Carrying machetes, the men whispered in their native Indian
language and stared at the pock marks of hundreds of bullets
Mexican Army troops had pumped into their schoolhouse Sunday during
a predawn attack. A gruesome silhouette of blood reveals a rebel
fighter's final moments _ shot dead, perhaps at close range, head
and back pressed against a wall.
</P>
<P>
   ``The people who died in here were all peasants,'' said
Francisco Ticurcio, a resident of El Charco, a Mixteco
(Meesh-TE-ko) Indian village buried at the end of a long, torturous
mountain road 105 miles south of Acapulco, southern Guerrero
state's famous tourist resort.
</P>
<P>
   Sunday's Army attack, which killed 11, wounded five and led to
the arrest of 21 suspected rebel affiliates, was a startling
reminder that leftist guerrilla movements _ other than the
Zapatistas in southern Chiapas state _ are still active among
Mexico's impoverished peasant Indians.
</P>
<P>
   Visibly nervous, Ticurcio said in broken Spanish that he doesn't
know who the 11 people were who died in the surprise shootout, the
worst such clash between the military and leftist rebels in Mexico
in two years. But he said masked rebels armed with guns and wearing
uniforms had been visiting this village of sugar cane fields and
thatched-roof huts almost once a month since last August.
</P>
<P>
   He said crowds of up to 70 people gathered to hear the rebels,
who usually numbered 15 _ four who spoke Spanish as their primary
language, including a woman, and 11 who were Mixteco Indians from
other isolated villages near El Charco in the Southern Sierra Madre
mountains.
</P>
<P>
   Those who died were identified as members of the Popular
Revolutionary Army, known as the EPR, a mysterious armed Marxist
group that had been largely silent for the past year. The EPR
announced its formation in June 1996, a year after Guerrero state
police stopped and shot dead 17 peasant activists who were
traveling on a road to attend a protest meeting near Acapulco.
</P>
<P>
   In August of that year, the EPR staged its battle debut with
bloody raids in seven states in which 18 people died. In early
1997, ambushes and clashes with the Army killed several soldiers
and at least two rebels. People in a village 60 miles north of
Acapulco were too afraid to claim the rebels' bodies.
</P>
<P>
   Some of the rebels discovered in El Charco may have been
affiliated with yet another group, the Popular Indigenous
Revolutionary Army, unknown to authorities until now, according to
Guerrero's attorney general.
</P>
<P>
   The attorney general, Servando Alanis Santos, said this week
that the state is investigating ``possible links'' to guerrilla
activity in El Charco with elected authorities in Ayutla, the
municipality where El Charco is.
</P>
<P>
   The president of Ayutla township is a member of Mexico's
center-left opposition party, the Democratic Revolution Party _ or
PRD _ which has long complained in Guerrero that its members have
been persecuted and killed by sympathizers of Mexico's dominant
political party, the Institutional Revolutionary Party, or the PRI.
</P>
<P>
   In the spring of 1990, PRD sympathizers were killed by state
police after they had occupied a city hall in the Guerrero town of
Cruz Grande to protest electoral fraud. Since 1996, some PRD
members have been accused of being sympathizers of the EPR.
</P>
<P>
   The attorney general's remarks about El Charco may signify a new
hostile attitude against the PRD here.
</P>
<P>
   On Monday afternoon Ayutla president Odilon Romero and a group
of supporters piled in a pickup truck and drove an hour into the
mountains to visit El Charco.
</P>
<P>
   Interviewed by foreign journalists, he called the attack ``a
lamentable event,'' and said he had long been aware of the
desperate poverty the Indians of El Charco and other villages
suffer in Guerrero.
</P>
<P>
   ``El Charco is a town that has always demanded services, like
potable water, electricity, jobs,'' Romero said.
</P>
<P>
   He said he knew nothing personally of EPR activity in El Charco
or other Indian villages, only information from news reports
indicating that as far back as 1996 rebels had visited some towns
in Guerrero to invite villagers to join them.
</P>
<P>
   ``I've always said using weapons to make change doesn't do any
of us any good,'' Romero added. ``I've proposed peace, not
violence.''
</P>
<P>
   El Charco, which means ``the puddle'' in Spanish, is a typical
poor Indian village of about 300. Residents are openly disgruntled
and complain about their poverty, but on Monday appeared reluctant
to talk about their feelings towards the rebels who had been
attempting to recruit among them.
</P>
<P>
   The villagers grow corn and sugar cane, and travel into Ayutla
on Sundays to sell avocados, bananas and other fruit they harvest
to earn cash.
</P>
<P>
   On Sunday morning, residents said, they awoke to a barrage of
gunfire and realized their schoolhouse _ a simple pastel-colored
cement building _ was under attack.
</P>
<P>
   The Army said it was on a routine patrol to search for marijuana
and poppy fields that are grown in the mountains here when soldiers
came upon the rebels. Villagers said the Army approached on foot
and appeared to have surrounded the school in a stealthy move.
</P>
<P>
   When bullets started flying, the villagers said, they fled into
the tropical hills around El Charco. Only late Monday afternoon did
they return to inspect the school, where pools of blood outlining
bodies stained the building's floor.
</P>
<P>
   Out on a basketball court, long trails of blood showed where
bodies were dragged out. Shattered glass covered the school's floor
and an outside walkway, evidence that bullets entered the school
and rebels had broken windows to fire back. Two Indian women in
long skirts and braids walked gingerly _ barefoot _ over the glass
and among third grade Spanish and mathematics workbooks scattered
about.
</P>
<P>
   The Army said it had taken a woman from Mexico City who was a
teacher into custody after the shootout. Villagers said El Charco
didn't have a female teacher, but that a woman was among the
Spanish-speaking rebels who met with them from time to time.
</P>
<P>
   ``She said she was a friend of the peasants,'' Ticurcio, the
Indian villager, said.
</P>
<P>
   The villagers said they had returned to inspect the damage,
guard their possessions and obtain food to eat. An Army patrol
stood by on a nearby bluff overlooking El Charco, maintaining
watch.
</P>
<P>
   Ticurcio and the others said they wanted the Army to retreat
completely from the area around the village.
</P>
<P>
   ``We are afraid of them,'' said Jose Jimenez, his ragged white
clothes smudged from a night sleeping in the woods. ``Of course we
are afraid of them.''
</P>
<P>
   &UR; For clients of the New York Times News Service &LR;
</P>
</TEXT>
