<HEADER>
A0915 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u l &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-MAASAI-WARRIOR-2ND &LR;  &UR; T     06-09 1159
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-MAASAI-WARRIOR-2ND </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
 
</HEADLINE>
   TAKE-BOS  
 (Undated): ... bad luck
<TEXT>
<P>
   ``But you can't look at it from a Western point of view,'' Gould
says. ``This is John's life we're talking about _ the only life
he's ever known.''
</P>
<P>
   Before passing judgment on the Maasai, Tome warns, consider
those things they simply do not have: child abuse, homelessness,
murder, stress-related disease, heart disease, depression,
materialism, loneliness, and suicide.
</P>
<P>
   ``Our life is very simple,'' he says. ``It's a beautiful way to
live, really.''
</P>
<P>
   At his lectures, Tome presents a slide show, with images of the
huts, cows, people, and stunning mountains and grasslands of his
home, the land called Maasai Mara, traversing Kenya and Tanzania.
That he loves the Maasai Mara is obvious: His eyes get sad, and he
speaks reverently of the natural beauty of the land he lives on.
The Maasai word for God, he says, is ``Inkai,'' the Maa word for
``blue sky.''
</P>
<P>
   He explains that the Maasai originated in Israel and moved on,
following their herds, to Egypt, Ethiopia, Sudan, and eventually
Tanzania and Kenya, where they remain. He knows this because of the
Maasai's meticulously held oral history, told and retold in his
village. Watusi and the Nubian cultures began as Maasai, and have
related languages and beliefs, he says.
</P>
<P>
   In his travels, Tome says, the only place he thinks even
remotely matches the natural splendor of Maasai land has been Utah,
the place he has liked the best. The place Tome has liked the
least, he says, is New York City, where everyone is mean and
rushing for no discernible reason, and where nature has been
entirely corrupted.
</P>
<P>
   Food has been a difficult issue for Tome, who during a recent
lunch interview ordered a roast beef sandwich _ eating only the
meat _ and whole milk, which he said ``tastes like water'' compared
to what they drink at home. He does not eat vegetables, all of
which he calls ``grass,'' or cow food. He did, however, enjoy a
piece of pound cake, and conceded that he could see how Western
culture would ``easily spoil many Maasai who might not be grounded
in their own culture.''
</P>
<P>
   Tome says that the Americans he most identifies with are Native
Americans, who have ``an incredibly similar history of having their
land stolen from them, of having been stuck on reservations.'' He
has also taken a liking to chubby blond women, according to Gould,
who says with a disapproving sigh that ``he has one in New York,
one in England, and one in Denmark.'' (Gould thinks of herself as a
mother figure.) Tome, when prodded, admits to liking ``upper-weight
women'' and to having fallen in love with a wealthy English hotel
owner, even to the point of asking his father if he would mind if
they married, but will not go into more detail than that.
</P>
<P>
   Conversely, the Americans Tome finds he has the least in common
with are African Americans. ``They seem to expect so much from
me,'' he says. ``It's like they want me to represent them somehow.
One even got mad at me the other day because I wasn't going around
teaching African-American history. That's crazy. I try to tell them
that I am from East Africa, and the slaves were taken from West
Africa, a world away from us. Americans in general don't understand
how big and diverse Africa is.''
</P>
<P>
   Tome is the oldest of 21 children born to one man and his three
wives. Tome's father taught him to tend cattle when he was a boy,
which he did every day. ``We don't play the way American children
do. We just start working. A Maasai 10 years old can handle so much
more responsibility than an American at 10 years old. The American
will have trouble just cleaning his room, but the Maasai can herd
400 cattle.''
</P>
<P>
   As a young boy _ he estimates that he was about 10 _ he killed
his first lion, by mistake, when he threw a spear at one that was
eating one of his cows. As an adolescent, he, with all the other
young men his age, went through the ritual to become a warrior and
killed another lion.
</P>
<P>
   There are rituals for women and girls, but Tome does not give
details, saying they are ``secret and we don't want them printed in
the paper.''
</P>
<P>
   Tome is still a warrior and will remain one until he is made an
elder. Warriors cannot marry, in case they die in battle. Tome says
many parents in his village are already courting him for their
daughters, because of his celebrity, which makes life hard for him.
``All these girls' parents want me to marry their daughters (when
he becomes an elder). I don't like to hurt people's feelings, so I
can't reject anyone. That's why I haven't married yet, because I
can't say no to any woman.''
</P>
<P>
   At the end of his presentation, Tome is bombarded with
questions. Some of them are good. Some are, shall we say, taken
from Hollywood stereotypes. But he is used to it. And he is
patient, just like his father, Retiti, who is his best friend and
mentor, and is known in the village for always thinking before
speaking, and for never raising his voice.
</P>
<P>
   ``The Maasai never shout,'' Tome says. ``Especially not to
children. Why do you do that here? It tortures them.''
</P>
<P>
   ``Don't the women get jealous if the husband has lots of
wives?'' someone asks.
</P>
<P>
   ``No, not really,'' Tome says. ``Sometimes, you know, there are
some jealous people.''
</P>
<P>
   ``Don't you run out of women if every man marries more than
one?'' asks another.
</P>
<P>
   ``No. Maasai men die in battles. And there are always more women
born. Of the 21 children in my family, only eight are boys. When
the baby comes, everyone waits and hopes it's a boy. When a girl
comes, everyone just says `Oh well' and goes on with their life.''
</P>
<P>
   Tome wants to go home. But more than that, he wants his home to
be around in 50 years. So he continues. Next stop, Disney World,
then back to Maine, then off to Arizona, back to Maine, to Utah, to
Maine, then off to Europe.
</P>
<P>
   ``How do you feel about the Western world?'' someone asks.
</P>
<P>
   ``I respect all cultures,'' Tome answers, carefully. ``All of us
are human beings. But there are many things I don't understand. The
rushing. The cars. You may think cars make your life easier, but
what are you going to do when you run out of clean air? And
television. Wonderful technology, but why don't you all just talk
to each other? And the way you treat the elderly and children here.
And materialism, and this obsession you have with physical
appearance. I miss home, where what matters most is how you treat
other people, how thoughtful you are.''
</P>
<P>
   ``Don't you worry that by setting up this school, Maasai
children will abandon traditional life for the luxuries of the
Western world?''
</P>
<P>
   ``It is easy to be seduced by the comforts of Western life,''
Tome says. ``But I think most Maasai would prefer to live in the
Maasai way. I would never think to leave home to adopt the Western
way of life. You wake up here, and see no clean environment. All I
want is for us to be respected enough to be able to live the way we
want.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-06-09-98 1454EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19980609.0137 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-06-09 14:57 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A0924 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u l &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-MAASAI-WARRIOR-BOS2ta     06-09 0992
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-MAASAI-WARRIOR-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
YOUNG MAASAI WARRIOR MOVES TO MAINE, DISCUSSES HIS CULTURE
</HEADLINE>
 2 takes with art (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By ALISA VALDES  
 c.1998 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   John Nemaru Ole Tome, a young warrior from the Maasai lands of
eastern Africa, stands at the head of a long conference table in
Cambridge, talking to a group of professional Americans about the
first time he saw an automatic door. (He'd thought the folks
telling him to walk through a glass wall were sadists.) He recalls
the first time he saw a television; he'd asked how they got the cow
small enough to put in a box.
</P>
<P>
   Tome's long hair is dyed deep red with ocher, plaited into
thousands of delicate braids. His left earlobe is elongated. When
he grins at his own mishaps, you notice that his four bottom front
teeth are missing. He wears red overlapping togas, more than a
dozen beaded necklaces, elaborate beaded headgear, and beaded
bracelets. He carries a large spear and shield, a foot-long knife
holstered at his waist, a carved walking stick, and a fly whisk
made of wildebeest tail _ that is to say, everyday Maasai men's
clothing. His audience wears the mall-purchased uniforms of the
working young: neutral trousers with white shirts and ties, pants
with pumps, suits with scarves.
</P>
<P>
   With the insight, timing, and cadence of a stand-up comedian,
Tome tells exactly how he came to live in York, Maine, about 7,500
miles from home and centuries removed from the Maasai world of his
upbringing _ a world of no electricity, written language, running
water, structured time, calendar, or medical care.
</P>
<P>
   As a child, Tome says, he saw his village ``exploited and
treated like wildlife'' by a government that used it as a tourist
attraction; he saw his ancestral land taken without permission. As
a very young man, he took a job at a tourist hotel near his village
so that he could teach himself English and Swahili by listening to
tourists. He asked questions about the Western world and told the
Westerners what he could about his.
</P>
<P>
   Earlier this year, he came to New England, setting up
headquarters in the York, Maine, home of Nancy Gould, a nurse he
met when she traveled to Kenya, and opening P.O. Box 402 and an
e-mail address, swara44(AT)aol.com. From here, Tome has manifested
his mission: to educate the Western world about the Maasai by
giving lectures, and to raise money. The funds would be used to
build the first school in his village, which, according to him,
would be the first school in Kenya to teach Maa, the Maasai
language, and Maasai history. He has already raised $100,000
speaking in places as disparate as a Hopi Indian reservation and
Disney World.
</P>
<P>
   Each day, he is brutalized by homesickness. He hates airplanes
and can't stomach most of the salty, processed foods our world
offers. His clothes draw stares and pointing everywhere he goes. He
has taken to wearing Western clothes occasionally, to blend in, but
he prefers his Maasai wardrobe. He is one of the most popular and
well-loved people in his village, but here, Tome is the consummate
outsider, looking in.
</P>
<P>
   But the journey continues, and will until he has raised half a
million dollars. Not, he says, so that the Maasai can one day
conform to the Western world _ rather so that the Maasai, once
known as Africa's fiercest warriors, can learn to defend themselves
against a new enemy: the encroaching decay wrought by television,
Twinkies, and cars.
</P>
<P>
   ``It took me a long, long time to get here,'' Tome begins his
talk. ``We Maasai walk everywhere. That's why we are so long and
skinny and have no heart disease. We walk all day long. It's normal
for us to walk about 40 miles a day. It took me many months to walk
here. I had to swim the ocean, too.''
</P>
<P>
   Tome pauses, half closes his eyes, and surveys the suits for
response. Everyone stares, dumbfounded, impressed, dubious, or just
plain uncomfortable.
</P>
<P>
   ``Not really,'' Tome says finally, enjoying their gullibility.
``Of course I took a plane. What do you think I am, crazy?''
Laughter.
</P>
<P>
   Tome goes on to explain that he finds airplanes quite boring,
except for going through the metal detector, which bleeps
convulsively, thanks to his enormous knife: ``They usually make me
give it to the pilot before we take off.'' He winks.
</P>
<P>
   Tome's travels are funded by the companies, universities, and
schools where he speaks (lectures run between $300 and $400, plus
expenses) and by friends such as Gould, who says her love for
Maasai culture explains why she has invested thousands of dollars
and endless hours helping Tome book his lectures. ``John doesn't
skim money off the top,'' Gould says in an interview in Maine.
``He's legit. He's not materialistic, so he saves every penny for
the school.''
</P>
<P>
   Gould, like many other Westerners who have visited Maasai land,
readily concedes that life in a Maasai village probably isn't for
everyone. Housing is a small hut made by hand from cow dung and
wood and shared _ with newborn livestock. The Maasai believe God
intended all cows to belong to them.
</P>
<P>
   Maasai mothers pry their children's lower front teeth from their
mouths with knives. Though anthropologists have theorized that this
is done for beauty, Tome explains that it began as a defense
against tetanus, which causes lockjaw.
</P>
<P>
   In a Maasai village, there is no running water or electricity.
Diet consists exclusively of blood (from live cows), milk, meat,
and, occasionally, cornmeal. Males must improve their manhood by
killing a lion with no more than spears or knives. Females can
expect to have their genitals mutilated without anesthesia, to lead
a life of carrying heavy bundles of firewood, and to be one of
several wives of a (usually) much older man, chosen by their
parents. Maasai people never know their age because the Maasai have
no set time and no calendar, in part because counting, like
pointing and posing for photos, is bad luck.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &QL; 
 &UR; MORE &QL; 
 &LR;  &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
