<HEADLINE>
COMPANIES HAVE TO OFFER GOOD BENEFITS TO KEEP EMPLOYEES
</HEADLINE>
  (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By DIANE LEWIS 
c.1998 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   With the US unemployment rate hovering at 4.3 percent, the
lowest level in 28 years, companies are doing all they can to
retain good employees.
</P>
<P>
   Such are the findings of a study of 378 US companies. Sponsored
by Manchester Partners International, a Boston consulting firm,
researchers reported that 67 percent of companies surveyed say
higher compensation and benefits are the best ways to hold on to
valuable managerial staff in a tight labor market.
</P>
<P>
   Fifty-two percent cited stock options, 27 percent offer profit
sharing, and 26 percent pointed to retention bonuses as effective
incentives. Others said they encourage casual dress, support
flexible hours and schedules, and offer tuition reimbursement.
</P>
<P>
   The companies reported an average annual turnover rate of 15
percent. One-third of the firms said it costs an average of $10,000
to replace a single employee.
</P>
<P>
   Call them surf abusers. That's what some employers are calling
employees who spend work hours playing computer games and surfing
pornographic sites on the Internet.
</P>
<P>
   One company, Elron Software Inc. of Cambridge, said it polled
100 companies that rely on Internet monitoring software to track
employee usage. Of the firms surveyed, 62 percent said they have
reprimanded an employee for surfing Web sites that are off limits
during work hours.
</P>
<P>
   How do you find the right employees in a tight labor market? You
train them yourself. The New England College of Finance, formerly
The New England Banking Institute, will join with banks, financial
services firms, high-tech companies, and universities to help
create a continual source of skilled labor for financial
institutions.
</P>
<P>
   In all, 250 banks are involved in the institute's new
educational agenda. So are International Business Machines Corp.,
Boston University, and the University of Wisconsin. The college
said it will collaborate with community organizations in Greater
Boston to develop a Financial Services Academy to train low-income
workers for entry-level jobs.
</P>
<P>
   Ruth M. Batson developed a foundation that awards education
grants to needy African-American students. Maura S. Doyle is the
first woman to become clerk of the Massachusetts Supreme Judicial
Court. Rosabeth Moss Kanter, a business professor at Harvard
University, helps companies manage change, and Jacqueline Weis
Liebergott is the first female president of Emerson College.
</P>
<P>
   These four women are among a dozen who will be honored Thursday
at the 4th Annual Academy of Women Achievers Awards luncheon at the
Sheraton Boston Hotel and Towers. Sponsored by the YWCA, the
luncheon is designed to encourage the advancement of women and
honor those who have broken through barriers to accomplish their
goals.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
