A0932 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u w &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-OLIPHANT-COLUMN-BOS &LR;      06-09 0864
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-OLIPHANT-COLUMN-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
HOLBROOKE: ``WORLD LOOKS TO WASHINGTON FOR MORE THAN RHETORIC''
</HEADLINE>
  (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By THOMAS OLIPHANT 
c.1998 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ So what does Kosovo represent?
</P>
<P>
   Not one to hestitate, Richard Holbrooke said: ``It's another
Bosnia. It emanates from the same roots. It presents many of the
same dangers, particularly an unraveling of all of southern
Europe's boundaries.''
</P>
<P>
   Holbrooke's reference was not simply to the proximity of the
former Yugoslav province. The architect of the Dayton agreement was
also speaking of Bosnia as a metaphor for post-Cold War crisis,
evil, aggression, and threats to core European and American values
and interests.
</P>
<P>
   ``There will be other Bosnias in our lives, areas where early
outside involvement can be decisive and American leadership will be
required,'' he writes in ``To End a War,'' his first-rate,
absorbing account of the sickeningly slow and then inspiring US
response to the war in which he was a central player.
</P>
<P>
   ``The world's richest nation, one that presumes to great moral
authority, cannot simply make worthy appeals to conscience and call
on others to carry the burden. The world will look to Washington
for more than rhetoric the next time we face a challenge to
peace.''
</P>
<P>
   As it will this week in Kosovo, where Holbrooke will once again
be a player. With the same evil _ mass murder as an instrument of
aggressive, suppressive policy flowing directly from Slobodan
Milosevic's Belgrade _ the moment for NATO's intervention with US
leadership appears at hand.
</P>
<P>
   What Holbrooke describes as ``classic preventive diplomacy'' has
yet to stop the Bosnia-like slaughter to force the majority, ethnic
Albanians, from their homes in the south. The dangers of escalation
and a spread across the Albanian border mount daily.
</P>
<P>
   President Bush and then President Clinton drew a hard line
against any violent suppression of autonomy for Kosovo's Albanian
population. It may have been easier, but both presidents were also
in the right when they did so.
</P>
<P>
   In his book, Holbrooke notes the seminal nature of Kosovo's role
in the Balkan history, culture, and recent horror. It is the
revered site of the battle 600 years ago where the Turks defeated
the proud Serbs and the spiritual capital of Serbia, even though 90
percent of its population is Albanian today. It is also the place
where Milosevic went in 1989 to ignite the modern period of
turmoil, war, and genocide. As Holbrooke also notes, this is where
a crowd that may have numbered a million people were inflamed as
Milosevic put a match to the dry wood of Serbian resentments.
</P>
<P>
   If, until his death in 1980, Josip Broz Tito used one-party,
independent (of Moscow) rule to govern six republics and five
nations that spoke four languages, practiced three religions, and
used two alphabets, Milosevic attempted the substitution of extreme
Serbian nationalism as master of this mess.
</P>
<P>
   A decade later, the carnage and wreckage of his unique
combination of demagoguery and megalomania are obvious. But
Milosevic still sits in Belgrade, in some ways with more insidious
consequences for his region than those flowing from Saddam
Hussein's continued presence in Baghdad.
</P>
<P>
   The core of ``To End a War'' is Holbrooke's riveting account of
the 14 days at Wright-Patterson Air Force Base in Ohio where the
Dayton agreement was negotiated. As someone with a fully developed
sense of history, the diplomatic trade, politics, writing, himself,
and the other players, he tells a great yarn. But the enormous
value and timeliness of the volume is its wrapping paper of history
and analysis leading into and out of the drama-stuffed conference.
</P>
<P>
   As both the cause of the carnage and the key negotiating partner
at Dayton, there is an inevitable, mixed nature to Holbrooke's
portrayal of the Serbian leader. His Monte Cristo cigars,
vulgarity, calculated volatility, and realism are present
throughout, offered to the reader with grudging fascination if not
admiration.
</P>
<P>
   At no time, however, does Holbrooke mince so much as a word in
describing what Milosevic did to cause and direct war and atrocity.
</P>
<P>
   Still, one cannot but wonder whether Holbrooke and the Clinton
administration will be able to shift to direct hostility toward the
man who was central to their success at Dayton in late '95. Bosnia
could be resolved in the context of Milosevic's continued rule;
it's not clear if Kosovo can or even should be.
</P>
<P>
   The ``other Bosnias'' of which Holbrooke writes comprise all the
hot, post-Cold War cases globally _ from the Persian Gulf and
Somalia to Northern Ireland, South Africa, Rwanda, and the Middle
East.
</P>
<P>
   Wisely avoiding the pretense of grand doctrine, he nonetheless
makes clear his preference for a responsibly activist mixture in
foreign policy of the strategic realism of Nixon, Ford, and Bush
with the more idealistic missions of Carter and Reagan.
</P>
<P>
   This way is already being wisely paved by Secretary of State
Madeleine Albright. And if Al Gore should get through the political
minefield in the year 2000, you are studying the words of her
deserving successor.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
