<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-06-09 15:04 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A0936 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u i &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-ASSETS-TERROR-BOS &LR;      06-09 1257
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-ASSETS-TERROR-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
SHOULD US USE FROZEN ASSESTS TO COMPENSATE VICTIMS OF TERRORISM
</HEADLINE>
  (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By MICHAEL KRANISH  
 c.1998 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ On April 9, 1995, Alisa Flatow, a Brandeis
University junior studying in Israel, boarded a bus to a beach
resort in the Gaza Strip. She never made it. A terrorist,
reportedly backed by Iran, drove a bomb-laden van into the bus,
killing Flatow and seven others.
</P>
<P>
   Now the legal legacy of Flatow's death _ and similar incidents
of violence against US citizens, including the 1988 bombing of Pan
Am Flight 103 _ could significantly affect the financial leverage
the US government can use to retaliate against countries that
sponsor terrorism.
</P>
<P>
   President Clinton must decide soon if the US-based assets of
embargoed nations, nearly $3 billion now frozen by Washington in US
banks, should be used to compensate the victims of terrorist
attacks, including $247 million that a US judge recently said
should be paid to Flatow's family.
</P>
<P>
   The problem for Clinton is that it would take only a few big,
successful lawsuits and big damage awards to drain most of the
frozen foreign assets of terrorist states and deprive him of a
major foreign policy tool.
</P>
<P>
   In the 1979 Iran hostage crisis, for example, the government was
able to quickly freeze about $12 billion in Iranian assets, which
was almost all turned over to Iran and an international tribunal as
part of an accord that freed the hostages. Now, US officials are
privately debating whether the effort to improve relations with
Iran would be harmed by paying the Flatows from about $20 million
in Iran's remaining real estate assets in the United States.
</P>
<P>
   White House officials declined to discuss the Flatow case on the
record because Clinton has not made a decision. But with little
notice, Clinton may have set a precedent for paying the Flatow
family when, in November 1996 he ordered $1.2 million in frozen
Cuban assets be paid to the families of four Miami-based pilots
shot down by the Cuban Air Force in February of that year.
</P>
<P>
   ``If anything, my case is even clearer,'' said Alisa's father,
Stephen Flatow, a New Jersey lawyer who said he hopes to spend much
of the compensation on charitable causes and posting rewards for
capturing terrorists. ``We have demonstrated that international
terrorism from Iran comes from the highest levels.''
</P>
<P>
   Flatow's request is not frivolous; he has an act of Congress and
an unprecedented court ruling on his side. Last year, Flatow filed
his suit after an antiterrorism act was amended to allow US
citizens to sue and collect damages from a foreign government that
sponsors terrorism. Congress, however, did not say how victims
could collect damages if a country fails to pay. Clinton supported
the bill.
</P>
<P>
   Then, in March, US District Judge Royce C. Lamberth in
Washington agreed with Flatow that Iran sponsored the terrorist
group responsible for killing Alisa. Her death was caused by a
nickel-sized piece of shrapnel that is believed to have ricocheted
off the bus ceiling into her head.
</P>
<P>
   ``An innocent girl was needlessly killed,'' Lamberth said. The
judge, after hearing testimony from the 20-year-old's friends and
professors at Brandeis, held Iran responsible for $247 million in
damages. Iran, which refused to represent itself before the judge,
has refused to pay the award. That prompted Flatow's lawyer,
Stephen Perles, to seek payment from the Iranian assets frozen by
the US government.
</P>
<P>
   ``One of the things we hope to accomplish with this litigation
is to change the way the United States is able to retaliate against
countries that murder our children through terrorist acts,'' Perles
said. ``In the past, frozen assets have remained just frozen
assets. ``We hope to use this litigation to add the financial sting
and release those assets to victims' families.''
</P>
<P>
   State Department spokesman James P. Rubin agreed after the
ruling in the Flatow case that Iran sponsors Palestinian terrorist
organizations. But Rubin, in a statement that upset Stephen Flatow,
added that the Clinton administration wanted dialogue with Iran and
said that ``our policy doesn't get affected by court judgments.''
</P>
<P>
   A presidential decision to freeze foreign assets is one of the
toughest economic sanctions. Privately, administration officials
expressed concern that using the frozen assets to compensate for
terrorist acts could backfire because the money would not be
available to use as leverage against a country.
</P>
<P>
   Once the funds are frozen, they accrue interest and become a
subject of negotiations. For example, the United States froze
Vietnam's US-based assets in the wake of the war and only released
them after relations between the two countries began to be
normalized recently. A tribunal is determining who gets the money.
</P>
<P>
   Flatow is not alone in eyeing the US government's trove of
frozen foreign assets.
</P>
<P>
   Last November, the families of three of the four ``Brothers to
the Rescue'' pilots who were shot down by the Cuban Air Force went
to court to seek damages against Cuba. With Cuban representatives
refusing to appear in court, a judge awarded the three families
$188 million. This was separate from the $1.2 million that Clinton
provided for the pilots' families in November 1996.
</P>
<P>
   Now a third and much larger case is winding through the courts.
About 160 families of the 270 victims of Pan Am 103 have sued
Libya, which has long been suspected of playing a role in the
destruction of the plane over Lockerbie, Scotland.
</P>
<P>
   Unlike the Cuba and Iran cases, Libya has sent representatives
to US court to deny the charges and has delayed the suit. Libya is
expected to challenge the constitutionality of the law that allows
the suits, potentially having an impact on all three cases.
</P>
<P>
   Senator Edward M. Kennedy, who has been working with 20 families
of Pan Am 103 victims from Massachusetts, said recently that he
supports the use of frozen foreign assets to compensate the
families. The issue could come before Congress if Clinton decides
he cannot take any action.
</P>
<P>
   ``When these families are awarded compensation by the court,
they should be able to collect,'' Kennedy said. ``In cases where
payment is refused, the United States is well within its right to
use a country's frozen assets to see that the families get the
justice they deserve.''
</P>
<P>
   In addition to the $20 million in Iranian assets, mostly in real
estate, the United States has frozen assets of Iraq, Libya, Cuba,
North Korea, the former Yugoslavia, and the Sudan. The funds, which
typically remain in US banks until they are unfrozen, add up to
$2.94 billion, including $1.4 billion from Iraq frozen during the
Gulf War.
</P>
<P>
   But the Flatow family stresses that this isn't about money. ``I
never expected to see a nickel,'' Stephen Flatow said. He said he
does expect to see justice, and now hopes the US government will
unfreeze Iranian assets to provide it.
</P>
<P>
   For Alisa's friends, the effort to win payment from Iranian
assets is part of an effort to keep her memory alive. Lauran
Sloane, Alisa's roommate at Brandeis, read a four-page testimonial
to Alisa at the March trial and is still grappling with loss of
what she called an ``incredible friendship.''
</P>
<P>
   ``I know how much she loved the state of Israel,'' Sloane said.
``She would not want people deterred from going, which terrorism
definitely does. I hope that it sends a message that the Flatows
want, that it will stop terrorism and violence.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
