<SLUG> BC-DINING-NYT-BUDGET </SLUG>
  
<TEXT>
<P>
   Food and dining stories in sight at this hour from The N.Y.
Times News Service for Wednesday, June 10:
</P>
<P>
   For information and repeats call the News Service at (212)
556-1927. And be sure to look for other stories from our partners:
Bloomberg News, The Boston Globe, Cox News Service, Hearst
Newspapers, The Arizona Republic, Kansas City Star, Fort Worth
Star-Telegram, Los Angeles Daily News, San Francisco Chronicle and
Seattle Post-Intelligencer.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; FEATURES: &LR;
</P>
<P>
   VIDALIA-ONIONS (Glennville, Ga.) _ In springtime, you know
you're in Vidalia country without reading the signs. As soon as you
leave the piny woods of Fort Stewart, the vast Army base, you come
upon an amazing sight: row after row of burlap bags stretching
across the sandy fields as far as the eye can see, full of onions
drying in the Georgia sun. A local curiosity only 25 years ago,
Vidalia onions have joined the ranks of seasonal foods keenly
awaited by American consumers. By R.W. Apple Jr.
</P>
<P>
   With recipe.
</P>
<P>
   With map.
</P>
<P>
   FRANCE-TURBOT (Paris) _ In a refrigerated warehouse at Roissy
Airport, near Paris, a man in a white lab coat lifts turbot out of
a cold seawater tank and lays them, one by one, into styrofoam
boxes. Now and then, a fish quivers its fins lethargically as it
settles into the box, but that is the only sign of life. Roughly 18
hours later, they arrive in Tokyo, where a truck fitted with water
tanks awaits them. The turbot are unpacked and slipped into the
tanks. Instantly, as if touched by a magic spell, they flutter back
to life. As incredible as their revival is, it is often brief. The
trucks deliver the fresh, live turbot to restaurants around the
city where many become part of dishes before the day is over. For
many chefs today, though, that is the point. They want to have the
freshest possible ingredients, no matter how extreme the measure is
to get it to them. By Amanda Hesser.
</P>
<P>
   NY-PIZZA-RENAISSANCE (New York) _ New York pizza is a phrase
synonomous with pizza greatness, yet for years New Yorkers could
find the genuine article in only a few isolated spots. Now,
pizza-lovers can rejoice: the true New York pizza is back in town.
By Eric Asimov.
</P>
<P>
   LOUVRE-RESTAURANT (Undated) _ Mon Dieu! The mother of modern
American cooking has been asked to open a restaurant at the temple
of French culture in Paris. Alice Waters whose restaurant in
Berkeley, Chez Panisse, has become a shrine to American cooking, is
to meet on Thursday with Helene David-Weill, the chairman and chief
excutive officer of the Decorative Arts Museum of the Louvre, to
discuss plans for the museum's 330 seat restaurant that is
scheduled to open at the end of the year 2000. By Marian Burros.
</P>
<P>
   SPAGO (Beverly Hills) _ When Wolfgang Puck opened Spago in West
Hollywood in early 1982, he changed American restaurants. He did
not do it by serving California cuisine or putting caviar on pizza;
in fact, he didn't do it with the food at all. Puck, and his wife
and partner, Barbara Lazaroff, were the first restaurateurs to
realize that rich Americans longed for great food without
formality. And so he began serving oysters without ostentation and
foie gras without fuss. Puck opened Spago Beverly Hills last year,
switching his focus from the casual West Hollywood location to a
far more refined setting. His restaurant changed with the times and
once again gave an early clue to a new direction for dining in
America. By Ruth Reichl.
</P>
<P>
   BABY-BROCCOLI (Undated) _ A new sprout in the enchanted broccoli
forest is causing semantic chaos in specialty produce markets and
leaving adventuresome cooks searching for words. The diminutive
hybrid _ mild, peppery and slightly sweet _ is basically a baby
broccoli. Its pale stems are as slim as spears and rarely exceed
six inches; the head is a loose cluster of flowerettes that
resemble infant broccoli rabe. By Molly O'Neill.
</P>
<P>
   With recipes.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; COLUMNS: &LR;  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   WINE-TALK (Undated) _ The accusation of fraud against Chateau
Giscours, one of the best-known wine properties in Bordeaux, could
drastically affect the entire region. What makes the system so
fragile _ aside from artificially high prices _ is the fact that it
is based on trust. Many fine wines are bought by people who know
little about the subject but assume that a famous label and high
price insure the best. By Frank J. Prial.
</P>
<P>
   SIMPLE-COOKING (Undated) _ The column: Salmon burger. By Mark
Bittman.
</P>
<P>
   with recipe.
</P>
<P>
   MASTER-CHEF (Undated) _ The column: Chocolate-cherry tart.
</P>
<P>
   With recipe.
</P>
<P>
   FOOD-NOTES (Undated) _ News and notes on food and dining.
</P>
