<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-UNIVERSITY-RESIGNATION-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
PRESIDENT OF UNIVERSITY OF TEXAS AT SAN ANTONIO RESIGNS
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By JEANNE RUSSELL  
 c.1998 San Antonio Express-News  
<TEXT>
<P>
   SAN ANTONIO _ Sam Kirkpatrick has announced he will resign as
president of San Antonio's only public university after nearly a
decade of service.
</P>
<P>
   The resignation, effective June 30, 1999, comes five weeks after
University of Texas System Chancellor William Cunningham visited
the troubled University of Texas at San Antonio campus. Both men
said the resignation was not forced.
</P>
<P>
   Kirkpatrick, 54, brought new programs and buildings to a young
University of Texas at San Antonio after his arrival in January
1990. Under his leadership, the university has added 30 new
degrees, including two doctoral programs with a third pending. A
downtown campus, for decades an unfulfilled promise to San
Antonio's inner city, rose on the site of a failed shopping mall.
</P>
<P>
   But in the last several months, Kirkpatrick's relations with
faculty and community groups have been strained. Professors reacted
angrily to an error-ridden attempt to equalize salaries. When the
No. 2 administrator, Provost Ray Garza, resigned in April, critics
questioned Kirkpatrick's commitment to Hispanics in leadership
positions.
</P>
<P>
   In the end, Kirkpatrick had used up much of the good will he
received when he took on the tough task of leading the university
through a decade of fast growth, changing demographics and rising
academic standards.
</P>
<P>
   ``You have to know when it's time to go,'' Kirkpatrick said
Monday, adding that his tenure has been ``far more successful than
I expected.''
</P>
<P>
   He said he planned to take a research fellowship at the American
Association of State Colleges and Universities in Washington D.C.
</P>
<P>
   Cunningham, who in April met with some faculty, students and
staff on a visit widely seen as an opportunity for him to assess
how the groups' relations with Kirkpatrick had soured, complimented
the president's accomplishments at UTSA.
</P>
<P>
   Cunningham said he had not asked for Kirkpatrick's resignation.
</P>
<P>
   ``I hope the next president will build on Sam's (Kirkpatrick's)
momentum,'' Cunningham said. The chancellor said he planned a
follow-up visit to UTSA next Tuesday, and would meet with the same
campus leaders to discuss the transition.
</P>
<P>
   Art Vega, who heads the Faculty Senate, said he felt
``cautiously optimistic'' about the news of Kirkpatrick's impending
departure and hoped Cunningham would hire a new president swiftly
for a smooth transfer of power. Vega is the former chairman of La
Raza Faculty and Administrators Association, a group that
criticized Kirkpatrick's shortage of high-level Hispanics.
</P>
<P>
   If Kirkpatrick stays through June 1999 as planned, he will have
lasted twice the national average of university presidents.
</P>
<P>
   Since 1990, the student population became nearly 40 percent
Hispanic and the faculty, 27 percent minority. The number of
Hispanic administrators, however, never reached community
expectations in a city where Hispanics are a majority.
</P>
<P>
   Linda Pritchard, associate dean of graduate studies, said
Kirkpatrick unsuccessfully tried to overcome UTSA's reputation as a
white, middle-class university serving San Antonio's North Side.
</P>
<P>
   ``UTSA is, quite rightfully, suffering for the sins of its
fathers, the ethnic politics of this city,'' she said.
</P>
<P>
   She credited Kirkpatrick for being a ``change agent,'' and said
the new leader could build on his accomplishments while repairing
relations with various university groups.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
