<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-ICE-CREAM-SANDWICHES-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
ICE CREAM SANDWICHES, HANDMADE TO ORDER  
 (JT) 
</HEADLINE>
   By MARIAN BURROS   
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ In the early 1980s, ice cream sandwiches were the
rage in New York City. Every ice cream shop made them, and there
were pushcarts that specialized in them, too. Then, like any fad,
they faded away.
</P>
<P>
   Almost. Standing in line recently at Sedutto's on First Avenue
between 78th and 79th Streets, I spied a canister of chocolate
wafer cookies and had a flashback: would they make sandwiches with
them?
</P>
<P>
   Not only would they make them, they would make them with any
flavor I wanted. My custom ice cream sandwich turned out to be a
marriage made in culinary heaven, the slight bitterness of
cappuccino ice cream playing off the chocolate, the cold creaminess
off the crisp cookie.
</P>
<P>
   You don't have to order cappuccino, of course, but you do have
to know to order the sandwiches because they are not listed on the
menu. They cost $2.25, just about the same price they were 15 years
ago.
</P>
<P>
   One small warning: eating them is not simply a matter of taking
a bite. They are squishier than the commercial kind, and there is a
certain skill required. Never try to cram the top and bottom cookie
and the ice cream filling into your mouth at the same time. Can't
be done. Just take a bite out of the lower cookie and a bit of the
ice cream. Then flip the sandwich over and repeat. In the end, it
is just barely possible to eat top, bottom and middle all together,
without having the ice cream fall to the floor.
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
