<HEADLINE>
THE FREEDOM TRAIL _ BIRTHPLACE OF AMERICAN LIBERTY
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By RICHARD P. CARPENTER  
 c.1998 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   BOSTON _ These are the sites that stir the soul.
</P>
<P>
   They are the places where the idea of freedom flourished, and
where some of the people who fought for that idea lived, worshiped,
died, and now rest forever.
</P>
<P>
   They are places like Faneuil Hall, where the cry of ``no
taxation without representation'' echoed through the meeting hall,
presaging the American Revolution; the Bunker Hill Monument, near
land where Colonel William Prescott is said to have shouted ``Don't
fire until you see the whites of their eyes!''; and the Granary
Burying Ground, where Samuel Adams, Paul Revere, and John Hancock
are buried.
</P>
<P>
   They are the sites, 16 in all, that make up Boston's Freedom
Trail, a 2 1/2-mile path, linked by a red-brick line, that draws
some 3 million visitors a year from throughout the world. It is a
trail that can be walked in as little as an hour but which leaves
an impression that may well remain with you always.
</P>
<P>
   No one can improve upon the meaning of these hallowed places,
which also include Paul Revere's home, the Old North Church (where
the two lanterns associated with Revere shone so brightly on April
18, 1775), the Boston Common, and the site of the Boston Massacre.
But people can make the sites more accessible, attractive, and even
entertaining. And they have done just that.
</P>
<P>
   Nowadays visitors _ and residents, too _ who walk the trail will
find new signs, informational kiosks, brass medallion markers, and
better pedestrian ramps. That's because of a million-dollar
appropriation last year by Mayor Thomas M. Menino, who recently
walked part of the trail at an event kicking off the spring-summer
tourist season. With the Old North Church looming in the background
and Paul Revere himself standing nearby, the mayor told a group of
schoolchildren, ``These are not just buildings _ they're part of
your freedom. ... We preserve the past for our future.''
</P>
<P>
   People who walk the trail will encounter the present as well,
what with cars wending their way down the city's narrow streets and
the occasional clatter of construction being heard. But Linda
McConchie, the new director of the Freedom Trail Foundation, says
she believes visitors will benefit from ``the intellectual
stimulation of the trail's urban context. It's the world we live
in.''
</P>
<P>
   Visitors should also benefit by meeting people from the past.
The Freedom Trail Players act as authentically costumed
ambassadors, telling people about life in Revolutionary Boston and,
perhaps equally important, offering directions and tips, such as
where to find a rest room. (They don't, however, try to pretend
you're in the 1700s. That would be hard to do, considering the
aformementioned cars and construction.) In addition, the Faneuil
Hall Marketplace historic characters, Ben Franklin among them, lend
a hand.
</P>
<P>
   And free 90-minute trail tours are conducted by Park Rangers
from April through October. Eight sites, primarily on the Freedom
Trail, constitute Boston National Historic Park, and since 1976 the
National Park Service has infused more than $50 million into
restoration and other improvements.
</P>
<P>
   More upgrades are on the way. This year, Menino will unveil the
city's handicapped-accessible guide to the trail. And thanks to a
grant from the Massachusetts Office of Travel &AMP; Tourism, the
Freedom Trail Foundation will publish a color visitor map and guide
and create a Web site. That grant is also responsible for bringing
back the Freedom Trail Players.
</P>
<P>
   Likewise, a major new exhibit, ``The Bloody Massacre on King
Street: The Boston Massacre of March 5, 1770,'' has opened at the
Old State House Museum at 206 Washington St., sponsored by the
Bostonian Society. Visitors can walk through a re-creation of the
moonlit Boston street where five men were killed in a clash with
British redcoats. Viewing the various displays _ including bullets,
a British musket, and autopsy reports _ people can ponder the
causes of those killings and be reminded that there were legal
maneuvers and courtroom drama long before the O.J. Simpson case.
</P>
<P>
   The Old South Meeting House has reopened, too, after a $7.2
million appropriation from Congress to the National Park Service.
This is where raucous pre-Revolutionary debates took place,
including one attended by 5,000 outraged colonists that led to the
Boston Tea Party. The historic space has been restored, with a
variety of new amenities, including a gift shop and those
all-important rest rooms.
</P>
<P>
   At the spring-summer kickoff event, Mary Jane McKenna, executive
director of the Massachusetts Office of Travel &AMP; Tourism, read a
proclamation at Faneuil Hall Marketplace, declaring Boston's
visitor season officially open. But she didn't stop there.
``There's nowhere in Disney with a Freedom Trail,'' she told the
onlookers. ``And we have buildings with all four sides!''
</P>
<P>
   That brought a hearty ``Huzzah!'' from the crowd.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
