<HEADLINE>
THERE'S A LOT GOING ON THIS SUMMER
</HEADLINE>
  (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By JERRY MORRIS  
 c.1998 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   Among items from the Titanic on view beginning July 1 at the
World Trade Center is a lamp that indicated the ship's direction.
The exhibit features more than 300 items recovered from the ship.
</P>
<P>
   Put three-cornered hats on a group of kids and something amazing
happens. Revolutionary Fun includes Colonial Williamsburg, where
the past comes to life every day.
</P>
<P>
   It's going to be a titanic summer for Boston. More than 300
events are planned, and the events range from below sea level to
the heights of Everest.
</P>
<P>
   Boston's waterfront will be particularly lively.
</P>
<P>
   ``Titanic: The Exhibition'' comes to the World Trade Center on
July 1. The show, the largest showing of Titanic artifacts to date,
will be set up next to the new Seaport Hotel and across from the
Trade Center. More than 300 objects recovered from the wreck site
will be presented throughout the two-hour exhibition.
</P>
<P>
   Visitors will be taken on a narrative and visual journey to the
bottom of the North Atlantic where the Titanic rests. The
exhibition will highlight the innovative technology used to explore
the Titanic wreckage. For information, call 888-744-7998. The show
runs through Nov. 1.
</P>
<P>
   While the exhibition is in town, the Museum of Science will
bring back to its huge Omni screen ``Titanica.'' Also on the screen
at the museum this summer is ``Everest,'' the dramatic story of a
science journey to the pinnacle of the world. Do reserve tickets,
as the film has been sold out since its opening this spring. For
tickets, call 617-723-2500.
</P>
<P>
   July 23-26 will see an international salute to the unsinkable
Old Ironsides, the USS Constitution, which is celebrating its 200th
birthday. Naval vessels from around the world will be coming to
Boston for the event, passing in review as the Constitution is
anchored by the Fish Pier.
</P>
<P>
   After the review, the Constitution and the vessels will be open
for touring at Charlestown Navy Yard.
</P>
<P>
   Other bicentennial events for the oldest active naval vessel in
the world include a Boston Pops concert at Harborlights,
competitions, a jazz brunch alongside the Constitution, fireworks,
and ``Liberty on Landsdowne Street,'' an international crew welcome
reception on this club-happy street. For information on harbor
cruises for this event, call Durgan Travel at 800-234-9959.
</P>
<P>
   And this is the 17th annual season for Boston Harborfest, which
has held the No. 1 spot among the Top 100 Events in North America
by the American Bus Association. Among the 160 events planned for
the celebration, June 30 to July 5, are fireworks, tours, the
greatest chowderfest anywhere (a tough choice in a city known for
its chowder), harbor island walks, and ship tours.
</P>
<P>
   Throughout the summer, the harbor is a great place for
exploring. Visitors can take sightseeing cruises, dinner cruies,
sail on tall ships, take a whale-watching cruise, cruise to Cape
Cod, and now, after a 20-year absence, go deep-sea fishing for blue
or bottom fish (call Boston Harbor Cruises at 617-227-4321).
</P>
<P>
   Of course, the place to be on July 4 is along the Charles River
for the annual Boston Pops concert. More than 500,000 people are
expected for the concert led by Keith Lockhart. This year's 25th
anniversary performance will again end with the stirring ``1812
Overture'' accompanied by church bells, cannons, and fireworks.
</P>
<P>
   There's a lot more on tap throughout the summer. Arthur's World
is at the Children's Museum, with lots of interactive exhibits, and
children will be able to fantasy play in their favorite Arthur
setting, which is designed to reinforce the message that being
smart and into books is cool. Reservations are recommended. For
tickets, call TicketMaster at (617 or 508) 931-2787 or at Filene's
locations. At the Museum of Science, Robotics features a huge
hands-on exhibit with the latest technology to demystify computers,
engineering, and artifical intelligence.
</P>
<P>
   Throughout the city, there will be music galore, with Boston's
Summer Music Festivals and everything from Bach to Blues. Along the
waterfront, Harborlights Music Festival will be featuring 30
international performers. On stage, Disney's ``Beauty and the
Beast'' will be at the Wang Theater from July 2 through Sept. 6.
</P>
<P>
   And that's just a sampling of what's on this summer. For
complete information and a guide to Boston, call the Greater Boston
Convention &AMP; Visitors Bureau at 888-SEE-BOSTON. Callers will also
receive a Family Friendly ValuePass with discounts to attractions.
</P>
<P>
   Other money-saving deals for visitors include the Boston
CityPass ($26.50 for adults, $20.50 for seniors 65 and older,
$13.50 for youths 13-18; under 13 is either free or very reasonably
priced), which provides a 50 percent discount to six major
attractions in the city. Also available is a visitor transit pass,
``The Visitor Passport,'' that provides discounts on attractions,
dining, tours, bike and sailboat rentals, shops, and unlimited
rides on the T. The pass is $5 for one day, $9 for three days, and
$18 for seven days.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   If you're heading for Santa Fe, the place to stay is Hotel Santa
Fe, the nation's only Native American-owned off-reservation hotel.
The hotel, a joint venture of Picuris Pueblo, represents an unusual
collaboration that has brought economic growth to Picuris and a new
blend of cultures to the city. Works by Native American artisans _
pottery, paintings, and weavings _ fill the hotel. Guests will find
a Native American restaurant, music, and history. The hotel
features every modern amenity along with New Mexican furnishing.
For information, call 800-210- &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Beginning July 1, there's a new way to get to Martha's Vineyard.
Motorcoach service will be offered from the Kingston MBTA station
to the ferry docks in Woods Hole. The service is a cooperative
effort by the Woods Hole, Martha's Vineyard and Nantucket Steamship
Authority and the Plymouth &AMP; Brockton Street Railway Co. The
one-way fare, which includes bus transportation and the ferry to
the island, is $12 a person. Advance reservations are not
necessary. The service also means that travelers from Boston and
South Shore communities can get to the island without a car.
</P>
<P>
   Oak Bluffs will hold its seventh annual Harbor Festival on June
13 (rain date is June 14). The festival features music, food and
lots of fun.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   So you'd like to become a travel guidebook author? Well, here's
your chance. The third annual Institute for Guidebook Writing will
be held in Cambridge, July 19-22. Six experienced authors,
including Arthur Frommer, the dean of American guidebook authors,
will participate in the weekend that will provide everything one
needs to know about writing guidebooks. For information on the $295
course, call Tom Brosnahan at 978-287-0540, or check the Web at
 &UR; tbros(AT)infoexchange.com
</P>
<P>
   &LR;  &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   If you're in New York City on Tuesday, join the 20th annual
Museum Mile Festival that runs from 6 p.m. to 9 p.m. from 82nd to
104th streets. Along the way, stop in at any of the nine top
museums; admission is free for the night. Along the route are El
Museo del Barrio; the Museum of the City of New York; International
Center of Photography; the Jewish Museum; Cooper Hewitt, National
Design Museum of the Smithsonian Institution; National Academy
Museum, School of Fine Arts; Solomon R. Guggenheim Museum;
Goethe-Institut New York/German Cultural Center; and the
Metropolitan Museum of Art.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   You've used UPS to send packages around the world, now let them
fly you to some sunny destinations. TNT Vacations is now using UPS
passenger jets on Bahamas and Aruba charter vacations. Michael
Bloomer, president of TNT, said it takes UPS only four hours to
convert their jets to passenger service, and because there are
fewer seats, there is more passenger leg room and comfort.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
