<HEADLINE>
NOTHING NAMES THESE PLACES
</HEADLINE>
  (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By RICHARD P. CARPENTER  
 c.1998 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   These American towns have nothing names: None, Mo.; Unnamed,
Wash.; Nowhere, Okla.; Nada, Texas; Nadaburg, Ariz.; No Name,
Colo., Nameless, Tenn.; and Nameless Cave, S.D. And those are just
a few of the peculiar names for neighborhoods, villages, towns, and
other locales described in ``A Place Called Peculiar'' by Frank G.
Gallant (Merriam-Webster, $14.95). Other examples:
</P>
<P>
   _Peculiar, Mo., where a place marker proclaims: ``In 1861-1864
while bloody battles raged throughout the Southern states nothing
happened here.'' How it got its name is a long story, having to do
with a government error.
</P>
<P>
   _Smut Eye, Ala., where a popular gathering spot was the smithy.
The shop was so dirty and sooty that men went home with ``smut'' in
their eyes.
</P>
<P>
   _Corkscrew, Fla., which took its name from the winding Corkscrew
River. The only problem is that the river doesn't wind much these
days.
</P>
<P>
   _Ducktrap, Maine, where the Penobscot Indians trapped ducks that
were molting and couldn't fly.
</P>
<P>
   _Loudville, Mass., a village in Northampton, which was named not
for the sometimes boisterous Clear Falls but for industrialist
Caleb Loud.
</P>
<P>
   As the author puts it, America takes a ``no-holds-barred,
call-'em-as-you-see-'em, idiosyncratic approach to place naming
that is not replicated anywhere else in the world.''
</P>
<P>
   &UR; Travel Trivia: &LR;  Which of the world's capital cities has the
highest elevation? (Answer at end of column.)
</P>
<P>
   &UR; Quotable: &LR;  ``They wanted to take us to historic places. We
wanted to go to Jack's Joke Shop.'' _ humorist Dave Barry,
describing a class trip to Boston when he was in the ninth grade in
Armonk, N.Y., in the 1960s. (The class also visited Salem, where a
student _ we can't imagine which one _ set off a stink bomb in the
secret staircase of the House of Seven Gables, causing the
cancellation of future trips.)
</P>
<P>
   &UR; Contest time: &LR;  You can win a trip to Shangri-La _ the hotel,
that is. Shangri-La Hotels and Resorts, a group of 35 award-winning
properties in the Asia-Pacific region, has added on-line bookings
to its Web site, www.shangri-la.com. To publicize that, Shangri-la
is sponsoring a 10-question contest on the site. Participants will
be asked about the hotel group and selected properties. (Hint: The
answers can be found throughout the Web site.) There will be a
drawing from among correct answers, and the winner and a companion
will be flown by United Airlines to Hong Kong for four nights each
at the Island and Shangri-La hotels there. The contest ends June
30.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; Casinos in Korea: &LR;  Casinos are popular with visitors to Korea _
so popular that 13 of the country's deluxe hotels, from Seoul to
Chejudo Island, have them. The largest is the Sheraton Walker Hill
hotel Casino in Seoul, and the hotel also presents a Las Vegas-type
stage show. At Korean casinos, all of which are
government-approved, you'll find all the popular games of chance.
But there's one thing you won't find: Korean gamblers. Koreans
aren't allowed to play.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; How's that again? &LR;  A notice on the board at the Graceland
Wedding Chapel proudly proclaimed: ``Lorenzo Lamas and Jon Bon Jovi
were married here!'' But not, as the sign might make it appear, to
each other.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; Did you guess it? &LR;  La Paz, Bolivia, at 12,001 feet, is the
highest-elevated capital city in the world.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &QL; 
Travel Tidbits is compiled from wire-service reports, news
releases, books, magazines, and the deepest recesses of the
author's mind. Send comments and questions to Travel Tidbits,
Boston Globe, Boston, MA 02107. Send e-mail to
carpenter(AT)globe.com. Include your name and community.
</P>
</TEXT>
