<DOCNO> NYT19980609.0174 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-06-09 16:28 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A1127 &Cx1f; tad-z
u w &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-online-ads-cox     06-09 1224
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-online-ads-cox </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    ADVOCACY GROUPS FINDING THE INTERNET A POWERFUL RESOURCE
 &HT;    By KEN FOSKETT
 &HT;    c.1998 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ When the tax-exempt group Putting Children First
was founded last year to promote school vouchers in Texas, it faced
a problem common to all such start-ups: How to attract contributors
and members who could mount an effective lobbying campaign?
</P>
<P>
   The answer came from a new but not unpredictable source: the
Internet. Mining the membership of Juno Online Services, the
nation's second largest carrier of personal e-mail accounts, the
Texas organization recently targeted its promotional advertising to
thousands of Texas e-mail users, many of whom e-mailed back,
wanting to be put on the group's mailing list.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's great,'' said Greg Talley, the group's executive
director. ``It's cheaper than a postage stamp.''
</P>
<P>
   Voters have long been accustomed to the glossy political
pamphlets that arrive in the mail before elections and the barrage
of television advertising on the evening news. But tax-exempt
groups such as Putting Children First are now experimenting with
the power of the Internet to distribute political issue
advertising, recruit supporters and wage on-line lobbying campaigns
in Congress.
</P>
<P>
   Another special interest group, which Juno declined to identify,
is paying Juno to send Juno's members an issue ad on legislation
currently before Congress. Voters who receive this ad will have the
option of e-mailing their member of Congress a pre-written letter
on the subject with a click of a mouse button.
</P>
<P>
   Juno also is talking to political candidates who could use the
company's database of 5 million members to send campaign literature
about themselves _ and their opponents _ to voters before the fall
elections.
</P>
<P>
   ``The potential for on-line advocacy is really fantastic,'' said
Oron Strauss of Net.Capitol, Inc., a private company that designs
Web pages for advocacy groups. ``The speed with which you can react
and mobilize large numbers of constituents or members is really
powerful.''
</P>
<P>
   All members of Congress now have e-mail addresses to communicate
electronically with constituents. Many candidates for political
office set up Web pages that prompt visitors to give them their
name and address to receive more information.
</P>
<P>
   Web sites for advocacy groups such as Americans for Tax Reform,
a conservative anti-tax group in Washington, have features that
allow visitors to read about an issue and then e-mail their member
of Congress about it.
</P>
<P>
   Friends of the Earth, an environmental group, recently launched
a Web site describing the costly environmental effects of driving
sports utility vehicles (SUVs). When Web surfers search for SUVs on
one of the Web search programs, they find the Friends of the Earth
site along with sites promoting SUVs.
</P>
<P>
   But the Juno Advocacy Network, a division of a New York company,
is taking issue advocacy a step farther, allowing advocacy groups
to target users unsolicited.
</P>
<P>
   In return for free e-mail, Juno members must complete a detailed
survey about their interests, financial position and family life
and agree to receive advertisements every time they log on to check
their mail.
</P>
<P>
   The company keeps its subscriber list confidential, but special
interest groups can come to Juno with a specific description of the
kind of people they would like to reach with their advertising.
</P>
<P>
   Putting Children First, for example, figured its ideal member
would be a mother between the ages of 25 and 45 who is also
religious. Juno quickly identified about 30,000 of the 361,000
members it has in Texas that fit the profile.
</P>
<P>
   Beginning two weeks ago, those Juno users checking their e-mail
were greeted by a colorful screen ad from Putting Children First.
</P>
<P>
   Charles Ardai, president of Juno, predicts that public interest
groups will soon value the speed of the internet and Juno's ability
to target voters based on their interests, background and street
address at little cost. On-line issue ads cost less than direct
mail, taking into account printing and production costs and
postage.
</P>
<P>
   ``Before a vote, we can get the word out from the people who
have an opinion to the people who are merely forming an opinion _
the constituents _ and then encourage (them) to send their opinion
... to their representatives,'' said Ardai. ``This would by postal
mail take weeks, if not months. But on line, a company could come
to us today and we could have a message up to our users ...
tomorrow.
</P>
<P>
   ``One of the reasons people don't write their Congress people
more often is because they don't know who they are. ... But here
you don't even have to know who your Congress people are ... We
know what ZIP code you are in. We know what district you live in,
and we can have a button on the screen that says click here and
your message will go to your representative.''
</P>
<P>
   Political advertising on the Internet is still so new that most
experts and observers are unwilling to predict how quickly it will
catch on, or just what it signifies for American democracy.
</P>
<P>
   Lynn Reed, who ran the Web page for the Clinton-Gore 1996
election campaign and advises candidates on how to use the Internet
for campaigning, says Juno's membership base is still too small to
make it cost-effective for candidates to send out campaign
literature to voters in their district.
</P>
<P>
   ``When the audience gets large enough, I think you will see
every campaign tactic (on the Internet) that you currently see in
other mediums,'' she says.
</P>
<P>
   Citing the potential for more ``sophisticated'' communication
between voters and politicians, Ardai noted that politicians could
e-mail a 12,000-word issue paper to voters for a fraction the cost
of mailing it. But he conceded that political dialogue in the
United States has been a ``steady drive in the other direction.''
</P>
<P>
   Members of Congress report that more and more of their
constituents use e-mail, and that they treat e-mail like ordinary
mail. But members of Congress also distinguish between constituent
letters and mass mailings prompted by a special interest lobbying
campaign.
</P>
<P>
   ``Personal messages are the most powerful,'' said Sen. Paul
Coverdell, R-Ga.
</P>
<P>
   For the moment, Juno also has the monopoly on on-line issue ads,
since other e-mail providers do not offer their services in
exchange for demographic information from subscribers that can be
sold to advertisers. Unless special interest groups have electronic
mailing lists of their own, they have to pay Juno for the
permission to use theirs.
</P>
<P>
   And Juno won't take just anything. Ardai and David Shaw,
chairman of D.E. Shaw &AMP; Co., which owns Juno, decided the company
won't run issue advertising from tobacco companies as ``a matter of
principle,'' said Ardai. Other types of advertising will be decided
on a case-by-case basis, he says.
</P>
<P>
   ``We don't want to be the arbiters of taste, certainly not
opinion, but we presume we will draw some lines,'' Ardai says.
``Something that would offend a member who merely holds a different
opinion, that's fair game. But something that would offend every
reasonable human being who saw it, that's not fair game.''
</P>
<P>
   (For use by clients of the New York Times News Service)
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
