<SLUG> BC-WELLS-FARGO-NORWEST-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
BANKS GET HIGH MARKS FOR LENDING, BUT WILL THAT CONTINUE AFTER
MERGER? 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By EDWARD IWATA  
 c.1998 San Francisco Examiner  
<TEXT>
<P>
   SAN FRANCISCO _ While investors cheered the proposed $34 billion
merger of San Francisco's Wells Fargo &AMP; Co. and Norwest Corp. of
Minneapolis, a consumer organization questioned whether the new
bank can keep up Wells Fargo's record as a strong lender to
businesses and consumers in low-income areas.
</P>
<P>
   The 1977 Community Reinvestment Act requires banks to provide
financial services to all neighborhoods where branches are found.
</P>
<P>
   Consumer watchdogs say that Norwest has done a fine job of
community lending in its home state of Minnesota. But California's
population and ethnic groups are more diverse, and their financial
needs are greater.
</P>
<P>
   ``Wells Fargo is a leader among banks of its size,'' said Robert
Gnaizda, general counsel at the Greenlining Institute in San
Francisco. ``The question now is: Can the new bank maintain that
same leadership? Can it commit to the same high level of
performance as the old Wells?''
</P>
<P>
   The new company, to be called Wells Fargo, will be based in San
Francisco and be headed by Norwest Chairman Richard Kovacevich.
Paul Hazen, the chief executive of Wells Fargo, will be the new
bank's chairman.
</P>
<P>
   In Minneapolis, Norwest executives said their bank haD a strong
reputation for working closely with community groups, including
Hispanics and Asians.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're very proud of our record, and we hope to maintain what
Wells Fargo has done in California,'' Norwest spokesman Larry Haeg
said.
</P>
<P>
   ``Our bank will respond to the needs of California's
communities,'' said Diane Lilly, president of the Norwest
Foundation, which gave $26 million last year to nonprofit
organizations in 16 states.
</P>
<P>
   Wells Fargo, as part of its 1995 merger with First Interstate,
promised to donate $30 million a year to nonprofit groups and loan
$4.5 billion a year for community reinvestments over the next
decade.
</P>
<P>
   ``We have a very strong commitment to the communities in which
we serve, and there won't be any changes in our existing
presence,'' said Lisa Rossi, a Wells Fargo spokeswoman.
</P>
<P>
   Gnaizda said the Greenlining Institute would meet this month
with Norwest executives to discuss the bank's practices on
community lending and charitable giving.
</P>
<P>
   Recent mergers in the banking industry have led to growing
criticism that bigger banks are charging higher fees for checking
and other services that hurt lower and middle-income customers.
</P>
<P>
   Norwest and Wells Fargo executives would not comment on fee
structures, saying it was too early to tell.
</P>
<P>
   But analysts call Norwest a consumer-friendly bank. It's the
nation's leading mortgage lender, loaning $60 billion last year to
homeowners. Norwest also offers an average of four products per
customer, from checking accounts to home loans. That is more than
any other banking rival.
</P>
<P>
   While investors and executives cash out big-time in the bank
megadeals, evidence is growing that small businesses and consumers
may lose out. Mergers often mean poorer service and higher prices
for bank customers, according to consumer advocates and
congressional critics.
</P>
<P>
   A Federal Reserve study last year showed that savings enjoyed by
bigger banks when they merge have not been passed on to consumers.
</P>
<P>
   Product and service fees charged by multistate banks are
``significantly higher'' than fees charged by banks doing business
in only one state, according to the Fed study.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS.) &QL; 
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Meanwhile, Wall Street analysts and executives at Wells Fargo
and Norwest predict that the merger should have no trouble clearing
federal regulators.
</P>
<P>
   Before signing off on mergers, the government looks at three
elements: the banks' financial resources, the antitrust issues and
the banks' performance under the Community Reinvestment Act, which
requires banks to provide services to all communities, including
poorer neighborhoods.
</P>
<P>
   Both banks are strong financially. To appease the Justice
Department on antitrust grounds, the banks may have to shed some
branches in the Southwest. On Community Reinvestment Act matters,
both banks are rated ``outstanding.''
</P>
<P>
   Consumer watchdogs hope that Norwest's entry into California
will heighten market competition among the state's big banks and
savings and loan institutions.
</P>
<P>
   ``With so much industry consolidation, my long-term fear is
consumers will have less choices and less diversity in services,''
said Ken McEldowney of Consumers Union in San Francisco. ``I hope
to see more aggressive competition for customers' accounts.''
</P>
<P>
   Wells Fargo has century-old business roots in the West and a
well-known market brand with its familiar stagecoach logo. The bank
also is strong in commercial lending, automated teller machines,
supermarket banking and on-line banking.
</P>
<P>
   Norwest is a respected, fast-growing community bank that
specializes in consumer finance. The bank is the nation's largest
mortgage lender, operating mostly in the Midwest and Southwest.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
