</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FRANCE-TURBOT-ART-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
FISH PURVEYORS TAKE FRESHNESS TO A NEW EXTREME 
</HEADLINE>
  (ART ADV: Photo is being sent to NYT photo clients. Non-subscribers
can make individual purchase by calling 212-556-4204 or -1927.) 
(ja) 
 By AMANDA HESSER    
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   PARIS _ Every two or three weeks in a refrigerated warehouse at
Charles de Gaulle Airport outside Paris, a man in a white
laboratory coat lifts live turbot out of a cold seawater tank and
lays them, one by one, into dry styrofoam boxes. The fish lie
almost completely still, but they are very much alive.
</P>
<P>
   Within minutes, 108 of the flat, spotted brown fish are packed
and sealed into boxes and whisked onto a plane. Roughly 18 hours
later, they arrive in Tokyo, where a refrigerated truck waits.
While passengers stumble off groggy and tired, the turbot, cool and
well rested, slip into tanks and, as if touched by a magic spell,
flutter back to life.
</P>
<P>
   But as incredible as their revival is, it is brief. The turbot
are headed to restaurants around the city, where they are likely to
become part of the menu before the day is over.
</P>
<P>
   The obsession with the freshest possible ingredients has reached
a new extreme. France Turbot, a fishery in western France, is the
first company in the world to ship live fish out of water to
destinations like Hong Kong, Tokyo and, just last week, Boston. But
others may soon follow in the wake of its success, including the
Browne Trading Co., a fish purveyor in Maine.
</P>
<P>
   Live fish does not come cheap. In the United States, it costs
more than twice as much as dead, freshly caught fish _ in the case
of turbot, about $17 a pound wholesale, compared with $8 a pound.
But, says Jean-Georges Vongerichten, the chef at Jean Georges in
Manhattan, the difference in taste is remarkable.
</P>
<P>
   ``When it's alive,'' he said, ``it's like a raw oyster. It has
an algae flavor. It's totally different.''
</P>
<P>
   The discovery that the turbot could survive out of water came by
accident at France Turbot, which sits hidden among tall grasses in
the middle of a marsh on Ile de Noirmoutier, an island just off the
coast near Nantes. Workers found that jumpers, or fish that leap
out of the water and land on the side of the concrete tanks, would
sometimes be alive even after a few hours. Researchers at the
company chalked up the turbot's resilience to its natural habitat
in coastal waters close to the ocean floor, which can sometimes dry
up at low tide.
</P>
<P>
   The company was already transporting live fish _ in seawater
tanks on trucks _ across Europe, so it began experimenting in 1992.
But it took almost six years to figure out how to ship the fish
without water.
</P>
<P>
   The resulting technique is surprisingly straightforward. The
process begins at the fishery, where the fish are not fed for
nearly a week, while the temperature of the water in the tanks is
gradually lowered. By shipping time, the water is 37 degrees, and
the fish's metabolism has slowed to such low levels that the fish
are in a hybernationlike state. They lie still on the bottom of the
tank. When the water temperature is this low, the turbot also load
up on oxygen, padding themselves for time out of water. And unlike
some fish, when turbot are out of water, they can absorb up to 40
percent of their oxygen through their skin.
</P>
<P>
   Once researchers understood how to extend the survival time,
they went to work on transporting the fish safely and soundly,
because, said Remi Dhellemmes, a manager at the fishery, ``the
survival rate is due to the lowest stress rate.'' If the stress
level is minimized, he said, so are any effects on the flesh or
sweet, mild flavor of the fish.
</P>
<P>
   Researchers spent six months designing a a light styrofoam box
that looks a lot like the pieces used for packing electronic
equipment. Each box holds just two fish _ 1{ to 2 pounds each and
about a foot long. A small compartment on the side holds a handful
of crushed ice to keep the air cool and humid during transport, and
space above and below the fish keeps oxygen circulating.
</P>
<P>
   France Turbot has been able to keep some turbot alive for 40
hours out of water, but its goal is less ambitious. It would rather
guarantee a 100 percent survival rate after 24 hours, so that the
fish can easily make the 18-hour journey from Paris to Tokyo.
</P>
<P>
   Once the fish are taken from water, timing is crucial. They are
swiftly transported in water tanks to Charles de Gaulle Airport _
about a five-hour drive from Noirmoutier. There, in their sort of
suspended animation, they are carefully positioned in the styrofoam
boxes, stacked inside a plastic-lined cardboard box and sealed,
much as a gift would be packed up to be sent in the mail. Then it
is a mad dash to the airplane.
</P>
<P>
   The first overseas shipment was last December. It went to Tokyo.
In Japan, where live fish is practically all that is sold,
importers were equipped for handling the turbot once they arrived
at the airport. The business took off at once, and now France
Turbot is shipping a total of about 1,000 pounds of live turbot to
Tokyo and Hong Kong every two to three weeks.
</P>
<P>
   Such success has moved the company to experiment with other fish
and shellfish. Crabs and eel will probably be next, Dhellemmes
said, because they are sturdy enough to withstand the trip
overseas. But not all fish can be shipped this way. In tests on
wild Dover sole, for instance, 1 of 20 were alive after about 24
hours out of water.
</P>
<P>
   ``The problem is that fish caught at sea is always a little
damaged, and they're not used to shipping conditions,'' Dhellemmes
said. ``So they die in transport.''
</P>
<P>
   And high-activity fish like sea bass and salmon consume their
oxygen too quickly to survive the long transport.
</P>
<P>
   Shipping this way is so expensive that it has to be foolproof.
Chefs and purveyors, though, seem willing to brush aside the cost
for the sake of a fresher product. Rod Mitchell, the director of
Browne Trading Co. in Portland, Me., who imported live turbot for
the first time last week, has his own plans for the live fish
business. He is constructing a tank system like the one used by
France Turbot, and he plans to ship local fish to restaurants
across the country by the end of this year.
</P>
<P>
   The demand, so far, is almost entirely from Asian restaurants,
where fresh fish means live fish. He is hoping that American and
French restaurants will come to the same conclusion. ``It's going
to take a lot of convincing,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Maybe. But Vongerichten, who started buying locally caught live
fish from New York Fish House in Elizabeth, N.J., three weeks ago,
said he may begin buying the live turbot, too.
</P>
<P>
   So far, he has used black sea bass, fluke and sea robin at the
restaurant. The fish arrive in styrofoam boxes filled with water
and oxygen, and because the restaurant does not have seawater
tanks, they are killed and filleted right away. Diners eating the
fluke, Vongerichten said, ``thought it was Dover sole because it
was so firm.''
</P>
<P>
   Not all chefs, though, are sold on the idea of live fish. ``I'm
not interested in it,'' said Eric Ripert, the chef at Le Bernardin
in Manhattan. ``The fish we receive here was in the water, what,
yesterday,'' he said. ``And I think it is extremely fresh.''
</P>
<P>
   ``In terms of flavor,'' he added, ``I challenge anyone to prove
to me live fish is better than one caught yesterday.''
</P>
<P>
   For now, the future for live fish sales in the United States is
unclear. But France Turbot is getting a good start.
</P>
<P>
   On Thursday, the company packed up 20 cool, sleepy turbot for
the first trial shipment to the United States. The fish were loaded
onto an American Airlines jet in Paris in the morning.
</P>
<P>
   At 3 p.m., they arrived at Logan International Airport in
Boston.
</P>
<P>
   At 6:30 p.m., Mitchell was lifting them from their boxes at the
Imperial Seafood Restaurant on Beach Street in Boston's Chinatown.
They were moist and cool and ready to move. The fish flipped and
twisted in his hand, and the instant they hit the water they
fluttered their fins and waved their bodies, moving like racehorses
out of the start. All 20 revived.
</P>
<P>
   But soon their number was 19. Albert Leung, one of the owners of
the restaurant, took one to the kitchen, where it was cleaned and
scaled, sprinkled with fresh ginger and gently steamed. He topped
it with shredded scallions, a few drops of hot oil, soy sauce and
nothing more. The flesh was pleasantly firm, sweet and saline, and
yes, completely different from turbot a day or two old.
</P>
<P>
   Ripert has at least one challenger. &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
