<HEADER>
A1167 &Cx1f; taf-z
u d &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-MASTER-CHEF-NYT &LR;      06-09 0846
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-MASTER-CHEF-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
A TART THAT GIVES CHOCOLATE AND BOOZY CHERRIES EQUAL BILLING 
</HEADLINE>
   (This is the seventh of eight columns by Daniel Boulud, the chef
and owner of Restaurant Daniel in Manhattan. His collaborator on
these columns is Dorie Greenspan.) 
 (HLW)  
 By DANIEL BOULUD   
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ When I was a kid, I was forbidden to drink alcohol
but was allowed to eat Mon Cheri, a chocolate-cherry candy that
tasted boozy and made me feel like a grown-up. This
cherry-chocolate tart, with its cherries poached in port, is
definitely not kid stuff, but it was inspired by those foil-wrapped
candies of childhood.
</P>
<P>
   The tart has three elements: a cocoa crust, cherries and a soft,
sensuous milk-chocolate filling. The challenge was to keep the
chocolate intense without letting it overwhelm the cherries.
</P>
<P>
   The crust was easy. I wanted it to have a full flavor (that is
why I based it on bitter cocoa powder), a crisp texture and a quiet
personality. The crust had to be a supporting player in every sense
of the word, and because it is not too sweet, it is.
</P>
<P>
   But chocolate is a notorious scene stealer. So I gave the
cherries the extra complexity they needed by poaching them in a
citrus-infused port. Cherries have a resilient firmness and their
own sweet, ever-so-slightly acidic taste. Poaching softened their
texture; using port gave them a deeper flavor, and tossing in an
orange added zing.
</P>
<P>
   Thus fortified, these cherries might have been a match for many
chocolates, but I chose companionable milk chocolate. When you
taste this tart, half the experience is cherries, half chocolate.
And to make certain the textures would be equally harmonious, I
decided on a satiny filling, a cross between a custard and a flan.
It is made with a runny ganache: a mixture of cream and chocolate
that's bound with eggs. Baked slowly in a moderately low oven, it
retains a silkiness that's the right counterpoint to the crisp
crust and semisoft cherries.
</P>
<P>
   I make miniature versions of this dessert at the restaurant, but
at home I serve a family-size tart. If you want, you can boil down
the leftover poaching mixture until it's thick enough to be poured
as a sauce (it's too good to waste) and serve it alongside the
tart.
</P>
<P>
   MILK CHOCOLATE AND CHERRY TART
</P>
<P>
   Time: 3 hours
</P>
<P>
   3 large eggs
</P>
<P>
   8 tablespoons unsalted butter, cut into 8 pieces, at room
temperature
</P>
<P>
   1 cup confectioners' sugar
</P>
<P>
   1{ cups all-purpose flour
</P>
<P>
   1/3 cup cocoa
</P>
<P>
   1 cup ruby port
</P>
<P>
   4{ tablespoons sugar
</P>
<P>
   { vanilla bean, split lengthwise and scraped
</P>
<P>
   1 thin strip of orange zest (all pith removed)
</P>
<P>
   Juice of 1 orange
</P>
<P>
   { pound cherries, halved and pitted
</P>
<P>
   4{ ounces high-quality milk chocolate, finely chopped
</P>
<P>
   1 cup heavy cream
</P>
<P>
   Pinch of finely grated orange zest
</P>
<P>
   Unsweetened whipped cream, for garnish.
</P>
<P>
   1. In a small bowl, lightly beat 1 egg, and set aside. In the
bowl of an electric mixer with a paddle attachment, combine butter
pieces, confectioners' sugar, flour and cocoa. Mix on low speed
until crumbly. Add the beaten egg, and mix until the dough comes
together in a ball.
</P>
<P>
   2. Divide dough in half, and shape into disks. Wrap in plastic,
and refrigerate one piece for at least one hour, or overnight.
(Freeze the other disk for another tart; it is necessary to make
the full quantity of dough to achieve the proper consistency.)
</P>
<P>
   3. While the dough is chilling, prepare the filling. In a small
saucepan, combine ruby port, 1 tablespoon sugar, vanilla bean,
strip of orange zest and juice. Bring to a boil, lower heat, and
simmer 10 minutes. Add cherries, bring back to a boil, then reduce
heat and simmer 2 minutes. Remove pan from heat, and cool to room
temperature. Drain cherries, reserving the port mixture, and pat
dry between paper towels. To make a sauce, strain the mixture into
a small pan, and boil down to a glaze; set aside.
</P>
<P>
   4. Preheat oven to 350 degrees. Butter an 8-inch-round,
1\-inch-deep fluted tart pan with a removable bottom. On a lightly
floured surface, roll dough to a thickness of [ inch. Fit dough
into pan, and trim excess even with the rim. Line the dough with
parchment paper or foil, and fill with dry beans or rice. Bake
until firm but not fully baked, 13 to 15 minutes. Remove the paper
and beans, and cool to room temperature.
</P>
<P>
   5. Reduce oven temperature to 300 degrees. Place chocolate in a
large heatproof mixing bowl. In a small saucepan, combine cream and
remaining 3{ tablespoons sugar. Bring to a boil, and immediately
add to the bowl of chocolate. Whisk until smooth. Add remaining 2
eggs, one at a time, whisking until smooth. Stir in grated orange
zest.
</P>
<P>
   6. To assemble, place the crust on a baking sheet. Arrange the
cherries, cut side down, in the crust. Pour over the chocolate
filling; it will come nearly to the top. Bake until the center of
the tart is gently set, 35 to 40 minutes. Cool to room temperature.
Serve drizzled with the port glaze and garnished with whipped
cream.
</P>
<P>
   Yield: one 8-inch tart (8 servings).
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
