<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-SWARTZ-COLUMN-$ADV16-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
HAVE WHEELS, WILL TRAVEL, EVER LIGHTLY 
</HEADLINE>
   By SUSAN SWARTZ   
 Santa Rosa (Calif.) Press Democrat   
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   I henceforth claim my section of the overhead bin. For too long
I have conceded it to any desperate passenger waddling down the
aisle with an elephant bag and nowhere to stash it.
</P>
<P>
   I have been one of those polite but invisible passengers. With
blind trust that my own bags are checked and stowed in the belly of
the same plane, I proceed right to my seat _ after my zone is
called, of course _ stash my purse and strap down.
</P>
<P>
   Then I check to see what movie's playing and white light the
plane. You know, envision the plane with a protective silver halo.
It's sort of like praying, but a psychic friend once told me about
white-lighting and I like the image.
</P>
<P>
   I am a likeable no-hassle passenger. I listen to the flight
attendants' safety routine. I observe the closest exit sign. I wait
patiently for the drink cart and complimentary peanuts, even when
they are barbecue-flavored sesame sticks.
</P>
<P>
   I let the guy in the seat in front of me lean so far back I end
up smelling of mint shaving gel. The worst offense I have ever
committed in the sky is to stash my gum in the airsick bag which is
all that's left, now that they've sealed up the ashtrays.
</P>
<P>
   I believe when you're airborne you need all the good karma you
can get. If flight attendants gave out stickers I would get a gold
star except that flight attendants never notice people like me.
</P>
<P>
   We are the ones who walk off the plane, thank the crew members
and get a look back like, ``Who are you?''
</P>
<P>
   They notice the others, the ones who require attention, the big
babies who demand playing cards and extra napkins and didn't really
mean to order a veggie plate because now the lasagna with meat
sauce looks good and who, somewhere in the middle of lunch,
proclaims he'll have an anxiety attack if he can't squeeze past the
cart in the aisle and get to the bathroom.
</P>
<P>
   All that's changed because I have crossed over. I have become
part of the carry-on crowd.
</P>
<P>
   It is another part of that lifelong process in becoming an
adult. To finally learn how to live for more than a week out of one
small bag, to get on and off a plane with said bag and not join the
anxious crowd grabbing for the same black bag regurgitated at the
baggage carousel.
</P>
<P>
   I have been flying since flight attendants wore hats, but I have
finally joined the jet set.
</P>
<P>
   It is because I now have wheels. My mobile bag was a gift from
someone who has been lecturing me for years on the hazards of
over-shlepping my bounds. He's right. My arms are tired. I need to
save them for writing stories and pulling radishes and waving
sparklers.
</P>
<P>
   Besides I find I like the image. You should have seen the new
efficient me my last spin through San Francisco International.
</P>
<P>
   I did not have to wait in line. I clipped along so very fine. I
looked like I was very smart. Because my suitcase is a cart.
</P>
<P>
   Only months ago I was a disheveled traveler. The kind that
flails and bumps along wild-eyed and overloaded through airport and
hotel lobby and along streets in faraway cities with no cabs.
</P>
<P>
   Coat askew, straps cutting into my shoulder, tote bags dangling
from my elbow, banging into strangers, clutching something in each
hand, tickets in an unknown pocket or between my teeth and with so
many pieces of baggage thumping my thighs, I was black and blue
before I unpacked.
</P>
<P>
   Now I walk through the airport calm and cool, like I've got no
more than a poodle on a leash.
</P>
<P>
   Here's a place for my newspaper and my tickets and a little
thing to attach to a book bag. All that's missing is a drink
holder.
</P>
<P>
   I, however, promise not to become one of those aisle jammers who
makes her bags her neighbor's burden like the woman on a flight
from Los Angeles who attempted to wrestle her two massive duffels
into the bin by balancing on an armrest and falling back onto the
head of the man in the next seat.
</P>
<P>
   In these cases flight attendants are like traffic cops, never
there when you need them to make a bust. Clearly, the offender's
bags exceeded the dimensions of a legal carry-on.
</P>
<P>
   I always wonder why men, limited to two carry-ons _ say, a suit
bag and a briefcase _ don't protest women boarding with their two
plus a purse that's big enough to hold a bottle of mineral water,
guidebook, extra socks and complete makeup supplies for a midflight
overhaul.
</P>
<P>
   But I don't want to start anything.
</P>
<P>
   (Susan Swartz is a columnist for The Press Democrat in Santa
Rosa, Calif. Her e-mail address is sfswartzpressdemo.com)
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
