<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-06-09 17:09 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A1241 &Cx1f; taf-z
u l &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-VIDALIA-ONIONS-ART-2T     06-09 1226
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-VIDALIA-ONIONS-ART-2TAKES-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
A GEORGIA ONION AS SWEET AS A PEACH 
</HEADLINE>
  (ART ADV: Graphic is being sent to NYT graphic clients.
Non-subscribers can make individual purchase by calling
212-556-4204 or -1927.) 
(ja) 
 By R.W. APPLE Jr.   
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   GLENNVILLE , Ga. _ In springtime, you know you're in Vidalia
country without reading the signs. As soon as you leave the piney
woods of Fort Stewart, the Army base where American troops trained
for the Persian Gulf war, you come upon an amazing sight: row after
row of burlap bags stretching across the sandy fields as far as the
eye can see, full of onions drying in the Georgia sun.
</P>
<P>
   A local curiosity only 25 years ago, Vidalia onions have joined
the ranks of seasonal foods keenly awaited by American consumers.
The name is protected by law now, like that of Bresse chickens or
Coca-Cola. Vidalias can be grown only in the distinctive soil of 13
contiguous counties between Macon and Savannah in southeast
Georgia, plus parts of seven others.
</P>
<P>
   In 1997, the total yield from 15,800 acres was 3.5 million
pounds, worth $89 million _ big money in a rural, historically poor
area where crossroads hamlets bear names like Daisy, Hopeulikit and
Ohoopee.
</P>
<P>
   People have eaten onions since antiquity; according to some
historians, the ancient Egyptians worshiped them. Robert Courtine,
the great French epicure, called the onion ``the truffle of the
poor,'' though the rich could hardly do without them, either. They
have only one flaw: eaten raw, they upset delicate digestions, and
their pungency lingers unalluringly on the breath.
</P>
<P>
   Jonathan Swift understood the problem perfectly:
</P>
<P>
   There is, in every cook's opinion,
</P>
<P>
   No savory dish without an onion;
</P>
<P>
   But lest your kissing should be spoiled
</P>
<P>
   The onion must be thoroughly boiled.
</P>
<P>
   Not if the onion in question is a Vidalia onion, named for the
small town from which the first Vidalias were shipped several
decades ago. Squat and thin-skinned, remarkably juicy and pale
ivory in color, Vidalias are sweet when raw, sweet when cooked and
succulent either way.
</P>
<P>
   Vidalias are to run-of-the-mill onions as foie gras is to
chopped liver, although it is the humble yellow or Spanish onion
that provides the deep, rich base for a thousand and one down-home
stews, braises and sauces.
</P>
<P>
   Bake Vidalias in a covered dish with herbs, olive oil and
balsamic vinegar; slice them in an onion, tomato and basil salad;
make a raw onion sandwich, or prepare something elaborate, like the
Vidalias stuffed with spicy sausage and topped with a cheese sauce
that have been a spring tradition for years at Elizabeth Terry's
award-winning restaurant in Savannah, Elizabeth on 37th.
</P>
<P>
   Jeff Bubin named his restaurant for them. At Vidalia, in
Washington, he goes through 20,000 to 30,000 pounds of sweet onions
a year, he said, using them in the marmalade that he puts on every
table; in his trademark baked onion recipe; in a dish of shrimp and
grits with caramelized onions, and even in an onion and black
pepper pound cake. When no Vidalias are available, he brings in
sweet onions from farther south, usually from Guatemala or Chile.
</P>
<P>
   ``But nothing comes close to Vidalias,'' Bubin said.
</P>
<P>
   Vidalia onions are grown from yellow Granex or Granex hybrid
seed. But this is one case where the environment matters more than
the lineage.
</P>
<P>
   William Randle, a professor of horticulture at the University of
Georgia at Athens, said the sandy, loamy soil found in parts of
southeast Georgia has a remarkably low sulfur content. Since sulfur
generates pungency in onions (and in their relatives shallots and
garlic), low sulfur means sweet onions. In addition, he said,
temperatures hereabouts are ideal _ above freezing during the
winter, then hot but not too hot in the spring, when heat is needed
for the rapid formation of the underground bulb on the onion plant.
</P>
<P>
   Similar conditions in other parts of the country enable farmers
there to grow excellent sweet onions, too. There are Walla Wallas
from southeast Washington state, Texas 1015's from South Texas,
Mauis from Hawaii and California Imperials from the Imperial
Valley, all produced in smaller quantities than Vidalias.
</P>
<P>
   A Toombs County farmer named Moses Coleman, or so local legend
has it, first noticed the exceptional sweetness of Vidalia onions.
He began growing them commercially in 1931, but the boom did not
begin until years later. There are now more than 150 onion growers
in this region, many of them former tomato farmers who lost their
markets in the early 1970s to Florida competitors who benefited
from a growing season that started earlier and lasted longer.
</P>
<P>
   Among all the producers, Elizabeth Terry and others here say,
Delbert Bland deserves the most credit for making the Vidalia onion
what it is today. A lanky, bearded, tobacco-chewing good old boy
who is likely to call a visiting Yankee ``hoss'' on first meeting,
he graduated from high school in 1974, when the local tomato
business was failing. He persuaded his father, Raymond, to try
onions. Their first planting, five acres, was a flop: ``bad yield,
worse sales.''
</P>
<P>
   But they persisted. Raymond Bland worked in the fields, as he
always had; at 71, he still drives a tractor almost every day.
</P>
<P>
   ``It broke my heart,'' Delbert Bland recalled, ``to see farmers
work hard all year, then take their crops to town and ask the guys
with neckties, `How much will you give me for this?' I didn't want
to live that way.''
</P>
<P>
   So the younger Bland, who is 41, went into sales, much
encouraged by a Wall Street Journal article describing Vidalias as
``the caviar of onions.'' He traveled the country, distributing
samples, tearing out Yellow Pages entries for supermarkets in city
after city, heading back to Glennville and sending off letters
(``badly typed at 12 words a minute,'' he says with calculated
self-mockery) to buyers for supermarket chains, big and small.
</P>
<P>
   Eventually, in 1983, he took an ad in Southern Living, an eighth
of a page, for $2,700. He sold 1,000 10-pound bags for $12.95
apiece, and a career as a direct marketer was born. Soon Bland
Farms was spending $300,000 a year on ads. Inspired by a similar
label on Florida grapefruit, Bland started affixing a sall decal
to each onion, identifying it as a true Vidalia. He sent 10 pounds
of onions to every food editor in the country, reaping a whirlwind
of free publicity.
</P>
<P>
   And from a student at Duke University who had been running a
modest retail business to help pay his way through school, Delbert
Bland bought the rights to a toll-free number (800-VIDALIA, or
800-843-2542) for a bargain price: $20,000.
</P>
<P>
   Raymond Bland was puzzled by the merchandising mumbo jumbo.
</P>
<P>
   ``My father never learned to read and write,'' Bland said. ``He
thinks if you're talking on the phone you're not working. So he
came to me one day and asked me, `Son, if you can get a phone
number free, what are you spending all that money for?'''
</P>
<P>
   He soon had his answer.
</P>
<P>
   For the 1998 crop, Bland Farms planted 2,600 acres in onions,
more than twice as much as any local competitor and almost a fifth
of the entire Georgia crop. Their packing sheds, which cover seven
acres, are the largest of their kind anywhere. At full tilt, Bland
Farms can process 30,000 50-pound bags of Vidalias a day.
</P>
<P>
   nn
</P>
<P>
   It is no backwoods enterprise. Planting and harvesting are
planned with the help of data from global positioning satellites.
Farm bosses communicate with walkie-talkies, and when I visited the
Blands in May, the desk of Delbert's wife, Sandra, a snappily
dressed former nurse who manages mail-order sales, held a computer
and the latest issue of Advertising Age.
</P>
<P>
   Bland onions are sold in all 50 states, in Britain and in
military commissaries around the world. The company mails 2 million
catalogs a year, through which it sells not only onions but baked
goods, relishes and salsas and other onion products. In dollar
volume, it is second only to the Northwest giant Orida in
supermarket sales of frozen onion rings.
</P>
<P>
   With 125 full-time employees and 1,200 or so seasonal helpers,
Bland Farms will gross something in the neighborhood of $30 million
in 1998.
</P>
<P>
   I remembered that this was the Bible Belt as well as Vidalia
country when I saw the bumper sticker on the back of Delbert
Bland's red Chevy pickup.
</P>
<P>
   ``Real Men Love Jesus,'' it said.
</P>
<P>
   Growing top-quality onions, Bland explained as we climbed in and
headed toward some of his nearby fields, is a painstaking process.
Seeds are sown by hand in seedbeds in September. Plants are pulled
up in November and December, then dropped by hand into predrilled
holes, 70,000 to an acre, by workers crawling on all fours.
</P>
<P>
   During the cool months, the onion-to-be forms its rings, and
when the first blast of heat hits, sometime in March, the rings
begin growing rapidly. Bland has measured the growth, and he said
an onion swells as much as an eighth of an inch every 24 hours
during the process called ``bulbing.''
</P>
<P>
   At harvest time, a flat blade is drawn under the onions, cutting
them from their roots and forcing them halfway out of the ground.
Then they are picked by hand and dropped into burlap coffee-bean
and potato bags, which are left in the fields to begin the drying
process that makes onions last longer.
</P>
<P>
   Back in the sheds, they are dried some more in warm rooms, then
hand sorted for size and quality. The best go into foam-lined boxes
for mail-order customers, the rest into bags or boxes. Some jumbos
are three inches in diameter, but size, in the experts' judgment,
has no impact on flavor.
</P>
<P>
   There is only one crop a year, harvested in April, May and June.
After that, Bland said, ``the gnats move in and the onions melt in
the heat.'' Soybeans take over most of the fields for the long, hot
summer.
</P>
<P>
   But technology, which Bland likes almost as much as he likes
marketing, has extended the season. A colleague of Randle's named
Doyle Smittle, now retired, adapted a storage technique that apple
growers had used for many years, and Vidalias are now available
from April through October. The growers get twice their spring
prices in the fall.
</P>
<P>
   The process is known as ``controlled atmosphere.'' Most of the
oxygen is extracted from huge, thick-walled rooms and replaced with
a mixture containing 92 percent nitrogen at a temperature of 34
degrees and a humidity of 75 percent. Oxygen is what makes onions
rot; nitrogen prevents that.
</P>
<P>
   In a control room nearby, an English-made monitoring system,
which looks sophisticated enough to monitor a space flight,
automatically takes a sample of the air in each room each hour and
sounds an alarm if anything is amiss.
</P>
<P>
   Does Delbert mean it, can Delbert possibly mean it, I wonder,
when he says: ``I don't eat onions myself. I'd much rather chew
tobacco.''
</P>
<P>
   STUFFED VIDALIA ONIONS WITH LEMON BUTTER SAUCE
</P>
<P>
   Time: 1 hour 15 minutes  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   6 medium Vidalia onions
</P>
<P>
   4 tablespoons butter, melted
</P>
<P>
   Salt and freshly ground black pepper
</P>
<P>
   1 pound bulk spicy sausage &QL;
</P>
<P>
   2 tablespoons minced fresh parsley
</P>
<P>
   1 tablespoon minced fresh sage
</P>
<P>
   3/4 cup grated white Cheddar cheese
</P>
<P>
   1 teaspoon minced fresh orange peel
</P>
<P>
   1 tablespoon extra virgin olive oil
</P>
<P>
   1 teaspoon minced garlic
</P>
<P>
   1 teaspoon minced shallot (optional)
</P>
<P>
   \ cup dry white wine or dry vermouth
</P>
<P>
   1 teaspoon minced fresh lemon peel
</P>
<P>
   1 tablespoon lemon juice
</P>
<P>
   \ cup heavy cream
</P>
<P>
   6 tablespoons cold unsalted butter, cut into pieces.
</P>
<P>
   1. Preheat oven to 350 degrees. Place a kettle of water on high
heat, and bring to a boil. Peel the onions, and cut off 1 inch from
each end. Using a sharp-edged spoon, scoop out the centers of the
onions to within about { inch of the bottom. Reserve the centers of
the onions.
</P>
<P>
   2. Place the onions in a shallow baking dish, drizzle with the
melted butter and season with salt and pepper to taste. Add boiling
water to the baking dish until it is halfway up the sides of the
onions. Cover with a lid or foil, and bake until the onions are
tender, about 30 minutes. Carefully transfer the onions from the
water to an oiled baking sheet, and set aside.
</P>
<P>
   3. Mince the reserved onion centers. In a medium skillet over
high heat, combine the minced onion, sausage, parsley and sage.
Saute, stirring well to break up and brown the sausage. Drain and
discard the fat. In a mixing bowl, combine the sausage, \ cup of
the cheese and orange peel. Spoon this mixture into the cavity of
each onion, and sprinkle the onions with the remaining cheese; set
aside. Keep the oven hot.
</P>
<P>
   4. Prepare the lemon butter sauce: In a small saucepan, combine
the olive oil, garlic, shallot, wine, lemon peel and lemon juice.
Bring to a boil and reduce to about 2 tablespoons. Add the cream,
and reduce to about 4 tablespoons. Reduce heat to medium. Whisk in
the cold unsalted butter one piece at a time, until it is melted
and the sauce is thick, about 1 minute. Strain the sauce; keep warm
or it will separate. The sauce may be kept warm in a thermos or
over a pan of hot water for up to 2 hours before serving.
</P>
<P>
   5. Return the onions to the oven until the cheese is melted,
about 5 minutes. To serve, spoon a pool of lemon butter sauce onto
each plate, and top with an onion.
</P>
<P>
   Yield: 6 servings. &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
