<DOCNO> NYT19980609.0201 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-06-09 17:15 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A1268 &Cx1f; taf-z
u l &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-LOUVRE-RESTAURANT-ART     06-09 0851
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-LOUVRE-RESTAURANT-ART-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
AMERICAN CHEF ASKED TO OPEN RESTAURANT IN LOUVRE 
</HEADLINE>
  (ATTN.: Calif.) 
(ART ADV: Photo is being sent to NYT photo clients. Non-subscribers
can make individual purchase by calling 212-556-4204 or -1927.) 
(ja) 
 By MARIAN BURROS   
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   Mon Dieu! The mother of modern American cooking has been asked
to open a restaurant at the temple of French culture in Paris.
</P>
<P>
   Alice Waters, whose restaurant in Berkeley, Calif., Chez
Panisse, has become a shrine to American cooking, is to meet in
California Thursday with Helene David-Weill, the chairwoman and
chief executive of the Museum of Decorative Arts of the Louvre, to
discuss plans for the museum's new 330-seat restaurant. The
building in which the museum is housed is being restored, and the
restaurant is scheduled to open at the end of the year 2000. The
restaurant will look out on the Tuileries Gardens.
</P>
<P>
   If the women, both of whom confirmed that the talks began in
December, can come to an agreement, it would mark a triumphant
return to Paris for Ms. Waters. She went to France 35 years ago,
when she was 19, when the French were raising food organically.
Today, many of their crops are heavily sprayed with pesticides.
</P>
<P>
   ``I lived at the bottom of a market street and took all of that
in by osmosis,'' Ms. Waters said. She brought it back to the United
States and opened Chez Panisse, where the cooking with local
ingredients is American with a Provencal emphasis.
</P>
<P>
   She and Mrs. David-Weill share the same philosophy. ``Alice
Waters is the quintessence of taste and savoir-faire,'' she said.
``She searches for perfection.''
</P>
<P>
   Were there no French chefs for such an undertaking? Mrs.
David-Weill said she did not find them. ``Probably there are very
good people in France but they didn't come to us,'' said Mrs.
David-Weill, whose husband is the chief executive of Lazard Freres,
the French investment banking firm. ``We thought Alice was very
good.''
</P>
<P>
   Last Christmas, when Ms. Waters was in Paris, intermediaries
introduced her to one of Mrs. David-Weill's board members. ``I want
this museum to be international and Alice loves France and
understands the way French people react,'' Mrs. David-Weill said.
``And she wants to come back to France.''
</P>
<P>
   In an interview two years ago to mark the 25th anniversary of
her restaurant, Ms. Waters said: ``The act of eating is very
political. You buy from the right people, you support the right
network of farmers and suppliers who care about the land and what
they put in the food. If we don't preserve the natural resources,
you aren't going to have a sustainable society.''
</P>
<P>
   And she added in an interview earlier this week, ``I feel it is
an obligation to help people understand the relation of food to
agriculture and the relationship of food to culture.''
</P>
<P>
   Ms. Waters has also worked on projects with schoolchildren that
dovetail with the museum's education programs. In 1994, she began
the Edible Schoolyard in Berkeley to teach children how to cook and
take care of the land. She envisions the Louvre restaurant as a
place where patrons can talk to the people who are cooking, where
informational cards explain where the food comes from.
</P>
<P>
   In France, a country especially chauvinistic about its food, the
question arises about a foreigner, and an American at that, opening
a restaurant in its cultural treasure. ``I am very happy because I
have heard very good comments about Alice Waters,'' said France's
only six-star chef, Alain Ducasse. He has three stars for his Paris
restaurant, which bears his name, and for his Monaco restaurant, Le
Louis XV. ``All countries know how cooking should be. Twenty-five
years ago, obviously the disparity was greater.'' That said,
Ducasse still thinks ``French chefs are the best technicians.''
</P>
<P>
   Pierre Gagnaire, chef and owner of the three-star Paris
restaurant bearing his name, said the choice of Ms. Waters was
``formidable.'' He described Ms. Waters as a ``vraie grande
cuisiniere'' _ a real good cook. Since French chefs are always
exporting themselves, he said, ``why would foreigners not come
here?''
</P>
<P>
   Ms. Waters is sensitive to the idea of an American taking over a
restaurant at the august Louvre. ``I could not do this by myself,''
she said. ``I couldn't possibly do it if there were any kind of
resistance. I would need to have good will.''
</P>
<P>
   She said she plans to use French suppliers and chefs, working
with an advisory committee of friends, including the chef Michel
Troisgros; Lulu Peyraud, the owner of Domaine Tempier, a winery in
Bandol, and the baker Lionel Pouillon. ``My French friends are very
excited,'' she said. ``They are very concerned about the future of
French food.''
</P>
<P>
   Ms. Waters still considers the possibility of such a
collaboration fantasy. ``The most powerful part for me is the
recognition by the French that Chez Panisse is a good place to be
and to eat,'' she said. ``It just took my breath away. It's the
most extraordinary thing that could happen to you: to be recognized
by people you want to recognize you.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-06-09-98 1715EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
