<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-06-09 17:22 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A1286 &Cx1f; taf-z
u e &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-LAMOUR-WESTERNS-2TAKE     06-09 0681
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-LAMOUR-WESTERNS-2TAKES-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
LOUIS L'AMOUR: THE PROUST OF THE PRAIRIE GALLOPS ON  
 (HLW) 
</HEADLINE>
   By BRUCE WEBER   
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   DURANGO, Colo. _ If you saw Maggie Rock in a movie, or read
about it in a novel by Louis L'Amour, you would recognize it as the
kind of craggy butte where hostile Indians might gather before
descending on a wagon train in the valley below. But late one
recent afternoon, there were just a couple of casual explorers on
the ridge, one of them Kathy L'Amour, the novelist's widow, who
goes up there a lot.
</P>
<P>
   A fit, lively woman in her 60s who favors embroidered western
shirts and lizard boots, she owns Maggie Rock, along with 1,800
acres of spectacular ranchland near this mountain town in the
southwest corner of the state. She and her husband bought most of
the ranch in 1983 after nearly 20 years of looking for one in the
region where he set some 40 of his 116 books, which have sold an
astounding 250 million copies.
</P>
<P>
   ``This was a research place for Louis,'' Mrs. L'Amour said.
``There are three Indian tribes _ the Utes, the Navajos and the
Apaches _ in the area. It's cattle country, sheep country, horse
country, mining country.''
</P>
<P>
   Just before the wind and the darkening sky (nothing to fool
around with at 9,000 feet) chased her back down the precipitous
ridge slope, Mrs. L'Amour remarked on the view _ the magnificent
valley 1,000 feet below, the 19th-century ranch house and barn the
size of matchboxes from this height _ and the life of her husband,
a self-educated man who died 10 years ago today at 80.
</P>
<P>
   ``Can you imagine what it was like for him, to go from having
nothing to having this?'' she said. The ranch is a fine symbol of
the empire of Louis (pronounced Louie) L'Amour, the most prolific
and beloved writer of westerns _ ``frontier fiction'' in publishing
parlance _ in American history, though he actually lived most of
the year in Los Angeles. It represents not only the territory he
described in his books but also a piece of the world that was
earned by his labor after spending the first half of his life in
wandering adventures, often in search of work.
</P>
<P>
   In sheer size, the ranch suggests the dimensions of L'Amour's
readership: it would take a mammoth basin like this one to hold all
the books he's sold, and maybe they wouldn't fit.
</P>
<P>
   The numbers defy belief. The 116 books by Louis L'Amour, most of
them paperback originals, are all in print _ in print! _ from
Bantam Books, his publisher for four decades, the last 16 of them
published since his death. They include 90 novels, 21 short-story
collections, four works of nonfiction and one book of poems,
``Smoke From This Altar,'' which was published first by a tiny
press in Oklahoma in 1939 and reprinted by Bantam in 1990. That is
his least-selling book, with a mere 107,000 copies in print.
</P>
<P>
   The best-selling book is ``Last of the Breed,'' a contemporary
novel about an American Indian pilot shot down in Siberia. (L'Amour
never felt constrained by the western genre, and he wrote several
books toward the end of his life that were huge crossover
successes, appealing both to his longtime fans and other readers
who never went near a western.) It reached No. 1 on the New York
Times best-seller list in 1986 and has 3.75 million copies in
print.
</P>
<P>
   ``Everything he's written on the fiction side has at least 1
million copies in print,'' said Stuart Applebaum, a Bantam vice
president who has been L'Amour's publicist since 1975. That does
not include ``Monument Rock,'' a just-published hardcover
short-story collection that had a first printing of 207,000.
</P>
<P>
   There are 190 million copies of L'Amour's novels out there, and
28 million copies of his short-story collections, which probably
makes him the best-selling short-story writer of all time. Perhaps
most remarkable is that although his work has been published in 26
languages over the years, the vast majority of the books, 223
million, have been sold in the United States and Canada. He has
sold close to 40 million books since his death.
</P>
<P>
</P>
<P>
   A Fearless Omniscience
</P>
<P>
   The attraction? L'Amour's prose does not, of course, rival
Proust's, nor do his characters show too much complexity; the good
guys and the bad guys are pretty clear from the beginning. But the
plots are more or less irresistible, moving to an inevitable
gunfight; the hardscrabble territory of the 19th-century West is
described with authenticity, and the frontier virtues (hard work,
perseverance, tenacity and skill in outdoor survival) are earnestly
espoused. He wrote with a fearless omniscience, entering the minds
of cowboys and Indians, sheriffs and cattle rustlers, women,
children and even animals.
</P>
<P>
   ``He was hungry, and he wanted meat,'' he wrote of a grizzly
bear in a 1968 novel, ``Down the Long Hills,'' ``and there were,
too, other possibilities of food where the man-smell was. He had
raided camps before this and gotten away with it.''
</P>
<P>
   But L'Amour never wrote about sex.
</P>
<P>
   In ``Education of a Wandering Man,'' an autobiographical volume
that was the last book he finished, he explained: ``I am not
writing about sex, which is a leisure activity. I am writing about
men and women who were settling a new country, finding their way
through a maze of difficulties and learning to survive despite
them.''
</P>
<P>
   He was, in other words, the kind of writer that Republican
presidents devour, that soldiers read in foxholes, that sixth
graders deconstruct in book reports. Letters from fans indicate
that many people would never read at all if it weren't for Louis
L'Amour. Aside from Stephen King, he may be the only writer with
his own personal book-of-the-month club; each month, subscribers
get a different leatherbound volume, and by now, some 25,000 people
have them all: 10 years' worth of L'Amour books. And though critics
have not been overly kind to L'Amour, he has his literary admirers,
including the novelist Louise Erdrich and Daniel Boorstin, the
historian and former Librarian of Congress.
</P>
<P>
   ``My father told a good story,'' said Beau L'Amour, the writer's
son, who is working on a biography that will concentrate on the
peripatetic years that his father referred to as his ``yondering''
days. ``And the western provides a great format for looking at our
society, how we got here. What happened on the frontier has a lot
to say about who we are.''
</P>
<P>
   Mrs. L'Amour and Beau are the caretakers of the L'Amour oeuvre,
which continues to grow. After his father's death, Beau, now 37,
discovered boxes of unpublished stories from the 1950s among his
papers; ``Monument Rock'' is the third volume of those to be
published. Three more are to follow, one each June, and they
include not just western stories but sea stories, boxing stories
and mysteries, among the many genres L'Amour took on when he was
scrambling to make a living selling short stories to pulp
magazines.
</P>
<P>
   Unpublished Novel, But It's Rough
</P>
<P>
   These went unpublished, Beau theorized, because as the pulps
began to dwindle, it became harder to publish stories. At the same
time, the paperback original emerged, and his father, always
concerned with making a living, went the route that would earn him
the most.
</P>
<P>
   ``And there's a novel,'' Beau said, speaking by phone from Los
Angeles, ``though it's a draft that's quite rough. It's a '50s
adventure story set in Chile.''
</P>
<P>
   Louis L'Amour was born in Jamestown, N.D., in 1908, the youngest
of seven children. His father, a Canadian (he changed the family
name to LaMoore; Louis eventually changed it back), was a
veterinarian and farm machinery salesman who, after a series of
local bank failures, moved the family to the Southwest in 1923.
Louis split from his parents to visit an older brother in Oklahoma,
and that started nearly three decades of wandering.
</P>
<P>
   He joined the circus, worked on ships and in mines, and became a
professional boxer, reading voraciously and writing when he could.
He served in Europe in World War II, and when he returned, he
settled in Los Angeles and began sending story after story to the
pulp magazines.
</P>
<P>
   Kathy L'Amour was 20 when she met her future husband in 1952;
she went on a double date with a woman in her acting class. The
other woman was Julie Newmar, who would go on to become, among
other things, Catwoman on the ``Batman'' television series. Ms.
Newmar's date, later her fiance, was Louis L'Amour.
</P>
<P>
   ``They went to New York,'' recalled Mrs. L'Amour, who still has
the sparkling smile and coquettish manner of a young actress of
that era. (She appeared in episodes of ``Death Valley Days'' and
``Gunsmoke.'') ``And they became disengaged. And one day, I was
driving down the street, and he was buying a newspaper on Sunset
Boulevard. And I stopped and said, `I don't know if you'll remember
me,' and he said, `I've been looking everywhere for you.' ''
</P>
<P>
   They were married in February 1956, and until he died she was
his personal assistant as well as his wife.
</P>
<P>
   ``He really loved to write, and he felt he wrote best when he
wrote a lot,'' she said. Once, she said, considering a move from an
electric typewriter to a computer, he was told by Beau that it
would take him six weeks to get accustomed to it, so he decided
against the switch, reasoning it would cost him an entire book.
</P>
<P>
   ``I miss the clack clack clack,'' Mrs. L'Amour said. ``He loved
to be at the typewriter, and I did the things that allowed him to
do that. He never paid a bill, never wrote a check. And I drove him
everywhere. He didn't drive. In return, he gave me this incredible
life.''
</P>
<P>
   L'Amour died of lung cancer, although he never smoked. One
theory, Mrs. L'Amour said, was that the cause was mica dust left in
his lungs from his days as a young man in the mines. But he was
robust virtually to the end. Standing just below Maggie Rock, Mrs.
L'Amour recalled the day her husband, in his late 70s, climbed
alone up the steep, thickly wooded ridge from the ranch.
</P>
<P>
   ``It just never occurred to me that I'd be here, and Louis
wouldn't be here,'' she said. ``That's how dumb I am. That it's 10
years since he's gone, that he's still selling so many books, it's
more of a publishing event than a personal one. I miss him every
day.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
