<SLUG> BC-WINE-TALK-(1,000)2TAKES-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
THE PERIL OF TAMPERING WITH WINE-BUYERS' ILLUSIONS 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (ATTN: France)  (mk) 
 By FRANK J. PRIAL   
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   Wine scandals are few and far between in Bordeaux but when they
occur, as in the current crisis involving Chateau Giscours, they
become major events, not just in France but worldwide.
</P>
<P>
   What piques public interest is not so much the numbers _ in this
instance, some 1,600 cases of Giscours' second-tier wine _ but the
irony. The Bordeaux wine trade fosters an image of itself as an
elite group, removed from the tawdry machinations of the
marketplace and governed by an old-fashioned code of honor. Because
of this unified image, trouble, even at only one chateau, resounds
throughout the region. When one chateau sneezes, all of Bordeaux
catches cold.
</P>
<P>
   By now most of the wine world is aware of the charges of
fraudulent winemaking leveled last week against Chateau Giscours, a
third growth in the 1855 classification of Bordeaux chateaus, and
one of the largest wine estates in the Bordeaux region. Giscours is
in the commune of Labarde, about 20 miles north of the city of
Bordeaux and a part of the famous Margaux wine district.
</P>
<P>
   Bordeaux prosecutors, acting on information supplied by
government fraud inspectors, have indicted two of the chateau's
employees, an enologist and the former cellar master who now lives
in Lebanon, and charged that under their direction, Chateau
Giscours engaged in fraudulent practices. These include mixing the
chateau's wine with cheaper wine from another district, mixing one
vintage with another and treating the wine with wood chips to
simulate barrel aging. Also, the indictments claim, sugar was added
to boost the wine's alcoholic content, and at one time or another,
water, milk or acid, to stretch the wine and to improve its bouquet
and taste.
</P>
<P>
   While the indictments mention only one vintage, 1995, French
press reports said that the investigation had been under way for
two years and that the inspectors had determined there had been a
pattern of fraud over an unspecified period of time. The inquiry
became public last week, just as prices for 1997 Bordeaux wines
were being released for the first time.
</P>
<P>
   The current owner of the vineyards and winery, a Dutch investor
named Eric Albada Jelgersma, said the charges had been exaggerated.
He added that he had been unaware of what was happening and would
buy back any of the wine cited, the chateau's 1995 second wine, La
Sirene de Giscours. Still to be determined is the impact of
Giscours' problems on the rest of the Bordeaux market _ and on the
public trust.
</P>
<P>
   Reactions in the wine trade ranged from anger to dismay as in
recent weeks, one chateau after another has announced prices for
the wines of 1997, a good but unexceptional vintage, that are up to
25 percent higher than those for 1996. In New York, Michael Aaron,
chairman of Sherry-Lehmann, a major retailer, announced that he
would not offer future contracts for the 1997s.
</P>
<P>
   Dedicated wine enthusiasts customarily buy future contracts;
that is, they pay for a wine two years before it is aged, bottled
and released, in expectation that its price will escalate by the
time it is shipped. ``Even though we will be obliged to purchase
some 1997s,'' Aaron said, ``we feel that offering futures on these
wines is not in the interest of our clientele.''
</P>
<P>
   In other words, the 1997s, unlike some previous, highly praised
vintages, are unlikely to increase in value over the next two
years. Current prices for Bordeaux wines are at levels unimaginable
even a decade ago. The 1997 opening price of Chateau Margaux, one
of the five so-called first growths of Bordeaux, announced last
month was 600 francs, or more than $100 a bottle, which translates
into a retail price of around $200.
</P>
<P>
   As always happens at or near the peak of the Bordeaux price
cycle, the chateau owners and Bordeaux exporters are being accused
of avarice and greed. And since such astronomical price levels have
little to do with the intrinsic quality of the wine and everything
to do with demand, any bad news might bring down the whole shaky
edifice.
</P>
<P>
   What makes the system so fragile is the fact that it is based on
trust. Many fine wines are bought by people who know little about
the subject but assume that a famous label and high price insure
the best. Often, they have no interest in drinking the wine; they
hold it, hoping to sell at an even higher price a few years later.
Bordeaux tampers with their illusions at its peril.
</P>
<P>
   There are inevitable _ and ominous _ parallels between the
current Bordeaux market and the market in the 1970s. In 1974, after
the prestigous firm of Cruse &AMP; Fils Freres had been found guilty of
similar charges _ vats in their cellars were found with labels
``can be used as Beaujolais in the U.S.'' _ the entire Bordeaux
market collapsed. Big exporting firms went bankrupt; great chateaus
were sold for pittances, their cellars clogged with unwanted wine.
Distributors and retailers in this country who had invested heavily
in the mediocre 1971 vintage and the poor 1972s lost sizable sums.
</P>
<P>
   Overnight, it seemed, no one was interested in Bordeaux and its
wines. The Bordeaux market did not fully recover until the early
1980s.
</P>
<P>
   Trust is important because it's not particularly difficult to do
what Giscours is accused of doing. A connoisseur might recognize
the deception; hardly anyone else would. Many cellar techniques can
be artificially replicated, which means that illegal activities are
often difficult to detect. Several Bordeaux chateau owners
maintained that the charges against Giscours were an indication
that the anti-fraud laws worked. In fact, most wine fraud
investigations stem from tips from disgruntled employees and
suspicious (or jealous) competitors. In Giscours' case, it was one
or more former employees who called in the inspectors.
</P>
<P>
   Many techniques banned in Bordeaux are permissible in other
countries and even in other parts of France. Using oak chips or
staves is common for inexpensive California wines; using sugar to
boost alcoholic content is legal in Burgundy, and the use of acid,
which adds zest to wines, is common in hot countries. Citric acids
are used in California.
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   nn
</P>
<P>
   Jelgersma, the owner of the vineyards at Chateau Giscours, noted
last week that only a small amount of wine from outside the Margaux
boundaries had been used and that it had gone only into the
chateau's second wine. Many Bordeaux chateaus bottle the wine from
their less impressive vats and from younger vines separately under
a second label.
</P>
<P>
   Jelgersma said that the illegal wine in the blend cited by the
prosecutors actually came from two Giscours vineyards just over the
line from the commune of Margaux. Giscours wines are entitled to
use the Margaux name on their labels. Wines from the two other
vineyard are entitled only to be listed as coming from the
Haut-Medoc, a less prestigious name.
</P>
<P>
   Jelgersma is referred to as the owner of Giscours; exactly what
he owns is unclear. Apparently, he owns the right to make the wine
but not the vineyards or the chateau. They still belong to the Tari
family, which bought the estate in 1952.
</P>
<P>
   In recent years, dissension among the Taris, exacerbated by
financial problems, had its effect on the wine. In 1995, Jelgersma
bought the production rights from Pierre Tari, who had succeeded
his father, Nicolas, as director of Giscours. The Taris have spent
much of the last five years fighting each other in the Bordeaux
courts.
</P>
<P>
   One Bordeaux figure, Bruno Borie, whose family owns Chateau
Ducru-Beaucaillou in St. Julien, saw darker elements at work.
``It's no coincidence that this story broke just when Bordeaux was
enjoying considerable prosperity,'' he said. ``That it broke during
a controversy over the 1997 prices, that it broke just as the press
of the world was descending on France _ and particularly on
Bordeaux _ for the World Cup, that it appeared first in Le Monde
rather than in the Sud-Ouest'' _ the leftist Paris newspaper rather
than in the possibly more understanding Bordeaux daily _ ``and that
it appeared on a national holiday'' _ June 1 _ ``when journalists
had little chance to check facts.''
</P>
<P>
   Writing about Chateau Giscours earlier this year, France's
best-known wine critic, Michel Bettane, observed: ``Little by
little, in the 1980s, the wine lost its reputation, even as nature
supplied us with a series of very great vintages. At present,
internal discord has completely paralyzed the evolution'' of the
Giscours wine.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
