<HEADLINE>
WEATHER 
</HEADLINE>
 (Editors: The following text accompanies the weather map for
Wednesday, June 10, sent to computer graphics clients of The New
York Times News Service. For information call 212-556-4204.) 
(th) 
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   Clusters of heavy showers and thunderstorms will douse parts of
the central Mississippi, Tennessee and lower Ohio River valleys
Wednesday. Storms will erupt as humid air 2,000 feet above the
ground racing north at almost 60 mph from the Gulf of Mexico is
lifted by a jet stream disturbance arriving from the southern
Plains.
</P>
<P>
   Missouri appears to be in the direct line of fire, with
rainfalls of five inches or more possible by Thursday morning.
Flash flooding is likely in some areas.
</P>
<P>
   Farther southwest, a few severe thunderstorms will flare up over
west Texas along a boundary separating dry air from the Rockies and
the plateaus of Old Mexico from gathering humid air from the Gulf
of Mexico. These storms will have the potential to spawn strong
winds, large hail and tornadoes.
</P>
<P>
   To the west, isolated vigorous thunderstorms are possible over
the southern Rockies as an upper-level trough of low pressure
pivots northeast from Baja California.
</P>
<P>
   Scattered potent thunderstorms will boil up over eastern Oregon
as a jet stream disturbance arrives from the Gulf of Alaska. To the
east, hit-or-miss strong thunderstorms will mushroom over the
northern Plains as an insurgent upper-level disturbance dips south
from Canada and lifts moist surface air.
</P>
<P>
   Some showers and thunderstorms will develop near a wavering
front strung across the Middle Atlantic States. Flooding will occur
in areas where a few heavy storms follow on the heels of one
another. Meanwhile, much of New England will be dry, save for
isolated showers in Maine.
</P>
<P>
   FOCUS: JUNE GLOOM
</P>
<P>
   Ocean fog and stratus settled over California shores on Monday.
At San Diego, 0.07 inches of rain also fell, establishing a new
record for the date. Protracted periods of low clouds are common at
the coast in June, giving rise to a local expression, ``June
gloom.'' Ocean fog forms when moist, Pacific air passes over chilly
offshore waters. In transit, this marine layer is cooled to the
point where net condensation begins and fog forms and then rolls
ashore. As coastal waters warm in July and August, the marine layer
typically grows thinner, allowing morning fog and low clouds to
disperse faster. &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
