<SLUG> BC-BROADWAY-BOXOFFICE-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
BROADWAY ATTENDANCE RECORD: 11.5 MILLION 
</HEADLINE>
   (bl)  
 By RICK LYMAN   
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ Attendance at Broadway shows hit an all-time high of
11.5 million during the season that just ended, according to
figures released Tuesday by the League of American Theaters and
Producers.
</P>
<P>
   The 1997-98 season, which closed with the presentation of the
Tony Awards on Sunday night at Radio City Music Hall, also saw a 12
percent increase in box-office grosses to $558 million, said Jed
Bernstein, the league's executive director.
</P>
<P>
   Part of the reason for the increases was the inauguration of
three new Broadway theaters: the New Amsterdam Theater, where Walt
Disney Co. opened ``The Lion King'' in December; the Ford Center
for the Performing Arts, where Livent opened ``Ragtime'' in
January, and the Kit Kat Klub in the revamped Henry Miller Theater,
where the Roundabout Theater Company opened its revival of
``Cabaret'' in March.
</P>
<P>
   Another contributing factor was that Broadway theaters were used
more often than they had been in the previous season, a total of
1,442 weeks compared to 1,347 the season before. The 1997-98 season
saw 33 shows open in Broadway theaters, the league said. Three were
musical revivals, 9 were new musicals, 8 were revivals of plays, 11
were new plays, and 2 (``Forever Tango'' and ``Patti LaBelle on
Broadway'') were designated as ``specials.''
</P>
<P>
   Producers for the biggest Tony winners said they had experienced
surges in ticket sales following the ceremony. ``Lion King'' drew
six awards, including one for best new musical, while ``Ragtime,''
``Cabaret'' and ``The Beauty Queen of Leenane'' all won four.
</P>
<P>
   But other shows, which failed to win an award, have decided to
end their struggle. Producers of ``The Diary of Anne Frank'' and
the musical ``1776,'' both revivals, announced Tuesday that they
would close after Sunday's performances. ``Honour,'' a new play
starring Jane Alexander, announced on Monday that it would also
close on Sunday.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's been a battle,'' said Stewart Lane, one of the producers
of ``1776.'' ``We fought the good fight.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-06-09-98 1736EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19980609.0213 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-06-09 17:38 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A1319 &Cx1f; taf-z
u l &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-SPAGO-NYT &LR;      06-09 0733
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-SPAGO-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
PUCK TAKES AMERICAN DINING IN ANOTHER DIRECTION 
</HEADLINE>
  (ART ADV: Photo is being sent to NYT photo clients. Non-subscribers
can make individual purchase by calling 212-556-4204 or -1927.) 
(ja) 
 By RUTH REICHL   
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   BEVERLY HILLS, Calif. _ When Wolfgang Puck opened Spago in West
Hollywood in early 1982, he changed American restaurants. He did
not do it by serving California cuisine or putting caviar on pizza;
in fact, he didn't do it with the food at all.
</P>
<P>
   Puck, a classically trained French chef who began his
apprenticeship at age 13, and his partner, Barbara Lazaroff, now
his wife, were the first restaurateurs to realize that rich
Americans longed for great food without formality.
</P>
<P>
   And so he began serving oysters without ostentation and foie
gras without fuss. He told his customers that they could come in
blue jeans if they wanted, and it turned out that they did.
</P>
<P>
   ``It should always feel like a party in the restaurant,'' Ms.
Lazaroff said then, as she and Puck took the starch out of fine
dining.
</P>
<P>
   Last year, the couple opened Spago Beverly Hills, switching
their focus from the casual West Hollywood location to a far more
refined setting. The new restaurant once again gave an early clue
to a new direction for dining in America.
</P>
<P>
   The food is better than ever. A recent meal that Puck cooked on
the regular chef's night off began with three extraordinary
appetizers that showed off the different directions traveled by
Puck's restless culinary spirit. Crayfish with beets from the Chino
Ranch was pure California cuisine, the best vegetables snatched
from the garden and left to speak for themselves. Hamachi, a single
soft slice of raw yellowtail served with ginger, seaweed and sticky
rice, was proof of Puck's enduring interest in Asian cooking. White
asparagus with horseradish cream, on the other hand, was straight
from his Austrian homeland.
</P>
<P>
   The next course was another homage to Austria. Puck's marrow
soup was the richest, most wonderful broth you could imagine,
filled with slices of poached marrow and a single, silky dumpling.
It was, simply, one of the best things I have ever eaten.
</P>
<P>
   It was followed by more white asparagus _ the season is so short
_ in brown butter and bread crumbs. And then langoustines from
Santa Barbara with fava beans dressed in apple balsamic vinegar and
pumpkinseed oil, two delicacies made only in Austria.
</P>
<P>
   Then the waiter proudly showed off an entire turbot steamed in a
jacket of ginger and garlic. The pure white fish was firm and
tender, the contrast with the herbs intense enough to frame its
clean flavor. Afterward the waiter appeared with the tiniest rack
of lamb, each chop no more than a couple of bites, surrounded by
roasted garlic and carrots.
</P>
<P>
   Finally there were cheese and just a morsel of dessert: tiny
lemon meringue tarts in a drizzle of berry coulis. The last flavor
was bittersweet and just right.
</P>
<P>
   It was a meal that demonstrated a chef at the height of his
power. And it was an answer to all the people who say it is
impossible for a chef to open inexpensive cafes, as Puck has done,
without losing his culinary edge. But what impressed me even more
than the food was the new maturity of service in the restaurant.
</P>
<P>
   The new Spago still feels like a party. But it is considerably
less casual than the old one. Busboys hover about, bringing bread
almost before you want it and keeping your glasses filled with
water. Waiters work harder: That turbot arrived as a whole fish to
be sliced at the table. There is a new seriousness to the wine
list, as well. The sommelier, Michael Bonacorsi (who came from
Masa's in San Francisco), has assembled a varied and unusual group
of wines to go with the food. Best of all, he talks about his
favorites with knowledge and absolutely no pretension.
</P>
<P>
   Americans have been slowly inventing a new style of service, one
that is different from the classic European model. The great
restaurateur Joe Baum was among the first to bend his energies to
this. Danny Meyer, the owner of Union Square Cafe and Gramercy
Tavern in Manhattan, has been another thoughtful practitioner of
the new, less formal American style.
</P>
<P>
   Meanwhile, out in California, Spago first made a statement 16
years ago, and now the new one is making another. It is one more
proof that American dining is coming of age.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-06-09-98 1738EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
