<DOCNO> NYT19980609.0214 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-06-09 17:40 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A1324 &Cx1f; taf-z
u e &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-FARM-FILM-REVIEW-NYT &LR;      06-09 0662
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FARM-FILM-REVIEW-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
`THE FARM: ANGOLA, U.S.A.': OF LIFE, AND DEATH, BEHIND BARS  
 (HLW) 
</HEADLINE>
   By JANET MASLIN   
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ No stereotypes about prison life intrude on the
candor and intimacy of ``The Farm: Angola, U.S.A.,'' the discreetly
searing documentary that shared top honors at this year's Sundance
Film Festival and opens at the Film Forum on Wednesday. With
extraordinary tact and acuity, the filmmakers Jonathan Stack, Liz
Garbus and Wilbert Rideau, who is an inmate, explore the world
inside a vast maximum security prison and consider the coping
mechanisms that make up everyday life there. The place is the
Louisiana State Penitentiary at Angola, a former slave plantation
named for its African population. Prisoners, 85 percent of whom
will die at Angola, do field work for as little as 4 cents an hour.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is the story of six men trying to overcome the odds,''
the film's narrator states. But those odds are indeed daunting.
Only four of the six subjects here are still alive when the film is
over. New inmates with long sentences learn that their friends and
relatives are liable to forget them. (The average Angola prisoner
never receives a visit after his first three years.) And the only
goals with even a prayer of being realized are spiritual ones.
``The Farm'' includes shockingly dismissive parole board
deliberations for a man who insists that he was wrongly accused of
two rapes by women who admitted thinking that all black men looked
alike and who received a 100-year sentence for those crimes.
</P>
<P>
   The parole board scene, like many other sequences here, attests
to the filmmakers' skill at unobtrusively entering the prisoners'
world and at avoiding trite, melodramatic ideas about
incarceration. No cafeteria fights or tin cups banging against bars
here; the inmates have become a tractable group thanks to the
virtual hopelessness of their situation. Some, like the model
prisoner Ashanti Witherspoon, who was sentenced to 75 years for
armed robbery and now counsels new inmates about what they can
expect, have become the helpful citizens they never were before.
All speak of their past crimes as if they were part of a separate
life.
</P>
<P>
   Logan (Bones) Theriot, now an old man dying of lung cancer,
recalls coming home from overseas to a wife who was pregnant by a
friend of his and of being enraged when she later treated the baby
badly. ``My wife and I had a little trouble and I killed her,'' he
says, while the camera visits the mug shot of a young,
vital-looking Logan. Barely a trace of his earlier self remains in
a man whose most formative years seem to have been lived at Angola.
Fellow prisoners are seen crying for Theriot and doing their best
to comfort him as the end draws near.
</P>
<P>
   Though every inmate in ``The Farm'' shares the dream of freedom,
the film explores what it means to be beyond fighting impossible
odds and seeking sustenance wherever it can be found. From the
white warden who notes pettily that it costs $10,000 a day to feed
5,000 men to the prison preacher who could be free if Louisiana's
governor signed his pardon, this thoughtful, gripping film examines
prison life from every imaginable angle except the unsurprising
ones. In conveying the humanity of prisoners lost in an unyielding
system, ``The Farm'' does for these men what they may never be able
to do for themselves.
</P>
<P>
   PRODUCTION NOTES:
</P>
<P>
   THE FARM: ANGOLA, U.S.A.
</P>
<P>
   Directed by Jonathan Stack, Liz Garbus and Wilbert Rideau;
produced by Stack and Ms. Garbus; directors of photography, Samuel
Henriques and Bob Perrin; edited by Mona Davis and Mary Mandardt;
music by Curtis Lundy; released by Gabriel Films. At the Film
Forum, 209 Houston Street, Manhattan. Running time: 93 minutes.
This film is not rated.
</P>
<P>
   WITH: George Crawford, Vincent Simmons, Eugene (Bishop)
Tannehill, Logan (Bones) Theriot, John Brown, Ashanti Witherspoon,
Burl Cain and Wilbert Rideau.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
