<DATE_TIME> 1998-06-09 17:41 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A1326 &Cx1f; taf-z
u e &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-SWEET-BOOK-REVIEW-NYT     06-09 1045
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-SWEET-BOOK-REVIEW-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
`BE SWEET': A CAREER BASED ON THE SECOND CHOICE 
</HEADLINE>
   (editors: publication notes at end of review)  
 (bl)  
 By RICHARD BERNSTEIN   
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   Once, seeing a camera pointing in his direction, the amiable and
celebrated parodist of Soviet life, Vladimir Voinovich, wiped away
the smile that was on his face and assumed a melancholy air.
``Satirists are supposed to look gloomy,'' he said as the
electronic flash illuminated his features.
</P>
<P>
   The same might be said of humorists, who in any case are more or
less indistinguishable from satirists. The same is certainly said
by Roy Blount Jr., who has entertained a loyal following of readers
with what must by now be thousands of rueful, poignant, funny
articles and a number of books. His latest, ``Be Sweet,'' is a
rambling variation on Voinovich's remark, summed up in various of
Blount's darker comments:
</P>
<P>
   ``There's not much constructive you can do with self-loathing
other than make humor.''
</P>
<P>
   ``Just as unsightly adolescents shave off patches of hair and
put studs in their noses to make it appear that they  &UR; mean &LR;  to be
ugly, I began to cultivate my comic potential.''
</P>
<P>
   ``Woody Allen once told an interviewer that being funny `is
always a second choice.' The first choice, I guess, is being . . .
sweet. Or happy, or something.''
</P>
<P>
   ``Be Sweet'' is a kind of memoir tracing Blount's humoristic
origins in what the pop psychologists call a dysfunctional family.
The attention here is especially on Blount's late mother, Louise, a
Southern woman whose parents died when she was a child and whose
fear of abandonment led her to cultivate the kind of guilt-inducing
tragic mien that has kept various funny men in business for
decades. ``My mother loved me to pieces, as she often said, and I'm
still trying to put them together,'' Blount writes.
</P>
<P>
   And so, his book of brief sketches, each of them vaguely focused
on some autobiographical element _ Blount's relationship with his
younger sister, his appearances on television talk shows, his
experience of being taken for other people _ elaborates on the idea
of funniness as a defense against melancholy and the lack of
self-regard, as a substitute for self-pity. Chapter after chapter
Blount brandishes the absurdist sensibility that has made him
famous, and he sometimes makes you laugh out loud as he does so.
</P>
<P>
   Likable as Blount is, though, and tickled, intrigued, touched as
you will be by certain passages of unillusioned self-revelation,
``Be Sweet'' remains an uneven, hit-or-miss piece of work. To put
this as an economist might: Blount's book is a literary version of
the law of marginal utility. The first few chapters are the most
enjoyable; what works beautifully when it comes in small doses
eventually reaches a point of diminishing returns as the author
meanders at book length through his subjects.
</P>
<P>
   It is not that bright and memorable passages are absent. Blount
is so smart and engaging that he couldn't avoid them if he tried.
But by the time you are midway through ``Be Sweet,'' you are awash
in deja vu. Blount repeats a bit too many times some of his
personal themes; at the same time, his riffs on other subjects,
like his struggles with ``female consciousness,'' have a more than
twice-told quality.
</P>
<P>
   Blount's technique is to sustain a kind of casual, contrarian
chatter full of free associations, self-interruptions, anecdotes,
jokes, limericks and other doggerel (most of which is very clever).
The starting point, as Blount reminds us several times, is that he
is 55; he is ``a single grandfather''; he lives alone. He is also
haunted by memories of a child wounded by the possessive,
emotionally terrified and terrifying Louise. `` `I just want to get
you children raised,' Louise used to say, `and then I want to
die,''' is the kind of thing Blount cites as evidence of his
mother's character. ``The time has come,'' he says, ``to lift the
family curse,'' and he is off and running on his diverse, diverting
but also jumbled remembrances.
</P>
<P>
   Here and there are sentences of pure genius. ``Miss Shirley,''
Blount writes of his eighth-grade teacher, ``was a large, confused
but obdurate, percolating but never quite fully brewed woman who
blew things out of proportion.''
</P>
<P>
   His efforts to understand his mother represent a shrewd and
affecting attempt at a kind of posthumous reconciliation. Some of
Blount's jokes _ there is an off-color one about Tonto and the Lone
Ranger that alone is almost worth the price of this volume _ are
very funny, even thought they come, like much else in ``Be Sweet,''
apropos of almost nothing.
</P>
<P>
   Blount's chapter called ``Sauce for the Genders'' _ which begins
with a citation from Yeats to the effect that many men have been
ruined by the desire for a wife and child _ is a good example of a
digressive style mixing charm with mannerism. He begins with a
memory of some embarrassment caused by his mother. He veers to the
subject of his youthful curly hair and then to his 1960s and '70s
haircuts. He riffs briefly on the differences between men and women
before going on to the walk-on role he played in the movie
``Philadelphia,'' his recollections of being taught to drive by his
mother (and her near-hysterical fearfulness), a joke about Adam and
Eve, an e-mail message about dying computer screens sent by his
sister, the Oedipal complex and an odd passage that he read in an
Ohio newspaper. This helter-skelter narrative is punctuated by
single-phrase paragraphs aimed at establishing an easy intimacy, a
kind of bar-stool familiarity with the reader:
</P>
<P>
   ``Papa boo-boo bye-bye.''
</P>
<P>
   ``I thought to myself, Well, gee.''
</P>
<P>
   ``Hey, everybody is interesting.''
</P>
<P>
   Throughout Blount's new book are examples of a mind that is
always rambunctiously engaged in an astonishing array of
activities, from playing in a writers' rock-and-roll band to
interviewing Willie Mays. But ``Be Sweet'' does not have its
author's usual effortlessness. It strains too hard for its effect,
which prevents it from being one of the more brilliant products in
Blount's otherwise impressive oeuvre.
</P>
<P>
   Publication notes:
</P>
<P>
   BE SWEET
</P>
<P>
   A Conditional Love Story
</P>
<P>
   By Roy Blount Jr.
</P>
<P>
   289 pages. Alfred A. Knopf. $24.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
