<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FOOD-NOTES-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
FOOD NOTES 
</HEADLINE>
  (mk) 
 By FLORENCE FABRICANT   
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ Tea in the garden is an inviting notion on a balmy
afternoon in late spring. And the new, umbrella-shaded garden at
Sweet Melissa in Cobble Hill, Brooklyn, fulfills the fantasy. Sweet
Melissa, a pastry shop and cafe that opened in April at 276 Court
St., serves tea from 1:30 to 5:30 p.m. daily except Monday. The
tea, brewed in old-fashioned china pots, is accompanied by
irresistible palmiers, scones, fruit tartlets or chocolate souffle
cakes.
</P>
<P>
   Melissa Murphy, who was the pastry chef at Home, Drovers Tap
Room and Home Away From Home, all in Greenwich Village, is the
co-owner and baker.
</P>
<P>
   Even if one doesn't linger for tea, the shop is worth a visit to
take home some delicate madeleines (75 cents each), a sugar-glazed
lemon tart ($14), fallen chocolate souffle cake ($24), moist banana
bread ($6), a nutty sticky bun ($2), a berry-topped custard tartlet
($3.50) or a thimble-size blueberry tartlet ($1).
</P>
<P>
   The shop also has tables indoors and serves light fare like
salads, soups and sandwiches ($4.50 to $8.95) until 10 p.m. from
Tuesday through Thursday, midnight on Friday and Saturday, and 5
p.m. on Sunday. It is closed on Monday.
</P>
<P>
   In French Kitchens
</P>
<P>
   It's one thing to dine in a place that carries two or three
Michelin stars in France, or to try to follow a recipe in a
cookbook written by the chef. But now nonprofessionals can spend
five or six days there cooking in restaurant kitchens alongside
great chefs like Alain Senderens and Michel Rostang in Paris,
Michel Troisgros in Roanne, Gerard Boyer in Reims and Jacques
Chibois in Grasse.
</P>
<P>
   L'Ecole des Chefs, run by Annie Jacquet-Bentley, a restaurant
consultant in Birchrunville, Pa., offers internships in 17 two- or
three-star French restaurants. Most of the restaurants accept only
one intern at a time, though some take couples. There are also
internships with Pierre Herme, the pastry chef at Laduree in Paris,
and with Potel &AMP; Chabot, the Parisian caterer.
</P>
<P>
   The price, which includes meals with the restaurant staff and a
workday of eight to 12 hours, is $1,950 in a two-star restaurant,
$2,450 in a three-star (accommodations and transportation not
included). Though no French is required, applicants are expected to
have cooking experience, and not all are accepted. Students and
recent graduates of culinary schools may also apply.
</P>
<P>
   L'Ecole des Chefs offers the same program to experienced working
chefs, but the cost is $3,900 in a two-star restaurant, $4,900 in a
three-star. Information: (610) 469-2500.
</P>
<P>
   Cliff's Notes for Cooks
</P>
<P>
   For a reference aid, Instant Culinary Guides are
information-filled bookmarks that can be slipped into cookbooks.
The slender, fold-out brochures, held in plastic sleeves, come in
three versions, offering advice on cooking terms, wines and
cheeses, or conversions and substitutions. The guides are $2.50
each at Barnes &AMP; Noble bookstores. The set of three can be ordered
by mail for $7.50, plus $2 for shipping, by calling (800) 636-0044.
(By mail, they do not come in the protective plastic sleeves.)
</P>
<P>
   Chocolates by the Number
</P>
<P>
   There's no guesswork with the chocolates of Joel Durand, a
confectioner in St.-Remy-de-Provence, France. He offers boxes of 32
squares of filled milk and dark chocolates, with each chocolate
marked with a number; a little guidebook lists the flavor of each.
And we're not talking just mocha or mint. The fillings are also
seasoned with star anise, chicory, lavender or a mixture of almonds
and black olives. My only complaint is that too many of the candies
are coated in milk, not dark chocolate, and lack the bitter
contrast that some of the wilder flavors need. The nine-ounce box
of chocolates is available at Aux Delices, 1075 East Putnam Ave.,
Riverside, Conn., or by mail for $30, plus shipping: (203)
698-1066.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
