<HEADLINE>
CULTURE NOTES: SONGWRITERS' HALL OF FAME; FIGHT OVER THE MARBLES;
STONES IN MOSCOW; PICASSO AT CORCORAN
</HEADLINE>
   (ja) 
 By   LAWRENCE   VAN   GELDER   
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   The songwriting team of Fats Domino and Dave Bartholomew; John
Barry, who wrote a dozen James Bond movie themes, and John
Williams, who wrote the scores for many Steven Spielberg films, are
to be inducted into the Songwriters' Hall of Fame Wednesday night
at the organization's annual dinner at the Sheraton New York Hotel
and Towers. Among others to be honored are Larry Stock (``You're
Nobody 'Til Somebody Loves You''), Diana Ross, Nancy Sinatra and
Paul Simon.  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Art Wars
</P>
<P>
   In the latest skirmish over the Elgin marbles, Greece accused
Britain Tuesday of arrogance in saying that the ancient sculptures
from the Parthenon were better preserved in London than in Athens.
The outburst was prompted by a new book, ``Lord Elgin and the
Marbles,'' by the British historian William St. Clair, which says
that in 1937, workers in the British Museum damaged the fifth
century B.C. marbles by trying to remove their honey-colored patina
with metal scrapers and powerful cleaners. Culture Minister
Evangelos Venizelos said the book buttressed Greece's case for the
marbles' return. Britain acknowledged damage but said it was
exaggerated. Officials maintain that the marbles should stay in
London, safe from the smog of Athens and accessible to millions of
visitors. Many museums fear that if Greece does win back the
marbles, the way may be opened for other nations to reclaim
treasures.
</P>
<P>
   On the Move
</P>
<P>
   The Rolling Stones are Moscow bound for the first time in their
30-year career. The Moscow show on Aug. 11 was announced Tuesday as
part of the revised itinerary for the European leg of the Stones'
world tour, beginning in Germany on Saturday and ending in
September in the Netherlands. Earlier this week, after the sale of
300,000 tickets, the Stones postponed the British part of the tour,
which had been scheduled for August. They said a revision of
Britain's tax laws would have cost them $19.5 million, forcing the
band's European tour into the red. The four British concerts have
been rescheduled for next June, in a new tax year.
</P>
<P>
   Shapes of the Future
</P>
<P>
   A new Picasso has taken up residence at the Corcoran Gallery of
Art in Washington. It is a rare oval oil painting, ``A Glass on a
Table'' (1913), that exemplifies Picasso's early creative visual
experiments. The painting, a gift to the Corcoran in memory of
Ingrid and Morton Leeds by their children, is on display through
June 22 as the focus of an exhibit of five Cubist-inspired works
and a Picasso etching.  &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
