<HEADER>
A1344 &Cx1f; taf-z
u e &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-OYAMADA-MUSIC-NYT &LR;      06-09 0923
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-OYAMADA-MUSIC-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
KEIGO OYAMADA: ECLECTICISM PERSONIFIED 
</HEADLINE>
   (bl)  
 By NEIL STRAUSS   
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   TOKYO _ Before speaking a word of greeting, Keigo Oyamada runs
around the offices of Trattoria Records, handing out elaborately
packaged CDs of cutting-edge Japanese rock bands, obscure English
girl groups, French chansons sung by Japanese vocalists and soccer
anthem compilations.
</P>
<P>
   Trattoria may be one of the most eclectic and interesting
boutique labels affiliated with a major record company (Polystar),
and not only does Oyamada help run it, he is also its best-selling
act, Cornelius (named after the chimpanzee from ``Planet of the
Apes''). He is on his first world tour and performs in New York on
Thursday night at Shine, at 380 Canal St. in Chinatown.
</P>
<P>
   In Japan, Oyamada is an unlikely pop star: thousands of teen-age
girls flock to his concerts to watch him play an idiosyncratic mix
of easy-listening music, psychedelic rock and hip-hop collage.
</P>
<P>
   In the United States, Oyamada has a cult reputation as a
Japanese analogue to Beck, a restlessly creative introvert
recording rickety, innovative songs from a channel surfer's point
of view. But the best way to understand Oyamada is to take a look
at Trattoria's bizarre back catalog of releases.
</P>
<P>
   For example, there are the solo albums by Bill Wyman of the
Rolling Stones that Oyamada reissued. ``I saw that Bill Wyman had a
record called `Monkey Grip,' and I liked the name,'' the
primate-fixated Oyamada said via a translator. ``And I could see
putting together an advertising campaign saying, `Trattoria signs
the Rolling Stones.' The albums didn't sell at all, though.''
</P>
<P>
   Then there's the album he released by the sprinter Linford
Christie. ``I was looking through the Polystar catalog one day, and
I saw an album cover with a picture of a guy running with a gold
medal around his neck and pulling a tire on a rope, and it cracked
me up so much I had to release it,'' Oyamada explained, laughing.
``I also liked the idea of putting out a record by an Olympic gold
medalist, especially since he sings the Spencer Davis Group's `Keep
On Running' really off tune.''
</P>
<P>
   Oyamada pulled the collar of his brown jacket over his mouth and
quietly added, ``And that didn't sell either.''
</P>
<P>
   Like many interesting musicians emerging in countries like
Germany, Sweden and Japan, Oyamada is as much a collector as a
musician.
</P>
<P>
   ``Growing up, I listened to a lot of music from overseas,'' he
said. ``And because of the distance that Japan was from all these
other countries, information about the bands, the music and the
scene it was coming from didn't necessarily follow. So I had to
create my own genres. I remember listening only to orange-colored
records, and I'd group them into my orange record series and just
listen to them as orange records. Or if there was skull imagery in
the album artwork, I'd think of them as the skull bands. I just
created my own genres and understandings of them, and that
influences what I do and maybe makes it different.''
</P>
<P>
   Oyamada began his career in a band called Lollipop Sonic and
then Flipper's Guitar, an influential Japanese band that played
gentle, British-influenced lounge pop. After the band broke up,
with Oyamada's partner Kenji Ozawa going on to become a pop star in
his own right, Oyamada reinvented himself as Cornelius.
</P>
<P>
   With each new album, the music seemed to be made more and more
from a listener's perspective than a musician's, with original
playing replaced by samples of everything from the Beach Boys to
``Planet of the Apes'' and songs turning into strange explorations
of pop minutiae.
</P>
<P>
   In his first American performance, at the South by Southwest
music convention this year in Austin, Oyamada fluctuated from
beautiful pop songs to textural noise, interrupting one song to
play a warbling note-for-note version of ``Love Me Tender'' on the
theremin _ an impressive feat considering the difficulty of
pinpointing pitches on that old electronic instrument.
</P>
<P>
   Every member of the band had bowl haircuts, sunglasses and
red-and-white crew-neck shirts. The reasoning behind this costume
is yet another example of how Oyamada copies (or apes) an idea and
then makes it his own.
</P>
<P>
   He said he derived the image from a photograph of Moe Tucker,
the drummer from the Velvet Underground. ``She was wearing a
striped shirt, and I liked the look,'' he said. ``Then I realized
everyone in the Velvet Underground had the same haircut in the
photo. Since the concept of Cornelius is that it is a band with
only one member, it made me think of using a clone idea. So I
dressed the whole band up likes clones of me.''
</P>
<P>
   On his current tour, Oyamada and his band will be wearing
clothing made by the Tokyo clothing company Bathing Ape, with which
he is associated. Its one-room outlet store, hidden in Tokyo's
Harajuku neighborhood, sells only three or four items, usually
T-shirts made with new designs every week, insuring that whenever
school is out the store is crammed with fans trying to get the
latest Bathing Ape wear.
</P>
<P>
   Oyamada, in fact, has become so ape-obsessed since adopting the
pseudonym Cornelius that to find out whether the law in ``Planet of
the Apes'' that ``Ape shall never kill ape'' was true, he got in
touch with a professor studying the field activities of apes.
</P>
<P>
   ``I was disappointed to find out that monkeys actually kill each
other,'' he said, burrowing his head in his Bathing Ape jacket and
sinking into silent reflection.
</P>
</TEXT>
