<HEADER>
A1346 &Cx1f; tad-z
u l &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-BOXING-FITNESS-COX     06-09 0801
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BOXING-FITNESS-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;    
 &HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Boxing helps women fight stress and calories
 &HT;    By Lillian Lee Kim
 &HT;    c. 1998 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   About two dozen people, mostly women, are warming up in the
boxing studio. They are all lithe, with sculpted, sinewy limbs.
They think they're in shape.
</P>
<P>
   The air conditioning is blowing full blast.
</P>
<P>
   In 15 minutes, it will feel like the Sahara.
</P>
<P>
   Boxing and its cousin, kick boxing, have moved from the ring
into the aerobics studio, picking up a sizable following in the
process. And eliminating sparring while keeping the element of
aggression has made fitness boxing and kick boxing, traditionally
male-dominated sports, vastly more appealing to women.
</P>
<P>
   ``We've seen a popularity explosion,'' said Bruce Frazier, who
teaches kick boxing at Australian Body Works in Atlanta. ``It's in
vogue. Michelle Pfeiffer does it. And, of course, having it on the
show (`Ally McBeal') hasn't hurt.''
</P>
<P>
   The new incarnation of this ancient sport is less bloody than
competitive boxing but more soul-satisfying than step aerobics.
It's based on two concepts.
</P>
<P>
   One: The training regimen used to turn competitive boxers into
superbly conditioned athletes also works for ordinary people who
want to get fit.
</P>
<P>
   Two: Punching something really hard is fun.
</P>
<P>
   ``There's something about the act of combat, whether it be real
or imagined, that lends a clarity to your thought,'' mused Frazier.
``For a brief time, you cannot think about the past or the future.
You can only think about the here and now.''
</P>
<P>
   So, boxing may be incredibly rigorous, but at least you get
something for your sweat.
</P>
<P>
   ``I've done many other types of exercises, and I find I get the
best workout with this,'' said Taronna Maines, 27, a doctoral
candidate in molecular biology who boxes at Jeanne's Body Tech in
Buckhead. ``Plus, it's such a stress reliever.''
</P>
<P>
   This combination of calorie-incinerating exercise and stress
therapy may explain why kick boxing has become the wunderworkout of
choice for A-list actresses. Kick boxing showed up in ``Romy and
Michele's High School Reunion'' and ``Kiss the Girls,'' and it's
one of the few things we know Jodie Foster does in her private
life. Several gyms in New York and Los Angeles are entirely devoted
to fitness boxing.
</P>
<P>
   The sport is fast becoming popular in Atlanta, too, where
several gyms offer classes. Rick Drew American Karate and
Kickboxing, which started kick-boxing classes in August, has 300
students.
</P>
<P>
   The sessions generally don't involve sparring. Instead, punching
and kicking moves are incorporated into a sort of aerobic routine,
exhausting in its demands for both speed and strength. Most classes
are at least an hour long.
</P>
<P>
   After just 15 minutes of air punches, the students' faces begin
to show fatigue. They perk up when they start hitting the heavy
bag.
</P>
<P>
   In the middle of the room, Ali Gibson has the classic boxer's
stance, gloves in front of her face, feet planted wide apart. She
glares at the bag as if it had insulted her and lands a hard jab,
then a hook.
</P>
<P>
   The beginners' inexperience shows here. Some just fling their
fists at the bag. Instructor Scott Grove moves around the room,
demonstrating the difference between a hook and a jab.
</P>
<P>
   ``There's a really fast learning curve,'' said Scott Daniels,
28, who has been boxing for 1 1/2 years. ``You don't have to feel
like an idiot for very long.''
</P>
<P>
   He started boxing for fitness because he didn't like biking or
running.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's a phenomenal cardiovascular workout, plus it's fun,''
said Daniels, who works as a financial planner. ``I've also enjoyed
it from the standpoint of just learning how to box.''
</P>
<P>
   It seems many boxing and kick boxing fans are defectors from
other types of aerobic workouts.
</P>
<P>
   ``They got tired of doing the same old step classes,'' said Jong
Han Kim of Kim Brothers World Tae Kwon Do Academy in Roswell,Ga.,
where classes are full. ``They like the idea of putting on
handwraps and boxing gloves. They really like to beat on
something.''
</P>
<P>
   Halfway through the class, Grove tells the students to pair up.
One holds the heavy bag steady while the other punches it 10 times,
rapid-fire. Then they switch and repeat.
</P>
<P>
   The punches get slower and slower. The batteries are running
down.
</P>
<P>
   ``There is something primitively satisfying about kicking and
punching something,'' Frazier said.
</P>
<P>
   Yes, but do it over and over again and your arms start to hate
you.
</P>
<P>
   At the end of class, the students look like they've been jogging
in a sauna. Sweat streams from places they didn't even know could
sweat.
</P>
<P>
   But they walk a little taller than they did when they arrived.
Some even strut a bit.
</P>
<P>
   They'll be back.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
