<HEADER>
A1347 &Cx1f; tad-z
u d &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-FOOD-DONE-COX     06-09 0931
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FOOD-DONE-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;    
 &HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    The hardest part of knowing how to cook may be knowing when to
stop
 &HT;    (EMBARGOED UNTIL JUNE 11: DFO NOT USE BEFORE THEN)
 &HT;    By Reagan Walker
 &HT;    c. 1998 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   Anne Willan examined the roast chickens that a student at her La
Varenne Cooking School in France was about to put back into the
oven and declared, ``Those look done to me!''
</P>
<P>
   The student, who was simply checking on the progress of the
birds, was puzzled. ``How do you know?'' she asked.
</P>
<P>
   Willan's first reaction was simply to say it was instinct. ``But
then I realized I do know. It looked crispy brown. It sizzled. You
could wiggle the leg, and it smelled heavenly.''
</P>
<P>
   Most of us have had those puzzling moments in the kitchen. The
recipe said to cook the roast for an hour. So why is it still so
rare? Your mother always told you to boil corn about 10 minutes,
but when you do, the kernels are shriveled and dry.
</P>
<P>
   Professional chefs such as Willan have learned that the answers
to such questions don't come from some divine inspiration, but
rather by using all five senses to carefully observe the cooking
process.
</P>
<P>
   Christophe Bruehwiler of Bruehwiler's Bakery in Sandy Springs
says he knows when a loaf of bread is done by touching it. ``It's
like the people you see thumping the watermelon at the farmers
market. You turn the loaf of bread upside down and hit the bottom
with your knuckles,'' he explained. ``If you hear a hollow sound,
then you know it's done.''
</P>
<P>
   For cookies, Bruehwiler goes mainly by sight. As a batch of
cookies nears the end of the baking process, he begins to watch.
``The recipe may say seven minutes. That doesn't mean the cookie
will be done in your oven in seven minutes,'' he said. ``A cookie
is so small and fragile, and a minute can really change the color
and the texture. So you have to look.''
</P>
<P>
   Famed Southern chef Edna Lewis says she can ``hear'' when a cake
is done. How? By pulling it from the oven and holding it to her
ear. If she hears ``quiet bubbling,'' she knows it's not quite
ready. When the bubbling subsides, she knows it's done.
</P>
<P>
   Detecting the moment of optimum doneness is arguably the most
important skill a cook can master, especially in dishes unadorned
with sauces or fancy dressings. ``When you cook things very pure,
then it shows all the mistakes,'' said chef Guenter Seeger of
Seeger's restaurant in Atlanta.
</P>
<P>
   In ``Cook It Right: Achieve Perfection With Every Dish You
Cook'' (Reader's Digest Books, $29.95), Willan tells home chefs how
to recognize exactly when more than 150 types of ingredients and
foods are cooked to perfection, from lobster to french fries.
</P>
<P>
   ``While I think people these days know a lot more about food,
they know a lot less about cooking,'' said Willan. ``They simply
don't recognize when something is well-cooked.''
</P>
<P>
   She drew on her own experience as the founder of La Varenne, the
famed cooking school, and as a cookbook author. She also sought the
secrets of expert chefs around the world. To illustrate, hundreds
of photographs and explanations of overcooked and undercooked
dishes are shown, next to their perfectly cooked counterparts.
</P>
<P>
   Even for experienced cooks, she found that there is sometimes
but one way to achieve the precise product they're seeking:
old-fashioned trial and error.
</P>
<P>
   ``We couldn't get a cake to fall, and we couldn't get a dark
line around the yolk of a boiled egg to show an overdone egg,''
laughed Willan. ``We ended up boiling 60 eggs for that one
picture.''
</P>
<P>
   Steak
</P>
<P>
   Underdone: The meat offers no resistance when pressed, and beads
of meat juice do not yet rise to the surface. Rare: Surface is
well-browned; meat is spongy when pressed in the center; beads of
juice are deep pink. Medium: Surface is crusty brown and meat
resists when the center is pressed; firm at the sides; beads of
juice on surface are deep pink. Well-done: Surface is crusty brown
and dry; meat is firm when pressed; beads of juice on surface are
clear.
</P>
<P>
   A perfect custard sauce will be creamy and smooth, and a clear
trail is left when a finger is drawn across the spoon. Flavor is
delicate, perfumed with vanilla.
</P>
<P>
   Green beans cooked just right will be tender enough to bend but
still slightly crisp. They're easy to cut with a knife. The color
is vivid and the taste well-defined and fresh.
</P>
<P>
   When a knife or fork is inserted at the thickest part of the
fish, the flesh nearest the bone flakes away easily and is no
longer translucent. The eye is opaque. If baked, barbecued, broiled
or pan-fried, the skin should be browned and crisp.
</P>
<P>
   A perfect muffin will be deep golden and starting to shrink from
the pan; the center rises to a shallow, cracked peak, and a skewer
inserted into the center comes out clean (but may be moist with
fruit). The inside texture is spongy and the muffin is fragrant.
Holey muffins (upper left) will be tunneled and often have a high,
broken peak as a result of overmixing or too much rising agent.
Underbaked muffins (upper middle) will be wet in the center, with a
pale crust; the batter has not yet peaked or begun to shrink from
the pan. Heavy muffins (upper right) have a batter that scarcely
rises, and the top of the muffin is flat; the crust is pale.
Overmixing is most likely the culprit.
</P>
<P>
   Pasta is ready when tender but still firm to the bite; pieces
show no tendency to stick together, and flavor is nutty. String
pasta, such as spaghetti and linguine, can be cut with your
thumbnail.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
