<HEADLINE>
&HT;    
 &HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    COLUMN:Elmore Thrash was good man around House
 &HT;    BY Celestine Sibley
 &HT;    c. 1998 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA--My friend Elmore Thrash died. He was as much a part of
the Georgia Capitol as the lady on the dome, as the gold dome
itself.
</P>
<P>
   He had been there 71 of his 83 years, serving as a little boy
page to the late Sen. Richard Russell, when he was speaker of the
Georgia House in 1927, and as the official House messenger for 40
years.
</P>
<P>
   I loved Elmore _ and so did the hundreds of Georgians who knew
him.
</P>
<P>
   He died Monday at an Atlanta nursing home; a service in Decatur
was held Tuesday, and a graveside service is at 11 a.m. today in
Gay.
</P>
<P>
   Although Elmore lived most of his life in Valdosta, where he was
in the real estate and house-building business and where there is a
state highway named for him, his parents are buried in Gay, and he
wanted to be buried beside them.
</P>
<P>
   As Marcus Collins, a longtime member of the House and former
revenue commissioner, said of Elmore, ``He was a giver, not a
taker.''
</P>
<P>
   It was true. I couldn't have spent 20 years covering the Georgia
House without the help of Elmore, who sat by the speaker for hours,
keeping tabs on developments. He spent more hours scurrying about
the chamber, talking to people and, even more important, listening
to people.
</P>
<P>
   When the phone in the press section rang, it was often Elmore
saying, ``Sugar, we adjourning in 20 minutes. That committee you
are interested in is meeting NOW. Better get there.''
</P>
<P>
   If I was ill, Elmore heard about it and called me to check. In
the winter when a new session of the General Assembly was shaping
up, Elmore arrived early in Atlanta and was present at the
preliminary indoctrination sessions. He often called to tell me he
was back in town, visiting his children and grandchildren and
getting ready for the upcoming session.
</P>
<P>
   Once Elmore and his then-wife Louise (they were later divorced)
came to Sweet Apple for supper, and Elmore took a marked interest
in all our projects. A make-do lavatory in the guest bathroom
troubled him a little. We didn't want a new one, and old ones were
hard to find. Not for Elmore. He called me from Valdosta one day. A
neighbor of his was tearing down an old house and there was a
marvelous old marble lavatory about to be thrown away.
</P>
<P>
   ``You want it, Sugar?'' Elmore asked. ``I'll bring it when the
session starts.''
</P>
<P>
   The bellboy at his hotel was surprised at the task of hauling a
bathroom fixture from a gentleman's room to a lady waiting beside a
pickup truck on the curb. Thereafter Elmore would ask, ``How are
things in your bathroom?''
</P>
<P>
   Elmore was literally reared in the Georgia House. His father and
his grandfathers were members, and so, of course, was their friend
Dick Russell. Elmore graduated from the University of Georgia and
served in the Army as a captain in World War II. He was elected
messenger in the House in 1955, serving the speaker and the members
gladly and taking on the problems of us in the press section.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
