<HEADER>
A1352 &Cx1f; tad-z
u d &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-FOOD-RECIPES-COX     06-09 2376
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FOOD-RECIPES-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Willan's cookbook has everything that a cookbook should
 &HT;    (EMBARGOED UNTIL JUNE 11: DO NOT USE BEFORE THEN)
 &HT;    By Reagan Walker
 &HT;    c. 1998 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   It's rare to find a cookbook that not only gives you recipes but
also provides ample explanation of the techniques needed to prepare
them. It's even rarer to find one that tells you what to do if
something goes wrong.
</P>
<P>
   We found Anne Willan's ``Cook It Right: Achieve Perfection With
Every Dish You Cook'' (Reader's Digest Books, $29.95) delivers
beautifully on all three points.
</P>
<P>
   The photos are the key to explaining technique. Award-winning
photographer Peter Williams worked with Willan and a crew of 10 for
eight to 10 hours a day over three weeks to shoot photos that
capture the precise moment the lobster is done or the texture of
stiffened scrambled eggs. They averaged a photo every 32 minutes _
no small feat in food photography.
</P>
<P>
   With many recipes, Willan includes ideas for quick fixes, or
ways to salvage a dish when something may have gone wrong. In some
cases, there's nothing you can do, and Willan will tell you so.
Some of her saves:
</P>
<P>
   -- Too much salt in a dish can be counteracted by adding a bland
ingredient, like potato, tomato or mushrooms or a dairy product
such as cream, milk or fresh cheese.
</P>
<P>
   -- For a dry, flavorless roasted chicken, douse with an
Asian-style marinade of soy sauce, sesame oil, garlic, ginger and
lime juice. Or cut the chicken into pieces, pull meat into shreds
and serve in a sauce or moistened with an herb vinaigrette.
</P>
<P>
   -- Try topping braised or glazed vegetables that are soft and
tasteless with something crispy, like fried ginger or leek.
</P>
<P>
   But the explanations and tips all work because the recipes are
so good. Just try some of the recipes below, which will allow you
to hone your skills on cooking pasta, steaming mussels, blanching
vegetables and making a caramel sauce. All delicious homework.
</P>
<P>
   MAIN DISH
</P>
<P>
   Spaghetti With Red Mussel Sauce
</P>
<P>
   Makes 4 servings Preparation time: 45 minutes Cooking time: 30
minutes
</P>
<P>
   For this simple, classic dish, seek out the freshest mussels and
ripest tomatoes.
</P>
<P>
   4pounds small mussels
</P>
<P>
   1/4cup plus 2 tablespoons olive oil
</P>
<P>
   2onions, finely chopped
</P>
<P>
   6garlic cloves, finely chopped
</P>
<P>
   3pounds tomatoes, peeled, seeded and chopped
</P>
<P>
   1bay leaf
</P>
<P>
   1pound spaghetti
</P>
<P>
   Salt and pepper
</P>
<P>
   2tablespoons chopped parsley
</P>
<P>
   Bring a large pan of salted water to a boil for the spaghetti.
Scrub mussels under cold running water, pulling off beards with a
small knife. Discard any mussels that do not close when tapped on
the counter.
</P>
<P>
   Steam the mussels open: Put them in a large pan, barely covered
with water, cover tightly and cook over medium heat until done (the
shells will have popped open), stirring once, 4-5 minutes. Take the
mussels from the pan, reserving about two cups of the liquid. Cover
the mussels to keep them warm, discarding any that are still
closed.
</P>
<P>
   Make the sauce: Heat 1/4 cup olive oil in a saute pan, add the
onions and saute until lightly browned, 4-5 minutes. Add the garlic
and continue cooking until fragrant, 1-2 minutes. Add the reserved
mussel juice to the pan, taking care to leave any sandy deposit
behind. Then add the tomatoes and bay leaf and simmer until sauce
is concentrated and just falls easily from a spoon, 5-8 minutes.
</P>
<P>
   Add the spaghetti to the boiling water and simmer, stirring
occasionally, until al dente, tender but still firm to the bite,
5-7 minutes. Drain, return spaghetti to the pan and toss with 2
tablespoons olive oil. Transfer to a large serving bowl and keep
warm. Discard the bay leaf from the sauce and add the sauce to the
mussels. Stir to mix, and reheat 1-2 minutes. Taste and adjust
seasoning; salt may not be necessary as the mussels are already
salty. Spoon mussels and sauce over the spaghetti, sprinkle with
parsley and serve.
</P>
<P>
   Per serving: 717 calories, 33 grams protein, 27 grams fat
(percent calories from fat, 34), 87 grams carbohydrates, 122
milligrams cholesterol, 468 milligrams sodium.
</P>
<P>
   MAIN DISH
</P>
<P>
   Veal Chops With Lemon and Roasted Red Pepper Relish
</P>
<P>
   Makes 4 servings
</P>
<P>
   Preparation time: 40 minutes Marinating time: 2 hours Cooking
time: 25 minutes
</P>
<P>
   This is an ideal recipe for perfecting your chop cooking and
also getting some experience working with roasted peppers, which
can be time-consuming but are well worth the effort.
</P>
<P>
   1lemon
</P>
<P>
   1/3cup plus 4 tablespoons olive oil, divided
</P>
<P>
   Salt and pepper
</P>
<P>
   4veal chops, cut 3/4 inch thick (about 1/2 pound each)
</P>
<P>
   3red bell peppers
</P>
<P>
   2onions, thinly sliced
</P>
<P>
   2garlic cloves, finely chopped
</P>
<P>
   1/3cup chopped mixed herbs (basil, oregano, marjoram, parsley,
thyme)
</P>
<P>
   Granulated sugar to taste
</P>
<P>
   4tablespoons water
</P>
<P>
   2tablespoons chopped parsley
</P>
<P>
   Grate the zest from the lemon and squeeze the juice. Combine 1/3
cup of the olive oil, lemon juice, salt and pepper in a nonmetallic
bowl. Lay the chops in a deep tray and pour olive oil mixture on
top. Cover and leave to marinate in the refrigerator for 2 hours,
turning occasionally.
</P>
<P>
   Meanwhile, make the red pepper relish: Preheat the broiler.
Roast the peppers under the broiler, turning occasionally, for 7-10
minutes or until the skin chars and bursts. Put them in a plastic
bag or cover them with wet paper towels to loosen the skin. When
cool, peel the peppers, discard the cores and seeds and cut the
flesh into 3/8-inch strips. Heat 2 tablespoons of olive oil in a
frying pan. Stir in the onion and garlic and saute until soft but
not browned, 3-4 minutes. Add the pepper strips, herbs, pinch of
sugar, salt and pepper. Saute until heated through and the flavors
are blended, 2-3 minutes. Taste and adjust the seasoning. Set aside
and keep warm.
</P>
<P>
   Drain the chops, reserving the marinade. Heat the remaining 2
tablespoons olive oil in a large frying pan, add the chops and fry
over fairly high heat until browned, then turn and brown the other
sides. Allow 4 minutes per side for lightly cooked meat, 5 minutes
per side for well-done meat. Transfer the chops to a platter and
keep warm.
</P>
<P>
   To make a jus: skim the fat from the pan, then add the water and
remaining marinade. Stir for 1-2 minutes over low heat to dissolve
the pan juices. Take the pan from the heat and stir in the lemon
zest and chopped parsley. Taste the sauce and adjust the seasoning,
if necessary. Spoon over the chops and serve with the red pepper
relish.
</P>
<P>
   Per serving: 367 calories, 41 grams protein, 19 grams fat
(percent calories from fat, 46), 9 grams carbohydrates, 146
milligrams cholesterol, 103 milligrams sodium.
</P>
<P>
   MAIN DISH
</P>
<P>
   Broiled Scallops With Prosciutto Cream Sauce
</P>
<P>
   Makes 4 servings Preparation time: 25 minutes Cooking time: 20
minutes
</P>
<P>
   When I served this dish to guests, they couldn't stop eating.
But then again, how can you go wrong with wine, butter, cream and
prosciutto? Good practice for cream sauces and seafood preparation.
</P>
<P>
   2 1/2ounces thinly sliced prosciutto
</P>
<P>
   2tablespoons butter
</P>
<P>
   1tablespoon olive oil
</P>
<P>
   1garlic clove, finely chopped
</P>
<P>
   1shallot, finely chopped
</P>
<P>
   1small carrot, very finely diced
</P>
<P>
   3tablespoons white wine
</P>
<P>
   1/3pound button mushrooms, diced
</P>
<P>
   1/4cup cream or creme fraiche
</P>
<P>
   2tablespoons butter, chilled and cut into pieces
</P>
<P>
   Salt and pepper
</P>
<P>
   1 1/2pounds scallops
</P>
<P>
   Vegetable oil for the grill or broiler rack
</P>
<P>
   2tablespoons butter
</P>
<P>
   2tablespoons chopped parsley
</P>
<P>
   Make the prosciutto cream sauce: Cut the prosciutto in thin
strips about 3/4 inch long. Heat the butter and olive oil in a
saucepan, add the garlic and shallot and saute until fragrant, 1-2
minutes. Add the carrot and saute until carrot begins to soften,
1-2 minutes. Pour in the white wine and boil, stirring, until
reduced by half. Stir in the mushrooms and cook until slightly
softened, 1-2 minutes. Stir in the cream or creme fraiche with the
prosciutto strips and boil until slightly thickened, 1-2 minutes.
</P>
<P>
   Turn the heat to low and gradually whisk in the butter pieces to
make a smooth, creamy sauce. Work on and off the heat, so that the
butter softens and thickens the sauce without melting to oil.
Season to taste with salt and pepper. Keep the sauce warm on a rack
over a pan of hot but not boiling water.
</P>
<P>
   Preheat the broiler. Discard the small crescent-shaped muscles
at the sides of the scallops. Rinse the scallops and pat dry with
paper towels. Place them on an oiled broiler rack, dot with butter
and season with salt and pepper. Set the rack about 3 inches from
the heat and broil the scallops until done, 2-3 minutes on each
side.
</P>
<P>
   Meanwhile, stir all but 1 teaspoon of the parsley into the
sauce. Spoon the sauce on 4 warmed plates, arrange the broiled
scallops on top and sprinkle with reserved parsley. Serve at once.
</P>
<P>
   Per serving: 442 calories, 36 grams protein, 29 grams fat
(percent calories from fat, 59), 9 grams carbohydrates, 140
milligrams cholesterol, 475 milligrams sodium.
</P>
<P>
   DESSERT
</P>
<P>
   Salty Caramel Sauce With Peaches and Ice Cream
</P>
<P>
   Makes 4 servings Preparation time: 10 minutes Cooking time: 15
minutes
</P>
<P>
   OK. It took me three tries to get the caramel sauce just right.
Once the sugar starts to brown, things happen fast. The first time
I burned it. The second time I was too cautious and came up with a
tasty but thin sauce. The third time? I used a candy thermometer
and it helped immensely. Was it worth it? You bet. This should
become a standard for Georgia peaches.
</P>
<P>
   6whole peaches
</P>
<P>
   3tablespoons dark brown sugar
</P>
<P>
   3tablespoons butter
</P>
<P>
   1cup granulated sugar
</P>
<P>
   1/2cup water
</P>
<P>
   1/4cup salted butter
</P>
<P>
   1cup heavy cream
</P>
<P>
   Vanilla ice cream (for serving)
</P>
<P>
   Preheat the broiler. Halve the peaches, discarding pits, and set
them, cut side up, in a buttered baking dish. Sprinkle with brown
sugar and dot with butter. Broil about 3 inches from the heat until
the peaches are tender and starting to brown, 7-10 minutes.
Meanwhile make a dark caramel syrup: In a heavy saucepan, heat the
sugar and water, stirring only once or twice, until the sugar is
dissolved. Boil rapidly, without stirring, until the syrup begins
to brown around the edge of the pan. Continue cooking over medium
heat until done, 1-2 minutes, swirling the pan occasionally so the
syrup colors evenly. Once it starts to brown, it colors quickly.
</P>
<P>
   When the caramel is dark, remove the pan from the heat and let
the bubbles subside. Add the butter, stir until smooth, then pour
in the cream. Note: Stand well back, as the caramel will sputter
and foam when butter and cream are added.
</P>
<P>
   To serve: Transfer hot peaches to individual plates and spoon
over any juice. Add a scoop of vanilla ice cream. If necessary,
reheat the sauce, stirring until the caramel is completely
dissolved and the sauce is hot. Spoon it over the peaches and serve
at once.
</P>
<P>
   Per serving (with 1/2 cup ice cream): 865 calories, 6 grams
protein, 54 grams fat (percent calories from fat, 56), 96 grams
carbohydrates, 214 milligrams cholesterol, 309 milligrams sodium.
</P>
<P>
   BREAD
</P>
<P>
   Summer Strawberry Mint Muffins
</P>
<P>
   Makes 16 muffins Preparation time: 15 minutes Cooking time:
20-25 minutes
</P>
<P>
   The combination is a bit odd at first, but the taste sensation
grows on you _ and fast. These muffins are best served warm.
</P>
<P>
   2cups all-purpose flour
</P>
<P>
   3/4cup granulated sugar
</P>
<P>
   3/4teaspoon baking powder
</P>
<P>
   1/2teaspoon salt
</P>
<P>
   2large eggs
</P>
<P>
   3/4cup milk
</P>
<P>
   2/3cup vegetable oil
</P>
<P>
   1cup hulled and chopped strawberries
</P>
<P>
   3tablespoons chopped fresh mint
</P>
<P>
   Preheat oven to 400 degrees. Butter medium-sized muffin pan and
sprinkle with flour, discarding excess. Sift flour, sugar, baking
powder and salt into a large bowl and make a well in center. In a
small bowl, whisk together eggs, milk and oil. Add egg mixture to
well and stir with a whisk until just mixed. Note: Do not beat
batter, or muffins will be heavy. Stir in strawberries and mint.
Spoon mixture into muffin cups, filling two-thirds full. Bake on
lower rack of oven until done, 20-25 minutes. Let cool slightly,
then turn out on a rack. Serve warm.
</P>
<P>
   Per serving: 182 calories, 3 grams protein, 9 grams fat (percent
calories from fat, 47), 22 grams carbohydrates, 28 milligrams
cholesterol, 120 milligrams sodium.
</P>
<P>
   SIDE DISH
</P>
<P>
   Indonesian Salad
</P>
<P>
   With Spicy Peanut Sauce
</P>
<P>
   Makes 4 servings Preparation time: 45 minutes Cooking time: 6-8
minutes
</P>
<P>
   Have trouble finding new ways to get the family to eat veggies?
Try this salad. The spicy peanut sauce is a lively accompaniment to
the fresh beans and sprouts.
</P>
<P>
   1cup crunchy peanut butter
</P>
<P>
   1/2onion, chopped
</P>
<P>
   1garlic clove
</P>
<P>
   1/4teaspoon red pepper flakes, or to taste
</P>
<P>
   1teaspoon ground ginger
</P>
<P>
   1/2teaspoon brown sugar
</P>
<P>
   Juice of 1/2 lime, plus more if needed
</P>
<P>
   3/4cup hot water, plus more if needed
</P>
<P>
   Soy sauce
</P>
<P>
   Black pepper
</P>
<P>
   1/2pound snow peas, trimmed
</P>
<P>
   1/4pound bean sprouts, cleaned
</P>
<P>
   1/2pound carrots, peeled and cut into julienne strips
</P>
<P>
   6ounces green beans, trimmed
</P>
<P>
   Make the spicy peanut sauce: In a blender or food processor,
combine the peanut butter, onion, garlic, pepper flakes, ginger,
sugar and lime juice. Puree until very smooth, adding hot water as
necessary so the mixture churns well. Work in more hot water or
lime juice, adding enough to make a sauce that is thick enough to
coat the back of a spoon. Taste and adjust the seasoning with more
lime juice, soy sauce and pepper. Set aside.
</P>
<P>
   Bring a large pan of salted water to a boil. Add the snow peas
to the water and leave 30 seconds. Drain, refresh with cold water
and drain again. Repeat the process for the bean sprouts and
carrots. Add the green beans to the boiling salted water and cook
until perfectly blanched, 4-6 minutes. Drain, refresh with cold
water and drain again. Arrange the vegetables in individual mounds
on a large serving platter. Serve the sauce separately in a bowl.
The salad may be served at room temperature or chilled.
</P>
<P>
   Per serving: 468 calories, 20 grams protein, 33 grams fat
(percent calories from fat, 64), 31 grams carbohydrates, No
cholesterol, 430 milligrams sodium.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
