<HEADER>
A1354 &Cx1f; tad-z
u t &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-GETAWAY-MEMPHIS-COX     06-09 0994
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-GETAWAY-MEMPHIS-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;    
 &HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Three to try: Memphis abounds in fine dining
 &HT;    By John Kessler
 &HT;    c. 1998 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   Memphis
</P>
<P>
   You could eat every meal here in a famous barbecue joint _
Willingham's, Corky's, the Rendezvous _ and convince yourself that
the four food groups consist entirely of pork. Chopped pork, sliced
pork, pulled pork and pork ribs are good enough to keep any errant
greens, grains and vegetables off your plate.
</P>
<P>
   But do try to tear yourself away from pit heaven (if not for
your own sake, at least for your cardiologist's) and sample at
least one of this city's finer dining establishments. With its
metro population topping 1 million, Memphis offers a wide range of
places to break bread _ and not just the white, squishy kind for
mopping up sweet tomato sauce.
</P>
<P>
   Here are three restaurants that could put Memphis on any
culinary map, even a kosher one:
</P>
<P>
   -- Aubergine: This East Memphis bistro, a quiet and
sophisticated haven for ladies who lunch and lovers who dine, got
quite a shake-up with the arrival of chef Jean-Christophe Blanc
earlier this year. Blanc has worked his way through France's finest
kitchens, most recently as sous-chef at Les Pres d'Eugenie, Michel
Guerard's Michelin three-star restaurant in the southwest. Owner
Gene Bjorklund, himself the chef for the past five years, first
invited Blanc to Aubergine for a brief stint as guest chef, but
things worked out so well for both that they've decided to make it
permanent beginning in October.
</P>
<P>
   There is an extra level of finesse in Blanc's food that shows
his training. A lightly dressed pouf of salad greens reveals a few
tiny snippets of herbs and minced bits of shallot clinging to the
leaves, and the flavors register ever so slightly on your palate. A
satiny asparagus and potato soup is as refreshing as cream soup can
be. And a dish of grilled Arkansas quail, marinated with mustard
and herbs and then set over a mushroom fricassee and natural jus,
treats top-drawer ingredients with respect.
</P>
<P>
   Scallops of veal, though, are tough and boring; perhaps Blanc
doesn't yet have the hang of cooking American meat. But they come
with a textbook-perfect brunoise (small dice) of vegetables and an
intriguing side of tempura-battered polenta wedges studded with
raisins and hazelnuts. Considering Blanc's skill, we're willing to
put up with his learning curve.
</P>
<P>
   Open for dinner Tuesday through Saturday and for lunch Tuesday
through Friday. 5007 Black Road, Suite 150. 901-767-7840.
</P>
<P>
   -- Automatic Slim's Tonga Cafe: Most Memphians would agree that
this Caribbean-themed spot serves the hippest chow downtown. The
split-level room across the street from the Peabody Hotel has a
deep downstairs room with a bar running the length of it, and a
smaller upstairs dining loft. The scene is women in short skirts,
sweet cocktails served in martini glasses, and generous portions of
spice-happy food served on Fiestaware. Noise zips through the
electric space, reverberating from both the naked tables and
pressed-tin ceiling, and on weekends an electric violin player adds
his strains to the din.
</P>
<P>
   The Yuparibbean menu brings a tasty ``Island tomato salad'' with
feta and roasted tomato vinaigrette and the house-special
coconut-crusted shrimp with mango relish. The latter were a little
burnt and a little too sweet on the night I tried them. I liked the
huachinango, a whole grilled snapper served with chopped tomatoes,
cucumbers and jalapenos. And I loved the Caribbean voodoo stew, an
enormous portion of shrimp, mussels, sea bass and whatnot in a
spicy, creamy tomato base set around a mound of rice. On top is a
cluster of excellent snow crab legs folded into a showy fan, a kind
of crustacean origami. You'll light up when you see it coming to
your table.
</P>
<P>
   Open Monday through Saturday for dinner and Monday through
Friday for lunch. 83 South Second St. 901-525-7948.
</P>
<P>
   -- Raji: If any non-barbecue restaurant in Memphis has a listing
in the gastronomic Who's Who, it's Raji. Owner Raji Jallepalli has
earned an international reputation for fusing the ingredients and
techniques of French cuisine with the spices of her native India.
Her following includes both Memphis blue bloods who crowd her
converted East Memphis house and a cadre of celebrity chefs and
food writers who join her at culinary seminars and demonstration
dinners throughout the country.
</P>
<P>
   Foodies love the style of dining at Raji. Each night she offers
a set four-course meal and recommends wines from her intelligent
cellar to match each course.
</P>
<P>
   I've eaten at Raji only once, but I was frankly disappointed by
the menu I sampled. A bland cucumber soup with lovely shrimp is
refreshing for a bite or two, but turns tiresome. Grouper (cooked
to a chewy medium rare) with jalapeno, garlic and ginger has little
of the promised spice but a whole lot of mashed potatoes that you
can tell are gluey from their sheen alone. Pork tenderloin with a
black mustard seed crust sports only a few charred bits of seed
that are discernible to the trained eye, but I don't imagine that
any tongue could actually taste them. The real flavor comes from
the familiar garnish of diced, sauteed apples and a slice of bacon
around the meat; it's not bad, but not memorable. The pot de creme
for dessert is sublime.
</P>
<P>
   Perhaps the food on the night I visited suffered because Raji
had just come back from a cooking trip and was late getting into
town. I was also among the last customers that evening, after
having cajoled my way into a 10 p.m. reservation. I understand from
reliable sources that Raji can be a brilliant cook. She is
certainly a great hostess, and her personality brings the dining
room to life. I still can't wait to see what she's capable of in
the kitchen.
</P>
<P>
   Open Tuesday through Saturday for dinner. 712 West Brookhaven
Circle. 901-685-8723.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
