</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-GETAWAY-PERU-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;    
 &HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Ancient Peruvian art await visitors to Tennessee's Bluff City on
the Mississippi
 &HT;    By John Kessler
 &HT;    c. 1998 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   Memphis
</P>
<P>
   When the Incas rose to power in the 12th century, they didn't
meet a neighbor in any direction _ along the coastal desert, in the
high plains or throughout the Andes _ that they couldn't conquer.
In little more than 10 years, a small, centralized nation that
numbered its inhabitants in the tens of thousands quickly
transformed into an empire of 10 million and built a civilization
renowned for its architecture, agriculture and metallurgy.
</P>
<P>
   Yet before the Incan empire, Peru was home to scores of distinct
cultures, each with its own accomplishments in the arts and
sciences. The Moche sculpted expressive facial portraits onto the
sides of pots. The Paracas performed successful brain surgery,
using blades to excise pieces of diseased brain and skull. The
Nazca carved enormous designs in the desert sand, requiring
hundreds of thousands of man-hours and knowledge of complex
mathematics.
</P>
<P>
   These are among the 35 cultures explored in ``Ancestors of the
Incas: The Lost Civilizations of Peru,'' on exhibit through Sept.
16 at the Pyramid in Memphis. The 300-some objects on display span
3,000 years and range from ceramics, geometric textiles and
ceremonial gold jewelry to several corpses mummified in a fetal
position, ready for their birth into the next world.
</P>
<P>
   ``Ancestors of the Incas'' is the latest venture from Wonders:
The Memphis International Cultural Series, the municipal agency
that curates splashy exhibits with cross-cultural themes.
</P>
<P>
   ``Ancestors'' probably won't make as big a splash as the
previous show, ``Titanic: The Exhibition,'' which last year drew on
our fascination with that subject to attract more than 600,000
visitors.
</P>
<P>
   Compared to ``Titanic'' and other blockbuster Wonders shows such
as ``Napoleon'' and ``Catherine the Great,'' the current exhibit
may seem a bit more cerebral and less showy. But it has its own
thrills. As you enter the exhibition space, the escalator swoops
down through a panoramic photomural of Machu Picchu, the Inca
palace set high in the Andean peaks _ a descent through the steep
terrain of Peru and through its many layers of ancient history.
</P>
<P>
   You begin in an adobe-finished gallery modeled after the
courtyard of Chan Chan, the capital of the Chimu empire. Objects
from different cultures and periods are grouped for their thematic
similarities. In one display, ceramic pots depict eerie
transformations, such as animal faces struggling forth from the
eyes of a potato. An audio guide provides background information on
specific objects, and narrator Martin Sheen gives it his gravest,
get-yourself-into-rehab reading. (A special tape is available for
children.)
</P>
<P>
   One pot depicts the wizened, wrinkled face of an old woman, in
realistic detail. Another is pure abstraction, bordered with a
geometric sea design borrowed from textiles. Unlike other world
cultures, the ancient Peruvians developed textiles before ceramics.
</P>
<P>
   The objects sure to draw the most attention are the three
mummies, creepily well preserved by their many layers of fabric
shroud and the arid climate of their burial sites. The centerpiece
of the exhibit, in a dim, backlit setting, is a 1,500-year-old
sorceress with eight feet of hair coiled down her side and eyes
that seem to follow your movements like a ghastly Mona Lisa.
</P>
<P>
   The exhibition leads through a gallery that is an
architecturally detailed rendering of Coricancha, a ruin in the
Incan capital of Cuzco built of precisely cut and fit stones.
Inside are 45 gold and silver artifacts unearthed from
archaeological sites of pre-Incan cultures. The famous Incan gold,
you may recall, was melted down into ingots by the Spaniards in the
16th century.
</P>
<P>
   The exhibition ends with a gallery depicting large renderings of
the Nazca lines on the carpeted floors and walls, as well as aerial
video footage of these mysterious desert doodles. I found this the
weakest part of the show, as it never quite conveyed the immense
scope and engineering effort involved. But, unlike past Wonders
exhibits, ``Ancestors of the Incas'' is best appreciated in the
small details rather than the grand scope.
</P>
<P>
   -- ``Ancestors of the Incas: The Lost Civilizations of Peru'': 9
a.m.-10 p.m. daily through Sept. 16. The Pyramid, downtown Memphis.
$12 adults, $11 seniors (age 60 and older), $6 youth (ages 5-16).
Tickets are sold for a specific date and entry time. Order by
telephone at 1-800-263-6744.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
