</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-GETAWAY-TIPS-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;    
 &HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    If you go to Memphis
 &HT;    By Paula Crouch Thrasher
 &HT;    c. 1998 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   -- Staying over: Memphis' oldest and grandest hotel is the
Peabody (home of the famous parading ducks), 149 Union Ave. ($160
single; $210 double); 1-800-732-2639. Across from the Peabody is
the small, exclusive Talbot Heirs Guest House, 99 S. Second St.,
with nine suites ($150-$250). 901-527-9772. Moderately priced
downtown hotels (about $80) include Brownstone Hotel, 300 Second
St., 901-525-2511; Comfort Inn Downtown, 100 N. Front St.,
901-526-0583; and Sleep Inn at Court Square, 40 N. Front St.,
901-522-9700.
</P>
<P>
   -- Area attractions: Historic Beale Street, where the blues were
born, is the spot for Memphis nightlife and a fascinating walking
tour into the city's past. The Memphis Zoo and Aquarium at 2000
Galloway Ave. is open daily (901-276-9453). The Memphis Botanic
Gardens at 750 Cherry Road covers 96 acres in Aubudon Park
(901-685-1566). The Memphis Pink Palace Museum, Sharpe Planetarium,
and IMAX Theater are in the complex at 3050 Central Ave.
(901-320-6320). And no trip to Memphis would be complete without a
tour of the city's most-visited tourist attraction, Elvis Presley's
Graceland, 10 miles from downtown (1-800-238-2000).
</P>
<P>
   -- Information: The Memphis Visitors Information Center, 340
Beale St., 1-800-873-6282.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
