<HEADER>
A1357 &Cx1f; tad-z
u e &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-TV-SURFER10-COX     06-09 0506
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-TV-SURFER10-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    As ``Magic Hour'' premires, ``Vibe'' receives walking papers
 &HT;    By Lyle v. Harris
 &HT;    c. 1998 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   Magic in, Sinbad out.
</P>
<P>
   Just prior to ex-Los Angeles Laker Earvin Johnson's debut in
``The Magic Hour,'' another late-night talker ``Vibe'' hosted by
the comic Sinbad was cancelled because of low ratings.
</P>
<P>
   ``Vibe'' was designed as a contender for the late-night throne
when it was unveiled last summer with unknown comedian Chris
Spencer sitting in the host chair. It premiered the same week as
another ill-fated syndicated talker ``The Keenen Ivory Wayans
Show.''
</P>
<P>
   ``Wayans'' was cancelled in February, and although ``Vibe's''
ratings surged when Sinbad took over for Spencer, the show has been
running on fumes for months.
</P>
<P>
   ``Our feedback from advertisers and our core viewers was
terrific,'' says Barry Thurston, president of Columbia Tristar
Television, which distributes ``Vibe.'' ``But in this very complex
and very competitive marketplace, it needed more viewers to sustain
itself.'' ``Vibe'' will stop airing Sept. 11.
</P>
<P>
   While ``Vibe'' was on its deathbed Monday, ``Magic'' celebrated
the birth of a bouncing baby talk show.
</P>
<P>
   In metro Atlanta, ``Magic's'' first show drew 87,100 households,
finishing second in its midnight time slot to the TBS movie
``Another 48 Hours'' which garnered 103,850 homes.
</P>
<P>
   But ratings don't tell the whole story. Looking robust and
relaxed, Johnson seemed at times to be apologizing for bothering us
with yet another unnecessary gabfest.
</P>
<P>
   A favorite guest on other talk shows, the 6-foot-9 Johnson
explained, ``I always wanted to try the other side of the desk but
these legs just wouldn't fit.''
</P>
<P>
   Another square peg on the show is comedian Craig Shoemaker, a
grad of the sycophantic sidekick school who misfired in his opening
joke about the NBA finals game in which the Chicago Bulls
shellacked the Utah Jazz.
</P>
<P>
   ``That was the worst beating on videotape since Rodney King,''
he quipped as the audience tittered nervously.
</P>
<P>
   Johnson spent most of the hour playing celeb kissy-face with
guests Arnold Schwarzenegger and Whitney Houston.
</P>
<P>
   Schwarzenegger made an unfortunate remark, calling Johnson and
NBA great Wilt Chamberlain ``two of the strongest animals I've ever
met.'' Later, in a fit of staged spontaneity, Houston revealed her
secret vacuuming fetish. And waddayaknow, there was a Hoover nearby
so she could demonstrate her technique. (Anyone who believes
Houston really cleans her own house, raise your hands.)
</P>
<P>
   Bandleader Sheila E. was the ``Magic Hour's'' lone bright spot.
Wearing a low cut, blue-sequined dress, she played drums like a
woman possessed, ripping up versions of Santana's ``Oyo Como Va''
and Parliament's ``Knee Deep.''
</P>
<P>
   If his ratings hold up, Johnson might survive his 13-week run.
If not, he'll be playing 2-on-2 pickup games with Wayans, Spencer
and Sinbad.
</P>
<P>
   Grade: ``Magic Hour'' _ D
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
