(For use by NYTimes News Service clients) The Los Angeles Daily News plans to move the following stories
today for use by NYTimes News Service clients. They will move in
the ``e'' entertainment news file. For questions, contact Jimmy
Johnson at the Daily News, (818) 713-3695. 
. 
DISCO-MUSIC (Los Angeles) _ Before it slipped onto the endangered
list and became the property of vinyl archeologists, disco _ that
thumping, syncopated, stylish blend of funk, soul, and Latin _ was
the sound of the '70s. Along with everything else from that era, it
might be coming back. By Fred Shuster. 
. 
MAGIC-TV _ (Los Angeles) Johnny Carson had to wait 30 years to have
a diva (Bette Midler) sing a song to him. Magic Johnson, the newest
member of the late night talk show circuit got the royal treatment
from Whitney Houston during his first show on Monday .  By Keith
Marder. 
. 
DIGITAL-NET (Los Angeles) _ For a quick and enjoyable read about
life as an Internet entrepreneur, check out Michael Wolff's ``Burn
Rate; How I Survived the Gold Rush Years on the Internet.'' The
term burn rate refers to how fast a company is ``burning'' its
capital. On the Internet, where most companies seem better at
spending money than making it, burn rate determines how long your
company has to live. By David Bloom. 
. 
EXPO-HiFi (Los Angeles) _ It's all about hardware, baby, as both
the ShowBiz Expo and Hi Fi '98 hit L.A. beginning Friday with more
big iron than a convention of blacksmiths. TheHi Fi '98 show
focuses on stereo and home-theater equipment. By David Bloom. 
. 
. 
