<SLUG> BC-MAGIC-TV-LADN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
GUESTS GIVE MAGIC AN ASSIST
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By KEITH MARDER 
c.1998 Los Angeles Daily News  
<TEXT>
<P>
   LOS ANGELES _ &UR;  &LR; Johnny Carson had to wait 30 years to have a diva
(Bette Midler) sing to him. Magic Johnson, the newest member of the
late-night talk-show circuit, got the royal treatment from Whitney
Houston during his first show Monday.
</P>
<P>
   Houston, who also vacuumed the set and joined bandleader Sheila
E. for a second song, showed just how far Johnson's star status
will help him lure big names to appear on ``The Magic Hour,'' (11
p.m. Monday through Friday, KTTV, Channel 11) and just how
comfortable they feel around him.
</P>
<P>
   That is both the show's main blessing and curse. Celebrities
willing to play along make you feel like you are part of the
Hollywood inner circle, but it also leads to contrived bits such as
the vacuuming and Arnold Schwarzenegger, the night's other panel
guest, giving Johnson a blatant set-up line.
</P>
<P>
   Schwarzenegger asked why he was the show's first guest. Johnson
went on about how his wife loved Arnold, his kids loved Arnold's
movies and ``Harrison Ford couldn't make it.''
</P>
<P>
   Still, that was funnier than anything sidekick _ and I use the
term loosely _ Craig Shoemaker came up with. During an opening
conversation with Johnson, the show's ``goofy uncle'' unleashed a
Madonna sex joke and one about Rodney King. Has he heard the one
about the Lindbergh baby?
</P>
<P>
   Johnson is certainly charming enough to carry a show, and for
his first shot at this gig, he was relaxed and entertaining. He's
already more polished than veteran stage performer Keenen Ivory
Wayans was during his entire talk-show run.
</P>
<P>
   Johnson's electric personality was particularly noticeable when
he did a person-on-the-street piece outside of the Chinese Theater
in Hollywood, where he asked regular folks to scream as an audition
for the sequel to ``Godzilla'' he was going to ``produce.''
</P>
<P>
   The show is billed as having ``60 smiles per hour,'' which may
be an underestimate. Johnson can guffaw with the best of them,
which will further ingratiate him with guests.
</P>
<P>
   If the audience has half as much fun as Johnson seems to be
having, his show could be the rookie that makes the cut.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-06-09-98 1807EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
