<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-EXPO-HIFI-LADN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
WHAT'S EMERGING ON HIGH TECH HORIZON
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By DAVID BLOOM  
 c.1998 Los Angeles Daily News  
<TEXT>
<P>
   LOS ANGELES _ It's all about hardware, baby, as both the ShowBiz
Expo and Hi Fi '98 hit L.A. beginning Friday with more big iron
than a convention of blacksmiths.
</P>
<P>
   The Hi Fi '98 show focuses on stereo and home-theater equipment,
with nearly 200 manufacturers taking over 140 rooms (minus the
beds) in the Westin Los Angeles Airport Hotel and demonstrating to
consumers their latest creations, said spokesman Michael Fremer, a
columnist for Stereophile magazine.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's like a car show, except you get to test drive the
equipment,'' Fremer said. Fremer suggested bringing a favorite CD,
laser disc, DVD or even vinyl LP along to play on systems, to
better judge the differences between systems.
</P>
<P>
   The show will include demonstrations of high-definition
televisions by the big manufacturers, and nifty new DVD players and
other audio products both cheap and expensive, Fremer said.
Numerous makers of accessories such as cables will be on hand as
well.
</P>
<P>
   The show also will feature a face-off between high-quality
successors to the creaky, 20-year-old CD format. The Super CD and
DSD formats offer much better sound than the current CD format, but
each comes with limitations that have kept either from winning the
battle of succession so far.
</P>
<P>
   Numerous seminars _ including ``how to tune a room,''
question-and-answer periods with Stereophile magazine editors and
help with home theater setups _ will be held during each of the
show's three days, Fremer said. And 22 different bands, about one
every hour the show is operating, will be playing.
</P>
<P>
   A three-day pass to the Hi Fi show is $25 in advance and $35 at
the door, Fremer said. A one-day pass is $20.
</P>
<P>
   The ShowBiz Expo at the Los Angeles Convention Center downtown
appeals to a different crowd _ people in the movie business _ and
includes exhibitors showing off everything you need to make a
movie, from coats of armor to lightning-bolt generators to the
Doggiecam, said show manager John Lewinski.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's tools and tips to make movies. It's for the
professional,'' Lewinski said. And the about-to-be professional.
</P>
<P>
   Among the dozens of seminars on four different tracks are a
``two-hour film school'' and ``writer's boot camp.'' Other topics
include digital film restoration, digital television's impacts on
production and independent filming on a micro budget.
</P>
<P>
   Keynote speakers include Peter Biskind, whose well-received
recent book ``Easy Riders, Raging Bulls'' chronicled the
transformation of the movie business during the past three decades.
</P>
<P>
   Other top speakers include Peter Bart, editor in chief of show
sponsor Variety, who will talk about the New Hollywood; and WebTV
CEO Steve Perlman and Todd AO president Salah Hassanein, both of
whom will talk about technology's effects on the entertainment
business.
</P>
<P>
   An exhibits-only pass for the expo is $35 per day, and a one-day
pass for the conferences costs $60. Other combinations of three-day
passes also are available. Both shows begin at 10 a.m. Friday
through Sunday.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-06-09-98 1808EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
