<DOCNO> NYT19980609.0238 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-06-09 18:13 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A1381 &Cx1f; ttj-z
u k &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-MEANS-COLUMN-HNS &LR;      06-09 0806
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-MEANS-COLUMN-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
RUN, ELIZABETH, RUN 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By MARIANNE MEANS  
 c. 1998 Hearst Newspapers  
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ A new poll suggests that Elizabeth Dole, head of
the Red Cross, may become the most formidable candidate the
Republicans could nominate for president in 2000.
</P>
<P>
   This is the stuff of political fantasy. The smart, sophisticated
southern lady would have great trouble overcoming the litmus tests
of the intolerant Republican right wing to win the nomination. But
if she managed that, she could give the Democrats fits in a general
election.
</P>
<P>
   A USA Today-CNN-Gallup trial heat pitting the wife of the GOP's
most recent presidential nominee against Vice President Al Gore,
the expected Democratic nominee, comes up with virtually a tie. She
edges him out by 2 percentage points, 48 to 46, within the polling
margin of error.
</P>
<P>
   This is not good news for Gore.
</P>
<P>
   Furthermore, in a hypothetical match-up with First Lady Hillary
Clinton, who has not indicated any interest in running, Elizabeth
Dole wins hands down, 55 percent to 40 percent.
</P>
<P>
   Are the Republicans wise enough to go for Dole? Do they have the
courage to be the first to put a woman at the top of a national
ticket?
</P>
<P>
   Would she run? She shows no sign of campaigning, although her
husband, former Sen. Bob Dole, keeps promoting her in public as a
potential president. Her name pops up regularly on lists of
possible candidates.
</P>
<P>
   On paper she certainly has the correct credentials, more
impressive than those of some male GOP candidates currently running
around the country hoping political lightening will strike. She
manages an organization with 32,000 employees and an annual budget
of nearly $2 billion. She has twice been a Cabinet officer. A
lawyer, she has served in the Reagan White House and on the Federal
Trade Commission.
</P>
<P>
   In person she is also a winner. Her public performances are
always businesslike, poised and genteel. She charmed the 1996
Republican convention with her composed walk-and-talk among the
delegates praising her husband's abilities. It was generally
considered a bigger hit than his own acceptance speech.
</P>
<P>
   None of this, however, is enough alone to explain her enduring
popularity. What is her secret?
</P>
<P>
   Her active role in her husband's losing presidential campaign
was supposed to help close the gender gap, the preference that
large numbers of women show for Democrats over Republicans. She was
meant to be the GOP counter to Hillary Clinton, who is a strong
campaigner.
</P>
<P>
   But Mrs. Dole did not have any noticeable political impact. Her
husband lost the bulk of the women's vote. The task was probably
impossible in any case. It was his name on the ballot, not hers.
</P>
<P>
   After his defeat, she returned to her post at the Red Cross,
where she has been a visible and effective advocate. This is a
white-hat role that reinforces her image as an honorable woman of
disciplined conduct and good intentions.
</P>
<P>
   Elizabeth Dole's personality is softer, more feminine in style
than Hillary Clinton's, which may have much to do with her high
approval ratings. Unlike the first lady, she avoids cutting-edge
policy statements that can offend as well as please. She has always
reflected the senator's views in public and never taken an
independent position.
</P>
<P>
   At 61, she is seen as an able administrator but not a
threatening figure to either men or women.
</P>
<P>
   She has an independent career and is her husband's full
political partner, but she has always played the traditional female
supporting role in public and has let her man have the center
spotlight when they are together. She twice gave up her own career
to campaign with him _ when he ran for vice president in 1976 and
for president in 1996.
</P>
<P>
   But her principal asset may be a lack of female competition. The
Republican Party has not produced many women of national political
stature, and none can match her name recognition.
</P>
<P>
   No matter. The next presidential election is two years away, an
eternity in politics. If Texas Gov. George W. Bush is re-elected
this fall, he may burst out of the chute as the GOP favorite with
such force that her name will vanish into the mists of time.
</P>
<P>
   And there is the real question of whether she would run. She is
known as a perfectionist who demands order, precise pre-preparation
and a tidy schedule. Reporters who covered her 1996 campaign
efforts say that she was not comfortable with the hurly-burly,
often chaotic conditions she encountered on the road. It is
difficult to imagine her plunging back into that campaign world in
two years or lusting to assume the complicated, messy burdens of
the presidency.
</P>
<P>
   But she would certainly liven things up for the Republicans. And
the senator would make an interesting First Husband. Run,
Elizabeth, run.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
