<SLUG> BC-HADDAWAY-COLUMN-TEX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
ONE THING YOU NEED TO KNOW ABOUT BARGAIN TRAVELING: IT'LL COST YA
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By RICH HADDAWAY 
c.1998 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   After one unrelentingly miserable week in Mexico, we were at
last heading home. We hailed a taxi in front of our hotel in
Cozumel. We picked the wrong one.
</P>
<P>
   It was a heap. It was on its last wheels. The trunk was held
shut with a coat hanger; there were no knobs inside to open the
doors or roll down the windows (they were up).
</P>
<P>
   The interior, in fact, was skeletal. The lining had been torn
away ages ago, and the doors were ribbed metal. Fumes and the
asphalt-heated air from the highway came up from holes in the
floor. It was a long way to the airport.
</P>
<P>
   Our son, 11 at the time, had not learned how to suffer in
silence. He went into operatic mode, panting, pulling at the collar
of his T-shirt, whining about the heat and wiping at his brow with
exaggerated sighs.
</P>
<P>
   In the middle of nowhere, halfway to the airport, the driver
ground the taxi to a halt. He said not a word as he opened the
door, pulling a wrench out of his back pocket as he stood.
</P>
<P>
   This was one big hombre. He came toward the back of the taxi,
opening the door where my son was sitting.
</P>
<P>
   James made a cowering jump into his mother's lap. The writing on
his face was easy to read: ``I'm going to be kidnapped! Murdered by
that wrench! I'll never complain again!''
</P>
<P>
   The driver paid him no mind. He grasped the nub of the former
handle with the wrench and turned, rolling down the window to give
the child some air and hopefully to shut him up. (He may not have
understood English, but he knew the universal language of whining.
Don't we all.) The driver slammed the door, got back in and away we
went to the airport. An uneventful plane ride home, and we were
safe at last.
</P>
<P>
   After a week of boiling temperatures, clouds of flies,
overbooked hotels and crowds of fellow cheapskate Americans, we
vowed never to travel again, and we didn't for four years. We had
been quite thoroughly burned.
</P>
<P>
   We've gotten better. Tentatively, we returned to the road _
several years later, in fact, we returned to Cancun and had a
glorious week in October.
</P>
<P>
   Meanwhile, we've learned one important lesson since our first
venture onto foreign soil almost 15 years ago.
</P>
<P>
   There's no such thing as a free taco.
</P>
<P>
   We had come looking for a bargain, expecting paradise at
half-price. We did get a good deal, but it was the underside of
paradise that we purchased.
</P>
<P>
   We have since learned that, like everything else, in travel you
get what you pay for. ``Off-season'' means less than ideal. Sudden
monetary devaluations, if they attract you, are going to attract
hordes of others. And everybody likes the tropics, especially bugs.
</P>
<P>
   I'm thinking about this because of what is going on in Asia now.
Americans will be pouring in, strutting their stuff, expecting the
world on a platter at plastic saucer prices.
</P>
<P>
   Where there are lots of Americans, there are people who have
learned from them some of the less-seemly ways of doing business:
Get away with whatever you can. Praise your product to high heaven.
Make it sound like a steal; Americans can't resist a bargain. Don't
worry about repeat business; the supply of fresh fools is endless.
</P>
<P>
   That free-taco lesson reverberates throughout the travel
business, upscale to downscale: You get what you pay for. If you
don't have the money to do a vacation right _ not necessarily the
top-of-the-line ticket, but not bargain-basement either _ then
don't go, or at least don't expect much.
</P>
<P>
   You'll have a lot better time in your own back yard, swatting
your very own, home-grown flies.
</P>
<P>
   (Rich Haddaway is travel editor for the Fort Worth
Star-Telegram. Write to him in care of the Fort Worth Star-Telegram
at 400 W. Seventh St., Fort Worth, TX 76102, or e-mail to
sttravel(at)star-telegram.com. Call him at (817) 390-7669. Visit
the Star-Telegram's online services on the World Wide Web:
www.star-telegram.com)
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
