<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BOHLS-COLUMN10-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    A&AMP;M football coach Slocum burned by baseball draft
 &HT;    By Kirk Bohls
 &HT;    c. 1998 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   AUSTIN _ One cannot blame R.C. Slocum for never going to another
baseball game in his life, and it's got nothing to do with the
designated hitter.
</P>
<P>
   Baseball could cost the Texas A&AMP;M football coach three prize
football players, or almost 20 percent of his last recruiting
class. It will surprise no one if quarterback Chip Ambres, wide
receiver Choo Freeman and tight end Greg Porter sign major-league
baseball contracts and forego their college football careers. All
three were among the first 80 picks of last week's free-agent
amateur draft.
</P>
<P>
   Considering that Spring Woods safety/wide receiver Robert
Ferguson is not expected to qualify academically and might attend
Tyler Junior College, Slocum might say goodbye to four of his 16
signees.
</P>
<P>
   Ambres, described by some as a better runner but worse passer
than former Longhorn James Brown, was a marquee signee, but
Freeman's potential loss could strike more damage because the
sprinter set a high school state record with 50 career touchdown
receptions. Freeman is said to be asking for a $1.4 million bonus
from the Colorado Rockies, while first-round pick Ambres is
expected to get at least $1 million from the Florida Marlins.
</P>
<P>
   The Aggies did, however, also sign highly regarded quarterback
Vance Smith of Fort Worth Christian, who's a better pro-style
thrower and who was recruited by Tennessee. And Columbus' Matt
Schobel, who might be moved to tight end, could get a stronger look
at quarterback even though he is reportedly up to 250 pounds.
Sounds like Schobel needs to run some bases if he wants to stay in
the backfield.
</P>
<P>
   While I got you:
</P>
<P>
   _ Tim Duncan's college coach, Wake Forest's Dave Odom, wasn't
surprised by his former player's big splash in the NBA. ``The only
thing that surprised me was he made first-team NBA,'' Odom said.
``I didn't think that would happen in maybe three years. He showed
he could keep his strength up. He always lost weight here from like
250 to 235. MVP? As soon as Michael (Jordan) and (Karl) Malone
leave, you can start talking about that.''
</P>
<P>
   _ If Notre Dame is considering joining the Big Ten and perhaps
giving up its lucrative contract with NBC, the sole remaining
big-time independent must be seriously worried about getting
squeezed out of marquee football games and possibly the Bowl
Championship Series.
</P>
<P>
   _ Next recruiting season should be ``probably the deepest year
for running backs in Texas in quite some time,'' according to Bobby
Burton of the National Recruiting Advisor. He sees 10 to 12
legitimate NCAA Division I-A running backs. Although none may be in
the Ben Gay-Leo Mills class, recruiters will be out in droves for
Andrews' Shaud Williams, Clarksville's Tyrone Richardson,
Needville's Broderick Williams and Big Spring's Tory Mitchell.
</P>
<P>
   _ Southern Cal pulled off a successful steal of home in its
College World Series title game win with the bases loaded, two outs
and two strikes on the batter, which is exactly why I prefer
college over pro sports. The CWS-record 61 homers are a bit much,
however.
</P>
<P>
   _ Put down Round Rock baseball coach John Langerhans and me in
favor of mandatory best-of-three high school playoffs in Class 5A
in lieu of the coin flip if coaches can't agree on a format. At
baseball clinics, he finds the choice ``almost unanimous'' among 4A
and 5A coaches. His Dragons were eliminated this year in a one-game
playoff with Conroe.
</P>
<P>
   _ NBC and Turner Sports are trying to start up a new pro
football league that will surely die before it starts. Cowboys
owner Jerry Jones doesn't wish bad on the league, saying, ``I'm
here because I like football. I'll be candid with you, anything
promoting football is not a negative.'' Here's an unsolicited tip
for NBC: Trash the new-league concept and offer marquee Sunday
college football games. Because of few quarterbacks and
cookie-cutter offenses, the NFL has stagnated.
</P>
<P>
   _ As for reports that former Texas basketball guard Luke Axtell
might not transfer to Kansas, family attorney Sherry Rasmus said,
``Luke isn't going to change his mind.''
</P>
<P>
   _ Saw an ESPN report suggesting the major leagues subsidize
college baseball by springing for wood bats at a cost of about
$100,000 a year per team. I've been saying that for years. The move
would help scouts better evaluate college pitchers and hitters and
enhance collegians' development, which would shorten their stay in
the minor leagues.
</P>
<P>
   _ Texas assistant hoops coach Ricky Stokes played in a college
all-star game at Portsmouth with an obscure guard out of somewhere
called Gonzaga. ``John Stockton was terrific,'' Stokes recalls. Did
you know Stockton's dad owns a tavern in Spokane?
</P>
<P>
   _ The Dallas Cowboys are a might snug with the near-$55 million
salary cap, within about $150,000, but team capologist Stephen
Jones says, ``If we saw a guy to get, we'd go get him.'' He calls
former Texas Christian wideout Jimmy Oliver, a former second-round
pick of San Diego, the team's ``wild card.''
</P>
<P>
   _ If I were Gregg Popovich, I'd pull the trigger and trade David
Robinson for Grant Hill. Spurs need scoring and will not be able to
afford both Robinson and Duncan in two years, and recent playoff
demise reiterates that Robinson _ the ultimate nice guy in sports _
will not lead San Antonio to the NBA Finals.
</P>
<P>
   _ New Cowboys boss Chan Gailey's offensive playbook at
Pittsburgh was an estimated 200 pages thick. He might even
incorporate a ``Slash,'' a la Kordell Stewart, at Dallas. ``It
might be Deion,'' said Gailey, who needs to be worried that Deion
Sanders will miss some of training camp and not be able to work on
his timing with Troy Aikman. Scrimmages with Oakland in El Paso and
possibly New Orleans in Shreveport will help Gailey not have to
play his regulars so much in the exhibition season.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By The AMERICAN-STATESMAN, AUSTIN, TX
</P>
<P>
   AP-NY-06-08-98 1957E
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
