r s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-SPORTS-HALL11-COX     06-09 0673
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-SPORTS-HALL11-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Waco Sports Hall of Fame seeks $2.5 million expansion, more
interactive exhibits.
 &HT;    By J.B. Smith
 &HT;    c. 1998 Cox News Service Tribune-Herald
<TEXT>
<P>
   WACO, Texas _ Picture a young sports fan crouching behind home
base while a virtual-reality Nolan Ryan winds up on the mound and
pitches a fastball, which then lands with a thud in the young
catcher's mitt.
</P>
<P>
   That's the kind of hands-on exhibit Texas Sports Hall of Fame
officials think would pull traveling families off Interstate 35 to
visit the Waco museum.
</P>
<P>
   Hall of fame supporters are hoping by 2000 to raise $2.5 million
to almost double the size of the museum and add more interactive
exhibits, educational programs and a sports research library.
</P>
<P>
   The statewide fund-raising campaign for the ``Project 2000''
improvements will begin later this year, with two illustrious
campaign co-chairmen: Former Dallas Cowboys coach Tom Landry and
Houston Astros owner Drayton McLane.
</P>
<P>
   Hall of fame board members say they hope to increase the
visibility and usefulness of the facility, which is the only
comprehensive sports museum in Texas.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think it has the potential to become one of the premier
sports museums in the country,'' said board member Bob Sheehy.
``There's such a love of almost all sports in Texas, plus we have
that natural Texas pride.''
</P>
<P>
   Sheehy said the museum has a good track record in its five-year
history in Waco, which should make fund raising an easier sell.
</P>
<P>
   The city of Waco, which funded the $1 million construction of
the original building in 1993, has set aside $100,000 in capital
improvement funds for the expansion.
</P>
<P>
   During a presentation last week to the Waco City Council, Sheehy
urged the council to consider pledging $250,000 toward the project.
Council members will consider the request in their budget talks
this summer.
</P>
<P>
   The $2.5 million would allow the Texas Sports Hall of Fame to:
</P>
<P>
   (BBOX)expand the 15,000-square-foot building to 27,000 square
feet, allowing more exhibit room. Officials say the current hall is
out of room, and many potential exhibits are in storage. For
example, the Waco museum was recently designated the official
repository for Southwest Conference memorabilia and records, but
there's no room for an exhibit.
</P>
<P>
   (BBOX)create a sports research library within the building, with
information on high school, college and professional sports figures
from Texas.
</P>
<P>
   (BBOX)fund a youth education program for use both at the museum
and in schools, involving traveling exhibits and occasional
appearances by hall of fame inductees. The museum would create a
sports history unit to be used in seventh-grade Texas history
classes.
</P>
<P>
   (BBOX)create interactive exhibits to hold the attention of
children while their parents browse the more static collections.
</P>
<P>
   ``The most important thing is that this could become an
educational facility for young people as well as entertainment,''
said Steve Fallon, the hall of fame's executive director. ``That's
why we're interested in having interactive displays.''
</P>
<P>
   Fallon said visits from schools, summer camps and day cares are
a big part of the reason that the hall of fame's attendance has
steadily increased over the past five years.
</P>
<P>
   Attendance at the hall of fame so far this year is up 18 percent
over last spring, and officials are expecting 30,000 visitors by
the end of the year, up from 27,500 last year.
</P>
<P>
   Fallon said the admission fee, which is $4 for adults, accounts
for only a small fraction of the museum's revenues. He said the
hall of fame is mostly funded by memberships and donations, much of
it from the Waco community.
</P>
<P>
   But he said he does expect the improvements to increase the
museum's drawing power and boost Waco's tourism potential.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think attendance certainly will increase,'' he said. ``What
an expansion like this does is allow the city of Waco another
selling point for its conventions.''
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
