u e &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-SWEDISH-BAllET-2TAKES     06-09 0666
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-SWEDISH-BAllET-2TAKES-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
DANCE REVIEW: 225 YEARS OF THE ROYAL SWEDISH BALLET  
 (HLW) 
</HEADLINE>
   By ANNA KISSELGOFF   
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   STOCKHOLM, Sweden _ As King Carl XVI Gustaf and Queen Silvia of
Sweden rode out from their palace in an open carriage on Saturday
to greet a populace celebrating the king's 25-year reign, the
clouds lifted. The sun shone not only on the plumed helmets of the
king's horse guard, riding with sabers drawn, but also on the
nearby Royal Opera, which, with its ballet company, was founded by
King Gustav III in 1773.
</P>
<P>
   Stockholm is awash in anniversaries, not the least of which is
being celebrated in the accurately if oddly titled 225 Years
Jubilee Festival of the Royal Swedish Ballet (1773-1998).
</P>
<P>
   Most companies would choose a bicentennial or a 250-year mark to
offer the kind of historical overview being provided in
performances this week by one of the world's oldest ballet troupes.
</P>
<P>
   But Frank Andersen, the Dane who has been the Royal Swedish
Ballet's artistic director for three years, could not wait.
Stockholm was named this year's European Cultural Capital, and the
opera house in which the ballet performs is celebrating its 100th
anniversary this year. Andersen decided that it was time to turn
the international spotlight on a company that has kept itself under
a bushel.
</P>
<P>
   Judging from the festival's initial mix of old and new, Andersen
reasoned rightly. The productions have been unusual, even
startling, and the intensity of the dancers is stunning.
</P>
<P>
   The festival's prime attraction for scores of visiting critics
and theater directors from China, Japan, Europe and America was the
opening bill: four reconstructions of works by Jean Borlin for Les
Ballets Suedois, the notoriously provocative company of expatriates
from the Royal Swedish Ballet based in Paris from 1920 to 1925.
</P>
<P>
   Millicent Hodson and Kenneth Archer, who reconstructed the
Nijinsky version of ``Le Sacre du Printemps'' for the Joffrey
Ballet in 1987, have shown their usual erudition and theatricality
in working with Cole Porter's sole ballet score in ``Within the
Quota'' and with Borlin's little-known ``Dervishes.'' But their
spectacular re-creation of Fernand Leger's Cubist decor and
costumes and of Borlin's geometric choreography in ``Skating Rink''
was the program's highlight. ``El Greco,'' the fourth ballet on the
all-Borlin bill, was rechoreographed in an apt Expressionist style
by the Swedish choreographer Ivo Cremer.
</P>
<P>
   In contrast to this avant-garde of the 1920s, the festival
recalled the Royal Swedish Ballet's beginnings with performances in
two gemlike royal court theaters outside Stockholm. On Monday night
at the Drottningholm Court Theater, which still uses 18th-century
stage machinery, the company danced two works in a pastoral genre
that Cremer based on 18th-century ballet pantomimes.
</P>
<P>
   The spirit of Baroque dance, mixed with 20th-century ballet
technique, prevailed in works by Mary Skeaping (``Return of
Spring'') and by Regina Beck-Friis (``Pygmalion'' and ``Opportunity
Makes the Thief'') on Saturday afternoon at the Confidencen Theater
at Ulriksdal. Kjerstin Dellert, the Swedish soprano who has guided
the renovation of the theater with Princess Christina, the king's
sister, told the audience that when Martha Graham saw it in ruins,
she said one could feel the energy of those who had performed
there. ``She told me, `Recreate the theater,' and I did,'' Ms.
Dellert said.
</P>
<P>
   Restored to its rococo charm, the theater nonetheless recalls
that a golden age in the arts ended with the assassination of
Gustav III at a masked ball in the opera house in 1792. Since then,
the Royal Swedish Ballet has had more than its share of ups and
downs. A renaissance during the Romantic era and in the 1950s has
not concealed the fact that Stockholm, unlike Copenhagen, is not a
ballet capital. Drama, as personified by the director Ingmar
Bergman, and opera take pride of place.
</P>
<P>
   nn
</P>
<P>
   It is easy to see why Rolf de Mare (1888-1964), the Swedish
founder of Les Ballets Suedois, and his star and choreographer,
Borlin (1893-1930), would be regarded as provocateurs by a
conservative ballet audience in Stockholm, where they were reviled
by the press.
</P>
<P>
   In Paris, they were free to produce a still-startling ballet
like ``Skating Rink,'' which, like all four Borlin re-creations on
view, received an astonishingly intense performance from the
Swedish dancers on Friday and Saturday at the opera house.
</P>
<P>
   Ms. Hodson, an American, and Archer, a Briton, originally
reconstructed ``Skating Rink'' in 1996 for the Zurich Ballet, and
here, as in their first productions of ``Dervishes'' and ``Within
the Quota,'' they bring a forgotten work to life and make us
understand it. How much is Borlin's choreography is debatable, but
as usual this team of scholars has captured the style and spirit of
each ballet.
</P>
<P>
   ``Skating Rink'' (1922) shocks even today by its intensity and
emotional cruelty. Inspired by a 1920 poem by the Italian Futurist
poet Riciotto Canudo, the choreography translates his images of
sexual tensions within a circling group of roller skaters at a
working-class rink. Like Canudo, Borlin made his truly infernal
round a symbol of the maelstrom of life.
</P>
<P>
   The choreography's simulated skating is a marvel as the dancers
step and stop, swing an arm across the stomach and bend a leg back.
The relentless, measured tread is emphasized by a fascinating and
insistent modular score by Arthur Honegger.
</P>
<P>
   Unlike ``Les Patineurs,'' Frederick Ashton's ice skating ballet,
``Skating Rink'' is not charming. Its sketchy plot recalls Kurt
Jooss' ``Big City.'' Here, too, a working-class lad loses his girl
to an outsider in a top hat.
</P>
<P>
   Yet Borlin's flattened style is more modernist, and the dancers
themselves become mobile Cubist shapes in bright colors that fuse
miraculously with the abstract forms above them on Leger's
backdrop.
</P>
<P>
   Within the dissolving patterns, individual characters come into
relief. A sailor rescues a tottering skater and woos her.
Repeatedly the women with marcelled hair and in heels hug men who
look like Jean Gabin wearing a cap. Inspired by the apache dances
of the 1920s, the embraces are tight and become the ballet's
leitmotif.
</P>
<P>
   The ensemble renders the choreography's kaleidoscopic detail
with astonishing precision, and the principals perform with
dramatic intensity. Jan-Erik Wikstrom has a striking deadpan
serenity as the poet who seduces Marie Lindqvist, mesmerizing in
her doll-like simplicity as the heroine. Anders Nordstrom has an
almost unbearable desperation in a fierce portrayal of the lover, a
study in human disintegration.
</P>
<P>
   That the heroine faints or dies while the whirlpool skating
continues at the end adds to a genuine pathos. In all, it is rare
to see dancers give so much of themselves in ballet.
</P>
<P>
   This is true also in the three other ballets. In ``Dervishes''
(1920), Hans Nilsson is riveting, looking positively ecstatic and
spent as he throws his head back as the head dervish in a spinning
solo once danced by Borlin. Ms. Hodson used a film fragment to
create new choreography for 10 men (the ballet once used five):
five dervishes and five soldiers who join them.
</P>
<P>
   As ``Skating Rink'' does in a different way, ``Dervishes''
succeeds through its changing patterns and use of repetition. The
mosque interior, based on Georges Mouveau's original design, and
the Orientalist motifs from Glazunov's ``Danse de Salome'' suggest
more than a pastiche. The other dervishes (Goran Svalberg, Brendan
Collins, Olof Westring and Joakim Stephenson) are impressive in
their concentration.
</P>
<P>
   An equally committed performance comes from Per Sacklen as an
angular tormented figure in a loincloth in ``El Greco'' (1920),
which Cremer rechoreographed in a neo-Expressionist style based on
images that Borlin drew from El Greco's paintings. Desire-Emile
Inghelbrecht, a French conductor, composed a turbulent score that
matches the Mouveau backdrop inspired by two paintings, ``Storm
Over Toledo'' and ``The Burial of the Count of Orgaz.''
</P>
<P>
   Like ``El Greco,'' the tale of a Swedish immigrant who sees
America as a dream factory in ``Within the Quota'' (1923) works
chiefly as a historical curiosity. The jazz-tinctured music by a
young Cole Porter is overwhelmed by Charles Koechlin's
orchestration. One can only smile at the satirical parade of
Hollywood types pursued by a Puritan as envisioned in a scenario by
the American expatriate Gerald Murphy, whose tabloid backdrop is
faithfully reproduced.
</P>
<P>
   The Royal Swedish Ballet has yet to show off its pure classical
technique in the festival. But in ``Quota,'' Carl Inger's acrobatic
immigrant, Collins' elegant black entertainer and Madeleine Onne's
dazzling flapper stand out with a projection that any ballet troupe
would envy.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
