<DOCNO> NYT19980609.0246 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-06-09 18:26 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A1406 &Cx1f; tad-z
r f &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-UNINSURED10-COX     06-09 0920
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-UNINSURED10-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    An Atlanta firm is helping patients apply for insurance
benefits. For hospitals, the side effect is fewer unpaid bills.
 &HT;    By Andy Miller
 &HT;    c. 1998 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA _ James Taylor of Smyrna underwent several operations
last year to improve his blood flow. The problem comes from a
hereditary vascular condition that killed his mother and sister.
</P>
<P>
   Taylor, 43, had no health insurance. But the surgeries were
performed at Cobb Hospital, and eventually he gained Medicaid
benefits that paid for most of those costs and subsequent medical
bills.
</P>
<P>
   Taylor had applied for the benefits with the aid of Clarissa
Urrutia of Atlanta-based Chamberlin Edmonds &AMP; Associates. Urrutia
and the firm guided him through the bureaucratic maze that
encumbers the benefits process.
</P>
<P>
   ``It would never have occurred to me to sign up, even though I'm
totally disabled,'' Taylor says. Without Chamberlin Edmonds, he
says, ``I would have been lost.''
</P>
<P>
   Chamberlin Edmonds bases its business on a population largely
ignored by the U.S. health care system: the uninsured. It's the
biggest such operation in Georgia. The private company contracts
with Cobb Hospital and 100 other hospitals, 60 of them in Georgia,
helping to convert uninsured patients into Medicaid and Medicare
beneficiaries, and to obtain disability benefits for them. Patients
with bare-bones insurance also can get new benefits.
</P>
<P>
   That way, hospitals recoup costs that normally go unpaid -- and
that eventually lead to higher medical charges for insured
patients. Those unpaid bills run into the millions of dollars.
Hospital costs in caring for uninsured patients in the state
totaled $638 million in 1996, or 8 percent of their overall costs,
according to GHA, an association of Georgia hospitals.
</P>
<P>
   Government offsets some of those costs. But at the same time,
the number of uninsured has steadily climbed, despite a vibrant
economy. An estimated 1.3 million Georgians, or 20 percent of
residents under age 65, have no health insurance. Nationally, the
estimate is 41 million.
</P>
<P>
   Some remedies are coming. Coverage is being extended to
thousands of children in Georgia -- and millions nationally --
through a new federal-state initiative.
</P>
<P>
   Chamberlin Edmonds, though, concentrates on disabled adults.
Such disabilities include cancer, AIDS, some cardiac disease and
major mental illness. Overall, Chamberlin Edmonds says it has
helped more than 100,000 patients in 11 states gain benefits. For
hospitals, it has recovered more than $300 million in revenue.
</P>
<P>
   Judy Starkey, owner and chief executive officer, helped found
the company 12 years ago, starting with a single hospital in
Thomasville. Now it has 170 employees and plans to expand further
in the Midwest and Northeast.
</P>
<P>
   ``They're the most renowned in the Southeast,'' says Cathy
Dougherty of Gwinnett Hospital System, also a client.
</P>
<P>
   In launching the business, Starkey knew how confounding the
health care system could be. And she knew how delinquent medical
bills can devastate a family.
</P>
<P>
   Son John, adopted at 3 months, has autism, and the family dealt
with gaps in its insurance in getting services for him. Later
Starkey worked in health care programs for the state Department of
Human Resources.
</P>
<P>
   ``I knew there were thousands of people disrupted and disjointed
by medical catastrophe,'' Starkey says. ``It is a terrible
financial and emotional strain for a family.''
</P>
<P>
   The firm helps hospital patients apply for Supplemental Security
Income, based on financial need and disability, which qualifies
them eventually for the federal-state Medicaid program. They also
can apply for Social Security disability insurance benefits, which
would allow them Medicare coverage. Once benefits are approved, a
hospital's bills can get reimbursed.
</P>
<P>
   ``A lot of (patients) can't get to the Social Security office or
can't get all the medical evidence together,'' says Fabricio
Barrera, assistant regional commissioner for the Social Security
Administration. The company, he says, ``helps us provide better
service to the public.''
</P>
<P>
   And it's free help for the patient. Chamberlin Edmonds gets a
percentage of what the hospital recoups.
</P>
<P>
   For Grady Memorial Hospital, Starkey's biggest client and a
``safety net'' provider, caring for the uninsured is a primary
mission. About 40 percent of the Atlanta hospital's patients have
no health insurance.
</P>
<P>
   Bob Barbier, CFO for the Grady Health System, says that in 1996,
Grady referred 4,472 patients to Chamberlin Edmonds. Of that
number, 1,901 were approved for benefits, 913 were rejected and the
others are pending.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's an excellent deal for Grady,'' said Barbier. Chamberlin
Edmonds, he said, has generated more than $10 million per year for
Grady.
</P>
<P>
   The company is an advocate for patients as well. ``They walk
them through an incredibly bureaucratic process. The patient's
bills get satisfied, and they get benefits that continue.'' The
payoff also has been good for Walter Paterson, 35, of Atlanta. He
was diagnosed with HIV this year as an uninsured Grady patient.
Now, with Medicaid benefits obtained through Chamberlin Edmonds, he
gets coverage for a multidrug cocktail that has improved his
condition.
</P>
<P>
   The company, Paterson says, ``did all the paperwork for me.
Thank God for them helping me.''
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By The Atlanta Journal-Constitution
</P>
<P>
   AP-NY-06-05-98 2233E
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
