<DOCNO> NYT19980609.0249 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-06-09 18:28 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A1411 &Cx1f; tad-z
r f &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-HOLSENDOLPH10-COX     06-09 0687
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-HOLSENDOLPH10-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Ernest Holsendolph's Business Commentary: Wireless wizardry
benefits consumers
 &HT;    By Ernest Holsendolph
 &HT;    c. 1998 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA _ Two years ago, when BellSouth bought Wireless Cable of
Atlanta and began collecting licenses to offer wireless, it sounded
like a throwback. I remembered television by microwave antenna more
than two decades ago, when many cities looked to that technology as
they waited for cable operators to get around to wiring the urban
areas.
</P>
<P>
   It was always a kind of second-class system, a service that
wavered when trees were in leaf and with which the signal was not
the same quality as cable.
</P>
<P>
   Last week BellSouth finally unveiled what it had in mind: a
digital update of the old service that has now leapfrogged what
most cable customers get. Up to 160 channels of entertainment,
nearly a third in pay-per-view channels. Unlike satellite
broadcasting, another cable rival, the new wireless can offer local
channels as well as the full array of cable offerings.
</P>
<P>
   Cable operators are not caught by surprise. In fact, all across
the country some of the fastest steppers in the video business are
phone companies, satellite distribution companies and others that
have been increasing their share of the multichannel television
market.
</P>
<P>
   Cable's share of that market slipped to 87 percent last year,
according to testimony to Congress last October by Decker Anstrom,
president of the National Cable Television Association. Now an
estimated 11.5 million households nationally get a multichannel TV
service, and cable's share has slipped further to about 85.5
percent, according to the NCTA.
</P>
<P>
   Dire as this may seem, cable companies like MediaOne here are in
the middle of upgrading their service to digital and will have
offerings that look very much like the BellSouth service.
</P>
<P>
   But while all the players are racing toward a digital finish
line, BellSouth now has parachuted into the game and could grab
restless cable customers waiting for a change.
</P>
<P>
   I asked Jeff Kagan, the media consultant who has tested the
BellSouth service, how he compared the traditional cable service to
the new one.
</P>
<P>
   ``The picture is sharper, you have greater parental control over
when the TV can be on and what channels can be viewed, and the
built-in TV guide is superior,'' Kagan said.
</P>
<P>
   Also, he said he liked the ``near'' television-on-demand, in
which a popular movie will be available at many starting times, so
you don't need to wait hours for a selection of choice.
</P>
<P>
   There are limits to the BellSouth service. For reasons of
geography the line of sight broadcasts cannot reach all households.
Where permissible, some of that gap is being filled in by selective
wiring of certain communities.
</P>
<P>
   Other phone companies, such as Ameritech, are relying upon
wiring or are building competitive digital systems that are mirror
images of the updated cable systems -- in places like Chicago,
Detroit, Cleveland and elsewhere.
</P>
<P>
   The BellSouth game plan, with its flexibility and mix of
wireless and wired, allows it to move faster and more cheaply to
garner a share of the television market.
</P>
<P>
   The assumption is that the BellSouth plan does not necessarily
take customers from cable. Logically, it might appeal to customers
who have been using satellite service but always wanted convenient
connections to local TV, or it might appeal to newcomers or people
with no service at all.
</P>
<P>
   What seems certain is that BellSouth is right on time for the
Atlanta consumer who loves the latest, is fascinated by technology
and loves to be first on the block with what's hot.
</P>
<P>
   Will BellSouth capture those customers for all time? Probably
not. Cable has a card to play: It will be able to offer digital
video, phone service and Internet connections.
</P>
<P>
   But the glory of these developments, and so much else in these
days of exploding technology, is that consumers will have more
choices. The competitive heat is turned up, and the race has picked
up in pace.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
