<DOCNO> NYT19980609.0250 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-06-09 18:29 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A1415 &Cx1f; tad-z
s w &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-DC-FUTURE-COX &UR; 1500&AMP;AD     06-09 2164
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-DC-FUTURE-COX </SLUG>
   1500&AMP;ADD-$ADV14  NATION'S CAPITOL LOOKING TO
BETTER POST-BARRY FUTURE
 &HT;     For release Sunday, June 14.
 &HT;     A photo to illustrate this story will move Wednesday to the New
York Times News Service.
 &HT;     Cox photos will move Wednesday to illustrate this story.
 &HT;     By LARRY LIPMAN 
 &HT;     c.1998 Cox News Service  
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ Next January, for only the second time in two
decades, someone other than Marion Barry will be sworn in as mayor
of the District of Columbia, the nation's capital.
</P>
<P>
   What that will mean for Washington is still unclear, but many
observers think it will be a positive development.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's like turning over a new leaf,'' said Charles Harris,
professor of political science at Howard University in the district
and author of a book examining the relationship between the city
and Congress. ``You have new hopes and you wait and see what is
going to happen.''
</P>
<P>
   One might argue it could hardly be any worse than the current
situation.
</P>
<P>
   _ The city's population has dropped from 606,000 in 1990 to
about 529,000 last year, its lowest level since the Depression.
</P>
<P>
   _ From 1987 to 1997, Washington had the highest murder rate
among cities with more than 400,000 residents.
</P>
<P>
   _ Its schools are a shambles. Washington has the lowest test
scores of any school jurisdiction in the metropolitan region. Last
year, the schools opened three weeks late to system-wide roof
repairs.
</P>
<P>
   _ In recent years, city services were so bad that the overloaded
morgue had to stockpile bodies on gurneys without body bags, the
water system was declared unsafe for three months in a row, and the
city-run nursing home shut down.
</P>
<P>
   _ The city-run prison in nearby Lorton, Va., was run so poorly
and lost so much money that the federal government took it over.
</P>
<P>
   _ City agencies responsible for public housing, foster children
and the mentally ill have been placed in court-ordered
receivership.
</P>
<P>
   _ Washington's potholes are legendary; whole blocks have parking
meters without heads.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's really sad that the nation's capital has become a
national joke,'' said Sen. Lauch Faircloth, R-N.C., chairman of the
Senate subcommittee that sets appropriations for the District.
``The city was in a terrible condition, a catastrophic condition.
You pick the part of the city that was not out of control.''
</P>
<P>
   Much, but certainly not all, of the blame for Washington's
problems can be laid at Barry's feet. As Washington's mayor, Barry
controlled a government that performed not only city functions, but
also state functions such as housing prisoners and providing
welfare and Medicaid to the poor.
</P>
<P>
   But Barry always had a not-so-silent partner just 13 blocks
away: the U.S. Congress, which still holds ultimate power over the
nation's capital.
</P>
<P>
   A quarter-century ago, Congress granted the city home rule
authority, giving it a large degree of autonomy over its own
affairs. In the last few years, Congress has largely taken it away.
</P>
<P>
   Three years ago, with the city's finances in disarray and
charges of corruption swirling around Barry's associates, the
Republican-led Congress created a control board with authority to
override the city government in slashing the bloated bureaucracy
and imposing fiscal discipline.
</P>
<P>
   Last year Congress went even further, stripping Barry's
authority over nine major city departments and giving it to the
control board.
</P>
<P>
   This spring, after Barry appointed a new police chief, Congress
took away his power to fire the chief without the control board's
approval.
</P>
<P>
   Last month, the board adopted sweeping reforms of city
regulations in such areas as zoning, professional licensing and
issuing environmental permits _ areas traditionally the purview of
a city council.
</P>
<P>
   The result is that many residents of the capital of the world's
foremost democracy consider themselves second-class citizens with
less of a voice in their political destiny than the residents of
U.S. territories such as Puerto Rico or Guam.
</P>
<P>
   ``Congress has always viewed this as the nation's capital,
whereas city residents have viewed it as the District of
Columbia,'' said Joseph McCormick, an associate professor of
political science at Howard University.
</P>
<P>
   Although Washington had an elected mayor and city council for
half of the 19th century, it was governed by a federal commission
for nearly 100 years until Congress approved home rule for the city
in 1973.
</P>
<P>
   Barry, in 1978, was the second mayor elected under the home rule
charter, winning again in 1982 and 1986. His bid for a fourth
consecutive term was interrupted by his conviction on drug
possession charges following an FBI sting operation in which he was
videotaped smoking crack cocaine with a woman in a district hotel
room.
</P>
<P>
   After six months in prison, Barry won a city council seat in
1992 and then trounced Mayor Sharon Pratt Kelly _ the reformer who
couldn't deliver _ in 1994. Last month, he indicated he didn't plan
to run for re-election, although he avoided specifically saying he
wouldn't run again.
</P>
<P>
   Clearly, one reason for his decision is that being mayor of
Washington isn't what it used to be. Nor is it likely to be again,
at least in the near future. Where the mayor once controlled more
than 35,000 employees, he now runs the 400-person recreation
department and some small municipal agencies.
</P>
<P>
   No matter who becomes Washington's next mayor _ and there are
already five major candidates _ he or she will have to cope with
the control board and its appointed chief management officer,
Camille C. Barnett, who operates much like a city manager.
</P>
<P>
   The new mayor also will have to work closely with Alice Rivlin,
the vice chairman of the Federal Reserve Board, nominated last
month by President Clinton to be the control board's new chair.
</P>
<P>
   That means two white women will hold the two most powerful
positions in a city whose population is more than 60 percent black.
</P>
<P>
   Under the legislation that set up the control board, it is
supposed to operate until the city has a balanced budget for four
consecutive years. Last year was the first, and this year's budget
also is expected to show surplus.
</P>
<P>
   So the incoming mayor will have to deal with the control board
for at least two more years, assuming the budget remains balanced.
</P>
<P>
   The larger question is whether, in a post-Barry era, Congress
might restore some of the powers of which it stripped the mayor in
the past two years. That will depend on congressional, as well as
city, politics.
</P>
<P>
   ``If a Republican Congress is still there, you're likely to see
powers continuing to be stripped away from the mayor's office,''
said Ron Walters, a professor of African-American studies at the
University of Maryland.
</P>
<P>
   Mark Plotkin, a political commentator on American University's
WAMU radio, said he agreed with Barry's charge that the
Republican-led Congress has been ``mean-spirited'' toward the
district, but said that behavior will be harder to justify after
Barry is gone.
</P>
<P>
   ``As long as Barry was there, the Republicans had a (reason) to
do anything to punish D.C.,'' Plotkin said. ``Without Barry, it
will be more difficult. The citizens of the district were penalized
for electing Marion Barry.''
</P>
<P>
   Harris, the Howard University professor, suggested that even if
Republicans retain control, there will be a better relationship
between the city and Congress in a post-Barry era, at least until
the new mayor establishes a track record.
</P>
<P>
   Faircloth, who has used his chairmanship of the appropriations
subcommittee to dictate policy to the District, is up for
re-election this November. Whether he keeps a hand on the
district's finances will depend on that election, and on whether he
chooses to remain chairman in the new Congress.
</P>
<P>
   In Faircloth's view, ``we need to put in place a structure to
prevent the destruction of the city we have seen over the last 20
years.'' For him, that means some form of city manager with closer
oversight by Congress.
</P>
<P>
   Andrew F. Brimmer, the control board chairman whose term was
extended for three months when it expired at the end of May, has
suggested that much of the city's governance be transferred
permanently to a trio of professional managers responsible for
management, finances and an independent inspector general.
</P>
<P>
   Whether the city will ever return to a strong mayor form of
government _ as it had before Barry's power was stripped _ is
uncertain.
</P>
<P>
   Although it's not what he advocates, Walters sees the next mayor
as potentially a transition figure toward a weak-mayor, city
manager form of government which is more beholden to Congress _ a
step back from the home rule era and the heady days when Washington
politicians pressed for statehood.
</P>
<P>
   Bernard Ross, professor of public administration at American
University, said that although other large cities operate well with
a city manager, many ``yearn for a strong political leader with
brokering skills and coalition-building skills.''
</P>
<P>
   Given Washington's contentious history, much of which is driven
by racial politics, Ross predicted that a weak-mayor form of
government would be politically unpalatable for the city's
residents, who already view themselves as politically downtrodden.
</P>
<P>
   Howard Gillette Jr., a professor of American civilization at
George Washington University and author of a book on the district's
history, said that regardless of who the next mayor is Washington
will continue having the same structural problems it has had for
nearly two centuries.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's going to clear the air, but the problems are not going to
be over without Barry,'' Gillette said.
</P>
<P>
   (Story can end here. Optional add follows.)
</P>
<P>
   Walters said people have ``wrongly pointed at (Barry) as the
person responsible for all of this. They've gotten it wrong.''
</P>
<P>
   Gillette, Walters and other argue that regardless of who runs
the city government, unless fundamental changes are made in its
relationship with Congress, problems will persist.
</P>
<P>
   Because Washington is a city without a state, it has many of the
same responsibilities that a state performs, but does not have many
of the offsetting revenue sources.
</P>
<P>
   Like many cities, Washington has seen an explosion of retail and
commercial activity in the suburbs of Maryland and Northern
Virginia. In 1992 and 1993, for example, the District added 29,000
square feet of new retail space, compared to 2.6 million for the
Maryland suburbs and 5.8 million for the Virginia suburbs.
</P>
<P>
   But while other cities surrounded by bustling suburbs are able
to recoup much of the retail tax revenues generated outside their
borders through revenue-sharing with their states, solitary
Washington cannot share in any state's bounty.
</P>
<P>
   Likewise, Washington _ unlike, for example Atlanta _ cannot
share with a state in the income taxes generated from city workers
who live in the suburbs. Since it approved home rule, a progression
of Democratic- and Republican-led Congresses have rejected the idea
of a D.C. commuter tax on suburban residents.
</P>
<P>
   Suburban workers account for just over half of the income
generated in the District, according to a study by the Center for
Regional Analysis at George Madison University.
</P>
<P>
   The Appleseed Center for Law and Justice, a Ralph Nader-founded
organization, estimated the District could receive nearly a
half-billion dollars a year if it was allowed to tax suburban
workers.
</P>
<P>
   Further adding to the District's difficulties, the city depends
largely on the federal government to determine how much the
government wants to pay in lieu of taxes for the billions of
dollars worth of property it owns in the city limits.
</P>
<P>
   Federal payments run about $660 million a year, but the
Appleseed Foundation suggests that the federal payment should be in
the range of $1.2 billion.
</P>
<P>
   Dec. 1, 2000, marks the bicentennial of Washington becoming the
nation's capital. Gillette thinks the anniversary will spark
renewed efforts among city residents to claim a greater political
voice.
</P>
<P>
   ``In the next year and a half there will be a lot of attention
to this form of governance,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Although it's not likely to happen, Gillette suggests a solution
that regularly surfaces in discussing Washington's future. If
Congress is unwilling to grant it statehood _ it would be 1/28th
the size of Rhode Island _ perhaps there should be a regional
referendum to determine whether the district should be revert back
to Maryland. A precedent for that was set in 1846 when the Virginia
portion of what was plotted for the district reverted back to
Virginia.
</P>
<P>
   McCormick, the Howard University professor, recalled a sign that
used to greet motorists who drove into Washington from suburban
Maryland. It read: ``Welcome to Washington, D.C., the Last
Colony.''
</P>
<P>
   As Congress became increasingly critical of Barry, it treated
Washington more and more like a colony. Reversing that trend will
be the biggest job for the city's next mayor.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; ENDIT &LR;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
