<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-TV-NOTES-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
TV NOTES: A SUMMER JOB FOR FOX; ABC WEIGHS A 2ND ``60 MINUTES'' 
</HEADLINE>
  (mk) 
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   Looking to expand on its effort to keep viewers from taking a
vacation from network television in the summer, Fox announced plans
Tuesday to infiltrate the next couple of months with a strategic
assortment of new programs, highlighted by seven original episodes
of its long-running soap opera, ``Melrose Place,'' and its first
attempt at a news magazine since 1994.
</P>
<P>
   Fox will also try a new series of stunts related to the Guinness
Book of World Records, a group of original movies and a few other
new episodes of existing Fox shows. In all, Fox said, 42 percent of
its programming will be original this summer, up a modest 2 percent
from last summer.
</P>
<P>
   Still, Fox's intent is to continue expanding the new programming
in July and August, when the broadcast networks' offerings have
traditionally been dominated by repeats. This ``see you in
September'' attitude has only encouraged viewers to sample cable
channels. A result has been further erosion of viewers who watch
the networks.
</P>
<P>
   All the networks have agreed that taking off in the summer makes
no sense, and have moved to sprinkle new fare among the repeats.
But Peter Roth, the president for entertainment for Fox, has made
halting the summer viewer exodus something of a cause.
</P>
<P>
   ``Call me stubborn,'' he said. ``Each year the number of
original shows should increase.''
</P>
<P>
   Last summer, Fox's most ambitious effort was a dramatic series
set in fourth-century Ireland called ``Roar.'' It proved a
disappointment. ``We learned some lessons last summer,'' Roth said.
``The reality-based shows do better than new dramas.''
</P>
<P>
   This summer, he said, he is hoping that ``Guinness World
Records: Prime Time'' will catch on. Various world-record-breaking
stunts will be attempted in the show, which is to be broadcast on
Tuesdays at 9 p.m. starting on July 28. But the new series sure to
draw the most attention is ``Fox Files,'' a news magazine from Fox
News, which thus far has provided only regular programming for the
company's all-news channel.
</P>
<P>
   The news magazine will be anchored by Catherine Crier and Jon
Scott and will be broadcast on Thursdays at 9 p.m. starting on July
16.
</P>
<P>
   The centerpiece of the Fox summer strategy is ``Melrose Place,''
which will return with new episodes on Mondays at 8 p.m. starting
July 27, picking up on the cliffhanger with which the last season
ended in April. Roth noted that ``Melrose Place'' began its run in
1992 in the summer ``and it proved it can work there.''
</P>
<P>
   The plan is to broadcast seven original episodes of the series
through the end of the summer, building to another cliffhanger on
Sept. 7, with a new season of ``Melrose Place'' beginning the next
Monday, Sept. 14, at 8 p.m., just before the season premiere of
``Ally McBeal.''
</P>
<P>
   Last season Fox did especially well with a miniseries version of
a Dean Koontz best seller, ``Intensity.'' The network will repeat
that on July 1 and 2, and will offer a new movie based on another
Koontz book, ``Hideaway,'' on July 8. Another original film,
``Disaster at the Mall,'' about a robbery at a shopping mall during
a flood, will be broadcast on July 29.
</P>
<P>
   Magazines, Magazines
</P>
<P>
   For months people inside and outside CBS News have been poking
and prying and practically listening at keyholes for gossip about
whether a second weekly edition of ``60 Minutes'' will be
authorized. The move is opposed by the producer and correspondents
of the Sunday night program but supported by Leslie Moonves and Mel
Karmazin, the top executives at the network, who hope the clout of
the ``60 Minutes'' name will bring in millions of viewers another
night of the week.
</P>
<P>
   So intense is the media interest that newspapers reported
Tuesday on what was essentially a kaffeeklatsch on Monday between
Karmazin and the ``60 Minutes'' correspondents, along with the
deputy executive producer, Phil Scheffler (Don Hewitt was in Canada
receiving an award at the annual Banff Television Festival). Each
side listened congenially to the other's arguments, and nothing was
resolved.
</P>
<P>
   While ``60 Minutes'' staff members were lavished with attention,
the other CBS news magazine, ``48 Hours,'' has been quietly revving
into overdrive to produce two nights a week of ``48 Hours,'' at
least until the fall.
</P>
<P>
   Susan Zirinsky, the executive producer, calls her show ``the
little engine that could.'' Its latest investigative story, to be
broadcast Thursday night at 10, has new information about the car
crash that killed Britain's Diana, Princess of Wales, and her
companion, Dodi Fayed, last summer. It includes previously secret
testimony to the French police from the bartender who served drinks
to their limousine driver, Henri Paul, before the crash and who now
says that he was told to lie to investigators about Paul's alcohol
consumption.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
