A1417 &Cx1f; tad-z
r f &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-SAMSUNG10-COX     06-09 0418
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-SAMSUNG10-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Samsung stops chip production to raise worldwide prices
 &HT;    By Omar L. Gallaga
 &HT;    c. 1998 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   AUSTIN, Texas _ Samsung Austin Semiconductor said its production
would not be affected by a plan by South Korean parent Samsung
Electronics Co. to temporarily stop production on memory chips.
</P>
<P>
   Samsung Electronics, the world's largest maker of memory chips,
said recently it was stopping production in its factories for a
week to combat a worldwide glut in memory chips that have dropped
prices on the products.
</P>
<P>
   Bill Cryer, a spokesman for Samsung Austin, said the company's
$1.3 billion memory production plant in Northeast Austin would not
be part of the work stoppage. ``We're still moving into our second
phase of production and we're ramping up here,'' Cryer said. ``We
will continue that.''
</P>
<P>
   The Austin plant is scheduled to reach full capacity by late
summer or early fall, he said, producing 64-megabit DRAMs for
customers including Dell Computer Corp. and Compaq Computer Corp.
</P>
<P>
   Cryer said some of the chips that are produced in Austin may be
held up at packaging plants in Korea, but that memory chips will be
received by Samsung's clients on time. ``They have made provisions
to make sure that all of our customers will be getting chips on
schedule,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Samsung Electronics' announcement came less than a week after
Hyundai Electronics Co., South Korea's second-largest producer of
memory chips, suspended production for seven days.
</P>
<P>
   Both companies have cited falling memory prices and
overproduction for their production halts. But while the companies
are counting on cutting back supplies of chips to spur demand,
Bruce Bonner, an analyst at research firm Dataquest, said the
production suspensions may not have the desired effect.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is something that happened just about the same time last
year,'' Bonner said. ``They've tried to do this before without
success. In the short term, it looks good because they get higher
prices. But prices will eventually drop and go back to where they
would have been in the first place.''
</P>
<P>
   According to Dataquest, prices have fallen about 25 to 30
percent in the last five weeks for 16-megabit and 64-megabit DRAMs.
South Korean companies Samsung, Hyundai and LG Semicon account for
about 40 percent of the world's memory chip production. This
article includes material from The Associated Press.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
