<SLUG> BC-ANDERSON-COLUMN-TEX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
PROM DATE GETS OFF ON WRONG FOOT
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By MONICA ANDERSON 
c.1998 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   Prom season has come and gone. The ill-fitting tuxedos have been
returned to the rental shops. The dresses have been dry cleaned and
hung at the back of the closet where terminal clothes go until mom
and dad forget how much they cost. Many pleasant or traumatic
memories will resurface each time the lovely photos are shown to
unsuspecting guests.
</P>
<P>
   Yes, all of this leaves me wondering if there is some sort of
connection between this smoke in the sky and all the socks that
disappear from the dryer. Why don't they disappear in pairs anyway?
Could it be some conspiracy by sock manufacturers where one of the
socks is designed to disintegrate after the third washing? Think
about it.
</P>
<P>
   Anyway, proms have really changed. When I was in high school, we
went to the prom with dates who were driving their parents'
``good'' car. We stayed until the prom was over and then we went to
IHOP and ate pancakes before going home.
</P>
<P>
   Not any more. Now the dates arrive in stretch limos as long as
your house. They stay at the prom about half an hour, then retire
to hotel suites for the all-night after-party. Just the thought of
that almost makes me want to go back to high school. I say almost
because one of my worst memories of high school involves the prom.
To make a long story short, I got stood up my sophomore year. Well,
maybe that's too short.
</P>
<P>
   It was the junior-senior prom but my boyfriend was a junior so I
was one of a handful of 10th graders planning to attend. The day
before, I had my hair styled into this elaborate beehive. I slept
on my face all night to keep from messing it up. That morning, I
painted my nails crimson red. My mother said that harlots wore that
color, but she wasn't home and it was her polish. Three hours
before the party, I started getting dressed. Every article had been
debated and carefully selected just for that occasion. I was ready
30 minutes early. My parents took pictures of me standing by the
pecan tree in our yard. At 6 o'clock, I went into my room so that I
could make a grand entrance when my boyfriend arrived. Two hours
later, I was still there. That's when my mother finally overruled
me and insisted on calling my date.
</P>
<P>
   I don't remember much after that. I don't remember what his
excuse was. I don't remember getting undressed. Nor do I recall
taking all of the bobby pins out of that beehive. Maybe my mother
did it. I can't even recall the guy's name. I only remember crying
until my eyes turned as red as my nails, and I remember the look of
anger on my father's face. That's all; the sound and the fury.
</P>
<P>
   After that, I had huge trust issues, self-esteem issues,
depression and a host of other emotional problems. I didn't recover
until I met this other really neat guy about a week later. In
retrospect, I should have known something was strange about that
prom date of mine. Other guys had dice or air fresheners hanging
from their rearview mirrors; he always had one, clean sock dangling
there. Live and learn, people. Live and learn.
</P>
<P>
   (Monica Frazier Anderson is a wife, mother and dentist. Call her
at (817) 548-5564, or write in care of the Arlington Star-Telegram'
at 1111 W. Abram St., Arlington, TX 76013. Visit the
Star-Telegram's online services on the World Wide Web:
www.star-telegram.com)
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-06-09-98 1831EDT &QL; 
