<HEADER>
A1426 &Cx1f; tad-z
r f &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-TECHTOOLS10-COX     06-09 0605
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-TECHTOOLS10-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Tech Tools: New computer brings enough pain to share
 &HT;    By Jack Warner
 &HT;    c. 1998 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA _ I'm writing this on my new 400-MHz computer, and I'm
not having as much fun as you might think.
</P>
<P>
   I have come to dread new computers. Used to be, getting a
computer was the most exciting thing in the world. I was like a kid
at Christmas. Now I'm like Scrooge. It's more work than it's worth.
</P>
<P>
   Here's what happens when a new computer arrives at my house:
</P>
<P>
   I shove my current computer to one side of the desk and set the
new one up on the other side. Nothing is hooked up but keyboard,
mouse and monitor. I've got to get a bunch of stuff from the old
computer onto the new one.
</P>
<P>
   Somebody sent me a gizmo to back up a computer using a VCR. I
haul it out and hook it up. It's complicated, and I think, although
I'm not sure, that I've got the right cables. Unless the VCR is
hooked to a television set, you can't tell what's going on.
</P>
<P>
   Nonetheless, I set out to back up about 500 megs of files. It's
slow, folks. Takes all evening. At 1 a.m., I rewind and attempt a
playback. Nothing there. Wrong cables, I guess. One entire evening
shot.
</P>
<P>
   The next evening I decide to try another approach. From a dusty
corner of the bookcase, I haul an old copy of LapLink and install
it. The program promptly announces it's too old for this version of
Windows 95 and probably won't run right.
</P>
<P>
   It's right, it won't. But it seems to run fine in DOS. So I hook
the two computers up with the parallel cable provided and start
transferring. It's fast, and things go well. Another evening down
the drain, but with good results.
</P>
<P>
   The next evening, it's time to prepare my old computer to begin
the trickle-down process to my wife. Format the drives, reinstall
Windows 95, shove her current computer to one side of her desk, set
my old one up on the other side and repeat the previous evening.
</P>
<P>
   All of this is punctured by various alarms over whether she can
find the disks to reinstall this program or that program, whether
all of these files or those files have been successfully
transferred, and so forth. There is much gnashing of teeth and
pulling of hair.
</P>
<P>
   The next step is to wipe clean both of the fixed disks on her
old computer and prepare them for the trickle-down to my daughter,
and I suppose I'll have to prepare my daughter's current computer
to trickle down to my granddaughters.
</P>
<P>
   In the cobbler's house, you see, everyone wears shoes, but since
the cobbler is an expert on shoes, no one else need even bother to
learn how to tie their laces.
</P>
<P>
   All right, enough with the whining. I'm sure you all want to
know just how wonderful my new 400-MHz Gateway is.
</P>
<P>
   Well, it's certainly very nice, but for those of us whose
demands are not great, I believe we have reached the outer limits
of performance.
</P>
<P>
   My old computer was a 200-MHz machine. The new one seems a
little faster on the Internet, but in running the programs I
normally use -- Microsoft Word, for instance -- there's scarcely a
difference.
</P>
<P>
   So if you are thinking of buying a new computer, and your needs
are not that great, I wouldn't spring for 400 MHz. I'd think along
the lines of 300, no more. Get 64 megs of RAM -- that'll probably
help more than extra processing speed.
</P>
<P>
   But really, I've hardly gotten to use the thing. I haven't run
any games on it. I haven't put any of the DVD stuff in the DVD
drive, chiefly because none of it interests me, but I will.
</P>
<P>
   Stay tuned, and feel my pain.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
