   INTERWEB _Four years ago they were five young friends crowded
into a mid-town studio apartment, dreaming up big ideas for a
company that would capitalize on the hot new technology of the day:
the Internet. Early this month, their fledgling company, Interweb,
was bought by a New York firm in a deal worth about $11 million in
stock. (Williams, Atlanta Journal-Constitution) ETA 8 p.m. ET.
</P>
<P>
   HOLSENDOLF-COLUMN _ ATLANTA _ Last week BellSouth finally
unveiled what it had in mind: a digital update of the old service
that has now leapfrogged what most cable customers get. Up to 160
channels of entertainment, nearly a third in pay-per-view channels.
Unlike satellite broadcasting, another cable rival, the new
wireless can offer local channels as well as the full array of
cable offerings. (Holsendolf, Atlanta Journal-Constitution) MOVED.
</P>
<P>
   UNINSURED _ ATLANTA _ An estimated 1.3 million Georgians, or 20
percent of residents under age 65, have no health insurance.
Nationally, the estimate is 41 million. Some remedies are coming.
Coverage is being extended to thousands of children in Georgia --
and millions nationally -- through a new federal-state initiative.
(Miller, Atlanta Journal-Constitution) MOVED.
</P>
<P>
   MOTOROLA _ AUSTIN, Texas _ Motorola Inc. gave preliminary
details about a voluntary severance package to employees recently,
the first step in slashing 15,000 jobs, or 10 percent of its
workforce. Motorola will make the severance package available to
employees whose age and years of experience at the company add up
to 75. Employees who opt to receive the package will receive a
week's pay for every year of service and other benefits depending
on their length of service. (Gallaga, Austin American-Statesman)
MOVED.
</P>
<P>
   SAMSUNG _ Samsung Electronics, the world's largest maker of
memory chips, said recently it was stopping production in its
factories for a week to combat a worldwide glut in memory chips
that have dropped prices on the products. (Gallaga, Austin
American-Statesman) MOVED.
</P>
<P>
   CYBERSCENE _ ATLANTA _ The Internet is truly a wonderful and
mysterious place. Besides offering information on how to do
anything from bake a cake to get rid of fleas, it's also the
world's biggest source of both free and inexpensive computer
programs. (Husted, Atlanta Journal-Constitution) MOVED.
</P>
<P>
   MACNEWS _ ATLANTA _ A program called Consultant is the best new
personal information manager to hit the Mac market in years -- and
it's a heck of a good deal, too. For about $50, you get a calendar
and electronic card file largely the equal of programs costing
twice as much. And, in some cases, it's easier to use and more
attractive. (Haddad, Atlanta Journal-Constitution) MOVED.
</P>
<P>
   JUSTFORFUN _ ATLANTA _ Canon's Digital Printer CD-200, which
ships next month, claims to be the industry's first color printer
to accept and print images directly from a digital camera's Compact
Flash card. (Davis, Atlanta Journal-Constitution) MOVED.
</P>
