<HEADER>
A1435 &Cx1f; taf-z
u f &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-CLOTHIERS-SUIT-ART-85     06-09 1137
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CLOTHIERS-SUIT-ART-850&AMP;ADD-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
RETAILER OF KNOCKOFFS SUES RIVAL OVER COPYRIGHT
</HEADLINE>
  
(ATTN.: Ohio, N.Y.)  (ART ADV: Photo is being sent to NYT photo clients.
Non-subscribers can make individual purchase by calling
212-556-4204.) 
(ja) 
 By JENNIFER STEINHAUER    
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   When a Paris court ordered Ralph Lauren to stop selling
knockoffs of Yves Saint Laurent's tuxedo dresses in 1994, the
message was clear: Fashion, at least in France, can be subject to
protection from the scheming scissors of competitors. But here in
the United States, should a simple blue-and-white-striped shirt
enjoy similar sanctuary?
</P>
<P>
   That is what a federal judge in Columbus, Ohio, will have to
decide when he considers a lawsuit filed by Abercrombie &AMP; Fitch,
the clothing store, against its competitor down the mall, American
Eagle Outfitters.
</P>
<P>
   In its suit, filed on June 2, Abercrombie &AMP; Fitch complained
that American Eagle had engaged in a ``deliberate and intentional
pattern of copying the Abercrombie brand.''
</P>
<P>
   Among its examples, Abercrombie said American Eagle's use of the
letters ``AE'' on baseball caps was a direct knockoff of the ``AF''
letters that decorate Abercrombie's hats. It also cited the use of
the word ``performance'' on labels and advertising and the use of
the words ``outdoors'' and ``authentic.'' American Eagle has turned
out copycat versions of everything from Abercrombie's crew shirts
to its striped blouses to T-shirts, the suit argues, and sells them
in a way intended to confuse buyers about who made them.
</P>
<P>
   The paradox in all this, many retail analysts say, is that
Abercrombie &AMP; Fitch itself has thrived by offering a middle-class
knockoff of the collection of preppy duds designed by higher-end
companies like Polo Ralph Lauren. And just about every mall store
has aped preppy looks at some point.
</P>
<P>
   ``We are dealing with basic merchandise here,'' said Dorothy
Lakner, a retail analyst at CIBC Oppenheimer in New York. ``We see
the same things from American Eagle, Abercrombie, and we would
throw in the Gap while we are at it. And Ralph Lauren is the
epitome of classic looks and merchandise. No one company has a lock
on it.''
</P>
<P>
   Abercrombie doesn't see it that way. In its suit, the retailer,
which was recently spun off by the Limited, claims a proprietary
right over color combinations of red, blue, gray and tan and
striped designs. It also contends that American Eagle has knocked
off its fake college sweatshirts favored by crew teams.
</P>
<P>
   But unlike, say, a Louis Vuitton handbag, most Americans, retail
experts say, would be hard pressed to look at the blue-and-white
striped shirt cited in the exhibits to the lawsuit and immediately
proclaim its designer. And Abercrombie sweatshirts that depict a
pair of lacrosse sticks seem to be little more than brand-name
versions of what is sold in college bookstores.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is taking something from the public domain and claiming
trademark rights on them,'' said Kim Landsman, an intellectual
property lawyer for Patterson, Belknap, Webb &AMP; Tyler in New York.
``It is like Harvard doing a crew shirt and Yale imitating it and
then Cornell imitating it, and Yale sues Cornell.''
</P>
<P>
   Without doubt, American Eagle's latest retailing strategy has
worked. Its sales and the price of its stock have taken off in the
last year as the company, which has 326 stores, has captured the
attention of less affluent young people than Abercrombie's target
shopper with its cheaper take on casual clothes. Net income, which
fell to $5.9 million in 1996 from $7.1 million the year before,
rose to $19 million last year. As a result, a stock price that was
a mere $3 at the beginning of 1997 closed Tuesday at $33.875, down
$1.125.
</P>
<P>
   Abercrombie, with 159 stores and net income of $24.6 million
last year, has been a hot retail stock; Tuesday its shares closed
at $44.4375, up 6.25 cents. American Eagle executives say they were
selling several clothing styles before Abercrombie, and they deny
that they copy the retail chain. ``It's a frivolous suit,'' said
George Kolber, American Eagle's chief operating officer. ``We have
been in this business for 20 years, at which time they were selling
pool tables and pens. So who is copying who?''
</P>
<P>
   American Eagle, which was founded in 1977 and went public in
1994, had been floundering, offering looks that were too young and
edgy for its traditional 20-something shopper who also bought
clothes at Gap and J.C. Penney.
</P>
<P>
   In 1996, American Eagle hit an all-time low after a terrible
Christmas. The company regrouped and decided to return to its
outdoorsy, casual looks. ``We went for key items,'' said Laura
Weil, chief financial officer at American Eagle. ``Graphic
T-shirts, which we have been doing for years. We have been trying
to build a brand for years.''
</P>
<P>
   American Eagle's use of its own name, initials and other words
on its clothes has become more prevalent in recent years, Ms. Weil
acknowledged. And there is little debate that American Eagle's
merchandise and advertising look very similar to those used by
Abercrombie.
</P>
<P>
   ``The Supreme Court has said that inherently distinctive
elements are protectable,'' said Landsman, the lawyer. ``But they
have left it to the lower courts to figure out exactly what that
means. And what gives Abercrombie a possibility of claiming
trademark rights is that it is a combination of elements and not
just one item.''
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   Indeed, knockoffs are a nightmare for almost every design house.
Plenty of companies make their living by taking furious notes from
Paris and New York runway shows and producing much cheaper versions
for mass consumption. Gianni Versace lamented it openly and often
to retailers like Bloomingdale's.
</P>
<P>
   But only in rare cases do designers or apparel companies take
their complaints to court. Tahari Ltd., a line of career clothes,
sued Donna Ricco Inc., a dress manufacturer, in 1995, accusing it
of trademark infringement and unfair competition. The case was
settled out of court.
</P>
<P>
   That is why the Abercrombie case is likely to be closely watched
by lawyers and all types of retailers. The neon-colored Taco Cabana
restaurant chain, for instance, succeeded in stopping another
Mexican restaurant from using its color and design motif, setting
the stage for contemplation in the courts about what exactly is a
protected use of a color, shape or marketing campaign. But the
challenge is determining where that distinction begins and where
the fair use of something in the public domain _ a crew shirt or
the look of a baseball cap _ends.
</P>
<P>
   ``Being very pro intellectual property is seen as protecting
art,'' Landsman said. ``But the public domain is important to art,
and it is important to commerce.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-06-09-98 1838EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
