<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-06-09 18:38 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A1437 &Cx1f; ttg-z
u k &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-GRIMES-HUMOR-COLUMN-$     06-09 0612
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-GRIMES-HUMOR-COLUMN-$ADV10-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
DON'T LET BUG SPRAY BUG YOU 
</HEADLINE>
  (For release Wednesday, June 10) 
 By DAVID GRIMES    
 Sarasota (Fla.) Herald-Tribune    
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   Like many Manatee County residents, I am worried about this
malathion thing.
</P>
<P>
   Agriculture officials are considering spraying the insecticide
over parts of west Bradenton to kill the few remaining
Mediterranean fruit flies that have not already succumbed to media
hype.
</P>
<P>
   The government says the spray is perfectly safe, as if it were
planning to spray our neighborhoods with a fine mist of Diet Coke.
The trouble is, many of us _ myself included _ know malathion as an
evil-smelling chemical that is sold in lawn and garden stores in
brown plastic bottles with the word WARNING! repeated over and over
in the directions.
</P>
<P>
   It requires homeowners to suit up in goggles, a breathing mask
and a long-sleeved shirt so as to avoid having this perfectly safe
substance come in contact with our skin or any other parts of our
body that we wish to remain functional.
</P>
<P>
   Clearly, malathion has a huge image problem that the government
needs to correct if it is to win public support for its spraying
program. First off, the government should probably stop advertising
malathion as the insecticide equivalent of Diet Coke. Some people
don't like Coke, diet or otherwise, and the thought of a cloud of
the stuff swirling through their doors and windows is not likely to
change their minds.
</P>
<P>
   Teen-agers might appreciate malathion more if it were compared
to Mountain Dew, while the baby boomers might be swayed by a
comparison to bottled water or herbal tea.
</P>
<P>
   The government might want to take this one step further and hint
that malathion is not only safe, it has many therapeutic side
effects.
</P>
<P>
   Who would not support an aerial spraying program that promised
whiter teeth and clearer skin, not to mention dissolving those
unsightly hand warts? Prolonged exposure to high concentrations of
malathion can help you lose lots of weight fast and also halts the
aging process in the sense that you cease to get any older.
</P>
<P>
   People with breathing disorders may find that their condition
improves with deep inhalation of malathion mist. Clogged or
constricted airways are reamed cleaner than if you had snorted a
handful of Drano.
</P>
<P>
   Speaking of Drano, how many people know that malathion makes an
excellent dessert topping? Not many, I bet.
</P>
<P>
   The beneficial qualities of malathion need not be limited to
humans. Since it works so well at killing Medflies, who's to say
that malathion would not be equally effective at eroding those
baked-on wads of love-bug carcasses cemented to the grill and
windshield of your car? Residents of West Bradenton could also be
advised to take their good silverware outside on spraying days as
malathion makes an excellent tarnish remover.
</P>
<P>
   Everybody seems to be suffering from stress nowadays, so it
might be a good idea to promote the tension-relieving qualities of
malathion. A mere five minutes a day of good, deep inhalation
relaxes the back and neck muscles as if you were being kneaded and
pounded by a gorgeous Swedish massage therapist, gender of your
choice.
</P>
<P>
   Speaking of gorgeous Swedish massage therapists, the government
might want to start the rumor that the malathion spray they plan to
use contains 20 percent Viagra that can be absorbed directly
through the skin.
</P>
<P>
   Even if the claim is false, the sight of thousands of West
Bradentonites running naked around their back yards might be enough
to scare the Medflies to death.
</P>
<P>
   (David Grimes is a columnist for the Sarasota (Fla.)
Herald-Tribune.)
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
