<HEADER>
A1440 &Cx1f; ttx-z
r e &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-YOAKAM-CDREVIEW-TEX     06-09 0697
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-YOAKAM-CDREVIEW-TEX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
DWIGHT YOAKAM FINDS HIS WAY `HOME'
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By SHIRLEY JINKINS 
c.1998 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   The prodigal plowboy is back.
</P>
<P>
   Dwight Yoakam's new album, ``A Long Way Home,'' is his first
collection of all-new material in three years, and it signals his
return from an eclectic musical pilgrimage that had him mimicking
Sinatra and offering up suicidal Christmas carols.
</P>
<P>
   Best of all, ``A Long Way Home'' is his first album (out of 11
on Reprise dating back to 1986) that includes only self-penned
tunes.
</P>
<P>
   Dwight succeeds here where other, like-minded innovators have
inexplicably failed: He has drawn himself back from the jagged
cliffs of lofty experimentation to the rock-solid music that is his
domain. His forays into acting (''Slingblade,'' ``The Newton
Boys'') have not diluted the innovation he brings to his music.
</P>
<P>
   Early on, we're reassured that this is really our hangdog,
hip-swaying Bakersfield bard, delivering spirited country music
once again with his deliciously self-affected whine.
</P>
<P>
   ``Same Fool'' leads off with an infectious dance beat, echoed by
another cut on down the playlist, ``I Wouldn't Put It Past Me.''
</P>
<P>
   The album's first single is ``Things Change,'' one of Dwight's
patented mysteries, a voyeuristic glimpse into a crumbling affair.
Lyrically, we know little of what went on before this freeze-frame
scene, only that it's much different now. A guitar throbs as the
scene plays out.
</P>
<P>
   Among the most stylistically interesting songs is ``The Curse,''
which is just that: ``Don't have happy thoughts for a while, don't
you even smile,'' Dwight warns an errant girlfriend, ``These are
the things I wish for you.''
</P>
<P>
   Another is a '50s-style country-pop radio ballad ``Yet to
Succeed,'' complete with staggered, rounded phrasing, and a full
string background with occasional steel guitar stabs. A quivering
bass solo hangs in front of the listener like a mirage on an arid
desert highway.
</P>
<P>
   Along about cut No. 6, ``A Long Way Home'' begins to exhibit its
only flaw _ a midpoint sameness like a stretch of straight road
between two mountain ranges. ``These Arms,'' ``That's Okay'' and
``Only Want You More'' are more variations on a honky-tonk theme,
but they actually serve as filler for meatier stuff toward the end
of the CD.
</P>
<P>
   Dwight's most earnest, least-affected vocal delivery of the
project is ``I'll Just Take These,'' a lovely ballad with the
clarity of a clear summer evening. A fiddle accompanies Dwight's
sorrowful tone, the antithesis of his trademark disaffection.
</P>
<P>
   Want irony? The sultry cowboy has always been a champ at that.
``Listen'' would seem to be a quiet plea for understanding from an
agitated lover, but no, the placating lyrics are delivered
full-throated. He's trying to be heard, he says, ``over the sound
of your fear.''
</P>
<P>
   The last two cuts, when paired, are crazily eclectic in that
quirky Dwight way.
</P>
<P>
   ``Traveler's Lantern'' is an old-time mountain ballad,
definitely Dwight digging back to his Appalachian roots with banjo
and fiddle accompaniment.
</P>
<P>
   Then, the album closer is, of all things, an Elvis sendup.
``Just somethin' I worked up,'' Dwight drawls before all the
hippy-shake stuff starts. ``M-m-maybe you like it, m-m-maybe you
don't.''
</P>
<P>
   We like it.
</P>
<P>
   _
</P>
<P>
   Rating: 4 stars.
</P>
<P>
   _
</P>
<P>
   Benefiting the homeless
</P>
<P>
   Dwight fans also should check out a new CD on his producer Pete
Anderson's own label, Little Dog Records: ``Will Sing for Food: The
Songs of Dwight Yoakam.''
</P>
<P>
   It's a charity offering to benefit the homeless, and it includes
14 cuts of Yoakam's greatest tunes (donated without royalties by
Yoakam) done by a distinguished and eclectic bunch of artists, none
of them superstars.
</P>
<P>
   Best cuts include David Ball's ``This Time,'' Reckless Kelly's
``Please Please Baby,'' Sara Evans' ``The Distance Between You &AMP;
Me'' and Rhonda Vincent's ``I Sang Dixie.'' And the Gillian
Welch-David Rawlings turn on ``Miner's Prayer'' is memorable.
</P>
<P>
   (Shirley Jinkins covers country music for the Fort Worth
Star-Telegram. Visit the Star-Telegram's online services on the
World Wide Web: www.star-telegram.com)
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
