u i &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-KOSOVO-YELTSIN-NYT &LR;      06-09 0791
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-KOSOVO-YELTSIN-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
YELTSIN VOWS TO LAUNCH DIPLOMATIC EFFORT TO END VIOLENCE IN
KOSOVO 
</HEADLINE>
  (th) 
 By ALAN COWELL    
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   BONN, Germany _ Russian President Boris Yeltsin, seeking to
forestall a NATO military incursion in the Serbian province of
Kosovo, promised on Tuesday to undertake a personal diplomatic
effort with the Serbian leadership in an effort to defuse the
violence there.
</P>
<P>
   Speaking after a day of talks with German Chancellor Helmut
Kohl, Yeltsin said NATO action would ``destabilize the situation in
the Balkans with unforeseeable consequences for all of Europe.''
</P>
<P>
   At the same time, German officials seem increasingly inclined
toward charting a military course to stop the violence in Kosovo,
where Slobodan Milosevic, the Yugoslav president, has cracked down
on an independence movement in the province, pitting government
forces against ethnic Albanian rebels.
</P>
<P>
   ``The more delicately we proceed, the greater are our chances
for a settlement of the conflict,'' Yeltsin said. It was not clear
when his effort would take place or exactly how it would be carried
out.
</P>
<P>
   NATO defense ministers are to meet in Brussels on Thursday to
discuss the fighting in Kosovo, which has inspired deep concerns
here about the likelihood of waves of refugees flooding Western
Europe. Germany took in hundreds of thousands who fled during and
after the Bosnian war and makes no secret of its aversion to
providing shelter for more Balkan refugees.
</P>
<P>
   The ``contact group'' on the Balkans _ the United States,
Britain, Germany, Italy, France and Russia _ is to meet at the
foreign ministers' level in London on Friday, along with Japan and
Canada, to discuss Kosovo.
</P>
<P>
   Volker Ruehe, the German defense minister, said on Tuesday that
it was crucial for the NATO ministers to examine military plans to
augment economic and political pressures on Milosevic.
</P>
<P>
   For his part, Kohl said at a joint news conference with Yeltsin
that Germany _ Russia's biggest trading partner and creditor _
would offer ``decisive support'' for Moscow as it seeks to contain
an economic crisis and pursues economic reform.
</P>
<P>
   ``These measures contribute significantly to increasing the
confidence of foreign investors,'' the chancellor said.
</P>
<P>
   Both German and Russian officials ruled out any further
injection of German money, saying Kohl's backing for Moscow's
reform measures was enough. ``Chancellor Kohl's personal support,
as a major international political figure, is important to
demonstrate that our policies are correct,'' Yeltsin said.
</P>
<P>
   Germany is Russia's closest European political ally, and Bonn's
backing is seen as important as Moscow seeks financial support from
the International Monetary Fund. Additionally, Kohl likes to depict
Yeltsin as a personal friend, seeking to base his diplomacy on a
network of personal relationships typified by his longstanding
friendship with Francois Mitterrand, the late French president, and
by the special friendship he has declared with President Clinton.
</P>
<P>
   Because of the personal relationships, though, it is often
difficult to disentangle diplomacy from domestic politics.
</P>
<P>
   Kohl, in particular, faces the nettlesome problem of trying to
win an unparalleled fifth term of office in elections in September.
</P>
<P>
   On Tuesday, his Social Democratic electoral opponents
resurrected the criticisms they lodged when Kohl met with Clinton
last month, accusing the chancellor of stage-managing media
coverage, in this case by barring television cameras from a
breakfast Tuesday with Yeltsin and Gerhard Schroeder, Kohl's
opposition challenger, who ranks in opinion surveys as Germany's
most popular politician.
</P>
<P>
   Government officials denied orchestrating the blackout, saying
Russian officials insisted on it to avoid becoming ensnared in
Germany's domestic politics.
</P>
<P>
   Nonetheless, Kohl ruled the sound bites with Yeltsin, reflecting
his campaign strategy of building voter support on his reputation
as a statesman _ not only as Europe's longest-serving leader, but
also as the key European interlocutor for the men he likes to call
``my friend Bill'' and ``dear Boris.'' Since the election campaign
has begun, Kohl seems to have let it be known that he sees
friendship as a two-way street.
</P>
<P>
   While not quite so effusive as Clinton was, Yeltsin referred on
Tuesday to the German leader's international stature in remarks
that seemed intended to feed into the campaign.
</P>
<P>
   Kohl and his Christian Democrats, in office for almost 16 years,
lag behind the Social Democrats in opinion surveys. But in recent
days, Kohl has received some heartening news suggesting that the
vote on Sept. 27 will be closer than was assumed a few weeks ago. &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
