<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-SANDIEGO-1000(2Takes)-TEX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
SAN DIEGO IS ALMOST TOO GOOD TO BE TRUE
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By RICH HADDAWAY 
c.1998 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   SAN DIEGO _ Everything was so new, so clean, so easy, it made me
a little nervous.
</P>
<P>
   Is this a real place? I wondered as we stepped into the
refurbished airport, slipped across the skybridge to our car-rental
bus and were whisked away to pick up our shiny little Chevy, all
within minutes.
</P>
<P>
   I really began to wonder after we hit the road. The palm trees
along freshly paved Harbor Drive were so new they looked rented.
More landscaping was going in, still perky from its pots. Traffic
was silky. The road curved along the bay, where unbarnacled boats
bobbed in the pale green water.
</P>
<P>
   ``No,'' I was thinking. ``This couldn't be real. We've landed in
the middle of a giant amusement park. That car-rental guy was
actually a ticket-taker, and now I'm on a ride through a new
megapark called SandiWorld. I'm actually not driving this car; it's
being guided by electrical currents beneath the fake asphalt.
Right?''
</P>
<P>
   Show me a homeless guy sprawled out under one of those palm
trees. Show me somebody pierced. Then I'll believe that San Diego
is a real city.
</P>
<P>
   Soon we were ensconced in our high-rise room at the thoroughly
modern Hyatt (the airport is in the middle of town, making
everything suspiciously convenient). At the hotel, everything was
perfect, extra pillows and all.
</P>
<P>
   We took a stroll next door, through an area called Seaport
Village. About 50 cute little quonset-hut-shaped shops, with names
like The Seasick Giraffe, specialize in such things as refrigerator
magnets, shoes, beachwear, shells, rocks and lots and lots of craft
collections. Is somebody going to stamp my hand so I can come back
tomorrow?
</P>
<P>
   Eventually the dream dispersed, but it took awhile. Surely San
Diego was a real place, I thought. With 2.1 million people, there
were bound to be a few misfits; they just weren't ganged up where
visitors could see them easily.
</P>
<P>
   That's because San Diego has remade itself for tourists,
especially families. With Disney-like determination, it has cleaned
up its harbor, brought in hotels, refashioned a historic area
called the Gaslamp Quarter and made it all easily accessible.
</P>
<P>
   All that work has made tourism the No. 3 industry in San Diego.
This city tries harder, if not a little too hard.
</P>
<P>
   _
</P>
<P>
   Three things put a city high on a family's must-visit list: 1)
It's clean and safe; 2) it's easy to get to and get around in; 3)
it's got something worth seeing.
</P>
<P>
   San Diego's tourist areas are as clean as a corporate whistle,
and safety was never a problem on our visit. Getting around was a
snap. And with only three days, we too soon ran out of time to hit
just the high points.
</P>
<P>
   It would be easy to do central San Diego without a car, but with
a family I wouldn't recommend it.
</P>
<P>
   You can leave the car in the hotel lot for days at a time,
though, if you use the Old Town Trolley. It's a bus system for
tourists. You can get on at any stop, hop off when you want, then
get back on and keep going around. The city's top tourist spots are
on the loop.
</P>
<P>
   Of course you'll have to put up with the jaunty banter and limp
jokes of the tour guide/drivers.
</P>
<P>
   We went across the bay bridge to Coronado Island for a peek at
the Pacific and a look at that Victorian hodgepodge of turrets and
cupolas called the Hotel del Coronado. Said our tour guide, Big Al
Your Pal: ``The hotel has had a lot of famous guests. In fact,
Orville Redenbacher would pop up here occasionally.''
</P>
<P>
   The whole tour is about two hours, but I doubt that you could
handle that much banter all at once. You'll want to get off and
look around. We hopped off at the zoo.
</P>
<P>
   What puts the world-class San Diego Zoo a cut above are the
natural settings of the exhibits: a rain-forest feel in one area,
desert in another. Most of the cages are minimalist. There's a
sense of freedom for the animals.
</P>
<P>
   We took a zoo tour on the double-decker bus _ the place is that
big. Then we doubled back to linger at the spots that interested
us. Eat your Wheaties. There are lots of hills and dales. And
you'll pay a lot for those Wheaties. A cheeseburger, fries and
large lemonade came to $9.37.
</P>
<P>
   Other trolley stops include Balboa Park, where the museums and
gardens are concentrated, and the historic area of Old Town, with
its Spanish heritage.
</P>
<P>
   Get another great overview of San Diego by taking a boat trip in
the harbor. The guide with Harbor Excursions was knowledgeable,
especially about all the naval ships docked on both sides of the
water, and didn't try so hard with the jokes. One of the aircraft
carriers we passed was the USS Taraway. It's twice as long as the
tallest building in San Diego, which is the Hyatt, at 40 stories.
</P>
<P>
   _
</P>
<P>
   We began to break free of the well-traveled tourist routes by
our second day. Gaslamp Quarter is what New York City's Times
Square will be in a few more years, I suppose _ most of the sin has
been washed away.
</P>
<P>
   It's a refurbished section of Victorian houses and businesses
near downtown; serious restaurants, boutiques and art galleries
have moved in. The tattoo parlors are on their way out.
</P>
<P>
   The rain came down that night. A thick, permeating drizzle grew
into real rain, then backed off into mist. It was a refreshing
touch of imperfection. Uncle Walt would have never permitted such a
thing.
</P>
<P>
   The weather improved the next day. We drove north up the coast;
here, the towns of northern San Diego County hug the sea-foaming
hills. It's a southern version of the Oregon coast.
</P>
<P>
   One of the first points north is Cabrillo National Monument, a
tribute to the Portuguese discoverer of the area. A lighthouse sits
on a promontory, a most glorious view with the bay on one side and
the ocean on the other. They say the whales can be seen from here.
</P>
<P>
   MORE
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
