<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-EARLY-FRONTPAGE-NYT </SLUG>
  
<TEXT>
<P>
   (pr) &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Here are the stories New York Times editors are planning for
Page 1, Wednesday, June 10. The NYT frontpage advisory, with layout
description, will move by 7:30 p.m. ET. The NYT News Service Night
Supervisor is Pat Ryan (212-556-1927).
</P>
<P>
   NIGERIA (Freetown, Sierra Leone) _ Less than 24 hours after the
death of the Nigerian dictator, Gen. Sani Abacha, the country's new
military leadership has signaled its intention to turn over power
to an elected civilian regime within four months, respecting a
previously established timetable. By Howard W. French. With
graphic.
</P>
<P>
   KOSOVO-U.S.-ASSESS (Washington) _ News analysis: While the
Europeans and the United States belatedly apply some economic
sanctions on Yugoslav President Slobodan Milosevic, officials say
there is little agreement about how to achieve a peaceful end. By
Steven Erlanger.
</P>
<P>
   MEDICARE-BENEFITS (Washington) _ Examining changes that will be
coming soon in the Medicare program and how the program's elderly
beneficiaries are going to cope with them. By Robert Pear.
</P>
<P>
   BAPTISTS (Salt Lake City) _ The Southern Baptist Convention, the
nation's largest Protestant denomination and an increasingly
conservative force among American religious organizations, are
expected to pass an addition to their creed that says that God
expects a woman to ``submit graciously'' to her husband's
leadership, and for a husband to ``provide for, to protect and to
lead his family.'' By Gustav Niebuhr. With photo.
</P>
<P>
   SIGNING-BONUSES (Undated) _ The sign-on bonus is proliferating
in America as employers, forced to bid for scarce workers, have
shifted some of the bargaining process from wages to less costly
one-time bonus payments. A recruiting tool that had been limited to
upper-level managers, highly skilled technicians and athletes is
spreading to many others. By Louis Uchitelle. 1,600 words.
</P>
<P>
   DIET-SUPPLEMENTS-HEALTH (Farmington, Utah) _ Here in the heart
of the nation's herbal and vitamin industry, a company called
Pharmanex produces 600 milligram capsules of a pulverized strain of
rice that appears to lower cholesterol. McGlashan calls Cholestin a
dietary supplement. Officials at the FDA call it something else: an
illegal, unapproved drug. On June 15, in Salt Lake City, a federal
judge will be asked to determine who is correct. The case is being
watched as a pivotal battle between the food and drug agency, which
is chafing against a 1994 law that left it almost powerless to
regulate vitamins and herbal products, and the dietary supplement
industry, which has been growing wildly since the law was passed.
By Sheryl Gay Stolberg.
</P>
<P>
   INDONESIA-CHINESE (Jakarta, Indonesia) _ In addition to looting
and arson that targeted Chinese neighborhoods in three days of
rioting last month, human rights and women's aid groups have begun
to document what they say appears to have been an organized
campaign of assaults, gang rapes and killings of ethnic Chinese
women. By Seth Mydans.
</P>
<P>
   Reefers:
</P>
<P>
   TOBACCO-CONGRESS (Washington) _ The Senate votes on whether to
cut off debate and bring the tobacco bill to a vote. By David E.
Rosenbaum.
</P>
<P>
   RUSSIA-CORRUPTION (Moscow) _ Russia's top official for economic
statistics was arrested Tuesday and accused of manipulating the
nation's financial data to help Russian companies avoid taxes. By
Michael R. Gordon.
</P>
<P>
   KOREA-U.S. (Washington) _ President Clinton meets with Kim Dae
Jung, the long-time dissident and now president of South Korea. By
John M. Broder.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
