<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-06-09 18:53 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A1466 &Cx1f; ttj-z
u w &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-CLINTON-SOUTHKOREA-HN     06-09 0904
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CLINTON-SOUTHKOREA-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
`NOTHING TO FEAR' FROM N. KOREA, S. KOREAN LEADER DECLARES 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By DAN FREEDMAN  
 c.1998 Hearst Newspapers  
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ President Clinton and South Korean President Kim
Dae-jung agreed Tuesday to a gradual, tit-for-tat approach on
improving relations with North Korea, with Kim boldly declaring:
``We have nothing to fear from North Korea.''
</P>
<P>
   At a joint news conference concluding a day of talks in the Oval
Office, Clinton said Kim did not ask him to lift sanctions _ a
centerpiece of U.S. policy toward the hard-line communist state
since the Korean War ended in stalemate 45 years ago.
</P>
<P>
   Instead, Clinton said, Kim asked him to ``support a policy of
reciprocity which would enable us to move forward with the
reconciliation of the North and South. And I said that I would be
prepared to do that.''
</P>
<P>
   Kim, a one-time pro-democracy activist who was exiled by the
South's former military government, became president in February.
He said his government would use its military alliance with the
United States as the foundation for its effort to convince North
Korea ``to open up.''
</P>
<P>
   Kim added that he hoped to encourage ``moderate elements'' in
North Korea. Without directly calling for lifting sanctions, Kim
said that should Washington choose to do so, ``we would not oppose
and we would cooperate.''
</P>
<P>
   Neither president spelled out what new steps South Korea would
take to soften the high level of brinkmanship that has
characterized relations between the two Koreas since fighting
ceased in 1953.
</P>
<P>
   But Clinton pledged to fulfill U.S. commitments to provide North
Korea with fuel oil that it had promised as part of the 1994
nuclear freeze agreement.
</P>
<P>
   The agreement obligated North Korea to freeze its nuclear
weapons program in return for replacement of its
plutonium-producing nuclear weapons reactors with safer models
financed by South Korea, Japan and other donor countries. North
Korea has allowed inspections and appears to be complying with the
weapons freeze.
</P>
<P>
   Differences between the two presidents on how to handle North
Korea were more a matter of tone and emphasis. At the news
conference, Clinton suggested his hands were tied because lifting
most elements of the trade embargo would require legislative
action. That is unlikely to happen with Republicans controlling
Congress.
</P>
<P>
   Nevertheless, Clinton praised Kim for his ``bold vision'' of
improved relations between the two Koreas. ``I'm very hopeful.'' He
also cast South Korea as a model of moderation in Asia, contrasting
its aversion to nuclear armaments with the recent atomic tests
conducted by India and Pakistan.
</P>
<P>
   Kim focused on North Korea's faltering economy and lack of food,
a situation he termed ``very bad.'' The more desperate it gets, the
more likely North Korea will be tempted to wage war on the South
or, alternatively, collapse and ``fall into our lap.''
</P>
<P>
   So, he said, ``for peace, for stability ... we need to induce
North Korea to open up ... and we have to help it in doing so.''
</P>
<P>
   Still, Kim called the regime of North Korean dictator Kim Jong
Il ``relatively stable.''
</P>
<P>
   The South Korean president was on the fourth day of a nine-day
state visit to the United States. His primary focus is rescuing his
country's ailing economy, which had been the 11th largest in the
world before the current economic problems.
</P>
<P>
   Kim's U.S. schedule is built around his effort to boost economic
investment in South Korea. On Monday he visited the New York Stock
Exchange. On Wednesday he is scheduled to speak to the U.S. Chamber
of Commerce. Later this week he will tour of California's Silicon
Valley.
</P>
<P>
   On Tuesday night, Kim and his wife Lee Hee-ho were the guests of
honor at a White House state dinner.
</P>
<P>
   South Korea is muddling through its worst economic crisis since
the Korean War. Its life support is an emergency $57 million cash
infusion from the International Monetary Fund.
</P>
<P>
   Clinton called the downturn ``a bump in the road'' and said
emergency financing guarantees would be available if South Korea
needs it in the future. He said he had called on Commerce Secretary
William Daley to lead a special trade mission to South Korea, which
now is running an $8 billion trade deficit with the United States.
</P>
<P>
   For Kim, 74, the visit to Washington had a sentimental side as
well. After spending seven years in prison and narrowly escaping
assassination at the hands of South Korean police agents in the
late 1970s, Kim settled in Washington as an exile.
</P>
<P>
   Unable to gain access to the White House, he remained committed
to changing South Korea's dictatorial regime to a democratic one.
He returned to South Korea in 1985, built his opposition party, and
won the election in December.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS.) &QL; 
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
<P>
   His visit has energized much of the growing community of Korean
Americans. Supporters interrupted opening ceremonies at the White
House with shouts of Kim's name.
</P>
<P>
   ``I have never felt more proud to be a Korean-born American than
during this visit,'' said Bonnie B.C. Oh, a professor of Korean
studies at Georgetown University who will serve as translator
Wednesday when Kim receives an honorary degree there.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think his being elected president has (proven) that (South)
Korea's many years as a pseudo-democratic country have passed.''
</P>
</TEXT>
