<DATE_TIME> 1998-06-09 18:54 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A1467 &Cx1f; ttx-z
r t &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-SANDIEGO-2ndTake-TEX     06-09 1002
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-SANDIEGO-2ndTake-TEX </SLUG>
 
SAN DIEGO: seen from here. 
<TEXT>
<P>
   Mission Beach, with its boardwalk full of in-line skaters,
looked like fun. The next town up, Ocean Beach, known to the
natives as Hippie Hollow, has a grittier look, just the opposite of
its northern neighbor La Jolla, the Beverly Hills of San Diego
County.
</P>
<P>
   Bunches of boutiques and restaurants crowd the cliffs here. We
stopped at George's Cafe and Ocean Terrace for lunch, a top-notch
place with tables spread out under an awning and the ocean close
enough to spit into. Don't do that, though. They wouldn't approve.
</P>
<P>
   _
</P>
<P>
   Our long weekend ended with a fresh-faced dose of corporate
tourism and a clang of reality _ SeaWorld and Tijuana.
</P>
<P>
   Everything at SeaWorld is slick, scrubbed and well-rehearsed. We
caught the Shamu show, in which the great killer whale jumped for
hand-held treats like a circus dog through hoops. I felt
embarrassed for it.
</P>
<P>
   But the kids loved it.
</P>
<P>
   Tijuana is a jarringly different world.
</P>
<P>
   The border is only an hour south by car or trolley. We parked at
one of the many lots on the border and took the bus across, which
will take you to the center of town. Don't try to walk it. It's a
long way.
</P>
<P>
   Tijuana was an assault on the senses _ mostly from the barkers
in their trinket stalls along the main drag, Avenida Revolucion,
and from the dirt and the frying meat and the children with
street-stained feet.
</P>
<P>
   You can't walk anywhere without the accosting voices: ``The
price is right! Almost nothing, sir! Nine-nine percent off!''
</P>
<P>
   A few hours in Tijuana was enough. It made clean-cut,
almost-perfect, sometimes-cloying San Diego look good.
</P>
<P>
   _
</P>
<P>
   IF YOU GO
</P>
<P>
   General information: San Diego Convention &AMP; Visitors Bureau,
Dept. 700, 401 B St., Suite 1400, San Diego, CA 92101-4237; (619)
236-1212; www.sandiego.org.
</P>
<P>
   Good deal: Write to the above address or call to receive the
``Sunny Money 1998 San Diego Super Savings'' coupon book for
discounts on attractions and special rates on hotels. Allow three
weeks for delivery.
</P>
<P>
   The weather: If El Nino is gone, it ought to be smooth sailing;
60s in winter, 80s in summer, generally a dry desert air; not that
sticky stuff they have in Orlando.
</P>
<P>
   Getting around: Old Town Trolley, (619) 298-8687. Two-hour
narrated trips around central San Diego. Adults, $20; age 12 and
under, $8. Also, Harbor Excursion: one-hour tour, $12 adult, $10
seniors, $6 children. (619) 234-4111. San Diego Trolley to Tijuana:
$1.75 each way. (619) 233-3004.
</P>
<P>
   San Diego Zoo: Try the Morning Zoo Rise, in which sections of
the zoo open at 7:30 a.m. so you can see animals waking up, playing
and enjoying breakfast. Some might be cranky. Usually on good
behavior are giant pandas Shi Shi and Bai Yun. Adults, $15; ages
3-11, $6; kids 2 and under, free. (619) 231-1515. Dual tickets (for
use within five days) for the zoo and the Wild Animal Park are
$33.55 for an adult, $19.95 for ages 3-11.
</P>
<P>
   Balboa Park: Experience 12 museums for $21 with the Passport to
Balboa Park, valued at $62. Museum of Art, Aerospace Museum, Museum
of Man and others. (619) 239-0512.
</P>
<P>
   Wild Animal Park: Dino Mountain, an area of robot monsters with
ear-piercing roars. The more traditional Heart of Africa is a
30-acre walking safari featuring 260 animals in diverse habitats.
The entire park is 2,000 acres near the town of Escondido. Adults,
$21.95; ages 3-11, $14.95; 2 or younger, free. Parking $3. (619)
234-6541.
</P>
<P>
   SeaWorld: New exhibit features manatees in a fresh-water
environment. Adults $30.95; ages 3-11, $22.95; under 3, free.
Parking $5. (619) 226-3901.
</P>
<P>
   Birch Aquarium: Currently featuring grunion runs, in which
hundreds of little grunions _ silvery fish _ glitter in the
moonlight as high-tide waves wash them to and fro on the beach
during their nocturnal mating ritual. (619) 534-FISH; 2300
Expedition Way, La Jolla. Adults, $6.50; 60 and over, $5.50; ages
13-17, $4.50; ages 3-12, $3.50. Parking $5.
</P>
<P>
   Museum of Contemporary Art, La Jolla: The museum is an artwork
in itself, white and sleek and perched on the side of the sea. $4
adults, $2 ages 65 and over; also $2 for ages 12-18; free for ages
12 and under. (619) 454-3541.
</P>
<P>
   Cabrillo National Monument and Point Loma overlook: Offers views
of San Diego and Coronado Island. Open 9 a.m. to 5:15 p.m. daily.
Admission is $5 per vehicle or $2 per person. (619) 557-5450.
</P>
<P>
   Tijuana: U.S. citizens may pass freely across the border without
a passport, as long as they stay in Tijuana. However, you may be
required to show proof of citizenship on your return.
</P>
<P>
   On stage: San Diego Playgoers Series this summer include
``Riverdance, Grease!, Miss Saigon'' and ``Les Miserables.'' (619)
235-8025.
</P>
<P>
   Let's eat:
</P>
<P>
   Sally's, at the base of the Hyatt. Eurotech decor with exposed
pipes, and the Eurotech waitstaff wears black and slinks around. I
had the chicken kudasai, chicken with noodles and a Thai peanut
sauce. Next to it was a nest of white rice noodles fluffed up in a
big-hair tangle with little bushes of rosemary stems in it. Very
California. (619) 232-1234.
</P>
<P>
   Casa de Bandini, Old Town. California Mexican food is the
specialty here, with a strong influence of the sea, such as shrimp
and crab enchiladas ($12.99) in a delicate red sauce. Even the
mariachi band was a cut above. (619) 297-8211.
</P>
<P>
   Let's sleep: San Diego hotel reservations, featuring more than
200 hotels: (800) SAVE-CASH. Bed and breakfast directory, (619)
297-3130.
</P>
<P>
   San Diego Marriott, $170-$235. Next to the convention center.
(619) 234-1500.
</P>
<P>
   Hyatt Regency, $215-$275. Stunning views of the harbor. Consider
the Regency Club plan. For approximately $35 a night extra, you get
continental breakfast for two and afternoon snacks and cocktails.
(800) 233-1234.
</P>
<P>
   Hotel del Coronado, $145-$335, with prime oceanfront rooms going
for more than $500 a night. ``Some Like It Hot'' was filmed here.
(619) 522-8000.
</P>
<P>
   _
</P>
<P>
   (Visit the Star-Telegram's online services on the World Wide
Web: www.star-telegram.com)
</P>
</TEXT>
