<SLUG> BC-GERMANY-ECON-ART-NYT </SLUG>
  
 EMPLOYMENT RISES IN GERMANY IN RUN-UP TO ELECTION  (ART ADV:
Graphic is being sent to NYT graphic clients. Non-subscribers can
make individual purchase by calling 212-556-4204.) 
(ja) 
 By EDMUND L. ANDREWS   
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   FRANKFURT, Germany _ Three months before the most difficult
election of Chancellor Helmut Kohl's career, some economists say
that he is buying as many new jobs as the German government can
afford.
</P>
<P>
   The government reported on Tuesday that the number of unemployed
workers declined by 223,400 in May, one of the biggest monthly
reductions in years. Government leaders called the report evidence
of a turnaround in German joblessness, which edged down to 11.2
percent from 11.3 percent in April.
</P>
<P>
   Coming after reports last week that the nation's economy grew at
a surprisingly strong annual rate of 3.8 percent in the first three
months of this year, the new statistics are expected to help Kohl's
struggling campaign for re-election in September.
</P>
<P>
   But the economists said the new data probably demonstrated
something quite different: the effect of heavy new public spending
on job-creation programs. Officials have announced plans to pump as
much as $3 billion into these programs, reversing cuts made a year
ago.
</P>
<P>
   ``The government hopes to take credit for this turnaround, but
the turnaround is something that the government has itself
engineered,'' said Hans-Juergen Meltzer, a senior economist with
Deutsche Bank Research.
</P>
<P>
   German joblessness is by far the biggest threat to the
re-election of Kohl, the leader of a center-right coalition who has
been in office since 1982. In polls, the chancellor consistently
lags behind the Social Democratic Party's candidate, Gerhard
Schroeder.
</P>
<P>
   Government officials and political allies of Kohl have been
chafing to improve their political prospects with evidence of an
economic turnaround. Indeed, a rough summary of the new
unemployment data was leaked last week to Bild, the daily tabloid
with the biggest circulation in Germany. And Kohl touted the
numbers in a speech a few days ago.
</P>
<P>
   ``Germany is looking forward to its second economic miracle,''
asserted Bernd Protzner, general secretary of the Christian Social
Union, the Bavarian sister party to Kohl's center-right Christian
Democrats. Economics Minister Guenter Rexrodt said the data
vindicated the government's policies of stimulating industrial
investment.
</P>
<P>
   Economists say the picture is more complicated. While agreeing
that German growth has accelerated, primarily because of higher
exports, they said job creation has remained anemic. The big
difference between this year and last, they say, is in the money
going to job programs.
</P>
<P>
   Last year, the government sharply reduced such spending, as
Germany needed to reduce its budget deficit in order to meet the
fiscal requirements for taking part in the single European currency
to be introduced next January.
</P>
<P>
   Many economists estimate that last year's cutbacks added about
200,000 people to the unemployment rolls. All told, Germany lost
about 420,000 jobs in 1997 and its unemployment rate came close to
12 percent.
</P>
<P>
   Unemployment has declined in each of the last three months,
though the overall number of new jobs has changed very little.
</P>
<P>
   In releasing the latest statistics, government officials
acknowledged that most of the big decline in joblessness stemmed
from seasonal factors. Job growth always picks up after the winter,
and unusually warm weather this past winter accentuated the normal
effect.
</P>
<P>
   On a seasonally adjusted basis, the government said,
unemployment declined by 60,000, to 4.32 million people _ less
dramatic than the headline figure, but still more than most
economists had predicted.
</P>
<P>
   In western Germany, seasonally adjusted unemployment eased to
9.4 percent in May from 9.5 percent in April. In the formerly
Communist east, which remains in deep economic distress, the level
dropped to 18.7 percent in May from 19.1 percent in April. In the
most severely depressed eastern state of Saxony-Anhalt, where
Kohl's Christian Democrats were trounced in elections last month,
20.3 percent of workers remain unemployed.
</P>
<P>
   Jan Hatzius, a Goldman, Sachs economist here, said unemployment
had almost certainly peaked and should be heading slightly downward
even without new job programs.
</P>
<P>
   But, he said, the evidence points to the important role of
government job programs. Although the full story will not be clear
until later this year, when the government publishes statistics on
May employment, which show the number of people in job-training and
make-work programs, Hatzius said there has yet to be much evidence
of net job creation.
</P>
<P>
   ``Unemployment started falling in January, and it has more or
less kept falling ever since then,'' he said. ``But employment has
not increased, and the difference between those numbers is largely
the people in jobs programs.''
</P>
<P>
   German labor leaders accused Kohl of manipulating unemployment
for political gain. ``The government has obviously spared no effort
to use job-promotion programs as a campaign instrument,'' said
Ursula Engelen-Kefer, deputy chairman of the German Federation of
Unions.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
