<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-JUDGES-COURTS-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
JUDICIARY 

</HEADLINE>
  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 
POLITICIANS RESPOND TO DeLAY CRITICISM BY SUPPORTING UNHINDEREDBy STEVE LASH 
c.1998 Houston Chronicle 
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ Former Republican and Democratic politicians,
citing recent criticism of federal judges by Rep. Tom DeLay,
R-Texas, joined lawyers and legal scholars Tuesday in support of an
unhindered judiciary.
</P>
<P>
   DeLay's call for the impeachment of ``activist'' judges who
``violate the Constitution and their oath of office'' is part of a
widespread attack on the independence of the judiciary from both
liberals and conservatives, said former Rep. Mickey Edwards,
R-Okla. Edwards assailed DeLay's statements as a threat to all
judges, who he said should be duty-bound to look to the law and not
public opinion before issuing decisions.
</P>
<P>
   DeLay made his controversial statement before the House voted
overwhelmingly this spring to pass his proposal, now before the
Senate, to prohibit federal judges from ordering the early release
of convicted felons because of crowding or other unacceptable
conditions. DeLay spokesman Michael Scanlon, responding to Edwards'
comments, said the congressman has not attacked the independence of
the judiciary but merely reiterated the constitutional prerogative
of Congress to hold judges accountable for decisions that encroach
on legislative functions, such as controlling prison population.
</P>
<P>
   Edwards, with former Clinton White House Counsel Lloyd Cutler,
chairs Citizens for Independent Courts, an ad hoc group of about 85
political and legal luminaries that seeks to court public opinion
to preserve judicial independence and protect judges from political
intimidation. The bipartisan group unites the oratory of liberal
former New York Gov. Mario Cuomo and the salty tongue of
conservative former Sen. Alan Simpson, R-Wyo.
</P>
<P>
   Cuomo, citing the widespread public distaste for O.J. Simpson's
murder acquittal, said people must nevertheless resist the desire
to have judicial decisions made by popular vote rather than by due
process. Voicing his displeasure that ``the poll has become
prince,'' Cuomo added judges must feel free to ignore popular
opinion in deciding cases.
</P>
<P>
   The United States would be much worse off if courts felt
compelled to bend to what the majority wanted, said the former
Democratic governor.
</P>
<P>
   ``Would the Congress of the time have overruled Brown vs. Board
of Education?'' Cuomo asked, referring to the Supreme Court's
landmark 1954 decision outlawing racially segregated schools.
``Almost certainly.''
</P>
<P>
   Simpson said a judge's ruling, no matter how unpopular, should
not make that jurist a target for impeachment. The former senator
said conservatives and liberals are both to blame for trying to
intimidate judges, particularly when it comes to Senate
confirmation of nominees for the federal bench.
</P>
<P>
   ``There are groups that gear up, flare up, smoldering the
nominee between the eyes,'' said Simpson, a member of the Senate
Judiciary Committee that held the bruising confirmation hearings of
failed Supreme Court nominee Robert Bork in 1987 and Supreme Court
Justice Clarence Thomas in 1991.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't want to see anybody get `borked' again,'' said
Simpson, noting the intense public relations campaign against the
conservative Bork. ``I was there. They turned him into a
gargoyle.''
</P>
<P>
   Edwards, noting ``the line between fair comment and
intimidation,'' said his group does not want to blunt legitimate
criticism of judicial decisions. ``Judges have to be accountable,''
he said. ``Courts have to be accountable.''
</P>
<P>
   Cutler, Edwards' co-chairman, said public confidence in judicial
fairness will wane if judges feel compelled to base their decisions
on polling data rather than the law. ``The independence of the
courts is absolutely key'' to the justice system, said Cutler who
also served as White House counsel during Jimmy Carter's
presidency.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
XXXX END OF STORY &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
