u w &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-COURTS-INDEPENDENCE-H     06-09 0644
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-COURTS-INDEPENDENCE-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
NEW LEGAL GROUP CALLS FOR MORE INDEPENDENT JUDGES 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By MARK HELM  
 c.1998 Hearst Newspapers  
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ A bipartisan group of legal experts and
politicians, including former New York Gov. Mario Cuomo, called
Tuesday for an end to choosing judges on the basis of their
popularity and political beliefs.
</P>
<P>
   Cuomo, a Democrat, along with former Republican Sen. Alan
Simpson of Wyoming, announced the formation of Citizens for
Independent Courts (CIC). The group, whose 80 members include
former FBI directors and appellate judges as well as several law
school deans, promised to fight the common practice of electing
judges and to urge Congress to stop blocking judicial nominees
because of their political beliefs.
</P>
<P>
   ``The poll has become prince, and now we have a kind of
sanctification of popularity in this country,'' said Cuomo, who was
once mentioned as a possible Supreme Court nominee.
</P>
<P>
   He said elections force judges to pay more attention to public
opinion than the law when deciding cases.
</P>
<P>
   ``Can you imagine if the Supreme Court went along with public
opinion in the 1950s and ruled the other way on Brown vs. Board of
Education,'' he said, referring to the 1954 decision that struck
down school segregation.
</P>
<P>
   Simpson, who spoke to the group from Cody, Wyo., also criticized
Congress for failing to fill many judicial vacancies over the past
two years. He blamed Senate gridlock for the lack of action.
</P>
<P>
   Currently, 75 federal courts have vacancies. However, of the 42
judicial nominees that President Clinton has sent to the Senate,
only 10 have made it out of the Judiciary Committee and are pending
before the full Senate.
</P>
<P>
   ``We don't want to lay blame against either Democrats or
Republicans for delays in the nomination and confirmation
process,'' Simpson said. ``But we simply cannot permit qualified
judicial candidates to be held up.''
</P>
<P>
   He said the Senate should stop judging nominees on whether they
are liberal or conservative and start judging them on whether they
are qualified.
</P>
<P>
   ``You shouldn't being asking these guys how they'll vote or
looking into their decisions in the past,'' Simpson said.
</P>
<P>
   He cited the failed nomination of appellate judge Robert Bork to
the Supreme Court in 1987 as an example of ``partisan fighting
taking over the confirmation process.'' Senate Democrats, he added,
conducted an intense background check of the conservative Bork and
produced material that included information on what movies he
rented, Simpson said.
</P>
<P>
   ``Before my eyes they turned him into a gargoyle _ a sexist,
racist invader of the bedroom,,'' Simpson said. ``I don't want to
see anyone get Borked again.''
</P>
<P>
   Cuomo agreed, saying that while he opposed Bork's nomination, he
felt Senate Democrats at the time acted improperly by asking the
former judge how he would rule on hypothetical cases.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's crazy to ask a judge to rule on something before he has
seen the facts of that particular case,'' Cuomo said. ``It's like
asking an umpire in baseball to call a strike or ball before the
pitch has been thrown.''
</P>
<P>
   CIC Co-chair Lloyd Cutler, a former White House counsel, said
that much political wrangling over judicial nominees could be
avoided by using a different system for choosing candidates.
</P>
<P>
   He suggested using bipartisan commissions at all levels of
government to consider nominees. The commissions would submit the
names of several qualified candidates to elected officials, who
would make the final choice. He did not address the question of how
Supreme Court nominees would be selected.
</P>
<P>
   ``Judges must be able to make decisions based on the law, free
from political pressure,'' Cutler said. ``We should not tolerate
political interference with judicial decisions and with judicial
powers.''
</P>
</TEXT>
