<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-NBA-JAZZ-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 10 &HT;    Jazz knows it's do-or-die time
 &HT;    By Jeffrey Denberg
 &HT;    c. 1998 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   CHICAGO _ After suffering a resounding 96-54 loss Sunday, the
Utah Jazz understand what's at stake on Wednesday night, when they
meet the Chicago Bulls in Game 4.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think it's do or die,'' Chris Morris said Tuesday. ``The
situation now puts us against the wall. We have to come out ready
and give it all we have; put it on the line like it's the last
game; make our point that we're a team that bounces back, that we
can tie this series.''
</P>
<P>
   Sunday's loss was the worst in Finals history, but Morris
recalled that the Jazz turned things around in the seminfinals
after losing Game 3 to San Antonio by 22 points.
</P>
<P>
   ``We came out and played well and won the series,'' Morris said.
``One reason is because we didn't dwell on it. When we lost in that
situation, we didn't think about basketball. Instead, we got
together, went to a mall. We need to do that now.''
</P>
<P>
   John Stockton says he places no particular importance on
Wednesday's game, because he believes every game should be
approached like a do-or-die situation.
</P>
<P>
   ``If you go in thinking of one game at a time, and that game
you're playing is the most important game you'll ever play, then
you play that one, hopefully win it, and do the same the next
game,'' Stockton said.
</P>
<P>
   But Utah's Shandon Anderson thinks the Bulls have a momentum
that will be hard to stop. Anderson said Chicago's desire to win
the title on Friday in front of their own fans, in what could be
Michael Jordan's last game, is overwhelming.
</P>
<P>
   ``We've got to win this one,'' he said. ``We've got to put the
pressure on them (to have a chance in the series). If we win, we
know we're going back to Salt Lake to play (Game) 6. Then we put
the pressure on them to win Game 5. The series is entirely
different then.''
</P>
<P>
   Antoine Carr said he is having no trouble dealing with Sunday's
whipping.
</P>
<P>
   ``Hey, I played in Sacramento, remember?'' he said. ``But we
definitely gotta step up. We don't want to go down 3-1. You have to
fight back; show you still have fight. We've got to come out
totally hyped up. Upset. Step up. Tell people this is the Jazz team
you're used to seeing and not the team that played the other
night.''
</P>
<P>
   Russell promised the people of Utah a Game 6 after the Jazz were
beaten by five points at home. He hasn't changed his tune.
</P>
<P>
   ``There will be a Game 6,'' he said. ``We need to come out and
play relaxed tomorrow night, and all the (talk of a a five-game
rout) will disappear.''
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
