<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 10 &HT;    Bulls know Jazz won't give up in game 4
 &HT;    By Curtis Bunn
 &HT;    c. 1998 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   CHICAGO _ They called it the ``We (Stink)'' dinner, a gathering
that ultimately galvanized the Utah Jazz after losing to the San
Antonio Spurs by 22 points in Game 3 of the playoffs' second round.
Greg Ostertag, Jeff Hornacek and John Stockton ate together and
admitted their woes to each other _ and then they came back to whip
the Spurs the next night and take the series in five games.
</P>
<P>
   No such occasion took place after the Bulls thrashed Utah by 42
points in Game 3 of the NBA Finals Sunday night at the United
Center. But the San Antonio experience is a source of comfort for
the Jazz, which hopes to show that the Chicago record-setting
clubbing does not signify Utah's imminent demise.
</P>
<P>
   ``We didn't have a dinner like that,'' Hornacek said. ``In this
case, we know what we have to do. And I know the guys are ready.''
</P>
<P>
   Ready for tonight's Game 4 against Chicago that could restore
some order to the series or push the Bulls, leading the series 2-1,
one more victory from their sixth NBA championship in eight years.
</P>
<P>
   But it'll take a dramatic turnabout for the Jazz to erase the
most anemic offensive display in NBA history in losing 96-54 in
Game 3 Sunday _ fewest points in a game, widest margin of defeat,
fewest points in a quarter-and-half.
</P>
<P>
   ``Our confidence is still the same, even though we got beat the
way we did,'' forward Karl Malone said. ``Our attitude is still the
same. Guys expect me to say we're scared to death; well, that's not
even an issue. . . . If you talk to everybody, this series is over
with. But this thing is not over with yet.''
</P>
<P>
   ``I've had two days to think about that game,'' coach Jerry
Sloan said, ``and I think we've put it behind us. This team always
bounces back from a poor performance. I'm always pleased with how
the team responds. I feel good that the guys will come ready to
play.''
</P>
<P>
   They would want to. Chicago dominated so thoroughly in Game 3
that Michael Jordan, Scottie Pippen and Co. spent much of the
fourth quarter on the bench, celebrating the play of the reserves.
And that show of excitement irked the Jazz.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't think they're taking us seriously at all,'' Malone
said. ``If I had beaten someone by 40, I don't think I would
(outwardly celebrate), even if I wanted to. . . . But when you see
things like that, it makes you want to play a little bit harder.''
</P>
<P>
   That's exactly what the Bulls anticipate from Utah.
</P>
<P>
   ``The Jazz will come out with energy and enthusiasm and fire,''
reserve guard Steve Kerr said. ``They're going to come at us.
They're mad. We just have to withstand their initial run. But the
slightest slip in concentration can spark a big run for them.''
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
