<SLUG> BC-NBA-NOTEBOOK-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 10 &HT;    NBA Finals Notebook
 &HT;    By Curtis Bunn &AMP; Jeffrey Denberg
 &HT;    c. 1998 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   Chicago _ Given two days off, a basketball player's attention
wanders into other areas, like baseball.
</P>
<P>
   Utah's Shandon Anderson, an Atlanta native, wore a Braves hat to
practice Tuesday and bragged on his team.
</P>
<P>
   ``Six runs in the ninth,'' he said. ``That was sweet. (They hit)
everything out of the infield. I got to confess I gave up on them,
but they came back and (beat Boston 7-6), anyway.''
</P>
<P>
   Anderson watched baseball on TV Monday night, but Karl Malone
went to Comiskey Park to watch another big man, Mark McGwire of the
St. Louis Cardinals.
</P>
<P>
   Malone said Tuesday he could not imagine hitting a baseball as
far as McGwire did in batting practice. ``It's pretty awesome. I
think probably other than _ I think he hit a home run (in his
second at bat) _ that's the only thing I wanted to see, really, was
just batting practice. I left after that.''
</P>
<P>
   All-Media team
</P>
<P>
   New Jersey's Jayson Williams was the most appreciated player in
the league this season, according to a vote of the media.
</P>
<P>
   Williams received 99 votes for the NBA all-interview team,
joined by Houston's Charles Barkley (88), Utah's Karl Malone (38),
Chicago's Michael Jordan (37) and San Antonio's Avery Johnson.
George Karl of Seattle drew 44 votes to lead coaches.
</P>
<P>
   The second unit consists of Grant Hill, Detroit; Tim Hardaway,
Miami; Dikembe Mutombo, Atlanta; Steve Kerr of Chicago, plus Reggie
Miller of Indiana, David Robinson of San Antonio and Brian Williams
of Detroit, in a tie. Del Harris finished second among coaches.
</P>
<P>
   Missing Atlanta
</P>
<P>
   Antoine Carr hasn't lived in Atlanta since the Hawks traded him
in February 1990, but the forward known as the ``Big Dawg'' still
has a strong interest in the city and his band.
</P>
<P>
   ``The group's called 'Status Quo' and it's doing all right,''
Carr said Tuesday. ``The guys have done some good stuff (rhythm and
blues and jazz), and I've a couple of song-writing contests. It's
something I like to do. We've got 18 songs down. We get a couple
more done, decide what goes on the (first) album and release it.
Hopefully, I'll make millions.''
</P>
<P>
   Comfortable Kukoc
</P>
<P>
   Phil Jackson said the reason Toni Kukoc is playing so well in
this series (12.7 ppg., 6.0 rebounds) is that he feels accepted
now.
</P>
<P>
   ``Toni felt like an outsider coming off the bench,'' Jackson
said. ``Even though he won the Sixth Man Award, and we told him how
much we appreciate his contribution, he wasn't comfortable.
</P>
<P>
   ``That changed when he became a starter. Toni feels now he's
really a part of the team. It shows on the court because he's a
very unique and skilled player.''
</P>
<P>
   Big helping little
</P>
<P>
   Karl Malone has said repeatedly that it's up to Utah's big men
to help the guards. It hasn't happened in this series. ``I still
say we have to step up and do the job,'' Malone repeated Tuesday.
``What a great opportunity this is to help (the guards) out. The
key to the series is for us to help the little guys.''
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
