<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-GUYTON-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Financier bringing his skills home
 &HT;    By Charles Haddad
 &HT;    c. 1998 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA _ Atlanta native Robert P. Guyton Jr. is returning home
from Silicon Valley to start a venture capital concern that will
specialize in investing in high-tech start-ups in the Southeast.
</P>
<P>
   Called Monarch Capital Partners, the firm plans to raise $20
million to invest. It has raised more than $10 million so far, says
Guyton.
</P>
<P>
   Guyton says he has financial commitments from investors
exceeding $20 million but hasn't decided whether to expand the size
of Monarch Capital.
</P>
<P>
   ``The venture capital opportunities in the Southeast are
tremendous,'' says Guyton, a 31-year-old financier. ``There are
lots of innovative ideas coming out of Atlanta. The Silicon Valley
by no means has a monopoly on young technology businesses with
great potential.''
</P>
<P>
   In particular, Guyton is focusing on Internet technology
companies. For example, he's looking at a company that provides a
new type of data compression that greatly enhances real-time video
on the Internet.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm looking at any technology that will take the Internet to
the next level,'' he says.
</P>
<P>
   Guyton returns to Atlanta after a successful stint in Silicon
Valley, where he was a partner at Trilogy Capital Partners, a
venture capital concern.
</P>
<P>
   He co-founded a company called Inktomi, which developed a
powerful Internet search engine and other software.
</P>
<P>
   California-based Inktomi's software is used by America Online,
Microsoft Corp., Intel Corp. and Yahoo! Inc.
</P>
<P>
   The company is expected to go public sometime this week.
</P>
<P>
   Before moving to California, Guyton was a vice president in the
corporate finance group at Robinson-Humphrey Co. in Atlanta.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
