A1484 &Cx1f; tad-z
u f &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-SUPERCOM-SMALLBIZ-COX     06-09 0278
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-SUPERCOM-SMALLBIZ-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    By Bill Husted
 &HT;    c. 1998 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA _ The nation's 12 million small businesses offer the
telecommunications industry a ``tremendous potential for sales in
the coming years,'' according to a national survey released at
SuperComm 98, the telecommunications trade show that opened in
Atlanta Sunday.
</P>
<P>
   The survey showed that small business owners are just now
beginning to adopt new telecommunications technologies. For
instance, the survey of 500 small business owners found only 8
percent of the businesses surveyed had a PBX system. Although 44
percent say they have e-mail at the office, most are not using it
heavily. About half say they send fewer than six e-mail messages a
week and only 13 percent report sending more than 30.
</P>
<P>
   Fewer than half _ 46 percent _ of small businesses have Internet
access in the office, while only 24 percent have their own Web
sites.
</P>
<P>
   Some of the more established technologies did better. Eight in
10 small businesses have a fax and at least one telephone line
dedicated to fax services. More than half _ 56 percent _ have a fax
modem on a computer.
</P>
<P>
   By contrast, only a third of the small businesses have voice
mail. In half of the offices, telephone messages are still being
taken by a receptionist or a coworker, and only two in 10 small
business owners say their messages are handled by a voice mail
system when they are out of the office.
</P>
<P>
   The survey was commissioned by the Telecommunications Industry
Association (TIA) and the United States Telephone Association
(USTA).
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
