<HEADLINE>
BUSINESS TRAVEL: HOTEL RATES, SKIING, CRUISES, AIRLINES 
</HEADLINE>
  (Eds.: duplication warning: also sent with `t' code) 
(bl) 
 By EDWIN McDOWELL   
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   Hotel room rates are expected to rise slightly this year, even
though occupancy rates will decline slightly, but travelers should
not be lulled into thinking they need not book well in advance.
With the economy still chugging along, rooms will continue to be
hard to come by in New York, Boston, San Francisco, Chicago and
other business cities.
</P>
<P>
   Chicago, for example, just added the Hyatt Regency McCormick
Place, a 33-story property. All of its 800 rooms are expected to be
open next month; more than 500 are already open. Even with that
capacity, the hotel already projects that more than 100 nights will
be sold out through the end of June 1999.
</P>
<P>
   Designed for business travelers, all rooms have desks, ergonomic
chairs and power strips with grounded outlets. There are also 53
suites, including 5 for entertaining clients. The hotel has an
indoor heated swimming pool with outdoor sun deck and a health club
with sauna and cardiovascular and strength training equipment.
</P>
<P>
   Poor Skiing in 2050?
</P>
<P>
   A warning for skiers: According to predictions at the recent
World Congress on Snow and World Tourism, climate change caused by
global warming will cause the snow line to withdraw significantly
up the mountains and snow cover can be expected to last for fewer
months. But there is no need to panic just yet, since the effects
are not expected to be felt for 30 to 50 years.
</P>
<P>
   Cruise Update
</P>
<P>
   Remember when cruise passengers wanted to leave their worldly
cares behind? They still can, but only if they don't turn on the
television in their cabins. More and more ships are offering live
news and sports via satellite, as well as an array of reruns for
children and adults.
</P>
<P>
   Princess Cruises, part of Peninsular &AMP; Oriental Steam Navigation
Co. of Britain, has CNN and ESPN live, and is adding BBC reruns to
its television schedule. It will also, of course, continue to show
reruns of the ``Love Boat'' series, which was filmed on the
original Sun Princess and two other Princess ships, and ran on ABC
television from 1977 to 1986.
</P>
<P>
   As one indication of how the cruise industry has grown,
literally, consider that the Sun Princess was 17,000 tons while the
Island Princess and Pacific Princess were 20,000 tons. By contrast,
the Grand Princess, which made its debut May 26 and is currently
sailing European waters, is 109,000 tons. While in nautical terms a
ton is not a measure of weight _ more formally known as a gross
register ton, it represents 100 cubic feet of internal capacity _
it is worth noting that any of those earlier ships would fit
comfortably in the Horizon Court, the 24-hour restaurant aboard the
Grand Princess.
</P>
<P>
   Speaking of huge ships, two days ago Cunard Lines _ recently
bought by Carnival Corp. and a group of Norwegian investors _ said
it was going to build ``the grandest and largest liner ever
built.'' Details will be announced.
</P>
<P>
   Airline Update
</P>
<P>
   In the last 10 days, Northwest Airlines and Delta Air Lines have
begun nonstop service to Japan _ Northwest with two flights a week
connecting Tokyo and Las Vegas, Nev., and Delta with daily nonstops
between Atlanta and Tokyo. On Oct. 2, Japan Airlines will operate
twice-weekly nonstops from Tokyo to Las Vegas. The Northwest and
JAL flights are largely a response to growing Japanese tourism to
Las Vegas, while the Delta flights reflect the growing Japanese
investment in the Southeast, which amounts to almost $14.5 billion,
and the region's exports to Japan, which exceed $5.5 billion a
year.
</P>
<P>
   Air New Zealand and Ansett Australia have agreed to join the
year-old Star Alliance in 1999, bolstering the alliance's access to
the Pacific, especially the South Pacific. The current alliance
members _ United, Air Canada, Lufthansa of Germany, Scandinavian
Airlines System, Thai Airways International and Varig Brazilian
Airlines _ already serve some 650 destinations worldwide, and
alliance flights average a takeoff every 15 seconds around the
clock.
</P>
<P>
   Alaska Airlines is again offering special summer fares to and
from three of the five cities it serves in the Russian Far East.
Round-trip fares to Vladivostok or Khabarovsk range from $585 from
Anchorage to $635 from Seattle, Reno or the San Francisco Bay area
to $735 from Las Vegas, Phoenix and greater Los Angeles. Round trip
to Yuzhno-Sakhalinsk is an additional $250 from each of those
American cities. Fares represent savings of 48 percent to 69
percent, and as usual, restrictions apply.
</P>
<P>
   Best Western International and the Arizona Biltmore Resort and
Spa are the newest members of the frequent-flier program of America
West Airlines.
</P>
<P>
   Austrian Airlines is offering trans-Atlantic round-trip
passengers a one-week car rental from Budget Rent-a-Car in Austria
for $163.80 a week, or less than $24 a day, including unlimited
mileage and taxes.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
