<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-06-09 19:09 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A1495 &Cx1f; tta-z
u f &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-SIGNING-BONUSES-2TAKE     06-09 1086
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-SIGNING-BONUSES-2TAKES-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
EMPLOYERS USING SIGNING BONUSES TO LURE SCARCE WORKERS 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (ATTN: Texas, N.Y., Fla., Iowa, Mont., Md.)  (mk) 
 By LOUIS UCHITELLE   
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   Unable to hire enough teachers, the Dallas school board voted
last month to lure them with $1,500 signing bonuses. Corporate
recruiters paid out much larger bonuses _ averaging $17,500 _ to
Cornell's business school graduates. Even Burger King has got into
the bonus game, offering $5,000 in some cities to hire away
restaurant managers from rival fast-food chains.
</P>
<P>
   The signing bonus is proliferating in America, and growing ever
larger as employers bid for scarce workers. A recruiting tool that
had been limited to upper-level managers, highly skilled
technicians and athletes, it is spreading today to many others,
even civil servants. The Labor Department, for example, is for the
first time offering a bonus of up to $4,000 to attract young
economists.
</P>
<P>
   The hiring bonus appears to be flourishing because employers,
faced with the lowest unemployment rate in a quarter-century, have
shifted some of the bargaining from wages to the less costly
one-time payments. And job applicants, accepting the shift, often
welcome the bonus as a windfall to pay off accumulated debt, or as
a measure of their value _ and status _ in the eyes of their new
employers.
</P>
<P>
   One 30-year-old woman, recently hired as a consultant at Price
Waterhouse, accepted the proffered $85,000 salary without
challenge, but balked at the $5,000 signing bonus. ``I barely had
to say that $5,000 was not enough, and they said, `Fine, would
$10,000 make you happy?' and I got that,'' she said. She declined
to give her name out of concern, she said, that other newly hired
consultants at Price Waterhouse who got smaller bonuses might be
resentful.
</P>
<P>
   The hiring bonus is just the latest tool that companies have
turned to in recent years to hold down wages. The others include
profit sharing, flexible schedules, tuition subsidies, stock
options, health club memberships and ``performance'' bonuses in
lieu of raises for those already on the payroll. While wages are
now rising a bit faster than they have in a decade, hiring bonuses
are ballooning and spreading across the work force _ absorbing some
of the pressure for still-greater income.
</P>
<P>
   ``Signing bonuses are certainly rising faster than starting
salaries,'' said Stephen Johansson, director of career services at
the Johnson Graduate School of Management at Cornell University.
``It is much harder to raise the starting salaries because you end
up having to pay people coming in the door more than those who have
been there two or three years and have done well. Most companies
have avoided raising wage scales.''
</P>
<P>
   The American Management Association, in a new survey of its
corporate members, found that 44 percent of the 344 who replied
paid signing bonuses to employees hired in the last year. That was
up from 30 percent last spring, the first time the association even
asked about the practice in its surveys.
</P>
<P>
   ``A lot of our clients offer the base pay up front, and then the
bonus in a second interview as the kicker to get people in the
door,'' said Jamie Hale, an executive at Watson Wyatt, the
management consulting firm. ``The bonuses range from 5 to 15
percent of a year's salary. In some cases, people have to pay them
back if they leave within six months. But if you attach too many
strings, the bonuses are not going to do what they are supposed to
do, which is get people on board.''
</P>
<P>
   For all its growing popularity, the signing bonus is hard for
the federal government to track and is not calculated as part of
the Employment Cost Index, a broad federal measure of worker
compensation. The index converts the various forms of income and
benefits into pay per hour. For the bonus, however, that cannot be
easily done, officials explain, because it has already been paid by
the time a new employee starts working.
</P>
<P>
   That means people have more spending money than the income
statistics suggest, even as labor costs may be putting greater
pressure on companies to raise prices than the Employment Cost
Index now indicates. The Federal Reserve considers the index an
important indicator of whether inflationary pressures are building
up sufficiently to justify an increase in interest rates to slow
the economy.
</P>
<P>
   One measure of the bonus' popularity is its spread over the last
year to most fast-food companies. ``If you are going to get good
people, you have to take them from a competitor, and the way to get
them is the bonus,'' said Anthony Austin, vice president for human
resources at Burger King, a unit of Grand Metropolitan PLC.
</P>
<P>
   Not that every Burger King employee gets one. Rarely are they
disbursed in Montana, say, or in other places where unemployment is
not so low. But in the tight labor markets of a Milwaukee or a
Tampa, Fla., the company finds itself paying an $8,000 to $10,000
bonus to recruit a $50,000-a-year area manager, and $3,000 to
$5,000 to win someone to a $35,000-a-year job as a restaurant
manager.
</P>
<P>
   ``Someone else will pay the bonus if you don't,'' Austin said.
</P>
<P>
   But counter clerks, earning $6 or $7 an hour, are not yet in the
loop. The odds are too great that they would take a $200 bonus and
quit within a week, Austin said. Instead, they get that amount as a
``retention'' bonus if they stay for six months.
</P>
<P>
   Sometimes, when a worker shifts to a new employer, the signing
bonus compensates for a benefit lost at the old job. That happened
to Sarah Peters, who joined the Principal Financial Group in Des
Moines last month as a writer in the public relations department,
earning more than $35,000 a year. She shifted from a similar job at
Mid-American Energy, a Des Moines power company.
</P>
<P>
   ``Principal recruited me,'' said Ms. Peters, who is 25, ``but I
have my wedding coming up in October and I hesitated to accept; it
meant giving up the vacation time I had accumulated for my
honeymoon.''
</P>
<P>
   As a signing bonus, Principal granted her a one-time-only extra
week of paid time off, to be taken whenever Ms. Peters wishes.
Normally, an employee at Principal, a big insurance company, earns
one paid day off, to be taken as vacation or sick leave, for each
two months of work. ``Principal is the employer of choice for
anyone in Des Moines,'' Ms. Peters said, ``but without that
vacation bonus, I would have definitely thought twice about taking
the job.''
</P>
<P>
</P>
<P>
   No one is more a target of the signing bonus than the college
graduate _ not only those receiving an MBA, but even those getting
a simple bachelor's degree. Three of every 10 graduates at the
University of North Carolina at Charlotte got bonuses this spring,
up from one in 10 two years ago, according to a school survey. And
at Cornell's management school, which had 260 graduates this
spring, 90 percent of the new MBA's who responded to a survey said
they had received bonuses from their new employers. That was up
from 63 percent two years ago.
</P>
<P>
   More striking were the skyrocketing amounts. The $17,500 average
bonus for this year's Cornell MBA class was nearly double the 1996
average of $9,400, and 43 percent above last year's $12,200.
</P>
<P>
   The bonus is spreading, for the first time, to the public
sector. The Labor Department has just started to use it, in the
Bureau of Labor Statistics, as has the Census Bureau. An act of
Congress is required to raise civil service pay scales, but bonuses
are legal under a rarely invoked law. In recent months, the Bureau
of Labor Statistics has paid bonuses ranging from $2,000 to $4,000
to nine newly hired employees, seven of them economists.
</P>
<P>
   ``I hired one guy and there was a competing bonus from another
agency,'' said Michael Allen, a personnel specialist at the bureau.
``The compensation packages were basically equal and he wanted to
work with us, but without the bonus he would not have accepted.''
</P>
<P>
   Short of teachers, the Baltimore Board of Education voted last
month to pay $5,000 to new teachers buying a home within the city.
There are two strings attached: The bonus must be used for the home
purchase and must be paid back if the teacher leaves the job in
less than five years.
</P>
<P>
   In Texas, the school boards in Dallas and Fort Worth are engaged
in what amounts to a bonus war. Fort Worth led off earlier this
year with a set of bonuses starting at $500 and rising to $2,000
for applicants who signed contracts by June 1.
</P>
<P>
   The Dallas board countered last month. Faced with 900 openings
for the coming school year, the board authorized a flat $1,500 for
each new hire. More than 200 signed up at a job fair on May 30,
including Linda Livingston, a 50-year-old English teacher who had
taught public school before and wanted the $28,500-a-year job to
help put two children through college.
</P>
<P>
   ``The bonus is kind of nice,'' she said, ``but that is all; you
can go through the money pretty fast.''
</P>
<P>
   But for Vicki Parker, a junior-high-school teacher in Lewistown,
Mont., the bonus being offered by Dallas made all the difference in
the world. Hearing of it on a radio news broadcast, she immediately
applied and her papers are being processed. ``I have cousins in
Dallas,'' she said.
</P>
<P>
   Montana has a surplus of teachers and Ms. Parker, who is 40 and
single, has never earned more than $17,000 a year in the state.
</P>
<P>
   ``Whenever a school system is willing to offer a bonus, there is
a need,'' she said. ``The $1,500 isn't so much, but they are
probably willing to do extra things for me, because they need me,
which is not the case here.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-06-09-98 1909EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19980609.0290 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-06-09 19:13 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A1501 &Cx1f; tad-z
u i &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-CLINTON-COX &UR;      06-09 1131
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CLINTON-COX </SLUG>
    
 &HT;     CLINTON DEFENDS TIANANMEN SQUARE VISIT; PUTS SERBS ON NOTICE
 &HT;     By BOB DEANS 
 &HT;     c.1998 Cox News Service  
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ President Clinton defended his plans to be received
near Beijing's Tiananmen Square on his state visit to China later
this month, and endorsed South Korea's economic restructuring
efforts Tuesday in a wide-ranging White House news conference with
Korean President Kim Dae Jung.
</P>
<P>
   Clinton also put ethnic Serbs on notice for their continuing
repression of ethnic Albanians in the former Yugoslav republic of
Kosovo, warning that he had authorized stepped up NATO contingency
planning as part of a broader effort ``to do all that I can to stop
a repeat of the human carnage in Bosnia and the ethnic cleansing.''
</P>
<P>
   Trying to boost confidence in the future of South Korea's
flagging economy, Clinton restored lending by the Overseas Private
Investment Corp. (OPIC) _ a government agency that guarantees loans
for private U.S. companies in high-risk countries _ and said that
the Commerce Department would put together a trade and investment
mission to South Korea soon.
</P>
<P>
   Clinton also gave his endorsement to President Kim's
implementation of economic reforms and financial restructuring as
recommended by the International Monetary Fund (IMF).
</P>
<P>
   ``I believe what has happened here is a bump in the road,''
Clinton said, referring to last fall's collapse in the South
Korea's currency and stock markets.
</P>
<P>
   But perhaps most striking about Tuesday's press conference,
however, were the questions not asked.
</P>
<P>
   In a stark return from scandal to statecraft, Clinton's
appearance marked the first White House press conference in five
months that didn't include a single question about Monica Lewinsky,
the key figure in a purported sex scandal that has rocked Clinton's
presidency.
</P>
<P>
   Apparently fearing viewers might tire of a solid diet of policy
questions, CNN cut away from its live coverage of the press
conference in a dramatic departure from its practice in recent
months, in which the cable company has carried dozens of White
House press events with a heavy focus on the Lewinsky matter.
</P>
<P>
   Even ABC's White House correspondent Sam Donaldson, known for
his tough questioning, shouted out a foreign policy question _
regarding U.S. intentions in Kosovo _ instead of his usual
across-the-room probes on the latest threads to the Lewinsky case.
</P>
<P>
   Clinton, who has weathered repeated grillings on the subject
from the podium is far from finished with tough questions
surrounding independent counsel Kenneth Starr's ongoing inquiry
into whether Clinton conducted an Oval Office affair with Lewinsky
then later urged her and others to lie about it under oath _
charges Clinton has denied.
</P>
<P>
   Nor was he completely spared the stain of scandal on Tuesday,
when CNN's Wolf Blitzer asked Clinton to explain his decision last
year to allow sophisticated satellite technology transfers to
China.
</P>
<P>
   Clearly briefed on that one, Clinton responded that he had
merely followed the recommendations of his State Department,
National Security Council and the Arms Control and Disarmament
Agency in allowing the sales.
</P>
<P>
   ``It was, from my point of view, a pretty routine decision,''
Clinton said.
</P>
<P>
   At least on Tuesday, however, Clinton was able to get beyond
questions about his alleged sex life and focus on substantive
issues.
</P>
<P>
   Standing beside Kim, who was elected last December after
surviving jail, torture and assassination attempts by dictatorial
regimes in Seoul in his career fight for democracy, Clinton rose to
question after high-brow question about security on the Korean
Peninsula, the future of U.S.-China relations and even Donaldson's
closer about a possible U.S. role in Kosovo.
</P>
<P>
   Clinton said the United States and Britain were near to
proposing a United Nations resolution that would authorize the use
of ``all necessary means'' _ a phrase denoting possible military
action in U.N. parlance _ to end the repression of ethnic Albanians
in Kosovo, where scores have been killed and more than 20,000
driven from their homes in a campaign by ethnic Serbs against
Albanians who make up 90 percent of Kosovo's population of two
million.
</P>
<P>
   Just next door to Bosnia, another former Yugoslav republic that
suffered at the hands of Serb para-military groups after breaking
away from the former Yugoslavia in 1992, Kosovo has long been seen
as a powder keg that could reignite war in the Balkans.
</P>
<P>
   Nearly four years of fighting in the region was brought to an
uneasy cease-fire two-and-a-half years ago, following U.S.-brokered
peace talks in Dayton, Ohio and the deployment of a massive
U.S.-led NATO force still on the ground in Bosnia.
</P>
<P>
   Referring to Kosovo, Clinton said, ``I am determined to do all
that I can to stop a repeat of the human carnage in Bosnia and the
ethnic cleansing. And I have authorized, and I am supporting, an
accelerated planning process for NATO.''
</P>
<P>
   Said Clinton, ``we do not believe any options should be taken
off the table.''
</P>
<P>
   Turning to his trip to China, scheduled from June 24 to July 3,
Clinton said U.S. interests in forging an effective relationship
with China outweighed the pleas of human rights activists in this
country that the president forego a scheduled welcoming ceremony in
front of the Great Hall of the People.
</P>
<P>
   Located adjacent to Tiananmen Square, seat of a democracy
campaign quashed by Chinese troops nine years ago in a bloody
crackdown that killed hundreds of unarmed citizens, the Great Hall
of the People is the public edifice of the Chinese government and
the place where all official state guests are formally welcomed.
</P>
<P>
   ``My own view is that, if this is going to be a state visit to
China, and I am going to be the guest of the Chinese, that they
should be designing the terms of the arrival ceremony, not me,''
said Clinton. ``I simply don't accept the proposition that
observing their diplomatic protocol in any way undermines my
capacity to advance the principles of the United States.''
</P>
<P>
   Clinton pledged to press U.S. concerns over China's continuing
human rights abuses in a ``clear and unambiguous,'' way.
</P>
<P>
   ``But,'' he said, ``I think that what Americans should want me
to do is to make sure that I am as effective as possible not only
in advancing our interests, but in standing up for our values. And
I'm going to do what I think is likely, in the short run and over
the long run, to make our country the most effective.''
</P>
<P>
   Citing last months' repeated nuclear weapons tests by India and
Pakistan, Clinton said ``it should be clearer than ever before that
we have a strong national interest in developing a constructive,
positive relationship with China.''
</P>
<P>
   &UR; For clients of the New York Times News Service &LR;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-06-09-98 1913EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19980609.0291 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-06-09 19:14 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A1504 &Cx1f; tad-z
u w &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-CLINTON-COX &UR;      06-09 1131
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CLINTON-COX </SLUG>
    
 &HT;     CLINTON DEFENDS TIANANMEN SQUARE VISIT; PUTS SERBS ON NOTICE
 &HT;     By BOB DEANS 
 &HT;     c.1998 Cox News Service  
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ President Clinton defended his plans to be received
near Beijing's Tiananmen Square on his state visit to China later
this month, and endorsed South Korea's economic restructuring
efforts Tuesday in a wide-ranging White House news conference with
Korean President Kim Dae Jung.
