u i &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-RUSSIA-CORRUPTION-425     06-09 0971
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-RUSSIA-CORRUPTION-425&AMP;ADD-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
TAX CRACKDOWN BEGINS WITH ARREST OF GOVERNMENT STATISTICIANS 
</HEADLINE>
  (th) 
 By MICHAEL R. GORDON    
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   MOSCOW _ The Yeltsin government began its long-overdue fight
against tax evasion by arresting the nation's top statisticians and
accusing them of manipulating data to help Russian companies avoid
taxes.
</P>
<P>
   The head of the State Committee for Statistics and his top
deputies were arrested in raids Monday night.
</P>
<P>
   Investigators said that more than $1.5 million in cash and
jewelry was seized from the officials' apartments. And Tuesday
night Russian television showed shoeboxes and briefcases full of
confiscated money.
</P>
<P>
   The arrests also raise probing questions about how the
government measures economic performance, an important issue for
jittery investors and for international financial institutions that
distribute aid to Russia.
</P>
<P>
   In one sense, the scandal is good news. In effect, the officials
are being accused of taking money to deliberately underestimate the
production of Russian enterprises and, thus, to help minimize their
tax obligations.
</P>
<P>
   That indicates that Russia's economy is larger than the
government's statistics suggest. The International Monetary Fund,
for example, has privately estimated that Russia's economic
production is roughly 20 percent greater than official government
estimates.
</P>
<P>
   But the case also illustrates the extent to which corruption has
infected the upper ranks of the government. And it undermines the
credibility of official statistics.
</P>
<P>
   ``It means that we know nothing about the performance of Russian
companies,'' said Mikhail Berger, an economic specialist and the
editor of the newspaper Segodnya. ``We don't know about the Russian
economy.''
</P>
<P>
   The State Committee for Statistics _ otherwise known as
Goskomstat _ has long been a formidable arm of the government
bureaucracy.
</P>
<P>
   During Soviet days, its reports about the nation's economic
trends could not be made public without the approval of top Soviet
leaders, who insisted that they accent the positive.
</P>
<P>
   The committee has continued to play a critical role following
the breakup of the Soviet Union. The committee gathers production
data from more than 22,000 large enterprises and surveys small
business. Its estimate of the nation's gross domestic product are
generally viewed as a barometer of Russia's economic performance.
</P>
<P>
   According to Goskomstat, the Russian economy grew by 0.8 percent
last year, reversing long years of decline. Russian officials hoped
it would grow by one or two percent this year until the nation was
hit by a financial crisis.
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   Estimating Russian economic activity has never been easy because
Russian enterprises chronically downplay their production to
minimize taxes.
</P>
<P>
   During Soviet times ``to report an increase in the amount of
production was to become a Hero of Socialist Labor,'' Yegor Gaidar,
the former prime minister, observed last year. ``Now it is to get
additional visits from the tax collector.''
</P>
<P>
   According to investigators, far from fighting the problem of
underreporting, the statistics committee was a willing accomplice.
</P>
<P>
   The case has been under investigation for a long time, and the
timing of the raids seemed designed to advertise the Yeltsin
government's campaign to go after tax delinquents.
</P>
<P>
   The Kremlin, however, has long talked about prosecuting tax
delinquents only to back away in the face of fierce political
pressure from powerful financiers and businessmen. And it remains
to be seen whether the arrests are a sign of a broader crackdown or
merely a token gesture.
</P>
<P>
   Prime Minister Sergei Kiriyenko said the arrests had been
personally approved by President Boris Yeltsin.
</P>
<P>
   ``The unscrupulous falsification and handling of information
facilitated tax evasion,'' Kiriyenko said during a brief visit to
Minsk. ``The state cannot tolerate it.''
</P>
<P>
   Specifically, investigators charged that Yuri Yurkov, the
chairman of the committee, and his aides were minimizing production
in return for bribes.
</P>
<P>
   The investigators charged that committee officials were taking
confidential production data from some enterprises and selling it
to competitors. More than 20 people were alleged to be part of the
ring, including the head of the committee's computer center.
</P>
<P>
   Yurkov pleaded guilty to the charges, according to the
government. He is one of the most senior government officials to be
charged with corruption.
</P>
<P>
   Elsewhere in the government, Boris Fyodorov, the new head of the
State Tax Service, announced that he was purging his office of
corrupt officials.
</P>
<P>
   In a move that has caused a political sensation, Fyodorov also
says he will begin by auditing the tax returns of the 1,000 richest
people in the country.
</P>
<P>
   Many international economists say they have never taken
Goskomstat's statistics at face value, but relied on them as a
gauge of economic trends.
</P>
<P>
   In contrast, the Central Banks' data on the size of the money
supply and the government's information on federal spending is
considered to generally reliable.
</P>
<P>
   The arrests are likely to lead to new, more encouraging
estimates of the size Russian economy.
</P>
<P>
   If Goskomstat's new leadership confirms that production was
understated, the nation's economic growth will be revised upward.
That will make it easier for Russia to meet its goal of keeping its
federal budget deficit to 5 percent or less of the gross domestic
product.
</P>
<P>
   Russian politicians and businessmen seemed uncertain Tuesday
night how far the crackdown on tax evasion will go. But many
believe that more arrests are likely.
</P>
<P>
   ``The political circles received the news like a bomb
explosion,'' the newspaper Izvestia said Tuesday night. &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
