<HEADER>
A1507 &Cx1f; gen-z
u w &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-STATES-SHUTER-NAT     06-09 0399
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-STATES-SHUTER-NAT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;     
 &HT;    
 &HT;      SHUSTER CAUGHT IN TURNPIKE TOLL MESS
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;     By Paul Kane  
 &HT;    c. 1998 States News Service  
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON, June 9 -- As President Clinton placed the finishing
touches on legislative wrangling over the $200 billion highway
bill, the Pennsylvania Turnpike Commission and Rep. Bud Shuster
said they reached a settlement over toll-free access to the
highway.
</P>
<P>
   Shuster, R-Everett, sparked a mini-controversy three weeks ago
when he slid a one-paragraph provision into the highway bill that
allowed for drivers to have free access to the turnpike between
Bedford and Breezewood, in between where the powerful lawmaker's
home.
</P>
<P>
   Shuster, chairman of the House Transportation Committee, said
the provision was not designed for his own personal benefit --
although it could lead to $83 a year in savings, or $500 over the
life of the bill, for Shuster, according to a Gannett News Service
estimate.
</P>
<P>
   Shuster contended the measure was needed because construction on
Route 30, which runs parallel to the turnpike, will force local
residents, including Shuster, onto the turnpike for a short drive
between Bedford and Breezewood.
</P>
<P>
   But turnpike commission members said the ``trust indenture'' set
up with bondholders forbid having any free access to the road,
regardless of what a powerful lawmaker said. ``We communicated
those concerns to Congressman Shuster's office,'' said Bill Capone,
a turnpike commission spokesman.
</P>
<P>
   For a legislative fix, Shuster got lawmakers to agree to a $3
million reimbursement from Washington to the commission, about the
value of all lost revenue from Everett residents driving for free
on the turnpike for the next six years.
</P>
<P>
   ``(The reimbursement) in effect would make the whole thing
revenue neutral,'' Capone said.
</P>
<P>
   As part of a corrections bill to the massive highway act, the
House approved the $3 million reimbursement last week, but the
Senate stalled on the corrections measure over an unrelated
provision about veterans who smoke.
</P>
<P>
   An aide to Shuster said it could take several months to resolve
the veteran smoker issue, but eventually the lawmaker will find a
way to ensure the turnpike commission gets its reimbursement.
</P>
<P>
   Regardless, on Oct. 1, the day the highway bill takes affect,
it's a free ride on the turnpike for everyone driving from Bedford
to Breezewood and back -- including Shuster.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
