<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-APPLEBEES-ANNIVERSARY-KAN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
A SATISFYING MILESTONE: APPLEBEE'S OPENING RESTAURANT NO. 1,000 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By JENNIFER MANN  
 c. 1998 Kansas City Star  
<TEXT>
<P>
   KANSAS CITY, Mo. _ The Florida sun was warm, the ocean waves
gentle, the salt-tinged breeze mild, and Abe Gustin, chairman of
Applebee's International Inc., felt about as good as a man could.
</P>
<P>
   Gustin described his surroundings by telephone in serene sighs
wrapped in an attitude of life is great. It was his preamble to a
look back at the once-scrappy little company he and John Hamra
started 10 years ago that today opens its 1,000th Applebee's
Neighborhood Grill &AMP; Bar.
</P>
<P>
   ``Gee, you know it's funny. Back when we first started this
thing, John and I wondered if we could ever get it to 100,'' Gustin
said. ``In fact, our goal was 100, and if we were really lucky we'd
get to about 150.''
</P>
<P>
   The Applebee's milepost store opens in Aurora, Colo., and Gustin
plans to be there. Gustin said the 1,000th restaurant was
satisfying on several levels.
</P>
<P>
   ``We like to sit around and talk about how many people we serve
each year. Last year we touched 300 million people in terms of the
number of guests at our restaurants, and I think that's really
something,'' Gustin said.
</P>
<P>
   Another goal, he said, was to make each of the company's
approximately 50 franchisees millionaires, ``and I think we've made
most of them multimillionaires,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Not that they haven't hit some potholes, including self-made
ones over the last year after rolling out a new menu with food
served on white, apple-ringed plates.
</P>
<P>
   Some of the new food items took more preparation than
anticipated, and the larger, heavier plates took more effort to get
to the table, resulting in slower service and sometimes tepid food.
</P>
<P>
   Applebee's Chief Executive Officer Lloyd Hill said the company
and its employees had been working hard to correct those problems.
</P>
<P>
   ``While it continues to improve, we may have pushed the envelope
a little bit, and that is the result sometimes when you push,''
Hill said.
</P>
<P>
   Another problem spot has been the affiliate chain, Rio Bravo
Cantina, which the company bought a few years ago. The thought
behind the acquisition was to give Applebee's franchisees another
vehicle to develop for their territories.
</P>
<P>
   But initial attempts to build the chain found investors getting
a less-than-acceptable return on their investments. This prompted
the company to design a prototype that would be less expensive to
build and operate but would serve the same number of patrons.
</P>
<P>
   Now, Hill said, investment returns from the new Rio Bravo
restaurants are more in line with what franchisees expect.
</P>
<P>
   At least one analyst wishes the company had thought twice about
buying a second concept. He sees restaurant companies do it all the
time.
</P>
<P>
   ``I always worry about any company that has a concept that works
looking for a second one,'' said Michael Smith of Fahnestock &AMP; Co.
``I mean, the roadside is littered with the carcasses of companies
that just couldn't stick to doing one thing and doing it over and
over and over again.''
</P>
<P>
   For instance, Smith said, any such company is in danger of
taking its focus off its cash cow and putting it on the problem.
</P>
<P>
   It's what Hill calls the action of limited resources no matter
how big or good.
</P>
<P>
   ``But the rationale for a second concept clearly came as a
demand from our franchise system, some of whom were approaching
(the limit of how many Applebee's could operate) in their
territories,'' Hill said.
</P>
<P>
   As kinks get worked out, Hill said, the growth of the Rio Bravo
chain could go any of several ways, including being developed
mostly by the company.
</P>
<P>
   In another road bump, company officials rang a bell of warning
on Wall Street last week when they notified analysts that May sales
at restaurants open at least one year were lower than the flattish
trends it has been experiencing of late.
</P>
<P>
   On that basis, some analysts downgraded their recommendation on
the company's stock, including Michael Fineman of Raymond James &AMP;
Associates.
</P>
<P>
   Fineman told Bloomberg News that he downgraded Applebee's from
``accumulate'' to ``neutral'' in part because of the slippage in
same-store sales.
</P>
<P>
   But others, including Janice Meyer of Donaldson, Lufkin &AMP;
Jenrette and Smith of Fahnestock, maintained their ratings. Meyer
rates Applebee's as ``market perform'' while Smith rates it
``strong buy.''
</P>
<P>
   Smith said Applebee's had never been a same-store-sales driven
company. He explained the strategy that Applebee's calls
``conscious cannibalization.''
</P>
<P>
   When an Applebee's reaches capacity, which is partly measured by
how long customers have to wait during peak dining hours, it builds
a new restaurant within a specific distance. The new restaurant
draws customers from the one running at capacity, thus the term
``conscious cannibalization.''
</P>
<P>
   The strategy has led the company to its 1,000-restaurant
milestone, which makes it by far the largest company in the
casual-dining segment. It's next closest competitor is Red Lobster
with about 700 units.
</P>
<P>
   ``It shows that we continue to be accepted into more
neighborhoods across America,'' Hill said. ``We think we can, to a
great degree, be a proxy for the family dinner table.''
</P>
<P>
   Finally, some analysts have criticized the company for adding
more expensive, upscale items such as steak and salmon to its
menus.
</P>
<P>
   But Hill said not to worry.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think if we keep our focus, we'll become an American icon
much like, well, like McDonald's has,'' he said.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
