A1509 &Cx1f; kan-z
r f &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-WORKING-WOMEN-KAN &LR;      06-09 0466
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-WORKING-WOMEN-KAN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
PROVIDING THE CHANCE TO ADVANCE 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By JILIAN MINCER  
 c. 1998 Kansas City Star  
<TEXT>
<P>
   Why do so many talented women abandon corporate America?
</P>
<P>
   To stay home with children, right?
</P>
<P>
   Wrong.
</P>
<P>
   ``The overwhelming majority don't go home,'' said Sheila
Wellington, president of the nonprofit Catalyst. ``They leave
because they can't find a way of balancing work and personal lives;
they go to companies where they think they have a fair chance of
advancement.''
</P>
<P>
   With that in mind, Catalyst recently released ``Advancing Women
in Business _ The Catalyst Guide: Best Practices From the Corporate
Leaders.'' The book is the first of a series on women in business
and focuses on recruiting, retaining and advancing women.
</P>
<P>
   Most companies now recognize that a diverse work force makes
economic sense, Wellington said. But they often unwittingly create
conditions that disadvantage women.
</P>
<P>
   The book profiles companies such as Motorola, Deloitte &AMP; Touche
and dozens of others that have succeeded in attracting and
retaining women.
</P>
<P>
   ``This book presents real-world success stories,'' Wellington
said. ``You can learn from these examples and adapt it to your own
culture.''
</P>
<P>
   For example, in the early 1990s Sara Lee decided to develop a
long-range diversity plan.
</P>
<P>
   The program focuses on goals to increase the representation of
women and minorities at management levels. As part of its effort,
the company identifies employees with potential and helps them get
the experience they need to advance.
</P>
<P>
   Similarly, the chief executive of Deloitte &AMP; Touche decided to
find out why the firm hired so many female candidates but why so
few became partners. The accounting firm spends millions of dollars
a year recruiting and training its staff, so retention is crucial.
</P>
<P>
   A study led to changes that include flexible work arrangements,
career development opportunities and careful tracking of
assignments.
</P>
<P>
   Do these policies make a difference?
</P>
<P>
   Deloitte &AMP; Touche saw a significant drop in turnover after
developing a program to enhance women's career opportunities.
</P>
<P>
   The Bank of Montreal enjoyed four years of record profits after
instituting a corporate strategy makeover that emphasized
attracting women managers and maximizing their potential. From 1991
to 1997, representation of women in executive positions increased
from 9 percent to 50 percent.
</P>
<P>
   That sounds great, but what if your company doesn't have a CEO
who is committed to diversity? Wellington suggested that employees
establish a women's network. Those groups, she said, shouldn't be
negative. They should offer management alternative solutions.
</P>
<P>
   And women's networks are the subject of the next Catalyst book,
due out this fall.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
