A1516 &Cx1f; kan-z
r l &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-FASHION-WHITE-KANSAS-     06-09 0452
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FASHION-WHITE-KANSAS-KAN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
LOOK OUT! 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 JACKIE WHITE  
 c. 1997 The Kansas City Star  
<TEXT>
<P>
   By the book
</P>
<P>
   In the next life, I want the job of the researcher assigned to
uncover the pithy, sartorial quotes for such how-to books as the
new Chic Series' Men's Wardrobe, (Alfred A. Knopf Inc., $25, 223
pages).
</P>
<P>
   Consider the kick digging up the Australian Aboriginal saying:
``The more you know, the less you need.'' It succinctly summarizes
the Chic Simple philosophy that having the right stuff at the right
time has less to do with quantity and more with quality and good
choices.
</P>
<P>
   And from Mark Twain: ``Clothes make the man. Naked people have
little or no influence in society.'' Then, there is ``I grow
old...I grow old.... I shall wear the bottoms of my trousers
rolled. Shall I part my hair behind? Do I dare to eat a peach? I
shall wear white trousers, and walk upon the beach.'' From T.S.
Eliot's ``The Love Song of J. Alfred Prufrock.''
</P>
<P>
   In the past five years, the Chic Simple series of books has
included a variety of such subjects as women's makeup, business
casual dressing, women's clothing and business attire.
</P>
<P>
   The genius is not just that they offer basic advice about
dressing well and appropriately without much effort and
interference from fashion trends. But also that the how-to stuff is
interspersed with entertaining cartoons, quotations and colorful
photography.
</P>
<P>
   The latest men's book is produced by Kim Johnson Gross and Jeff
Stone, and written by Woody Hochswender, all formerly or presently
associated with Esquire magazine.
</P>
<P>
   It covers such subjects as how many suits you should own _
enough so that they can be effectively rotated and never worn two
days in a row. And what shoes you can wear with shorts _ almost
anything from a leather sandal and Topsiders to athletic shoes and
a polished loafer. The book includes a glossary of terms and list
of sources with web site addresses. It's a must-have manual for
most.
</P>
<P>
   Other notes;
</P>
<P>
   - If you're tired of tie decisions, you could live with one tie,
a black wool knit for all occasions.
</P>
<P>
   - Tradition has it that the bottom button on a vest is left
unfastened thanks to the royal girth of Edward VII who could not
make the garment reach.
</P>
<P>
   - Horn rim glasses will make you look smart, but unglamorous.
</P>
<P>
   Do coupons help?
</P>
<P>
   If you want to dress like a star, save all your money. The July
Marie Claire magazine enumerates what it costs some celebs to dress
the way they do, if and when they pay for their clothes. Ashley
Judd, with Manolo Blahnik shoes and dresses from Armani, Richard
Tyler and John Bartlett, runs up a walloping bill of $35,175.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-06-09-98 1923EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
