<DOCNO> NYT19980609.0300 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-06-09 19:24 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A1518 &Cx1f; kan-z
r l &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-FASHION-SHOES-KANSAS-     06-09 1229
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FASHION-SHOES-KANSAS-KAN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
SHOE MUCH? 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 JACKIE WHITE  
 c. 1997 The Kansas City Star  
<TEXT>
<P>
   In the old days women's shoes were decreed with the same force
as, say, skirt lengths, long hair and frosted pink lip colors.
</P>
<P>
   Somewhere, it would seem, a scroll was unfolded and word on the
look of the moment came down _ ta da! _ pointed toes. Then it was
the chunky shoe, the loafer, Gucci's high-heeled loafer or the
backless mule. And so it went. Not long ago you wouldn't be caught
napping in a canoe in the river without the rounded toe.
</P>
<P>
   Now you can lose that memory. Welcome to the new world of
footwear, where the word choices is, well, a serious
understatement. The list of trends is long, starting with sandals _
enjoying history-making popularity _ clogs, wedges and shapely high
heels that look as if they belong in a modern art museum.
</P>
<P>
   If the fashion magazines seem fond of pointed toes, they are no
more valued than squared toes, flat soft slippers, curvy Sabrina
heels, straps and athletic-inspired sneakers with a status label on
a platform. Choose from fabric shoes, stretch shoes, shoes with
raffia and cork trimmings, even a clear Cinderella high-heeled
evening slipper. And that's just the beginning.
</P>
<P>
   ``There have never before been so many varieties,'' says David
Wolfe, the fashion director for Doneger Group, a New York
consulting service. ``It's a smorgasbord.''
</P>
<P>
   But for all the dizzying variety in styles, one common buzzword
permeates the entire shoe industry. It probably falls off
executives' lips over lunchtime salads and haunts secret laboratory
tests. That word is comfort.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's what we hear again and again as a priority from the
consumer,'' says Cheryl Holland, the vice president for women's
merchandise at Halls, a Kansas City specialty store.
</P>
<P>
   Shoe designer Stuart Weitzman says now when he talks to women in
retail stores, the first thing they invariably say is not how
beautiful a shoe is but ``It is so comfortable.'' A shoe can be
ugly, he says, and still be a best seller if it's comfortable.
</P>
<P>
   Much of the technology developed by the athletic shoe industry
has been appropriated in the fashion arena. Weitzman, for instance,
has added extra cushioning to his upscale dress shoes this year and
in the future will incorporate the fit-to-foot molding of running
shoes. ``It's all about technology,'' he says.
</P>
<P>
   Modern stretch fabrics with spandex offer more comfort because
they hug the foot and hold it in place. Whether it's a covered
molded business pump, a short boot or Walter Steiger's $270 stretch
ankle strap with a plump heel similar to modern chair legs, it is
considered a safe bet.
</P>
<P>
   Even the pointed-toe pumps, directional for fall and seen on
many evening shoes now, are not the old machete-sharp killers. As
Holland, at Halls, notes, the points are narrowed well beyond the
end of the foot so that the toes are never actually crunched.
</P>
<P>
   Feeling good
</P>
<P>
   Meanwhile, the drive for the C word combined with fashion has
led the movement to the flat, the ``most high-fashion shoe,'' says
Greg Andrews, fashion director for Nordstrom stores in the Central
States.
</P>
<P>
   Whether it's a ballet slipper or menswear oxford, the flat has
made an impressive return in part because it fits well with the
summer fashion of capris and knee pants and very long skirts,
Andrews says. The soft slipper was a regular on the fall fashion
runways with the long skirts.
</P>
<P>
   Also in the comfort mode, the concept of the Euro-walking shoe
is on the rise. Indeed, the sneaker or athletic look is not new,
but the same brands are styled into fashionable sandals and other
shapes as new hits.
</P>
<P>
   For one example, the Aquatali.MDSD/.MDNM/a, a waterproof
platform sandal, is not the prettiest shoe, but it's a runaway best
seller at Halls in Kansas City. Mephisto shoes, at Nordstrom and
Halls, are cushioned walking shoes with phenomenal growth in the
United States in recent years.
</P>
<P>
   Mephisto was developed in Europe 35 years ago and introduced in
this country as a walking shoe a little more than eight years ago.
The styling has evolved recently from an athletic look to include
sandals, clogs and men's dress shoes. In the last year the company
has had a 60 percent to 70 percent increase in business, says Dick
Meckfessel, the Mephisto USA president.
</P>
<P>
   Fueled by high interest in health and comfort, the feel-good
shoe.MDBO/.MDNM/ concept is the ``fastest-growing shoe category,''
Meckfessel says.
</P>
<P>
   It has at least eliminated a splinter in the fashion aesthetic
of many fashion-minded people offended by working women in New York
and other cities who hiked to the office in their athletic sneakers
with dress pumps in their bags. They no longer have to change.
</P>
<P>
   Show your toes
</P>
<P>
   Certainly sandals of all styles are the news this summer,
whereas five years ago, Weitzman says he couldn't sell sandals.
NBC's Katie Couric has been wearing closed-toe chunky heel sandals
lately. And the rage in quirky colored toenail polishes is giving
women the opportunity to coordinate toe colors with open-toe shoes.
</P>
<P>
   But do you wear open sandals to work? Certainly guidelines of
what to wear and when have blurred. Not long ago few professional
women would have thought of pairing their business suits with shoes
that look fitting for the beach. But some women have no qualms
apparently in the Midwest and the East.
</P>
<P>
   David Wolfe, the analyst, says that after women stopped feeling
obligated to wear hosiery in the office last summer, it broke down
the final barrier to sandals.
</P>
<P>
   ``Personally, I'm not fond of looking at black toenail polish,''
he complains.
</P>
<P>
   Women who love shoes
</P>
<P>
   Certainly the array of shoes means mostly good news for women
who indeed love shoes.
</P>
<P>
   Marsha Watkins, who works in purchasing at Hallmark Inc. in
Kansas City, is delighted. She used to design her own clothing, so
she was very conscious of her shoes. Then a trip to Spain and a
look at the variety of leathers heightened her awareness of shoe
design and she began to appreciate even more the feet and shoes.
Now she may go out and buy up to 15 pairs at one time and estimates
her current collection at 180 pairs.
</P>
<P>
   Although she wears mostly dress pumps to work, she still is
open-minded. ``I don't believe in having one kind of shoe. I like
platforms, wedges. We are so lucky now. Nothing is unacceptable.''
</P>
<P>
   Then there is Maria O'Keeffe, who used to crave shoes. The
Hallmark artist loved shoes so much she bought high heels she
couldn't walk in on the streets in San Francisco where she lived at
the time and kept them packed in boxes at her office. She could
slip them on to tromp off across the room to the copy machine, say,
or a meeting.
</P>
<P>
   She loved shoes so much that she once found herself following a
woman through a Kansas City specialty store because she thought her
shoes were great.
</P>
<P>
   ``I was debating with myself, `Should I ask where she got them
or not?' Then I realized that I already owned those shoes and had
never worn them.''
</P>
<P>
   These days her priorities have shifted and she no longer
collects footwear, but she still has boxes of stilettos stacked in
her office (``for little children to play with''). And for the
record on this day, she is wearing a gray skirt, gray tights and
chartreuse suede sandals. Is that a shoe person or not?
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-06-09-98 1924EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
