<DOCNO> NYT19980609.0301 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-06-09 19:25 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A1520 &Cx1f; kan-z
r l &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-FASHION-HANNANT-KANSA     06-09 0815
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FASHION-HANNANT-KANSAS-KAN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
WEARABLE CREATIONS WITH FINE ART FLAIR 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 JACKIE WHITE  
 c. 1997 The Kansas City Star  
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ Douglas Hannant always thought he wanted to be a
painter. But after his first job as a display artist at Swansons,
the Kansas City upscale specialty store, in the 1980s, he never
felt quite the same about it.
</P>
<P>
   He went on to work in display at Macy's Midwest, Filene's
Basement in Boston and, eventually, Barney's in New York, but he
wasn't able to shake the obsessive drive to create clothes that
came upon him that first year in Kansas City.
</P>
<P>
   ``In that kind of environment for the first time, I think I
caught a bug at Swansons,'' the New York designer says now, more
than a decade later.
</P>
<P>
   By the summer of 1997, he had a showroom, a partner and retail
customers. His clothes had been showcased in the Fifth Avenue
windows of Bergdorf Goodman, New York's creme de la creme of
department stores.
</P>
<P>
   Then his life took an even brighter turn. He picked up the
support and endorsement from designer Geoffrey Beene, considered
one of America's foremost creators. After Beene saw his clothes at
Bergdorf's, he wrote an encouraging note to Hannant and later
called to offer his own showroom for his first press show last
fall.
</P>
<P>
   It was ``an unbelievable moment,'' Hannant says, when he
suddenly knew he was on his way.
</P>
<P>
   Creative urge
</P>
<P>
   Hannant is a dark-haired, handsome man in his 30s with a
straightforward manner, imploring eyes that betray a hopeful
vulnerability and a certain bravado. He grew up in rural Indiana,
about 100 miles north of designer Halston Frowick's home place.
</P>
<P>
   Against the initial protests of his family, he took up painting.
And like other Midwestern-bred designers such as Halston and Bob
Mackie, he admits that the monotony of his surroundings drove him
to creative thinking as a means of escape.
</P>
<P>
   ``You were always drawn to find something more exciting than
what you had,'' he says.
</P>
<P>
   He ultimately went to art school in Missouri and took a field
trip with a class to Kansas City, where he met couture buyer Ruth
Nan, then with Swansons. She helped him get a job in a display
department, and in a small ironic twist, Nan was in Beene's
showroom last fall for Hannant's first show. Her buy of his line is
bringing him back to Kansas City this month.
</P>
<P>
   Hannant's clothes are priced in couture designer range,
comparable to the Donna Karan Collection or Geoffrey Beene. A
jacket costs $1,200; blouses, $300; cardigans run to $1,500.
</P>
<P>
   The styling reflects an elegant ease, a decided sense of luxury
and a newness that, like an early morning dew, hasn't quite settled
in place.
</P>
<P>
   In his recent fall runway show, during New York fashion week,
Hannant's message centered on floor-sweeping wrap skirts trimmed
with leather strips tied to the side and very fluid pants. ``Pants
that fall like a skirt,'' he says. ``Very hip and modern.''
</P>
<P>
   He also introduced a puffy, shimmery new textile of mohair
encased in two layers of silk tulle. ``It's a fine arts approach,
like a sketch with a charcoal drawing,'' he explains. And he has
rights to a dry-cleanable fur that makes the lavish fur trimmings
he uses more feasible.
</P>
<P>
   His clothes are not for everyone, he acknowledges. He leans
toward close-cut silhouettes, and customers are often creative
people. ``Interior designers and architects,'' he says. ``People
who appreciate line.''
</P>
<P>
   That customer ``has to have a sophisticated eye, but then that
woman exists everywhere.... When I lived in Kansas, I dressed the
same way I do now.''
</P>
<P>
   He is confident that he has the right track. ``You have to
listen to your gut,'' he says about the creative process he goes
through tucked away at his isolated country home in Pennsylvania.
``No matter where I am I would design the same way.''
</P>
<P>
   His ideas, he insists, don't come from the streets or museum
exhibitions, and he staunchly resists trends and themes. ``I can't
imagine taking a trip, say to India, and designing a collection
around it.''
</P>
<P>
   He is on a quest for something special that he thinks women
want. He envisions himself working as a fine artist might, pulling
images from within, evolving with his own work, not with the
market.
</P>
<P>
   On the downside, it is still a formidable challenge to break
through the fashion establishment, and it's an ongoing struggle for
a newcomer without a wealthy backer to attract stores.
</P>
<P>
   ``You can do good fashion, but when you don't have $80,000 for
an ad in Vogue ...'' it's difficult, he says.
</P>
<P>
   And when his fall collection was small and his runway show
short, the trade journal Women's Wear Daily suggested he was short
on ideas as well.
</P>
<P>
   But never mind. His vision is focused on bigger things. Fashion
is art, he insists. ``Something beyond decorating the body. It's
shape built on the body.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
