<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-06-09 19:26 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A1522 &Cx1f; kan-z
r l &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-FLAG-DAY-KANSAS-KAN &LR;      06-09 0617
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FLAG-DAY-KANSAS-KAN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
A PATRIOTIC PAUSE FOR THE PLEDGE 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 EDWARD M. EVELD  
 c. 1997 The Kansas City Star  
<TEXT>
<P>
   So you never know quite what to do to commemorate Flag Day,
which is today, June 14. Besides flying the flag, of course.
</P>
<P>
   Stand around and recite the Pledge of Allegiance? Sing ``You're
a Grand Old Flag''?
</P>
<P>
   Well, yeah.
</P>
<P>
   As it happens, this Flag Day marks the 19th annual National
Pause for the Pledge of Allegiance, when people across the country
are asked to stop what they're doing at 6 p.m. (Kansas City time)
and recite the pledge.
</P>
<P>
   This may be the first you've heard of the National Pause. Pat
Perluke, a volunteer with the National Flag Day Foundation in
Maryland, is working on that.
</P>
<P>
   Flag Day and the National Pause are big deals at Fort McHenry in
Baltimore harbor, the spot where the Americans turned back the
British in 1814 and Francis Scott Key got the inspiration to write
``The Star-Spangled Banner.'' An all-day celebration is planned.
</P>
<P>
   Perluke and others with the foundation want that energy to
spread throughout the country. They've been working the last few
years with other national organizations to pump up Flag Day and
participation in the National Pause.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's important for an individual growing up in America to
understand the patriotic symbols of our country,'' Perluke said.
And Flag Day, after all, marks the day in 1777 the Second
Continental Congress adopted the Stars and Stripes as the national
flag.
</P>
<P>
   Barbershoppers, to name one group, want to help. At its meeting
in Kansas City in April, the board of the Society for the
Preservation and Encouragement of Barbershop Quartet Singing in
America voted to provide the musical backdrop for the National
Pause.
</P>
<P>
   Although the vote came too late for many barbershop chapters to
get organized this year, they're a patriotic bunch and hope to join
more Flag Day and National Pause events in coming years.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is right down the heart of our Main Street,'' said Reed
Sampson, spokesman at the society's national office in Kenosha,
Wis.
</P>
<P>
   Perhaps Flag Day's big participation problem is its proximity to
Independence Day, a national holiday that practically defines
summertime and patriotism with its cookouts, parades and fireworks.
Little Flag Day hardly stands a chance.
</P>
<P>
   The remedy, said Perluke, is to consider Flag Day the start of
the country's patriotic season and the Fourth of the July its
closing. In fact, the ``Twenty-One Days to Honor America'' _ June
14 to July 4 _ is an idea officially sanctioned by Congress.
</P>
<P>
   Perhaps the simplest way to kick off the season, then, is to
participate in the National Pause. It certainly won't take much
time. Francis Bellamy of Rome, N.Y., gets credit for writing the
original pledge and for keeping it brief.
</P>
<P>
   While campaigning to establish Columbus Day as a national
holiday in the early 1890s, Bellamy described his vision of flags
flying from coast to coast and wrote the words he thought Americans
should use to honor the banners:
</P>
<P>
   ``I pledge allegiance to my flag and the Republic for which it
stands, one nation, indivisible, with liberty and justice for
all.''
</P>
<P>
   The pledge has been embellished a bit over the years. In 1923
``my flag'' became ``the flag of the United States.'' In 1924 ``of
America'' was added. Congress recognized the pledge in 1942 and in
1954, as America grew worried about godless communism, added
``under God'' to follow ``one nation.''
</P>
<P>
   And so: ``I pledge allegiance to the flag of the United States
of America and to the republic for which it stands, one nation,
under God, indivisible, with liberty and justice for all.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
