<SLUG> BC-MOVIE-CAN'T-REVIEW-KAN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
CAN'T HARDLY WAIT IS FAR FROM MEMORABLE 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 ROBERT W. BUTLER  
 c. 1997 The Kansas City Star  
<TEXT>
<P>
   ``Can't Hardly Wait,'' a comedy, opens today and is rated PG-13
for teen drinking and sexuality and for language. Running time is 1
hour 35 minutes. Two out of four stars.
</P>
<P>
   If ``Can't Hardly Wait'' is remembered for more than five
minutes after the lights come up it will be for Ethan Embry, a
young actor who combines a pleasant goofiness with an aura of
genuine substance.
</P>
<P>
   Embry _ who was amusing as the nearly mute bass player in Tom
Hanks' ``That Thing You Do!'' _ provides the only genuine moments
in ``Can't Hardly Wait,'' a frantic but not very funny high school
comedy about the big party that unfolds on graduation night.
</P>
<P>
   With the entire class heading off in different directions, it's
the perfect time to end relationships, launch new ones, settle old
scores or initiate a major change in one's life.
</P>
<P>
   Not that anything of importance happens. The screenplay by
co-directors Deborah Kaplan and Harry Elfont (they also wrote ``A
Very Brady Sequel'') gives us a half dozen or so characters and
lets them collide amid much chaotic boozing and dancing.
</P>
<P>
   The big news on graduation day is that star athlete Mike (Peter
Facinelli) has dumped his girlfriend of four years, the gorgeous
Amanda (Jennifer Love Hewitt). Being college bound, the egoistic
Mike figures a full-time steady will be a drag on his dating style.
</P>
<P>
   This is great news for Preston (Embry), the bright but socially
uncool guy who has worshipped Amanda ever since she transferred to
the school in their freshman year. He still has the desperate love
letter he wrote to her way back then; tonight's party will be the
opportunity to deliver it.
</P>
<P>
   His plan elicits eye-rolling from his best friend, Denise
(Lauren Ambrose), a cynic whose intolerance of teen idiocy has made
her a perennial outsider. Nonetheless, Preston ventures forth,
determined to declare his everlasting love.
</P>
<P>
   Meanwhile, brainy geek William (Charlie Korsmo) and a couple of
his ``X-Files''-obsessed pals plot a public humiliation of top jock
Mike, who has made their high school years a living hell. And Kenny
(Seth Green), a white kid who ineptly affects a gangsta rap
lifestyle, ventures forth to lose his virginity, only to find
himself locked in a bathroom with the girl he used to pick on.
</P>
<P>
   Let's give Kaplan and Elfont credit for this, at least: they've
cast the film with young actors who look like real kids instead of
``Baywatch'' bimbos or Chippendale's hunks.
</P>
<P>
   But there's no getting around the fact that ``Can't Hardly
Wait'' is third-rate ``Dazed and Confused'' (or, if you will,
fifth-rate ``American Graffiti'').
</P>
<P>
   The acting is only as good as it needs to be. Hewitt is yet to
land a film role that allows her to do much more than look pretty
and scream (at some point she's going to have to tackle a role
without cleavage); the rest of the players are on so briefly that
they must rely on broad strokes to present their characters. Only
Embry makes it all worthwhile.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-06-09-98 1927EDT &QL; 
