<HEADER>
A1525 &Cx1f; kan-z
r e &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-MOVIES-SIXDAYS-REVIEW     06-09 0624
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-MOVIES-SIXDAYS-REVIEW-KAN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
SIX DAYS ISN'T ORIGINAL BUT IT WORKS 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 ROBERT W. BUTLER  
 c. 1997 The Kansas City Star  
<TEXT>
<P>
   ``Six Days, Seven Nights,'' an adventure romance, is rated PG-13
for language, sensuality and brief violence. Running time is 1 hour
36 minutes. Three out of four stars.
</P>
<P>
   Yes, it's wildly unoriginal. And, no, it hasn't a serious
thought in its head.
</P>
<P>
   But who's complaining? ``Six Days, Seven Nights'' works.
</P>
<P>
   This witty romantic adventure from director Ivan Reitman and
screenwriter Michael Browning is a frothy blend of genres _ mostly
screwball comedy, action film and buddy flick _ that borrows
shamelessly from a dozen other titles (``Romancing the Stone,''
``The African Queen,'' ``Father Goose'' and ``The Flight of the
Phoenix,'' for starters).
</P>
<P>
   But the movie nevertheless seems fresh and invigorating despite
this massive recycling. In fact, it's the perfect summer movie _
lightweight but never dumb.
</P>
<P>
   Of course it also has Harrison Ford in one of his most likable
performances, playing a gin-soaked, sun-baked, island-hopping bush
pilot who never met a drink or a pretty girl he didn't want to know
better.
</P>
<P>
   And let's quickly dispense with the issue prurient minds want to
know _ mainly whether audiences will accept actress Anne Heche, the
significant other of comic Ellen DeGeneres, in a hetero role.
</P>
<P>
   Here's the deal: The ghost of Ellen lingers over this production
for maybe the first two minutes, max. Heche is a good enough
actress that only the most homophobic viewer will be unable to
accept her in this part, and they'll be denying themselves the
pleasures of a very good comic performance.
</P>
<P>
   The setup is simplicity itself. Big Apple magazine editor Robin
Monroe (Heche) is treated by her fiance, Frank (David Schwimmer of
``Friends''), to a vacation on a tropical isle.
</P>
<P>
   When her boss orders her to a nearby island to oversee a one-day
photo shoot, she charters a flight with a pilot named Quinn (Ford),
a grizzled dropout who likes tinkering with things, whether they're
airplane engines or women.
</P>
<P>
   Robin is at first hesistant to get on board. ``Where's its
mommy?'' she wonders, eying the tiny craft.
</P>
<P>
   Her fears are justified. A storm drives them off course, fries
their radio, and sends them crashing onto the beach of an
unidentified island. The stranded duo bicker, forage for food and
become the object of a manhunt by a boatload of modern-day pirates.
</P>
<P>
   ``Pirates?'' Robin expodes in amazement. ``As in `Aaaargh'?''
</P>
<P>
   They also use their ingenuity to repair the seemingly
irreparable airplane.
</P>
<P>
   And did we mention that their relationship evolves from
backbiting to romance?
</P>
<P>
   Meanwhile, back at the resort, Frank goes through the various
stages of grief in about 20 minutes and finds himself being
comforted in a most imtimate fashion by Quinn's girl of the moment,
a dancer named Angelica (Jacqueline Obradors).
</P>
<P>
   It's almost too simple, yet it's all been executed with terrific
aplomb.
</P>
<P>
   There are a handful of very funny lines, but the real spark
comes from the two leads. Ford's wry charm has rarely been more
effective, and with his ability to combine sex appeal with
self-deprecation he's in the same league as Cary Grant.
</P>
<P>
   Heche is the real surprise, proving herself an adept physical
comedian with a polished sense of timing.
</P>
<P>
   And Schwimmer has several priceless moments as the faithless
fiance whose attempts at fidelity are doomed to failure.
</P>
<P>
   Director Reitman (``Twins,'' ``Dave'') handles it all with just
the right touch, tossing in plenty of drop-dead scenery and a
nail-biter of a tropical storm. Mostly, though, he lets his two
leads work their magic on the audience.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
