<SLUG> BC-FBN-GIANTS-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
FASSEL UNHAPPY WITH MILLER'S TARDINESS 
</HEADLINE>
  (mk) 
 By BILL PENNINGTON   
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   EAST RUTHERFORD, N.J. _ Giants linebacker Corey Miller arrived
at Giants Stadium for the team's passing camp on Tuesday, one day
later than coach Jim Fassel had been expecting him.
</P>
<P>
   Fassel made sure he told Miller he was not happy. Miller in turn
said he was a little bitter over the pay cut the Giants compelled
him to agree to last week.
</P>
<P>
   The two then said there would be no grudges kept. There was
plenty of evidence to the contrary.
</P>
<P>
   Miller, for example, said he wants a new contract after the 1998
season _ even though he is already under contract with the Giants
for 1999. And he insisted he wasn't going to give up his starting
job at strongside linebacker _ an assignment the coaches have
indicated could go to Marcus Buckley.
</P>
<P>
   Fassel, meanwhile, said that as head coach he can't get overly
upset every time a player disappoints him. Then, he added, ``But
you better be ready to keep score.''
</P>
<P>
   So a dispute over attendance at what is a voluntary June workout
was officially defused and yet perpetuated at the same time.
</P>
<P>
   Miller said he did arrive in New Jersey on Monday as he had told
the Giants he would. His flight from his South Carolina home
arrived at Newark Airport around 3 p.m. Fassel said he had expected
Miller to participate in Monday morning's workout and was
displeased that Miller did not call to say where he was.
</P>
<P>
   ``I guess the courteous thing to do would have been to call,''
Miller said. ``But I didn't think anything about it because it was
a voluntary camp. You apologize and move on.''
</P>
<P>
   Miller had more to say about his newly restructured contract, a
transaction that reduced his 1998 salary from $1.5 million to
$900,000.
</P>
<P>
   ``Am I happy about it?'' Miller said. ``Not at all. I'm not
angry, but I'm a little bitter about it. Not at anyone. But it's
something I think about every day. I'm using it as motivation. I've
got to prove to them my real worth.
</P>
<P>
   ``If I'm going to be viewed by stats, well then I've got to do
what's right for Corey Miller. I'm going to have a big year. And
when it's my turn, I'm going to be very aggressive about my
contract.''
</P>
<P>
   And though his Giants contract expires after the 1999 season,
Miller believes he will be in a good bargaining position for a
raise after this season.
</P>
<P>
   ``They made a business decision,'' said Miller, who added that
the Giants assured him he would get the opportunity to rush the
passer more this year. ``But so will I.''
</P>
<P>
   As for his starting job, Miller said the competition with
Buckley and the second-year player Ryan Phillips will be good for
the team.
</P>
<P>
   ``But I'm still the starter,'' he said. ``I'm very confident
that my role will be the same as it was last year.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
