<SLUG> BC-CANTORS-CONCERT-REVIEW-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
MUSIC REVIEW: DEVOTION AND VIRTUOSITY IN THE CANTORIAL TRADITION 
</HEADLINE>
   (bl)  
 By ALLAN KOZINN   
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ To commemorate the 50th anniversary of the founding
of the Cantors Assembly, nearly two dozen cantors from synagogues
across the country took to the stage of Carnegie Hall on Monday
evening and performed classic settings of prayers from the Sabbath
and holiday services. That the concert had a celebratory quality
was not surprising: the assembly's aim was to put its most
virtuosic members in the spotlight and to honor the compositions of
several generations of cantors.
</P>
<P>
   Still, a few clouds hovered over the event. The organization was
started because its founders believed that the art of cantorial
singing was imperiled.
</P>
<P>
   Many of Europe's best cantors died in the Holocaust, and
liturgical compositions that existed only in unpublished
manuscripts were lost or destroyed. Cantors who had immigrated to
the United States early in this century, however, had established a
cantorial tradition here, and the Cantors Assembly has built on
that.
</P>
<P>
   But now cantors face a new challenge: traditional cantorial
singing, with its combination of operatic dramatic style and
melismatic elaboration in Middle Eastern modal scales, is rapidly
falling out of fashion. At many Orthodox and Conservative
synagogues, young congregants object that virtuosic singing shifts
the attention from the text to the cantor. In any case, the current
preference is for the more direct, folksy prayer settings by Rabbi
Shlomo Carlebach and his followers.
</P>
<P>
   It may seem surprising that synagogue music is as susceptible to
trends as other musical forms. But the kind of cantorial singing
heard at Carnegie dates back less than 200 years, making it a
recent development by Jewish standards. Still, several of the
compositions on the program captured and evoked the devotional
spirit with an artistry and depth of feeling that the newer style
has not yet matched.
</P>
<P>
   Moshe Ganchoff's ``Atoh Yodea'' (``You Know All Mysteries'') and
Pierre Pinchik's ``Rozo d'Shabbos,'' a mystical prayer in Aramaic
about the preparation for the Sabbath, use florid, modal passage
work both as an evocation of antiquity and as a way to touch the
heart. Jacob Ben-Zion Mendelson and Faith Steinsnyder Gurney,
respectively, gave them stunning, emotionally unguarded readings.
The leaps in the melody line of Max Helfman's ``Shema Koleinu''
(``Hear Our Voices'') made for a theatrical setting, but Melvin
Luterman's commanding performance brought the work's more serious
grounding into focus.
</P>
<P>
   Other highlights of the three-hour program included Yossele
Rosenblatt's invitingly elaborate version of ``Uvenucho Yomar''
(``And When the Ark Rested'') sung by Farid Dardashti and Dov Keren
with a cantorial choir, and Louis Lewandowski's choral setting of
Psalm 150, which had an almost Handelian punch. Sol Zim, singing
his own ``Al Shlosh Dvorim'' (``On Three Things'') and David
Propis, singing Joseph Gross' setting of ``Ani Ma'amin'' (``I
Believe With Perfect Faith'') represented a more ebullient, Hasidic
approach to prayer.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
