<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-ALICE-THEATER-REVIEW-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
`TINY ALICE': ONTOLOGICAL BUT FUN 
</HEADLINE>
  (Eds: Production notes at end of review.) 
(mk) 
 By BEN BRANTLEY   
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   HARTFORD, Conn. _ The play, all too fittingly, is about a
crucifixion of sorts. And when it opened on Broadway late in 1964,
many critics and theatergoers felt they had been handed a
custom-made hammer and set of nails to use on its author. Edward
Albee, at that moment, was still garlanded in the success of 1962's
``Who's Afraid of Virginia Woolf?,'' and he had been thrust onto
cultural heights that have not been visited since by an American
playwright. The successor to Williams and Miller, he was being
called; the future of the country's theater.
</P>
<P>
   Then along came ``Tiny Alice,'' and the nasty, protracted
lynching of Albee, which would continue for a good two decades,
began in earnest. What was this self-important, pretentious
gobbledygook that Albee was trying to put over? Even respectful
reviews expressed irritation and puzzlement over the bizarre,
verbally dense and sexually lurid allegory about a man (played by
John Gielgud) in search of God; others went straight for the
jugular in alarmingly personal terms, describing the work with
phrases like ``homosexual nightmare.''
</P>
<P>
   Albee, never one to explain himself, was nonetheless reduced to
holding a news conference in which he asked if audiences ``really
want as little from the theater as those critics who believe they
reflect its taste would have them believe.'' He even cut his script
in hopes of clarifying the play's themes. People still scratched
their heads and muttered angrily, as they would through most of
Albee's other plays on Broadway, before he became its most eminent
pariah.
</P>
<P>
   It's hard not to feel slightly nostalgic for an era in which a
play could produce such heated debate as much because of its form
as its content. (Terrence McNally's as yet unseen ``Corpus
Christi'' has been attacked purely on the basis of the latter.)
Still, the dominant sensation in watching Mark Lamos' energetic,
engaging revival of ``Tiny Alice'' at the Hartford Stage Company,
starring Richard Thomas in a role he was born for, is nostalgia of
a different kind: for daring, original new plays as tightly
constructed, elegantly written and (most surprisingly) defiantly
funny as this one proves to be.
</P>
<P>
   For however enigmatic ``Tiny Alice'' may be, it practically
gallops through the story it has to tell, flashing wit like a
shark-toothed smile and reminding you that whatever Albee's faults,
he certainly knows how to hustle an audience's attention all the
way to the final curtain.
</P>
<P>
   Like the excellent Broadway revival of ``A Delicate Balance''
several seasons ago, this production finds the fierce theatrical
vitality with which Albee infuses his philosophical puzzles. Even
considering the unanswerable mysteries of faith and divinity, he is
as much of a showman, in his own literary way, as a Belasco or a
Barnum.
</P>
<P>
   The plot of ``Tiny Alice,'' in coldblooded summary, is
definitely off-putting. Brother Julian (Thomas), a lay secretary to
a Catholic cardinal (Tom Lacy), is enlisted as an intermediary
between the church and the glamorous, Croesus-like Alice (Sharon
Scruggs), who is considering donating a hefty chunk of her millions
to the institution.
</P>
<P>
   Julian, who years earlier suffered a nervous breakdown over his
inability to reconcile his idea of God with its earthly
representations, finds himself drawn into the sinister menage of
Alice and her present and former lovers, the unctuous, amoral
attorney known simply as Lawyer (Gerry Bamman) and a droll, breezy
butler called Butler (John Michael Higgins). Alice's castle of a
home becomes Julian's, too, and he falls in love with his hostess
while everyone around him conspires to bring him to the sensational
martyrdom he has, on some level, always sought.
</P>
<P>
   That's the easy part. ``Tiny Alice'' is packed with enough
symbols to inspire a century's worth of doctoral theses. Albee's
ingenious twist here, however, is to use symbols with dogged
literal-mindedness. The cardinal, for example, is shown in the
play's opening scene to keep pet cardinals in a cage that resembles
a Gothic cathedral. Alice's castle is represented in miniature in
her library (the formidable replica is the cornerstone of John
Arnone's appropriately iconographic sets). Alice herself, it
develops, is only a stand-in for the more universal spirit Julian
has always courted.
</P>
<P>
   Albee carries this idea of symbol versus substance through to
everything from the jousting, pun-filled dialogue to the names of
the characters. What he is doing is portraying the simple-minded
inadequacy of human shorthand for the unknowable, exactly what
Julian has rebelled against and what also finally undoes him. As a
theatergoer, you're sunk if you don't find the levity in this.
Albee's themes are dead serious, but his portrayal of them is
deliberately jokey.
</P>
<P>
   This is appropriate for a playwright who cites both Sophocles
and Noel Coward as his spiritual ancestors. Lamos often emphasizes
the Coward-ish aspect, flavoring the work's semantic volleys with
the lightness and crispness of drawing-room badinage.
</P>
<P>
   Ms. Scruggs flounders a bit in the role created by Irene Worth
(which is understandable once you realize what the part is), and
presenting her, in Constance Hoffman's nouveau riche costumes, as a
Women's Wear Daily-style socialite was not a good idea. But the
others, especially Higgins, find appealingly varied balances of
archness and weary malice that set off the concentrated earnestness
of Thomas' performance.
</P>
<P>
   From his time as a television idol as good old John-Boy Walton,
Thomas has glowed with an aura that mixes passion, anxiety and
innocence, and it's the perfect combination for the doomed,
spiritually questing Julian. Amid the barbed worldliness of the
play's other characters, he remains untouched by irony, as sincere,
worshipful and baffled in his erotic attraction to Alice as he is
in his piety.
</P>
<P>
   Thomas hasn't found the variety and modulation required to sell
his difficult final monologue, a stumbling block in any production
of ``Tiny Alice.'' Otherwise he is nearly flawless, and it's hard
to imagine any actor so suited to the function Albee has said
Julian should serve: ``Brother Julian is in the same position as
the audience. He's an innocent. If you see things through his eyes,
you won't have any trouble at all.''
</P>
<P>
   That was certainly not the consensus in 1964. But audiences who
have since sat through television shows like ``Twin Peaks'' and the
conspiracy-theory movies of Oliver Stone have surely grown more
tolerant of sinister ambiguity as a basis for mainstream
entertainment. There's plenty of ontological cud to chew in ``Tiny
Alice.'' But you can just as easily approach it as a chilling
Gothic potboiler with cosmic implications. Perceived on that level,
it's at least as much fun as ``The X-Files.''
</P>
<P>
   PRODUCTION NOTES:
</P>
<P>
   `TINY ALICE'
</P>
<P>
   By Edward Albee; directed by Mark Lamos; sets by John Arnone;
costumes by Constance Hoffman; lighting by Donald Holder; sound by
David Budries; production dramaturg, David Allen; associate
director, Ned Canty; production stage manager, Deborah Vandergrift;
assistant stage manager, Kevin Thompson. Presented by Hartford
Stage, Michael Wilson, artistic director; Stephen Albert, managing
director. In Hartford.
</P>
<P>
   With: Richard Thomas (Brother Julian), Gerry Bamman (Lawyer),
Tom Lacy (Cardinal), John Michael Higgins (Butler) and Sharon
Scruggs (Miss Alice).
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
