<SLUG> BC-SOC-WORLDCUP-ADVANCE-LADN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
WORLD CUP KICKS OFF
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By SCOTT FRENCH 
c.1998 Long Beach Press-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   PARIS _ The planet's premier event sporting or otherwise has the
world's attention focused squarely on France, where the World Cup
soccer championships kick off Wednesday amid fears of mayhem that
imperil this proud land's image and its well-being.
</P>
<P>
   Thirty-two nations, eight more than ever before, are set to
compete in the 16th edition of the tournament, a
multibillion-dollar affair in which so many side issues from the
threat of terrorism to the pursuit of the almighty franc threaten
to overshadow what occurs on the field.
</P>
<P>
   The tournament, devised 70 years ago by Frenchman Jules Rimet
and contested every four years since 1930 (with a 12-year lapse
during and immediately following World War II), also possesses
great unifying power, bringing together the world in ways nothing
else, not even the Olympics, is capable.
</P>
<P>
   An estimated 37 billion people from every country on Earth will
tune in to some part of the World Cup over the next month, with
nearly 2 billion watching when the champion is determined July 12
at the futuristic Stade de France in Saint-Denis, a Parisian suburb
where the tournament will begin Wednesday when reigning champion
Brazil takes on Scotland.
</P>
<P>
   More than a half-million people are expected to trek to France
for the event, which will feature 64 matches in 10 stadiums around
the country, in Bordeaux, Lens, Lyon, Marseille, Montpellier,
Nantes, Saint-Etienne, Toulouse and at two venues in Paris, the
Parc des Princes and the Stade de France.
</P>
<P>
   The event kicked off Tuesday night with the spectacular ``La
Fete du Football,'' four processions through Paris culminating in a
wild celebration at the Place de Concorde. At its center are four
six-story tall ``giants,'' representing the Americas, Asia, Africa
and Europe, which will meander through the streets of Paris,
accompanied by thousands of dancers, musicians and acrobats in a
five-hour spectacle that will shut down the capital.
</P>
<P>
   The figures' meeting at Concorde signifies the power of the
World Cup, its capacity to unify, to bring the planet together in
celebration of what is known as ``the people's game.''
</P>
<P>
   But as the Brazilians, who are seeking an unprecedented fifth
championship, and the host French and Italy and Spain and another
half-dozen serious contenders for the title capture the world's
focus, diverse forces are expected to attempt to divert attention
from the game to other matters.
</P>
<P>
   Some 7,000 police officers, augmented by security forces from
other countries and from the French Foreign Legion, are spread
throughout the country, many watching for terrorist action. More
than 100 Muslin extremists, most with ties to Algeria's
fundamentalist regime, have been arrested in advance of the Cup,
but officials acknowledge that the threat of trouble remains.
</P>
<P>
   More problematic may be transportation strikes that could
cripple the ability of fans to move about from venue to venue. Air
France pilots have been on strike for more than a week, and rail
workers are slated to walk off the job on Wednesday. Subway and bus
strikes, and road shutdowns by truckers have been threatened. Any
such action reflects poorly on the French.
</P>
<P>
   ``For some days, France will be at the center of attention for
the whole world, host to the entire planet,'' French president
Jacques Chirac said last week. ``Our welcome must be exceptional
and perfect, and I hope that everyone will display a spirit of
responsibility.''
</P>
<P>
   Anything less could affect profits. Tournament organizers expect
receipts of $400 million, with advertisers and merchandisers
reaping far more. It is possible to purchase just about anything
with some relationship to the Cup, from condoms to candy to the
usual T-shirts and flags.
</P>
<P>
   What really matters will occur on the fields, the ``pitches,''
in the parlance of the sport. The Brazilians, featuring a potent
lineup starring 21-year-old superstar Ronaldo, are widely
considered favorites, although their form leading up to the Cup has
been spotty. Several other teams, including Yugoslavia and Germany
two of the United States' three first-round opponents also are in
the hunt; the majority, including the Americans, would consider far
less to be success.
</P>
<P>
   The U.S. squad, competing in its third successive Cup, opens
Monday against the Germans at Parc des Princes. Only the top two
teams in each of eight groups qualify for the knockout phase, so
the Americans need to overcome either the Germans, who are
three-time champions, or the Yugoslavs (June 25 in Nantes),
possibly the most talented team in the tournament.
</P>
<P>
   The other U.S. foe promises confrontation of a different sort.
But neither the Yanks nor Iran, who face off June 21 at Stade
Gerland here in Lyon, consider the meeting anything more than a
sporting clash.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By The PRESS TELEGRAM, LONG BEACH, CALIFORNIA
</P>
</TEXT>
