<HEADLINE>
U.S. ATTORNEY SAYS TEXAS PROSECUTOR'S OFFICE FACES CRIMINAL PROBE 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By DANE SCHILLER  
 c.1998 San Antonio Express-News  
<TEXT>
<P>
   VICTORIA, Texas _ Federal prosecutors told the U.S. District
Court Tuesday that they are investigating a South Texas district
attorney's office for criminal wrongdoing. It was the first time
authorities have admitted the criminal probe since thousands of
documents were seized from the Webb County courthouse late last
month.
</P>
<P>
   Assistant U.S. Attorney Don DeGabrielle argued against having to
return the criminal files that FBI agents seized from District
Attorney Joe Rubio's office in Laredo.
</P>
<P>
   ``These (files) are evidence, in the government's opinion, of
criminal wrongdoing,'' DeGabrielle told Judge John Rainey at a
hearing here.
</P>
<P>
   But Rubio's attorney, Donato Ramos, countered that the seizure
of the files has crippled operations in Rubio's office and has left
state prosecutors unable to do their jobs.
</P>
<P>
   ``Unless we immediately get these files back, it will be
extremely difficult and nearly impossible for the district
attorney's office to continue to function,'' Ramos said.
</P>
<P>
   At Rainey's urging, federal prosecutors agreed to return the
approximately 5,000 criminal case files in increments.
</P>
<P>
   Rubio, who was not called as a witness during the two-hour
hearing, sat quietly beside two lawyers representing him, as an
individual, and the district attorney's office.
</P>
<P>
   ``We are satisfied with the outcome,'' Rubio said outside the
courthouse. ``Hopefully, we will be able to get the office back to
100 percent within two weeks.''
</P>
<P>
   Rainey signed a series of still-sealed search warrants used by
FBI and Internal Revenue Service agents to raid Rubio's office, as
well as homes and other offices in Laredo homes, the weekend of May
29.
</P>
<P>
   The judge ordered both sides to agree on what to do about the
files, which the FBI hauled from Rubio's office in a truck, or he
said he would do so on his own.
</P>
<P>
   ``We have an on-going investigation. We have to be sensitive to
both sides concerned,'' Rainey told the lawyers.
</P>
<P>
   The two sides agreed the FBI would begin returning the files in
increments starting next week and would complete the transfer by
June 26. Some files already have been returned, the court was told.
</P>
<P>
   DeGabrielle said the FBI already had taken steps to accommodate
Rubio and his staff by making some copies available and allowing
Rubio and his staff to assist when the files were seized in the
raid.
</P>
<P>
   ``We normally don't allow people potentially charged with
criminal offenses to participate in the execution of a search
warrant,'' DeGabrielle told the judge.
</P>
<P>
   ``We are certainly very mindful of the disruption of the
execution of this warrant,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   At least 142 people in Laredo have been drawn into the federal
probe. Among them are Rubio, his father, a bail bondsman,
prosecutors and investigators in Rubio's office, a justice of the
peace and a former state district judge.
</P>
<P>
   Documents that are a portion of one search warrant, which were
obtained by the San Antonio Express-News, show the federal
prosecutors are looking into the way Rubio's office handled at
least 128 criminal case.
</P>
<P>
   In particular, the investigation is looking at what Rubio's
office did in dropping charges, agreeing on plea-bargains, and
sending some suspects to pre-trial diversion programs rather than
proceeding to trial.
</P>
<P>
   Investigators apparently are examining possible links between
the way those decisions were made and the personal finances of 14
people, including several in the district attorney's office.
</P>
<P>
   FBI agents seized personal bank records, check books, income tax
returns, expense accounts and other individual records in addition
to the criminal files.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS.) &QL; 
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Meanwhile, Rubio's lawyers backed away from their earlier
threats to ask Rainey to unseal confidential documents related to
the case and to challenge the basis for the FBI's search.
</P>
<P>
   But Ramos told the judge that Rubio's office needs more time to
consider arguments over unsealing the documents, particularly the
affidavit federal agents used to secure the warrants.
</P>
<P>
   Rainey gave lawyers for Rubio and the San Antonio Express-News,
which also has asked the court to unseal the documents, until
Tuesday to file briefs with him.
</P>
<P>
   The judge said he would decide within two weeks whether to issue
an order or set a hearing on the motions to unseal the information.
</P>
</TEXT>
