<SLUG> BC-SOC-WORLDCUP-BRAZIL-LADN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
BRAZIL LOOKING LIKE ANYTHING BUT FAVORITES
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By SCOTT FRENCH  
 c.1998 Long Beach Press-Telegram  
<TEXT>
<P>
   PARIS _ There's Ronaldo, of course, the world's premier soccer
player. And there's Roberto Carlos, who may be even better. And
there's Leonardo and Bebeto and Denilson and Edmundo and Dunga and
Cafu and Giovanni ... the list goes on and on.
</P>
<P>
   Brazil, which takes what it hopes will be the first step toward
a pentacampeon
</P>
<P>
   an unprecedented fifth World Cup championship when it meets
Scotland in the tournament opener this evening at the Stade de
France in Saint-Denis, has as impressive a collection of soccer
genius as might be imagined.
</P>
<P>
   What Brazil doesn't appear to have is a very good team
</P>
<P>
   if all the hype suggests it must be favored to hoist the trophy
come July 12, then few are buying into it.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is a pale imitation of the glory days of Brazilian
football ...,'' charged Antonio Pimenta, the managing editor of
Estado e Sao Paulo
</P>
<P>
   . ``There is no collective game, no synchronization. It's every
player for himself, and (Coach Mario) Zagallo has a lot to do with
this.''
</P>
<P>
   Zagallo, who has been a player or coach for each of Brazil's
four titles, has taken the brunt of criticism for his squad's
ragged play leading up to the World Cup. The tenor of the damnation
goes something like this: He is not fit to coach a team of Brazil's
stature ... he lacks the ability to orchestrate the talent at his
disposal ... he hasn't a clue and is clueless about that.
</P>
<P>
   ``What you will see in France is not real Brazilian football,''
says Carlos Alberto, who captained Brazil's greatest side to the
1970 World Cup crown. ``We have some wonderful players, but Zagallo
will not let them improvise. He has no right to manage the national
team.''
</P>
<P>
   Lance
</P>
<P>
   calls him ``incoherent,'' and O Globo
</P>
<P>
   claims he ``doesn't have to conditions to coach anything, much
less the national team.''
</P>
<P>
   Brazil's rabid fans lack faith, too. Only 11 percent of them
believe their squad is capable of the title, down from 70 percent
just last month. A series of lackluster performances, in a loss to
Argentina in late April, a draw with Spanish club Athletic Bilbao
last month, even in a romp over Andorra last week, hints that
somewhere, at sometime, this squad will fall.
</P>
<P>
   Even Zagallo's bosses aren't satisfied. They assigned Zico, the
greatest Brazilian player between Pele and Ronaldo, to serve as
``technical director''; it hasn't made much difference yet.
</P>
<P>
   Injuries have taken their toll; neither Romario nor Juninho are
with the team (and defenders Aldair and Andre Cruz are out today
with minor ailments), and if what remains Ronaldo, Roberto Carlos
and the like are indeed capable of anything, that includes failure.
</P>
<P>
   The evidence is everywhere, and it's been mounting since
February, when a lesser Brazilian side settled for ties with
Jamaica and Guatemala and lost to the United States at the CONCACAF
Gold Cup. Zagallo shrugged off the performances, saying that ``the
real Brazil always shows up when it matters.''
</P>
<P>
   It matters now, and the team hasn't shown up yet. It lacks focus
and leadership, and there have been several disputes in camp, most
involving the mercurial Edmundo, who has fought with Leonardo, been
in a skirmish with Junior Baiano and openly criticized Zagallo's
decision to start Bebeto in Romario's stead.
</P>
<P>
   But there's also all that talent, and it must count for
something.
</P>
<P>
   ``If Brazil loses, it's absurd,'' says Leonardo. ``If we win,
it's normal.''
</P>
<P>
   Says Ronaldo: ``In Brazil it is victory or exile there is
nothing in between. ... I believe in this team.''
</P>
<P>
   ``I still believe,'' Leonardo adds, ``that Brazil will be
champions. But I also know one mistake and it will be over.''
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By The PRESS TELEGRAM, LONG BEACH, CALIFORNIA
</P>
</TEXT>
