<HEADLINE>
GALAXY ADJUSTS TO WORLD CUP
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By FRED J. ROBLEDO  
 c.1998 San Gabriel Valley Tribune  
<TEXT>
<P>
   PASADENA -- Anyone looking for Galaxy coach Octavio Zambrano
this morning won't find him.
</P>
<P>
   Practice is cancelled. And there's a simple reason why . . . The
World Cup has started.
</P>
<P>
   Zambrano's message was clear: Don't phone his office or reach
him at home, because he's not sure where he'll be.
</P>
<P>
   ``Well, I know I won't be in the office, there's too much going
on there,'' Zambrano said. ``I don't want to be disturbed with
phone calls and questions while the games are on.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'll be watching them at home, by myself,'' he said
cautiously. ``Change that, I won't be at home. I'll be at a place
where nobody knows where I'm at. I'll be incognito, a special
place. I just don't want to be bothered, I need to concentrate on
the games.''
</P>
<P>
   All practices aren't cancelled this month, but Zambrano did
decide to give his team a couple of days off this week. The Galaxy
leads the league with a 12-2 record.
</P>
<P>
   The Galaxy, which only has four games scheduled during the World
Cup, doesn't play again until June 18, when it plays host to
Colorado at the Rose Bowl.
</P>
<P>
   ``I gave the guys a couple of days off this week to relax,''
Zambrano said. ``We've been going full steam since the season
started, and since the World Cup is beginning, I thought they
deserved a day off to enjoy the opening game and get their juices
going again.''
</P>
<P>
   Actually, Zambrano has changed the entire practice schedule
during the World Cup. Instead of practicing at 9:30 a.m., the team
won't start until 5 p.m.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think we all should be at home watching the games,''
Zambrano said. ``I don't want to be in practice thinking about the
Brazil score or have the players thinking about a particular
game.''
</P>
<P>
   For Zambrano, the World Cup is like a coaching video.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm a student of the game,'' he said. ``I see the game not so
much from the fans' viewpoint or just to see a good match. I watch
the different strategies used by different coaches. For me, it's
more of an analytical thing. I want to learn more about the games,
that's why I don't want to be disturbed when I'm watching them.''
</P>
<P>
   From a mental standpoint, practice following the games will make
the players more competitive.
</P>
<P>
   ``Without a doubt,'' Zambrano said. ``I think anytime you watch
a sporting event of high caliber, it pumps you up. How many people
go out and play basketball when a game is over?
</P>
<P>
   ``When you see a Michael Jordan play, it gives you the urge to
go and play hoops yourself. That's what's going to happen. We will
watch the greatest players in the world showcase their skills and
it will give us an energy boost when we get to practice.''
</P>
<P>
   Defender Greg Vanney is looking forward to the evening sessions,
but says it won't be fun for everyone.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think the wives might not be too happy about it,'' he said.
``But for us, we'll get more out of it. I think these games will
motivate us and the practices will show that when we get there.''
</P>
<P>
   Midfielder Martin Machon says it will certainly change his
routine.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'll be waking up early in the morning,'' he said. ``All the
things I'm used to doing will change during the day.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's for the better though. This is a time when you can
actually enjoy the best soccer in the world. In the end, it will be
good for everyone because it will be a full month where our days
consist of soccer all day long.''
</P>
<P>
   -30-
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By The SAN GABRIEL VALLEY TRIBUNE, WEST COVINA,
CALIFORNIA
</P>
</TEXT>
