<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-EIDENBERG-COX </SLUG>

<TEXT>
<P>
   CEO belives mergers driven by rapid advances By Chris Burritt
</P>
<P>
   C. 1998 Cox News Service
</P>
<P>
   ATLANTA _ Although he dismissed the latest speculation British
Telecom might target his own company, Bell Atlantic Corp., the
chief executive of the biggest Baby Bell predicted further
consolidation in the global telecommunications industry.
</P>
<P>
   Bell Atlantic Chief Executive Ivan Seidenberg said Tuesday that
rapid advances in information technology are driving mergers and
acquisitions. The result: Giant companies are selling bundles of
services ranging from Internet access to local telephone service,
to consumers and to corporate America.
</P>
<P>
   The trend would accelerate, Seidenberg said, if the U.S.
government eased regulations over emerging technologies such as the
Internet.
</P>
<P>
   ''The single best thing regulators could do to jump-start
investment in new technologies is to move out of the way faster,
leaving pricing and investment decisions to the marketplace, where
they belong,'' Seidenberg said in luncheon remarks at SuperComm,
the communications conference at the Georgia World Congress Center.
</P>
<P>
   Seidenberg didn't specify which companies he thought might be
ripe for acquisition. But the big trade show, which runs through
Thursday, is abuzz with talk of the big deals of recent months _
and of others that could be in the works.
</P>
<P>
   With its acquisition last year of Nynex Corp., Bell Atlantic is
the biggest Baby Bell _ for now. San Antonio-based SBC
Communications Inc. is set to become the biggest, with its proposal
to buy Ameritech. It acquired Pacific Bell last year.
</P>
<P>
   Atlanta-based BellSouth Corp. has talked to potential partners,
but so far is flying solo amid the spate of mergers that has
companies now dwarfing BellSouth.
</P>
<P>
   On Tuesday, Emory University marketing professor Jagdish Sheth
told a gathering of industry executives that British Telecom, which
lost out to WorldCom Inc. in the bidding for long-distance carrier
MCI Communications Corp., might now seek a merger with Bell
Atlantic of New York.
</P>
<P>
   Sheth reasoned that both companies would benefit from the
massive flow of online information between New York and London,
where British Telecom is based.
</P>
<P>
   Later, Seidenberg told reporters, ''I do not see that as
realistic. But you never say never.''
</P>
<P>
   Rather than pursue acquisitions, Bell Atlantic is expanding its
high-speed data services, such as the Internet, to attract more
customers. At the same time, Seidenberg said, the company will seek
alliances with providers of other services.
</P>
<P>
   ''We do not think you need to merge to become global,''
Seidenberg said. ''We think you need to improve your brand to
become global.''
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
