<HEADER>
A1576 &Cx1f; ttj-z
u s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-worldcup-HNS &LR;      06-09 1203
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-world </SLUG>
 cup-HNS  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By JOHN P. LOPEZ  
 c. 1998, Houston Chronicle  
PARIS _ They stood on lush grass under a bright Southern California
sun four years ago, hugging one another and taking turns kissing
what is probably the most cherished trophy in sports.
<TEXT>
<P>
   Their place in world soccer was secure. Their superiority was
unquestioned.
</P>
<P>
   Brazil was king.
</P>
<P>
   ``When you hold the World Cup in your hands,'' Brazilian striker
Bebeto said, ``it's like touching heaven.''
</P>
<P>
   No team has been more divine in the World Cup's 68-year history
than Brazil, which has won an unprecedented four championships and
redefined the game with a style and creativity all its own.
</P>
<P>
   Poetry in motion is not a clich for this marvelous team. It is
an edict from the millions of Brazilian fans every time the storied
yellow jerseys take the stage.
</P>
<P>
   For Brazilians, the game is not a game but a drama, in which the
actors need no introduction _ or surnames. Bebeto, Ronaldo, Dunga.
Every Brazilian knows those names well, and they know what to
expect of them.
</P>
<P>
   Victories are not a matter of how, or even how many, but, ``Was
it beautiful enough?'' Was it stylish moves and perfectly placed
one-touch passes? Was it dribbling through two defenders and
spinning heads with quickness? Was it curving passes to the only
spot on the field where a speeding yellow-shirted striker could
fire a shot? Was it attack, attack, attack and impossible skill
leading to impossible plays?
</P>
<P>
   And what about the faces? Could the drama be told with one
glimpse at a Brazilian player's face? Did he sufficiently writhe in
agony when the ball bounced off the crossbar? Was enough sweat
pouring off his brow? Did he bleed for the sake of the game? And
when he scored, did he sprint across the field flailing his arms,
pulling off his jersey and screaming an ear-piercing wail? Was it
the face of a king?
</P>
<P>
   Four years later, Brazil still has the look.
</P>
<P>
   There are numerous contenders for the ultimate prize, and
intriguing questions abound when it comes to Brazil's greatness.
Beginning today, 32 teams will play 64 games in hopes of winning
the World Cup.
</P>
<P>
   But as the 1998 World Cup tournament opens today at the Stade de
France in Saint-Denis with Brazil facing Scotland, Brazil seems
most capable of drinking from the Cup again.
</P>
<P>
   ``The (Brazilian) team we played in 1990 was great, the one in
1994 was great, but this one is better,'' said Scotland goalkeeper
Jim Leighton, who drew the unenviable task of trying to stop the
yellow and blue today, in a game expected to be seen by hundreds of
millions of people. ``They have more pressure on them than any team
in the world, but they seem to be at their best when the games mean
the most.''
</P>
<P>
   Four years ago, Brazil whipped through the tournament, actually
playing its poorest game in the final against Italy but winning the
Cup on penalty kicks. Brazil also is the only nation to have
appeared in every World Cup tournament and since 1958 only twice
has failed to reach at least the semifinals.
</P>
<P>
   Lest we forget, the acknowledged greatest soccer player in
history, Pel, was Brazilian.
</P>
<P>
   ``Reaching the finals of the World Cup always is in the back of
your mind,'' Brazilian striker Ronaldo said. ``When you are a kid,
when you play for the clubs, in Europe, you always think about
coming to the World Cup and winning it for Brazil. It's what you
have to do or you shouldn't go back home.''
</P>
<P>
   Still, recent outings have had Brazil's partying legion of fans
feeling less than festive about prospects for 1998.
</P>
<P>
   Today's game, while expected to be a Brazil victory, is
considered huge. It could serve as an indication for which
Brazilian team came to France, the one that has won all but three
international games since 1993, or the one that has lacked its
familiar flair and confidence in recent weeks.
</P>
<P>
   Only last week, the team could do no better than a 1-1 draw with
a professional club team from Spain, Athletico Bilbao. Earlier, the
Brazilians lost a pair of international exhibition matches against
Argentina and the United States. It also pulled out a sluggish 1-0
exhibition win over Paris club team Racing.
</P>
<P>
   Even today's opposing coach, Scotland's Craig Brown, said of the
Brazilians: ``In recent games, they have not played as a team. It
is one thing for a team to have excellent players, and Brazil
surely does. But they are not really playing as a unified team at
the moment. It is in moments like these that any team, including
Brazil, can be upset.''
</P>
<P>
   The recent efforts were so out of character for the Brazilians
that headlines such as, ``They looked like a flock of sheep,''
blared across the country.
</P>
<P>
   Also, a national poll regarding Brazil's World Cup prospects _
yes, they really had a national poll about this _ indicated 57
percent of the population was ``terrified'' Brazil would not win
the Cup. Some 31 percent said they were ``pessimistic,'' and only
11 percent predicted victory.
</P>
<P>
   ``Not winning is the unthinkable,'' Ronaldo said. ``We have to
come together, and we will. Really, we have only been together with
this full team for a few days. When we start playing for the Cup,
it will flow.''
</P>
<P>
   The biggest reason things have not flowed is the reason the
nation is concerned. Romario, the marvelous scorer of 1994, will
not play in the tournament after injuring a calf last month.
</P>
<P>
   Romario, who was expected to be an explosive veteran leader to
complement the talented Ronaldo, 21, will be replaced by 1994
veteran Bebeto, whom many consider past his prime.
</P>
<P>
   ``We had plans for this World Cup, but now they won't happen,''
Ronaldo said. ``Romario is a great player, the sort who makes the
difference and can decide a game.
</P>
<P>
   ``We are sad, but this does not mean that we shouldn't be
favorites. It doesn't mean we won't prove that Brazil is still
Brazil when we play Scotland. We can still win the Cup.''
</P>
<P>
   They can still put on the face of kings, for sure.
</P>
<P>
   Ronaldo, after all, seems capable of carrying this side.
</P>
<P>
   But what might prove the best weapon for this team is defense.
The keeper, Taffarel, is a 1994 veteran and proven stopper. And
defensive star Roberto Carlos was runner-up to Ronaldo for the
European Player of the Year last season.
</P>
<P>
   When Brazil has played its best, it often has been Roberto
Carlos starting some thrilling length-of-the-field attacks with his
array of moves and dribbles up the field.
</P>
<P>
   And when it hasn't been Roberto Carlos, it has been midfield
veteran Dunga, another longtime national-team member, starting the
attacks.
</P>
<P>
   ``I have to say that the current team is more talented than the
teams I have been on before, but it is not yet better
emotionally,'' Dunga said. ``When we start playing more intensive,
with more humility and less inconsistency, you'll see the Brazil
you want to see.''
</P>
<P>
   The kings want to keep their crown.
</P>
<P>
   Today, more than 80,000 fans at Stade de France and fans across
much of the world will get their first glimpse of the defending
champs.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't know if we will win, but we can win,'' Bebeto said.
``Brazil always can win. It's up to God and luck to decide if we
will do it.''
</P>
</TEXT>
