<HEADER>
A1579 &Cx1f; tic-z
r l &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-COLORADO-QUEST-AZR &LR;      06-09 0933
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-COLORADO-QUEST-AZR </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
GRAND QUEST SEEKS COLORADO RIVER'S FIRST BOATER 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by N.Y. Times News Service clients)  
 By SAM LOWE  
 c.1998 The Arizona Republic  
<TEXT>
<P>
   COTTONWOOD, Ariz. _ The path chosen by Doug Carithers is a
lonely one. It takes him into lost places and sites only a few will
ever visit as it winds through canyons and libraries, old books and
the Internet.
</P>
<P>
   Carithers is on a quest. He believes there's an error in
recorded history, and he thinks it should be fixed. So he has
devoted a substantial portion of the past 25 years hiking into
canyons, searching through history books, interviewing people,
poring over maps and looking for support.
</P>
<P>
   The object of this passion is one Denis Julien, a French trapper
and explorer who worked the canyons and rivers of Utah in the early
1800s. Julien's name appears infrequently in writings about that
time because he was associated with Meriwether Lewis for a while
and was involved in the Louisiana Purchase as a government agent.
</P>
<P>
   But Carithers maintains that Julien earned a niche in history
that is currently occupied by Maj. John Wesley Powell, the
geologist and anthropologist who became a national hero after
exploring the West. Powell's most famous journey began in Green
River, Wyo., in May 1869. It lasted three months, covered 900 miles
and didn't end until his group passed safely through the Grand
Canyon.
</P>
<P>
   Carithers has no disagreement with most of that. But one little
segment pushes him onward. It's the theory that during the epic
journey, Powell and his fellow travelers became the first White men
to traverse the Green and Colorado rivers in southeastern Utah.
Carithers maintains that Julien boated into the area years before.
And that he carved his name into the sandstone canyon walls to
prove it.
</P>
<P>
   Sometimes, Julien wrote his full name, followed by a date. Other
times, it was ``D. Julien'' or simply his initials, but always
dated. The years were all around 1836.
</P>
<P>
   ``There are eight known inscriptions carved into rock that tell
me Julien was there long before Powell,'' Carithers said while
tracing Julien's alleged route on a huge map hanging from the wall
of his home in Cottonwood. ``I've seen five of them.''
</P>
<P>
   Several of the inscriptions are near the confluence of the Green
and Colorado Rivers in Cataract Canyon, in Canyonlands National
Park in southeastern Utah. Carithers spent part of his formative
years in the area. His father was a National Park Service ranger at
Canyonlands and at Navajo National Monument in northeastern
Arizona, and he followed in his footsteps.
</P>
<P>
   He was a riverboat operator on the Green River for eight years,
three of them as a Canyonlands ranger like his dad.
</P>
<P>
   Now he's a car salesman in Cottonwood, but his search goes on,
most of it from his home.
</P>
<P>
   ``I've made a couple of trips back since leaving there in
1976,'' he said, ``but now I do most of my research here.''
</P>
<P>
   He has three notebooks filled with his personal observations
from his time on the river and interviews with anyone he can find
who might know anything about Denis Julien. He has them arranged in
book form and is looking for a publisher.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm not trying to detract from John Wesley Powell,'' he said.
``I only want to add to the legacy of Denis Julien. I want to get
his story out and put it in history books.''
</P>
<P>
   Carithers and early historians say the inscriptions prove that
Julien was in the canyons formed by the two rivers more than 30
years before Powell. But such claims are debunked by Powell
supporters, he says, because ``they sort of regard Julien as just a
greasy old fur trapper.''
</P>
<P>
   Powell biographers acknowledge the inscriptions but have
inferred that Julien didn't float down the rivers. Their contention
is that he trapped and hunted the riverbanks but never actually put
boat into water. They support that, Carithers said, by noting that
most of the inscriptions are on the same side of the rivers.
</P>
<P>
   But Carithers says at least one of the ancient pieces of
graffiti is across the water from the others and that there were
probably several others that have been eroded by time or washed
away by rising water.
</P>
<P>
   ``On the average, somebody discovers a Julien signature once
every 20 to 25 years,'' he said. ``The total is probably in the
dozens, but they're lost, disputed or not authenticated. Julien's
signature on a rock is the most sought-after inscription in the
West. It's the Holy Grail for people like me.''
</P>
<P>
   In the search, little scraps of information become milestones.
Carithers hauled out copies of the July 1933 ``Utah Historical
Quarterly,'' which contained an article titled ``The Mysterious D.
Julien.'' In it, the author quotes Frederick S. Dellenbaugh,
historian of Powell's two expeditions, who wrote in 1872:
</P>
<P>
   ``After about seven miles the trend of the canyon became more
easterly, and we saw the mouth of the Grand, the junction (of the
Green with the Grand) that hidden mystery which, unless we count D.
Julien, only nine White men, the Major's first party, had ever seen
before us.''
</P>
<P>
   The article also observes that a survey party later found the
name ``D. Julien'' carved into the rock in five different places,
all with the date of 1836.
</P>
<P>
   Carithers also scans the Internet for additional snippets of
information and has established contact with some supporters;
anyone interested in joining his search may contact him at
kemosabe(at)cybertrails.com via e-mail.
</P>
<P>
   ``Julien wasn't just a smelly old trapper,'' Carithers insisted.
``He deserves a place in history. I want to give him that.'' &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-06-09-98 2004EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19980609.0324 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-06-09 20:04 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A1580 &Cx1f; taf-z
u f &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-AIRPORT-MALLS-ART-2ND     06-09 0875
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-AIRPORT-MALLS-ART-2NDTAKE-NYT </SLUG>
  
 UNDATED: you'd like.'' 
<TEXT>
<P>
   Another issue for airport retailers is a shortage of good labor.
This problem bedevils the entire retail industry, of course, but
enticing employees to travel to far-flung, traffic-strewn locations
can be particularly rough. What is more, employee parking areas are
often 20 minutes from the airport, adding unpaid travel time to a
worker's day.
</P>
<P>
   Airport retailers also need staff on hand for much longer days,
because many airport companies, like BAA, insist that all stores be
open from the minute the first flight lands _ usually around 6 a.m.
_ to the time the last one pulls out, about 10 p.m.
</P>
<P>
   ``Denver is miles and miles from civilization, and they are
having staffing problems,'' said Bruce Van Kleeck, director of
member services for the National Retail Federation in Washington.
``And other airports are having real problems.'' Retailers said
they were being forced to add at least $1 an hour to employees'
wages to compete.
</P>
<P>
   Then there is inventory. Bringing it into the airport can be
tricky because of security issues and because airplanes take up the
space where a truck bay would be at a shopping center. Since the
stores themselves are so tiny, there is little space to stock
items.
</P>
<P>
   Pittsburgh has dealt with the problem by creating a
sophisticated _ and costly _ system in which inventory travels from
a stock room down the service road, through the airport on
underground carts and pops up inside the stores.
</P>
<P>
   ``At older airports you have to lug that inventory right through
security,'' said Ms. Byrd of Unison Consulting. ``The worst is when
you have a food vendor carting lettuce through a security
checkpoint, which is fundamentally unsightly.''
</P>
<P>
   While many people are in a hurry to get in and out of shopping
malls these days, the average time spent in an airport store can
literally be seconds, so efficiency is everything.
</P>
<P>
   At Tie Rack stores, for example, solid ties are bunched
together, so shoppers can go right to what they want, said Mary
Calder-Ricci, the company's senior regional manager. And chatter is
cut short. At a Main Street or mall shop, an employee might give
fashion advice, but ``in an airport you just want to help them get
out of the store,'' she said, adding that shoppers rarely wait for
gift wrap.
</P>
<P>
   Airport shoppers tend to want one of two things: something they
forgot to pack or a last-minute gift for a child or spouse left
behind on a business trip. Shops _ like the PGA Golf Stores and the
Discovery Channel or Smithsonian stores _ selling items that make
good, fast gifts tend to do well, said the experts. So do stores
with well-known names selling belts, scented soap or simple shirts.
</P>
<P>
   ``A lot of times you pack at the last minute, and so it is great
that they have basics here,'' said Gina Sataro, 29, who lives in
Hartford and who recently flew into National to visit her sister in
Washington. ``I blow past the souvenir shops. I'm not interested in
those.''
</P>
<P>
   And of course it has to fit in a suitcase. Victoria's Secret did
not do well with cushy robes, Johnson, the airport retail manager,
said, faring far better with filmy nightgowns.
</P>
<P>
   Airport stores have such limited space that they try to carry
only their best-selling items. The general rule is that retailers
will stock these shops with the 20 percent of their merchandise
that generates 80 percent of their sales. The Gap store at
National, for instance, has a smattering of basic sweaters, a few
cute baby outfits and a relatively small selection of jeans.
</P>
<P>
   A few hours spent at National seemed to underscore that shoppers
like to spend time in stores they know best. The Gap and Bath and
Body Works were relatively busy, while the National Zoo store was
fairly quiet. ``It seemed the stores have catered to where your
mind is when you're here,'' said Linwood Robinson, who lives in
Atlanta and was cruising the Gap after dropping his wife off.
``That's what makes it great. It has things you need.''
</P>
<P>
   Interestingly, the best customers tend to be people who work in
airports. At the Victoria's Secret store at National, for instance,
blue stockings, purchased by flight attendants, accounted for 18
percent of total sales this winter.
</P>
<P>
   At Altitunes Partners LP, a chain of airport-based music stores,
20 percent of the business comes from employees. Amy Nye Wolf, who
founded the company when she realized she was always getting tired
of the music she brought on long trips, said she has started
offering special discount programs to airport employees, and keeps
her stores well stocked with reggae, rap and heavy metal music.
</P>
<P>
   Many retailers are cagey about their airport strategy.
Spokeswomen for Gap Inc. and Intimate Brands, the unit of Limited
Inc. that operates Bath and Body Works and Victoria's Secret,
refused to comment on their smattering of stores or future plans.
</P>
<P>
   But many retail and real estate experts expect that more and
more retailers will try to move into airports. ``It does represent
a profitable new store strategy,'' said Jeffrey Green, president of
the Green Group, a real estate consultant in Detroit. ``But you
need the large number of connecting visitors to make it work
well.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-06-09-98 2004EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19980609.0325 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-06-09 20:04 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A1581 &Cx1f; tdt-z
b d &Cx13;  &Cx11;  ufshaughnessy &LR;      06-09 0794
</HEADER>
<BODY>
 ufshaughnessy 
<TEXT>
<P>
   CHICAGO _ Michael Jordan and Scottie Pippen appear to be on the
brink of winning their sixth championship together (despite the
nitwit antics of Dennis Rodman), which would be the same number of
rings Bill Russell won with Bob Cousy.
</P>
<P>
   Jordan is universally acclaimed as the best player ever, and
Pippen is a card-carrying member of the 1992 Dream Team and the
NBA's All-Time Top 50 Social Register.
</P>
<P>
   So what about it? Are Michael and Scottie the best tandem in the
history of the NBA?
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't think they're the best two guys to play together,''
said Red Auerbach, the only individual who has been part of the NBA
since its inception.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't think there's an answer. With Cousy and Russell, you
got the break and got the ball. It was the same with Jabbar and
Magic. With Jordan and Pippen, you've got movement, defense, and
everything else, but you're not sure you got the ball. It's hard to
make a comparison.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'd rather have Cousy and Russell than Jordan and Pippen.
Who's gonna get you the ball? You can't go anywhere without the
ball. Also, it would be very difficult for me to pick Jordan and
Pippen ahead of Jabbar and Magic.''
</P>
<P>
   Dr. Jack Ramsay, who won a world championship coaching the
Portland Trail Blazers, said, ``There's several ways of looking at
it. I think of a tandem as guys who feed off each other, and I'd
have to say Karl Malone and John Stockton do that more than any two
players I've seen. But as for the most talented duo, I'd have to go
with Jerry West and Elgin Baylor.''
</P>
<P>
   There are other perfect-pair candidates. Larry Bird, Kevin
McHale, and Robert Parish played alongside one another for 12
seasons and certainly stand as the greatest trio in NBA history.
Reduced to a pair, Bird and McHale are the obvious twosome, but
they never really fed off one another. Theirs was a Ruth-Gehrig
dynamic: two all-time greats with totally different personalities
and approaches to the game.
</P>
<P>
   The West-Baylor tandem ruled the NBA for more than a decade, and
when they retired, they were viewed as the best ever at their
respective positions. Then along came Magic Johnson, who reinvented
the guard position and got to play alongside Kareem Abdul-Jabbar
for 10 seasons.
</P>
<P>
   This correspondent won't forget a scene from Logan Airport
during the 1984 Finals. Those were the days of commercial air
travel for teams, and when the Lakers arrived in steamy Boston for
Game 5, there was tremendous traffic (what a surprise) and few
cabs. Kareem and Magic shared a taxi, which provoked an apoplectic
Bob Ryan to exclaim, ``How can they put them both in the same cab?
That's like letting the president and vice president ride in the
same aircraft!''
</P>
<P>
   Jordan and Pippen have been through it all together. They are
megatalents, made better by the presence of each other. Granted,
Pippen needs Jordan more than Michael needs Scottie, but Mike might
not have all those rings without the contributions of his sidekick.
Pippen's talents were masked in his early seasons, but Bird's eyes
were opened when he teamed with Pippen in Barcelona (conversely,
the Olympic experience somewhat diminished the reputation of the
estimable Malone). Pippen has proven to be something more than Ed
McMahon. And how often can a coach claim that his two top scorers
are also his best two defenders?
</P>
<P>
   Asked about Pippen, Jordan said, ``It's like playing with a twin
brother. It takes a lot of pressure off me offensively and
defensively. Defensively, it's nice to have another player out
there who works as hard as I do. Offensively, I think the best
thing that happened for Scottie was when I stepped away for two
years. Now his confidence is just as strong as mine. And his
competitiveness is just as strong as mine.''
</P>
<P>
   Pippen said, ``With Michael and myself, you have two guys out
there who are a total threat and who have all-around ability to
play hard on both ends of the court because it makes you more
dominant as a team. When Michael is not out there, I look to be
more aggressive on the offensive end. When he is out there, I look
to be more aggressive defensively because I feel that I can create
things on the defensive end that he can do on the offensive end.''
</P>
<P>
   The Jazz certainly experienced that Sunday when Pippen played
like an All-Pro strong safety, making the veteran Jazz look like a
high school junior varsity squad as the Bulls romped to a record
96-54 victory in Game 3 of the Finals.
</P>
<P>
   In head-to-head competition, Pippen and Jordan look for all the
world like a better twosome than Malone and Stockton. Historians
will have to decide the rest, but in a mythical game of two-on-two,
whom would you take over Scottie and Michael?
</P>
<P>
   &UR; ufauthor &LR;
</P>
<P>
   Dan Shaughnessy is a Globe columnist.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
