u w &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-MEDICARE-OPTIONS-NYT &LR;      06-09 0337
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-MEDICARE-OPTIONS-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
MAIN MEDICARE ALTERNATIVES AUTHORIZED BY CONGRESS 
</HEADLINE>
  (With MEDICARE-BENEFITS.) 
(th) 
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   Older Americans and some disabled people will soon have more
health insurance options. Here are the main alternatives authorized
by Congress. Different options will be available in different parts
of the country.
</P>
<P>
   ORIGINAL MEDICARE: Beneficiaries can use any hospital and can go
to any doctor who accepts Medicare patients. The government
regulates doctors' fees and most other aspects of the program.
</P>
<P>
   HEALTH MAINTENANCE ORGANIZATION: Patients must use doctors,
hospitals and suppliers approved by the HMO. But the plan may pay
for prescription drugs and other items not covered by the Medicare
program.
</P>
<P>
   HMO WITH POINT-OF-SERVICE OPTION: Patients meet most of their
medical needs by using doctors and hospitals on an approved list.
But they may go outside the network if they are willing to pay
extra.
</P>
<P>
   PREFERRED-PROVIDER ORGANIZATION: Beneficiaries may use any
doctors or hospitals, but are charged less if they use those on an
approved list.
</P>
<P>
   PROVIDER-SPONSORED ORGANIZATION: This plan is owned and operated
by the doctors and hospitals that provide most of the services to
beneficiaries.
</P>
<P>
   PRIVATE FEE-FOR-SERVICE PLAN: Patients may go to any doctor or
hospital, but there may be substantial costs for beneficiaries
because the federal government does not limit the premiums that may
be charged. The plan gets a fixed amount of federal money for each
beneficiary. Doctors are paid a separate fee for each service.
</P>
<P>
   MEDICAL SAVINGS ACCOUNT: Beneficiaries choose a private
insurance policy with a high deductible to cover catastrophic
expenses. Medicare pays the premium and deposits money in a savings
account, which is used to pay routine medical expenses. Patients
may have to use their money to pay medical bills if the savings
account is insufficient.
</P>
<P>
   Source: 1999 Medicare handbook; Balanced Budget Act of 1997.
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
