A1587 &Cx1f; tad-z
s f &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-PARAGON-COX     06-09 0468
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-PARAGON-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Patent infringement case leaks into bankruptcy court
 &HT;    By Tom Walker
 &HT;    c. 1998 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA _ The latest damage claims filed by Procter &AMP; Gamble and
Kimberly-Clark against Paragon Trade Brands might be likened to
attacking a mosquito with a howitzer.
</P>
<P>
   How else compare claims of up to $8.7 billion against a company
whose market value is just shy of $47 million, whose 1997 sales
totaled $562 million, and whose stock closed at $3.93 3/4 Tuesday,
down 50 cents?
</P>
<P>
   It's diaper warfare between Norcross-based Paragon, which makes
store-brand versions, and two giants that together own 74 percent
of the $3.6 billion disposable diapers market.
</P>
<P>
   Procter &AMP; Gamble makes Pampers and Luvs diapers. Kimberly-Clark
makes Huggies.
</P>
<P>
   The bankruptcy court filing by Paragon is part of a long-running
patent-infringement case over leak-proof diapers.
</P>
<P>
   A federal court ruled in December that Paragon infringed two
Procter &AMP; Gamble patents. In self-defense, Paragon shortly
afterward filed for Chapter 11 bankruptcy protection.
Kimberly-Clark has filed a similar suit against the company.
</P>
<P>
   Bobby Abraham, chief executive of the Norcross company, called
the action by the bigger companies ``an obvious effort to grossly
over-inflate their claims in order to force a settlement without
regard to the underlying value of the claims.''
</P>
<P>
   Neither company could be reached for comment, but some analysts
agree with Abraham.
</P>
<P>
   ``As a major private label supplier, Paragon is of great concern
to premium-brand companies,'' said Fred Allvine, a professor of
management at Georgia Tech. ``Private label companies are a major
source of price competition to P&AMP;G and Kimberly-Clark.''
</P>
<P>
   Ragen MacKenzie analyst Daniel F. Nelson said he takes Abraham's
comment at face value. ``These guys are probably trying to bully
the company (Paragon) into some sort of settlement, or make it look
so bleak some of its customers will give up,''
</P>
<P>
   If that's their motive, it isn't working, according to Alan J.
Cyron, chief financial officer. ``The court actions have not
affected our day-to-day operations. Our customers have been very
supportive,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   The numbers back him up so far. Paragon reported revenue of
$138.3 million for the first quarter ended March 27, up from $135.7
million a year earlier and $136.4 million in the fourth quarter.
The company posted a profit of $6 million, or 50 cents per share,
in the latest quarter.
</P>
<P>
   As for the future, Abraham said the company is working with the
creditors' committee, Procter &AMP; Gamble and Kimberly-Clark ``to
reach a reasonable business resolution as quickly as possible which
protects the interests of all our stakeholders.''
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
