<TEXT>
<P>
   The Los Angeles Daily News plans to move the following general
stories for use by NYTimes News Service clients, AMs and PMs of
Wednesday, June 10 and thereafter. For questions about stories,
contact Jeremy Bagott at the Daily News, (818) 713-3702.
</P>
<P>
   JDPOWER-HMO (Los Angeles) _ J.D. Power &AMP; Associates, the
marketing company, Tuesday released the results of its
second-annual health plan quality study. More than 80,000 plan
members in 20 U.S. markets were queried on their level of
satisfaction with their HMO, PPO, POS, etc. The results show HMOs
held their own against supposedly more customer-friendly plans like
PPOs. By Ben Sullivan. (Will move in the ``f'' financial news
file.)
</P>
<P>
   BASKIN-GIVEAWAY (Los Angeles) _ In a promotion sure to bring
brain freeze to overeager customers, Baskin-Robbins is giving away
free Cappuccino Blasts at 180 ice cream stores after 5 p.m. until
store closing today in Southern California, Connecticut and
Louisiana. Later this month, the same promotion will be offered in
Michigan and Northern California. By Deborah Adamson. (Will move in
the ``f'' financial news file.)
</P>
<P>
   CA-WHALE (Ventura, Calif.) _ A pod of humpback whales, called
the ``Ballerinas of the sea'' because of the aquatic acrobatics,
have come unusually close to the Ventura coast this year and have
taken up residence between Ventura and Santa Cruz Island. Drawn by
large plankton blooms and krill that have been stirred up by El
Nino, the humpbacks are breaching and nosing up to boats in the
area. By Don Holland. (Will move in the ``a'' national and ``n''
California news files.)
</P>
<P>
   DALLY-SENTENCE (Ventura, Calif.) _ Michael Dally is set to be
sentenced to life in prison this morning for the 1996 kidnapping
and murder of his wife, Sherri Dally. The jury voted 7-5 in favor
of a death sentence _ short of the unanimous vote that is required
for a death sentence. Prosecutors declined to retry the penalty
phase, meaning Dally will be automatically sentenced to life in
prison without parole. Last week his attorney requested a new trial
because of trial errors and alleged prosecutorial misconduct. The
judge is to rule on those issues before the sentencing. By Michael
Coit. (Will move in the ``n'' California news file.)
</P>
</TEXT>
