<HEADER>
A1594 &Cx1f; tta-z
u w &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-MEDICARE-BENEFITS-1     06-09 1441
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-MEDICARE-BENEFITS-1,000&AMP;ADD-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
MEDICARE RECIPIENTS TO GET NEW HEALTH INSURANCE OPTIONS 
</HEADLINE>
  (EDS: See sidebar, MEDICARE-OPTIONS.) 
(th) 
 By ROBERT PEAR    
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ Thirty-eight million Medicare beneficiaries will
soon be flooded with information about new health insurance
options, and most of them are likely to be thoroughly confused,
according to consumer advocates, members of Congress and Medicare
officials.
</P>
<P>
   The new options were created by Congress last year to give
beneficiaries a wider variety of choices, like those available to
many workers in private industry who receive insurance coverage
from their employers.
</P>
<P>
   But Michael Hash, deputy administrator of the Federal Health
Care Financing Administration, who is supervising the new program,
said that ``many beneficiaries do not understand the basics of the
original Medicare program,'' much less the exotic variations of
managed health care devised by Congress.
</P>
<P>
   The government plans an extensive education and publicity
campaign and will soon send a new Medicare handbook, with a
detailed description of all the options, to every Medicare
beneficiary's household.
</P>
<P>
   Federal officials said they had tested the materials in ``focus
groups'' of beneficiaries, and said the results were not
encouraging. Beneficiaries are often overwhelmed by the number of
choices, Hash said, and ``even well-educated beneficiaries have
difficulty understanding them all.''
</P>
<P>
   Illene Gordon, a caseworker for Senate Majority Leader Trent
Lott, R-Miss., predicted that congressional offices would ``be
flooded with calls'' from constituents baffled by the Medicare
options, which include not only health maintenance organizations,
but also preferred-provider organizations, provider-sponsored
organizations, medical savings accounts and private fee-for-service
plans.
</P>
<P>
   John Rother, director of legislation and public policy at the
American Association of Retired Persons, said, ``Most beneficiaries
will have a hard time sorting through the new choices because of
their complexity, and because the Medicare population has very
little experience with managed care. It's not what they had when
they were working. We can anticipate a high level of confusion.''
</P>
<P>
   The new options, most of which will become available late this
year, offer the possibility of extra benefits, including
prescription drugs and other items not covered by the standard
Medicare program, the national health care plan for the elderly.
But they may also expose beneficiaries to higher costs and more
uncertainty.
</P>
<P>
   Equally important, the new options represent a great national
experiment in health policy, enabling private health plans to
compete with Medicare's government-run insurance program. Consumers
will decide which model works best.
</P>
<P>
   Different options will be available in different parts of the
country, and no one knows for sure how many private health plans
will enter the potentially lucrative Medicare market. If
beneficiaries are satisfied with the way they get health care now,
they do not have to make a change.
</P>
<P>
   Six million beneficiaries are in an HMO or other type of managed
care today. The Congressional Budget Office predicts that the
number will soar to 17 million by 2008.
</P>
<P>
   Rep. Jim McDermott, D-Wash., a psychiatrist, said, ``I am really
worried that when 38 million beneficiaries _ 26 million households
_ get the new Medicare handbook, confusion will reign. Our casework
staff will be inundated with questions just before the November
elections.''
</P>
<P>
   Rep. Pete Stark, D-Calif., the ranking Democrat on the Ways and
Means subcommittee on health, said the handbook was ``a waste of
$40 million.'' In fact, he said, ``it could actually be worse than
a waste of money because of the confusion it will create for
seniors and their families.''
</P>
<P>
   An excerpt from the handbook reads: ``If you had a supplemental
policy and dropped it to enroll in a Medicare managed care plan, or
Medicare Select policy for the first time, and you choose to
disenroll from the Medicare health plan or Medicare Select policy
within 12 months of enrolling, then you can go back to the Medigap
policy you had before joining the Medicare health plan, if it is
still offered, or purchase Medigap policies A, B, C or F. This
protection is only available during the 63 days after leaving the
health plan.''
</P>
<P>
   Dr. Robert Berenson, director of Medicare's Center for Health
Plans and Providers, said he doubted that his 85-year-old mother
would fully understand the new options, even though she used to
work in a doctor's office.
</P>
<P>
   Judith Hibbard, a professor of health policy at the University
of Oregon in Eugene, said, ``Some of these options are so new and
so complex, it's very difficult for anyone to know what is best, or
even what questions to ask. It's uncharted territory.''
</P>
<P>
   Marilyn Moon, a trustee of the Medicare trust fund, said that at
least 20 percent of beneficiaries had Alzheimer's disease, memory
problems or other mental impairments that would make it difficult
for them to understand the new options. And that does not include
people with low literacy skills or very poor eyesight, said Ms.
Moon, an economist at the Urban Institute.
</P>
<P>
   Nationwide surveys by the Education Department have found that
40 percent of the elderly have very limited ability to read and use
printed materials.
</P>
<P>
   On the other hand, many older people are active and alert, well
versed in the complexities of medical care and money management.
Younger beneficiaries may have had some experience with managed
care in their working years.
</P>
<P>
   Most of the health plans will become available late this year.
But they may begin enrolling Medicare beneficiaries sooner, if they
have signed contracts with the federal government.
</P>
<P>
   In most cases, the new plans will receive a fixed amount of
federal money for each beneficiary, regardless of how much care the
person requires. By contrast, under the original Medicare program,
doctors receive a separate fee for each service they perform and
hospitals are paid an additional amount each time a patient is
admitted.
</P>
<P>
   The changes in Medicare have profound implications for thousands
of employers who provide health benefits to retirees, supplementing
Medicare. Stephen Parahus of Segal Co. in New York, a consulting
concern that specializes in employee benefits, said, ``Many
Medicare-eligible retirees will find the new array of choices
bewildering.'' Accordingly, he said, employers ``should brace
themselves for a torrent of questions and requests for
assistance.''
</P>
<P>
   The government will answer questions about the new program on a
toll-free telephone line. But the toll-free service will not be
immediately available in all states, and consumer advocates predict
that callers will face long waiting times because Medicare has not
hired enough operators.
</P>
<P>
   Hash estimated that the government would need more than 2,000
people to answer calls at the busiest times of day.
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   The Medicare handbook will contain detailed information
comparing the cost, benefits and performance of HMOs and other
health plans. There will be more than 500 different versions of
this section of the handbook, each tailored to a specific local
market, Hash said.
</P>
<P>
   Another Medicare official, Jean LeMasurier, said, ``It's really
an absolutely overwhelming project'' to compile such data, produce
the handbooks and mail them to consumers. Rep. Bill Thomas,
R-Calif., said, ``We are very concerned about whether this
old-fashioned government bureaucracy can change in time to do the
job of consumer education.''
</P>
<P>
   Medicare beneficiaries will also receive mail solicitations and
brochures directly from HMOs and other health plans that want them
to enroll.
</P>
<P>
   But William Scanlon, director of health care issues at the
General Accounting Office, an investigative arm of Congress, said
the marketing materials often omitted important information and
could mislead consumers.
</P>
<P>
   Sen. John Breaux, D-La., said it was extremely difficult to
compare the costs and benefits of private health plans being
offered to Medicare beneficiaries because their brochures did not
use a standard format or terminology.
</P>
<P>
   Thus, for example, a health plan that offers to pay for $1,300 a
year in prescription drugs might seem more attractive than a plan
that covers only $1,000. But, Scanlon said, the plans typically
measure drug usage in different ways. Some use retail price, some
use wholesale price and some use a discounted version of the
wholesale price. &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-06-09-98 2011EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
