<SLUG> BC-IRONSIDES-SAIL-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
NAVY SAYS IT'S TOO RISKY TO TAKE USS CONSTITUTION TO SEA
</HEADLINE>
  (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By DAVID ARNOLD AND CHRIS BLACK  
 c.1998 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   It seemed a dream almost too good to be true, that the nation
could dust off a 200-year-old ship, suit it up in a back brace and
new sails, then venture forth from one celebration to another as
sailing proof that a nation's youth is eternal and time can be
fooled.
</P>
<P>
   But in the end, it turned out to be just that _ too good to be
true. Tuesday, the Navy announced that the USS Constition will not
be visiting coastal ports this summer or anytime in the future. In
fact, they say the ship may never sail again to ensure it survives
for generations to come.
</P>
<P>
   ``After weighing the benefits and associated risks of taking
this priceless national treasure back to the sea, I decided that
the nation is best served by conducting any future operation of Old
Ironsides in ... the sheltered waters of Massachusetts Bay,''
Admiral Jay L. Johnson, chief of naval operations, said Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
   He added that while it is feasible that the ship may sail again,
``there are no plans to participate in any such events,'' he added.
</P>
<P>
   The ship passed its $250,000 stress test three weeks ago, but
the whims of the weather would be too chancy, according to the
Navy.
</P>
<P>
   The news came as a total surprise to officials in Gloucester,
which was counting on a visit from the ship in early August to help
the city celebrate its 375th birthday.
</P>
<P>
   ``We still haven't heard anything from the Navy, so I can't
really find the right words at the moment,'' said Michael Costello,
executive director of the Cape Ann Chamber of Commerce. He said
that just three weeks ago, a Navy official had sat in on an
organizational meeting as city officials detailed plans to shuttle
hundreds of school children out to the ship for an Aug. 4-7 visit.
But that's off as of Tuesday, leaving more than a few people in the
lurch.
</P>
<P>
   For example, Bill Cunningham, owner of Captain Bill's Whale
Watching and Deep Sea Fishing in Gloucester, said he has turned
down several bookings for a 75-foot vessel so he could make the
boat available for transportation to Old Ironsides.
</P>
<P>
   ``I've been working with the Navy since last summer. This will
be costing me some money. The Navy has a strange way of doing
things because I had every indication three weeks ago that Old
Ironsides was coming for sure,'' Cunningham said.
</P>
<P>
   Portsmouth, N.H., was slated to be the second port of call, but
Robin Comstock, president of that city's Chamber of Commerce, said
Portsmouth ``always knew there was uncertainty in the visit.''
</P>
<P>
   The Navy's decision undoubtedly will disappoint organizers of
the OpSail event in New York City, who had proposed the
Constitution lead the parade of tall ships expected there two years
hence.
</P>
<P>
   The Navy said the ship will not venture beyond about eight miles
of Deer Island so it can scoot for home in threatening weather. The
ship will leave its berth at the Charlestown Naval Shipyard for the
annual turnarounds _ Bunker Hill Day next Friday, and Independence
Day. Old Ironsides is also scheduled for a harbor tour under tow
July 23 to salute naval vessels from five nations, visiting Boston
to celebrate the 200th anniversary of the ship's first sail.
</P>
<P>
   Admiral Johnson's announcement ends an intense debate between
those who wanted to protect the ship and those who wanted to
showcase the powerful Navy symbol in sails up and down the Eastern
Seaboard. Washington lawmakers received strong indications that the
Navy had decided to keep the ship close to its Boston berth a week
ago, but no official announcement was made until WGME-TV in
Portland broke the story Monday night.
</P>
<P>
   Senators Olympia Snowe, a Maine Republican, and John Chafee, a
Rhode Island Republican and former Navy Secretary who wanted the
ship to make a stop in Newport, expressed disappointment but
supported the decision.
</P>
<P>
   ``The Navy has made its decision in order to protect the best
interests of the Constitution and this nation,'' said Snowe.
</P>
<P>
   Massachusetts officials were delighted. Senator Edward M.
Kennedy said, ``Old Ironsides has been saved once again. The Navy
is obviously right to give the very highest priority to
safeguarding the ship against any possible danger. No vessel more
clearly symbolizes the ideals, the heritage and the history of our
country than Boston's own USS Constitution.''
</P>
<P>
   Mayor Thomas M. Menino, who is in Ireland and has made a cause
celebre of keeping the ship home, said ``I'm grateful the US Navy
has exercised sound judgment on this issue. Over one million people
visit the ship annually in Charlestown, which is where she should
stay, safe and sound.''
</P>
<P>
   Another satisfied customer is US Navy Cmdr. (Ret.) Robert
Gillen, a former Constitution captain who led a public relations
campaign with more than a dozen other former captains to keep the
ship clear of a potential sea cruise.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is very, very commendable,'' said Gillen. ``The Navy did
the right thing.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
