<SLUG> BC-CLINTON-STARR-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
VERNON JORDAN RETURNS TO GRAND JURY; LEWINSKY LAWYERS SEEK
IMMUNITY 
</HEADLINE>
  (ja) 
 By STEPHEN LABATON    
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ As Vernon Jordan Jr., the presidential adviser,
returned to testify before a federal grand jury on Tuesday, Monica
Lewinsky's new lawyers met again with prosecutors in the
independent counsel's office to begin discussions about a possible
immunity agreement.
</P>
<P>
   The brief meeting was described Tuesday as ``just the
beginning'' of what could be lengthy negotiations between
prosecutors in the independent counsel's office and Ms. Lewinsky's
new lawyers, Jacob Stein and Plato Cacheris, who are trying to head
off an indictment of their client. The negotiations have been
renewed since last week, when Ms. Lewinsky dismissed her primary
lawyer, William Ginsburg, who failed to secure a deal for immunity
from prosecution months ago.
</P>
<P>
   Emerging early on Tuesday afternoon from the courthouse after
his fifth appearance before the grand jury, Jordan said he did not
anticipate being called again. Jordan, a close friend of President
Clinton, repeated that he had been asked by the grand jury about
what efforts he had undertaken on behalf of Ms. Lewinsky to find
her a job and a lawyer at a time when lawyers for Paula Corbin
Jones were seeking information from Ms. Lewinsky about her
relationship with the president.
</P>
<P>
   ``In early March, I said I helped Ms. Lewinsky get a lawyer, I
helped her get a job, I had assurances that there was no sexual
relationship and I did not tell her to lie,'' Jordan said. ``That
was the truth then, and that is the truth now.''
</P>
<P>
   With the assistance of the lawyer found by Jordan, Ms. Lewinsky
ultimately filed an affidavit in the Jones lawsuit in which she
denied having a sexual relationship with Clinton. But her affidavit
is contradicted by comments she made in secretly recorded
conversations with a former colleague, Linda Tripp, according to
lawyers and others who have heard the tapes.
</P>
<P>
   Ms. Jones' lawsuit was dismissed two months ago by a federal
judge in Arkansas. Tuesday her lawyers asked a federal appeals
panel to extend the deadline for court filings to July 22 from June
22. The lawyers said they sought the delay because the Supreme
Court will soon decide a different sexual harassment case that
could have legal implications for the Jones suit.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
