u w &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-TOBACCO-COX &UR; 540&AMP;ADD &UR; S     06-09 0861
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-TOBACCO-COX </SLUG>
   540&AMP;ADD  SENATE BREAKS TOBACCO BILL LOGJAM
 &HT;     By LARRY LIPMAN
 &HT;     c.1998 Cox News Service  
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ The procedural logjam that threatened passage of a
comprehensive tobacco bill appeared to break late Tuesday, raising
the possibility of final Senate action as soon as this week.
</P>
<P>
   The bill _ which would boost cigarette prices $1.10 a pack,
raise $516 billion over 25 years and supersede state settlements
such as those already reached in Florida and Texas with cigarette
makers _ still faces an uncertain future in the House, which has
been waiting for Senate action before taking up the contentious
issue.
</P>
<P>
   Late Tuesday, the Senate voted 52-46 for an amendment by Sen.
Paul Coverdell, R-Ga., to earmark $16 billion over the next five
years for drug-fighting efforts, including increased interdiction
efforts and new drug awareness and drug testing programs.
</P>
<P>
   The money would double the drug interdiction budget for the
Coast Guard, Customs Service, and Defense Department, and provide
$10 million a year in grants to states that instituted voluntary
drug testing for teen drivers license applicants.
</P>
<P>
   Action on Coverdell's amendment came as senators appeared to be
closing in on an agreement to consider the most contentious issue
yet facing the bill _ whether and by how much to reduce the
so-called marriage tax on some couples to offset the impact of the
higher cigarette prices.
</P>
<P>
   The Senate is expected to vote Wednesday on a proposal by Sen.
Phil Gramm, R-Texas, to use a portion of the tobacco tax revenues
to reduce the ``marriage penalty,'' or the higher income taxes most
couples pay because they file joint rather than individual returns.
</P>
<P>
   Gramm's original proposal would have earmarked $52 billion in
tax reductions over five years. Late Tuesday that amount appeared
to have been scaled back to $16 billion over five years.
</P>
<P>
   Democrats had fiercely resisted Gramm's amendment as too great a
raid on their plans to use the tobacco money for anti-smoking
efforts, but a Democratic spokesman said Tuesday night ``there is
going to be a tax (reduction) amendment in this bill that is not
viewed as a killer amendment.''
</P>
<P>
   Movement on the drug amendment and the marriage tax amendment
appeared to breathe new life into the measure, which Senate
Majority Leader Trent Lott, R-Miss., had threatened to pull earlier
in the week.
</P>
<P>
   ``Reports of the death of this legislation are premature,'' said
Sen. John McCain, R-Ariz., the bill's chief sponsor.
</P>
<P>
   ``Even though things are not bubbling over with excitement on
the floor itself, I think there is some quiet progress being made
in meetings behind the scenes,'' said Sen. John Kerry, D-Mass., the
Democratic floor leader on the bill.
</P>
<P>
   At the White House, President Clinton also sounded optimistic
about the tobacco bill's fate, telling reporters, ``I do believe
that the possibility of getting a comprehensive bill out of the
Senate is greater now than it was this morning. There are still
problems, to be sure, but we're getting closer to, I think, a
principled compromise.''
</P>
<P>
   Earlier in the day, a Democratic attempt to limit debate on the
bill and force a final vote failed 42-56 along largely party lines.
But a Democratic staffer said later that the vote to invoke cloture
may have convinced Republicans that they would not be able to evade
the tobacco issue because Democrats would seek to bring it up
regardless of what bill was pending on the floor.
</P>
<P>
   (Story can end here. Optional add follows.)
</P>
<P>
   Much of Tuesday's debate focused on Coverdell's amendment and a
Democratic alternative that was offered late in the day, but failed
on a 53-45 vote.
</P>
<P>
   Coverdell's amendment would take about $16 billion over five
years from money generated by the tobacco bill and spend it on
drug-fighting programs. The Democratic alternative would have
authorized spending about $10 billion on anti-drug efforts, but the
money would have come from general revenue.
</P>
<P>
   Coverdell's amendment also contained provisions that would allow
students victimized by drug violence to be transferred at federal
expense to another school, including a private school. Democrats
argued that such a proposal was tantamount to a federal school
voucher program, which they have repeatedly blocked.
</P>
<P>
   Coverdell called the Senate vote ``a powerful statement that the
nation has to pull itself together and have the will to confront
this'' drug problem.
</P>
<P>
   Earlier Tuesday, Coverdell said drug abuse is ``the number one
problem. The cost to American society is as great on the drug side
as it is on the tobacco side, and in the perception of parents and
families and teenagers, it is a far greater problem.''
</P>
<P>
   But Democrats objected that Coverdell's amendment would siphon
billions of dollars a year from anti-smoking program in the tobacco
bill. They argued that attacking smoking was a significant step in
fighting drugs.
</P>
<P>
   ``The gateway drug to substance abuse is smoking,'' said Sen.
Edward M. Kennedy, D-Mass. ``The correlation is powerful, it's
compelling and it's convincing.''
</P>
<P>
   &UR; (For use by clients of the New York Times News Service) &LR;
</P>
</TEXT>
