<SLUG> BC-CLINTON-KIM-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
PRESIDENT MEETS KOREAN LEADER, DEFENDS CHINA'S WELCOMING PLAN
</HEADLINE>
  (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By ANN SCALES  
 c.1998 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ President Clinton on Tuesday defended his decision
to participate in an arrival ceremony in Bejing's Tiananmen Square
when he goes to China this month.
</P>
<P>
   Clinton said that being welcomed at the Great Hall of the
People, on the edge of the site of the killings of prodemocracy
protesters in June 1989, would not undermine his ability to press
China on human rights.
</P>
<P>
   But the US House apparently disagreed Tuesday, voting 305-116
for a nonbinding resolution urging Clinton not to participate in
the ceremony.
</P>
<P>
   `My own view is that if this is going to be a state visit to
China and I am going to be the guest of the Chinese, that they
should be designing the terms of the arrival ceremony, not me,''
Clinton said.
</P>
<P>
   ``I simply don't accept the proposition that observing their
diplomatic protocol in any way undermines my capacity to advance
the principles of the United States,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Clinton made his remarks about his state visit to China from
June 25 to July 3 at a joint news conference with South Korean
President Kim Dae Jung. Kim, a longtime political dissident who
spent seven years in prison, is on his first state visit to the
United States and was welcomed Tuesday at an eleborate White House
ceremony, complete with a 21-gun salute.
</P>
<P>
   During the welcoming ceremony, Clinton paid tribute to Kim's
heroic rise from political prisoner to president, comparing him to
Lech Walesa of Poland, Vaclav Havel of Czechoslovakia, and Nelson
Mandela of South Africa.
</P>
<P>
   Kim is trying to persuade the United States to loosen sanctions
on North Korea, a step the Clinton administration says should be
contingent on North Korea living up to an agreement to shun nuclear
weapons.
</P>
<P>
   Clinton, at the news conference, said the South Korean leader
``did not ask me to lift sanctions. What he asked me to do was to
work with him to support a policy of reciprocity which would enable
us to move forward with the reconciliation of the North and the
South. And I said that I would be prepared to do that.''
</P>
<P>
   Kim acknowledged that ``based on our experience, it's very
difficult to say that you can trust a communist,'' but said it is
important to negotiate with North Korea and its leader Kim Jong-il
to avert economic collapse in that country and head off possible
military provocation.
</P>
<P>
   ``Our intent is to persuade North Korea to make it feel safe in
opening up and so that it can resuscitate itself,'' Kim said. He
pointed to China and Vietnam as models of communist governments
that have opened markets for trade.
</P>
<P>
   Kim did not mention Clinton's trip to China, but Clinton said
they had discussed it during their day of meetings, although he did
not give any specifics.
</P>
<P>
   ``In view of the recent economic events in Asia and the nuclear
tests on the Indian subcontinent, it should be clearer than ever
before that we have a strong national interest in developing a
constructive, positive relationship with China,'' Clinton said.
</P>
<P>
   He added: ``I think that what Americans should want me to do is
to make sure that I am as effective as possible not only in
advancing our interests, but in standing up for our values.''
</P>
<P>
   In addition, Clinton defended his decision to approve a new
permit for Loral Space and Communications Ltd. to launch its
satellites on Chinese rockets, despite Justice Department
objections.
</P>
<P>
   Congress is examining whether Clinton was influenced by hundreds
of thousands of dollars in campaign contributions and whether Loral
gave China sensitive information about rocket guidance systems that
could improve the accuracy of China's military missiles, a charge
the company has denied.
</P>
<P>
   ``I didn't resist the advice of the Justice Department,''
Clinton said Tuesday. ``I took the advice of the National Security
Council, the Defense Department, the State Department, and the Arms
Control and Disarmament Agency.
</P>
<P>
   ``It was, from my point of view, a pretty routine decision,'' he
said. ``I thought, on balance, if all those agencies felt that it
was the right thing to do and furthered our national interest, that
I would do so.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-06-09-98 2020EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
