<DOCNO> NYT19980609.0337 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-06-09 20:22 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A1611 &Cx1f; taf-z
u f &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-GODZILLA-AD-COLUMN-NY     06-09 1136
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-GODZILLA-AD-COLUMN-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
ADVERTISING: HOW MERCHANTS REGISTER A MIDDLING `GODZILLA'
</HEADLINE>
   (ja) 
 By STUART ELLIOTT   
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ With ``Godzilla'' turning out to be more of a limping
lizard than a leaping lizard at the box office, the scores of
promotional, licensing and merchandising partners that anticipated
the film would be a summer blockbuster must now hope that size
won't matter after all.
</P>
<P>
   ``Godzilla,'' which opened on May 20, had been promoted
relentlessly for more than a year with a breathless teaser campaign
insisting that ``Size does matter.'' And though the movie,
distributed by the Tristar unit of Sony Pictures Entertainment, has
already sold $114-million worth of tickets to American filmgoers
through Sunday, it is widely being perceived as a disappointment
because all that sizable pre-release boasting led industry analysts
to expect spectacular results.
</P>
<P>
   The fact that so many size queens are already decrying how
``Godzilla'' is faring is indicative of the huge risks that
marketers take when they seek to take part in and capitalize on the
hoopla and hyperbole of Hollywood. Companies that are more familiar
with selling toys, soft drinks or T-shirts must try forecasting far
in advance which films may capture the fancy of an increasingly
fickle public and then place what amount to multimillion-dollar
bets on the outcome.
</P>
<P>
   In the case of ``Godzilla,'' declines in ticket sales in the
second and third weekends of 59 percent and 46 percent,
respectively, have made it difficult to meet the ambitious goal of
Sony executives for a $200 million American box office bonanza. But
does that necessarily mean shoppers will shy from all the
``Godzilla'' products seeking to benefit from what was supposed to
be a monstrous blast of star power?
</P>
<P>
   ``The jury is still out,'' James Mammarella, editor of License
magazine, said on Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
   ``Retailers won't mark down merchandise instantaneously because
the box office drops off,'' Mammarella said in an interview from
the Jacobs K. Javits Center in midtown Manhattan, where he was
attending the opening of the Licensing '98 International trade
show, ``and kids don't read Variety.''
</P>
<P>
   ``It could have a life of its own at retail,'' he added, ``even
if there's a cloud over it.''
</P>
<P>
   Some advertisers say they benefited from the pre-opening blitz
orchestrated by Sony, cushioning them from potential subsequent
shortfalls.
</P>
<P>
   ``We were able to tie in with the hype of the movie, which was
touted as the biggest thing out there,'' said Steve Lunceford, a
spokesman for the Sprint Corp. in Kansas City, Mo., which chose
``Godzilla'' as one of three films for a ``Summer Movie
Spectacular'' ticket giveaway for long-distance customers.
</P>
<P>
   Another promotional partner, the Taco Bell fast-food chain owned
by Tricon Global Restaurants, is reporting signs of life at its
7,000 stores after spending an estimated $60 million before the
release date to peddle ``Godzilla'' merchandise like cups and cup
holders and a ``Find Godzilla and Win'' game.
</P>
<P>
   ``We are very pleased with the results,'' said Vada Hill, chief
marketing officer at Taco Bell in Irvine, Calif. ``We have gotten
our strongest sales numbers of the year.''
</P>
<P>
   The primary reason, he added, is that the company strives in
developing film tie-ins to ``create a world in our restaurants that
leverages `the sweet spot,' the intersection of the movie and the
Taco Bell brand.'' He said, ``And if the world we create is
compelling, it takes on a life of its own, disconnected from the
movie.''
</P>
<P>
   A humorous television commercial centered on the ``Godzilla''
promotion _ which features the Taco Bell Chihuahua crying ``Here,
lizard, lizard'' and setting out a tiny trap for the elusive
creature _ has drawn widespread praise. Mammarella even suggested
that the Taco Bell spot could serve ``as a shot in the arm for the
merchandising'' of the ``Godzilla'' licensed products in stores
like toys and apparel.
</P>
<P>
   Hill said: ``What the ad depends on is a knowledge of
`Godzilla.' It doesn't depend on you seeing `Godzilla' or seeing
`Godzilla' half a dozen times. If you have that knowledge, you will
get the joke.'' The commercial was created by the TBWA Chiat/Day
unit of Omnicom Group in Venice, Calif.; the promotion was created
by the Irvine office of Wunderman Cato Johnson, a unit of Young &AMP;
Rubicam Inc.
</P>
<P>
   At the Hershey Foods Corp., which is selling candy with
``Godzilla'' themes, ``it's probably a little too soon to receive
feedback from retailers or sales reps in the field,'' said Mike
Kinney, a spokesman in Hershey, Pa.
</P>
<P>
   ``But we had an excellent buy-in,'' he added, referring to the
advance sale of the candy to stores before the film was released,
``so at this point it's a very successful tie-in for us.''
</P>
<P>
   Hershey too was aware that movie-themed products need to stand
on their own legs if, as it appears, the legs of a giant lizard are
not strong enough for support.
</P>
<P>
   ``Our products are fun and visually appealing in and of
themselves,'' Kinney said, ``even if you don't have a chance to see
the movie.''
</P>
<P>
   Products more directly related to ``Godzilla,'' like toy
likenesses of the beast, may prove more problematic.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm making calls to licensees and while it's a little early,
the patterns are clear that it will not be a booming success,''
said Martin Brochstein, executive editor at The Licensing Letter
newsletter.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's rare at best when a movie does not do well and the
ancillary products did,'' he added.
</P>
<P>
   The ``Godzilla'' producers and Sony executives pursued an
unconventional strategy to help generate interest in the licensed
merchandise: They insisted that nothing revealing the lizard's full
appearance be placed on sale before the movie opened. Usually, such
products flood stores before a film's premiere.
</P>
<P>
   ``The secrecy seems to be backfiring on them,'' said George
Papaioannou, an entertainment industries analyst at Donaldson,
Lufkin &AMP; Jenrette in New York. ``It's a lesson learned, in this
case.''
</P>
<P>
   However ``Godzilla'' ultimately performs, marketers are already
looking ahead to other summer films with a panoply of promotional
partners, including ``The X-Files,'' which has deals with companies
including the Oldsmobile division of the General Motors Corp.,
``Armageddon,'' with links to advertisers like Nestle Chocolate and
Confection, and ``Small Soldiers,'' with a line of _ yes, small
soldiers, from Hasbro Inc.
</P>
<P>
   And beyond the summer, there will be elaborate merchandising and
licensing programs involving the home video release of ``Titanic,''
scheduled on Sept. 1, with Sprint as a participant, and the
introduction next year of the first of three ``prequels'' in the
``Star Wars'' series of films, with Taco Bell as a participant.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-06-09-98 2022EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
