<DATE_TIME> 1998-06-09 20:23 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A1614 &Cx1f; taf-z
u f &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-GOLDMAN-MARKETPLACE-1     06-09 1055
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-GOLDMAN-MARKETPLACE-1,000(2TAKES)-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
MARKETPLACE: PRIVATE FIRM, PUBLIC AMBITION  
</HEADLINE>
  (mk) 
 By JOSEPH KAHN   
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ As the partners of Goldman, Sachs &AMP; Co. debate
whether to turn Wall Street's premier private investment bank into
a public company, they might mull this paradox: They are earning
record profits advising clients to do deals they themselves would
never do.
</P>
<P>
   As a partnership, Goldman does not issue stock, the basic
currency of big mergers and acquisitions. So while it helped link
Daimler AG to Chrysler Corp. and brought BankAmerica together with
Nationsbank, two of the biggest deals in the global rush to
consolidate, Goldman has husbanded its partners' capital and
shunned the risky mergers game.
</P>
<P>
   All that may change, some Goldman insiders say, if the partners
back a plan to go public at the firm's annual meeting on Friday.
Going public would help Goldman buy other firms to expand at home
and abroad. It would level the playing field with its fast-growing
rivals, including Merrill Lynch, Morgan Stanley Dean Witter and
Salomon Smith Barney, all of which are publicly owned.
</P>
<P>
   Some outside bankers say that public ownership might make
Goldman a target for big commercial banks, though few expect
Goldman would agree to any deal that could compromise its fiercely
independent culture.
</P>
<P>
   How aggressive Goldman becomes depends on how partners react to
the firm's strategic plan, a study of options drawn up under the
leadership of Henry Paulson Jr., Goldman's co-chief executive.
People familiar with the broad outlines say it explores ways that
Goldman, as a public company, could rapidly expand in areas in
which it considers itself small or weak.
</P>
<P>
   Among the most likely acquisition targets: a major American or
European asset management company or a Japanese brokerage house.
Goldman in the past has sought close ties with T. Rowe Price, a
Baltimore-based mutual fund manager with about $100 billion in
assets. Some Goldman bankers say the firm should also consider an
alliance with Daiwa Securities, Japan's second-largest broker after
Nomura and the only leader there that has yet to find a partner.
</P>
<P>
   Goldman wants to add to the mutual funds and other assets its
manages so that it can rely more on recurring fees and less on
volatile trading and underwriting revenues. Nearly all major
American brokers have tried to grab a bigger share of Japan's
securities market, especially since that country's long recession
has reduced the cost and barriers to entry.
</P>
<P>
   ``The question is how to expand more quickly,'' said a Goldman
partner who will participate in Friday's debate and declined to be
identified. ``No one wants to radically remake the firm. But there
is some frustration that we are not a part of all the deal
making.''
</P>
<P>
   Any shopping spree by Goldman would add to the financial world's
consolidation frenzy, especially if the respected banking house
puts its seal of approval on the recent trend of combining
insurance, commercial banking and investment banking. It would also
be a sign that in the race to become global players, even the most
successful banks and fund managers need a public currency _ stock _
to make transactions.
</P>
<P>
   By some measures, Goldman has fallen behind leading rivals. It
manages $160 billion in assets, well under Merrill Lynch's $450
billion. Goldman's elite client list is the envy of Wall Street.
But Morgan Stanley has combined its blue-chip corporate business
with a retail brokerage network selling stocks to main street
investors, earning the steady fees and high margins those accounts
bring.
</P>
<P>
   A Goldman spokesman said on Monday that even if the partners
decided to take the firm public, that did not mean Goldman would
abandon its strategy of growing internally rather than through
acquisitions. He rejected as ``rumors'' the idea that Goldman had
an informal shopping list of companies it would like to buy.
</P>
<P>
   The spokesman agreed that to have stock to make purchases was a
factor in the debate over issue shares, but added, ``I don't think
it's a primary factor.'' He added, ``It's a factor in the sense
that you don't know what the world will be like, and this gives you
more options.''
</P>
<P>
   Goldman has considered and rejected the idea of selling shares
as part of an expansion plan half a dozen times in recent years,
and it might decide to pass this time as well. Profits, after all,
are running at a record level, with the firm set to earn more than
$2 billion in this year's first half, compared with about $3
billion all of last year. Most of those profits come from the
firm's bread-and-butter business of trading, underwriting and
providing client advice.
</P>
<P>
   And even if Goldman could tap public capital markets instead of
relying primarily on partners' capital, it would not necessarily
follow the path blazed by other Wall Street financiers, like
Sanford Weill of the Travelers Group. Weill recently agreed to
merge his company with Citicorp, the largest financial deal in
history.
</P>
<P>
   ``I would think that the idea of being part of Citibank would
send shivers up and down the spine of every person at Goldman,''
said one retired partner, who asked not to be named. ``On the other
hand, the firm has to have the currency to make strategic
acquisitions. It now has its hands tied.''
</P>
<P>
   In the past, the firm has tended to grow internally, making only
small acquisitions. When Goldman wanted to break into the European
asset management fund business, it bought the small British pension
fund manager Cinman, a deal valued at the time at less than $100
million. When publicly traded Merrill Lynch pursued a similar
vision last year, it snapped up the leading European player,
Mercury Asset Management, paying $5.3 billion.
</P>
<P>
   Similarly, several American investment banks have scrambled to
expand their presence in Japan. Goldman has performed well there
but has fallen behind rivals like Merrill and Salomon in striking
alliances. Salomon earlier this month spent $1.6 billion for a 25
percent stake in Nikko Securities. To date, Goldman has followed a
more conservative strategy in Japan, finding partners to help
distribute its mutual funds but avoiding major capital commitments.
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   nn
</P>
<P>
   A small number of current and retired Goldman executives at
least loosely entertain the idea of much bigger deals. One
possibility is a merger with a commercial bank eager for Goldman's
investment banking expertise. Chase Manhattan, J.P. Morgan and
BankAmerica, three of the largest American banks, would make the
most logical fits, some bankers say.
</P>
<P>
   All of those banks have stock market values so far above even
the highest values placed on a public offering by Goldman that they
could swallow the Wall Street firm with little trouble. All have
strong traditional banking businesses but lag far behind Goldman in
investment banking.
</P>
<P>
   If the firm decides to issue stock priced at $20 a share, ``then
Chase offers us $25 a share, we would at least have to consider
it,'' said one current Goldman partner. ``My own feeling is that
the way to unlock Goldman's true value is through a merger'' rather
than a public offering of stock, he added.
</P>
<P>
   But such alliances remain long shots. Even if Goldman decides to
go public, it seems unlikely to risk diluting the tightly
integrated, highly motivated culture it has nurtured over recent
decades by blending itself with a large outsider.
</P>
<P>
   Moreover, Goldman is not only one of Wall Street's most
profitable creations, it is also one of its most egocentric.
Bankers there say they would never agree to be dominated by a
commercial bank, with its eight-hour days and fatter management
structure. Thus, Goldman would insist on a difficult reverse merger
in any linkup with a big commercial bank, putting its own
executives in control of a combined entity.
</P>
<P>
   At any rate, Goldman will probably need all its in-house mergers
and acquisitions expertise if it decides to go public. ``I wonder
if they know the kind of pressure they will be under if they
actually pull the trigger,'' said one outside banker.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
