s e &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-TV-THORNBIRDS-CHAMBER     06-09 0551
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-TV-THORNBIRDS-CHAMBERLAIN-$ADV14-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
DID HE LOVE HER? OH, YES! 
</HEADLINE>
   (For release Sunday, June 14)  
 (JT)  
 By ANITA GATES    
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   Watching the early scenes of ``The Thorn Birds,'' when Father
Ralph de Bricassart was too young and dashing for his own good,
it's hard to believe that Richard Chamberlain was 48 at the time.
</P>
<P>
   ``I stayed young a remarkably long time and then fell apart,''
Chamberlain, 63, says with a laugh.
</P>
<P>
   Of course, in ``The Thorn Birds,'' physical beauty sometimes
appears to be an annoyance anyway. Poor Father Ralph can't go
anywhere, it seems, without rich dowagers trying to seduce him or
strangers coming up to tell him how beautiful he is. Chamberlain,
who probably began having the same problems when he was the star of
NBC's ``Dr. Kildare'' (1961-66), was at the height of his reign as
king of the mini-series (it was three years after ``Shogun'') when
``The Thorn Birds'' appeared on ABC in 1983.
</P>
<P>
   Chamberlain, who now describes himself as ``a Hawaiian beach bum
who paints and occasionally acts'' (he has lived full time on the
island of Oahu, outside Honolulu, for eight years), says he hasn't
watched the mini-series _ all 10 hours of it _ in several years but
remembers it as pretty fabulous and even praises Rachel Ward's
performance. (The latter opinion was not shared by many critics at
the time.)
</P>
<P>
   ``I think that romantic love is the most interesting topic in
the world,'' Chamberlain says by way of explaining the story's
popularity. ``And the more obstacles there are between the lovers,
the more interesting the story gets.  &UR; God &LR;  was between us.''
</P>
<P>
   Every reader of Colleen McCullough's 1977 novel knows that
Meggie Cleary truly loves Father Ralph all her life, but does he
truly love her back? Chamberlain's simple answer: yes.
</P>
<P>
   ``It was a real soul-mate relationship,'' he says. ``They were
utterly, absolutely meant for each other.'' And were it not for
Ralph's committed relationship with God, and his being a little
``dazzled by the power of the church,'' Chamberlain adds, ``they
would have been extremely happy.''
</P>
<P>
   In an era when a fictional Roman Catholic priest like the one on
ABC's series ``Nothing Sacred'' can be persecuted by conservative
groups just for being open-minded, it's strange to consider that in
1983 there was no uproar over the story of a priest's affair with a
married woman.
</P>
<P>
   ``There were some objections, but it was nothing earthshaking,
as I recall,'' Chamberlain says. ``I think the thing that disturbed
the Church was not that he slipped once, but that he sort of kept
up the relationship.'' (On at least one subsequent visit to
Drogheda, a silver-haired Father Ralph spends the night in Meggie's
bed.) The United States Catholic Conference's only publicly stated
objection, however, was that the mini-series ran during Holy Week.
</P>
<P>
   Since then, Chamberlain hasn't been hiding out completely. He
appeared on Broadway most recently as Henry Higgins in a revival of
``My Fair Lady,'' in late 1993 and early 1994. There was even a
``Thorn Birds'' sequel (``The Missing Years'') in 1996, best
forgotten. But the entertainment industry has changed since 1983,
too.
</P>
<P>
   ``The business has just gotten too tough for me,'' Chamberlain
says. So mostly he paints.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-06-09-98 2024EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19980609.0341 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-06-09 20:25 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A1619 &Cx1f; tta-z
u i &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-KOSOVO-U.S.-ASSESS-NY     06-09 1053
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-KOSOVO-U.S.-ASSESS-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
ANALYSIS: HAS THE WEST LEARNED FROM MISTAKES IN BOSNIA? 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (ATTN: Miss., Ind., Neb., Okla.)  (th) 
 By STEVEN ERLANGER    
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ The last war in the Balkans lasted four years and
took more than 200,000 lives before President Clinton and NATO
finally intervened. With the impetus of severe NATO air strikes,
the United States and its envoy, Richard Holbrooke, brought the
warring Bosnians together at Dayton, Ohio, and hammered out a
peace, enforced by NATO troops.
</P>
<P>
   But now another part of the Balkans is aflame, a small province
in Serbia called Kosovo, and once again world powers are
floundering in an effort to devise a coherent policy to put
pressure on Yugoslav President Slobodan Milosevic and contain the
conflict.
</P>
<P>
   The United States and Holbrooke have already been criticized for
conceding too much to Milosevic in order to get him to talk, for
the first time, with Ibrahim Rugova, the leader of the Kosovo
Albanians, who is seeking a nonviolent road to independence.
</P>
<P>
   After Holbrooke met Milosevic last month, the United States
persuaded the Europeans to delay imposing sanctions on the Serbs.
But Milosevic used what was supposed to be a period of dialogue to
crack down on the Kosovo Liberation Army and its civilian
supporters.
</P>
<P>
   On Tuesday, the Europeans and the United States belatedly
imposed some sanctions on Milosevic and talked about
``accelerating'' NATO planning for air strikes. But there is little
agreement about how to achieve a peaceful end to the fighting _
especially since the West does not support independence for Kosovo,
but ethnic Albanians in Kosovo and elsewhere are willing in
increasing numbers to fight for it.
</P>
<P>
   Independence for Kosovo is unthinkable to Milosevic and the
Serbs, given the centrality of the province to Serbian history,
religion and culture, said Warren Zimmermann, the American
ambassador to Yugoslavia from 1989 to 1992.
</P>
<P>
   ``While Bosnia was an adventure for Milosevic and the world
recognized its independence,'' Zimmermann said, ``it's much harder
for Milosevic to make concessions in Kosovo, which is recognized as
part of Yugoslavia.''
</P>
<P>
   With the crackdown, the level of support in Kosovo for Rugova
and his nonviolent approach is slipping. ``Washington is still
hoping there can be a political process and dialogue to be had, but
the prospects are gloomy and fading,'' a senior Western diplomat
said Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
   To Carl Bildt, once the European Union's senior representative
in Bosnia, the lack of decisive action by the West is ``deja vu in
Kosovo.'' To Marshall Freeman Harris, a former State Department
official who quit over American inaction in Bosnia, ``the West is
screwing it up again.''
</P>
<P>
   While Kosovo presents different problems, Harris said, ``it's
the similarities that count _ you have the same protagonist,
Milosevic, and the same goal, which is to drive out non-Serbs and
kill them if necessary.''
</P>
<P>
   ``You can't just build a firewall around the problem,'' he said,
``which is what I fear the U.S. wants to do.''
</P>
<P>
   Holbrooke argued in a recent interview that in Kosovo, unlike in
Bosnia, both the United States and NATO have become involved early,
and that Washington and the Europeans are working closely together,
showing that ``the main lessons'' of the Bosnian horrors have been
learned.
</P>
<P>
   Already there is a strategy, Holbrooke argued. The
Milosevic-Rugova dialogue is vital to a solution, he said, and the
selective use of sanctions, as carrot and stick, is vital to
getting Milosevic to talk substantively. The third tier, of
potential NATO military action and air strikes, is vital to
deterring Milosevic from violence against civilians.
</P>
<P>
   But Holbrooke goes silent when asked if Washington now, unlike
in the early days in Bosnia, has found the balance between
diplomacy and force. ``It's too early to tell,'' he said finally.
</P>
<P>
   While the West has learned lessons since Bosnia, ``has Slobodan
Milosevic learned anything?'' asked Holbrooke, who probably knows
him better than any Westerner and whom Milosevic insists on dealing
with. ``That remains to be seen.''
</P>
<P>
   Some, like Harris and Zimmermann, suggest that what Milosevic
has learned is how to manipulate the hesitation of the West.
</P>
<P>
   Zimmermann says Kosovo poses greater dangers of regional
instability than Bosnia did. ``I feel more sympathy for the
administration's dilemma,'' he says. ``But you don't get out of it
by coddling Milosevic, and we've done too much of that over the
last two to three years. The man doesn't take well to coddling _ he
just absorbs it and then does whatever he wants.''
</P>
<P>
   That is a theme being taken up more consistently by Republicans
in Congress, beginning with Senate Majority Leader Trent Lott of
Mississippi and including moderates like Sen. Dick Lugar of
Indiana.
</P>
<P>
   ``I detect a shift on the Republican side on this,'' said Sen.
Chuck Hagel, a Nebraska Republican on the Foreign Relations
Committee. ``The reality is, when you start dissecting this, we're
probably going to have to put NATO troops in there. The longer we
wait, the worse it'll get.''
</P>
<P>
   Such sentiments from legislators normally eager to get American
troops out of Bosnia has taken the White House by surprise, and
contributed to a toughening of language.
</P>
<P>
   It was President George Bush who, in 1992, first warned
Milosevic of military action if he moved against Kosovo, a message
repeated by Clinton in 1993, but heard little since. Bush's warning
was cited Tuesday by Sen. Don Nickles, R-Okla.
</P>
<P>
   Asked about Kosovo on Tuesday, Clinton said the United States
favors the use of ``all necessary means to try to avoid `ethnic
cleansing' and the loss of human life,'' and said: ``The main thing
is, I am determined to do all I can to stop a repeat of the human
carnage in Bosnia and the `ethnic cleansing.'''
</P>
<P>
   Even so, there is little appetite for new military commitments.
</P>
<P>
   Stopping Serbian violence in Kosovo, however it might be
managed, could only raise the ambitions of the Kosovar guerrillas
and would do little to help Rugova, who also favors independence.
It is far from clear that the West can force a negotiated solution
of autonomy because both the Serbs and the ethnic Albanians already
think the time for serious talking is past. &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
