<SLUG> BC-KOREA-CHINA-U.S.-ART-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
CLINTON REJECTS PLEAS TO AVOID TIANANMEN CEREMONY 
</HEADLINE>
 (Eds.: budgeted earlier as KOREA-U.S.) 
(ART ADV: Photo is being sent to NYT photo clients. Non-subscribers
can make individual purchase by calling 212-556-4204 or 1927.) 
(bl) 
 By JOHN M. BRODER   
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ President Clinton rejected appeals Tuesday that he
avoid an official welcoming ceremony in Tiananmen Square in Beijing
when he visits China this month, saying that he could not dictate
to China's leaders how he should be received in their country.
</P>
<P>
   Appearing at a news conference with South Korean President Kim
Dae-jung, Clinton said that his planned appearance at Tiananmen
Square, the scene of a deadly crackdown on democratic protesters
nine years ago this month, did not signal that he was endorsing
Beijing's suppression of dissent.
</P>
<P>
   Last week the House voted, 305-116, to approve a nonbinding
resolution demanding that the president avoid the plaza on his trip
to China, which is to begin June 25.
</P>
<P>
   ``My own view,'' Clinton said Tuesday, ``is that if this is
going to be a state visit to China and I am going to be the guest
of the Chinese that they should be designing the terms of the
arrival ceremony, not me. And I simply don't accept the proposition
that observing their diplomatic protocol in any way undermines my
capacity to advance the principles of the United States.''
</P>
<P>
   Addressing another issue that has generated opposition to his
policy toward China, the president said his approval this year of
China's launching a U.S. satellite over the objections of the
Justice Department was ``a pretty routine decision'' made on the
recommendation of other agencies.
</P>
<P>
   This was the first time that Clinton has addressed questions
from the press on the satellite deal, which is the subject of a
congressional investigation. Lawmakers are seeking to learn whether
U.S. national security was harmed by the decision and whether the
president was influenced by large campaign contributions from
Bernard Schwartz, chief executive of the satellite maker, Loral
Space and Communications Ltd.
</P>
<P>
   The White House has rejected a call from 152 members of Congress
that Clinton postpone his China trip until questions about the
satellite have been resolved.
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   On Korea, Clinton rebuffed gentle pressure from Kim to ease U.S.
economic sanctions against communist North Korea. Kim has argued
publicly and privately that the U.S. sanctions are
counterproductive, driving the fearful North Korean leadership
further into isolation and alienation.
</P>
<P>
   Kim said reconciliation between the Koreas and an improvement in
U.S.- North Korea relations ``should be promoted in harmony.''
</P>
<P>
   But Clinton said Kim had not directly asked him to lift the
sanctions, adding:
</P>
<P>
   ``What he asked me to do was to work with him to support a
policy of reciprocity, which would enable us to move forward with
the reconciliation of the North and the South. And I said that I
would be prepared to do that.''
</P>
<P>
   He said easing sanctions would require congressional approval,
but did not pledge to seek such changes. He hinted at some
``executive flexibility'' in some categories of economic punishment
of the North, but did not promise to exercise his authority. ``What
I told President Kim I would do is to work with him,'' Clinton
said.
</P>
<P>
   The president also announced the resumption, after seven years
of support by the Overseas Private Investment Corp. for U.S.
companies doing business in Korea, saying improved conditions for
workers warranted the lifting of restrictions on the loan
guarantees.
</P>
<P>
   Clinton also said he and Kim had discussed a bilateral
investment treaty, an ``open skies'' agreement for unrestricted
airplane service between the United States and South Korea and
South Korea's recent decision to order $1 billion worth of Boeing
airliners.
</P>
<P>
   Much of the discussion between the two concerned South Korea's
economic crisis, both a symptom and a cause of the financial panic
gripping much of East Asia. Last year, the International Monetary
Fund arranged a $58 billion rescue package for South Korea, helping
stabilize exchange rates and slowing the downward slide of the
economy.
</P>
<P>
   Much of Kim's nine-day visit here is devoted to rebuilding
investor confidence. Monday in New York he visited the New York
Stock Exchange and addressed U.S. business leaders, reassuring them
that South Korea was undertaking a sweeping reorganization of the
economy, rooting out decades of corruption and featherbedding.
</P>
<P>
   Kim's visit to the United States is his first since he became
president in February, after a lifetime in opposition to what had
for decades been a one-party state.
</P>
<P>
   At an elaborate arrival ceremony at the White House on Tuesday
morning, Kim, who 17 years ago was under a death sentence from
Seoul, was met by a 21-gun salute and warm praise from Clinton. He
compared Kim to former protesters and political prisoners who rose
to the leadership like Lech Walesa of Poland, Vaclav Havel of the
Czech Republic and Nelson Mandela of South Africa. They are all
heroes who changed the world by their individual courage, Clinton
said.
</P>
<P>
   The president added, ``Standing with me today is living proof,
Kim Dae-jung, a human rights pioneer, a courageous survivor and
America's partner in building a better future for the world.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
