<SLUG> BC-SOC-WORLD-CUP-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
BRAZIL FEELS THE HEAT FROM ARDENT FANS
</HEADLINE>
  (ja) 
 By JERE LONGMAN    
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   ST. DENIS, France _ The World Cup is starting Wednesday and
Brazil is like a pot ready to boil over, a Brazilian journalist
breathlessly told Coach Mario Zagallo Tuesday. Could he offer some
reassuring words to the people back home, something that would turn
the heat down to simmer?
</P>
<P>
   ``I can say the system that works the fastest is the nervous
system, but I can assure you that Brazil will overcome that,'' said
Zagallo, who, at 66, has been a coach, assistant coach or player on
all four of Brazil's World Cup champion teams. ``They can have
trust in us to overcome the anxiety.''
</P>
<P>
   After months of unsatisfying results, worrisome injury and
recent inner turmoil, Brazil sets out to defend its World Cup title
against Scotland. What remains unanswered is whether Brazil can
play to the same samba beat that its fans will display in the
80,000-seat Stade France here in the northern Paris suburbs.
</P>
<P>
   From Pele, to the roiling Brazilian news media, to the nervous
fans on the streets of Rio and Sao Paolo, everyone is concerned
that while Brazil has the best players in the world, it may not
have the best team.
</P>
<P>
   Losses to the United States and Argentina have exposed
weaknesses. A leg injury has cost Brazil the services of Romario,
the most valuable player of the 1994 World Cup. The former star
Zico has been brought in to perch on Zagallo's shoulder as an
assistant. Some believe that the players have become fatigued
touring the world in the service of their corporate sponsor, Nike.
All of Brazil hopes for the best, but fears the worst.
</P>
<P>
   ``I've been on the national team for 10 years and it is always
the same,'' the midfielder Leonardo said. ``But I think all of this
is good. It's the World Cup.''
</P>
<P>
   Leonardo is currently at the center of an uproar about a fight
he supposedly got into recently with his volatile teammate,
Edmundo.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's not true,'' Leonardo said. ``People talk, and it gets
blown up into this big thing.''
</P>
<P>
   Edmundo also sent the news media into a frenzy with a radio
interview stating that he was more fit and talented than Bebeto and
should be starting at forward alongside Ronaldo, who is considered
the world's best player. Zagallo has chosen Bebeto against a
Scottish team that surrendered only three goals during qualifying,
and he seems completely nonplussed by the turmoil that surrounds
his team.
</P>
<P>
   ``Brazil is under pressure just like it was in 1958 and 1962,''
he said. ``There is no difference.''
</P>
<P>
   The two other teams in Brazil's group, Morocco and Norway, will
also play Wednesday night in Montpellier, France. The 32-team
tournament will be played at 10 sites around the country and will
conclude with the final here on July 12. The Americans open on
Sunday against Germany in Paris.
</P>
<P>
   Tuesday, the United States won by 4-0 in a closed-door scrimmage
against a French second-division team, Gueugnon. Coach Steve
Sampson, seeking to build depth in case one of his players gets the
red card under a new rule prohibiting tackling from behind, played
a number of his players out of position and received goals from
Brian McBride, Cobi Jones, Brian Maisonneuve and Ernie Stewart.
</P>
<P>
   The Americans hope to advance to the second round. For Brazil,
there is only one acceptable outcome.
</P>
<P>
   ``We must win,'' Leonardo said. ``Second place is not enough.'' &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
