<SLUG> BC-NIGERIA-ABIOLA-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
DAUGHTER OF NIGERIAN ELECTION WINNER LEADS A PROTEST
</HEADLINE>
  (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By DAVID L. MARCUS  
 c.1998 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ As a student at Harvard, Hafsat Abiola worked and
prayed for the day when General Sani Abacha, the dictator who
controlled Nigeria, would leave power. Only then, Abiola concluded,
would her father and other political prisoners be freed.
</P>
<P>
   With Abacha dead of an apparent heart attack, only to be
replaced by another army general, Abiola, 23, did not know whether
to feel hopeful or glum Tuesday. It was too early to tell whether
the day-old regime of General Abdusalam Abubakar would be a
transition to democracy or simply the continuation of the Abacha
era's brutal corruption.
</P>
<P>
   At noon Tuesday, Abiola joined two dozen other protesters
outside the Nigerian Embassy in Washington, calling for the
military to turn over power to the legitimate, elected president.
That man is Abiola's father _ Moshood K.O. Abiola, imprisoned after
winning the 1993 presidential elections.
</P>
<P>
   The protesters did not believe that Nigeria will honor its
promise to restore a civilian government to power in October. They
said Abiola should start serving his four-year term immediately _
all except Hafsat and her young-er sister, Khafila, 19. The sisters
are focusing first on the release of all Nigerian political
prisoners, including hundreds of labor leaders, environmentalists,
journalists, students, and human rights activists.
</P>
<P>
   ``The Nigerian military is weakened, but they want to go about
business as usual,'' Hafsat Abiola said over the din of the crowd.
``We have to seize this opportunity. We have to resist, to free the
political prisoners, to demand a change.''
</P>
<P>
   Abiola managed to graduate from Harvard last year with honors
despite tragedies in her home country. For most of the time she was
studying in Cambridge, her father was in solitary confinement in
the capital, Abuja, unable to receive medicine for his high blood
pressure, unable to see his family or his lawyers. And two years
ago this month, Hafsat's mother was shot dead in broad daylight.
</P>
<P>
   No one has been charged with the crime, and the Abacha regime
has refused to investigate. The Abiolas are from the southern
Yuroba people, and they hold little sway with the government.
</P>
<P>
   Since graduating, Abiola has cared for her sister and three
younger brothers. She also has become an unofficial spokeswoman for
the exile community, speaking at forums of Amnesty International
and to college audiences. In February, after Abiola made a moving
speech, the New York City Council named the intersection of Second
Avenue and 43d Street in Manhattan Kudirat Abiola Corner, after her
mother. That way, the employees of the nearby Nigerian Consulate
are reminded of the killing every day they go to work.
</P>
<P>
   ``Hafsat is an incredible lady,'' said Dapo Olorunyomi, a former
political prisoner who attended the embassy protest Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
   Thanks to sources in Abuja, Abiola recently learned that her
father had been transferred to solitary confinement in Aso Rock,
the presidential compound. The Abiola children think their father,
a millionaire publisher and entrepreneur, was being held hostage.
</P>
<P>
   General Abacha, 54, died before dawn Monday. Soon after, the
Abiolas heard that their father had been whisked away from the
presidential compound by armed guards. Tuesday, despite repeated
calls to Abuja, they were unable to learn his whereabouts.
</P>
<P>
   ``I have already lost my mom,'' Abiola said. ``The idea that I
might lose my dad as well is frightening.''
</P>
</TEXT>
