<HEADER>
A1628 &Cx1f; tad-z
u a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-DEATHPENALTY-COX     06-09 0547
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-DEATHPENALTY-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Death row inmate to receive new sentencing trial
 &HT;    By Bill Rankin
 &HT;    c. 1998 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA _ A condemned man on Georgia's death row for 24 years
deserves a new sentencing trial because his lawyer called no
witnesses and offered no evidence to spare his client from the
electric chair.
</P>
<P>
   In a ruling issued Tuesday, the 11th U.S. Circuit Court of
Appeals said if a jury could hear all the evidence on behalf of
Wilburn Wiley Dobbs, ``a reasonable probability exists'' that he
would not have been sentenced to die.
</P>
<P>
   The unanimous ruling was written by Judge Joseph Hatchett, a
President Carter appointee, and joined by two Republican
appointees, Judges Gerald Tjoflat and Stanley Birch.
</P>
<P>
   Dobbs, now 49, was sentenced to death in May 1974 for the
shotgun killing of Roy Sizemore, a 67-year-old Chickamauga, Ga.
grocer, during an armed robbery. Dobbs also fired and missed a
milkman who entered the store during the holdup and fractured the
skull of a 62-year-old woman with the butt of his shotgun as he
fled the store. According to Justice Department records, there are
fewer than 10 others in the country who have been on death row
longer than Dobbs.
</P>
<P>
   The Dobbs case has been denounced by human rights groups that
have accused his lawyer, Donald Bennett of Chattanooga, Tenn., of
being so racially biased he did not effectively represent Dobbs,
who is black. Bennett has also admitted in court testimony to using
racial slurs and believing that blacks ``in general are inferior to
whites morally and intellectually.''
</P>
<P>
   But the federal appeals court, one step below the U.S. Supreme
Court, did not address any racial allegations. Instead, it
summarily criticized Bennett's performance. While Bennett produced
no mitigating evidence during the sentencing phase of the trial,
witnesses could have testified that Dobbs's mother ``would often
not allow him to stay in the same house with her, and when she
(did), she ran a brothel where she exposed him to sexual
promiscuity, alcohol and violence.''
</P>
<P>
   While the aggravating factors in the case are ``deplorable,''
Hatchett wrote, they ``do not rise to such a level as to overshadow
the significant mitigating evidence that Dobbs's jury had no
occasion to consider.''
</P>
<P>
   ``Wiley is very relieved and extremely grateful,'' one of his
lawyers, Michael McIntyre, said.
</P>
<P>
   Dobbs's appeal, which had been rejected by numerous courts,
appeared futile until McIntyre found the stenotype tapes, long
thought to be lost, of Bennett's closing argument in the death
penalty phase of the case. When the U.S. Supreme Court learned in
1993 of their existence, it ordered that the tapes be reviewed.
These tapes produced a transcript that showed Bennett did not even
ask the jury for mercy or to spare his client's life.
</P>
<P>
   Bennett not only failed to produce any mitigating evidence, he
read extensively from a 1972 U.S. Supreme Court opinion that
invalidated the death penalty. Bennett said that while the high
court had reinstated the penalty, it was likely to overturn it
again, leading jurors ``to believe that a death sentence would not
result in Dobbs's execution,'' Hatchett's ruling said.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
