<HEADER>
A1629 &Cx1f; tad-z
u f &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-GM-STRIKE-COX     06-09 0914
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-GM-STRIKE-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    More plants at risk for shutdown
 &HT;    By Mike Drummond
 &HT;    c. 1998 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   DAYTON, Ohio _ Another General Motors Corp. truck assembly plant
plant fell idle Tuesday from the United Auto Workers strike in
Flint, Mich., raising fears of not if, but when more plants will
close.
</P>
<P>
   ``This strike will shut down the whole company, no doubt about
it,'' said Jim Harbour of Harbour and Associates in Troy, Mich.,
publisher of an annual report on the automotive manufacturing
industry.
</P>
<P>
   As many as 18 assembly plants in the United States, Canada and
Mexico could be crippled for lack of parts within days or weeks _ a
repeat of the paralysis caused by a 1996 strike at two GM brake
plants in Dayton.
</P>
<P>
   A truck assembly plant in Flint ceased operations Tuesday. It
joins the Moraine, Ohio truck assembly plant and five other
assembly or parts plants in Auburn Hills, Buick City and Orion
Twp., Mich., and Oshawa, Ontario, that have shut down since workers
at GM's Flint Metal Center walked off the job last week. The Flint
Metal Center produces fenders, hoods, doors and other stamped sheet
metal parts.
</P>
<P>
   As a result, more than 16,000 North American GM workers were
idle as the strike entered its sixth day.
</P>
<P>
   When the Flint strike is settled, it will take at least two or
three days before the Moraine plant will see any new parts and can
resume production of GMC Jimmy, Chevrolet Blazer and Oldsmobile
Bravada sport utility vehicles, analysts said.
</P>
<P>
   Meanwhile, workers and officials at GM's local Delphi Chassis
Systems plants said their jobs could be next, as the strike's
effect ripples through the world's largest automaker.
</P>
<P>
   ``If a truck plant is not making trucks, they're not going to
need our suspension components,'' said Keith Bailey, vice president
of the International Union of Electronics Workers Local 755, which
represents about 2,600 salaried employees at the Delphi Kettering
operation.
</P>
<P>
   Bailey said the Kettering plant could be shut as early as next
week.
</P>
<P>
   If the strike lingers, businesses beyond GM also would feel the
sting. Mayo Industries in Dayton, for example, would be forced to
layoff at least four of its 35 employees should the GM brake plant
close, said Jim Reidenbach, operations manager. Mayo supplies
returnable plastic trays for the plant.
</P>
<P>
   Adding to workers' anxiety is the uncertainty whether the state
will award unemployment benefits to idled local GM workers. A
spokesman for the Ohio Bureau of Employment Services said officials
are still mulling the decision.
</P>
<P>
   For GM and its workers, bad news is building like storm clouds.
GM faces a second threatened walkout Thursday at its Delphi
Automotive Systems' East parts factory in Flint. The plant and an
adjoining Delco facility employ about 5,800 members of UAW Local
651. The plant makes speedometers, tachometers and other instrument
panel parts for nearly all of GM's cars and trucks.
</P>
<P>
   ``If that (strike) happens, nobody will be working in any GM
plant,'' predicted one local union official, who declined to be
named.
</P>
<P>
   Union walkouts cost GM $1.2 billion after tax in 1996 _ most of
that as a result from a 17-day strike at GM's Dayton brake plants _
and $330 million last year. The automaker has had a more troubled
relationship with the UAW than rivals Ford Motor Co. and Chrysler
Corp., in part because GM is cutting its U.S. hourly work force of
about 225,000 by 5 percent annually. Ford and Chrysler have added
workers or maintained employment levels.
</P>
<P>
   Economic observers speculated that GM could take advantage of
the labor woes to hasten the closure or sale of some of its
troubled plants, including two Delphi brake plant operations in
Dayton.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're really on the border line with some of our GM plants and
their alleged lack of profitability,'' said professor Robert
Premus, chairman of the economics department at Wright State
University. ``The longer the strike carries out, GM may feel
pressure to close their more marginal plants.''
</P>
<P>
   Premus cited two Delphi brake plants. Combined, the plants have
lost more than $40 million in the past two years and projections
show they could lose as much as $262 million in the next five
years.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't know that the company welcomes labor strife,'' Premus
added. ``But I think they'll take advantage of it and hasten some
of the structural changes they're trying to bring about ...
including outsourcing and moving operations overseas.''
</P>
<P>
   Flint's metal center is a poster child of inefficiency,
according to the 1997 Harbour Report, an annual automotive
manufacturing study.
</P>
<P>
   In 1996, the center's 101 ``pieces per worker'' ranked the plant
33rd of 38 plants in North America, compared with 437 pieces per
worker at Toyota Motor Corp.'s Georgetown, Ky., complex and 754
pieces per hour at Honda Motor Company's East Liberty plant.
</P>
<P>
   Nearly 3,400 workers are employed at GM's Flint center. The
strike is the seventh at a GM plant in the United States since
early 1997.
</P>
<P>
   Flint union leaders said GM reneged on some of the $300 million
investment planned for the their plant. They also object to what
they say are GM's plans to cut 191 jobs.
</P>
<P>
   GM maintains the union has not cooperated with changes to make
the plant more competitive. The company insists it has made a
significant portion of the planned investment, though officials
will not say how much.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
