<HEADER>
A1630 &Cx1f; tad-z
u a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-NERVE-COX     06-09 0728
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-NERVE-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Vets demand truth on nerve gas report
 &HT;    By Arthur Brice
 &HT;    c. 1998 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA _ The largest Vietnam veterans' group in the nation is
calling for a congressional investigation into whether the U.S.
military used poison gas to kill American deserters during the war.
</P>
<P>
   Secretary of Defense William Cohen ordered the Pentagon on
Monday to investigate allegations in a CNN/Time magazine news story
that U.S. special forces used sarin nerve gas during a 1970 raid
into Laos to kill American deserters. A Pentagon report is due
within 30 days.
</P>
<P>
   But the 53,000-member Vietnam Veterans of America wants an
independent probe.
</P>
<P>
   ``You got the people involved investigating themselves,'' said
Joe Sternburg, acting executive director of the group.
</P>
<P>
   No member of Congress has requested an investigation, but Rep.
David Skaggs (D-Colo.), a member of the House intelligence
committee who was a Marine in Vietnam, said he asked the committee
staff to see what the CIA knew.
</P>
<P>
   In addition, Sternburg said, any such raid would have been
conducted by a special operating group (SOG), which often didn't
work within regular military structures.
</P>
<P>
   ``You're going to find SOG was outside the lines,'' Sternburg
said Tuesday. ``Investigating traditional military sources will not
get the answers.''
</P>
<P>
   That assessment was shared by journalist Seymour Hersh, who won
the 1970 Pulitzer Prize for breaking the story of the My Lai
massacre.
</P>
<P>
   ``You aren't going to see documents,'' Hersh said. ``That's like
seeing documents saying John F. Kennedy authorized the
assassination of Fidel Castro.''
</P>
<P>
   Although the Pentagon says it has found no information to
substantiate the allegations, Defense Department officials insist
they will conduct a thorough investigation.
</P>
<P>
   ``We have a vested interest in finding out what the truth is,''
Pentagon spokesman Bill Darley said.
</P>
<P>
   Former Defense Secretary Melvin Laird said Monday that the U.S.
military shipped a ``small amount'' of sarin to Vietnam in 1967 but
never used it. Laird also expressed skepticism about the
allegations. ``I have no recollection of any operation like that,''
Laird told The Associated Press. ``It doesn't seem logical to me.
And I never approved it.''
</P>
<P>
   According to CNN and Time, the 1970 raid into Laos was called
Operation Tailwind.
</P>
<P>
   Darley confirmed that a Sept. 11, 1970, raid into Laos was
dubbed Operation Tailwind. But the Pentagon spokesman said the
three-day operation by 16 U.S. Army special forces soldiers,
commonly known as Green Berets, and 110 Montagnard troops was
carried out as a ``diversionary attack,'' not to hunt down American
deserters.
</P>
<P>
   ``It was to create chaos and confusion and relieve pressure off
an ongoing CIA operation,'' Darley said.
</P>
<P>
   Darley said he did not know the nature of that CIA operation.
Central Intelligence Agency spokeswoman Anya Guilsher declined to
comment, referring all questions to the Pentagon.
</P>
<P>
   Stanley Olchovik, a former 30-year Green Beret who directed
long-term reconnaissance operations into North Vietnam, said
Tuesday he was not aware of any attempts to kill American deserters
nor did he know about any use of chemical weapons.
</P>
<P>
   However, Olchovik said, special operating groups worked under
tightly compartmentalized conditions.
</P>
<P>
   Hersh said he knew that American military officials were
concerned about deserters but he never heard about any organized
assassination missions. He said he did find out, though, about an
assassination.
</P>
<P>
   ``I interviewed somebody two years ago who was an assassin,''
Hersh said. ``There was some kid who they thought was sabotaging
helicopters, so he took him out.''
</P>
<P>
   Some veterans say they doubt that deserters were targeted for
assassination.
</P>
<P>
   There would have been no reason to kill most deserters, said
Phil Budahn of the American Legion. ``By and large a defector is
not a threat. A defector is a private. A defector is a corporal. He
does not know anything of military importance.''
</P>
<P>
   Regardless, said Steve Bramham, a national board member for
Vietnam Veterans of America, no deserters should have been killed.
``Personally, not speaking for the VVA, I believe that even if they
were defectors, they should have been brought to trial,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
