<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-RUDOLPH-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Auction of suspected bomber's items fetches sizeable crowd, sum
 &HT;    By John Harmon
 &HT;    c. 1998 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   MURPHY, N.C. _Notoriety does have some advantages for Eric
Robert Rudolph, the North Carolina man accused of the fatal bombing
of a Birmingham abortion clinic.
</P>
<P>
   Items he left behind brought top dollar at an auction Tuesday
that attracted a sizeable crowd and several professional
collectors, and much of the money would go to Rudolph if he chose
to show up and claim it.
</P>
<P>
   The contents of storage unit 91, mostly assorted household junk
and handtools abandoned in January when Rudolph fled arrest, were
auctioned to cover unpaid rent.
</P>
<P>
   A mini-storage auction normally attracts only a handful of
buyers and brings a few hundred dollars, said Cal Stiles, owner of
Cal's Mini Storage. But Rudolph's stuff drew almost 100 people,
with 80 items selling for $2,639, mostly to collectors and dealers
of memorabilia.
</P>
<P>
   Last seen in Murphy the day after the Jan. 29 Birmingham
bombing, Rudolph is on the FBI's Ten Most Wanted list. A $1 million
reward awaits anyone who provides information that leads to his
arrest.
</P>
<P>
   ``You got to figure that in 20 years we'll be reading about him
in the history books,'' said Mark Rowan, a Marietta collectibles
dealer who purchased a number of items, including a a metal foot
locker for $100. ``I wouldn't have given you $10 for it without it
being connected with him.''
</P>
<P>
   Several items, most notably a desk lamp and a metal locker, were
still covered with black fingerprint powder.
</P>
<P>
   The items that attracted the most aggressive bidding and highest
prices were four search warrants, two originals and two facsimiles
sent to owner Stiles demanding that federal agents be allowed to
look through Rudolph's storage locker. The warrants were executed
earlier this year.
</P>
<P>
   One original warrant brought $370, while the other sold for
$260. The fax copies went for $250 and $225.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm an auctioneer myself and I plan to auction it,'' said Jan
Weeks who bid the $370 for one of the warrants. ``It's a gamble,
but I think I can make money on it.''
</P>
<P>
   Agents of the FBI and the U.S. Bureau of Alcohol, Tobacco and
Firearms had already confiscated a number of items from the locker,
auctioneer Bob Grove told the crowd. Earlier reports said
authorities had found evidence in the locker of dynamite and nails
of the same type used in the bomb.
</P>
<P>
   Investigators also have questioned merchants in western North
Carolina about whether Rudolph had bought wiring like that used in
the Birmingham bomb and in bombs used in three bombings in Atlanta.
</P>
<P>
   ``Here's a box of wires... no comment,'' joked Grove, as he held
up a cardboard box filled with wires and household electrical
switches.
</P>
<P>
   Bidders paid as much as $30 each for several bags containing
hundreds of re-load cartridges of various calibers for both rifles
and pistols. Such cartridges are commonly used by veteran hunters.
</P>
<P>
   Though Rudolph's notoriety focused the spotlight on the auction,
Stiles said such public sales are routine. ``If an account is
delinquent,'' he said, ``we auction the contents to clear the
unit.''
</P>
<P>
   Under state law, Stiles explained, he is entitled to $235 of
unpaid rent on the 10-foot by 10-foot unit, plus the auction
expenses. The remaining amount will be handed over to the Cherokee
County Clerk of Court to be held in an escrow account for Rudolph
in case he returns.
</P>
<P>
   Rudolph is also wanted for questioning for possible involvement
in a string of nail-bomb attacks that terrorized Atlanta in 1996
and 1997, including the fatal bombing at Centennial Olympic Park
during the Summer Games.
</P>
<P>
   In one of the most intensive manhunts ever in the South, scores
of agents have combed the mountainous area around Murphy over the
past four months. About 75 agents are continuing to work in the
area, doggedly seeking any clues of Rudolph's whereabouts.
</P>
<P>
   ``I suspect that when he is arrested, (the items) will skyrocket
in value,'' said Grove. ``A lot of these dealers are hoping to make
a big profit.''
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
