u a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-TIME-SCHAFER-COX     06-09 0439
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-TIME-SCHAFER-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Georgia man gets new libel trial
 &HT;    By Bill Rankin
 &HT;    c. 1998 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA _ An Austell, Ga. man Time magazine misidentified as an
alleged international terrorist has won the opportunity to present
his libel case against the magazine again.
</P>
<P>
   Michael Schafer, 44, lost his federal case in an April 1996 jury
trial against Time, but on Tuesday the 11th U.S. Circuit Court of
Appeals ruled that Schafer deserved a new trial.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm glad the court upheld what we thought was right,'' Schafer
said after learning about the decision. ``Just how wrong the
magazine was in publishing that story is going to come out.''
</P>
<P>
   In its April 27, 1992, cover story on the 1988 bombing of Pan
American Flight 103, Time reported that Iranian terrorists had
downed the plane over Lockerbie, Scotland, because it was carrying
a U.S. anti-terrorist team. The crash killed all 259 aboard and 11
people on the ground.
</P>
<P>
   Accompanying the article was a photograph of a man identified as
David Lovejoy, a reported double agent for the United States and
Iran who allegedly told terrorists which plane to destroy. But
Schafer was the man in the picture, and he sued the magazine for
libel.
</P>
<P>
   After deliberating a few hours, an eight-person jury found that
Time should pay no damages to Schafer, a commercial floor cleaner
and former international news cameraman.
</P>
<P>
   In its ruling Tuesday, the federal appeals court said that U.S.
District Judge Willis Hunt correctly instructed the jury on the law
governing libel cases. But the the applicable law is ``confusing,''
said the opinion, written by Judge Stanley Birch.
</P>
<P>
   When instructing jurors, Hunt said that to prove libel, Schafer
had to show that Time acted negligently and deliberately tried to
injure him.
</P>
<P>
   ``Not everything that comes from the pen of a writer who harbors
a deep and personal hostility toward the subject need be of a type
calculated to injure,'' Birch wrote in a unanimous opinion for a
three-judge panel.
</P>
<P>
   Dennis Webb, Schafer's attorney, expressed satisfaction with the
ruling, saying that if the court had not reconciled the conflict
between having to prove both negligence and deliberate
maliciousness, ``there would be no more libel cases.''
</P>
<P>
   Webb said Schafer will return to court against Time unless the
magazine offers an acceptable settlement. ``We're not in this thing
for fun,'' he said. ``We're on a mission.''
</P>
<P>
   Peter Canfield, Time's attorney, said the magazine will ask the
full court to reconsider the decision.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
