<DATE_TIME> 1998-06-09 20:35 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A1633 &Cx1f; taf-z
s t &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-TRAVEL-PORTUGAL-EXPO-     06-09 1074
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-TRAVEL-PORTUGAL-EXPO-$ADV14-3TAKES-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
A MARINE-THEMED WORLD'S FAIR 
</HEADLINE>
   (For release on Sunday, June 14.)  
 (JT)  
 By ALAN RIDING    
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   LISBON, Portugal _ Ever since Britain and France began holding
universal exhibitions in the late 19th century to boast of their
power and prowess, world's fairs have had a political agenda. So
Portugal can be forgiven for looking beyond education and
entertainment in organizing its first international fair, Expo '98,
which opened in Lisbon on May 22 and runs through Sept. 30. Quite
simply, it wants the world to take note that Portugal, a tiny
backward dictatorship 25 years ago, is now a modern, self-confident
democracy. And it wants to remind us that this country, too, has a
glorious past.
</P>
<P>
   Of course, it needed an excuse. For that, its Spanish neighbors
conveniently pointed the way. Six years ago, Spain organized its
own coming-out party, Expo '92 in Seville, around the quincentenary
of Columbus's first trip to the New World, and chose ``The Age of
Discoveries'' as its theme. Portugal has used this year's 500th
anniversary of Vasco da Gama's opening of the sea route from Europe
to India to justify its show. And echoing its own 15th-, 16th- and
17th-century history as a great seafaring nation, its Expo theme is
``The Oceans: A Heritage for the Future.''
</P>
<P>
   The story of the oceans, past, present and future, is recounted
in six thematic pavilions, while 146 participating nations
(including landlocked countries like Switzerland and Bolivia) have
created pavilions that also deal with water, rivers, seas and
oceans. Their messages are many: with oceans covering 70 percent of
the world's surface, Planet Earth should really be called Planet
Water; the oceans that gave birth to life are now being polluted to
death; the oceans, the first highway of communication between
distant civilizations, remain the last unexplored frontier; and,
yes, if Portugal's empire once stretched from Brazil to Angola and
Mozambique as far as Goa, Macao and East Timor, it was thanks to
its intrepid navigators.
</P>
<P>
   Still, the $2 billion spent on the show would be a stiff price
to pay were Expo '98 no more than public relations. But, for all
their new national pride, the Portuguese remain a pragmatic lot.
Thus, Expo '98 has become the occasion for restoring historic
buildings and improving Lisbon's thoroughfares and public
transportation. Further, by situating the fair on a former
industrial wasteland, the government has set in motion a vast
program of urban renewal that includes construction of the stunning
10-mile-long Vasco da Gama Bridge across the Tagus River and of a
new Oriente railroad station designed by the Spanish architect
Santiago Calatrava.
</P>
<P>
   Portugal has also learned the lessons of Seville: Expo '92
involved construction of scores of buildings _ most of which now
stand empty. So, rather than inviting participating countries to
compete with fancy designs, Portugal has provided temporary
quarters for each national pavilion. As a result, this fair is less
visually spectacular and covers only 150 acres, compared with
Seville's 540-acre site. But since most permanent buildings have
been assigned a post-Expo function, the area is unlikely to slide
back into decay, not least because the Pavilion of Portugal will
become the seat of the Portuguese government.
</P>
<P>
   The fair's projected 10 million visitors may well find all this
irrelevant, yet it goes some way toward answering the question of
why anyone still bothers to hold a world's fair. It may have made
sense to bring the world to a single city before air travel,
television and the Internet placed the world within easy reach. But
a world's fair is probably only justified today if it leaves a
significant legacy for the city where it is held.
</P>
<P>
   Still, at least for the visitor, the effort is justified by the
great variety of experiences on offer. In this case, the theme
itself could not be more universal. And where else is it possible
to travel from country to country as simply as wandering around a
small town? The site and the pavilions open at 10 a.m. daily, with
all but one of the pavilions closing at 8 p.m. (the Pavilion of
Virtual Reality stays open until midnight). After that, there is a
rich program of music, dance, theater and other entertainment,
climaxing nightly at 11:45 p.m. with ``Acqua Matrix,'' a light,
sound and fireworks extravaganza at the Olivais Dock. And to keep
visitors going until the site closes at 3 a.m., there are a host of
restaurants, fast-food outlets and stand-up snack bars.
</P>
<P>
   But where to start? The length of the lines is one variable. The
length of the planned visit is another, because one day will not
suffice to ``do'' all of Expo '98. On the other hand, while it is
not necessary to see everything, there are some ``musts.''
</P>
<P>
   The most popular building is already the $70 million Ocean
Pavilion, which is in fact a new kind of aquarium called an
Oceanarium. Designed by the American architect Peter Chermayeff,
who has built five other aquariums around the world, it is inspired
by the idea that the world's oceans constitute a single body of
water. Its principal feature is a large central swimming tank that
contains fish from all oceans and rocks, corals and flora from
different marine environments. Large windows on two floors give
visitors the impression they are scuba-diving. Then, on each corner
of the building, which is itself surrounded by the water of the
Olivais Dock, the sea life of the Antarctic, the Atlantic, the
California Pacific and the Indian Ocean have their own sections.
The Oceanarium will continue to operate after Expo.
</P>
<P>
   In the Pavilion of Portugal, designed by the renowned local
architect Alvaro de Siza Vieira, the aim is to recall Portugal's
own seafaring past. This is done through a multiscreen re-enactment
of the arrival of Portuguese navigators in Japan in 1543 in which
special effects bring alive ancient Japanese screen paintings
recording the event. For Expo '98, the Portuguese government also
financed excavation of a 17th-century Portuguese ship that sank at
the entrance to the Tagus River as it returned from the East.
Spices, pottery and bronze recovered from the ship are on display
beside a large video screen presenting a computer simulation of
their discovery.
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
</P>
<P>
   Perhaps the most distinctive building on the site is the bulbous
Utopia Pavilion, which is in fact an indoor stadium with a capacity
for 15,000 destined to become Lisbon's first multipurpose arena.
For the moment, it is being used six times a day to present a
24-minute multimedia theater show recreating the dreams and myths
inspired by the oceans. In contrast, the Knowledge of the Seas
Pavilion and the Pavilion of the Future aspire to be more
educational: the first covers the history of ocean travel and
exploration, culminating with what appears to be a 130-foot boat
under construction; the other focuses more on the threat to the
world's oceans posed by pollution.
</P>
<P>
   But word is already out that the Pavilion of Virtual Reality
promises the most fun. Indeed, in the hope of discouraging
inevitable crowds, it is the only pavilion for which an extra
ticket is required. In groups of 40, visitors climb aboard a marine
shuttle (on a mobile platform) to visit underwater ruins, a trip
they experience through a virtual reality movie. The shuttle then
suffers an accident, and visitors must take refuge in a deep-sea
research center, with fish swimming by the portholes. After two
more adventures, a special elevator, with video screens on floor
and ceiling, finally takes the travelers back to safety.
</P>
<P>
   If this high-tech pavilion's problem is not to be overrun by
crowds, the challenge for the national pavilions is to draw as many
people as possible. And it is here that the crucial variables of
money and imagination come into play. In the main, poor countries
have fairly modest pavilions, offering films and posters promoting
investment and tourism along with stands selling local handicraft.
A few have tried harder: Peru is displaying breathtaking
pre-Hispanic gold objects belonging to the so-called Lord of Sipan
and excavated barely a decade ago, while Lebanon has built a small
wooden copy of a Phoenician sailboat.
</P>
<P>
   It is apparent, though, that most tourists prefer an experience
to information, which is why several pavilions have come up with
clever gimmicks to insure they are noticed. Sweden, for instance,
invites visitors to walk through four egg-shaped forms _ created by
artists and scientists with humor and poetic license _ to
experience Stockholm's climate at different times of the year, from
rainy spring through scorching summer and chilly fall to frozen
winter. Finland's pavilion has placed an ice rink beside a huge
model of the prow of an ice-breaking ship. On the bridge, tourists
can try their hand at steering an ice-breaker, thanks to a
simulator similar to one used for training.
</P>
<P>
   Germany has taken up the theme of marine exploration by creating
an imaginary research station 300 feet below the waves, reachable
by an elevator equipped with video screens that serve as
``windows'' into the imaginary deep. Visitors then walk through
various control rooms, packed with interactive screens, ships
models and state-of-the-art marine machinery, finally climbing
aboard a so-called Expo-jet for a space ride through time from
Lisbon's Expo '98 to the next world's fair, Expo 2000, to be held
in the German city of Hanover. In contrast, Argentina takes people
back through time, with a sound-and-light walk among remnants and
models of dinosaurs found in northwest Argentina. More topically,
six times a day, this pavilion also offers a 12-minute exhibition
of live tango dancing.
</P>
<P>
   Most countries keep close to the oceans theme, and few have more
experience taming the seas than the Netherlands. In its pavilion,
visitors walk up a ramp, which resembles a large dike and, through
a film and myriad models, are then taken on a tour of the country's
land reclamation projects, busy ports and new generation of
windmills. Italy has offered a collection of model vessels, from
14th-century Venetian rowing boats to the cruise ships and oil rigs
of today. Even more stunning is Greece's 25-foot-long model of the
Athena, a 130-foot-long warship dating from 650 B.C. that had no
fewer than 174 oarsmen on board.
</P>
<P>
   The U.S. pavilion, one of the largest at Expo '98, does a fair
job of mixing education and entertainment. Its basic message,
though, is promotional: that the United States is at the vanguard
of marine science and technology. For children, there is a chance
to handle sea slugs used in neurological research, to touch an
iceberg and to follow a whale-tagging exercise through a satellite
connection to the north Atlantic. For adults, there is a copy of
the United States Navy's Deep Sea Rover, a small submarine that
explores the seabed. For everyone, there is a remarkable
eight-minute film of deep-sea life filmed by the Woods Hole
Oceanographic Institution. Near the pavilion, the United States is
also sponsoring a sculpture, ``The Luso-American Wave,'' which will
carry the names of prominent Portuguese who migrated to the United
States.
</P>
<P>
   Of course, part of the fun _ and exhaustion _ of a world's fair
is not knowing quite where you are. Certainly I was unsure of what
I was looking for much of the time. But this does make for
surprises. Monaco? The principality is hardly a world naval power
(despite a marina crammed with luxury yachts), yet it has one of
Europe's oldest aquariums, while its well-designed pavilion reminds
us of its role in protecting the Mediterranean. Israel likes to
claim it has four coastlines _ on the Mediterranean, the Dead Sea,
the Sea of Galilee and the Red Sea. Its pavilion combines a display
of copies of ancient maps and a model of a boat from the time of
Jesus found at the Sea of Galilee with a photo exhibition marking
Israel's 50th anniversary. Poland decided to exhibit and promote
amber in its pavilion. Switzerland's water theme is built around
the four great rivers that have their source in the Swiss Alps.
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
</P>
<P>
   It is a measure of the energy expected of visitors that
countries invariably calculate a minimum time for visiting their
pavilions. Some, like Germany, which estimates a 40-minute visit,
evidently do not expect people to see all of the fair in a day.
Those that organize groups of tourists to pass through a series of
films or exhibits also make escape more difficult if the show grows
tiresome. Spain, for example, offers four movies about the oceans
and their problems lasting a total of 20 minutes, with the
pavilion's most interesting section _ a minimuseum of 16th- and
17th-century tapestries and paintings _ only accessible after the
films. With a good many pavilions, though, it is possible to take a
peek and, if nothing entices, to keep going.
</P>
<P>
   One thing is clear: no two days are alike at Expo '98. Every
country has its national day when it is expected to do something
special (the American national day here is June 14). Fifteen
open-air stages offer a variety of music every evening, from
Portuguese fado songs to jazz. Visitors also have a chance to
dance. A more unusual form of entertainment is provided by
allegorical carts, representing sea monsters called olharapos,
which put on shows across the site. One of the high points will be
the visit of some 120 tall ships, which will put into Lisbon
between July 31 and Aug. 3 as part of the Cutty Sark Tall Ships'
Race.
</P>
<P>
   Yes, in the end, perhaps that is Expo's principal appeal: that
no matter how much you plan, no matter how carefully you study your
map and guidebook, there is always an unexpected event and a
surprise discovery. And remember, in the world of Expo, there are
people from myriad countries and cultures who speak English and are
eager to make friends. So it is possible to measure Expo '98 by the
number of pavilions visited. But it is also possible to gauge
pleasure by the number of addresses exchanged with people from
distant lands. In that sense, a world's fair can also be a true
world's crossroads.
</P>
<P>
   NAVIGATING A WORLD'S FAIR
</P>
<P>
   Getting There
</P>
<P>
   The Expo '98 site, along the Tagus River close to the airport,
can be reached from downtown Lisbon by car, taxi, bus, subway,
train and even boat. A parking area is linked by shuttle bus to the
North Entrance. Taxis, buses, subways and trains all arrive at the
new Oriente railroad station, with direct access to the site
through the Sun Entrance. A river taxi, which leaves from the
Terreiro do Paco in Lisbon, drops visitors at the Tagus Entrance
(with an Expo ticket the ride is free).
</P>
<P>
   The Basics
</P>
<P>
   Tickets for one day and night (10 a.m. to 3 a.m.) cost $30; half
price for seniors and children (children under 5 enter free).
Evening tickets (8 p.m. to 3 a.m.) cost $12. Tickets for three days
cost $74; half price for seniors and children. Tickets for the
Pavilion of Virtual Reality cost $4.85; $3 for seniors and
children.
</P>
<P>
   Information: (351-1) 891-9898. For tickets, it is best to
contact your travel agent or purchase them upon arrival. Web site:
www.expo98.pt.
</P>
<P>
   Sea breezes should take some of the sting out of the summer
heat, and most of the pavilions are air-conditioned. But it is wise
to be armed with hat or parasol _ as well as comfortable shoes _
because walking in the sun is unavoidable and there is little shade
at the site.
</P>
<P>
   Getting Around
</P>
<P>
   A fleet of minibuses linking the main entrances will carry
passengers free from one end of the site to the other.
</P>
<P>
   A cable car ($3) offers a panoramic view of the fair as well as
the river and the new Vasco da Gama Bridge. A similar view is
possible from the Vasco da Gama Tower (admission: $3) near the
North Entrance.
</P>
<P>
   Where to Eat
</P>
<P>
   A wide range of eating choices includes 50 kiosks selling
baguette sandwiches, crepes, pizzas and the like, as well as seven
fast-foot outlets a la McDonalds. Five self-service restaurants
also offer traditional Portuguese dishes at modest prices ($10 to
$15 a person for a main dish, desert and soda). Some pavilions also
have stands selling local delicacies (the French pavilion has an
oyster bar, for example).
</P>
<P>
   Quality restaurants are also available. The Vasco da Gama Tower
has a good one 250 feet above the ground, while the menu at the
restaurant in Portugal's Pavilion is well described by its name, A
Viagem dos Sabores (A Journey of Tastes), aimed at introducing
visitors to Portuguese gastronomy. Unsurprisingly, the local
cuisine leans heavily on fish and seafood, with sea bass and crabs
particularly popular, although there is nothing more Portuguese
than a dish involving dried cod, or bacalhau. Lunch or dinner for
two, including wine (and definitely try Portuguese wine), runs to
about $80 at these establishments.
</P>
<P>
   Among a score of other sit-down restaurants, the Brazilian-run
Chimarrao, overlooking the Olivais Dock, has a wonderful salad bar,
while waiters circulate with a variety of meats and sausages, which
are cut at each table; $40 for two with wine or beer.
</P>
<P>
   Indeed, the world's fair also offers a tour of the world's food,
with the United States, Germany, the Philippines, Venezuela,
Mexico, Turkey, Uruguay, Finland and Spain all operating
restaurants outside their pavilions. Prices vary between $40 and
$80 for two with wine.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
