<SLUG> BC-SHELTER-BLAST-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
AT LEAST TWO DIE IN MONTREAL EXPLOSION
</HEADLINE>
  (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By COLIN NICKERSON  
 c.1998 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   MONTREAL _ A powerful explosion ripped apart a homeless shelter
Tuesday in this city's historic Old Quarter, killing at least two
people and seriously wounding 20. Another victim was believed to
have been buried in rubble.
</P>
<P>
   The explosion was one of two deadly blasts Tuesday, both
apparently accidental, that rocked cities in eastern Canada.
</P>
<P>
   In Saint John, New Brunswick, an explosion followed by a huge
fireball engulfed gasoline-making facilities at Canada's largest
oil refinery. One person was killed and two were injured.
</P>
<P>
   After the Montreal blast, fire department rescuers and search
dogs burrowed through the debris of the Accueil Bonneau shelter in
search of one or more victims who were thought to have been buried.
</P>
<P>
   The explosion forced police to close much of the city's heavily
touristed Old Quarter to pedestrians and motor traffic.
</P>
<P>
   A Roman Catholic nun who worked at the mission was reported
missing after the blast, and there was a possibility that others
might have been trapped.
</P>
<P>
   ``We have no precise information, but we believe there is at
least one shelter worker, maybe more, still under the debris,''
said Alain Michaud, a spokesman for the Montreal Fire Department.
``We are trying to get complete quiet so we can listen for
groans.''
</P>
<P>
   The blast, which went off shortly after noon, followed the
accidental cutting of a natural gas pipe in the building by a
contractor hired to repair meters, according to fire officials and
the gas company.
</P>
<P>
   A warning was given minutes before the explosion, and witnesses
said people were rushing into the street when the blast blew out
the front of the three-story structure, crushing cars and
shattering the windows of nearby tour buses.
</P>
<P>
   ``There was a strong smell of gas, then a terrible noise, and
then everything was ruins and smoke,'' said a shelter worker whose
blouse and skirt were drenched with blood.
</P>
<P>
   Hundreds of strollers were in the vicinity of the explosion,
although there were no reports of injuries to tourists or other
bystanders in one of Canada's most-visited historic districts. At
least 20 people, all workers or homeless people at the shelter,
were rushed to area hospitals.
</P>
<P>
   Two people, both reportedly female volunteers from the shelter,
died of their injuries. Another five were reported to be in
critical condition.
</P>
<P>
   The homeless shelter is attached to the Chapel
Notre-Dame-de-Bonsecours, whose statue of the Virgin Mary with arms
outstretched to the St. Lawrence River is a Montreal landmark made
famous as ``Our Lady of the Harbor'' in the Leonard Cohen song
``Suzanne.''
</P>
<P>
   In the Atlantic province of New Brunswick, meanwhile, one oil
worker was killed and two suffered injuries after a blast touched
off a major fire at the mammoth Irving Oil refinery in Saint John.
</P>
<P>
   Billows of smoke rose over the city as firefighters worked to
contain flames at the refinery. Hundreds were evacuated around the
refinery in the east end of the city.
</P>
<P>
   ``There was a boom, like the sound of a plane breaking the sound
barrier, then a huge fireball rose from the hydro-cracker,'' a
witness told Canadian television.
</P>
<P>
   The cracker tower is the tall structure, common to all
refineries, where crude oil is refined.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
