u a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-BAPTIST-COX     06-09 0407
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BAPTIST-COX </SLUG>

<TEXT>
<P>
   Baptist define marriage as non-equity union
</P>
<P>
   By Gayle White
</P>
<P>
   C. 1998 Cox News Service
</P>
<P>
   SALT LAKE CITY, Utah _ Southern Baptists on Tuesday adopted a
clear definition of marriage and called on wives to be submissive
to their husbands.
</P>
<P>
   The 8,300 messengers, or eligible voting members, attending the
annual convention here in the Salt Palace, added language to the
denominational statement of faith that describes marriage as ''the
uniting of one man and one woman in covenant commitment for a
lifetime'' and says ''a wife is to submit herself graciously to the
servant leadership of her husband.''
</P>
<P>
   The statement also says that a husband ''is to love his wife as
Christ loved the church'' and that ''children, from the moment of
conception, are a blessing.''
</P>
<P>
   ''We are saying to the culture this is God's plan for family
life,'' said Anthony Jordan, exedutive director of the Baptist
Convention of Oklahoma, who chaired the committee that drafted the
statement. ''It is not only a better way, it's the best way.''
</P>
<P>
   An effort by the Rev. Tim Owings, pastor of First Baptist Church
in Augusta, Ga., to call for mutual submission of husband and wife
failed, as did a motion by a Huntsville, Ala., pastor to add
language specifying that widowed or single men and women could be
considered a family.
</P>
<P>
   At a news conference following the vote, some committee members
said some of their wording--especially as it applies to women-- is
frequently misinterpreted by people who do not understand the
Bible.
</P>
<P>
   ''Submission is not a negative word,'' said Mary Mohler, a
housewife married to Albert Mohler, president of Southern Baptist
Theological Seminary in Louisville. ''It may not be a politically
correct word or a popular word, but it is a biblical word.''
</P>
<P>
   And committee member Dorothy Patterson, an educator married to
newly elected Southern Baptist Convention president Paige
Patterson, said that along with a husband's leadership ''comes
responsibility for providing for the household and protecting the
household.''
</P>
<P>
   After his election Tuesday, Paige Patterson, president of
Southeastern Baptist Theological Seminary, said the statement on
the family ''represents what Baptists have believed over the
years'' and added, ''I don't see it as being a negative statement
about anybody or anything.''
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
