<SLUG> BC-TOBACCO-SENATE-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
TOBACCO MEASURE MAY SURVIVE SENATE, AMENDMENTS GET CONSIDERATION
</HEADLINE>
  For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By BOB HOHLER  
 c.1998 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ With President Clinton intervening to salvage his
antitobacco initiative, Senate leaders agreed last night to keep
the bill from drifting into limbo by permitting votes on several
disputed amendments.
</P>
<P>
   Two days after the Senate majority leader, Trent Lott, declared
the $516 billion plan ``dead in the water,'' the Senate voted 52-46
for a GOP proposal to use $16 billion of the tobacco money to
combat drug abuse.
</P>
<P>
   Every Democrat opposed the five-year plan, which would increase
drug interdiction funding, ban needle-exchange programs and provide
vouchers for students who have been victims of drug-related crimes
to change schools. The only Republicans who voted against the
measure were Senators John H. Chafee of Rhode Island and James M.
Jeffords of Vermont.
</P>
<P>
   The Senate then rejected a less costly Democratic alternative to
the Repubican plan by a vote of 53-45.
</P>
<P>
   But the voting results were seen as far less crucial than the
fact the votes occurred.
</P>
<P>
   In their struggle to change the way cigarettes are sold and
marketed in the United States, proponents of the antitobacco
measure said their prime goal is to push some form of legislation
through the Senate and the House so a joint conference committee
and the White House can produce a final plan.
</P>
<P>
   Without the votes last night, the initiative was in serious
jeopardy of dying before reaching a final vote in the Senate. The
House has yet to act.
</P>
<P>
   The agreement permitting the votes followed lengthy negotations
among several key senators and last-ditch phone calls yesterday
from Clinton to Lott and Senator Tom Daschle of South Dakota, the
Democratic leader.
</P>
<P>
   ``We are working hard to get this thing back on track and get
into a position where a good comprehensive bill can pass the
Senate,'' Clinton said at a news conference with South Korean
President Kim Dae Jung.
</P>
<P>
   The bill's chief sponsor, Senator John McCain, an Arizona
Republican who earlier had raised the possibility he would withdraw
the legislation because of unyielding opposition from a small group
of GOP conservatives seeking a major tax cut in the measure,
expressed cautious optimism after the agreement.
</P>
<P>
   ``In the words of the late Mark Twain, the reports of the death
of this legislation are premature,'' McCain said. ``However, we
certainly by no means have total confidence we will reach a
successful conclusion.''
</P>
<P>
   The logjam broke in part when the conservative group, led by
Senator Phil Gramm, a Texas Republican, agreed to scale back his
plan to tap tobacco revenues to offset reductions in the so-called
marriage tax penalty. After negotiations with McCain and Senator
John F. Kerry of Massachusetts, the Democratic point man on the
bill, Gramm reduced the amount of tobacco money he will propose
using to offset the tax cut from $50 billion over five years to
$16.8 billion over the same period.
</P>
<P>
   The Senate is scheduled to vote Wednesday on Gramm's plan and a
Democratic alternative.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're beginning to break out and start moving now,'' Kerry
said in an interview. ``This is a very important development.''
</P>
<P>
   The progress followed a midday vote on a motion by Daschle to
end debate on the antitobacco measure and force a final vote. The
motion, which required 60 votes to pass, was defeated 56-42, 18
votes shy.
</P>
<P>
   Every Republican voted against the Daschle motion, as did two
Democrats from tobacco-farming states, Senators Wendell H. Ford of
Kentucky and Charles S. Robb of Virginia.
</P>
<P>
   But Daschle had vowed to force additional votes daily on
shutting off the debate, hoping to increase public pressure for
passing the bill.
</P>
<P>
   Senator Edward M. Kennedy, a leading proponent of cracking down
on the tobacco industry, said Daschle's strategy paid off. ``It
sent a very powerful message,'' he said, ``and the Republicans
blinked.''
</P>
<P>
   McCain said a final vote on the measure could follow debate on
several other amendments, including measures aimed at aiding
tobacco farmers and capping the fees lawyers receive for suing
tobacco companies.
</P>
<P>
   Meanwhile, House majority leader Richard Armey said the House
would not consider such sweeping legislation. Instead, the House
will focus on a narrow bill to reduce youth smoking.
</P>
<P>
   Armey also said the House would not use revenues from the bill
to reduce the marriage penalty. ``We're not going to use the
tobacco settlement as a cash cow for any purpose,'' he said.
</P>
</TEXT>
