<SLUG> BC-JAVA-CONSERVATIVE-SPI </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
COMPANY TARGETS COFFEE SALES TO CONSERVATIVES 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By JOEL CONNELLY  
 c.1998 Seattle Post-Intelligencer  
<TEXT>
<P>
   SUMNER, Wash. _ With a slogan whose theme dates back to a 1960
speech by Barry Goldwater _ ``The coffee that's taking America
back!'' _ a Sumner, Wash.-based coffee company is targeting its
sales to right-thinking Americans.
</P>
<P>
   The Original Conservative Coffee Company is marketing roasts
with names that will warm the hearts of Clinton enemies. The blends
may be light, but the humor runs to heavy name-calling and
innuendo.
</P>
<P>
   A Yasser Are-A-Rat Blend mocks the Palestinian leader. ``It's a
darker roast,'' explained co-founder Michael Wilson.
</P>
<P>
   The Endangered Species: The Spotted N.O.W. Blend takes aim at
environmentalists as well as feminists. The company's decaf roast
is called Gore's Blend. A lighter blend is entitled Say Hey: Paula
and Monica. The biggest seller is An American Hero Blend, a coffee
that celebrates Ronald Reagan.
</P>
<P>
   ``We are looking to a politically conservative market, people
who espouse the Judeo-Christian heritage on which our country was
founded,'' Wilson explained.
</P>
<P>
   ``Taking back'' has been a slogan of the right for nearly four
decades, since Goldwater told conservatives they could ``take back
this party'' in a richly blended speech to the 1960 Republican
National Convention.
</P>
<P>
   Ronald Reagan told conservative activists in the 1970s that it
was their duty to ``take back America.''
</P>
<P>
   But coffee?
</P>
<P>
   Well, the morning drink that helped wake up Seattle's national
image has long been associated with liberals and intellectuals.
</P>
<P>
   In Washington, D.C., where Wilson worked as a lobbyist, a pair
of coffee houses _ Politics and Prose, and Kramer's Books and
Afterwards _ long have been spots where civil libertarians,
consumerists and environmentalists gather to plot.
</P>
<P>
   Seattle has no greater center of intellectual brew than the
basement of the Elliott Bay Cafe, where book readings provide a
nucleus for gatherings of feminists, conservationists, poets and
aging followers of liberal politicians like Warren Magnuson and Al
Rosellini.
</P>
<P>
   In Wilson's view, however, the coffee market is shifting to the
right. ``We are going to make sure it shifts properly,'' Wilson
said. ``For the three months we have been up and running, we are
running ahead of expections. Conservatives are coming out of their
closets, or I should say out of their shells.''
</P>
<P>
   The Original Conservative Coffee Company is, for the moment,
catering to individualism. ``Everything we do is mail order,''
Wilson said. ``We do not have a store. We do not provide coffee to
stores.''
</P>
<P>
   The company is taking orders over the phone (1-888-RIGHT-81) and
via its webside, http://www.toccc.com.
</P>
<P>
   As with environment-oriented businesses at the other end of the
political spectrum, The Original Conservative Coffee Company
donates a portion of every month's profits to the cause.
</P>
<P>
   The current recipient of its largesse is Focus on the Family,
the Colorado-based radio program of the Rev. James Dobson. Dobson
has been in the news for threatening that Christian conservatives
will abandon the Republican Party if it does press their agenda.
</P>
<P>
   Its blends were recently featured in a Wall Street Journal
article. Its web site features endorsements from KVI talk show
hosts Kirby Wilbur and Michael Medved. To sell itself, the company
is using the us-against-them language prized by conservative direct
mail specialists: ``Liberals have labeled us the most controversial
coffee company in America.''
</P>
<P>
   The Sumner-based conservatives have yet to deliver any evil
empire jokes about Starbucks.
</P>
<P>
   It's worth noting, however, that the chairman of its giant
competitor, Howard Schultz, is a Democratic contributor much in
evidence during President Clinton's Seattle fundraising visit last
November.
</P>
<P>
   ``People who drink coffee in the United States, who are coffee
savvy, understand that Puget Sound is the coffee capital of
America,'' Wilson said. ``Not only are we (in a) liberal area, but
we are up against the heavies. We have our niche. We are out to
sell coffee to people who have the same political views that we
do.''
</P>
<P>
   Still, the Original Conservative Coffee Company is seeking to
take advantage of a national brouhaha with major local
implications.
</P>
<P>
   Its newest blend, which went on sale June 1, is entitled
American Entrepreneur.
</P>
<P>
   ``While the Justice Department attempts to strong-arm companies
such as Microsoft, we believe that it is time to wake up America to
this coming threat,'' explained a company release.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
