<SLUG> BC-PHILLY-NRA-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
PHILADELPHIA MAYOR ACCEPTS CHALLENGE TO TEST ENFORCEMENT OF GUN
LAWS
</HEADLINE>
   (ja) 
 By MICHAEL JANOFSKY   
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   PHILADELPHIA _ Pushing his figurative poker chips into the pot,
Mayor Edward Rendell called the National Rifle Association's hand.
</P>
<P>
   Throughout the NRA's 127th annual convention, which concluded
here Tuesday, the group's leaders campaigned for a new approach to
reducing gun-related violence in big cities. They said they wanted
full cooperation of federal and local authorities in one city to
test the theory that strict enforcement of existing gun laws and
intensive gun-use education in public schools would dramatically
cut the incidence of crime.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't agree with much of what they stand for,'' Rendell
said. ``But if they put the resources behind it, I'd be more than
willing for the city to serve as a prototype for their idea. No
question it could help.''
</P>
<P>
   In remarks just after his election as NRA president on Monday,
the actor Charlton Heston made a plea for the chance to try the
approach and suggested that Philadelphia, which has an unusually
high rate of violent crime, would make an ideal proving ground.
</P>
<P>
   Rendell, who was not invited to attend the convention, said in
an interview on Monday night that he would welcome any strategy
that would drive down the number of homicides in Philadelphia,
where more than 400 people have died of gun shots every year since
1989.
</P>
<P>
   But Rendell warned that the NRA's approach was too naive, given
the complexities of fighting crime in a metropolis. The largest
obstacle, he said, is the millions of dollars that would be needed
to build more prisons and detention centers, hire additional
prosecutors and expand the number of judges hearing criminal cases.
</P>
<P>
   And he disputed the NRA's contention that cities like
Philadelphia were not aggressive enough in prosecuting criminals. A
former prosecutor himself, Rendell said that Pennsylvania's prison
population increased by 30 percent over the last four years, to
34,000 inmates from 26,000, and that a typical sentence was ``twice
as long as it was in the 1980s.''
</P>
<P>
   ``We're doing exactly what the gun advocates want,'' he said.
``But their ideas can never work alone.''
</P>
<P>
   Like the NRA, Rendell and other big-city mayors have been
searching for innovative ways to stem violent crime. In
Philadelphia, stolen guns and the multiple purchases of guns have
been a particular problem.
</P>
<P>
   But while the NRA argues that stronger law enforcement would
deter criminals, Rendell said that, as a practical matter, tracking
the illegal sale of guns through record-keeping and background
checks _ which the NRA opposes _ would do more to help the police
and prosecutors build stronger cases and focus their efforts.
</P>
<P>
   Rendell said that ``personalizing guns'' through new
computer-chip technology would also go a long way toward ending the
kind of recent schoolyard shootings that killed and injured
students and teachers in places like West Paducah, Ky., Jonesboro,
Ark., and Springfield, Ore.
</P>
<P>
   As the NRA was electing Heston on Monday, Rendell and officials
for a dozen other cities were meeting with gun makers to share
ideas on how to reduce the risk of unauthorized and illegal uses of
guns. The group formed a committee to develop ideas over the next
four to six months.
</P>
<P>
   But Rendell said nothing intrigued him more than technology that
would prevent anyone but the registered owner of a gun from firing
it.
</P>
<P>
   ``Just in Philadelphia, 30 percent of the police officers shot
are shot by their own guns,'' he said. ``If we can stop that from
happening to police officers, why not for every purchaser? It's not
the only answer, but it would go a long way toward keeping guns in
the hands of their legitimate owners.''
</P>
<P>
   The debate over implementing such technology has raged for
several years, and generally, the NRA and manufacturers have
objected, arguing that personalizing guns is a form of restriction
and that the technology would drive up the cost of the weapon.
</P>
<P>
   Rendell said the same kinds of objections were raised by car
manufacturers decades ago when air bags were being considered.
</P>
<P>
   ``Now,'' he said of the car makers, ``they're putting side air
bags in the doors. And they're doing it voluntarily.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
