<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-MARKET-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
THREE-DAY RALLY IN STOCKS FIZZLES
</HEADLINE>
   (ja) 
 By SHARON R. KING    
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ A three-day rally in stocks fizzled on Tuesday and
left major market indexes mixed, illustrating Wall Street's renewed
concerns about the corporate earnings outlook and some wariness
about the near-term prospect for interest rates.
</P>
<P>
   But a rally among some Internet-related shares pushed technology
stocks higher, as the Nasdaq composite index closed above 1,800 for
the first time since May 22. Falling energy prices pushed up
transportation stocks, and news concerning prescription drugs
continued to buoy pharmaceutical shares.
</P>
<P>
   Blue-chip issues bore the brunt of the declines, with the Dow
Jones industrial average falling 19.68 points, to 9,049.92.
Financial services companies like American Express, J.P. Morgan)
and Wells Fargo, as well as some multinational companies such as
McDonald's, which had been higher in recent days, had some of the
largest retreats.
</P>
<P>
   Concerns about Wednesday's congressional testimony of the
Federal Reserve chairman, Alan Greenspan, also helped weaken
blue-chip issues, analysts said, as investors expressed some
concern that the Fed could still raise interest rates sometime
soon.
</P>
<P>
   ``The consensus seems to be that rates will not be going
higher,'' said Charles Johnson, a managing director and head equity
trader at Blaylock &AMP; Partners. ``But there is that nervousness in
the marketplace that maybe the Fed sees something that we don't,''
which would justify an interest rate increase, he said.
</P>
<P>
   A continuing flow of earnings warnings from companies is keeping
investors worried about the outlook for corporate profits, analysts
said.
</P>
<P>
   Tuesday, Billing Concepts, a billing agent for the
telecommunications industry, warned that earnings could fall below
expectations in its third and fourth quarters due to a decline in
demand. Arrow International, a maker of disposable medical
products, said fiscal third-quarter sales are likely to increase
less than expected because of slowing international orders.
</P>
<P>
   A decline in oil prices pushed the stocks of companies like
Chevron and Exxon lower after the Paris-based International Energy
Agency forecast a decline in Asian demand for oil. However, the
oil-price drop lifted stocks of transportation companies,
particularly airlines. Gains in such carriers as Alaska Air Group
and US Airways Group lifted the Amex airline index 4.1 percent and
the Dow Jones transportation average 3.11 percent, its biggest
one-day gain this year.
</P>
<P>
   Led by a 4-point rise in Pfizer, the Standard &AMP; Poor's 500 index
inched up 2.69 points to 1,118.41. Pfizer soared to 112 7/16 on
news that the Food and Drug Administration said the company's
impotence-treatment drug, Viagra, did not directly cause the deaths
of 16 users.
</P>
<P>
   The Nasdaq composite index gained 12.99 points to 1,800.76,
pulled higher by a broad rally in Internet stocks on news of a deal
between General Electric's NBC and the struggling web service Cnet,
which shot up 12[, or 37 percent, to 45[. Lycos, Yahoo, America
Online, Netscape Communications and Earthlink Network all rose.
Lycos also gained after receiving a patent for its ``spider''
search technology.
</P>
<P>
   But some Internet-related shares that had caught investor
attention in recent weeks are now languishing. K-Tel International,
which soared to 33 15/16 after the company announced in April that
it would sell music on the Internet, fell 33/64, to 11\.
</P>
<P>
   Other prominent losses Tuesday included Chromatics Color
Sciences International shares, which fell about 49 percent before
partly recovering to close at 6{, down 2 5/16. The company develops
technologies to scientifically measure skin color in order to
detect jaundice in infants.
</P>
<P>
   Asensio &AMP; Co., a firm which bets that stocks will go down,
recommended selling the stock on Tuesday. Asensio said that
Chromatics' principal product has no sales and licensing potential
and that irregular trading activity may have occurred in the stock
among owners, including two Dreyfus micro-cap mutual funds that
have sizable holdings in Chromatics.
</P>
<P>
   A Dreyfus spokesman called the allegations ``unsubstantiated.''
And Darby Macfarlane, the chief executive of Chromatics, said the
company was ``working diligently to put out a detailed report'' to
counter the Asensio claims.
</P>
</TEXT>
