<HEADER>
A1667 &Cx1f; tic-z
r a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-DOMESTIC-VIOLENCE-AZR     06-09 0948
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-DOMESTIC-VIOLENCE-AZR </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
TRYING TO KILL SPOUSE WAS TURNING POINT FOR SHELTER FOUNDER 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by N.Y. Times News Service clients)  
 By JULIE AMPARANO  
 c.1998 The Arizona Republic  
<TEXT>
<P>
   (Undated) - She wanted him to die that night.
</P>
<P>
   For nearly four years, Betty DellaCorte Ryan had endured her
husband's slaps, kicks and punches. They often left her in a bloody
mess and heading for the emergency room.
</P>
<P>
   She could tell this night was going to be another bad one by the
way he was ranting and screaming at her. Lately, he had been
threatening to pull out his gun.
</P>
<P>
   ``You're shacking up with men,'' Ryan recalls him yelling at
her. Then, he shouted for another beer. That was her cue.
</P>
<P>
   She walked into the kitchen, pulled out a fistful of valiums,
got a beer from the refrigerator and began dropping the capsules
into the can. She was amazed at how calm and natural it all seemed.
</P>
<P>
   ``One, two, three, four, five, six, seven, eight, nine, ten,
eleven. That should do it,'' she says she thought and added: ``I
slept so good that night.''
</P>
<P>
   Her husband passed out before he could finish the beer, but
survived.
</P>
<P>
   That night in 1971 was a turning point for Ryan. It pushed her
to become a pioneer in the battle against domestic violence. Ryan
founded Faith House in 1974, one of the first domestic abuse
shelters in Arizona and the country. Six years later, she opened a
Faith House in Prescott to help victims in less urban areas.
</P>
<P>
   Today, her legacy has grown. There are eight licensed shelters
in Maricopa County, with a little more than 200 beds for domestic
abuse victims. Other agencies, such as homeless shelters, also
provide beds to domestic violence victims.
</P>
<P>
   In July, she expects to break ground on a five-acre
domestic-violence center with services that will include plastic
surgery to fix wounds, counseling for batterers and victims, crisis
housing for victims and job training. The shelter, she says, will
be called Prospect Park, after a place in Brooklyn where she sought
refuge from an abusive home.
</P>
<P>
   Sitting in her patio office last week, Ryan looks back on her 65
years of life. So much of it, she says, seems like such a distant
nightmare. &UR; Nights she spent crouched in her front-yard bushes to
escape the beatings. All the bruises she tried to cover with
makeup. A broken nose. And the time she woke up with a gun to her
head and he pulled the trigger.
</P>
<P>
   The gun was empty that time. And she vowed there would be no
next time. She filed for divorce the next day.
</P>
<P>
   She was already attending Al-Anon classes, a 12-step program for
families of alcoholics. It helped her understand why she stayed
with her abuser and how she could break the cycle of violence she
kept repeating and repeating.
</P>
<P>
   Turning and looking out the window, Ryan says life had always
been a violent one. She recounts a childhood memory.
</P>
<P>
   She is four years old and in the kitchen of her Brooklyn home,
clinging to the front of her mother's legs. Her mother has her arms
wrapped around her, trying to block the blows to the child's back.
</P>
<P>
   Still, her father continues to beat her until she slides down
her mother's apron, catches her two front teeth on it and they rip
out.
</P>
<P>
   ``They were loose already,'' said Ryan. ``See, even to this day
I tend to minimalize it.''
</P>
<P>
   Minimalizing and rationalizing was how Ryan says she made it
through life.
</P>
<P>
   First, she did it for her father. Later, it was for her first
and second husband.
</P>
<P>
   Her first husband also had been abusive. Ryan says he was very
controlling and criticized everything she would do. By the time she
divorced him in 1963, after 11 years of marriages and the birth of
two daughters, she says she had little self esteem left and fell
victim to a physically abusive second husband.
</P>
<P>
   ``That was all I knew,'' confesses Ryan, who divorced her second
husband after three-and-a-half years. ``I didn't know there was any
other way.''
</P>
<P>
   Al-Anon, Ryan says, helped her realize she had choices. It also
got her started in the domestic violence business. From her Al-Anon
meetings, Ryan had met other women who were being beaten by their
husbands. She began offering them and their children shelter in her
home.
</P>
<P>
   ``I would wake up in the morning and see these women and
children asleep in our living room,'' recalls Lisa Gebhardt, Ryan's
38-year-old daughter. ``At first, I really resented it. I wanted
nothing to do with it.''
</P>
<P>
   Today, Lisa and her sister, Robin Burke, are part of the Faith
House team. Robin runs the Prescott shelter and Lisa manages the
alternative programs in Phoenix.
</P>
<P>
   After two years of taking domestic violence victims into her
home, Ryan decided to convert her residence officially into the
first domestic abuse shelter.
</P>
<P>
   For five years, the shelter ran only with volunteers and
donations. Later, bingo games helped fund the programs and build
the Prescott facility.
</P>
<P>
   At first, Ryan would do practically everything. Her right-hand
assistant was _ and still is _ Flo Mills, another domestic-abuse
survivor. The two women would take the victims to Al-Anon meetings
and counseling sessions and wipe away their tears.
</P>
<P>
   ``Actually, we would cry with them,'' says Ryan, who today
mostly handles chief executive duties, such as securing funding,
and lobbies for stricter laws.
</P>
<P>
   Reflecting on how her life has changed, Ryan wants to provide
hope to other women.
</P>
<P>
   ``Look at me. People told me it couldn't be done. They told me
what I had was a dream and they couldn't invest in a dream,'' says
Ryan. ``That's why we call it Faith House, because it was built on
faith.''
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
Julie Amparano can be reached at by email at
julie.amparano(at)pni.com.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
