<DATE_TIME> 1998-06-09 21:02 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A1674 &Cx1f; tta-z
u i &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-NIGERIA-ART-500&AMP;ADD-N     06-09 1160
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-NIGERIA-ART-500&AMP;ADD-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
NIGERIA'S NEW LEADER COMMITS TO OCTOBER ELECTION 
</HEADLINE>
  (ART ADV: Graphic is being sent to NYT graphic clients.
Non-subscribers can make individual purchase by calling
212-556-4204 or -1927.) 
(th) 
 By HOWARD W. FRENCH    
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   FREETOWN, Sierra Leone _ Nigeria's new military leader said
Tuesday he would turn over power to an elected civilian government
by Oct. 1.
</P>
<P>
   Aides to the new head of state, Gen. Abdulsalam Abubakar, also
hinted Tuesday that they were were preparing to release some of the
country's vast pool of political prisoners as a gesture of
goodwill.
</P>
<P>
   Abubakar's is the same timetable previously announced by Gen.
Sani Abacha, the dictator who died Monday. But Abacha was the sole
candidate for president in August elections, and the new leadership
did not make clear whether that date was firm and whether it would
allow genuine opposition candidates to run.
</P>
<P>
   Nigerian opposition groups Tuesday stepped up the pressure on
the new government, renewing calls for a large pro-democracy
demonstration on Friday.
</P>
<P>
   Abubakar's brief speech Tuesday night left unresolved crucial
questions about Nigeria's political future.
</P>
<P>
   Abubakar pleaded for ``constructive engagement'' and not
isolation from the international community, and urged exiles to
adopt a spirit of national reconciliation, saying: ``We remain
fully committed to the social-political transition program of Gen.
Sani Abacha's administration. We will do everything to ensure its
full and successful implementation.''
</P>
<P>
   Earlier in the day, a senior military spokesman explained that
this commitment meant ``abiding by the Oct. 1 handover date'' set
by Abacha.
</P>
<P>
   Foreign diplomats and Nigerian political analysts said the
announcement appeared to be the first strong indication that top
officers who want the army to loosen its direct political control
are gaining power after Abacha's death.
</P>
<P>
   Abubakar appears to belong to that faction. Among the group of
potential successors to Abacha, he is known to have chafed at the
Nigerian army's corruption and political maneuvering to keep power.
</P>
<P>
   But diplomats and Nigerian military analysts note that other
generals until recently pointed to the Indonesian dictatorship of
former President Suharto as a political model for Nigeria, Africa's
most populous country.
</P>
<P>
   Nigeria's large opposition is giving little credit to the
military after more than a decade of hearing government promises of
democracy that went unfulfilled.
</P>
<P>
   ``We don't think this announcement will change anything,'' said
Asaze Lanrwe Chunwa, an official with the Civil Liberties
Organization. ``There is still no freedom of expression. The
military wants to pull off a highly regimented transition. And even
if we had elections, there would still be the unresolved question
of June 12.''
</P>
<P>
   June 12 is the date of the 1993 elections, Nigeria's most
democratic ever, in which businessman Moshood Abiola was widely
believed to be winning convincingly until the military suspended
vote counting, setting the stage for Abacha's takeover.
</P>
<P>
   The election of Abiola, who has remained in prison since 1994,
has been a touchstone for the opposition to military rule,
especially in Nigeria's south, where he is from. Friday is the
fourth anniversary of the canceled election.
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   Whether Abubakar, a self-conscious professional who has avoided
overtly political roles such as state governorships and ministerial
appointments, can muster the political savvy and support needed to
pull off a credible election is only one of the challenges facing
the new leadership.
</P>
<P>
   The civilian opposition will be looking for signs that the
military is prepared to let political parties field their own
candidates and campaign free of manipulation by the army.
</P>
<P>
   One of these signs would be the release of Abiola, along with
the former President Olusegun Obasanjo, the only general in the
country's history to surrender power to an elected government.
Doing so would win praises from the international community, but
the enthusiasm unleashed in Nigeria could snowball into a popular
movement against the military that would be difficult to contain.
</P>
<P>
   The new leader served as the military commander in northern city
of Kano, and as chief of military intelligence under Gen. Ibrahim
Babangida, whose government ended in 1993. The two men come from
the same northern town of Minna and used to be neighbors. But
Abubakar was not known to have much influence in Abacha's inner
circle.
</P>
<P>
   Abacha did assign him two difficult tasks: to announce a coup
that critics say was really a pretext to arrest Obasanjo.
</P>
<P>
   In the military, those who have urged that the generals end
their direct involvement in politics include Maj. Gen. Ishaiya
Bamayi, the new defense chief of staff who is an ally of Abubakar,
and Babangida, one of Abacha's predecessors as president.
</P>
<P>
   ``After five years of carefully kept silence under Abacha,
Babangida began making statements a couple of weeks ago that were
unambiguous signals about the need to bring military rule in
Nigeria to an end,'' said one Western diplomat with longtime
experience in the country. ``These seemed very unusual at the time,
but in retrospect, it seems that they may have expressed a powerful
tide that was already moving against Abacha, and aimed to sweep him
away, if necessary.''
</P>
<P>
   Still dissidents are wary about Babangida's association with
Abubakar. Babangida is nicknamed Maradona, after the Argentine
soccer star, for his deft improvisation as he repeatedly broke
transition promises.
</P>
<P>
   Tuesday, even many of the Nigerians who are prepared to give
Abubakar some benefit of the doubt are asking themselves whether he
could ever muster the strength to organize a transition that makes
a clean break with the military-dominated rule of the past?
</P>
<P>
   ``He is not known for the forcefulness of his character, and he
has no real constituency among the security forces,'' said one
senior Nigerian officer who spoke on the condition of anonymity.
``There are several men who rose up as confidants of Abacha who
have much more direct links to the troops or who know how Abacha
amassed his fortune and presumably now want their chance to do the
same, and how he manages to out-maneuver them is far from clear.''
</P>
<P>
   Abacha had allowed five political parties to operate but
carefully vetted their candidates all the way down to local
elective offices. And as the Aug. 1 date for the vote approached,
with a planned Oct. 1 handover, his military coerced each of the
parties, included two that briefly resisted, into adopting the
president as the sole candidate.
</P>
<P>
   Tuesday, an official military spokesman spoke of ``some problems
in the dates for the presidential election,'' seemingly overlooking
the fact that the only approved presidential candidate, Abacha, had
just died. &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
