<SLUG> BC-EXECUTION-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Supreme Court puts 'hold' on
 &HT;    By Rhonda Cook
 &HT;    c. 1998 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   JACKSON, Ga. _ The U.S. Supreme Court, just minutes before the
scheduled 7 p.m. execution of David Cargill on Tuesday night, asked
state officials to ``hold'' _ but did not issue a stay _ to delay
the execution of the convicted double murderer.
</P>
<P>
   The day was marked by a series of court challenges and pleas for
mercy from the state Board of Pardons and Paroles and Butts, (Ga.)
County Superior Court Judge Arch McGarity. But no one who could
stop the execution for the 1985 murders agreed with Cargill's
attorneys and his family, who argued that the 39-year-old man no
longer deserved to die.
</P>
<P>
   Cargill and his younger brother, Tommy, both of Phenix City,
Ala., were convicted of a winter night armed robbery of the Premium
Oil Station in Columbus, Ga. and the execution-style slaying of
Cheryl and Danny Williams, which orphaned four boys ages 2 to 10.
</P>
<P>
   The Williamses worked days at a now-closed textile mill near
Columbus. Cheryl Williams worked at the service station to earn
extra money for the family. Her husband often stopped by to help
her close.
</P>
<P>
   During the robbery, $482.79 was taken.
</P>
<P>
   The couple was forced to lie face down on the floor of the
service station. Each was shot twice in the head.
</P>
<P>
   Cargill's death sentence was upheld by the U.S. Supreme Court in
April.
</P>
<P>
   Cargill, 26 at the time, was sentenced to death for shooting the
two parents in the back of the head while his brother, then 21, was
sentenced to life in prison.
</P>
<P>
   Tommy Cargill was in a cell at Smith State Prison at Glenville,
Ga. as his brother prepared to go to the electric chair at the
Georgia Diagnostic and Classification Prison.
</P>
<P>
   David Cargill spent the day with his aging, ailing mother, a
sister, a niece and a chaplain. After they left at 3:30 p.m.,
Cargill had his last meal of steak, baked potato, salad and vanilla
ice cream. Then his head and a leg were shaved to prepare for the
execution.
</P>
<P>
   Cargill was to be the 23rd man to be executed in Georgia since
1983. But unlike his predecessors, the day he was scheduled to die
came with virtually no notice from the world outside the prison.
</P>
<P>
   Not even the boys who were orphaned _ three of them now adults
and one 15 _ made a fuss, unlike the surviviors of murder victims
in previous executions.
</P>
<P>
   There were no television trucks parked outside the Georgia
Diagnostic and Classification Prison equipped for live reporting.
</P>
<P>
   Only eight death penalty opponents and a half dozen supporters
of executions gathered for the moment Cargill, 39, was scheduled to
sit in the state's electric chair.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
