<SLUG> BC-TEX-DRIVING-DEATH-ART-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
3 WHITES CHARGED IN BRUTAL KILLING OF BLACK 
</HEADLINE>
   (ART ADV: Graphic-map is being sent to NYT graphics clients.
Non-subscribers can make individual purchase by calling
212-556-4204.)  
 (bl)  
 By CAROL MARIE CROPPER   
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   DALLAS _ A black man was recently dragged to his death from the
back of a pickup truck in a rural section of Texas known for racist
and Klan activity, and on Tuesday three white men were charged with
the murder.
</P>
<P>
   The broken body of James Byrd Jr., 49, was discovered on Sunday
morning by residents of an area just outside the East Texas town of
Jasper, population 8,000. As he walked home from his parents' house
Saturday night, Byrd was apparently picked up by the men sometime
after midnight and taken to a wooded area, where he was beaten,
then chained to the truck and dragged for two miles.
</P>
<P>
   Jasper County District Attorney Guy James Gray called the
killing ``probably the most brutal I've ever seen'' in 20 years as
a prosecutor. Byrd's torso was found at the edge of a paved road,
his head and an arm in a ditch about a mile away, according to an
affidavit.
</P>
<P>
   Police charged Shawn Berry, 23, Lawrence Brewer, 31, and John
King, 23, with murder. According to the district attorney, Brewer
and King had racist tattoos and were Ku Klux Klan supporters,
leading investigators to believe the killing was racially
motivated.
</P>
<P>
   The suspects were apparently roommates in a Jasper apartment.
</P>
<P>
   Jasper Mayor R.C. Horn said the victim came from a ``beautiful
family.'' Byrd's sisters said he had been on disability and did not
have a car but often accepted rides from acquaintances or walked
around Jasper, where the number of blacks almost equals that of
whites.
</P>
<P>
   Horn said there have been no unusual racial problems in the
town, built on the timber industry. ``Jasper is a city that has a
strong bind together, both black and white,'' said Horn, who is
black.
</P>
<P>
   But Gary Bledsoe, president of the state chapter of the National
Association for the Advancement of Colored People, said the eastern
part of Texas, which includes Jasper, has been considered a problem
area and a hotbed of Klan activity for years.
</P>
<P>
   He pointed to problems in 1993 integrating a housing project in
nearby Vidor, for decades an all-white town, where an avowed white
supremacist threatened the first black residents, and teen-agers
dressed in sheets confronted black newcomers.
</P>
<P>
   Bledsoe called for adding kidnapping charges, making the killing
a capital crime. He said that he planned to go to Jasper to help
authorities with the investigation and that the NAACP wanted to
help organize a community response, such as a march or rally.
</P>
<P>
   Horn said local church leaders were planning a prayer meeting at
the courthouse square for this Monday night.
</P>
<P>
   According to the police affidavit, items left in the woods and
along the dirt logging road where Byrd was first dragged led the
authorities to the suspects. One item was a cigarette lighter
inscribed with a Klan symbol that police said they believed
belonged to a suspect.
</P>
<P>
   Berry told police he had been riding around with the other
suspects when he saw Byrd walking and offered him a ride, according
to the affidavit. Byrd and Berry might have known each other
because they had the same parole officer, according to The
Associated Press. Byrd served six years in prison for theft and
violating parole. All three suspects have criminal records for
offenses from burglary to drug possession and served jail time
together.
</P>
<P>
   After Byrd was picked up, King became upset and began cursing,
Berry is quoted as saying in the affidavit. The men stopped at a
convenience store, and then King drove to the dirt road, saying he
was about to scare Byrd. The other suspects began to beat the
victim, Berry told police.
</P>
<P>
   The FBI may seek to charge the suspects with violating the
victim's civil rights, said Al Tribble, an FBI special agent in
Houston.
</P>
<P>
   The national NAACP is also watching the case, said Jean
Hitchcock, acting chief operating officer for the organization.
``We call upon all Americans to stand up and be counted and to
condemn this for the heinous crime that it is.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
