<HEADER>
A1685 &Cx1f; taf-z
u f &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-NBC-CNET-965&AMP;ADD-ART-     06-09 1305
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-NBC-CNET-965&AMP;ADD-ART-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
NBC BUYING A PORTAL TO THE INTERNET 
</HEADLINE>
  (ART ADV: Graphic is being sent to NYT graphic clients.
Non-subscribers can make individual purchase by calling
212-556-4204 or -1927.) 
(sw) 
 By SAUL HANSELL   
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ Venturing into the most competitive area of the
Internet, NBC said on Tuesday that it had agreed to buy a
controlling stake in Snap, an upstart search and directory service
from its creator, Cnet Inc. The television network said it was also
buying a 4.9 percent stake in Cnet itself.
</P>
<P>
   NBC, a unit of the General Electric Co., is endorsing the view
that Internet directory companies, or search engines, like Yahoo
and Excite, are emerging as the cornerstones of profitable on-line
ventures. Such portals, as the directory sites have come to be
called, have started charging large fees from World Wide Web sites
to which they direct Internet users.
</P>
<P>
   In addition, portal sites, taking a page from the success of
America Online, are beginning to offer their own versions of
services like electronic mail and chat rooms as a way of engaging
users of Web pages on which the portals sell advertisements.
</P>
<P>
   The deal, which could total $39 million by the time it is
completed, represents the first time a broadcast network has
entered the Internet portal market, although all the networks have
built or acquired various sites that offer content like news,
sports or entertainment. NBC, for example, is already a co-owner
with the Microsoft Corp. of the MSNBC network, which is available
on both cable and the Web.
</P>
<P>
   At the same time, a range of companies, including the Netscape
Communications Corp. and Microsoft, are building their own portal
services. And big companies including Walt Disney and Time Warner
have been exploring buying part or all of the various directory
services.
</P>
<P>
   The most popular of these are Yahoo, Excite, Infoseek, Lycos and
Alta Vista, a Digital Equipment Corp. unit _ each of which is among
the most frequented sites on the Web. Yahoo is consistently the
Internet's most popular site, according to Relevant Knowledge, a
company that measures Web traffic.
</P>
<P>
   ``Media companies now realize that the Internet is important and
that they have to be there,'' said Brian Oakes, an analyst with
Lehman Brothers.
</P>
<P>
   For Cnet, the deal vindicates its decision to build Snap, which
has been widely criticized by investors. Cnet's first business,
television programs and Internet sites about computers, has been
the most successful original programming on the Internet. But many
saw Snap, which ultimately cost the company $25 million to build,
as an expensive distraction that was far too late to catch up with
the likes of Yahoo.
</P>
<P>
   Cnet's stock has floundered over the last year, rising only 15
percent through Monday, a period in which Yahoo's stock quintupled.
But on Tuesday, Cnet's shares surged nearly 37 percent to close at
$45.125.
</P>
<P>
   ``This has saved Cnet's bacon,'' said David Simons, managing
director of Digital Video Investments, a research firm. ``Snap was
not gaining the sponsorship or the franchise it had anticipated.''
</P>
<P>
   NBC said it was not deterred by Snap's low ratings. ``Snap is a
first-class service that is ready to handle millions of users,''
Robert Wright, the president of NBC, said at a news conference.
``It is not as well known as it could be, and our job is to make it
more well known.''
</P>
<P>
   Indeed, NBC's strategy appears to have been to buy the least
successful of the portal sites and build it through constant
promotion on the television network. The aim is to build Snap's
name recognition among the 80 percent of U.S. residents who are not
yet using the Internet, so that when they venture into cyberspace
it will already be familiar to them.
</P>
<P>
   NBC has agreed to pay $5.9 million for 19.9 percent of Snap and
has a three-year option to buy a further 40.1 percent of the
service for $32 million. The rest of Snap will be owned by Cnet.
From the start, a majority of Snap's board will be NBC executives,
although Halsey Minor, Cnet's chief executive, will stay on in the
near future.
</P>
<P>
   Separately, Cnet has purchased 4.99 percent of Cnet's stock for
$26 million, or $32 a share.
</P>
<P>
   To turn a $25 million investment into a company valued at $60
million would be a good return in any other industry, but it is
hardly the magic multiplication that many Internet companies have
come to expect.
</P>
<P>
   Analysts said that the most positive aspect of the deal for Cnet
was that it would no longer be responsible for Snap's continuing
losses, which have been running at $1.2 million a month.
</P>
<P>
   ``The single most important moment in the life of an Internet
company is when it starts to make money, said Keith Benjamin, an
analyst with BancAmerica Robertson Stephens, long a fan of Cnet's
stock. ``This will let them turn a profit in the third quarter.''
</P>
<P>
   For NBC, the deal offers a relatively inexpensive way to enter
the Internet portal business. The publicly owned search companies
range in value from $850 million for Infoseek to $5.5 billion for
Yahoo. Of course, all those companies have far greater audiences
than Snap does. But that was integral to NBC's bet.
</P>
<P>
   ``With the enormous valuations these other companies have, it's
hard to structure a deal,'' said Tom Rogers, president of NBC's
cable and Internet group. ``Snap didn't have all the traffic yet
that creates the valuations.''
</P>
<P>
   While NBC expects to build Snap's audience through extensive
promotion on its television programs, network executives declined
to specify the amount of air time they would give such promotions.
</P>
<P>
   ``Nobody will miss the fact, regardless of what day part you
look at, that there's something out there called Snap as a key
starting point to the Internet,'' Rogers said.
</P>
<P>
   The companies said they had not decided whether to use the NBC
brand name on the Snap service.
</P>
<P>
   NBC executives said that the company's goal was to run Snap as a
stand-alone business, not to use it mainly to promote its other
television and Internet programs.
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS.)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   The venture will be kept at arm's length from MSNBC, which
network executives said would probably provide news to both Snap
and Microsoft's new portal service, Start. Meanwhile, Snap will be
free to draw content both from other NBC affiliates and other
competing sources of programming.
</P>
<P>
   Similarly, Cnet will continue to produce programs for the USA
and Sci-Fi cable networks, although it may explore television
ventures with NBC in the future.
</P>
<P>
   Eventually, NBC and Snap executives said they would consider
selling part of Snap to the public in a stock offering. Having
publicly traded shares, at the high prices Internet companies now
fetch, would make it easier for Snap to acquire related Internet
companies.
</P>
<P>
   News of NBC's acquisition helped buoy the stock on Tuesday of
most other Internet portal companies, which have lagged in recent
weeks. Yahoo's shares, for example, jumped $8.50 to close at
$117.875.
</P>
<P>
   Some analysts argued that NBC's deep pockets and vast reach
could turn Snap into a potent competitor.
</P>
<P>
   ``Investors have the infinite-sum, unlimited-possibility
syndrome,'' said Simons of Digital Video Investments. ``What they
miss is that the promotion costs for everyone will go up. This is
the beginning of the great Internet marketing wars.''
</P>
<P>
   While such pressure may press the portal companies and other big
media corporations to explore more such deals, analysts said they
might be frightened off by the market valuation of the top portals.
</P>
<P>
   ``Snap was the safest play for a traditional company because it
is the weakest player,'' said Mr. Oakes of Lehman. ``The other
companies may not be bought until one of them stumbles,'' he said.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
