<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-NY-CONVENTION-CENTER-300&AMP;ADD-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
JAVITS CENTER EXPANSION PLAN CLASHES WITH STADIUM PROPOSAL 
</HEADLINE>
   (bl)  
 By CHARLES V. BAGLI   
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ State officials are scrambling to salvage a $750
million plan to expand the Jacob K. Javits Convention Center on the
West Side of Manhattan, which has collided with the Giuliani
administration's proposal to build a stadium for the New York
Yankees and a developer's efforts to erect a sprawling apartment
complex.
</P>
<P>
   The state, which controls the Javits Center, had hoped to double
the center's exhibition space to 1.5 million square feet by
extending the convention hall from 38th Street to 42nd Street, a
plan that officials and hoteliers said would let New York compete
with other cities for tens of millions of dollars in convention
business and anchor the western end of a rejuvenated Times Square.
</P>
<P>
   But discussions between executives at the convention center and
the developer, Larry Silverstein, who owns a key parcel of land
needed for the expansion project, collapsed recently when the
Giuliani administration failed to support the state's plans. Any
state project north of the convention center would require city
assistance to close streets and redirect traffic.
</P>
<P>
   Real estate executives and state officials say Silverstein
concluded that Mayor Rudolph Giuliani would not approve expansion
plans that did not include a baseball stadium just south of the
Javits Center.
</P>
<P>
   ``There's nothing happening with the expansion of the convention
center on 42nd Street,'' Silverstein said. ``So we're going forward
with our project. To sit and wait makes no sense at all. I couldn't
afford to delay this any further.''
</P>
<P>
   Real estate executives and state officials said the Javits
expansion was only the latest example of how the debate over a
future home for the Yankees was overshadowing everything from the
city budget to a new location for the New York Stock Exchange.
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   Mitchell Moss, director of the Taub Urban Research Center at New
York University, said he was surprised that the mayor had been
concentrating so heavily on the stadium.
</P>
<P>
   ``The Yankees are sucking up all the oxygen at City Hall,'' Moss
said. ``It's shocking to think that a baseball stadium is more
important than a convention center or stock exchange. New York's
future lies in tourism, finance, communications and entertainment,
not in professional baseball.''
</P>
<P>
   Giuliani has revived a plan to build a billion-dollar stadium on
the West Side of Manhattan that he said would prevent the Yankees
from leaving New York and generate $1 billion a year in economic
activity.
</P>
<P>
   The administration has commissioned several studies and recently
set up a delegation of nine officials to visit new ball parks in
other cities to assess their economic impact. On May 28, the group
led by Joseph Rose, chairman of the City Planning Commission, and
Charles Millard, president of the Economic Development Corp.,
visited Baltimore and Oriole Park at Camden Yards.
</P>
<P>
   ``I guess that says something when folks come out of New York to
see how others do it,'' said Charles Graves, the director of city
planning in Baltimore, who met with the delegation. ``We talked
about design, siting, political and economic issues.''
</P>
<P>
   Rather than wait for the Javits expansion, Silverstein plans to
build two residential towers with 1,800 apartments on the block
along 42nd Street between 11th and 12th Avenues. The apartment
complex would form an insurmountable roadblock to what state
officials said was the best route for the expansion.
</P>
<P>
   On Tuesday, state officials were urging Silverstein to
reconsider. At the same time, the officials are reluctant to press
the mayor because they want to avoid an open battle with him during
Gov. George Pataki's re-election campaign.
</P>
<P>
   ``The last three years have proven how vital the Javits Center
can be to New York,'' said convention center chairman Robert Boyle.
``We intend to build on that record. But in light of Silverstein's
plans, we would have to consider less desirable options for
expansion.''
</P>
<P>
   Real estate executives and state officials say privately that
the problems with the Javits expansion are the latest example of
the Giuliani administration's almost single-minded effort to
resolve the future of Yankee Stadium.
</P>
<P>
   Monday, the mayor vetoed nearly $5 million from the budget that
the City Council had allocated for itself, surprising Council
Speaker Peter Vallone, who is in a dispute with the mayor over the
stadium.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-06-09-98 2117EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19980609.0386 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-06-09 21:19 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A1689 &Cx1f; taf-z
u w &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-CREDIT-CARDS-BANKRUPT     06-09 1053
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CREDIT-CARDS-BANKRUPTCY-1,000(2TAKES)-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
HOUSE SET TO VOTE ON MAJOR OVERHAUL OF BANKRUPTCY SYSTEM 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (ATTN: Pa., Mass., Conn., Fla., Tenn.)  (mk) 
 By KATHARINE Q. SEELYE   
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ The House is preparing to vote Wednesday on the
first major overhaul of the bankruptcy system in two decades,
legislation that could allow the credit and banking industries to
reap billions of dollars.
</P>
<P>
   Coming at a time when credit-card lending is among the most
profitable sectors of an intensely competitive banking industry
that has little room for growth, the legislation has prompted the
credit card and banking businesses to spend millions of dollars to
push the bill.
</P>
<P>
   The theory of the measure, sponsored in the House by Rep. George
Gekas, R-Pa., is that thousands of people are shucking their
responsibilities, driving up their debts and then declaring
themselves insolvent under Chapter 7 of the bankruptcy code, which
forgives most debts. The legislation would make it more difficult
for consumers to use Chapter 7 while giving banks, credit card
companies, department stores and other lenders more authority to
recoup what they are owed.
</P>
<P>
   The industry estimates that of the 1.37 million people who filed
for bankruptcy last year, between 15 percent and 25 percent had the
means to pay their debts. It says that the debts of these dishonest
people are passed on to consumers in higher prices and higher
interest rates that cost every American household about $400 a
year.
</P>
<P>
   The industry estimates that by reducing the number of people who
file under Chapter 7 and putting others on a more rigorous
repayment schedule, it could recoup $4 billion a year.
</P>
<P>
   Many Democrats in Congress and consumer advocates have
criticized the bill as a billion-dollar bouquet to the credit-card
industry. They say that while companies complain about people not
paying their debts, they also send out more than 2 billion
``pre-approved'' credit-card solicitations _ 12 for each person in
America annually. Critics say this can tempt vulnerable people to
borrow more.
</P>
<P>
   ``They could easily see a billion a year in windfall profits
from this legislation,'' Elizabeth Warren, a professor at Harvard
Law School and strong critic of the bill, said of the credit-card
industry. ``They will do it by squeezing hard-pressed families out
of the bankruptcy system and continuing to collect from them $50
here and $50 there.'' She said that could add up to billions.
</P>
<P>
   The full Senate is to take up a more lenient version of the bill
later this summer.
</P>
<P>
   Both versions would apply only to those people filing for
bankruptcy whose incomes are above the national median of $50,000 a
year for a family of four. Those earning less could still file
under Chapter 7 of the bankruptcy law, which eliminates all debts,
or under Chapter 13, which allows a judge to set a repayment
scheudle.
</P>
<P>
   Under the House bill, debtors who are deemed able to repay 20
pecent of their debt over five years would not be allowed to file
under Chapter 7. The Senate version gives the bankruptcy judge more
leeway in setting a repayment plan.
</P>
<P>
   If committee votes are any indication, both the House and Senate
will pass their versions of the bill, and will have to reconcile
them later.
</P>
<P>
   The Clinton administration has said that it opposes the House
bill in its present form. In a May 21 letter to Congress, Jacob
Lew, acting director of the Office of Management and Budget,
objected to a provision that would impose what he described as ``a
rigid and arbitrary'' income test to determine who could file for
bankruptcy.
</P>
<P>
   Both President Clinton and first lady Hillary Rodham Clinton
have also expressed concern that the legislation would force
debtors to pay back credit card companies before making alimony and
child-support payments.
</P>
<P>
   But the bill is a clear priority for the industry. Last year
alone, more than 100 financial-services companies spent more than
$40 million to push this bill and other banking legislation through
Congress, according to lobbying-disclosure records. Much of that
money rained down on Washington's K Street corridor of professional
lobbying firms. The records do not include the undoubtedly higher
amounts spent so far this year, when scores of lawyers and industry
lobbyists swarmed over the House and Senate Judiciary Committees as
they gaveled the 177-page bankruptcy bill to approval.
</P>
<P>
   The bankruptcy issue has been cooking along behind the scenes on
Capitol Hill for a couple of years. But even as it has drawn closer
to the floor, it has been overshadowed by tobacco legislation and
other matters.
</P>
<P>
   Sen. Christopher Dodd, D-Conn., described the bankruptcy bill as
``a freight train going 90 miles an hour.'' Referrring to the
hordes of financial-services lobbyists who have been packing the
Capitol corridors, Dodd added: ``It's hard to find someone on K
Street who hasn't been called in to work on this bill.''
</P>
<P>
   Virtually anyone who is owed money has spent money lobbying for
the bill. Included are department stores like J.C. Penney, which
spent $500,000 on banking legislation last year, and Sears Roebuck,
which spent $240,000, according to records on file with Congress.
The International Council of Shopping Centers devoted $360,000. The
reports for the first six months of 1998 are not due until August.
</P>
<P>
   Especially eager to see this legislation are the credit card
companies and other money lenders. Visa spent $1.3 million last
year on lobbying, according to records, and MasterCard
International spent $390,000. The Money Store, a financial services
company based in Union, N.J., with a loan portfolio of $10 billion,
spent $1.2 million on lobbying last year.
</P>
<P>
   Many interested parties turned to experienced K Street lobbyists
to push the issue. The American Financial Services Association, the
main trade group that provides credit to consumers, paid $600,000
to the firm of Barbour Griffith &AMP; Rogers. Haley Barbour, the former
chairman of the Republican National Committee, is a senior partner
in the firm. The association also helped organize fund-raisers for
Reps. Bill McCollum, R-Fla., and Bill Jenkins, R-Tenn., who
co-sponsored the legislation.
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   nn
</P>
<P>
   In addition, the industry has boosted its campaign contributions
to members of both houses of Congress who are playing key roles.
Under the banner of the National Consumer Bankruptcy Coalition, the
industry has given $1.6 million to House and Senate candidates so
far in the 1997-98 election cycle, according to an analysis by the
Center for Responsive Politics.
</P>
<P>
   Bruce Markell, a bankruptcy specialist at Indiana University Law
School, said the bill was such a priority for lenders because
credit cards were so profitable. Three-fourths of all households
have at least one credit card, and three-fourths of those carry
debt from month to month at 18 percent. The prime audience for
credit cards, he said, is women between 25 and 40 years old.
</P>
<P>
   ``They make money on being able to target those people who incur
debt and can barely pay it off,'' Markell said, noting the
widespread opportunities to use credit cards these days to buy
everything from gas to food. At the end of 1997, Americans owed
$422 billion in credit-card loans, twice as much as at the end of
1993.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-06-09-98 2119EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
