<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BIZGLANCE-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
BUSINESS AT A GLANCE
</HEADLINE>
  (pr) 
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   BLUE-CHIP RALLY FADES, BUT INTERNET SHARES GAIN
</P>
<P>
   A three-day rally in blue-chip stocks lost stamina, leaving
major market gauges mixed. The stumble illustrated some renewed
concerns about the corporate earnings outlook and the prospect for
interest rate changes ahead of congressional testimony Wednesday by
Alan Greenspan, Fed chairman. The Dow Jones industrial average fell
19.68 points, to 9,049.92. But sharp gains among some
Internet-related shares pushed technology stocks higher, and the
Nasdaq composite index rose 12.99 points, to 1,800.76, its fourth
straight gain and first close above 1,800 since May 22. Drug and
transportation shares also gained. Treasury prices were little
changed, as investors awaited Wednesday's testimony.
</P>
<P>
   BOEING TO CUT 747 PRODUCTION
</P>
<P>
   Boeing said it would cut production of 747 aircraft in 1999,
because of slow growth in Asia. The company also said it would
reduce more jobs than the 12,000 previously announced beginning in
mid-1998.
</P>
<P>
   LENDERS BACK BANKRUPTCY OVERHAUL
</P>
<P>
   The credit card and banking businesses are spending millions of
dollars to push for the first big overhaul of the bankruptcy system
in two decades. The House is preparing to vote Wednesday on the
bill, which would make it tougher for consumers to escape their
debts. Lenders could recoup some $4 billion a year.
</P>
<P>
   KEY COURT TEST: HERB OR DRUG?
</P>
<P>
   A case to be heard in Federal court in Salt Lake City next
Monday is being closely watched as a pivotal battle between the
Food and Drug Administration and the wildly growing dietary
supplement industry. At issue is Chinese red yeast sold here by
Pharmanex under the name Cholestin to lower cholesterol. The FDA
calls it an unapproved drug.
</P>
<P>
   MERGER FORMS OPTIONS RIVAL
</P>
<P>
   The American and Philadelphia stock exchanges agreed to merge,
creating a powerful options trading rival to the dominant Chicago
Board Options Exchange.
</P>
<P>
   ANTI-SMOKING IMPASSE MAY END
</P>
<P>
   The first signs developed that the impasse in the Senate on
anti-smoking legislation might be broken, as The Senate voted,
52-46, for a Republican amendment to use some of the money raised
from higher cigarette prices on drug abuse programs.
</P>
<P>
   SPEED SOUGHT IN MICROSOFT TRIAL
</P>
<P>
   A federal judge said that he would limit to six to 12 each the
number of witnesses either Microsoft or the government may call
during the September trial of the antitrust suits filed by the
Justice Department and 20 states. The goal is to avert a lengthy
proceeding.
</P>
<P>
   COURT ALLOWS KEATING NEW TRIAL
</P>
<P>
   Charles Keating, the former savings and loan executive who
became a symbol of the 1980's savings and loan scandals after the
$3.4 billion collapse of Lincoln Savings, is entitled to a new
trial on Federal securities charges because jurors improperly
learned of state convictions on similar charges, an appeals court
ruled.
</P>
<P>
   GERMANY'S UNEMPLOYMENT DROPS
</P>
<P>
   The number of unemployed workers in Germany fell by 223,400 in
May, sending the jobless rate down one-tenth of a point, to 11.2
percent. That and last week's report of strong economic growth are
expected to help Chancellor Helmut Kohl's struggling campaign for
re-election in September.
</P>
<P>
   OXFORD NAMES FISCAL CHIEF
</P>
<P>
   Troubled Oxford Health Plans named Yon Yoon Jorden as chief
financial officer. She is now the chief financial officer at an
energy joint venture and was previously the fiscal head of
Wellpoint Health Networks.
</P>
<P>
   RUSSIAN STATISTICIANS ARRESTED
</P>
<P>
   The Russian government arrested the head of the State Committee
for Statistics, Yuri Yurkov, and his top deputies and accused them
of manipulating data to help Russian companies avoid taxes. The
arrests bring into question how the government measures economic
performance.
</P>
</TEXT>
