<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-06-09 21:21 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A1692 &Cx1f; tad-z
u w &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-GINGRICH-COX10     06-09 0411
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-GINGRICH-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 10 &HT;    Modest donations fuel Gingrich PAC
 &HT;    By Mark Sherman
 &HT;    c. 1998 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ When political pros talk about Speaker Newt
Gingrich as a possible presidential candidate, they often cite his
ability to raise money _ lots of it and in small contributions.
</P>
<P>
   The speaker's political action committee, which he uses to help
other GOP congressional candidates and fund his own political
operation, is a good example.
</P>
<P>
   In April, the latest month for which figures are available, the
Monday Morning PAC raised $125,000, of which $96,000, or more than
three quarters of the total, came in small donations.
</P>
<P>
   That unusually high percentage of contributions of under $200
comes from the PAC's aggressive use of direct mail solicitations,
said Mike Shields, Gingrich's campaign spokesman.
</P>
<P>
   Gingrich's political aides have employed the same strategy for
his own campaign fund-raising committee. Since January 1997,
Friends of Newt Gingrich has received $3.8 million in
contributions. Individuals contributed $2.5 million, two-thirds of
the total, in donations of less than $200, according to an analysis
of Gingrich's contributions by the nonprofit Center for Responsive
Politics, which tracks campaign finance issues.
</P>
<P>
   The $200 threshold is significant because campaigns must report
the name of their contributors, addresses and amounts of larger
contributions.
</P>
<P>
   Larry Makinson, the center's executive director, said smaller
contributions, which are not itemized, are often ``cleaner''
because they do not have the taint of special interest money.
``That's money that usually is coming from an individual who likes
what you have to say'' without any expectation of access or
influence, Makinson said.
</P>
<P>
   Gingrich is one of the more aggressive users of direct mailings
in Congress, and has the added advantage of a national travel
schedule to attract contributors. Another top House Republican,
Majority Leader Dick Armey of Texas, also has a large percentage of
small givers. Of the $1.5 million he has raised since January 1997,
$800,000, or more than half, came in contributions of less than
$200, according to the center's analysis.
</P>
<P>
   By contrast, House Democratic leader Dick Gephardt of Missouri
reported that just $300,000 of the $3.1 million he has raised in
the past 18 months was in sums of less than $200.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-06-09-98 2121EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
