<DOCNO> NYT19980609.0390 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-06-09 21:21 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A1693 &Cx1f; tad-z
u w &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-TOBACCO-COX10     06-09 0449
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-TOBACCO-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 10 &HT;    Senate action on tobacco bill could come to quick conclusion
 &HT;    By Larry Lipman
 &HT;    c. 1998 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ The procedural logjam that threatened passage of a
comprehensive tobacco bill appeared to break late Tuesday, raising
the possibility of final Senate action as soon as this week.
</P>
<P>
   The legislation _ which would boost cigarette prices $1.10 a
pack, raise $516 billion over 25 years and supersede settlements
made between some states and cigarette makers _ still faces an
uncertain future in the House, which has been waiting for Senate
action before taking up the contentious issue.
</P>
<P>
   Late Tuesday, the Senate voted 52-46 along party lines for an
amendment by Sen. Paul Coverdell (R-Ga.) to earmark $16 billion
over the next five years to boost the nation's drug interdiction
efforts, register convicted drug dealers, restrict federally backed
loans for students convicted of drug possession and ban federal
financing of needle exchange programs.
</P>
<P>
   The money would double the drug interdiction budget for the
Coast Guard, Customs Service, and Defense Department, and provide
$10 million a year in grants to states that institute voluntary
drug testing for teen drivers license applicants.
</P>
<P>
   The Senate is expected to vote today on a Republican proposal to
use a portion of the tobacco tax revenues to enable reduction of
the ``marriage penalty'' _ higher income taxes paid by many couples
because they file joint rather than individual returns _ as well as
help the self-employed pay for health insurance.
</P>
<P>
   The original proposal by Sen. Phil Gramm (R-Texas) would have
earmarked $52 billion in tax reductions over five years. Late
Tuesday that amount appeared to have been scaled back to $16
billion over five years.
</P>
<P>
   Movement on the drug amendment and the marriage tax amendment
appeared to breathe new life into the tobacco measure, which Senate
Majority Leader Trent Lott (R-Miss.) had threatened to pull earlier
in the week.
</P>
<P>
   ``Reports of the death of this legislation are premature,'' said
Sen. John McCain (R-Ariz.), the bill's chief sponsor.
</P>
<P>
   At the White House, President Clinton also sounded optimistic
about the tobacco bill's fate, telling reporters, ``There are still
problems, to be sure, but we're getting closer to, I think, a
principled compromise.''
</P>
<P>
   Clinton talked by phone with Senate leaders of both parties
during the day and dispatched top aides to participate in
discussions.
</P>
<P>
   And leaders signaled they were ready to accept the proposals as
part of the cost of clearing a major anti-teen-smoking measure.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
