<SLUG> BC-AMEX-PHILLY-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
AMERICAN AND PHILADELPHIA EXCHANGES AGREE TO MERGE
</HEADLINE>
   (ja) 
 By GRETCHEN MORGENSON    
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   The American Stock Exchange and the Philadelphia Stock Exchange
agreed to a merger late on Tuesday that would create an options
trading powerhouse to rival the giant Chicago Board Options
Exchange.
</P>
<P>
   The chairman of the American Exchange, Richard Syron; the
chairman of the National Association of Securities Dealers, Frank
Zarb, and the acting chief of the Philadelphia exchange, John
Wallace, announced the deal after the market closed. Terms were not
disclosed.
</P>
<P>
   The merger must be approved by two-thirds of the seat holders on
both exchanges and by the Securities and Exchange Commission.
</P>
<P>
   The idea for a merger began to take shape over the last few
months in conjunction with the pending merger of the NASD, the
parent of the Nasdaq stock market, and the American Exchange. A
combined American and Philadelphia exchange would trade about 40
percent of all equity options in the nation based on volume. Until
now, the Chicago exchange has dominated this lucrative market,
trading about 42 percent of equity options.
</P>
<P>
   In recommending that seat holders accept the deal, the board of
the Philadelphia exchange is rejecting a merger proposal from the
Chicago exchange. The offer from the American Exchange may have had
more appeal because it would keep the Philadelphia trading
operations in place for up to five years. The Chicago exchange's
offer required the Philadelphia options traders to move their
businesses to Chicago within two years. The deal also grants
Philadelphia seat holders 12-year transferable permits to trade
existing Philadelphia products and new securities. The Chicago deal
offered options traders the right to trade in Chicago for a minimum
of five years.
</P>
<P>
   The merger could address some concerns among big brokerage firms
that executions on the Philadelphia exchange were not as fast as
those on other exchanges. Outdated systems contributed to slow
confirmations of trades, for example.
</P>
<P>
   In an interview, Syron said: ``The power across the entire
American economy is shifting from the producer of goods to the
consumer. This merger confirms that the shape of the industry going
forward will be dictated by investors.''
</P>
<P>
   The Philadelphia exchange was founded in 1790 as the first
organized stock exchange in the nation. It trades options on 800
stocks, 13 indexes and 100 foreign currency contracts, which trade
in pairs. It also executes trades on shares listed on the New York
Stock Exchange.
</P>
<P>
   Of the 505 seats on the Philadelphia exchange, 400 give the
holder the right to trade options. A single exchange seat with
options rights sold for a record $280,000 this year.
</P>
<P>
   The most lucrative part of the Philadelphia exchange's business
is its trading of equity options on the shares of the Dell Computer
Corp. Volume in Dell options make it the second-biggest option
contract traded in the United States, behind the Intel Corp.
</P>
<P>
   Last year, management turmoil rocked the Philadelphia exchange
when its longtime chairman, Nicholas Giordano, was ousted and
Wallace took over. Through companies they own, Wallace and members
of his family own 30 seats.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-06-09-98 2121EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19980609.0392 </DOCNO>
