<HEADER>
A1697 &Cx1f; taf-z
u a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-NYC-COL-AMBULANCE-CUT     06-09 0781
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-NYC-COL-AMBULANCE-CUTBACKS-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
COMMENTARY: CASH SQUEEZE MAKES IT HARD TO SAVE LIVES 
</HEADLINE>
   (bl)  
 By DAVID GONZALEZ   
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ Joe Perez's pulse quickens when the phone rings
inside his storefront office at the Bedford-Stuyvesant Volunteer
Ambulance Corps. The adrenaline rush psyches him up to respond to a
cardiac call or some other code-red emergency. It also fuels his
response to the corps' lingering code green, a lack of funds that
has left these trailblazers having to perform triage on their
bills.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're going belly up,'' Perez said. ``Every other call is
someone calling for money. Our copy machine, they want to take it
out of here. Everybody is suing us.''
</P>
<P>
   And not for malpractice. Since Perez and Rocky Robinson founded
the corps 10 years ago, it has helped cut the area's ambulance
response time from half an hour to minutes. Some of its ``vollies''
have gone on to take pre-med courses or advanced training to become
nurses and paramedics.
</P>
<P>
   Cutbacks in state and city financing since the mid-1990s
resulted in the elimination of two emergency medical technician
training programs that took young people off the streets and
welfare recipients off the dole.
</P>
<P>
   The cash crunch has forced the Brooklyn corps to ground three of
its four ambulances because they are too expensive to maintain,
resulting in fewer runs and less income from insurance
reimbursements. Even a city-owned lot where it parks its ambulances
and storage trailer was endangered, since Robinson learned last
month that the property was on a list of sites under review for
possible auction.
</P>
<P>
   ``We seem to be losing everything,'' Robinson said. ``If we had
the lot, we would have a place we could call our own, even if we
don't have money to insure the ambulances. We could go back to
running to calls on foot like in the beginning. We're not too
proud.''
</P>
<P>
   Patrick Muldowney, a spokesman for the Department of Citywide
Administrative Services, insisted that it was all a
``misunderstanding'' and that no one intends to sell the lot.
``Somebody got a letter and misunderstood it,'' he said.
``Regardless, they will be taken care of.''
</P>
<P>
   The corps avoided eviction by auction a few years ago, when its
supporters lobbied to remove the lot from the list of available
properties. Community advocates said that to consider returning it
to the auction block would typify an outdated land-use policy that
usually mandates that city-owned properties be auctioned, rather
than sold directly to any group. ``There is no program that really
reviews disposition with any rational approach,'' said one borough
official advising the corps. ``It's chaotic.''
</P>
<P>
   There was plenty of mayhem on the streets when the corps came
into being 10 years ago. Robinson thinks his group has enough of a
track record saving and changing lives that their efforts should be
recognized as having as much value as any purchase price.
</P>
<P>
   ``When we first started, this city was going through a
revolution,'' he said. ``A lot of people don't realize it, but on a
regular basis, we had to hit the ground in our trailer because of
gunfire. In this neighborhood, we went through a civil war.''
</P>
<P>
   While corps leaders try to acquire the lot, they have been
cheered by some victories, including $200,000 in state funds to
train people in advanced life support. Offered together with the
Downstate Medical Center, the course would place its graduates on
the way to becoming emergency medical technicians. Stephen Villano,
Downstate's vice president for planning and institutional
advancement, said he hoped that the contract would spur others into
supporting the corps. He was especially concerned about foundations
that make one-shot gifts and some of Brooklyn's successful native
sons who have yet to do the right thing.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is not a liberal, fuzzy program, but a conservative
program that takes people on welfare and gives them a marketable
skill,'' he said. ``We need to raise the awareness of foundations
that this is a long-term commitment. This is a 24-hour-a-day,
7-days-a-week operation, and one contribution doesn't do it.''
</P>
<P>
   In the meantime, the corps looks for new ways to raise money.
Last summer, corps members tried running a restaurant in the
trailer they have parked on the lot. It failed. Robinson, on leave
from the city's Fire Department because of an aneurysm, recently
tried to go back on active duty as an emergency medical technician.
</P>
<P>
   ``Nothing doing,'' he lamented. ``My blood pressure is 220 over
150. My aneurysm might pop any day. I'm broke. The corps' broke. If
I don't have money coming in, I can't even help myself.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
