<SLUG> BC-BKN-FINALS-NOTEBOOK-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
HORNACEK AIMS TO UNLEASH (AND HIT) JUMP SHOTS 
</HEADLINE>
  (th) 
 By SELENA ROBERTS    
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   CHICAGO _ Jeff Hornacek has the look of a minivan dad who would
blend into the suburbs if not for an extraordinary shooter's touch.
The Utah Jazz is relying on this accounting major's soft jumper to
help crack the Bulls' defense in Game 4 of the NBA finals Wednesday
night at the United Center.
</P>
<P>
   Once Hornacek missed his first four shots in the first quarter
of Game 3, he became hesitant, which caused a trickle-down effect.
</P>
<P>
   Not sensing an offensive threat, Michael Jordan and Scottie
Pippen felt free to roam and create chaos in the second quarter,
and that is when the 96-54 debacle began. While Hornacek was not
taking credit away from the Bulls, he was not cowering in the face
of their defense either.
</P>
<P>
   ``We can't overadjust to what they did,'' Hornacek said Tuesday.
``You can't change an offense. We looked at the tape and saw the
things that they were doing weren't that big a deal. We just didn't
make shots. I think we overemphasized how they did it. We got the
shots we wanted. We just didn't make it.''
</P>
<P>
   Hornacek is a key to keeping the Bulls' defense honest. If the
Bulls disrupt the pick-and-roll, someone is usually open. Often,
that is Hornacek. But thus far in this National Basketball
Association championship series, Hornacek has been unusually
inconsistent, going from a 2-for-10 night in Game 1 to a 7-for-11
effort in Game 2. Part of this unreliability is because of injury.
</P>
<P>
   Hornacek needed seven stitches after a ladder from his garage
fell on his head just before the series began. Then, in Game 1, he
was seen limping on an injured Achilles' heel. Jordan preyed on him
to a point, but with help on defense, Hornacek has managed to keep
himself in the games.
</P>
<P>
   The longer he lingers on the perimeter, the more dangerous he is
to the Bulls' defensive formula, if he can make his shot.
</P>
<P>
   ``That's what a lot of it comes down to,'' Hornacek said. ``If
you make them, it puts a different spin on everything.''
</P>
<P>
   HANDLING MALONE IS A CINCH
</P>
<P>
   The player is Dennis Rodman. The subject is basketball, for
once. Rodman has played Karl Malone well in this series, often
irritating and nudging the Jazz superstar away from the post and
out of position. It's a snap, if you ask Rodman.
</P>
<P>
   ``Karl can't beat me off the dribble, so that's one thing,''
Rodman said. ``He's basically an awkward player. He's just an
average player to me. Once he's inside, he tries to bully you and
get a cheap foul. If the referees let me play, I can play Karl
Malone every day of the week.''
</P>
<P>
   IT'S HARD TO STAY MAD AT PIPPEN
</P>
<P>
   Fans in Chicago have chosen to handle Scottie Pippen's
imperfections with amnesia. He has been forgiven by most when he
refused to go into a 1994 game against the Knicks. With 1.8 seconds
to go, Pippen chose to sit and sulk if the ball was not going to be
in his hands for the game-winning shot. Toni Kukoc took the shot
and won the game.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't care if they forget it or not,'' said Pippen, who will
be a free agent July 1. ``I think I've had a great career here.
I've had a great career over all as a basketball player. And I
think I will be remembered here forever. How they remember me, that
just depends on who it is.''
</P>
<P>
   MALONE TAKES IN BATTING PRACTICE
</P>
<P>
   Karl Malone spent Monday night escaping the stress of the finals
by watching Mark McGwire take batting practice before the Cardinals
played the White Sox at Comiskey Park. The burly Malone, who tried
out for his high school baseball team only to leave after watching
a pitch zip by his face, was awestruck at McGwire's power.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't know if I can imagine myself hitting one like that,''
said Malone, who watched McGwire belt his 29th homer before heading
back to the hotel. ``Really, the only thing I wanted to see was
batting practice. That was awesome.''
</P>
<P>
   CAPTIVE HOME VIEWERS
</P>
<P>
   Game 3 of the finals on NBC produced a 16.2 Nielsen rating, 14
percent above last year, and the second-highest rated Game 3 in
history. Through three games, NBC's 17.0 rating is the highest in
history, 5 percent above the 16.2 for the first three games of the
1993 finals. In Chicago, the game earned a 44.8 rating and a 66
share, while the Salt Lake City market produced a 41.1 rating and a
66 share.
</P>
<P>
   Each rating point equals 980,000 television households. Share is
the percentage of televisions in use at a particular time.
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
