<HEADLINE>
ADVERTISING NOTEBOOK 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (ATTN: N.Y., Ill., England)  (th) 
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   ACQUISITIONS BY THREE COMPANIES
</P>
<P>
   Three agency companies have made acquisitions for undisclosed
financial terms.
</P>
<P>
   New Paradigm Corp., an Internet company in New York, acquired a
majority interest in Schoen, Kapelus &AMP; Cipriano in Harrison, N.Y.,
an agency that specializes in travel, tourism and hospitality
accounts. Schoen, Kapelus, which is being renamed SKC Advertising,
has 10 employees and estimated billings of $3 million from clients
like Kemwel Holiday Autos. Milton Kapelus, 61, president of Schoen,
Kapelus, will head SKC as president.
</P>
<P>
   Agency.com in New York, which had owned a majority stake in
Spiral Media, an Internet and digital media communications company
in New York, acquired the remaining shares to give it 100 percent
ownership. Spiral will operate as a subsidiary of Agency.com under
the name Spiral Media, an Agency.com company.
</P>
<P>
   Art Williams, 31, chief executive at Spiral, was named to the
additional position of executive vice president for operations at
Agency.com. Spiral has 35 employees and billings estimated at $7.5
million from clients like AT&AMP;T and Unilever. The deal was the third
in recent days for Agency.com.
</P>
<P>
   And Research International Group in London, a custom research
consulting company that is part of WPP Group PLC, acquired another
custom research company, Conway/Milliken &AMP; Associates in Chicago.
Conway/Milliken has 90 employees and annual revenue of more than
$12 million; it will operate as a division of Research
International USA under present management. &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
