<SLUG> BC-TOBACCO-BILL-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
SENATE BACKS TAX CUT, DRUG AMENDMENT FOR NEW ANTI-SMOKING BILL 

</HEADLINE>
  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  By BENNETT ROTH 
c.1998 Houston Chronicle 
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ After limping along for weeks, the Senate made
modest progress Tuesday on anti-smoking legislation, as GOP
lawmakers reached agreement on a tax cut and anti-drug provisions
they insist must be part of the overall package.
</P>
<P>
   The drug measure would increase funding for drug fighting
efforts _ $16 billion over five years _ while authorizing the use
of federal funds to pay for school vouchers for students who are
victims of school violence.
</P>
<P>
   The Senate approved the drug amendment, 52-46, with all but two
Republicans voting for it and all the Democrats opposing it.
</P>
<P>
   Meanwhile, GOP leaders announced they had reached agreement on a
tax-cut plan to eliminate the marriage penalty for couples making
under $50,000 annually.
</P>
<P>
   The tax cut would be paid for from revenues generated from
raising cigarette prices by $1.10 a pack. The amendment, sponsored
by Sen. Phil Gramm, R-Texas, is expected to be voted on Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
   The flurry of action came as Democrats had expressed growing
impatience with the pace of debate. The Senate is now in its third
week of consideration of a bill that would impose broad federal
regulation of tobacco products.
</P>
<P>
   They have forced a series of votes this week to prod Republicans
into voting on the complete bill and to halt the offering of
numerous amendments they contend are intended to weaken the
measure.
</P>
<P>
   The 56-42 vote Tuesday against ending debate was largely along
party lines, with a handful of tobacco state Democrats joining
Republicans in opposing the move.
</P>
<P>
   ``The tobacco companies have to be cheering after that vote,''
said Sen. Richard Durbin, D-Ill., who with his Democratic
colleagues has grown increasingly pessimistic that the Senate will
agree on anti-tobacco legislation this year.
</P>
<P>
   In recent days Republican Majority Leader Trent Lott, R-Miss.,
has suggested that the measure may be dead if Democrats continued
to balk at GOP proposals.
</P>
<P>
   But the bill's sponsor, Sen. John McCain, R-Ariz., voiced
optimism that the Senate will be able to complete work on the bill.
</P>
<P>
   His position was echoed by President Clinton, who suggested that
Senate leaders were working out differences over how to proceed.
</P>
<P>
   ``There are still problems, but we are getting closer,'' said
Clinton during a news conference with Korean President Kim
Dae-Jung.
</P>
<P>
   Lawmakers believed they had made progress paring down the
tax-cut proposal, which initially would have cost $17 billion over
five years and $30 billion over 10 years. The new plan would cost
$16 billion over five years and $30 billion over 10 years.
</P>
<P>
   The Democrats, who fear that the Gramm plan would drain money
earmarked for public health programs, plan to offer a more modest
tax cut proposal that includes a health care tax break for the
self-employed.
</P>
<P>
   The drug amendment offered by Sen. Paul Coverdell, R-Ga., drew
Democratic criticism largely because it included a school voucher
plan for victims of drug-related violence. The plan calls for use
of federal funds to pay for students to transfer to other public,
parochial, or private schools. Local school officials would
determine who would be eligible.
</P>
<P>
   The Coverdell amendment would also ban taxpayer funding of
needle exchange programs, which are supported by public health
officials as a way of reducing the chances of drug users
contracting the AIDS virus.
</P>
<P>
   The drug bill would restrict loans for students convicted of
drug possession and trafficking and give states incentive grants if
they institute voluntary drug testing for teen driver's license
applicants.
</P>
<P>
   The Democrats offered a scaled-back amendment that would have
placed a one-year moratorium on funding for needle exchange
programs and allow students who are victims of violence to be
transferred to other public schools but not private or parochial
schools. It lost 53-45.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
XXXX END OF STORY &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
