<SLUG> BC-CALIF-INDIAN-GAMBLING-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
TRIBAL LEADERS SEEK U.S. HELP IN FIGHT OVER GAMBLING IN CALIFORNIA
</HEADLINE>
   (sw) 
 By BRETT PULLEY   
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ In an intensifying battle against the governor of
California and the gambling industry of Nevada, more than 100
Native American tribal leaders have traveled here this week to try
to halt what they call a threat to their casinos and even their
reservations.
</P>
<P>
   The political and legal disputes center on a gambling compact
that Gov. Pete Wilson made with one tribe in March. Other tribes
contend that without trying to negotiate statewide, Wilson has
demanded that they either sign the restrictive, far less profitable
compact or shut down their casinos, which the governor says are
operating illegally.
</P>
<P>
   So far, all but a few of the 38 tribes that operate casinos in
the state have refused to accept either option, and the federal
attorneys there have initiated court proceedings to seize some
14,000 slot machines from those tribes' casinos.
</P>
<P>
   Lanny Davis, the former special counsel to President Clinton who
has been enlisted by the tribes, said that the leaders in
Washington want to convince Congress and Attorney General Janet
Reno that Wilson's refusal to negotiate with the Indians unless
they first shut down their casinos is a violation of their rights.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're in Washington to ask the U.S. government to fulfill its
historic, legal and moral obligation to act as our trustees in
requiring the governor to come to the negotiating table,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   The tribal leaders say the battle is more than an economic and
political issue, and is one they are willing to fight for.
</P>
<P>
   ``We are trying to head off a potential powder keg,'' said Mary
Ann Andreas, tribal chairman of the Morongo Band of Mission
Indians, which operates a casino just outside Palm Springs, and has
refused to accept the governor's terms. The Morongo tribe, like
others, Ms. Andreas said, is fearful not only of losing most of the
economic gains that they have realized from operating casinos for
the past several years, but also of losing some of the sovereign
rights granted them through treaties with the government.
</P>
<P>
   ``What's at stake is our survival,'' she said. ``This could mean
devastation.''
</P>
<P>
   Although states are required to negotiate casino gambling
compacts with tribes under the Indian Gaming Regulatory Act _ a
federal law passed in 1988 _ Wilson had refused to do so because he
said that the existing casinos were already operating illegally and
he would only negotiate with them if they first ceased their
operations. Wilson signed what he called a model compact with the
Pala band of Mission Indians, a tribe that has never had casino
gambling on its reservation in northern San Diego.
</P>
<P>
   ``If a tribe was permitted to operate illegal gaming until such
time that they entered into a compact with the state, then they
would never have an incentive to conclude a compact negotiation,''
said Dan Kolkey, Wilson's secretary of legal affairs.
</P>
<P>
   The casinos have proliferated into a statewide industry that now
employs about 15,000 people and earns what some industry experts
believe is more than $500 million in revenues. The Pala compact
stipulates regulations such as mandatory age requirements for
gamblers, and state laws regarding hiring, worker's compensation
and collective bargaining.
</P>
<P>
   But what the tribes say would cause them to lose about 85
percent of their revenues is the compact's limitation of the type
and total number of slot machines that they can use. With the slot
machines that are currently in use by the tribes, customers receive
predetermined jackpot amounts, and the casino takes a percentage of
everything that goes into the machines _ like the machines used in
places like Las Vegas and Atlantic City, N.J. However, California
law only allows for the use of what is known as ``lottery'' style
slot machines, which pays winners based on the machine's proceeds
and divides the jackpot among the players and the casino.
</P>
<P>
   Wilson won the support of the Justice Department, who agreed
with the governor that the tribes were violating federal law by
operating without compacts, and began seeking court approval to
seize machines that don't function in adherence to the Pala
compact.
</P>
<P>
   To hold off the changes being imposed by Wilson, the tribes have
filed a lawsuit in state superior court contending that the
governor lacked the authority to sign the Pala compact because he
did so without prior approval from the state legislature. A hearing
in that case is scheduled for later this month.
</P>
<P>
   Lawsuits filed by the U.S. attorneys trying to seize the
machines are also being contested by the tribes. Meanwhile, voters
in the state are being asked to vote on a ballot initiative in
November that would supersede the Pala compact and award the tribes
with a compact allowing them more control over their casinos and
the machines that they use.
</P>
<P>
   The ballot initiative is expected to attract millions of dollars
from both the Indian casinos as well as gambling interests in Las
Vegas, where the Indian casinos are viewed as a threat. Industry
experts estimate that as much as 30 percent of Nevada's casino
customers come from California, and a newly formed group, The
Coalition Against Unregulated Gambling, which includes Nevada
casino interests, has vowed to defeat the ballot initiative.
</P>
<P>
   ``Politicians like Governor Wilson are robbing the tribes and
Vegas interests are providing the ammunition,'' said Daniel Tucker,
president of the California Nations Indian Gaming Association.
</P>
<P>
   In other states, where Indians are either seeking compacts or
negotiating the renewal of existing compacts, the standoff in
California is being watched closely.
</P>
<P>
   ``What is happening in California, if not stopped, will
establish dangerous precedents, reaching across the nation and far
into the future,'' Mark Macarro, chairman of the Pechanga Band of
Luiseno Indians, said in a hearing that was attended by members of
California's congressional delegation here on Tuesday. The Pechanga
tribe's casino is located in the Central Valley of Southern
California.
</P>
<P>
   ``The governor's ability to use his political clout, U.S.
attorneys and courts to maneuver the tribes into a no-win position,
with a compact designed to ultimately make tribal government gaming
unprofitable, will become the standard model used by other states,
recalcitrant governors and foes of Indian gaming,'' Macarro
predicted.
</P>
<P>
   The tribal leaders have warned that the government's current
hard-line position and its ongoing effort to remove the machines
could lead to an armed standoff or violent confrontation.
</P>
<P>
   ''What we have here is the state of California coming in and
cannibalizing tribal soil,'' said Anthony Pico, chairman of the
Viejas band of Kumeyaay Indians, who operate a casino 35 miles east
of San Diego and said he signed the compact under duress. ``We
can't have that. We would die first.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
