<SLUG> BC-MICROSOFT-TRIAL-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
JUDGE PLANS TO LIMIT WITNESSES IN MICROSOFT TRIAL
</HEADLINE>
   (ja) 
 By JOEL BRINKLEY    
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ Trying to avert a lengthy proceeding, a federal
judge said on Tuesday that he planned to limit the number of
witnesses the Microsoft Corp. and the government may call during
the September trial for the antitrust suits filed by the Justice
Department and 20 states.
</P>
<P>
   After meeting privately with lawyers for both sides just before
a court hearing on Tuesday morning, District Court Judge Thomas
Penfield Jackson said: ``It is my expectation to enter an order
limiting the number of witnesses to between 6 and 12 each.''
Further, the judge added, direct testimony should be submitted in
writing in advance and court testimony limited to cross
examinations.
</P>
<P>
   ``If good cause is shown,'' the judge added, he would consider
expanding the number of allowed witnesses.
</P>
<P>
   Neither Microsoft lawyers nor the government officials objected
to the proposal, because it would bear equally on each side.
Microsoft had suggested that it might call numerous witnesses from
the computer industry, apparently leading Jackson to worry that the
trial, which opens Sept. 8, might stretch through the rest of the
year.
</P>
<P>
   ``I am prepared to devote the month of September to this
trial,'' the judge said.
</P>
<P>
   The lawsuits charge Microsoft, the world's largest software
company, with leveraging its monopoly in personal-computer
operating systems to win control of other major products in the
software industry, particularly the browsers used to gain access to
the World Wide Web.
</P>
<P>
   Both Microsoft and the government lawyers have noted that they
will have to rush to prepare for trial in just three months. The
judge said he planned to call the two sides back to court for
progress reports through the summer.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
