A1715 &Cx1f; taf-z
s t &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-TRAVEL-PORTUGAL-CASTL     06-09 1072
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-TRAVEL-PORTUGAL-CASTLES-$ADV14-2TAKES-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
HILLTOP CASTLES GUARD PORTUGAL'S PAST 
</HEADLINE>
   (For release Sunday, June 14.)  
 (JT)  
 By MITCHEL LEVITAS    
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   Portugal's age of glory is written on water. Its 15th- and
16th-century explorers, trained at King Henry the Navigator's
school at Sagres, carried the flag of the tiny kingdom across
uncharted oceans to places as distant as Mozambique and Macao,
Greenland, Brazil, Australia and India. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   But the toll of defending a global empire proved too high even
for a superpower. Soon, with squandered wealth spreading decadence
at home, Portugal fell from the pinnacle of greatness with a crash.
By 1578, when King Sabastiao and his nobles were slain in a
reckless war with Morocco, the House of Aviz was near collapse. It
was easy for Spain to invade and conquer its neighbor, a
humiliation that still smolders, despite a war of independence won
by Portugal 330 years ago.  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Even now, as Lisbon is polished and renewed for Expo '98,
Portugal remains the most reluctant country in Europe when it comes
to embracing modernization. Change is held at arm's length. ``The
future for the Portuguese,'' observe the art historians Hellmut and
Alice Wohl, in their book ``Portugal'' (Scala Books), ``is
`saudade': the longing for a retrieval of past greatness rendered
irretrievable by fear of an unknown, nonexistent punishment, and by
guilt over what one has not done.'' &QL;
</P>
<P>
   But why settle for memories of billowing sails and sunken
caravels? Monumental evidence of even earlier glory remains vividly
alive behind the walls of tiny hilltop villages like Monsanto,
Marvao and Monsaraz, and in fortified towns like Castelo de Vide
and Elvas. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Lined up like sentinels along Portugal's mountainous eastern
border with Spain, medieval castles glisten in the evening fog,
lighted from below by the golden hue of powerful lamps. The castles
look as if Hamlet himself is about to prowl the dark corridors or
shout his revenge from the ramparts. Still standing are the
crenelated walls, arched entries, slender guardhouses and massive
keeps, moats, towers, dungeons, cisterns, churches and palaces. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Six and seven hundred years after defying waves of invaders,
there are dozens of castles remaining in remarkably good shape or
carefully restored. Not until 1297, when the kingdom was solidly
established more or less along its present boundaries, did
Portugal's castles come to embody a virtually sacred role. They
still do, combining religion, history and patriotism into a
profound sense of national meaning. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   On a two-week trip to Portugal in January, my wife, Gloria, and
I visited a dozen of these remarkable medieval hill towns.  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   The steep, cobbled streets, houses of gray granite blocks and
gigantic weathered boulders of Monsanto's castle _ Mons Sanctus, it
was called _ is where such history begins. Not for nothing did the
government name it Portugal's ``most typical village'' as long ago
as 1939. In any other country, the honor would have brought instant
ruin: souvenir shops and sidewalk vendors, clamoring guides and bad
restaurants. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Yet as far as we could tell, Monsanto has but one cafe, where
the chief sport seems to be sipping the terrific espresso while
watching tourists scrape their fenders on the narrow stone walls as
they try to climb the corkscrew turns into the castle _ after
missing the sign (if there was one) that warns drivers to park
below and walk. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Most of the 2,100 villagers live outside the walls. Inside,
there are no guides, no restaurants, almost no rooms to rent and
one hotel, a comfortable 10-room government-owned pousada, part of
the extensive and luxurious national hotel chain in historic
buildings. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Monsanto's castle walls, carved out of the same living quarry
that shaped the town, look as if they had grown mysteriously out of
the ground: huge craggy rocks and weathered boulders big as a
whale's back or small as a hippopotamus. From a height of 2,500
feet, the village looms over a vast plain of corn and plantations
of cork oaks and olive trees. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Climbing to the summit along a twisting path bordered by mottled
green lichens and ferns, we suddenly came upon a pair of pigs in a
grassy enclosure curiously venturing from a round stone hut that
may have housed animals since Roman times. The fiercely protective
castle now suggests an image of domesticity and impregnable
grandeur.  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Our next stop, Castelo de Vide, is about 85 miles away, in a
loop to the south. It's not a hard drive because most of it is
along a modern four-lane divided highway; the secondary roads are
paved, as they are throughout the country, and are usually well
maintained and not heavily traveled. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Castelo de Vide is just west of the Spanish border and displays
a cheerful architectural harmony of whitewashed houses on narrow
streets. Doorways are filled with plants and potted flowers, and
the town's beautifully proportioned main square, shaped roughly
like a trapezoid, is lined with small shops and two-story
buildings. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Not much remains of Castelo de Vide's 14th-century castle,
except five impressive towers and the massive, rambling walls that
enclose part of the town and hug the landscape. A prosperous
agricultural town that once had the largest Jewish population in
Portugal, Castelo de Vide seems unchanged from centuries past. Even
the stone pillory post in front of the medieval town hall
(virtually every Portuguese town has a carved pelourinho topped by
protruding arms of wrought iron from which the unfortunate accused
was whipped and tortured, frequently as a precursor to death by
hanging) does its part to preserve symbolically a sense of
Portugal's strong traditional values, if not the punishment that
enforces them. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   ``Nothing has changed here for 800 years,'' we are told by Joao
Miguel Goncalves Maroc, a 30-year-old pilot who trained in Dallas,
now lives in Lisbon and is visiting his grandfather, an 86-year-old
man sharing drinks with his cronies at a small crowded cafe just
off the square. ``On Fridays, the farmers still come to town to
shop for the week and meet their friends. Weekends, it's empty.''
Of the young people, he says that about half remain in town and
marry; the rest leave for Lisbon, as he did, or seek work elsewhere
in Europe. &QL;
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
</P>
<P>
   A few blocks away in the medieval quarter _ down flights of
steps from a small room that was a 13th-century synagogue _ is the
town fountain. With its pyramidal stone roof supported by six small
marble pillars, it is said to be the oldest fountain in Portugal.
The mineral waters here and elsewhere in town made it famous as a
medieval spa. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Has anything changed? Not that we can see. The water still
splashes softly in the base of the fountain, then silently drains
under the edge of a tiny plaza that slopes up like a scallop shell
to a rim of ancient houses with carved stone window frames and
Gothic doorways. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Marvao, just a few miles away, is a 12th-century time capsule.
The castle, built into the rock, encloses an entire village of
about 250 people. Perched on a craggy platform 2,700 feet above the
valley floor are dazzling white houses with small iron balconies,
the church of Espirito Santo, a primary school, a fascinating small
museum of local lore, a gracious pousada, a few shops, cafes, and
rooms to rent. Cobbled streets wind mysteriously or end abruptly.  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   It's an amazing place, magical, unblemished and yet quite real,
a curious outpost of history that goes back to the Iron Age.  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Walking through the maze of castle courtyards and towering
walls, we spot a number of small, locked wooden doors. Suddenly,
one door opens to our touch. There's even a light switch in the
stone wall on the right. We know enough to flick the switch and we
see an enormous cistern carved from the castle rock and lighted by
bulbs in the low, arched ceiling. The water is fed, we later
notice, by runoffs carved in the stone floors of the courtyard.
Peering left and right at the bottom of a short flight of stone
steps at the water's edge, we could not see either end of the
cistern. Later we learned that it is estimated to hold a six-month
supply of water _ long enough to survive your average serious
siege. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   About 45 miles south of Marvao (also just a hop from the Spanish
border), is Elvas, a virtual museum of fortification, but on a
grand scale compared to Marvao. A modern, bustling small city of
18,000 people, Elvas is enclosed by some of the most elaborate
battlements in Europe _ moats, drawbridges, iron gates and four
star-shaped bastions whose great walls rise majestically from the
plains below. There, the past and present co-exist without apparent
tension.  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Traffic zooms around the octagonal 16th-century Church of Our
Lady of Consolation, past the pillory post on the edge of the
well-preserved Arab quarter, and down to the main plaza, paved with
white, gray and black stones in a pattern of Renaissance cubes. No
city planner or private developer even imagines ripping down a
block for new housing, a shopping mall or a new industrial
district. The stores may have plate glass windows, but water still
runs to the fountain in Largo da Misericordia along the topmost
tier of arches of an aqueduct more than four miles long that took
more than 100 years to finish. That was in 1622.  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Leaving Elvas, we drive on a flat curving road, which suddenly
ascends to the arched gate leading to the 13th-century castle
village of Monsaraz. Along the road are fields and groves littered
with some of Europe's richest neolithic finds, including a circle
of 50 boulders surrounding a towering seven-ton phallic-shaped
stone, tombs of huge rock slabs, and a profusion of dolmens,
menhirs and other megaliths put in place five and six thousand
years ago. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Only in Portugal can a vast outdoor museum of the earliest human
habitation make a nearly intact medieval fortress seem almost
modern. Not until 1167 were the Moors of Monsaraz defeated by
Geraldo the Fearless, but the castle he conquered had been a Roman
stronghold, too. The amphitheater for Portuguese bullfighting was
the stage for Roman dance and drama. Walking along the rows of
stone seats open to the neolithic vista beyond is like having a
ringside ticket to 50 centuries of history. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Within the walls of Monsaraz live about 90 people, and outside,
at the foot of the walls, about 150 more. The two main streets are
still paved with slivers of shale; three horizontal rows
alternating with three vertical rows. You can walk around the
village, a tableau of whitewashed houses, orange trees, a domed
church and the dilapidated House of the Inquisition, in half an
hour, but that would be a mistake. The handful of small shops that
sell objects of cork (statues, boxes, bottles), pottery or textiles
are inviting.  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   The restrained proprietors, mostly women, wait behind the
counters of the shops we visit, ready to help but hoping that we
will discover for ourselves the appeal of a carved wooden
candlestick or the intricate patterns of an embroidered shawl _ all
handmade in Portugal and many in the region. Unlike many tourist
shops the world over, these are not stocked with tomahawks made in
China or key rings from Mexico; Portugal is too poor to import
trinkets by the ton and too proud to hawk its handicrafts as though
they were T-shirts. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Such resistance to commercialization, along with a gentle sense
of ceremony and a deep feeling for the land and its traditions,
have almost miraculously preserved Portugal's walled towns and
villages _ so far.
</P>
<P>
   Where to stay, where to eat
</P>
<P>
   The dozens of state-run pousadas, strategically situated in or
near major tourist destinations throughout the country, almost
invariably offer the most comfortable accommodations and, often,
the finest food in the area. Though they're not cheap compared with
what is generally available (and there are plenty of adequate,
clean and inexpensive hotels, rooms and pensions), the pousadas
offer a real bargain for value received. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   For a convenient base of operations there are three pousadas in
Estremoz, about a two-hour drive east of Lisbon. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   At the  &UR; Rainha Santa Isabel,  &LR;  (351-68) 33 20 75, a former
palace on the highest hill overlooking Estremoz, and next door to
the medieval castle keep, a double in season is $195 a night (all
prices include a generous buffet breakfast and VAT.) The antique
furnishings remain fit for a king, and the architectural scale of
the halls, ceilings, marble staircases and tapestries is
appropriately royal, too. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   For the same price, the  &UR; Pousada dos Loios, &LR;  (351-66) 24051, in
Evora offers a matchless location in the beautiful capital of the
Alentejo region: 10 yards from a remarkably preserved second- or
early-third-century Roman temple. The rooms are rather small
(appropriately?) in this former convent, but the public spaces and
the cozy bar are delightful. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Three nights of our two-week trip we stayed in small hotels
along the way, when either there was no pousada nearby, or it was
full. That wasn't bad either, though the dim lights and bare walls
of our room in the  &UR; Hotel Turismo da Guarda &LR;  were disappointing;
(351-71) 22 33 66. But $87 a night was a bargain, and it was a
short drive to Monsanto, where the pousada was full.  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   At least as spectacular as the most upscale pousada is the
 &UR; Hotel Convento de Sao Paulo,  &LR; (351-66) 99 91 00, a former convent
perched high on a hill within a private 3,000-acre unspoiled forest
above Redondo, a short drive to the walled village of Monsaraz.
Opened in 1993 after almost two years of reconstruction of a
near-ruin, the hotel is now a posh hideout for a handful of
tourists and a corporate retreat designed for productive
relaxation: walks through the ancient forest, swimming pool, game
rooms, high-tech meeting rooms, air-conditioning and 17 huge,
tastefully appointed rooms (no two furnished alike) off the long,
wide hallways lined with azulejos, painted blue tiles, from the
16th and 17th centuries. Doubles cost about $160 to $175, including
breakfast.  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   &UR; Pousada de Santa Luzia &LR;  in Elvas, (351-68) 62 21 94, opened in
1942 and was the first in the country. Its modern architecture of
glass, brick and wood is in stark contrast to the classic
restorations of most other pousadas (doubles are about $100,
including breakfast). We had been tipped off about lunch here,
especially the signature dish _ bacalhau dourado (golden salt cod,
with virtually invisible slivers of fish, onion and potato mixed
with the fluffiest eggs imaginable) _ probably the best food we had
in Portugal (about $8).  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   A close second was a lavish six-course Sunday buffet ($21) at
the  &UR; Dom Joao IV. &LR;  the former Covento das Chagas de Cristo, in Vila
Vicosa, a 45-minute drive from Elvas, among the most recent hotels
to open in Portugal; (351-68) 98742. Just off the plaza, dominated
by the grand ducal palace, the pousada had been a convent, a
mausoleum for duchesses, then abandoned and left to collapse when
the government stepped in and restored it with taste and rustic
elegance. Doubles are about $162, with breakfast.
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
