<SLUG> BC-BKN-ARATON-COLUMN-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
SPORTS COLUMN: RODMAN IS NOBODY'S BUSINESS BUT THE BULLS' 
</HEADLINE>
  (th) 
 By HARVEY ARATON    
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   CHICAGO _ Oh, now Dennis Rodman should be consigned to where he
really belongs, in wrestling rings and on couches next to the most
qualified psychologists, and Jay Leno.
</P>
<P>
   Now Phil Jackson should stand up for the sake of decency and the
coaching fraternity and for impressionable kids who are getting the
idea it is all right to abandon those who depend on them for an
enterprising night of nihilism with Hulk Hogan in Detroit.
</P>
<P>
   ``Winning has never been that important to me,'' Jerry Sloan
announced in disdainful, jaw-jutting fashion Tuesday before his
Utah Jazz prepared for what we are here for in the first place,
Wednesday night's fourth game of the National Basketball
Association finals. ``We'd find a way to remove him from the
organization.''
</P>
<P>
   That is easy for Sloan and former coach and current ESPN
commentator Jack Ramsay and every columnist right up there on
Moses' mountain to say.
</P>
<P>
   The well-intentioned but twisted logic here is that Jackson and
the Bulls should sever Rodman, cut off their nose rings to spite
their face, in the middle of a championship series they are
leading, 2-1.
</P>
<P>
   Fire their best rebounder and inside defender after Rodman
shunned Monday's light practice and news media availability to
become ``Rodzilla'' at a wrestling show for a cool quarter million.
</P>
<P>
   ``He didn't wrestle, did he?'' Jackson said, trying to maintain
perspective, more than a sense of humor, because last week, in Salt
Lake City, the predictable act of theatrical intransigence was an
all-nighter in Las Vegas after Game 1. ``In the end, Dennis always
comes back and tries extra hard to please.''
</P>
<P>
   This is just not good enough for those who claim Rodman is
making a cartoon out of what could be Michael Jordan's farewell.
Ramsay said that no other coach would put up with Rodman not on the
bench for the start of the game and not at practice the morning
after.
</P>
<P>
   Sloan asserted that Rodman's chronic disobedience is some grave
threat to basketball's moral high ground, which is like accusing
the clown of subverting the integrity of the circus.
</P>
<P>
   Compared to some of the company many NBA players keep, Hulk
Hogan is practically the dean of Harvard Business School.
</P>
<P>
   Of course, Rodman is the Joker to Jordan's Batman and Scottie
Pippen's Robin. In his third and presumably last season with what
no longer is a mere basketball team but a collection of action
heroes, Rodman as what Jackson calls the ``anti-hero'' has made
himself a windfall as Jordan's evil twin.
</P>
<P>
   With Rodman around, Jordan has become more of a deity than ever.
The star of the show would never think of leaving his team in the
middle of the playoffs to gamble into the morning hours, now would
he?
</P>
<P>
   Unless Rodman becomes insubordinate or violent on the court,
what else can Jackson do at this point? He knows that Jordan's
presence keeps Rodman from distracting the others.
</P>
<P>
   A fairer criticism of Jackson and Jordan is that they signed
onto Rodman's return in the first place after he broke every team
rule for two years and, worse, assaulted a courtside photographer
during a game last season. David Stern could have made the same
example out of Rodman he eventually made of Latrell Sprewell. He
didn't, probably because Rodman had value to the franchise that
carries his league.
</P>
<P>
   Jackson admits he agreed to have Rodman back with no illusion
that he would transform himself into Steve Kerr. When he was asked
Tuesday what, if any, authority he has over Rodman, his facial
expression suggested incredulity. ``No one has authority over
Dennis _ that's his problem,'' Jackson said. When someone compared
Rodman to a kindergartner, Jackson said the situation is ``more
like special ed.''
</P>
<P>
   Every team has recalcitrant players, but Jackson is the rare
power coach who doesn't have to use it to prove he has it. It is
his most redeeming coaching quality.
</P>
<P>
   Four years ago, when Pippen removed himself from an end-game
playoff situation against the Knicks, Jackson walked into the
locker room and waited to see what his players would do. Bill
Cartwright stood up, teary eyed, and said to Pippen, ``How could
you do that to us?''
</P>
<P>
   Pippen, properly chastened by a respected veteran, apologized.
The team got beyond the worst move of Pippen's career without
Jackson having to say a word. Now one of Jackson's assistants,
Cartwright said: ``That was different from this. With Dennis, we
just leave it to Phil. He knows how to handle Dennis.''
</P>
<P>
   He knew Rodman would put him in this situation when the Bulls
re-signed him. He was ready to publicly live with it. If he can,
it's none of Jerry Sloan's business. &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
