<SLUG> BC-CLINTON-CHINA-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
CLINTON REBUFFS CRITICS OF UPCOMING TRIP TO CHINA 

</HEADLINE>
  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  By NANCY MATHIS 
c.1998 Houston Chronicle 
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ President Clinton on Tuesday defended his trip to
China later this month and agreed to a ``policy of reciprocity'' to
induce North Korea to become more open.
</P>
<P>
   Clinton, hosting South Korean President Kim Dae-Jung in an
official state visit, opened the door for easing, but not lifting
as Kim had suggested, some U.S. economic sanctions against North
Korea if the communist nation, now plagued by food shortages, made
moves to reconcile with South Korea.
</P>
<P>
   In a news conference with Kim, Clinton turned aside complaints
from Americans on the political left and right who are pressing him
to avoid an official welcoming ceremony at Tiananmen Square, where
the Chinese Army massacred students and supporters of a
pro-democracy movement nine years ago this month.
</P>
<P>
   ``My own view is that if this is going to be a state visit to
China and I am going to be the guest of the Chinese, that they
should be designing the terms of the arrival ceremony _ not me. I
simply don't accept the proposition that observing their diplomatic
protocol in any way undermines my capacity to advance the
principles of the United States,'' Clinton said.
</P>
<P>
   Because of the Asian economic crisis and the nuclear arms race
in India and Pakistan, Clinton said it should be ``clearer than
ever before that we have a strong national interest in developing a
constructive, positive relationship with China.''
</P>
<P>
   He noted that China has released several political prisoners
since Chinese President Jiang Zemin visited the United States last
year. ``I intend to make our views clear and unambiguous,'' Clinton
said.
</P>
<P>
   Clinton also defended his approval of a waiver for Loral Space &AMP;
Communications, owned by a major Democratic donor, to use a Chinese
missile to launch one of its satellites.
</P>
<P>
   At the time, the Justice Department was investigating whether
Loral officials gave the Chinese illegal information that could
improve its missile technology. The Justice Department opposed the
waiver, contending it could damage any future prosecution.
</P>
<P>
   ``I didn't resist the advice of the Justice Department. I took
the advice of the National Security Council, the Defense
Department, the State Department and the Arms Control and
Disarmament Agency,'' Clinton said. He said the State Department
has the responsibility to make the recommendation and the other
agencies concurred.
</P>
<P>
   ``From my point of view it was a pretty routine decision,'' he
said.
</P>
<P>
   In welcoming ceremonies on the South Lawn and at the news
conference, Clinton offered praise for President Kim, once a
dissident placed on death row by a South Korean military regime and
the first leader of an opposition party to win a presidential
election there in 50 years.
</P>
<P>
   Clinton praised Kim for his efforts at outreach to North Korea
and offered some modest proposals to help South Korea overcome the
economic slump affecting all of Asia. But, Clinton said, the
critical issue of lifting sanctions on North Korea was not brought
up.
</P>
<P>
   ``President Kim did not ask me to lift sanctions. What he asked
me to do was to work with him to support a policy of reciprocity
which would enable us to move forward with the reconciliation of
the North and the South. And I said that I would be prepared to do
that,'' Clinton said.
</P>
<P>
   He noted lifting most sanctions would take an act of Congress,
but he has authority to take some actions.
</P>
<P>
   Kim, 75, appearing frail and weary, added, ``We have nothing to
fear from North Korea. To induce them to open up will be beneficial
not only to the interests of our two countries, but to the peace of
the peninsula and Northeast Asia.''
</P>
<P>
   He said lifting sanctions would be up to the Americans, but ``we
would not oppose and we would cooperate.'' Kim has encouraged North
Korea, ruled by the elusive Kim Jong Il, to open its markets as
China and Vietnam have.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't think anybody knows well enough about him,'' Kim said
of the North Korean. ``Based on our experience, it's very difficult
to say that you can trust a communist. But we feel the need to
negotiate, and once you've reached an agreement, to hold them up to
that agreement.''
</P>
<P>
   Weather extremes and central planning have left the North
Koreans with food shortages and famine. But Kim said the government
there remains relatively stable. He expressed concern, however,
that if the problems continue North Korea ``could go the road of
military provocation.''
</P>
<P>
   North Korea's threat to develop its nuclear potential prompted
an international response in 1994. North Korea recently revived
those threats after it was unable to acquire enough crude oil.
Clinton said the United States was working to resolve the problem.
</P>
<P>
   Neither Clinton nor Kim offered any timetable for U.S. troops to
end their duties along the demilitarized zone that has separated
the two Koreas since the war ended in 1953.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
XXXX END OF STORY &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
