<DOCNO> NYT19980609.0407 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-06-09 21:49 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A1723 &Cx1f; taf-z
u a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-NY-WORLD-CUP-NYT &LR;      06-09 1356
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-NY-WORLD-CUP-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
NEW YORK'S LATIN IMMIGRANTS PASSIONATELY AWAIT WORLD CUP 
</HEADLINE>
   (bl)  
 By VIVIAN S. TOY   
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ At least once a year, Juan Ospina finds himself
driving 24 hours nonstop just to watch a soccer match. He sometimes
takes off from work to head to one of the Queens bars that
broadcast games from South America.
</P>
<P>
   And in case there was any doubt of his devotion, he has been
known to shave the name of his native country, Colombia, onto the
back of his head and paint the colors of the Colombian flag across
his face.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think the people at work think I'm a little crazy,'' said
Ospina, a translator at Queens County Family Court. ``But soccer is
in the blood of most Latin American countries, and people will go
to extremes for their teams.''
</P>
<P>
   Ospina and six buddies have spent the last year planning a
weeklong sojourn to France to watch their team play in the 1998
World Cup tournament, which starts Wednesday. They joke that their
wives have stopped speaking to them, but they have what they want:
tickets for next Monday's match between Colombia and Romania.
</P>
<P>
   While few Americans find themselves seized by the mania and the
fierce national pride involved in the World Cup, immigrants like
Ospina from soccer-mad countries have waited four long years for
this event. Now, they are ready; to scream, to drink, to wallow in
misery or stop traffic in jubilation.
</P>
<P>
   Imagine the Super Bowl, day after day, for an entire month.
</P>
<P>
   Nowhere is that more apparent than in neighborhoods along
Roosevelt Avenue, a bustling spine of immigrant Queens. Under the
rumbling el, dozens of restaurants and sports bars that cater to
Latin Americans have been advertising for weeks that they will
broadcast the 64 World Cup games on ``pantallas gigantes,''
huge-screen television sets. Shops sell T-shirts emblazoned with
the World Cup mascot, a rooster named Footix. Vendors wander the
street selling Colombian and Mexican flags, World Cup key chains
and other trinkets.
</P>
<P>
   Latin American immigrants have more than usual to focus on this
year, because for the first time in World Cup history, four South
American teams, Brazil, Argentina, Colombia and Chile, along with
Mexico, are ranked among the top 10 teams by the sport's
international body.
</P>
<P>
   Because of the six-hour time difference with France, all games
will be televised in the New York City (on ABC, ESPN, ESPN2 or
Channel 41) during the day. While many soccer fans have been
stocking up on videotapes to record what they miss while they're at
work, others have pleaded with their bosses to let them watch the
matches live.
</P>
<P>
   ``I've been trying to get the owner to put a television in,''
said Nubia Garrido, a waitress at La Pequena Colombiana, a
restaurant on Roosevelt Avenue. ``But he just keeps saying, `We'll
talk about it.''' So instead, Ms. Garrido, like many others, has
started planning World Cup parties at home on her days off. ``It's
much more fun to be together and watch,'' she said.
</P>
<P>
   Police precincts in northern Queens, meanwhile, have plotted
their strategy for handling soccer revelers after each game
involving a Latin American country. A special task force has been
prepared, with dozens of mounted police officers with riot gear.
</P>
<P>
   Police learned the hard way four years ago just how passionate
people in the area can be about their beloved futbol and the Copa
Mundial.
</P>
<P>
   ``We got caught with our pants down four years ago,'' said
Officer Earl Dawson, a community affairs officer in the 115th
Precinct in Jackson Heights. ``We didn't realize that there's this
whole geopolitical culture to the World Cup.''
</P>
<P>
   The disturbances in parts of Queens in 1994 certainly never
approached the soccer rioting that has become familiar in Europe
and Latin America. But thousands of soccer fans rushed onto
Roosevelt Avenue, stopping traffic and shutting the thoroughfare
with impromptu soccer games and raucous rejoicing.
</P>
<P>
   When Brazil beat Italy to win the championship, Latino fans
drove up and down Fresh Pond Road in Maspeth to taunt the residents
in the largely Italian area. When police tried to disperse the
crowds, fans hurled eggs, firecrackers and bottles at police. A few
officers were hurt and six people were arrested.
</P>
<P>
   This year, police in the 115th and 110th Precincts have mapped
out the schedule of matches and kept tabs on the teams' rankings
with the help of local bar owners and soccer sites on the World
Wide Web to figure out how to deploy police officers. ``Ninety
percent of it is all good-natured rivalry and it's not a hostile
crowd,'' said Officer Noel Colon. ``But if you don't want it
turning into a wild party on the street, you have to prepare for a
riot.''
</P>
<P>
   He noted that precincts in other ethnic strongholds _ like an
Italian area on Arthur Avenue in the Bronx, or the Jamaican
neighborhood around Flatbush Avenue in Crown Heights, Brooklyn, and
the Brazilian enclave on Broadway in Astoria _ will also be on the
alert.
</P>
<P>
   Police officials said that fans were especially frenzied in 1994
because the World Cup was played in the United States, and busloads
of people headed to and from New Jersey to watch matches at the
Meadowlands. This year, the time difference could work in their
favor, since people are less likely to drink heavily while they are
watching games early in the day. ``But if one of their team wins,''
Colon said, ``forget it. Total mayhem.''
</P>
<P>
   Jorge Alarcon, the owner of Chibcha, a Colombian restaurant in
Jackson Heights that has seven large-screen television sets, has
worked closely with police. ``I think they understand now that it's
just our people's celebration, and it is a big pride to see your
country in the World Cup,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Ospina said he and his friends _ who used to play in one of the
many soccer leagues started by immigrants across the city _ have
been among the crowds that swarmed onto Roosevelt Avenue. ``It's
just a big party, and when you're all together out there, it just
makes the moment better,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Armando Martin, a travel agent at San Francisco Travel on
Roosevelt Avenue, is a Colombian immigrant, but he said he would be
watching Argentina and Brazil closely, too. ``Of course I am for
Colombia, but if they lose I will be just as much for Argentina or
Brazil, because we are all from the same side, South America,'' he
said.
</P>
<P>
   Martin said he was lucky because his boss, Piero Adjemiantz, had
already agreed to tune the office television set to the games. ``Of
course we will watch,'' said Adjemiantz, an Argentine immigrant.
``It's our national game, and every country plays futbol except the
Americans.''
</P>
<P>
   Major League Soccer in the United States recently expanded to 12
teams, and ABC this year decided to increase the number of games it
shows to 12 (from one), but many Americans are still only vaguely
aware of the World Cup and may have never heard of such giants as
the Brazilian star Ronaldo, considered by many to be the greatest
player in the world.
</P>
<P>
   Ospina and his friends, though, were positively giddy about
their coming trip when they gathered for a pickup soccer game
Friday night. For the last 10 years, they have gone on soccer road
trips at least twice a year, travels that have brought them to
Florida and California as well as back home to Colombia.
</P>
<P>
   Ospina, 35, sheepishly admitted that he did not become a diehard
soccer fan until he arrived in Queens as a teen-ager in 1980 and
eventually joined Sporting Colombia, a local soccer team that
disbanded last year because ``we all got too old and fat,'' he
said.
</P>
<P>
   ``I wanted to identify with other immigrants, and playing and
watching soccer somehow made me feel a little bit closer to my
country,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   But before they have even packed their bags for France, Ospina
and his crew have already started planning for 2002, when the World
Cup will be played in Japan and South Korea.
</P>
<P>
   ``All we have to do is work, pay taxes, die and follow the
team,'' said Fernando Diaz, another Bogota native who now lives in
Richmond Hill. ``We're already working on our Japanese.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-06-09-98 2149EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19980609.0408 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-06-09 21:50 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A1724 &Cx1f; taf-z
s e &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-COLTRANE-JAZZ-ART-$AD     06-09 0786
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-COLTRANE-JAZZ-ART-$ADV14-800(2TAKES)-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
COLTRANE'S SON, BUT WITH HIS OWN SOUND 
</HEADLINE>
  (For release Sunday, June 14.) 
 (ART ADV: Photo is being sent to NYT photo clients. Non-subscribers
can make individual purchase by calling 212-556-4204.)  
(JT) 
 By BEN RATLIFF    
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   It's a perfect indicator of jazz's restricted place in American
society that Ravi Coltrane _ who is the son of John Coltrane _ was
nobody special as a boy growing up in Woodland Hills, a suburb of
Los Angeles, far away from the bohemian world. He was nearly 2 when
his father died of liver cancer in 1967, and the family moved from
Long Island to the San Fernando Valley, where he lived with his
mother, Alice Coltrane, and three siblings. Of course, he was
suddenly somebody very significant when he arrived at the
California Institute of the Arts to study tenor and soprano
saxophone, because John Coltrane _ who played the same instruments
_ is still the apotheosis of the jazz sainthood myth.
</P>
<P>
   ``When I went to Cal Arts,'' Coltrane, 32, said, ``I was
starting out late, I couldn't play at all, and I had this name that
people weren't used to dealing with. I constantly kept this in my
mind: I'm here to do one thing. I just wanted to learn about this
music and see if I can deal with it as a player. And I'm still
thinking like that.''
</P>
<P>
   After graduating, Coltrane moved to a second-floor apartment and
rehearsal space overlooking a commercial avenue in Queens in 1991,
and started a long apprenticeship with various band leaders,
including Elvin Jones, Jack DeJohnette, Wallace Roney, Joanne
Brackeen and Steve Coleman. He lives there still, with his
girlfriend, Kathleen Hennessy. Relaxed and athletic-looking, he sat
at his piano bench a few weeks ago, slapping a chessboard queen
into the palm of his hand while he talked, the phone ringing every
few minutes.
</P>
<P>
   ``There's a lot of stuff going on,'' he said, a bit regretfully.
``Too much, sometimes. I'd rather be working than not working, but
I think I'll get a better feel for things after this year is
over.''
</P>
<P>
   After appearing as a sideman on 29 records, Coltrane made a
debut album, ``Moving Pictures'' (RCA/BMG), released last month.
Since then he has played a week at Sweet Basil in New York, taken a
few trips to Europe and has already been occasionally misquoted
talking about his father in a rush of interviews. He will perform
tonight in one of the biggest events of the Texaco New York Jazz
Festival: a double bill with his group and that of his namesake,
the sitarist Ravi Shankar, at Town Hall. Coltrane will be joined by
his mother on piano; she has rarely performed in public since
taking up the study of Indian religion and philosophy in the 1970s.
Ms. Coltrane said that she expected to play two John Coltrane
pieces _ ``Crescent'' and ``Resolution,'' a section from the longer
work ``A Love Supreme.''
</P>
<P>
   ``Moving Pictures'' is a rare jazz record. It isn't dazzling;
Ravi Coltrane's music works on you more slowly. He has a warm,
streamlined tone, and he's partial to small, sharp motifs and
pockets of silence rather than the endless stuffing of notes
through complicated harmonic grids. Along with the tenor
saxophonists Mark Turner and Greg Tardy, Coltrane is one of a
growing number of jazz players in their early 30s who are making
their mark, an age at which some of their own ideas about music
have had time to cool and harden.
</P>
<P>
   The positive effects of that waiting process is obvious to any
listener. It's clear that Coltrane hasn't been bossed around by a
producer. The first track on the record gives you the idea: it's
Coltrane and the trumpeter Ralph Alessi playing free improvisations
with the Jamaican drum trio Ancient Vibrations, barely jazz at all.
Thereafter, the compositional ideas are kept simple, the drummer
Jeff Watts turns in a memorable performance as rhythm predominates,
and by the end of the album you're left with an accurate indication
of Coltrane's talent. And, no, he sounds nothing like his father.
Where John's music was urgent and prolix, Ravi's is cool and
concise.
</P>
<P>
   Coltrane has gained a sense of quiet pride and tact from living
with his surname, where others in his position might have spiraled
off into brash delusions. From the start, he had been approached
with offers to record as a band leader. ``From the minute I picked
up the horn,'' he said, ``I started to see that I was going to get
some breaks that other guys wouldn't get.'' Some of those potential
breaks felt undeserved. ``You can tell,'' he said firmly, ``when
somebody has the `Coltrane' thing in their eyes.''
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
</P>
