<SLUG> BC-BAPTISTS-TEX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
`SUBMISSIVE WIVES' STATEMENT SOLIDIFIES CONSERVATIVES' HOLD ON
BAPTISTS
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By JIM JONES 
c.1997 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   SALT LAKE CITY _ Conservatives hammered home another spike in
their domination of the Southern Baptist Convention on Tuesday by
adopting a statement affirming a biblical hierarchy for the family
stating that ``a wife is to submit graciously to the servant
leadership of her husband.''
</P>
<P>
   Also symbolizing conservative dominance, Baptists elevated
55-year-old Paige Patterson _ a Texas born biblical inerrantist who
led the 1980s conservative takeover of the Southern Baptist
Convention _ to the presidency of the nation's largest Protestant
group.
</P>
<P>
   He was elected by acclamation without opposition.
</P>
<P>
   Surprisingly, some delegates opposed the statement on ``The
Family,'' but it was approved overwhelmingly by more than 8,000
delegates during the opening day of the convention that continues
through tomorrow.
</P>
<P>
   Delegates defeated an amendment by the Rev. Tim Owings of the
First Baptist Church of Augusta, Ga., which would have changed the
passage about women submitting to their husbands. Owings, referring
to a passage from Ephesians, wanted to reword the proposal to say
that ``both husband and wife are to submit graciously to each
other. ...''
</P>
<P>
   ``If we are going to amend the Baptist Faith and Message
Statement, let's do it in accordance with scripture,'' Owings said.
</P>
<P>
   A Florida delegate agreed with Owings, saying the idea of women
submitting to men was stated by God after Adam and Eve had lapsed
into sin in the Garden of Eden.
</P>
<P>
   ``Hierarchy replaced partnership after their sin,'' he said.
``This (idea of men being over women) is a curse rather than a
thing of God.''
</P>
<P>
   Backers of the original wording, the Rev. Adrian Rogers of
Memphis, Tenn., the former convention president, argued that the
proposed amendment did not reflect the entire Bible teaching about
women submitting to men.
</P>
<P>
   Another messenger, the Rev. Dennis Wiles of the First Baptist
Church of Huntsville, Ala., unsuccessfully tried to amend the
proposal to make the definition of a family also apply to include
single people, couples without children, widows or widowers.
</P>
<P>
   ``Many of my church members fit into this category, and I think
it should have been added,'' Wiles said in an interview.
</P>
<P>
   Patterson, president of Southeastern Baptist Theological
Seminary in Wake Forest, N.C., said the statement is not anti-woman
but is a much needed affirmation of the traditional family. He
noted that it says husband and wife are of ``equal worth before
God.''
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't see it as anti-anything,'' Patterson said at a news
conference after the vote. ``The Bible is crystal clear in
assigning certain roles to husbands and wives.''
</P>
<P>
   The proposal marked the first time in 35 years that the Baptists
have amended their Faith and Message Statement, a general statement
of Baptist beliefs. The new addition stands against homosexual
marriages or unions of heterosexual couples living together outside
marriage.
</P>
<P>
   It states, ``God has ordained the family as the foundational
institution of human society ...marriage is the uniting of one man
and one woman in covenant commitment for a lifetime. It is God's
unique gift...to provide for the man and the woman in marriage the
framework for intimate companionship, the channel for sexual
expression according to biblical standards.''
</P>
<P>
   While stating that the husband is to love his wife as Christ
loves the church, the statement declares: ``A wife is to submit
graciously to the servant leadership of her husband even as the
church willingly submits to the headship of Christ.''
</P>
<P>
   It continues: ``She, being in the image of God, as is her
husband...has a God-given responsibility to respect her husband and
to serve as his helper in managing the household and nurturing the
next generation.
</P>
<P>
   ``Children from the moment of conception are a blessing and
heritage from the Lord. Parents are to teach their children
spiritual and moral values and to lead them...children are to honor
and obey their parents.''
</P>
<P>
   At his news conference, Patterson said the statement backing
only heterosexual marriage should not be construed as `gay
bashing.''
</P>
<P>
   ``Southern Baptists love them (gays and lesbians) and wish them
to know Christ and help them to make corrections in their
lifestyle,'' Patterson said.
</P>
<P>
   His wife, Dorothy, was on the committee that drafted the
statement. In an interview prior to its adoption, Patterson was
asked if he supported it.
</P>
<P>
   ``I pretty much have to,'' he joked. ``My wife was on the
committee that wrote it.''
</P>
<P>
   The Rev. Julie Pennington-Russell, one of about 1,500 women who
are ordained ministers in the Southern Baptist Convention, said she
thought the statement will drive many away from the
conservative-controlled denomination.
</P>
<P>
   ``What this does is provide a potential litmus test of
orthodoxy,'' said Pennington-Russell, who will become senior pastor
of the Calvary Baptist Church in Waco on Aug. 1.
</P>
<P>
   She is believed to be the first woman to be a senior pastor of a
Baptist church in Texas.
</P>
<P>
   Lynn Clayton, editor of the Louisiana Baptist Message, the state
Baptist newspaper, said one ramification of the statement is that
seminary professors in the six Southern Baptist seminaries may be
pressured to say they do not support the concept of women being
ordained ministers.
</P>
<P>
   However, Ken Hemphill, president of the Southwestern Baptist
Theological Seminary in Fort Worth, said the statement doesn't
directly address that issue.
</P>
<P>
   Although Baptists historically have opposed creeds and supported
freedom of conscience, the Baptist Faith and Message Statement is
an important doctrinal document. For example, professors at all six
of the denominations' seminaries are required to sign the
statement.
</P>
<P>
   (Visit the Star-Telegram's online services on the World Wide
Web: www.star-telegram.com)
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
