<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-SEXONLINE-SFCHRON </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (For use by clients of the New York Times News Service)  
 
 Sex a Big Hit Among Cyber Surfers   By Jon Swartz  
 c.1998 San Francisco Chronicle  
 
In the first comprehensive poll of sexual habits in cyberspace, a
team of psychologists concluded yesterday that ``erotic pursuits''
are among the most frequent uses of the Internet and that ``sex''
is the most-searched word online.
<TEXT>
<P>
   ``Sexuality is a big phenomenon in our society _ and it is
mirrored on the Internet,'' said Alvin Cooper, the San Jose
cybersex expert who conducted the survey. ``Males and females go
online for arousal, entertainment and information.''
</P>
<P>
   The ``click-and-tell'' poll's results are based on anonymous
responses from 9,000 Internet users who filled out a 47-question
survey posted on the MSNBC Web site in March and April. It asked
what they look at, who they talk to and what they get out of it.
</P>
<P>
   The poll found a healthy appetite among males for sex sites and
pornography online _ and not the seamy behavior that some people
fear is rampant online.
</P>
<P>
   Sexual activity online is a form of escapism, the survey found.
The researchers concluded that in many cases, men interested in
cybersex hole up in a back room at night, peering at nude images on
their computer screens and ignoring their partners. Women, in turn,
sometimes ignore their companions by engaging in marathon chat
sessions that sometimes escalated into romances.
</P>
<P>
   Among the survey's conclusions:
</P>
<P>
   _Five out of six people who cruise the Net for sexual material
are male.
</P>
<P>
   _Men prefer viewing sexually explicit Web sites twice as much as
women (50 percent vs. 23 percent). More than half &UR;  &LR; of the men
surveyed said they download adult-oriented material.
</P>
<P>
   ``Men don't want entanglement in a relationship,'' said
psychologist Coralie Scherer, a survey co-author. ``They just want
to look.''
</P>
<P>
   _Women were twice as likely as men to participate in chat rooms
(49 percent vs. 23 percent). More than half said they do not
download explicit material.
</P>
<P>
   ``The Net offers anonymity so women can experiment, and there is
a safety factor from rape and venereal disease,'' said Cooper,
clinical director of the San Jose Marital and Sexuality Centre. ``I
call it the `triple A' of the Internet _ access, affordability,
anonymity.''
</P>
<P>
   _Female cybersex surfers tend to be younger than their male
counterparts. Most women who responded to the poll were in the 18-
to 34-year-old age bracket (59 percent), while males were equally
divided among 18-to-34 (46 percent) and 35-to-49 (36 percent).
</P>
<P>
   _Nearly 80 percent of men and women in the poll viewed erotic
material from their home computers.
</P>
<P>
   _Both sexes admitted (61 percent) to occasionally lying online.
</P>
<P>
   Those expecting evidence of online sexual deviance and addiction
will be disappointed by the survey's results.
</P>
<P>
   A vast majority of people polled (92 percent) said they spent
less than 11 hours per week in online pursuits.
</P>
<P>
   Only 8 percent of those surveyed claim they spend more than 11
hours per week online, which would constitute addiction, according
to Cooper.
</P>
<P>
   By comparison, about 3 to 6 percent of the general population
has some form of sexually compulsive disorder, Cooper said.
</P>
<P>
   Cyberaddicts often exhibit a bumper crop of psychiatric
disorders, like manic depression and alcohol abuse, that require
treatment, said psychiatrist Nathan Shapira of the University of
Cincinnati College of Medicine.
</P>
<P>
   ``The Net is as much about sex education and information as it
is about sexual predators and pedophiles,'' Cooper said. ``This
shows that people are taking their sexual habits to the Internet.''
</P>
<P>
   Those habits include an insatiable thirst for steamy Web sites.
</P>
<P>
   According to Relevant Knowledge, a Washington, D.C.-based market
researcher, 9.6 million users, or about 15 percent of all Web
users, logged on to the 10 most popular sex sites in April.
</P>
<P>
   There are an estimated 70,000 sex-related Web sites, accounting
for a sizable chunk of the $4 billion U.S. adult-entertainment
industry.
</P>
<P>
   Although the anonymous poll guarantees confidentiality, some
question its veracity.
</P>
<P>
   Vanderbilt University business professor Donna Hoffman, a
leading online pollster, has called the self-selected survey
``scientifically worthless for drawing any useful conclusions.''
She compared it to a recent People magazine cyberpoll that named
Hank the Angry Drunken Dwarf, a cohort of radio personality Howard
Stern, as the sexiest man in America.
</P>
<P>
   ``This should be considered fun, not a scholarly research
project,'' Hoffman said.
</P>
<P>
   Others have questioned the validity of such an ambitious
undertaking. ``The poll lacks depth but perhaps has breadth,'' said
Kimberly Young, a University of Pittsburgh psychologist and author
of a book on online addiction. ``It dovetails or confirms some of
my findings, particularly that women fantasize online and men are
more visual.''
</P>
<P>
   Young interviewed 400 &UR;  &LR; people either face to face or over the
phone for her book on cyberaddiction, called ``Caught in the Net.''
</P>
<P>
   Even MSNBC officials said they posted the survey online
( &LR; www.msnbc.com &LR; ) for fun, and not to obtain hard scientific
results.
</P>
<P>
   Nonetheless, Cooper insists the survey offers an accurate
illustration of sexual browsing. He said more than 4,500 submitted
surveys were ``weeded out'' because of irregularities and
duplicated answers.
</P>
<P>
   ``Our numbers are in line with Relevant Knowledge, which is the
Nielsen of online polling,'' he said. ``Besides, people tend to be
more forthcoming about their sexual behavior in an online setting.
Sometimes it's harder to talk about HIV and other personal subjects
face to face.''
</P>
<P>
   The results will be the subject of research papers and articles
in academic journals, Cooper said.
</P>
</TEXT>
