<HEADER>
A1728 &Cx1f; ttj-z
u s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-dale-HNS &LR;      06-09 0849
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-dale-HNS </SLUG>
  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
<TEXT>
<P>
   DaleRobertson
</P>
<P>
   France is gracious &QL; 
host but little else
</P>
<P>
   &UR; c. 1998, Houston Chronicle &LR;  &QL; 
PARIS _ A teen-age house guest of mine, who portends to be France's
biggest soccer fan, inadvertently scheduled himself for an extended
stay in Houston that overlaps the start of the World Cup by almost
two weeks.
</P>
<P>
   ``What have I done?'' Romain said, grabbing his head, when I
told him of his mistake. But he recovered quickly.
</P>
<P>
   ``It is OK,'' he said, smiling. ``I will be back in time to see
France win.''
</P>
<P>
   So that's one luv-ya vote for Les Bleus, the home team for Coupe
de Monde '98, which kicks off today with Brazil vs. Scotland at the
Stade de France in the blue-collar Paris suburb of Saint-Denis,
where in pre-revolutionary times the French kings were buried.
</P>
<P>
   Speaking of dead kings, most Frenchmen view their country's
soccer chances more cynically than Romain. Although among the
planet's most rabid soccer countries and a major source of stars
for the elite clubs of Europe, France has been a miserable World
Cup failure since the competition was founded in 1930 by Jules
Rimet and Henri Delaunay.
</P>
<P>
   Who were Frenchmen, of course.
</P>
<P>
   Over the 68 years and 15 tournaments, held quadrennially except
for a 12-year hiatus around World War II, Brazil has won four World
Cups, and the West Germans and the Italians three apiece. Argentina
and Uruguay are twice champions, and England captured the one
contested on its home sod in 1966.
</P>
<P>
   Unbearable pressure
</P>
<P>
   Not only have Les Bleus _ not to be confused with Italy's
blue-jerseyed warriors, the Azzurri _ never held aloft the Cup,
they never have reached the final. And, worse, the French didn't
qualify to participate in the past two football fetes, missing out
on a trip to the United States in 1994 when they failed to beat
Israel or tie Bulgaria, losing to the latter with seconds to go.
</P>
<P>
   The next morning, the newspaper Liberation ran the headline:
``FRANCE QUALIFIES! FOR 1998!''
</P>
<P>
   Which is now. With new coach, Aime Jacquet, a lame duck and in
trouble with the other 60 million experts _ Romain included _ with
whom he shares citizenship for utilizing a cautious,
defense-oriented style, France must go forth and try to withstand
the stifling pressure of its mission improbable.
</P>
<P>
   The Italians can relate to France's hard place next to that
rock. In 1990, they were the hosts playing before a hysterical
populace. I remember being in a remote village the night of a game
and listening while every home, mostly dark except for the blue
glare of the TV, erupted in roars when an Italian player did
anything other than fall on his face. And that's what Italy,
collectively, did in the end.
</P>
<P>
   Nothing, of course, was expected of the Americans in '94 except
for them to be good sports. It was our party, but we didn't have a
big dog in the fight. Reaching the second round was a huge
accomplishment, and it will be no less of one for the U.S. team
here as well.
</P>
<P>
   The short list of championship contenders is just that: Brazil
and Argentina from South America; Germany, Italy and Spain from
Europe; and, out of Africa, Nigeria.
</P>
<P>
   Argentina defeated Brazil in a friendly and has the softest of
groups through which to play, meaning it can save energy for the
big matches. But Brazil is Brazil and Ronaldo is Ronaldo, the most
gifted and stylish of the 704 players in the tournament.
</P>
<P>
   Spain is 31-1 since the last World Cup but shares France's
problem, a lack of past successes to provide comfort in moments of
current crisis.
</P>
<P>
   The Italians have lost two key defensive specialists from the
runner-up team of '94, but they remain a heavy on historical
momentum alone. As do the Germans, who, although aging, seldom make
mistakes and have a tremendous will to win.
</P>
<P>
   Handful of favorites
</P>
<P>
   The Nigerians might not have a national mandate to win, but they
have sufficient talent. Four years ago, they came within three
minutes of beating Italy, and when they claimed the gold medal in
the '96 Olympics, they caught Brazil and Argentina from behind.
</P>
<P>
   Internal jealousies have created discord and might reduce the
Nigerians to underachieving malcontents. If not, a breakthrough
seems immiment, and fittingly so because outgoing Federation
Internationale de Football Association president Joo Havelange has
been a good friend to the African soccer federations during his
iron-willed 24-year tenure.
</P>
<P>
   Critics of the 82-year-old Brazilian say he bought African votes
to heighten his grip on soccer's governing body, but nobody can
argue he hasn't grown the competition on his watch. TV income in
1978 was $100 million; in 2002, it will be $750 million.
</P>
<P>
   Soccer is serious business, even with what must still be
described as tepid support from the United States. America's
passion for sport might be extreme but no more so than the rest of
the world's. For France, the Coupe de Monde '98, is certain to be a
source of intense national pride yet, ultimately, severe national
angst.
</P>
<P>
   Sorry, Romain. But bonchance anyway.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
