<DOCTYPE> MISCELLANEOUS TEXT (slug-filter) </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-06-09 22:05 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A1738 &Cx1f; ttf-z
u f &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-PHOTO-FULL-UPDATE-NYT     06-09 1276
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-PHOTO-FULL-UPDATE-NYT </SLUG>
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATTENTION EDITORS: The following photos are part of tonight's
New York Times Photo Package, moving 6/09/98. Photo clients will
automatically receive these photos via AP's PhotoExpress or may
download them from either the Wieck Photo Database in Dallas at
972-392-0888 or from NYTPhotos on Newscom at 305-448-8411.
Non-clients can make individual purchases by calling 212-556-4204.
</P>
<P>
   (NYT16) ELLENVILLE, N.Y. -- June 9, 1998 -- NY-CATSKILLS-COMIC,
6-09 -- Allan Tresser, a Catskills fixture and feuder, shows off
his moves. Tresser, the 77-year-old ``tummler,'' has been
entertaining hotel guests in the Catskills for nearly 60 years and
is self-proclaimed king of Simon Says. (Librado Romero/New York
Times Photo)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT15) NEW YORK -- June 9, 1998 -- VOUCHERS-EDUC, 6-09 --
Public-school children present a card to two benefactors, Theodore
Forstmann, left, and John Walton. A group of business leaders
pledged Tuesday to raise $200 million for a national voucher
program that would permit at least 50,000 inner-city public-school
children to attend parochial and other private schools over the
next four years. (Angel Franco/New York Times Photo)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT14) SALT LAKE CITY -- June 9, 1998 -- BAPTISTS, 6-09 -- The
Gestes Family praying on the first day of the Southern Baptist
Convention at the Salt Palace in Salt Lake City: from left, Joanie,
Caleb, 4, Clay, 8 and Jackie, the father. The convention amended
its essential statement of beliefs Tuesday to include a declaration
that a woman should ``submit herself graciously'' to her husband's
leadership and a husband should ``provide for, protect and lead his
family.'' (Monica Almeida/New York Times Photo)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT13) BALTIMORE -- June 9, 1998 -- BEST-HON, 6-09 -- At
center, the big-haired winner of the recent fifth-annual Best Hon
contest in Baltimore. Hons are as much a part of Baltimore's
cultural landscape as crab cakes, the Orioles and Harbor Place.
They have earned their sociological niche for greeting friends and
strangers alike the same way Q ``Howya doin', Hon?'' Q and speaking
in ``Bawlmerese,'' a dialect indigenous to the area and virtually
unknown anywhere else. (Marty Katz/New York Times Photo) *LITE
</P>
<P>
   (NYT12) PITTSBURGH -- June 9, 1998 -- AIRPORT-MALLS-2, 6-09 --
Some passengers pass by without sampling the wares at the
Pittsburgh airport mall. In the last few years, dozens of national
retailers have opened airport shops, invading what has long been
the domain of newsstands, duty-free shops and the occasional live
lobster stand by establishing small outposts of the Gap, Victoria's
Secret and the like. Such stores are joined by a full array of food
chains, including Starbucks and Legal Sea Foods. (Scott
Goldsmith/New York Times Photo)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT11) PITTSBURGH -- June 9, 1998 -- AIRPORT-MALLS-1, 6-09 --
Some passengers relax in the Brookstone store at the Pittsburgh
airport mall. In the last few years, dozens of national retailers
have opened airport shops, invading what has long been the domain
of newsstands, duty-free shops and the occasional live lobster
stand by establishing small outposts of the Gap, Victoria's Secret
and the like. Such stores are joined by a full array of food
chains, including Starbucks and Legal Sea Foods. (Scott
Goldsmith/New York Times Photo)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT10) WASHINGTON -- June 9, 1998 -- KOREA-U.S., 6-09 --
Presidents Clinton and Kim Dae Jung at a welcoming ceremony at the
White House on Tuesday. Clinton compared Kim to former protesters
and political prisoners like Lech Walesa, Vaclav Havel and Nelson
Mandela. (Stephen Crowley/New York Times Photo)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT9) UNDATED -- June 9, 1998 -- CLOTHIERS-SUIT, 6-09 --
Abercrombie &AMP; Fitch has filed a lawsuit contending that American
Eagle has engaged in a ``deliberate and intentional pattern of
copying the Abercrombie brand.'' An example from exhibit 4 in the
lawsuit shows similar sets of shirts, belts and baseball caps from
Abercrombie &AMP; Fitch, left, and American Eagle, right. (Jack
Manning/New York Times Photo) *LITE
</P>
<P>
   (NYT8) BOSTON -- June 9, 1998 -- MAASAI-WARRIOR-BOS, 6-09 -- Ole
Tome, whose U.S. base is in York, Maine, stands out in downtown
Boston during a recent visit. His mission: to educate the Western
world about the Maasai culture by giving lectures, and to raise
money. ``We Maasai walk everywhere,'' he says. ``That's why we are
so long and skinny and have no heart disease.'' (Tom Herde/Boston
Globe Photo) *LITE
</P>
<P>
   (NYT7) NEW YORK -- June 8, 1998 -- FRANCE-TURBOT-2, 6-8 -- After
the trip accross the Atlantic in dry, styrofoam boxes the turbot
flutter back to life once in the tanks at the Imperial Seafood in
Chinatown. The France Turbot company has been able to keep some
turbot alive for 40 hours out of water, but its goal is less
ambitious. It guarantes a 100 percent survival rate after 24 hours,
so that the fish can easily make the 18-hour journey from Paris to
Tokyo. (Ed Quinn/New York Times Photo)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT6) NEW YORK -- June 8, 1998 -- FRANCE-TURBOT-1, 6-8 -- Live
turbot arrive at Imperial Seafood in Chinatown. In France the fish
are put, one by one, into dry styrofoam boxes and transported to
the United States. Unlike some fish, when turbot are out of water,
they can absorb up to 40 percent of their oxygen through their
skin. (Ed Quinn/New York Times Photo)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT5) NEW YORK -- June 8, 1998 -- BABY-BROCCOLI, 6-8 --
Brocoletti and broccolini goes by several aliases, but this small
tender broccoli hybrid, available year-round, has the appealing
tenderness of a spring green. Unlike with conventional broccoli,
the edible part is not the stalk, but only the tender side shoots.
Unlike its larger ancestor, which is harvested once a season,
broccolini is harvested five times a year and is therefore more
like a firm, yet pliant sprout. (Boyd Hagen/New York Times Photo)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT4) NEW YORK -- June 8, 1998 -- NY-PIZZA-RENAISSANCE, 6-8 --
At Angelo's on West 57th Street in Manhattan, pizza is a family
affair. In April the Angelis-Tsoulos clan combined forces and
opened Angelo's. They are just one of the three families
responsible for a pizza renaissance in New York. (Suzanne
DeChillo/New York Times Photo)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT3) BERKLEY, Calif -- June 8, 1998 -- LOUVRE-RESTURANT, 6-8
-- Alice Waters enjoys a glass of wine at the Chez Panisse's
outdoor bar. Ms. Waters, whose restaurant has become a shrine to
American cooking, has been asked to open a 330-seat restaurant at
the Louvre in Paris. ``I am very happy because I have heard very
good comments about Alice Waters,'' says France's only six-star
chef, Alain Ducasse. (Jim Wilson/New York Times Photo) *LITE
</P>
<P>
   (NYT2) LOS ANGELES -- June 8, 1998 -- SPAGO, 6-8 -- Wolfgang
Puck samples some of his own work at his new Spago in Beverly
Hills, Calif. The new Spago is considerably less casual than the
first Spago which opened in West Hollywood in early 1982. Yet,
Puck, a classically trained French chef, continues to reinvent food
and once more proves that American dining is coming of age. (Susan
Werner/New York Times Photo) *LITE
</P>
<P>
   (NYT1) HOUSTON -- June 8, 1998 -- HABITAT-PRISONERS-HNS, 6-8 --
Inmate Ray Williams hammers together interior walls for houses at
the Habitat for Humanity warehouse in north Houston. More than two
dozen Texas inmates will be part of the 6,000 volunteers who will
be building 100 houses next week in the Houston area. As part of
the weeklong project, 25 Texas inmates from Jester Unit II in
nearby Huntsville will build one of the homes. (Kirk Wagner/Houston
Chronicle Photo)
</P>
<P>
   The New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
