<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-GRAIN-RESCUE-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
RESCUERS CLAW THROUGH MOUNTAIN OF GRAIN  
 (JT) 
</HEADLINE>
   c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   WICHITA, Kan. _ While anxious family members waited and prayed,
dozens of rescue workers desperately dug through tons of grain and
debris on Tuesday in search of four men who were trapped after an
explosion at one of the world's largest grain elevators in this
Midwestern city.
</P>
<P>
   Eighty rescue workers made their way to a 200-foot area in one
of four tunnels at the bottom of the elevator, using shovels and a
grain vacuum to clear a path.
</P>
<P>
   The four missing men were believed to be working in that area at
the time of the explosion on Monday, and search dogs reinforced the
belief that humans were in the area.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm relatively confident there are spaces in between grain
piles and debris,'' said Kenneth Cox, division chief of the
Sedgwick County Fire Department. ``We've got a good chance of
bringing them in alive.''
</P>
<P>
   Rescuers were faced with tons of rubble and grain as they
searched for the missing workers. Two people died in the grain-dust
explosion, which is believed to have occurred when a spark ignited
dust suspended in the air, at the DeBruce Grain elevator.
</P>
<P>
   The explosion occurred about 9:20 a.m. central time on Monday.
It shook homes miles away and left 11 people injured.
</P>
<P>
   The complex, which has a capacity of 24 million bushels, had
been cited at least twice in the last few years for excessive grain
dust by inspectors from the U.S. Agriculture Department.
</P>
<P>
   The Occupational Safety and Health Administration sent
investigators to the scene Tuesday, and a local official said the
agency had not been notified of the Agriculture Department's
earlier findings.
</P>
<P>
   ``I wish we had been,'' said Thomas Marple, area director for
the federal safety agency. ``We might have been able to do
something about it before the explosion.''
</P>
<P>
   Searchers have been focusing on 800 feet of a 1,600-foot tunnel.
As of Tuesday night, less than 200 feet was left to be excavated,
Cox said. Progress was slower Tuesday than Monday because rescue
workers had to resort to a different method of shoring up the
ceiling of the tunnel.
</P>
<P>
   The families of the four missing men, who were described by
officials as maintenance workers, stood by at Oatville Elementary
School to get updates on the search for their loved ones. Some sat
outside at picnic tables in the afternoon sunlight, waiting for
word. Every two hours, the families heard from officials, who then
briefed reporters.
</P>
<P>
   ``They're anxious to see what's going on,'' said the Rev. Dave
Castleberry, minister of the Glenn Park Christian Church in
Wichita.
</P>
<P>
   ``They're optimistic. We're on the same boat and we're
encouraging one another. ``There are tears off and on. We're all
trying to get through it. We're praying constantly.''
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
