<HEADER>
A1753 &Cx1f; taf-z
s e &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-ARCHITECTURE-VINOLY-$     06-09 1224
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-ARCHITECTURE-VINOLY-$ADV14-750&AMP;ADD-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
GLASS: IT CAN COVER A CASSEROLE, AND ALSO ENCHANT AN EYE 
</HEADLINE>
   (For release Sunday, June 14.)  
 (JT)  
 By HERBERT MUSCHAMP    
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   It is easy to laugh at the utopian fervor with which early
20th-century architects championed the use of glass. ``The face of
the earth would be much altered if brick architecture were ousted
everywhere by glass architecture,'' wrote the poet Paul Scheerbart,
a cheerleader for the so-called Glass Chain, a group of
Expressionist architects whose belief in glass was virtually
religious. ``We should then have a paradise on earth, and no need
to watch in longing expectation for the paradise in heaven.''
</P>
<P>
   What a chucklehead! But then you go cruising around town in a
car with a moon roof, or visit a house with a glass-enclosed
atrium, your mood naturally brightens, and you realize: Scheerbart,
Bruno Taut, Walter Gropius and their fellow glass fanatics weren't
such fools.
</P>
<P>
   A new project by Henry Smith-Miller and Laurie Hawkinson goes
far toward recapturing the early modern enthusiasm for glass. A
remodeling and expansion of the Corning Glass Center in Corning, N.
Y., the Smith-Miller &AMP; Hawkinson design is not large in scale. But
it restores an aura of enchantment to a material that has become
commonplace and to a period of architecture that, not long ago, had
fallen out of style.
</P>
<P>
   The centerpiece of Corning's corporate campus, just west of
Elmira, N.Y., the Glass Center was designed in 1951 by Wallace
Harrison of Harrison &AMP; Abramowitz, architect of the Metropolitan
Opera House, the United Nations Headquarters and other New York
landmarks. Originally, the center consisted of just two buildings,
joined in an L-shape. One of these was the Steuben factory, an
industrial shed capped with a flaring ventilator roof, where all of
Steuben's glittering glassware is produced to this day. Attached to
the shed was a low, International Style glass box that housed a
glass museum and other attractions.
</P>
<P>
   Remember the Lens? If you grew up in the fifties, you may well
have a memory of it tucked away somewhere: the gigantic reflecting
lens made by Corning for the telescope at Mount Palomar
Observatory. The disk came out of the oven with flaws, so its
mirrored surface was never polished. Instead, the lens became the
Glass Center's iconic exhibition. Its roundness and honeycomb
structure were ominous, a spooky mandala of modern science, while
the flaws gave it the quality of a Japanese object of meditation.
You couldn't tell if this was the eye of humankind staring at the
heavens, or the other way around.
</P>
<P>
   The juxtaposition of the Glass Center's two structures told a
story: how modern architecture evolved from the industrial
vernacular of sheds, factories, greenhouses. Like a vase blown from
a lump of molten sand, culture could be fashioned from raw matter.
The culture here was corporate at its most benign. Besides the
museum, the center contained a library, a small theater for musical
performances, even a bowling alley for Corning employees. This was
the statement of an enlightened company in a company town.
</P>
<P>
   The loveliest feature of Harrison's design was a round
courtyard, enclosed by (naturally) the world's largest curved glass
sheets. A small fish pond was fitted with a glass bottom, which
helped to illuminate the cafeteria one floor below. For a time,
this was the place to lunch in Corning: a light, lucid, open space
for the postwar way of life.
</P>
<P>
   This style of gracious modern living did not survive the 1960s.
Eventually, the cafeteria was moved to another part of the campus,
the courtyard covered over. Other assaults on the Glass Center's
integrity came from outside. A highway-widening program paved over
the ends of the center's original curved driveway, leaving its
entrance ramp flapping in the wind.
</P>
<P>
   Soon, the clarity that was the point of the entire exercise had
been forgotten. In 1972, the Michigan architect Gunnar Birkerts was
hired to design a new building for the glass museum and library. A
silvery-skinned structure with a curvilinear, free-form shape, the
museum wraps around one corner of Harrison's building like a giant
glass-eating amoeba.
</P>
<P>
   The Glass Center's decline mirrored that of the movement that
produced it. But Smith-Miller and Hawkinson's plan, while deeply
sympathetic to Harrison's, should not be mistaken for a modernist
revival. Instead of restoring Harrison's building, they have
rethought the Glass Center in contemporary terms. The guiding idea
seems to be: If it's broken, break it some more.
</P>
<P>
   Smith-Miller and Hawkinson were initially hired four years ago
to create a temporary exhibition gallery in a corner of Harrison's
building. On the basis of that project, they were invited to expand
and remodel the entire center. The plan is being constructed in
phases and is to be completed in May.
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   The plan's most prominent architectural features are two slim,
glazed additions, clamped to the east and west sides of Harrison's
building like a pair of faceted quartz bookends. The western
addition, now completed, contains a lobby for a new auditorium, a
cafe and overhead corridors that link the Steuben factory to the
Birkerts building. More important, the addition creates a visual
and spatial whole out of the center's three structures. The
addition's irregularly angled facade serves as a poised, push-pull
mediator between the existing buildings' volumes and voids.
</P>
<P>
   The addition to the east side of Harrison's building is somewhat
larger and will contain the center's main entrance lobby and an
orientation theater. Sheer formal exuberance, however, is this
addition's chief function: the play of reflections and the glimpses
of light and space within as visitors pull up along a new sloping
driveway. Here, as in Jean Nouvel's Cartier Foundation in Paris,
the objective is to expand the expressive properties of glass by
extending sheets of it beyond the building envelope. At Corning,
the effect is heightened by the angling of the wall's segments. The
angles insure that the glass is seen not only as three-dimensional
planes but as two-dimensional edges.
</P>
<P>
   In the 750-seat auditorium, glass is visible only in the light
bulbs. But the faceting motif continues in the acoustical baffles,
wooden panels that stretch across the upper side walls in sharp,
angular folds. Beneath the wood, panels of unpolished green-gray
serpentine stone wrap the lower part of the hall in a discreet
mineral frame.
</P>
<P>
   ``If brick architecture were ousted everywhere ... '' Polemical
phrases like Scheerbart's help explain the conventional view that
modern architects were out to sabotage tradition. But as Smith
Miller and Hawkinson's design makes clear, they have been among its
most dedicated custodians throughout this century. There is a Glass
Chain that runs from Joseph Paxton to Taut to Mies van der Rohe to
Harrison to Nouvel to David Chipperfield to Toyo Ito and beyond. No
other architects of this century have displayed more vibrantly such
traditional qualities as lucidity, harmony, wholeness, scale,
procession and the creativity necessary to renew their continuity
from one generation to the next. At Glass Center 2000, the chain
goes on.
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
