</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BKN-JAZZ-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
AFTER ITS RAPID DEMISE, JAZZ SEEKS RESURRECTION 
</HEADLINE>
  (jt) 
 By MIKE WISE    
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   CHICAGO _ Four days ago, they were the most economical and
efficient team in basketball. One minute away from putting Michael
Jordan's team in a two-game hole on its home floor, the Utah Jazz
appeared to have all the artillery necessary to end the Chicago
Bulls' championship reign.
</P>
<P>
   Now, Karl Malone and John Stockton are 48 minutes away from
going down, 3-1, and being devoured by the Bulls. They will take
the United Center floor on Wednesday night for Game 4 of the league
championship series searching for their confidence and anything
resembling an offense.
</P>
<P>
   ``We don't have to be told that tomorrow is a must-win game,''
the reserve center Greg Foster said on Tuesday. ``You can sense it
and feel it. Giving away another game would be like giving up our
hopes of winning a title.''
</P>
<P>
   In the worst loss in finals history, a 96-54 defeat in Game 3,
Utah scored the fewest points in a National Basketball Association
game _ playoffs or regular season _ since the inception of the shot
clock in 1954.
</P>
<P>
   After leading by 1 point with less than a minute remaining in
Game 2 before falling to the Bulls, the Jazz has essentially gone
from putting Chicago on the ropes to desperately needing a victory
on Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
   The Bulls, meanwhile, have no intention of going back to Salt
Lake City for either Game 6 or 7, preferring to end the series in
five games on Friday in Chicago.
</P>
<P>
   ``We've always responded well after a tough loss like that, so
there's no reason to think any different,'' Malone said. ``I like
our attitude now.''
</P>
<P>
   Indeed, the Jazz has dealt with adversity well in the playoffs
this season. Utah was down, two games to one, to the Houston
Rockets in a three-of-five-game first-round series. The Jazz
rebounded and won in five games on its home floor. In the second
round, Utah was annihilated by San Antonio in Game 3 at the
Alamodome before coming back to win Game 4 and close the Spurs out
in Game 5.
</P>
<P>
   But that was Houston and San Antonio. This is Jordan, Scottie
Pippen and the ring dynasty. If the Bulls win Game 4, Chicago will
almost be assured of winning its sixth title in eight seasons.
</P>
<P>
   ``If we can create distance between them and us, we can put
ourselves a step closer,'' Jordan said. ``We can put them closer,
put their backs closer to the wall, put them in a panic
situation.''
</P>
<P>
   The Bulls have made the necessary adjustments after a Game 1
loss in overtime, letting Pippen play off his man and operate as a
roving help defender. Dennis Rodman has plastered himself on
Malone's elbow, and no one on the Jazz roster has been able to
contend with Jordan physically.
</P>
<P>
   About the only good news for the Jazz going into Wednesday's
game was that its power forward did not skip practice on Monday to
hang out with Hulk Hogan and a cast of professional wrestlers in
Detroit. Rodman is indeed at it again.
</P>
<P>
   Chicago's irascible forward caused so much of a distraction by
skipping practice and flying to Detroit on Monday to participate in
a World Championship Wrestling extravaganza, the parties involved
almost forgot they had a game to play on Wednesday night at the
United Center.
</P>
<P>
   While Coach Phil Jackson and the Bulls welcomed their wayward
forward back with open arms, Jerry Sloan and the Jazz simply could
not relate. Instead of dealing with how they might recover from
their record loss, Sloan and his team wondered aloud how a
flamboyant role player could make a mockery of the league
championship series.
</P>
<P>
   Asked how he would discipline Rodman for his latest
transgression, ``First of all, I wouldn't have him,'' Sloan said.
``That's what makes the question real simple, because Dennis,
everybody knows what he's about. Winning has never been that
important to me. I'd just as soon lose if I had to be put in that
situation.
</P>
<P>
   ``There are things I can deal with. Guys have a problem once in
a while, I can deal with that. But I can't deal with it when
winning is the only thing there is.''
</P>
<P>
   Though the Bulls and the NBA were each planning to fine Rodman
$10,000, the implication from the Jazz seemed to be that the Bulls
organization was letting Rodman make a mockery of the finals, that
Chicago would put winning before proper, old-school decorum.
</P>
<P>
   ``We always talk about where this league is going without
Michael Jordan,'' Sloan said. ``I think it's important to realize,
if we want it to go in the other direction, where there is no
discipline and no respect, then those things will be important. To
me, they aren't. I know how corny it sounds, but when that is more
important than the game itself, we've lost our whole reason for
being here.''
</P>
<P>
   The Bulls were not buying that theory. Jackson said, ``In the
end result, Dennis always comes back and tries extra hard to
please.''
</P>
<P>
   Bulls center Luc Longley said: ``I like having Dennis as a
teammate. The things he's brought to this team are far greater than
anything he is taking away from the team. Some of those long road
trips, he spices it up a little. He's a good bloke to have
around.''
</P>
<P>
   Longley added: ``Anyway, aren't we supposed to be talking about
basketball today? I would think Game 4 is fairly huge for the Jazz,
wouldn't you?''
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
