<HEADLINE>
SUDDENLY METS FANS CAN BE HEARD 
</HEADLINE>
  (ja) 
 By DAVE ANDERSON   
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ When the ``Let's Go, Mets'' chant was heard in recent
years, it too often was a waste of loyal lungs. Most of those Mets
teams usually didn't go anywhere except down to the dungeons of the
National League East.
</P>
<P>
   It's all different now. Mike Piazza's arrival nearly three weeks
ago suddenly provided Mets fans everywhere with a rebirth, with a
contender to root for, a team to believe in. Bobby Valentine
noticed this on the recent road trip through Florida, Philadelphia,
Pittsburgh and Boston.
</P>
<P>
   ``That's the first time,'' the Mets' manager recalled, ``that
I've heard the `Let's Go, Mets' chant on the road before it was
drowned out by the local fans.''
</P>
<P>
   But when Valentine heard it at Shea Stadium during Tuesday
night's game with the Tampa Bay Devil Rays, it wasn't drowned out.
It got louder as Hideo Nomo spun out of his corkscrew windup for
the first time in a Mets uniform.
</P>
<P>
   With the Dodgers, the 29-year-old right-hander's record was 2-7
with a 5.05 earned run average. Piazza, his Dodger catcher for more
than three seasons, described Nomo's problems there as ``walking
guys, big-inning trouble.''
</P>
<P>
   Over five innings Tuesday night, Nomo's performance was not much
different: four runs, five hits, five strikeouts, three walks, a
wild pitch and a balk.
</P>
<P>
   About three hours before the game, Nomo was sitting at his
locker, his back turned. He was reading a scouting report on the
Devil Ray hitters. At the next locker, Masato Yoshii was asked if
the report was in English or Japanese.
</P>
<P>
   ``In English,'' Yoshii said through his interpreter, Bobby
Norton, ``but basically, it's in Baseball.''
</P>
<P>
   As if Baseball were an international language. But more and
more, of course, it is. More and more Latin American major leaguers
speak it. So do Nomo, Yoshii and the Yankees' Japanese import,
Hideki Irabu.
</P>
<P>
   ``Nomo is a good competitor,'' Valentine said. ``He's got a good
fastball, a good forkball. I hope he's a good teammate. I just
don't know yet.''
</P>
<P>
   But the Mets' manager didn't consider the difference in real
language (as opposed to the language of Baseball) as a determining
factor in a ballplayer being a good teammate. To him, real language
is the least important factor.
</P>
<P>
   ``The first thing is the willingness to be a teammate,''
Valentine said. ``With pitchers, when they're out there together in
batting practice, that's when you see some kind of togetherness.
</P>
<P>
   ``The other time is when there's a good play behind or when he
makes a bad pitch _ whether he's with them and they're with him.
Yoshii is good that way. He has a lot of traits that help people.''
</P>
<P>
   On a Mets staff that is the National League's best with a 3.02
earned run average, Yoshii has a 4-2 record, Rick Reed is 7-3, Al
Leiter 6-3 and Bobby Jones 5-3. Reed had a perfect game through 20
batters against the Devil Rays on Monday night before Wade Boggs'
double over center fielder Brian McRae's head.
</P>
<P>
   ``When Rick's not pitching, he really watches hitters during a
game,'' Valentine said. ``He watches their feet, their swing, their
reaction to certain pitches.''
</P>
<P>
   But more than anything else, Reed's control and command of his
three pitches has made him a potential member of the National
League team for the July 7 All-Star Game in Colorado.
</P>
<P>
   ``The one thing he's always been able to do consistently is
throw the ball over the plate,'' Valentine said. ``He doesn't walk
many people. And he has three pitches that complement each other.
</P>
<P>
   ``He has a fastball that will break to the outside part of a
left-handed batter's strike zone. He has a slider or a cutter that,
if he throws it to the center of the plate, will break to the
outside of a right-handed batter's strike zone. And he has a change
of pace that will break down.
</P>
<P>
   ``If you're the batter, when the ball is out there,'' Valentine
said, pointing a few feet away, ``you don't know where the ball is
going. One goes this way, one goes that way and one stops.''
</P>
<P>
   But for the Mets, the best is yet to come _ the three-game
series with the Yankees that begins two weeks from Friday at Shea
and the National League wild-card race with the Cubs, Astros,
Giants and Padres. If the Mets qualify, it would be the first time
that both the Yankees and the Mets were in the post-season playoffs
together.
</P>
<P>
   Even Yankee fans should be chanting, ``Let's Go, Mets.'' In any
language. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
