<SLUG> BC-BKC-RHODEN-COLUMN-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
SPORTS COLUMN: AT ST. JOHN'S, A NEW ERA REQUIRES A BIG NAME  
 (JT) 
</HEADLINE>
   By WILLIAM C. RHODEN    
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   There was a split second of hesitation on the other end of the
line. Eric Barkley, the all-America guard who will attend St.
John's in September, learned that he might be the linchpin for a
new coach's championship aspirations.
</P>
<P>
   Mike Jarvis, the man St. John's wants to hire as its new head
basketball coach, wants to win a national title. Championships
begin at the point. Barkley is expected to be the man at the point.
</P>
<P>
   ``Hey, I want that, too,'' Barkley said. ``I never think about
me being a key part to a national championship team. But if he's
willing to go that far, I am, too. Let's go.''
</P>
<P>
   Barkley had an early introduction to the realities of big-time
basketball last month when Fran Fraschilla, who recruited him and
attended some of his games at Maine Central Institute, was suddenly
dismissed as the St. John's coach.
</P>
<P>
   No one from the school called Barkley in advance. He was
browsing the Internet when he learned of the dismissal. ``At first
I didn't believe it, because you cant believe everything you
read,'' he said. ``Then I went to my room and I saw it on ESPN. I
was just surprised.''
</P>
<P>
   Barkley rushed to see his coach, Max Good, and told him he was
transferring. ``I panicked a little,'' he said on Tuesday by
telephone from Maine. ``I was shocked, you know, Coach Fran being
as he had two years on his contract. I thought he would at least
get the chance to coach me. So when it happened, I just panicked.
Immediately, I didn't want to go there.''
</P>
<P>
   Good told him to relax, to think about it. He thought about it,
and decided to come anyway. ``I wanted to honor my commitment,'' he
said. ``I didn't want people to think I don't honor my commitment.
And my mother really wanted me to go there.''
</P>
<P>
   Barkley left Maine for New York Tuesday night, and Wednesday
afternoon he will head over to St. John's and meet with his
teammates. But as of Tuesday night, they were an army without a
general.
</P>
<P>
   In a bizarre chase for a high-profile coach, St. John's has
backed itself into a corner; wrapped in a veil of silence, it has
put itself in a situation where it cannot lose, but cannot win,
either. If it hires a successful, high-profile coach, it runs the
risk of losing him to the National Basketball Association after a
few seasons. If it hires a hot up-and-coming coach, it risks losing
him to a program perceived to be on a higher level.
</P>
<P>
   What it wants to do with Jarvis is establish itself as one of
those programs at the highest level.
</P>
<P>
   Mike Jarvis is asking for $800,000; St. John's has spent the
last week or so devising ways to give it to him, which would
effectively make him the highest-paid coach in St. John's history
and one of the highest paid in the Big East Conference. There were
excellent younger candidates, Paul Hewitt at Siena and Bob McKillop
at Davidson.
</P>
<P>
   Barkley said he preferred a new name. ``I like the underdog
coaches,'' he said. ``The underdog always wins. Look at St. John's.
They were the underdogs, they made it to the tournament. The
high-profile coach will come in with a lot of pressure. He's got to
take everything under control. Some players may not accept that.
</P>
<P>
   ``By his salary being that much, he's going to want us to be,
like perfect. I'm ready to accept it. I'm ready to play. I'm just
worried about the other players. Are they with me? Ron is with me,
definitely, Glover, definitely, Tyrone.''
</P>
<P>
   He was referring to his future teammates, Ron Artest, Tyrone
Grant and the incoming freshman Anthony Glover.
</P>
<P>
   ``Basically we're just going to be a target,'' Barkley said.
``Everybody's going to be out to get us,''
</P>
<P>
   An official familiar with the negotiations said that Jarvis
wants to be able to compete for the national championship; he
cannot do that at George Washington. He feels he can do it at St.
John's, in a high-profile city and a high-pressure conference.
</P>
<P>
   The instant the contract is signed, St. John's will have
catapulted itself out of the mom-and-pop phase of the business and
into the new millennium. New arenas, escalated women's program.
High octane.
</P>
<P>
   Barkley is ready to play. The Fraschilla firing, Barkley said,
``went through one ear and out the other.''
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm not going to be depressed or let a coach bring down my
career and my future status because he got fired,'' Barkley said.
``That's between him and the school.''
</P>
<P>
   But the incoming freshman admitted that this first dose of
reality hit him a little in the heart. ``Yeah, it did a little
bit,'' Barkley said. ``But life goes on. I got to move on.''
</P>
<P>
   The deed is nearly done. St. John's, for better or for worse,
begins a new era with a new coach. The old standard of judging
whether a coach and a school are compatible is no longer relevant.
In an age of mega-marketing, when eyes are glued to the ratings, a
high profile is tantamount to the right fit.
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-06-09-98 2220EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
