<SLUG> BC-BOEING-SLOWDOWN-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
ASIAN CRISIS FORCES NEW CUTS AT BOEING
</HEADLINE>
   (ja) 
 By LAURENCE ZUCKERMAN    
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   The Boeing Co. announced on Tuesday that weakening demand in
Asia would force it to cut production of its wide-body jets even
deeper than the company had previously indicated, resulting in
further job cuts.
</P>
<P>
   Boeing, the world's biggest aerospace company and the country's
leading exporter, said it would cut production of the 747 jumbo jet
by 30 percent early next year rather than the 20 percent reduction
it had hinted at two weeks ago. It will also cut production of the
newer 777 to five a month from seven a month.
</P>
<P>
   The move surprised Wall Street analysts who follow Boeing
because only a month ago the company was saying that strong orders
for the 777 might force it to raise the rate above seven a month.
</P>
<P>
   ``Things must be moving fairly quickly for this to come out in
the form it has,'' said Byron Callan, an analyst at Merrill Lynch &AMP;
Co. in New York.
</P>
<P>
   The 747, which carries more than 400 passengers, is the biggest
commercial jet on the market and is Boeing's most profitable
airplane by a wide margin. But it is mostly used to fly over the
Pacific Ocean to and from Asia. Since an economic crisis began to
sweep over much of Asia nearly a year ago, air traffic has plunged
and many airlines have delayed orders for new airplanes.
</P>
<P>
   ``The continued slow traffic growth in Asia has caused some
airlines to negotiate slides in deliveries of their 1999 747 orders
or to substitute other Boeing airplane models for their existing
747 orders,'' said Fred Mitchell, Boeing's executive vice president
of airplane production.
</P>
<P>
   Boeing said it would reduce production of the 747 to 3.5 a month
in the second quarter of 1999 from its current rate of five a
month.
</P>
<P>
   The Seattle-based company has been plagued by problems since
last fall, when it was forced to halt production on the 747 and
narrow-body 737 jets because it did not have enough parts and
experienced workers to assemble the planes fast enough. The
production difficulties have since forced the company to take
billions of dollars in charges against earnings.
</P>
<P>
   The great fear on Wall Street was that by the time Boeing
recovered the boom in demand for new jets that began in 1996 would
begin to subside. That sequence of events may appear to be coming
to pass, though many analysts believe that strong demand for new
aircraft will continue.
</P>
<P>
   Boeing said Tuesday that demand for its narrow-body planes,
especially the latest version of the 737, the world's most popular
commercial jetliner, remained strong. That is an indication of the
continued strength of the economies in Europe and North America,
where a larger number of smaller planes are used than in Asia.
</P>
<P>
   The production-cutback announcement came after the stock market
had closed. Boeing shares rose 25 cents, to $46, on the New York
Stock Exchange.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
