<HEADLINE>
FORMER SALOMON CHIEF TO REJOIN LAW FIRM THAT REPRESENTS BUFFETT 
</HEADLINE>
  (th) 
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   Robert Denham, the former chairman and chief executive of
Salomon Inc., will rejoin Munger, Tolles &AMP; Olson, the Los Angeles
law firm where he long served as the primary lawyer for Berkshire
Hathaway Inc., headed by Warren Buffett.
</P>
<P>
   Denham, 52, joined Salomon as general counsel in 1991 in the
wake of a bond-trading scandal. He became chairman and chief
executive the next year, serving in that position until Travelers
Group bought Salomon late last year.
</P>
<P>
   As a partner at Munger, Tolles, Denham will specialize in
mergers and acquisitions and financial regulation. He also plans to
resume his old duties as one of Buffett's lawyers and,
unofficially, as Buffett's investment banker and financial adviser.
</P>
<P>
   Buffett does not rely heavily on investment banks to arrange
acquisitions or help determine fair prices for his investments,
preferring to keep that work in-house, Denham said. As a result,
his lawyers often assume some duties normally associated with
bankers. &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
