<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BEST-HON-ART-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
BALTIMORE JOURNAL: THE HONS LINGER ON 
</HEADLINE>
   (ART ADV: Photo has been sent to NYT photo clients. Non-subscribers
can make individual purchase by calling 212-556-4204.)  
 (JT)  
 By MICHAEL JANOFSKY    
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   BALTIMORE _ The crowd grew quiet, knowing a solemn moment was
finally at hand. Pamela Foresman stepped forward. These were her
final minutes as Baltimore's Best Hon, the title she won at the
Cafe Hon last year.
</P>
<P>
   ``My reign may be over,'' Ms. Foresman said, handing a bouquet
of flowers to Sharon Gill, her successor. ``But once a Hon, always
a Hon.''
</P>
<P>
   OK, so what is a Hon, and why are they beloved enough that 200
people would spend a nice weekend afternoon in a restaurant parking
lot to celebrate their existence?
</P>
<P>
   Fact is, Hons are as much a part of Baltimore's cultural
landscape as crab cakes, the Orioles and Harbor Place. They have
earned their sociological niche for greeting friends and strangers
alike the same way _ ``Howya doin', Hon?'' _and speaking in
``Bawlmerese,'' a dialect indigenous to the area and virtually
unknown anywhere else.
</P>
<P>
   At the recent fifth-annual Best Hon contest, Ms. Gill, a
44-year-old legal secretary, defeated two other contestants with
her quintessential Hon look: black stretch pants, faux tiger-skin
shirt, high-heeled sandals and wildly teased hair that takes her as
long as ``two arries'' _ translation from Bawlmerese, two hours _
to set properly in place.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is my very first booty pageant,'' she told adoring fans.
</P>
<P>
   Of course, the accent, with its mangled vowel sounds and
fractured syntax, is not limited to Hons. Included in the day's
festivities was the Best Bawlmerese contest, in which one man sang
``Home on the Range,'' where in his version ``the deer and the
cantaloupe'' play. Finishing first was a pair of beehived
11-year-old Honchkins _ Chiari Lattanzi and Leah Platek _ who sang
a hilarious Bawlmerese version of ``My Heart Will Go On,'' the
theme song from the film ``Titanic.''
</P>
<P>
   The filmmaker John Waters has made a career of feasting on the
idiosyncrasies of Hons, setting ``Pink Flamingoes'' and
``Hairspray'' in the Baltimore neighborhoods he knew growing up.
All his characters speak in Bawlmerese, and many of his female
characters dress like Hons.
</P>
<P>
   But Hons and Bawlmerese seem harder to find now. As Baltimore
has polished its image with downtown redevelopment, new hotels,
first-class sports stadiums and reborn commercial centers, the Hon
life style, like the old, working-class neighborhoods that spawned
them, is slipping into the shadows of progress.
</P>
<P>
   Here in Hamden, a central neighborhood that was once a hotbed of
Hons and their families, the main thoroughfare, 36th Street, has
taken a decidedly upscale turn in the last few years, with new
restaurants, boutiques and refurbished row houses.
</P>
<P>
   ``Main Streets are making a comeback, not just here but all
across the country,'' said Denise Whiting, 39, owner of Cafe Hon
who strapped on a foot-high beehive wig for her role as emcee.
``People are rethinking cities, to get them back to what they once
were, the hub of major activity.''
</P>
<P>
   But the changes, here as elsewhere, have not come without pain,
especially to residents who find gentrification scary and
expensive.
</P>
<P>
   ``Older people are afraid of change,'' Ms. Whiting said. ``They
don't necessarily see it as positive. They're frightened by it.
They even felt more comfortable with the drug addicts and
prostitutes.''
</P>
<P>
   It was largely to celebrate the old Hon ways that Ms. Whiting
opened her 1950s-style restaurant six years ago and began the Best
Hon contest a year later. But even that seems to have gentrified,
with more faux Hons entering than real ones. The first year's
winner seemed legitimate enough, Kelly Gambino, a forklift
operator. But subsequent titles were captured by a professional
dancer, a medical writer and, last year, by Ms. Foresman, 32, a
lawyer who deflates her beehive for the courtroom.
</P>
<P>
   She said she was saddened that Hons were disappearing, ``like
drive-in theaters.'' But she vowed to continue doing her part to
keep them alive, if only in spirit.
</P>
<P>
   ``Last year, someone asked me where all the Hons have gone,''
she told the crowd in parting remarks. `'It made me think that a
lot of things are gone, and we need to save 'em. Like duck-pin
bowling.''
</P>
<P>
   &UR;
</P>
<P>
   &LR;  &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
