<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-NY-SLEEPING-JURORS-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
JUDGE DISMISSES THREE JURORS FOR SLEEPING 
</HEADLINE>
  (ja) 
 By BENJAMIN WEISER    
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ In American courtrooms, the government rests after
presenting its case. The defense, too, rests. But woe to any jurors
who nod off during a trial.
</P>
<P>
   On Monday, three jurors were thrown off a major gang trial after
the judge in the case, Shira Scheindlin of federal district court
in Manhattan, determined that they had ``spent the better part of
many trial days asleep.''
</P>
<P>
   ``These folks have taken a bit of a nap here and there,''
Scheindlin said as, in a highly unusual step, she dismissed the
three jurors. ``I want to make sure that everybody has a fair
trial.''
</P>
<P>
   The issue of the sleeping jurors had been simmering for weeks in
the case, in which seven men stand accused of membership in a
violent narcotics gang in the Bronx.
</P>
<P>
   Since early March, the jury has been hearing the case under
heavy security, with extra marshals in the courtroom and with the
jurors being referred to only by number.
</P>
<P>
   As the trial neared its conclusion, a court transcript shows,
lawyers on both sides voiced concerns about the sleeping jurors,
and the judge agreed that three of them had ``been a problem.''
</P>
<P>
   With the jury out of earshot, the prosecution suggested the
possibility of kicking three drowsy jurors off the case as a group,
but the defense disliked dismissing them as ``a package deal,'' as
one lawyer put it.
</P>
<P>
   It was a touchy issue for all the parties. With the stakes so
high for their clients, who could face life in prison if convicted,
none of the defense lawyers wanted to anger any jurors. And
sometimes defense lawyers have been known to prefer that jurors go
to sleep _ at least when the government is presenting its evidence.
</P>
<P>
   After hearing arguments from both sides on Friday, Scheindlin
had her staff research the issue. When she arrived in court on
Monday, she said she had decided that three jurors _ two regular
jurors and one alternate _ would have to go.
</P>
<P>
   ``These three jurors have spent an inordinate amount of time
asleep,'' she said. ``I conclude that they could not have heard a
significance percentage of the testimony.''
</P>
<P>
   Some of the defense lawyers made a last-ditch effort to keep
jurors on the panel. One lawyer, Labe Richman, said that he did not
see Jurors 7 or 16 sleeping.
</P>
<P>
   But Scheindlin disagreed. Juror 16, for example, sometimes had
``his head tipped far back asleep,'' the judge said.
</P>
<P>
   Another defense lawyer, Daniel Nobel, suggested that although
Juror 7 ``had her eyes closed, we don't really know if she was
asleep or not.''
</P>
<P>
   ``She could sit there with her eyes closed and listen,'' he
said.
</P>
<P>
   The judge disagreed with him, too.
</P>
<P>
   Calling the three jurors into the courtroom, she thanked them
for their willingness to show up every day. ``But I did watch
carefully and there were times that each of you fell asleep,'' she
said.
</P>
<P>
   All three were excused, and the two regular jurors were replaced
with alternates. The rearranged jury began its deliberations
Tuesday.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
