<HEADER>
A1771 &Cx1f; tad-z
u a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-SCHOOL-FAILURE-PROMOT     06-09 0720
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-SCHOOL-FAILURE-PROMOTION-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    By Margo Rutledge Kissell
 &HT;    c. 1998 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   GREENE COUNTY, Ohio _ A Fairborn, Ohio fifth-grader failed all
main subjects throughout the school year, but was promoted to the
sixth grade anyway.
</P>
<P>
   For the year, the 11-year-old Five Points Elementary student
brought home F's in reading, communication skills, spelling,
mathematics, science, social studies and health. An F means ``work
shows insufficient growth for advancement to a higher level,'' the
report card said.
</P>
<P>
   ``He made straight Fs in all the main subjects. The only thing
he didn't have an F in was gym, art and music,'' Yvette Sales said
of her son. The district's decision to promote him outrages her.
</P>
<P>
   Homework is the problem, both mother and son admit.
</P>
<P>
   ``I just don't want to do it on my spare time. School is six
hours, not 24,'' the boy told a reporter.
</P>
<P>
   The boy even understands the value he places on education. His
mother tells him ``20 times a day'' that you need an education to
get a job, the boy said, adding he's been grounded throughout the
year for bringing home failing grades.
</P>
<P>
   But Fairborn City School District administrators believe they're
right but are willing to work with Sales to reconsider the
decision.
</P>
<P>
   ``Based upon my knowledge of this situation, the school has
taken into account a variety of factors and made a decision they
feel is best for the child,'' Superintendent Steve Clifton said.
</P>
<P>
   Clifton said school districts commonly use a number of factors _
not just grades _ to decide whether a student is promoted to the
next grade. Furthermore, the district tried to involve Sales in the
decision to no avail.
</P>
<P>
   Sales, though, said she was never contacted and will demand that
her son remain in the fifth grade. She doesn't know how he'll be
able to grasp sixth-grade material.
</P>
<P>
   The district's decision, she said, also has taught her son a bad
lesson: he can still be promoted even though he did no homework and
received Fs in all the main subjects all year.
</P>
<P>
   Individual districts establish their own policies to determine
whether students are promoted or retained, said Monica Zarichny,
spokeswoman for the Ohio Department of Education.
</P>
<P>
   Fairborn's Promotion and Retention of Students policy states
that ``promotion procedures demand continuous analysis and study of
the cumulative student case history records so that guesswork and
conjecture may be reduced to a minimum and decisions may be as
objective as possible.''
</P>
<P>
   Until this year, Sales said her son was a fair student _ earning
Bs, Cs, and Ds _ and is going through a phase of laziness and
rebellion. The boy's teacher also said he was capable of doing the
work, but didn't complete homework, Sales said.
</P>
<P>
   Ron McDermott, a principal for 27 years, said the school has
tried to get Sales more involved in helping her son improve his
grades. ``We have done everything in our effort to provide the
interventions and to get parental involvement with limited
success,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   The boy's report card said he was absent 23 days during the
school year, which Sales said was because of asthma problems and
other illnesses. Sales, a 28-year-old single mother of four who did
not attend high school, said she has tried to do her part and she
has preached ``the value of an education'' to her children, who
range in age from 4 to 11.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't want my kids to live the life I have and struggle,''
she said, adding she put her pursuit of a GED on hold to get a job.
</P>
<P>
   McDermott said the decision to pass the boy was made after
consulting with the teacher and a team of other school officials.
Factors including age, previous retentions, parent participation,
academic ability and a student's attitude can factor into whether
to promote a student. Sales said her son has never been held back.
</P>
<P>
   Clifton would not discuss this case or the student's grades
because of confidentiality rules, but said he stands by the
decision
</P>
<P>
   ``I think many principals from time to time struggle with what's
in the best interest of kids and it's not always apparent to the
public that we serve that there are credible efforts being made to
serve the best interest of the student,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
