<DOCNO> NYT19980609.0434 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-06-09 22:29 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A1776 &Cx1f; ttj-z
u a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-BAPTIST-WIVES-HNS &LR;      06-09 1211
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BAPTIST-WIVES-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
BAPTIST LEADERS DEFEND `SUBMISSIVE WIVES' STATEMENT 

</HEADLINE>
  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  By RICHARD VARA 
and CECILE S. HOLMES 
c.1998 Houston Chronicle 
<TEXT>
<P>
   SALT LAKE CITY _ Southern Baptist Convention leaders Tuesday
defended a new doctrinal statement on the family that defines the
role of husbands as providers and leaders and asks that wives
``submit graciously to the servant leadership of her husband.''
</P>
<P>
   Delegates overwhelmingly approved the addition of the family
statement to the Baptist Faith and Message in a show of hands vote
on the opening day of the annual national convention meeting at the
Salt Palace. The 35-year old Baptist Faith and Message consists of
denominational statements on spiritual issues although it is not
binding on the 15.9 million members. However, it is the closest
thing to a creed, which the convention has.
</P>
<P>
   Anthony Jordan, chairman of the statement committee, called it a
biblical response to family deterioration and cultural immorality.
</P>
<P>
   ``Divorce, homosexuality, abortion and abuse all tear at the
fabric of the family,'' said Jordan, an official of the Baptist
General Convention of Oklahoma. ``While there have been a barrage
of books from every perspective on the family, we have failed to
give a clear call to biblical principles of family life.''
</P>
<P>
   ``Marriage is the uniting of one man and one woman in a covenant
for a lifetime,'' said the statement, which implicitly rejects
homosexuality and divorce.
</P>
<P>
   While husbands and wives are equal before God, they have
different roles, the statement said. ``A husband is to love his
wife as Christ loved the church,'' it said. ``He has the God-given
responsibility to provide for, to protect and to lead his family.''
</P>
<P>
   ``A wife is to submit graciously to the servant leadership of
her husband even as the church willingly submits to the headship of
Christ,'' it reads. ``She, being in the image of God as is her
husband and equal to him, has the God-given responsibility to
respect her husband and to serve as his helper in managing the
household and nurturing the future generation.''
</P>
<P>
   Reaction among Baptists not attending the meeting varied.
</P>
<P>
   ``Basically I agree with the biblical admonition that wives
should submit to their husbands,'' said Doris Gardner Ratliff, wife
of the Rev. Joe Ratliff, pastor to Houston's 9,000-member Brentwood
Baptist Church.
</P>
<P>
   Modern believers must understand the context of the admonition,
she said. It was made at a time when Christians were not adhering
the moral principles they should follow. Christians today embrace
the precept because they believe Scripture applies to modern life.
</P>
<P>
   ``What that does mean is that hopefully the wife has been led to
a Christian man by the Holy Spirit who she can respect enough to
submit to,'' she said. ``What that doesn't mean is _ if you don't
respect your husband and you know in your heart that he is not
leading you and your family in the right way _ that doesn't mean
you should let him lead you down a path of destruction.''
</P>
<P>
   But other Baptists were sharply critical of the amendment's
passage, linking it to the convention's increasingly conservative
course in the past decade and to earlier social dilemmas perplexing
the convention.
</P>
<P>
   ``The amendment is historically consistent,'' said Bill Leonard,
a Baptist historian and dean of Wake Forest University's Divinity
School in Winston-Salem, N.C. He noted Baptists more than 100 years
ago used certain biblical texts to defend slavery _ something the
convention publicly repented over and apologized for several years
ago.
</P>
<P>
   ``I wonder if it will be another century before they apologize
to women,'' Leonard said.
</P>
<P>
   Some Baptists have interpreted the statement as suggesting that
women should stay home to care for children rather than work. The
statement also describes children as a blessing from God beginning
from the ``moment of conception.''
</P>
<P>
   The Rev. Tim Owings of Georgia tried to amend the statement
arguing that Scripture in the writing of the Apostle Paul required
mutual submission between spouses. ``Husbands, wives and children
are as followers of Jesus to submit to each other and supremely to
the lordship of Christ,'' Ownings said. ``If we are going to amend
the Baptist Faith and Message, let us do so being true to Holy
Scripture and not contrary to it.''
</P>
<P>
   The amendment failed as did an amendment by Dennis Wiles of
Alabama, who proposed to include single adults, widows, widowers
and childless couples in the statement. He said the statement was
directed to marriage and parenting.
</P>
<P>
   The statement's seven-member committee, which included two
women, defined the conservative family definition.
</P>
<P>
   ``The whole issue comes down to a matter of Scripture,'' said
Mary Mohler, wife of Southern Baptist Theological Seminary
President Albert Mohler.
</P>
<P>
   ``It does not take a scholar to be able to interpret what is so
clearly laid out in God's blueprint for the family'' Mary Mohler
said. ``Submission is not a negative word. It may not be
politically correct word, it may not be a popular word, but it is a
biblically correct word, and that's what counts.''
</P>
<P>
   Both Mary Mohler and fellow committee member Dorothy Patterson,
wife of convention president Paige Patterson, said they obeyed
their husbands in family issues.
</P>
<P>
   Committee member Richard Land, director of the convention's
religious liberty agency, said the statement did not prohibit women
from working outside the home. But Land said if a husband did not
want his wife to work, she should not.
</P>
<P>
   Paige Patterson, who was elected convention president Tuesday
without opposition, also defended the statement in his first
presidential press conference.
</P>
<P>
   ``It is a statement that is made in a time of growing crisis in
the family,'' Patterson said. ``Frankly, I am a little surprised
that anybody is surprised (by the statement),'' he said. He said
Southern Baptists have long followed the biblical model of family
long before the advent of feminism and women's rights.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't see it as a negative statement against anybody or
anything,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   The original version of the Faith and Message Statement was
drafted in 1925, in a period of great disagreement among Protestant
liberals and conservatives over Scripture interpretation.
</P>
<P>
   The language added Tuesday was prepared by seven-member
committee, with members taken from top Baptist leaders. Of the two
women on the committee, one was Dorothy Patterson, wife of the new
convention president.
</P>
<P>
   Baptists may also have adopted the amendment because the
convention is meeting for the first time in Salt Lake City,
headquarters of the Church of Jesus Christ of Latter-day Saints.
Prior to the convention's opening Tuesday, Baptists erected large
billboards and conducted an evangelism blitz, an unusual move among
Mormons who are also known for their proselytizing zeal.
</P>
<P>
   Baptists ``wanted to speak strongly about the family in Mormon
territory because the strongest national claim that Mormons make
about their faith is the strength of their families,'' Leonard
said. ``It's not insignificant that this was done in Utah, right
after he effort to evangelize Mormons.''
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
XXXX END OF STORY &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
