<SLUG> BC-DATA-ENCRYPT-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
U.S. AND INDUSTRY DISCUSS DATA ENCRYPTION
</HEADLINE>
  
(ATTN.: Calif.)  (ja) 
 By JERI CLAUSING   
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ Leading computing executives, including Microsoft's
chief executive, Bill Gates, huddled for two hours on Tuesday with
Attorney General Janet Reno and the director of the FBI to discuss
disagreements between the industry and the government over data
scrambling.
</P>
<P>
   After the meeting, the White House said it hoped that the talks
would lead to an easing of export restrictions on data encryption
technology by fall.
</P>
<P>
   ``The presence of industry leaders encourages us now to redouble
our efforts with industry,'' said a White House official who spoke
on the condition of anonymity. ``Without a solution, we risk losing
our lead in this important technology.''
</P>
<P>
   Any agreement ``must include further real relaxation in export
controls,'' the official said, adding: ``We are still discussing
exactly what those relaxations should be. That's the $64,000
question.''
</P>
<P>
   The executives who took part in the meeting at the office of
Sen. Dianne Feinstein, D-Calif., had little to say afterward. But
their very presence in one room was highly unusual _ a sign of just
how critical it has become for high-technology companies, privacy
advocates and the administration to resolve their years-long
stalemate on encryption.
</P>
<P>
   The United States currently prohibits, without special
permission, the export of strong encryption, a policy that even the
Clinton administration has acknowledged is hurting the dominance of
American encryption technology in the international marketplace.
</P>
<P>
   But the administration, under pressure from Louis Freeh, the FBI
director, has insisted that any easing of export controls be
coupled with creation of a system that guarantees law enforcement
quick access to encrypted files.
</P>
<P>
   The FBI has been pushing for a third-party key recovery, or
``key escrow,'' system, that would essentially require anyone who
uses encryption to file a ``spare key'' for that data-scrambling
code with a company set up for that purpose. This method is
supposed to guarantee law-enforcement agencies access to encrypted
computer files in criminal investigations.
</P>
<P>
   Industry and privacy groups have balked at any third-party
recovery systems, a position that has stalled attempts to ease
export controls.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-06-09-98 2233EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
