<SLUG> BC-NY-LI-POWER-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
NEW YORK UTILITY RECORDS SHOW HUGE DEMAND BY ITS CHIEF
</HEADLINE>
   (ja) 
 By BRUCE LAMBERT    
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   GARDEN CITY, N.Y. _ Newly released documents show that members
of the Long Island Lighting Co.' board were trying to keep the
compensation package of the company's chairman secret but were
worried that the chairman was demanding so much _ $63 million _
that it would force the issue into the open.
</P>
<P>
   According to minutes of the board's private meeting on May 18,
just days before Lilco was set to go out of existence, board
members did not want to give the chairman, Dr. William Catacosinos,
the compensation he was demanding but feared that if they did not
concede, the dispute would become public.
</P>
<P>
   Such a disclosure, they feared, could result in a backlash from
Albany and Lilco shareholders that could jeopardize the company as
it was about to close two major deals, completing a partial
takeover of its electrical service by the state through the Long
Island Power Authority and merging its remaining divisions with the
Brooklyn Union Gas holding company to form the Marketspan Corp.
</P>
<P>
   ``This will open a Pandora's box and create more aggravation
from Albany than we would dream of,'' a consulting director, Eben
Pyne, warned, according to the minutes.
</P>
<P>
   ``If that occurred before the closing, which is less than two
weeks away, and the disagreement was disclosed,'' he said, ``I
suspect that would be the beginning of shareholder lawsuits and
Albany becoming concerned.''
</P>
<P>
   Defending Catacosinos' service to Lilco, Pyne urged the board to
negotiate a fair settlement. But he warned, ``If we don't, then I
believe that we're in for a storm and a disaster.''
</P>
<P>
   In fact, Catacosinos and the board kept their dispute private
and eventually agreed on the $42-million compensation package on
May 27 _ just one day before he signed the final papers completing
the takeover and merger.
</P>
<P>
   The board minutes bolster accusations, made by Gov. George
Pataki and other critics of the Lilco payments, that Catacosinos
and Lilco's directors purposely concealed the payments. Former
Lilco officials, who have now assumed posts in Marketspan, have
contended that the payments were based on policies that Lilco
publicly disclosed over the years.
</P>
<P>
   Pataki has denounced the payment to Catacosinos, along with $25
million more paid to 25 other Lilco officials, as a form of
robbery. He has called on Marketspan to rid itself of the former
Lilco officials who were involved in the special payments,
including Catacosinos, now chairman of Marketspan, the other
recipients of special compensation and the former Lilco directors
who authorized the payments.
</P>
<P>
   At the governor's request, the payments are being investigated
by the state attorney general, Dennis Vacco, and the state Public
Service Commission. Catacosinos received a subpoena on Monday to
appear before investigators next Monday.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is further evidence of the outrageous conduct of this
company and apparently confirms their attempt to conceal the
information,'' Vacco said on Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
   Although Catacosinos presided over the May 18 meeting, the
minutes indicated that the board was in a deep conflict with him.
Besides Catacosinos, 10 other directors were present and one was
linked by telephone. At certain points, recesses were taken so that
eight directors could confer with their independent counsel. There
are references to personal consultants hired by Catacosinos to
calculate his compensation.
</P>
<P>
   The most extensive comments in the minutes were from Pyne, a
nonvoting official affiliated with Lilco for 40 years.
</P>
<P>
   ``I understand our concern with respect to potential
shareholders' litigation and Governor Pataki's possible concerns if
there was a disclosure of a dispute with respect to the Lipa
transaction,'' Pyne was quoted as saying, referring to the Long
Island Power Authority.
</P>
<P>
   ``If, as I understand it, the board intends to offer Bill a
take-it-or-leave-it number,'' he continued, ``that could place Bill
in the untenable position of having to notice the board that he
will arbitrate.''
</P>
<P>
   In that event, Pyne said, the dispute would have to be disclosed
in company documents.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
