<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-PUBLIC-LIVES-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
PLAYING YOURSELF  
 CLOSING THE KITCHEN  
 MINOR OMISSION 
</HEADLINE>
  (mk) 
 By JAMES BARRON   
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ ``Usually I'm the person standing on the sidewalk
going: `Look, they're filming a movie; are there any movie
stars?''' said Lisa G., a radio personality who also appears as an
entertainment reporter on WCBS-TV (and who uses only the first
letter of her last name, which is Glasberg).
</P>
<P>
   But this time, she was one of the stars in a scene in ``Macbeth
in Manhattan.'' The script called for her to play herself and
interview John Glover, the actor, outside the Cherry Lane Theater
in Greenwich Village.
</P>
<P>
   ``It was an out-of-body experience, hearing them say, `Lights,'
`Speed,' `Action,' and being there in the middle of it,'' she said.
</P>
<P>
   And apparently Glover was not prepared for the Lisa G. approach
to acting.
</P>
<P>
   ``He said, `Do you want to rehearse our lines?''' she recounted.
``I said, `No.' This was when we were waiting in the holding area.
I was feeling intimidated and my mind just went blank. He said,
`Oh, come on. I think it will help us get into the scene.'
</P>
<P>
   ``He didn't want me to take anything personally because of his
character, which I knew about from reading the script: I was almost
a thorn in his side, and he didn't want to be interviewed, but I
had to talk to him, just a reporter doing my job.''
</P>
<P>
   The scene was shot in a single take. Then came her close-up. ``I
had to say: `Excuse me, I haven't done this before. What do we do?'
It wasn't an easy question to ask.''
</P>
<P>
   Rent Gets No Stars
</P>
<P>
   Anne Rosenzweig, the chef, is throwing in the toque at Arcadia,
a restaurant on East 62nd Street near Madison Avenue with a
woodsy-looking wraparound mural.
</P>
<P>
   Ms. Rosenzweig said that she and her partner in Arcadia, Ken
Aretsky, would close the 15-year-old restaurant on June 20 after
failing to negotiate a new lease with a landlord she said had
demanded a big rent increase. She would not say how much Arcadia
had been paying or how much the landlord wanted.
</P>
<P>
   ``Back then it seemed like a huge amount,'' she said. ``Now it
seems very reasonable, but not in this real estate market.''
</P>
<P>
   A representative of the landlord did not return calls for
comment.
</P>
<P>
   Skip the Mouse
</P>
<P>
   The single-spaced biography from the Children's Scholarship
Fund, the business group behind a $200 million push for a national
school-voucher program, said that his accomplishments included
``creating Coke Classic's polar bear mascot.''
</P>
<P>
   It said that he ``consulted for many major international
businesses and helped them with mergers and acquisitions within the
entertainment industry.'' It mentioned Matsushita's deal for MCA
and Sony's takeover of Columbia Pictures.
</P>
<P>
   It said that he was a co-founder of Creative Artists Agency, the
powerhouse talent agency. It said that he sold his stake in
Creative Artists in 1995.
</P>
<P>
   It even said that he began his career as a tour guide at
Universal Studios ``and then moved to a similar job at 20th Century
Fox.''
</P>
<P>
   But it did not say that Michael Ovitz, who is becoming a major
investor in Livent, the entertainment company based in Toronto that
produced ``Ragtime,'' was president of Walt Disney Corp. for 15
months in 1994 and 1995 (until he was ousted by that other
Hollywood Michael, Michael Eisner).
</P>
<P>
   The biography was drafted for Ovitz in April, before the Livent
deal was announced. As for not mentioning his time at Disney, a
spokesman for Ovitz said, ``Mr. Ovitz spent 25 years of his career
building CAA, and that's the focus of his bio.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
