<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-EXECUTION-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 10 &HT;    Couple's killer is put to death 13 years later
 &HT;    By Rhonda Cook
 &HT;    c. 1998 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   JACKSON, Ga. _ There were no stays _ just a 2 1/2-hour ''hold''
_ so double murderer David Cargill went to his own state-sanctioned
death Tuesday night with barely a notice from the world outside the
prison.
</P>
<P>
   The day was marked by a series of court challenges and pleas to
the state Board of Pardons and Paroles, Butts County, Ga. Superior
Court Judge Arch McGarity and the U.S. Supreme Court. But no one
who could stop the execution for the 1985 murders agreed with
Cargill's attorneys and his family, who argued that the 39-year-old
man no longer deserved to die.
</P>
<P>
   Not even the boys orphaned when Cargill killed Cheryl and Danny
Williams during a winter night gas station robbery in 1985 in
Columbus, Ga. spoke out, unlike the survivors of murder victims in
the previous 22 executions held in Georgia since December 1983.
</P>
<P>
   There were no television trucks parked outside the Georgia
Diagnostic and Classification Prison equipped for live reporting.
Only eight death penalty opponents and a half dozen supporters of
executions gathered outside for the moment Cargill sat in the
state's electric chair.
</P>
<P>
   Cargill and his younger brother, Tommy, both of Phoenix City,
Ala., were convicted of the armed robbery of the Premium Oil
Station in Columbus and the execution-style slaying of the
Williamses, the parents of four boys ages 2 to 10.
</P>
<P>
   The Williamses worked days at a now-closed textile mill near
Columbus. Cheryl Williams worked at the service station to earn
extra money for the family. Her husband often stopped by to help
her close.
</P>
<P>
   During the robbery, $482.79 was taken. The couple was forced to
lie face down on the floor of the service station. Each was shot
twice in the head. Cargill, 26 at the time, was sentenced to death
for shooting the couple; his brother, then 21, was sentenced to
life in prison.
</P>
<P>
   David Cargill spent Tuesday with his aging, ailing mother, a
sister, a niece and a chaplain. After they left at 3:30 p.m.,
Cargill had his last meal of steak, baked potato, salad and vanilla
ice cream. Then his head and a leg were shaved to prepare for the
execution.
</P>
<P>
   Cargill asked for forgiveness Tuesday and said he hoped his
execution would bring closure to those he hurt, said Scott
Stallings, a spokesman for the state Department of Corrections. The
U.S. Supreme Court asked Georgia officials just before 7 p.m., the
scheduled time for the execution, for time to review the case. Once
the court had declined to act on his appeal, Cargill's execution,
witnessed by 22 people, began at 9:42 p.m. He was pronounced dead
at 9:50 p.m.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
