<HEADER>
A1786 &Cx1f; taf-z
s e &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-ANTIQUES-WODEHOUSE-$A     06-09 0914
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-ANTIQUES-WODEHOUSE-$ADV14-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
A FARSIGHTED COLLECTOR EVEN AS A BOY, BY JEEVES! 
</HEADLINE>
   (For release Sunday, June 14)  
 (JT)  
 By RITA REIF    
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   In 1927, when James H. Heineman was 10, he demonstrated a
bibliographic bent: he began buying first editions of the novels of
his favorite author, the British writer P.G. Wodehouse, whose works
poked fun at bumbling English aristocrats. The young Jimmy avidly
devoured Wodehouse's stories about Bertie Wooster and Jeeves in
Never-Never Land, the escapades of Rupert Eustace Psmith and the
sagas at Blandings Castle. But rather than read them in hardback,
Jimmy found paperback editions. He was the son of a collector, and
to preserve the pristine state of the hard-bound copies he stowed
them unopened on bookshelves in his family's home in Brussels.
</P>
<P>
   Over the next 60 years, Heineman, who died in 1994, continued to
buy the works of Pelham Grenville (Plum) Wodehouse, amassing a
collection of some 6,300 items. Among them are at least one copy
each of the nearly 100 novels Wodehouse wrote as well as short
stories, plays, book reviews, lyrics and caricatures of the author.
In 1981, Heineman lent part of the collection _ a few hundred
choice pieces _ to the Pierpont Morgan Library in Manhattan for an
exhibition commemorating the centenary of Wodehouse's birth.
</P>
<P>
   Next Sunday, Heineman's entire Wodehouse collection goes on view
for the first time at Sotheby's in New York, where it will be
auctioned in 150 lots on June 26. The stunning assortment of
Wodehousiana, the most comprehensive ever offered, is expected to
command a total price of $600,000.
</P>
<P>
   Letters and other objects in the collection also shed new light
on Wodehouse's involvement with the Nazis during World War II. In
1940, the author was seized by the Germans at his home in Le
Touquet, France, taken to Germany and briefly interned. The Nazis
then moved him to a hotel in Berlin, where his wife, Ethel, joined
him. There, in the summer of 1941, Wodehouse made five
controversial radio broadcasts to the United States in which he
made light of his life in an internment camp. ``It has been in many
ways an agreeable experience,'' he said, adding, ``It keeps you out
of the saloons and gives you time to catch up on your reading.''
</P>
<P>
   A phonograph recording of one of the broadcasts will also be
sold, along with some letters and documents, in a lot estimated to
bring $7,000. The sale's most important offering is a set of 12
letters, written by Wodehouse to a friend, Baroness Anga von
Bodenhausen, in which he reveals his plan to work in German films
during the war. Sotheby's expects that the letters will fetch
$30,000.
</P>
<P>
   ``They have paid me a nice fat sum for option rights,''
Wodehouse wrote to the baroness in March 1942. ``If they decide to
use one of my novels as a picture, I get another lot of money. So I
am quite well off and Ethel has been buying some wonderful hats.''
</P>
<P>
   Americans were outraged by the broadcasts, as were the British,
who accused Wodehouse of treason, saying he had participated in
Nazi propaganda. But Wodehouse was not without his defenders, among
them the authors Evelyn Waugh, George Orwell and Malcolm
Muggerridge and to a lesser degree Heineman.
</P>
<P>
   ``Jimmy thought Wodehouse's actions showed a political naivete
of an almost incredible kind,'' said Charles Gould, a Wodehouse
expert who teaches English literature at the Kent School in
Connecticut.
</P>
<P>
   The British royal family did not officially forgive Wodehouse
for his activities with the Nazis until 30 years after the war had
ended. In 1975, six weeks before Wodehouse died at 93, Queen
Elizabeth II made him a Knight Commander of the Order of the
British Empire.
</P>
<P>
   Wodehouse fans will find many rarities in the sale, the scarcest
of which is a copy of ``The Intrusion of Jimmy,'' published in New
York in 1910. The book cost $1.50 when published and was reissued a
year later at 50 cents. Sotheby's expects this copy, which is
inscribed by the author and has its original dust jacket, to sell
for about $6,000. That would be a record for a Wodehouse book.
</P>
<P>
   Wodehouse's work as a songwriter for Broadway and Hollywood is
less well known. His most notable lyrics were for the song ``Bill''
from the Jerome Kern musical ``Showboat,'' and a copy of the sheet
music for the song is one of 505 items related to his musical
career being offered by Sotheby's. The lot also includes posters,
playbills and phonograph recordings and may sell for as much as
$3,000.
</P>
<P>
   Heineman's father, Dannie, had amassed an extensive collection
of books and papers _ manuscripts, letters and books by Einstein,
Mozart and Balzac. He managed to get much of it out of Belgium
before the German occupation and, 20 years ago, the Heineman
foundation donated it to the Morgan Library.
</P>
<P>
   The younger Heineman was not so lucky. He left his earliest
Wodehouse acquisitions at home in Brussels when he was sent to New
York on the eve of World War II to work in the offices of the
family business. Shortly after Pearl Harbor, Heineman, an American
who had lived abroad until then, was drafted by the Army and went
back to Europe as a warrant officer.
</P>
<P>
   ``In 1944, I managed to make my way to my parents' home,'' he
later recalled. He found it surprisingly intact after four years of
German occupation: the rugs, the furniture, even the flooring, had
not suffered. ``However,'' he said, ``my Wodehouse books had
vanished.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
