<HEADLINE>
PLAYERS ARE TRADING PLACES ON OFFENSIVE LINE 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by N.Y. Times News Service clients)  
 By STEVE SCHOENFELD  
 c.1998 The Arizona Republic  
<TEXT>
<P>
   The shuffling and experimenting on the offensive line continues.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; Jerome Daniels, an offensive tackle as a rookie last season, is
working at right guard, a 360-pound right guard.
</P>
<P>
   ``Big guards who are athletic, explosive and can play are
something special,'' first-year offensive line coach  &UR; George Warhop
said.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; Alan DeGraffenreid, who experimented at center during last
month's minicamp, is working at left tackle.
</P>
<P>
   ``He's a unique player,'' Warhop said. ``He has the ability to
play several positions. The guy never had played center before.
Don't be surprised if some time he lines up at guard.''
</P>
<P>
   DeGraffenreid feels comfortable at any position, even at tight
end, where he has been working on goal-line situations.
</P>
<P>
   ``I want to be the  &UR; Eric Metcalf of offensive linemen,'' said
DeGraffenreid, referring to the wide receiver/running back/return
specialist.
</P>
<P>
   Rookie  &UR; Anthony Clement, the second-round draft pick from
Southwestern Louisiana and heir apparent to  &UR; Lomas Brown at left
tackle, is working during this week's rookie camp at right tackle.
</P>
<P>
   ``He hasn't played right tackle in two years, but we're focusing
in on that right now,'' Warhop said. ``We're trying to create some
competition there.''
</P>
<P>
   Warhop said Tuesday that four of the five offensive line
positions are wide open, with only Brown assured of a starting
job. &QL; 
Diet plan &QL; 
Warhop said he would like to see Daniels, a third-round pick of the
Miami Dolphins a year ago, get his weight down to about 335 by the
start of training camp next month.
</P>
<P>
   Daniels, whose teams have nicknamed him ``Pudding,'' said he is
shooting for 340.
</P>
<P>
   ``I see a nutritionist once a week and am dropping four or five
pounds (a week),'' he said. ``Now I do most of my eating midday.
I've cut out the late-night meals. I'm steadily getting to the
weight they want.'' &QL; 
Two-wheelers &QL; 
Cornerback  &UR; Tom Knight and tight end  &UR; Chris Gedney have begun
riding their bicycles to camp each day.
</P>
<P>
   They're doing it to try to get in shape.
</P>
<P>
   ``It takes me 40 minutes to get home with a head wind,'' Gedney
said.
</P>
<P>
   Knight, a first-round pick a year ago, said his teammates have
teased him about not having another ride.
</P>
<P>
   ``They're all talking about me,'' Knight said. ``They wonder why
I can't drive and what's wrong. I tell them nothing is wrong. It's
just a great experience, riding around _ 3{ miles each way _ taking
in this wonderful Arizona weather.'' &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
