u s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-bullssider-HNS &LR;      06-09 0751
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-bulls </SLUG>
 sider-HNS  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
Rodman's 
truancy 
profitable
<TEXT>
<P>
   Wrestling pay dwarfs &QL; 
fines; teammates riled
</P>
<P>
   Rodman
</P>
<P>
   &UR; By MICHAEL MURPHY &LR;  &QL; 
 &UR; c. 1998, Houston Chronicle &LR;  &QL; 
CHICAGO _ The aftermath of the Bulls' 42-point victory on Sunday
has been interesting, to put it mildly.
</P>
<P>
   And put the emphasis on the ``math'' in aftermath.
</P>
<P>
   You practically need an abacus to total up the records set in
Chicago's 96-54 victory over the Jazz in Game 3 of the NBA Finals,
but to the Bulls, the only numbers of note this week are one, one
and 20,000.
</P>
<P>
   The first refers to the number of practices Dennis Rodman has
skipped this week. The second refers to the number of World
Championship Wrestling events he has chosen to attend. And the last
refers to the number of dollars Rodman was fined _ $10,000 by the
NBA for skipping Monday's media availability session and $10,000 by
the Bulls for missing Monday's practice.
</P>
<P>
   Not that it mattered to Rodman.
</P>
<P>
   No, the amazing technicolor dreamboat to so-called rebels
everywhere picked up a cool $250,000 for his appearance with pal
Hulk Hogan on TNT's Monday Nitro wrestling event in Detroit.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's all good,'' Rodman said at Tuesday's practice session.
``I made some good friends and made a lot of money.''
</P>
<P>
   Those friends Rodman spoke of obviously weren't his teammates,
who were not pleased with the incident. It is only the latest
addition to what Michael Jordan calls Rodman's attendant
``baggage'' _ which looks more like a steamer trunk with each
passing day.
</P>
<P>
   Jordan was certainly steamed at Tuesday's practice.
</P>
<P>
   Instead of answering questions about how the Bulls were up 2-1
in the best-of-seven Finals, which resume tonight at the United
Center, Jordan instead found himself fielding questions about
Rodman's whereabouts and impact on the team.
</P>
<P>
   ``Phil (Jackson, the Bulls' coach) addressed that today _ I
didn't know where he was,'' Jordan said. ``Somebody said he was
wrestling somewhere. I told Phil that whatever he (Rodman) got
paid, that he should distribute it to the players, split it up
evenly. I don't know if he's going to do that, but Phil was pretty
upset by it.''
</P>
<P>
   Jordan's suggestion of disbursing the $250,000 among the rest of
the team seems like a better solution than what the Bulls and the
league decided upon. You do the math: $250,000 minus $20,000 for
fines still comes out to a pretty hefty chunk of change.
</P>
<P>
   According to Jackson, however, it is the media's fault for
glamorizing Rodman's aberrant behavior, his outrageous appearance
and his often-ridiculous statements.
</P>
<P>
   ``He's only taking your (the media's) focus away from the
Finals, not ours,'' said Jackson of Rodman. ``You're focusing on
him, and you're the ones who have made him what (he's become).
That's exactly one of the problems. He becomes an anti-hero figure
in this society, and that's a problem.''
</P>
<P>
   Oh, and all this time everyone thought the problem was Rodman's
skipping practice to go to a wrestling match in another state.
Jackson doesn't see that as a problem, even if his Bulls are trying
to prepare for Game 4 of the NBA Finals.
</P>
<P>
   ``Having worked with people, professional athletes, in this
business for a long time, and having been one myself, I think the
focus should be that Dennis is a unique individual, and maybe, in
some sense, handicapped, but who is finding an occupation in which
he is doing extremely well,'' Jackson said. ``(Look at it that way)
rather than trying to make him out to be some dysfunctional
character. Dennis is functioning probably as well as he can
function under a system like this, and it's a wonderful thing that
he's been able to find employment.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't know if he could have employment in the 9-to-5 world.
I doubt if he could. But he's made it in this world, and that's
great. For us, it's even better if he can bring the best of himself
to the court. And that's what we ask him for.''
</P>
<P>
   Other than fines, Jackson seems content to ignore Rodman's
behavior, but his teammates seem to be wearying of the sideshow and
of Jackson's way of dealing with all the distractions.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's par for the course,'' said Luc Longley of Rodman's
behavior and Jackson's willingness to overlook the incident.
``That's the way he's behaved all year, and that's the way he's
behaved the last two years. We're sleeping in a nest that we helped
to build. It's our acceptance of him and our tolerance of him that
has perpetuated this stuff.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
