<SLUG> BC-JDPOWER-HMO-LADN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
HEALTH PLAN CUSTOMERS POLLED
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
BY BEN SULLIVAN  
 c.1998 Los Angeles Daily News  
<TEXT>
<P>
   LOS ANGELES _ J.D. Power and Associates, a company best known
for rating cars based on customer satisfaction surveys, has turned
its sights again on the health care industry.
</P>
<P>
   For the second year, the company teamed with the Ann Arbor,
Mich.-based Medstat Group to rate HMOs, fee-for-service plans,
preferred provider organizations and other health plans, based
solely on what their members say about them.
</P>
<P>
   Tuesday's results, which will be sold back to the health care
industry in customized reports, partially vindicate the
much-maligned health maintenance organization, organizers said. An
HMO was the top-rated plan in more than half the 20 metropolitan
markets where customers were surveyed.
</P>
<P>
   ``Some HMOs scored poorly (but) enrollees rated many HMOs higher
than traditional fee-for-service plans in several health care
markets,'' said Dennis Becker, a Medstat vice president.
</P>
<P>
   To conduct the survey, J.D. Power and Medstat sent
questionnaires to 81,000 members of 181 different health plans,
asking them to rate the performance of their plan in 11 different
categories. The survey pool was made up of employees at companies
that do business with Medstat. As a result, only health plans
serving those employees were included in the study.
</P>
<P>
   The survey results are not aimed at consumers, said Medstat
spokeswoman Andree Joyaux. ``This is for the industry ... primarily
the health plans and purchasers,'' Joyaux said.
</P>
<P>
   In California, only members in the San Francisco area were
included in the study, and no plan there emerged ``significantly
above other plans,'' according to the study. Another survey focused
exclusively on California is in the works, Joyaux said.
</P>
<P>
   Reports of the study's results will be sold to health plans and
other interested parties for ``thousands of dollars,'' Joyaux said,
to help plans better meet the needs and wants of consumers.
</P>
<P>
   But with dozens of other employer-, consumer- and
industry-supported health plan surveys already around, some
question the need for the product.
</P>
<P>
   ``There are so many other surveys out there that this could be
redundant with information being provided by other sources,'' said
Blue Cross of California spokeswoman Elise Anderson. ``Is there
anything in it that doesn't already exist?''
</P>
<P>
   X X X
</P>
</TEXT>
