<HEADER>
A1795 &Cx1f; tic-z
r s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-BKW-MERCURY-PREVIEW-A     06-09 0726
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BKW-MERCURY-PREVIEW-AZR </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by N.Y. Times News Service clients)  
 By JEFF METCALFE  
 c.1998 The Arizona Republic  
<TEXT>
<P>
   PHOENIX - Faster than Cheryl Miller can blast her right foot
into the scorer's table and break her big toe, the balance of power
in the WNBA has swung to the Western Conference.
</P>
<P>
   The question is whether Miller can preserve her other foot from
damage in what promises to be an emotion-charged, parity-driven
crusade. At stake is not only the conference title but a record
good enough to earn a precious playoff berth.
</P>
<P>
   Three of the four playoff teams in the inaugural season were
from the Eastern Conference, including the Houston Comets, who won
it all and now are in the West. That immediately takes Miller's
Mercury down a notch from defending West champion in preseason
predictions. Some are dropping Phoenix further, below the
fast-finishing Los Angeles Sparks.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think, when you go strictly on talent, that LA will be tough
to beat,'' Houston Coach Van Chancellor said.
</P>
<P>
   The Mercury might be, too, once the players who joined the team
this week after the World Championships find their way into a new
motion offense. The cut to a roster of 11 comes today before the
team departs for its opener Thursday in Sacramento.
</P>
<P>
   Miller said she would rather be faced with tough decisions than
having too few talented players to fill the roster. She compared
her predicament to what Danny Ainge went through this season with
the deep Suns.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're in a wonderful situation,'' she said.
</P>
<P>
   The six incoming players (Michele Timms, Michelle Griffiths and
Kristi Harrower of Australia; Mikiko Hagiwara of Japan; Marlies
Askamp of Germany; and Maria Stepanova of Russia) must ``sink or
swim,'' Miller said. ``Right now after throwing them in the water,
I saw a lot of people doing the backstroke and feeling good about
themselves.''
</P>
<P>
   Once beyond today's roster decisions _ ``Emotions are high right
now,'' Miller said _ the Mercury's goal will be to stand at least
2-1 after the first five days of the season, then use a five-day
break to fully integrate the World Championships players into the
system.
</P>
<P>
   What should emerge by June 21, a home game against Charlotte, is
a bigger and better shooting Mercury than the team that fought off
the Sparks to win the West but was held to a league-low 41 points
in a semifinal playoff loss to the New York Liberty.
</P>
<P>
   With 6-foot-8 first-round draft pick Stepanova and probably 6-3
veteran Pauline Jordan providing reinforcements, frontcourt
starters Jennifer Gillom and Toni Foster will wear better
throughout the 30-game season. And with a microfiber basketball
that is billed as being easier to handle, the 6-5 Askamp could
raise her scoring average into double figures.
</P>
<P>
   Houston (Sheryl Swoopes, who missed much of last season after
giving birth to her son) and Los Angeles (Allison Feaster) both get
an injection of scoring punch at small forward. But Phoenix
acquired its own lower-profile help.
</P>
<P>
   Second- and third-round draft picks Andrea Kuklova of Slovakia
and Brandy Reed flashed their offensive skills during exhibition
wins over Utah. Hagiwara, if she makes the roster, is coming off a
sparkling international tour and might thrive in an offense more
like that of the Japanese national team.
</P>
<P>
   Gillom and Timms, who turn 34 and 33 this month, carried much of
the load in a 16-12 regular season that included an an 8-3 start
and a six-game losing streak. They need help and rest if the
Mercury is to reach a second postseason with bullets left in the
chamber.
</P>
<P>
   Miller, too, was spent by season's end, carrying the weight of a
franchise that led the league in attendance (13,703 average) and
has doubled its season ticket base to 9,000. She tripled her
assistant coaching staff but is no less intense. The broken toe
that will require her to wear a soft cast for four to six weeks
came in the exhibition opener just before she was hit with a
technical foul.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm an emotional person,'' she said. ``Would I have done
anything different (to avoid the injury)? Probably not. The only
thing it affects is my clothing attire. Instead of a complete 10,
I'm a 9.''
</P>
<P>
   And no less bold than last season in her public predictions.
``We're bringing this bad boy (WNBA title) home,'' she promised the
crowd after the home exhibition. &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
