A1796 &Cx1f; taf-z
u a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-NY-DOMINICAN-PRESIDEN     06-09 0732
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-NY-DOMINICAN-PRESIDENT-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
DOMINICAN PRESIDENT CHEERED BY STUDENTS IN NEW YORK 
</HEADLINE>
  (mk) 
 By ANDY NEWMAN   
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ The guest speaker at George Washington High School in
Washington Heights on Tuesday was not quite a local boy made good.
Leonel Fernandez Ryna regretted to report that he had grown up a
few neighborhoods south and attended rival Louis Brandeis High
School.
</P>
<P>
   But the 700 or so screaming, cheering, sign-waving students who
packed the school auditorium to give the 44-year-old Fernandez a
rock star's welcome did not seem to mind. It is not often, after
all, that the president of the Dominican Republic _ homeland of
more than 80 percent of the school's students _comes to visit.
</P>
<P>
   Fernandez, who spoke on Monday at the U.N. meeting about
fighting illegal drugs, decided to make a detour to the city's most
overwhelmingly Dominican neighborhood to preach against drug use.
He reminded the students that though most of their cousins back
home were far less fortunate than they were, they had one
significant advantage: drugs are used by less than 2 percent of
those over 12 years old in the Dominican Republic.
</P>
<P>
   Though Washington Heights has partly recovered from the crack
plague of the early '90s, students said drugs were still easily
available there.
</P>
<P>
   The Dominican Republic itself, according to U.S. authorities, is
a major conduit for drugs entering this country. At the United
Nations, Fernandez said that the demand for drugs in the United
States was what made the illegal trade in the Dominican Republic so
profitable and attractive. But he has also vowed to get tough with
drug traffickers.
</P>
<P>
   Fernandez spoke of his humble roots and said that even though he
had heard when he was growing up on 95th Street that in America,
anyone can become president: ``I never thought I'd become president
of anything.''
</P>
<P>
   But Fernandez, who was elected in 1996, drew his loudest
applause when he spoke of the changes he was bringing to the
island.
</P>
<P>
   ``When you get back to the Dominican Republic,'' he said,
``you're going to see a lot of things that you have here _
McDonald's, Burger King, pizza that you can call and get delivered.
And all the cable channels. All the kids there can watch the
Chicago Bulls and the Utah Jazz just like you.''
</P>
<P>
   After his 15-minute speech, which was given in Spanish,
Fernandez, a former lawyer, remained seated at a desk at the front
of the stage and fielded questions from the students, mostly about
his domestic policies. What was he doing to improve the country's
chronic electricity shortage? Buying new plants from Germany and
Spain. Why not sell off drug-traffickers' property to raise money
for the power plants? Already being done.
</P>
<P>
   How has the country changed in the last two years? Fernandez
ticked off accomplishments like better bus service in the capital,
an unaccustomed absence of political scandals, upgraded hospitals
and more computers in the schools.
</P>
<P>
   He also reminded the students that starting in the year 2000,
Dominican citizens who live abroad will be able to vote by absentee
ballot in elections back home. (They will not be able to vote for
him, however: Dominican presidents cannot serve two successive
terms.)
</P>
<P>
   Despite the warm welcome, Fernandez received mixed grades from
students afterward.
</P>
<P>
   ``He was giving real answers, not just saying things to make us
happy,'' said Cris Marcario, a senior and a student government
representative who said he was inspired to continue in politics.
</P>
<P>
   But Jaime Rodriguez, a 15-year-old sophomore, disputed
Fernandez's claims of having moved the country forward. ``Mostly,
he lied,'' she said. ``The past two years, when I go home, I don't
see too much difference. They're doing things about the appearance
but not the big problems. People are wasting their money buying
generators because there's no electricity. That's what my father
has in his house there.''
</P>
<P>
   Rosa Gonzalez, 18, a senior, said that Fernandez had the common
touch. ``He's so simple, he's just like us,'' she said. ``He's an
ordinary man, he's nice and he wants us to succeed.'' But she had
mixed feelings about Fernandez's modernization programs. She was
excited about McDonald's but had reservations about cable
television. ``I guess it's pretty nice,'' she said, ``but they
should have their own channels.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
