<HEADER>
A1805 &Cx1f; taf-z
u a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-NY-PROSECUTOR-QUITS-N     06-09 0805
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-NY-PROSECUTOR-QUITS-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
PROSECUTOR IN LOUIMA BRUTALITY CASE TO RESIGN
</HEADLINE>
   (ja) 
 By DAVID W. CHEN    
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ In a decision that surprised legal observers and led
to speculation about its timing, the lead federal prosecutor in the
Abner Louima case said Tuesday that she would resign and return to
her former job at a private law firm in Manhattan.
</P>
<P>
   The announcement by Catherine Palmer, an assistant U.S.
attorney, was made three months after the federal government took
over the prosecution of four police officers with the 70th Precinct
in Brooklyn who are accused of a brutal attack on Louima, a Haitian
immigrant, in August. A fifth member of the precinct, a sergeant,
has been indicted and accused of helping the four cover up the
attack.
</P>
<P>
   The case is expected to be among the biggest, and most
explosive, handled in some time by the U.S. attorney's office for
the Eastern District, touching the tender issues of police
brutality, race, civil rights and police cover-ups. Both the U.S.
attorney's office and the lawyers representing the police officers
have begun to delve into the case, and the trial is expected to
begin possibly by the year's end.
</P>
<P>
   Even so, Ms. Palmer said that she could not pass up an
opportunity to rejoin Latham &AMP; Watkins to concentrate on law
involving patents and trademarks. She had worked at that firm from
September 1994 to November 1996, and her time there was bookended
by two stints at the U.S. attorney's office, starting in August
1985.
</P>
<P>
   ``I've been a prosecutor for 11 years, which is a long time,''
Ms. Palmer said in a telephone interview. ``I'm 42, and it's time
for me to move on to something else.''
</P>
<P>
   Ms. Palmer's resignation, which was reported this week in The
Village Voice, surprised many in the legal world. She has a
reputation of being tenacious and fiercely competitive, a star
prosecutor who reportedly relished the chance to work on the Louima
case.
</P>
<P>
   Her resignation comes at a controversial juncture. On Friday,
The New York Post reported that the FBI was investigating whether
federal prosecutors and agents and New York police detectives tried
to coerce testimony from witnesses and to strengthen the testimony
of other potential grand jury witnesses.
</P>
<P>
   Tuesday, Ms. Palmer and William Muller, a spokesman for the U.S.
attorney's office in Brooklyn, declined to comment on that report.
But Ms. Palmer said that it was ridiculous to infer that her
resignation was related to an investigation, whispered or realized,
by the FBI.
</P>
<P>
   ``There is absolutely nothing to it, and that's the truth,''
said Ms. Palmer, adding that she told her boss, Zachary Carter, the
U.S. attorney in Brooklyn, about her resignation in early May.
``Unfortunately, I'm just the victim of some bad timing with the
Post article last Friday.''
</P>
<P>
   Shortly after joining the U.S. attorney's office in 1985, Ms.
Palmer began to concentrate on Southeast Asian heroin smuggling.
She quickly earned a reputation as a tough and vigilant prosecutor,
picking up the sobriquet of ``Dragon Lady'' from drug smugglers. In
1990, Ms. Palmer barely escaped an assassination attempt from a
booby-trapped package sent to her office.
</P>
<P>
   She left the U.S. attorney's office in 1994 to work for Latham &AMP;
Watkins. But she returned to government work less than two years
later, telling friends that being a prosecutor was more exciting
than private practice.
</P>
<P>
   Three months ago, she was assigned the Louima case _ a plum,
high-pressure job.
</P>
<P>
   The authorities contend that Louima was beaten in a police car
by four officers after being arrested outside a Flatbush nightclub
after a brawl. The authorities say that one of those officers then
rammed a stick into Louima's rectum while another officer held him
down.
</P>
<P>
   The state later indicted Justin Volpe, Thomas Wiese, Charles
Schwarz and Thomas Bruder on assault charges, and Volpe and Schwarz
on sexual abuse charges.
</P>
<P>
   In February, the federal government took over the prosecution,
citing a variety of civil rights charges, and indicted Sgt. Michael
Bellomo, accusing him of helping the four cover the case up.
</P>
<P>
   On Tuesday, in light of Ms. Palmer's resignation, Muller said
that her partner on the Louima case, Ken Thompson, would continue
with the prosecution. He will be joined by Loretta Lynch, chief
assistant U.S. attorney, and Margaret Giordano, a member of the
special prosecutions unit.
</P>
<P>
   Ms. Palmer's last day at the U.S. attorney's office is Friday.
Her first day back at her old firm is on Monday.
</P>
<P>
   Tuesday, defense lawyers in the Louima case were still trying to
absorb the news.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm a little dismayed because I know Cathy Palmer's personal
honesty and integrity and I think the case will sorely miss her,''
said Joseph Tacopina, whose client is Wiese.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
