<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-NY-ARRESTS-NOTIFY-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
POLICE DID NOT TELL CHILD AGENCY BEFORE MAKING ARRESTS 
</HEADLINE>
  (mk) 
 By BENJAMIN WEISER   
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ Police acknowledged Tuesday that they had failed to
notify New York City's child welfare agency before arresting a
Bronx couple charged with running a large-scale drug operation in
which their young sons were said to have been used as couriers of
drugs and money.
</P>
<P>
   The boys, who are 6 and 10, were left after the arrests with a
relative who lives in the same building where their father was
accused of basing a lucrative narcotics operation. In asserting on
Monday that it had told the city's administration for Children's
Services about the children before going out to arrest their
parents on Friday and Saturday, the Police Department left the
impression that the child welfare agency had delayed in acting to
help the children.
</P>
<P>
   But Tuesday, Marilyn Mode, the Police Department's deputy
commissioner for public information, confirmed the child welfare
agency's statement that police had not alerted it until Monday
afternoon. ``I was given inaccurate information,'' she said.
</P>
<P>
   Leonora Wiener, a spokeswoman for the child welfare agency, said
that the agency had not learned about the case from police until
Monday afternoon, and moved quickly to put the boys and their two
teen-age sisters in foster care. The boys received medical
examinations Tuesday and were to be placed with a foster family,
possibly as early as Tuesday night, she said.
</P>
<P>
   The custody questions were raised after New York City Police and
federal Drug Enforcement Administration agents arrested the boys'
father, Manuel Grullon, on Friday and their mother, Maria Polanco,
on Saturday at their apartment building at 162 W. 165th St.,
leaving the children in the care of a relative who lives in a
nearby building.
</P>
<P>
   The government said in court papers that Grullon and several
associates ran a drug trafficking operation from that building, at
1055 University Ave., in a group of apartments they controlled, as
well as from inside its lobby and from a bodega on the ground
floor.
</P>
<P>
   Prosecutors said on Monday that the University Avenue building
had long been the site of pervasive drug dealing.
</P>
<P>
   In all, prosecutors said, more than two dozen of Grullon's
associates and customers were charged in the joint investigation by
police and the DEA, which lasted eight months.
</P>
<P>
   One law enforcement official said that Grullon's organization
sold as much as $50,000 a week in heroin, cocaine, and crack
cocaine in the High Bridge section of the Bronx and elsewhere.
Grullon told one witness, who was secretly cooperating with the
government, that he controlled ``most of the narcotics business''
in the University Avenue area of the Bronx, according to a federal
complaint signed by two federal prosecutors in Manhattan, Steven
Peikin and Laura Birger.
</P>
<P>
   That complaint, which was unsealed on Monday, describes two
instances earlier this year in which it says Grullon used his sons
in drug deals, in both cases to carry crack cocaine in their
jackets.
</P>
<P>
   In one instance on Feb. 3, Grullon negotiated a drug deal in a
car, and told the buyer _ a convicted drug dealer working
undercover for the Drug Enforcement Administration _ that he would
send his son to collect the payment, the complaint says.
</P>
<P>
   Several minutes later, one of Grullon's sons _ the document did
not say which _ entered the car, removed a bag containing about 100
grams of crack cocaine from his pocket and gave it to the buyer.
The customer gave the boy $2,400, and the boy left the car, the
complaint says.
</P>
<P>
   Grullon and his family lived at 162 W. 165th St., and a neighbor
said in an interview Monday night that although their four children
tended to play loudly, they were polite and appeared to be in good
health. The neighbor, Barbara Colon, said that Grullon's young sons
especially enjoyed playing handball.
</P>
<P>
   Emma Rodriguez, who is married to the building's superintendent,
said: ``They are good tenants, no problems. The kids are OK.
They're good kids.''
</P>
<P>
   She said that when police and federal drug agents arrested Ms.
Polanco on Saturday morning, the children had to be roused from
their sleep. ``They took the kids out to the hallway and told them
to put their hands up,'' Ms. Rodriguez said. ``The children were
all crying and so was their mother.''
</P>
<P>
   Ms. Rodriguez said that police ``asked me if I would take care
of the kids because their mother is arrested.'' She said that she
kept the children until their aunt, Ms. Polanco's sister, Carina,
who lives at the 1055 University Ave. address, called on Saturday
afternoon and picked up the four children.
</P>
<P>
   If convicted, both Grullon, 38, and Ms. Polanco, 37, could be
sentenced to life in prison. The parents are being held without
bail pending further proceedings. Lawyers for both have declined
comment.
</P>
</TEXT>
