<P>
   KOSOVO-U.S.-ASSESS (Washington) _ News analysis: While the
Europeans and the United States belatedly apply some economic
sanctions on Yugoslav President Slobodan Milosevic, officials say
there is little agreement about how to achieve a peaceful end. By
Steven Erlanger.
</P>
<P>
   INDONESIA-CHINESE (Jakarta, Indonesia) _ In addition to looting
and arson that targeted Chinese neighborhoods in three days of
rioting last month, human rights and women's aid groups have begun
to document what they say appears to have been an organized
campaign of assaults, gang rapes and killings of ethnic Chinese
women. By Seth Mydans.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; NATIONAL _ GENERAL (Moved in ``a'' category) &LR;
</P>
<P>
   DIET-SUPPLEMENTS-HEALTH (Farmington, Utah) _ Here in the heart
of the nation's herbal and vitamin industry, a company called
Pharmanex produces 600 milligram capsules of a pulverized strain of
rice that appears to lower cholesterol. McGlashan calls Cholestin a
dietary supplement. Officials at the FDA call it something else: an
illegal, unapproved drug. On June 15, in Salt Lake City, a federal
judge will be asked to determine who is correct. The case is being
watched as a pivotal battle between the food and drug agency and
the dietary supplement industry. By Sheryl Gay Stolberg.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; WASHINGTON _ (Moved in ``w'' category)  &LR;
</P>
<P>
   MEDICARE-BENEFITS _ Thirty-eight million Medicare beneficiaries
will soon be flooded with information about new health insurance
options, and most of them are likely to be thoroughly confused,
according to consumer advocates, members of Congress and Medicare
officials. By Robert Pear.
</P>
<P>
   CREDITCARDS-BANKRUPTCY _ Millions spent in lobbying by credit
card companies to win passage of a bill that would move them up in
the pecking order of claimants. By Katharine Q. Seelye.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; BUSINESS DAY _ (Moved in ``f'' category)  &LR;
</P>
<P>
   SIGNING-BONUSES (Undated) _ The sign-on bonus is proliferating
in America as employers, forced to bid for scarce workers, have
shifted some of the bargaining process from wages to less costly
one-time bonus payments. A recruiting tool that had been limited to
upper-level managers, highly skilled technicians and athletes is
spreading to many others. By Louis Uchitelle.
</P>
<P>
   AIRPORT-MALLS _ It is not easy to squeeze into a dressing room
with two pieces of carry-on luggage and a laptop to try on a pair
of jeans. And the sight of three airline captains hovering over a
table of pink lingerie at Victoria's Secret still draws a second
glance. But such scenes are quietly becoming as integral to air
travel as jet lag, weather delays and nondairy creamer. A number of
airports, somewhat surreal spaces where travelers were once content
to buy a few magazines and stare nervously at a clock, are starting
to look a lot like malls. By Jennifer Steinhauer.
</P>
<P>
   (ART ADV: Graphic has been sent to NYT graphics clients. Photo
has been sent to NYT photo clients.)
</P>
<P>
   GOLDMAN-MARKETPLACE (New York) _ As the partners of Goldman,
Sachs &AMP; Co. debate whether to turn Wall Street's premier private
investment bank into a public company, they might mull this irony:
They are earning record profits advising clients to do deals they
themselves would never do. By Joseph Kahn.
</P>
<P>
   CLOTHIERS-SUIT _ When a Paris court ordered Ralph Lauren to stop
selling knockoffs of Yves Saint Laurent's tuxedo dresses in 1994,
the message was clear: Fashion, at least in France, can be subject
to protection from the scheming scissors of competitors. But here
in the United States, should a simple blue-and-white-striped shirt
enjoy similar sanctuary? That is what a federal judge in Columbus,
Ohio, will have to decide when he considers a lawsuit filed by
Abercrombie &AMP; Fitch, the clothing store, against its competitor
down the mall, American Eagle Outfitters. By Jennifer Steinhauer.
</P>
<P>
   (ART ADV: A photo has been sent to NYT photo clients.)
</P>
<P>
   GODZILLA-AD-COLUMN _ With ``Godzilla'' turning out to be more of
a limping lizard than a leaping lizard at the box office, the
scores of promotional, licensing and merchandising partners that
anticipated the film would be a summer blockbuster must now hope
that size won't matter after all. By Stuart Elliott.
</P>
