<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BBO-NY-DIVERSITY-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
A UNITED NATIONS OF PITCHERS 
</HEADLINE>
  (ja) 
 By MURRAY CHASS   
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ The United Nations is in New York, so why shouldn't
the city's baseball teams look like a United Nations of players.
The pitching staffs, in particular, are taking on that look.
</P>
<P>
   Hideo Nomo, the Mets' newest representative from Japan, made his
first start at Shea Stadium Tuesday night. At the same time,
Orlando Hernandez, who brought the name El Duque with him from
Cuba, pitched for the Yankees in Montreal.
</P>
<P>
   Of the last 16 games _ eight for each team _ eight were started
by pitchers who have come here from other countries: Nomo and
Masato Yoshii, also from Japan, for the Mets, and for the Yankees,
Hernandez, Hideki Irabu from Japan and Ramiro Mendoza from Panama.
</P>
<P>
   At spring training, after Hernandez went through his first
workout with the Yankees, catcher Joe Girardi considered the
potential pitching lineup and said: ``We're going to have quite a
universal staff. Cone is American. Pettitte is French. Irabu is
Japanese. Wells is Martian.''
</P>
<P>
   The Martian has since pitched a perfect game, and Irabu has the
lowest earned run average among starting pitchers in the major
leagues. But when baseball people talk about the
internationalization of the game, they don't mean Mars.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think it's great for New York,'' said Omar Minaya, the Mets'
assistant general manager, who is one of baseball's leading experts
on international scouting. ``The New York fan is very fortunate.
The summer of 1998 is great not only because both teams are doing
well but also because of the different type of players, especially
the pitchers who are taking the mound.''
</P>
<P>
   Baseball is becoming more international. As many of the best
athletes in the United States turn to other sports, major league
organizations have widened their search for talent, mining the
fields of Latin America, scouting the Far East, traveling to
Australia. These days if a team hears about a prospect, it will
send someone to check him out, wherever he lives and plays.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think Nomo coming to New York is the confirmation of this
global type of change in baseball,'' Minaya said. ``New York fans
have a chance to see what is the future of the game.''
</P>
<P>
   Nomo created a major stir when he landed in Los Angeles for the
1995 season. He was the National League rookie of the year that
season, then pitched a no-hitter the following year. His unusual
pitching style, in which he turns away from the batter before
releasing the ball, and his ability to strike out batters in
bunches made him a hit not only with Dodger fans but baseball
followers everywhere.
</P>
<P>
   Nomo, still nearly three months from his 30th birthday, has
slipped with his performance in succeeding seasons and is more or
less on pitching trial with the Mets. If he can regain the form and
consistency that attracted so much early attention, he could become
even bigger than he was with the Dodgers. Los Angeles is big, but
New York is bigger. He would become a star all over again, only
this time a bigger star. On the other hand, if he continues to
pitch ineffectively and inconsistently, he would be written off as
a flash who didn't sizzle in the pan long enough.
</P>
<P>
   With Shea fans noisily wanting to see a vintage performance,
Nomo displayed little sizzle Tuesday night. He struck out five in
five innings, but he gave up five hits, three walks and four runs,
the last on a balk. Dave Mlicki could have done that, in fact did
just that often before the Mets traded him to the Dodgers for Nomo.
</P>
<P>
   Hernandez initially was supposed to return to Columbus after his
impressive debut at Yankee Stadium last Wednesday night, but the
Martian's aching shoulder and the owner's wishes bought him an
extended stay. Now, after pitching a four-hitter in the Yankees'
11-1 victory Tuesday night, he will most likely remain permanently.
Even if Joe Torre wanted to keep Mendoza in the rotation instead of
shifting him to the bullpen, his boss almost certainly would
overrule him. A change in the rotation could have an impact on the
pitching matchups for the interleague series between the Yankees
and the Mets at Shea later this month.
</P>
<P>
   For anyone hoping for a Nomo-Irabu matchup, it won't happen
unless a rainout affects the Mets' schedule. Pitching in rotation,
Nomo would start June 25, the day before the series starts. Yoshii,
though, would start the third game.
</P>
<P>
   Irabu could start against the Mets, depending on how George
Steinbrenner makes out the Yankees' rotation. If Irabu, who starts
in Montreal Wednesday, continues to start every fifth day, he also
will pitch the day before the Yankees play the Mets. But the order
could be changed if El Duque remains in the rotation.
</P>
<P>
   Rey Ordonez, for one, would like to see his countryman pitch
against the Mets. The Mets' shortstop recalled Tuesday that he
faced El Duque in Cuba in 1990. ``He doesn't remember what he did
against him,'' Cookie Rojas, the Mets' coach said acting as
interpreter, ``but he remembers that he had pretty good control and
good command of his pitches.''
</P>
<P>
   Would Ordonez like to face him again? ``It would be nice to see
him again,'' the shortstop said.
</P>
<P>
   That matchup remains to be seen, but there's no question that
Hernandez, if not now in the near future, will add a Cuban flavor
to New York's U.N. pitching platoon. But with the Mets providing an
integral part of that platoon, it will put to the test the status
of the New York Mayor as host to this United Nations. A good host
would appear at Shea to greet the foreign guests. The mayor, alas,
has shown no inclination to make that gesture. He continues to
recognize only the Yankee delegation. &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
