<DATE_TIME> 1998-06-09 23:10 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A1905 &Cx1f; ttj-z
u a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-JASPER-SUSPECTS-HNS &LR;      06-09 1211
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-JASPER-SUSPECTS-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
NEIGHBOR RECALLS SUSPECTS IN TEXAS MURDER AS BEING `JUST WILD' 

</HEADLINE>
  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  By T.J. MILLING 
and RONNIE CROCKER 
c.1998 Houston Chronicle 
<TEXT>
<P>
   JASPER, Texas _ Neighbors in the tiny Timbers Apartments complex
knew him as Bill, an extensively tattooed ex-con, prejudiced but
not overtly so, apparently trying to get his act together after
getting out of prison.
</P>
<P>
   John William King didn't have any racist paraphernalia in his
weathered but tidy one-bedroom apartment, at least not when the
manager visited it recently. His white supremacist tattoos might
have been a hint, but nobody got close enough to make them out.
</P>
<P>
   Shawn Allen Berry was just a polite buddy who stopped by a
little too often, ``not the ring leader type,'' said the apartment
manager who declined to give her name.
</P>
<P>
   Two or three weeks ago, Lawrence Russell Brewer showed up,
tattoos dotting his arms, supposedly just a friend in from Dallas
for a week's visit, the manager said. In reality, he, like the
others, was a veteran of the Texas Department of Criminal Justice.
</P>
<P>
   Once Brewer arrived, things started to get a little rowdy,
late-night drinking bouts, some marijuana smoking and a few
screaming matches with sundry girlfriends, but nothing the likes of
the crime the three now stand accused of, the gruesome murder of a
black man.
</P>
<P>
   ``I just thought they were just wild,'' said L. Cartwright,
King's neighbor. ``I look at prejudice as ignorance, so I thought
they were just ignorant. I really didn't know they had that type of
hate inside.''
</P>
<P>
   Cartwright, who is black, said the management had warned him
when he moved in that his neighbor was prejudiced. He said he could
``feel'' King's racism but there wasn't any one thing he could put
his finger on to prove it. King was just distant, said hello just
once in the six weeks Cartwright lived there, his front door one
small step away from King's.
</P>
<P>
   Several other neighbors confirmed Cartwright's account: the boys
were rambunctious and loud, but didn't seem particularly dangerous
or outwardly racist. They didn't even sport Confederate flags on
their cars, which is not uncommon in this area.
</P>
<P>
   For the first few weeks Cartwright lived there, he said, King,
23, was apparently staying on the straight and narrow, living a
fairly quiet life with his 17-year-old pregnant girlfriend, who
worked at a hamburger joint. But after Brewer showed up and Berry
started coming around more often, the parties started and the
relationship with the girl soured.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think that's when he started going back to his old ways,''
Cartwright said.
</P>
<P>
   The girl showed up a few more times, once to write an
expletive-laced note in the dust on King's new girlfriend's Ford
Bronco. ``I'm pregnant with Bill's baby,'' it said.
</P>
<P>
   The couple's shouting matches, similar ones between Berry and
his girlfriend and the late night parties led to complaints from
neighbors and eventual eviction proceedings by the management.
</P>
<P>
   But King headed the manager off in court, got the judge to give
him time to clean up his act. ``He was running me around,'' she
said. ``He was smart.''
</P>
<P>
   She posted another eviction notice on King's door June 2, but it
took the Jasper County Sheriff's Department's arrest of the three
Sunday to really get him out. On Tuesday, a handwritten notice,
stating ``Evicted!'' and dated the day before was plastered on the
apartment door.
</P>
<P>
   Neighbors stood in the yard shaking their heads at the turn of
events.
</P>
<P>
   ``He (King) never did anything racist,'' Cartwright said. ``He
just wasn't very friendly ... You know, just someone not to mess
with.''
</P>
<P>
   Records show King had done two stints in Texas prisons. First,
he received 10 years for a burglary in Jasper County but was
released on shock probation in early 1993. He returned as a parole
violator in June 1995, and was released to Orange County last July.
He had served his time at the Jester 2 Unit in Richmond.
</P>
<P>
   Berry, also 23, was a co-defendant with King and also was
sentenced to 10 years for the Jasper County burglary. Prison
records show he arrived at Jester 2 in October 1992 and was
released on shock probation the following January.
</P>
<P>
   Still, news of Berry's arrest was a shock to others who knew him
in Jasper. Mike Twine, a 21-year-old black man, said he used to
compete against him in local rodeos.
</P>
<P>
   ``I never thought he'd do anything like this,'' said Twine, who
said Berry seemed like a friendly individual with no hatred for
blacks.
</P>
<P>
   When Lawrence Brewer Sr.'s son arrived home in Sulphur Springs
from his latest trip to the penitentiary, there was one striking
change: Tattoos covered much of both arms.
</P>
<P>
   The elder Brewer said he told him getting the tattoos was ``a
sickness.''
</P>
<P>
   The exchange was typically tense for a father and son who had
grown estranged over the younger man's drug use and legal problems
from the time he was 18 or 19 years old. The young man left in a
huff.
</P>
<P>
   Authorities say the tattoos indicate the ex-con's affiliation
with the white supremacy movement. That comes as another sad
surprise to his father, a retired infantry soldier who served in
Vietnam and spent 20 years in the Army. He swears his son was not
reared like that.
</P>
<P>
   ``That's as great a shock to me as what they done,'' he said
from his Sulphur Springs home in northeast Texas. Traveling the
country in the military his three sons and two daughters went to
school and church with numerous blacks and Hispanics, he said, with
no troubling incidents.
</P>
<P>
   ``If he was involved in any type activity like that, it had to
be when he was in the pen.''
</P>
<P>
   Brewer described his son as a ``normal kid'' who dropped out of
school in the 11th grade but went on to earn an equivalency
diploma. ``He's no dummy,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   The problems started, Brewer said, with serious drug abuse in
the young man's late teens. That was something he could not abide
of someone living at his home.
</P>
<P>
   Prison records show the younger Brewer, now 31, served time in
the Beto I prison unit at Tennessee Colony. He was incarcerated on
a seven-year sentence for breaking into a house in July 1987, then
paroled the following February; went back with 15 years on a drug
possession charge in May 1989, then was paroled in May 1991; was
returned to prison on a parole violation in February 1994 and got
out again last September.
</P>
<P>
   Lawrence Brewer Sr. said he thought his son had straightened out
his life this time, but that he went through a series of jobs and
left the area after a breakup with his girlfriend _ presumably on a
bus bound for Houston. He said he had not seen his son in about six
months and had never even heard of Jasper. He received word of the
latest arrest from a friend who had seen a news report.
</P>
<P>
   Brewer said that, if his son is guilty, he deserves whatever
punishment is coming. His sympathy, he said, is reserved for Byrd's
family and for his own wife who is grieving for their son.
</P>
<P>
   ``I sure feel sympathy for the victim in this case,'' Brewer Sr.
said. He repeated the sentiment several times.
</P>
<P>
   ``If the color of your skin is gonna cause you to be killed,''
he said, finally, ``there's something wrong with society.''
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &QL; 
XXXX END OF STORY &QL;
</P>
