<SLUG> BC-NY-TAXES-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
BUDGET FEUD COULD RESULT IN HIGHER PROPERTY TAXES 
</HEADLINE>
  (mk) 
 By NORIMITSU ONISHI   
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ The political deadlock over the shape of the city's
next budget could cause owners of single-, two- and three-family
houses to pay about $50 more in taxes in the next fiscal year. And
the Council and the mayor's office blamed each other for the
increase.
</P>
<P>
   In the past, the mayor's office and the City Council were able
to persuade the state Legislature to allow the city to manipulate
property tax rates to keep property taxes for those homeowners
artificially low. But Tuesday, aides to Mayor Rudolph Giuliani and
Speaker Peter Vallone said that because of the budget feud, it was
unlikely that the two men would make the trip together this year to
Albany to lobby for the legislation.
</P>
<P>
   Vallone and Giuliani have been locked in fiscal gamesmanship
since the Council defied the mayor and passed its own budget last
Friday. On Monday, the Council _ as it usually does in June _
reviewed the city's property tax rates and left the overall rate
unchanged. But taxes will rise for those homeowners unless a state
rate is also changed.
</P>
<P>
   Each side vowed Tuesday to try to persuade the
Democratic-controlled Assembly and the Republican-controlled Senate
to agree on a bill to limit the increases.
</P>
<P>
   ``We will go to Albany ourselves,'' said Randy Mastro, deputy
mayor for operations. ``The mayor will try to reverse this
situation himself.''
</P>
<P>
   Thomas McMahon, the director of the Council's Finance Division,
said the Council had, on its own, persuaded Assembly leaders
Tuesday to introduce a bill to limit the increases.
</P>
<P>
   ``If the Giuliani administration is ready to join us, mazel
tov,'' McMahon said.
</P>
<P>
   Taxes on property from single-family homes to condominiums to
skyscrapers are calculated each year according to a complicated
city and state formula based on property market value. In previous
years, the mayor and the Council have lobbied together to limit the
increases on the politically influential group of owners of single-
and two- and three-family homes, essentially keeping the rate flat.
</P>
<P>
   But this year _ because the mayor and speaker failed to lobby
Albany to reduce that percentage from its 5 percent level _ the
taxes levied on property owners will more closely reflect their
real market value, fiscal experts said.
</P>
<P>
   That has left those owners facing an average $50 a year increase
in property taxes, while the city's co-op, condo and
apartment-building owners will actually benefit with decreases
averaging $65.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is one of the benefits of little skirmishes between the
mayor and the Council,'' said Raymond Horton, president of the
Citizens Budget Commission. ``Finally, we're getting property tax
reform because the mayor and Council cannot agree on a budget.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
