<HEADER>
A1928 &Cx1f; taf-z
s e &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-DANCE-JACOBS-PILLOW-A     06-09 1286
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-DANCE-JACOBS-PILLOW-ART-$ADV14-700&AMP;add-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
NEW SPICE FOR A STAPLE OF SUMMER 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (ATTN: Mass., N.C., Fla.)  
 (For release Sun., June 14)   (ART ADV: Photo is being sent to NYT photo clients. Non-subscribers
can make individual purchase by calling 212-556-4204 or 1927 .) 
 (JT)  
 By JENNIFER DUNNING    
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   On June 23, when the nation's oldest summer dance festival opens
in tiny Becket, Mass., it will have a new director, Ella Baff.
Running Jacob's Pillow Dance Festival is hard work, but Ms. Baff is
full of ambitious visions. For one thing, she would like to give
the 10-week event a stronger musical profile. For another, she
talks excitedly about winterizing the Pillow's rustic cabins so
that artists can work there year round.
</P>
<P>
   Some of those cabins date back to the early 1930s, when the
modern-dance pioneer Ted Shawn and his Men Dancers company built a
handful of studios on lush sprawling farmland in Becket in the
Berkshires.
</P>
<P>
   Performances began in 1932, at first for elderly dowagers in the
area. But by the 1940s, after Shawn's company had disbanded, the
Pillow was well on its way to becoming a festival known and
cherished for its smorgasbord approach to dance, with each program
a wildly diverse mix of genres.
</P>
<P>
   Though bigger, sleeker and internationally known now, the Pillow
has retained a good deal of its early atmosphere, remaining a home
away from home, where dancers and choreographers can create as well
as present new work. For Ms. Baff, who was appointed in April, it
is a sanctuary for thought as well as action. ``It's a very
peaceful place, a spiritual place,'' she said. ``An ideal
environment for sound thinking.''
</P>
<P>
   Looking over the lineup of attractions at the festival, which
opens with performances by Ballet Hispanico and the Bebe Miller
Company, one could be forgiven for assuming that the Pillow might
be a pretty hectic place for reflection.
</P>
<P>
   There will be programs by 19 companies and solo dancers in the
two theaters, with additional events on an informal outdoor stage.
Eleven dances and works-in-progress have been commissioned by the
Pillow, which won this year's prestigious Capezio Award for service
to the field.
</P>
<P>
   Listening to Ms. Baff's intense and far-ranging conversation in
a Manhattan restaurant, it soon becomes clear that she relishes
meeting challenges head-on.
</P>
<P>
   She comes to the Pillow via Cal Performances, which produces
arts events at the University of California at Berkeley, where she
was program director and director of education and community
projects. Growing up in New York City in an arts-conscious family
that also produced the stage actress Regina Baff, she studied music
as well as dance. ``To this day, music is one of the most important
things in my life,'' said Ms. Baff, who declined to give her age.
</P>
<P>
   ``It was never in my mind to be an arts administrator,'' she
continued. ``In fact, it makes me wince on a certain level. There
was no such thing as `arts administration' when I was coming up.
But I certainly respect the field, which is primarily about
supporting artists and having the arts be better appreciated by the
public.''
</P>
<P>
   Being an arts administrator is also about having a passion for
the arts, she added, citing Ivan Sygoda, a director of the Pentacle
performing-arts service organization and a tireless dancegoer, as
epitomizing ``the love and internal understanding of the arts''
that are central to good administration.
</P>
<P>
   Presenting artists and developing community programs at Cal
Performances, known for the adventurousness of its dance
productions, was also good preparation for her new job. As director
of education, Ms. Baff created more than 100 programs that brought
audiences and artists together and offered young people
opportunities to immerse themselves in the arts.
</P>
<P>
   Ms. Baff has arrived at a festival that only recently, under the
direction of the previous director, Sali Ann Kriegsman, pulled
itself back from the brink of bankruptcy. ``The board and staff
demonstrated an exemplary institutional will,'' Ms. Baff said.
``Businesses go through this. Arts organizations go through this.
The measure of success to me is not so much what happened but the
result produced. Now the big work occurs to keep the Pillow
healthy. The need for contributions is never-ending.''
</P>
<P>
   The festival's operating budget for the 1997-98 season is $3.2
million. The Pillow has paid off its deficit and plans to invest a
$1 million grant from the Doris Duke Charitable Foundation so that
interest may be accumulated to pay for commissioning works and
much-needed repairs to its 150-acre site, an important part of
American cultural history, as well as a stop on the Underground
Railroad.
</P>
<P>
   This season's performers were chosen by Ms. Kriegsman, but Ms.
Baff worked on the programming. That has helped her to envision
some future directions for the festival.
</P>
<P>
   ``This summer,'' she said, ``we have a very, very compelling
group of composers working with our choreographers. Mark Morris
will collaborate with John Harbison, and the choreographer Joanna
Haigood and the composer and singer Linda Tillery have created a
site-specific piece that evokes the experiences of slaves fleeing
north on the Underground Railroad.''
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   Ms. Baff is excited about the mix of jazz composers and
choreographers who are collaborating this season, among them Bebe
Miller with Don Byron, Donald Byrd with Max Roach, Vernon Reid with
Geri Allen. Most dance companies cannot afford to pay musicians and
perform to taped scores, but Dianne McIntyre will appear with the
jazz composer Lester Bowie and his Brass Fantasy. ``I'd like to be
able to have them all come up and participate,'' Ms. Baff said.
</P>
<P>
   She hopes the emphasis on jazz will draw more music lovers to
the Pillow and is plotting a means to attract Berkshires theater
lovers and antiques hunters as well. ``Two million people pass
through the Berkshires each summer,'' she said. ``Of course I want
them all to come to the Pillow. I want to encourage more public
access at the Pillow. I want to encourage people to see the entire
picture of Jacob's Pillow. The whole is greater than the parts,
though the parts are quite incredible, too.''
</P>
<P>
   Ms. Baff would also like to make it possible for visitors to
watch occasional classes and rehearsals, or, while strolling
through the grounds, to catch glimpses of conversing artists like
Meredith Monk and Edward Villella, director of the Miami City
Ballet, both of whom will be at the Pillow this summer.
</P>
<P>
   There are many opportunities, Ms. Baff said, to capture the
``accidental audience'' as it passes by and to provide chances for
learning in a casual but stimulating way _ ``the kind of planned
spontaneous combustion that is very exciting for everyone,'' she
explained.
</P>
<P>
   ``I Want the public to consider dance in the broadest and
richest way,'' she said. ``I'd like to present more dance from
other countries. While I want to support the home team, I also have
a big appetite for the world. Wherever you travel, there is better
and less good art. I don't care if it's from Bali or the Bronx. I'm
looking for work that is going to engage people.''
</P>
<P>
   The nation's other major summer dance festival, the American
Dance Festival in Durham, N.C., has always been affiliated with
academic institutions. But when the school year begins, the Durham
festival must end. The Pillow, on the other hand, could operate all
year. Even now, a few artists work there in the fall and spring. If
the studios and living spaces were winterized, Ms. Baff said, they
could have year-round residencies.
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
