<HEADER>
A1929 &Cx1f; taf-z
s e &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-KEN-LOACH-MOVIES-$ADV     06-09 1031
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-KEN-LOACH-MOVIES-$ADV14-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
AN UNREPENTANT LEFTIST MOVES BACK INTO SIGHT 
</HEADLINE>
   (For release Sun., June 14)  
 (JT)  
 By ALAN RIDING    
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   LONDON _ Surprisingly perhaps, given his distaste for the
prevailing social order, Ken Loach was never an angry young man.
Shy and soft-spoken, he was almost 30 by the time he set off down
the path that three decades later earned him recognition in Europe
as the dean of leftist movie makers. Until then, he simply
personified the new social mobility of postwar Britain: born of a
``working-class Tory'' father, he did his military service in the
Royal Air Force, studied law at Oxford University, tried his hand
at acting and then joined the BBC as a television director.
</P>
<P>
   Yet at the BBC, he turned radical, making his name in 1966 with
a television docudrama called ``Cathy Come Home,'' which for the
first time denounced homelessness in Britain. And well into the
1970s, in the tradition of Italian neo-realists like Vittorio De
Sica, Loach continued to make television and feature films with
strong social content. Then, in 1979, Prime Minister Margaret
Thatcher started her conservative revolution, and financing
evaporated for his kind of socialist realism.
</P>
<P>
   ``If the British movie industry at the time had any perception
of what I did, it was that I made films in an impenetrable dialect,
driven by a kind of hard-line Marxist view, which no one would want
to see,'' Loach, 61, recalled in a recent interview over coffee at
a bookstore in central London, ``and, if they did want to see them,
they wouldn't understand them anyway.''
</P>
<P>
   By the late 1980s, however, the pendulum had begun to swing away
from Thatcherism. Britain had changed: it was no longer a nation
with an economy dominated by government-owned industries and
powerful trade unions, and awareness of the social cost of factory
and mine closings was growing. Suddenly, thanks to backing from
Britain's Channel Four Films, Loach was able to work again.
Starting in 1990 with ``Hidden Agenda,'' set in troubled Northern
Ireland, he demonstrated with a series of small-budget movies that
he was just as energetic and politically committed as he had ever
been. For some in Britain, his ideological drumbeating seemed
antiquated, but he was unfazed.
</P>
<P>
   ``Carla's Song,'' which was made in 1996 and opens in New York
on June 26, is the fifth movie of his comeback. The others are
``Riff-Raff'' (1991), about union-busting in the construction
industry; ``Raining Stones'' (1993), about a grim housing project
in Manchester; ``Ladybird, Ladybird'' (1994), about a distraught
single mother of four, and ``Land and Freedom'' (1995), about the
Spanish Civil War. ``My Name Is Joe,'' which was finished recently
and has no release date in the United States yet, was well received
at the Cannes International Film Festival last month, with Peter
Mullan winning the best actor's award for his role as a reformed
alcoholic struggling to rebuild his life in a rundown Glasgow
neighborhood.
</P>
<P>
   ``Carla's Song,'' though, is unusual in that Loach takes his
story outside Britain. He did this once before, in ``Land and
Freedom,'' which follows a young Englishman who volunteers to fight
against Franco's forces in the late 1930s. But in ``Carla's Song''
he has tackled an international conflict that until recently at
least was highly topical: the war that pitted the United
States-backed contras against Nicaragua's leftist Sandinista
government during much of the 1980s.
</P>
<P>
   Set in 1987, the film starts in Glasgow. George, a bus driver
played by Robert Carlyle (``Trainspotting,'' ``The Full Monty'')
meets and is smitten with Carla (Oyanka Cabezas), a young
Sandinista exile who dances on sidewalks to make ends meet. He
offers to help her, but Carla is hesitant, only slowly revealing
her pain at fleeing Nicaragua's war and at abandoning a badly
wounded boyfriend. George tries to distract her, taking her for a
drive around Loch Lomond in his double-decker bus. But eventually
he concludes that she has to return home and that he will go with
her.
</P>
<P>
   In Nicaragua, speaking nothing but English with a strong
Glaswegian accent, George feels he has arrived on a different
planet. But through Carla he meets peasants who boast of the
Sandinistas' land-distribution program, and he learns that the
United States is trying to crush the revolution. He is also caught
in a contra attack on a Sandinista village and wonders just what he
is doing there: he has followed a woman and found himself in a war.
</P>
<P>
   ``We didn't want the usual device of the fearless reporter or
the person who goes there with the aim of discovery,'' Loach
explained. ``The point was to take a guy who is a humorous,
thoughtful guy but who doesn't even know where Nicaragua is. We
wanted a person drawn in against his wishes.''
</P>
<P>
   The idea for the film came from Paul Laverty, 41, a Glasgow
lawyer who did human-rights work in Nicaragua in the mid-1980s and
who in 1992 sent Loach a movie treatment out of the blue. The
director encouraged Laverty to try his hand at screenwriting, and
after three years of writing and rewriting, the script for
``Carla's Song'' was completed. ( Laverty also wrote ``My Name Is
Joe.'') Of course, by the time the Nicaraguan section of the film
was shot, early in 1996, the fighting was long over and the
Sandinistas had been voted out of office. But Loach was soon
persuaded that the United States had been the guilty party in the
war.
</P>
<P>
   ``My judgment in the end was that if the Americans had not
intervened,'' he said, ``a lot of things that went wrong with the
Sandinistas would not have gone wrong because it came out of their
inevitable inability to keep the revolution afloat.''
</P>
<P>
   Carlyle, who has been a great admirer of Loach's political
engagement since they worked together on ``Riff-Raff,'' said that
like his character in ``Carla's Song,'' he had experienced deep
culture shock arriving in Nicaragua.
</P>
<P>
   ``In no way can you be prepared for that kind of third-world
poverty,'' he said. ``It affected me profoundly. A lot of people
who know me well said it changed me. It made me see things
differently.''
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
