<HEADER>
A1943 &Cx1f; tic-z
r a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-DOMESTICVIOLENCE-AZR &LR;      06-09 0982
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-DOMESTIC </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
FOUNDER OF DOMESTIC ABUSE SHELTERS EXPANDS SERVICES
</HEADLINE>
 VIOLENCE-AZR   (For use by N.Y. Times News Service clients)  
 By JULIE AMPARANO  
 c.1998 The Arizona Republic  
<TEXT>
<P>
   She wanted him to die that night.
</P>
<P>
   For nearly four years, Betty DellaCorte Ryan had endured her
husband's slaps, kicks and punches. They often left her in a bloody
mess and heading for the emergency room.
</P>
<P>
   She could tell this night was going to be another bad one by the
way he was ranting and screaming at her. Lately, he had been
threaten ing to pull out his gun.
</P>
<P>
   ``You're shacking up with men,'' Ryan recalls him yelling at
her. Then, he shouted for another beer. That was her cue.
</P>
<P>
   She walked into the kitchen, pulled out a fistful of Valium, got
a beer from the refrigerator and began dropping the capsules into
the can. She was amazed at how calm and natural it all seemed.
</P>
<P>
   `` `One, two, three, four, five, six, seven, eight, nine, ten,
eleven. That should do it,' '' she says she thought to herself. ``I
slept so good that night.''
</P>
<P>
   Her husband passed out before he could finish the beer, but
survived.
</P>
<P>
   That night in 1971 was a turning point for Ryan. It pushed her
to become a pioneer in the battle against domestic violence. In
1974, Ryan founded Faith House, one of the first domestic abuse
shelters in Arizona and the country. Six years later, she opened a
Faith House in Prescott to help victims in less urban areas.
</P>
<P>
   Today, her legacy has grown. There are eight licensed shelters
in Maricopa County, with a little more than 200 beds for domestic
abuse victims. Other agencies, such as homeless shelters, also
provide beds to domestic violence victims.
</P>
<P>
   In July, she expects to break ground on a 5-acre domestic vio
lence center with services that will include plastic surgery to
repair damage, counseling for batterers and victims, crisis housing
for victims and job training. The shel ter, she says, will be
called Prospect Park, after a place in Brooklyn where she sought
refuge from an abusive home.
</P>
<P>
   Sitting in her patio office last week, Ryan looked back on her
65 years of life. So much of it, she says, seems like such a
distant nightmare. &UR; Nights she spent crouched in her front-yard
bushes to escape the beatings. All the bruises she tried to cover
with makeup. A broken nose. And the time she woke up with a gun to
her head and he pulled the trigger.
</P>
<P>
   The gun was empty that time. And she vowed there would be no
next time. She filed for divorce the next day.
</P>
<P>
   She was already attending classes at Al-Anon, a 12-step program
for families of alcoholics. It helped her understand why she stayed
with her abuser and how she could break the cycle of violence she
kept repeating and repeating.
</P>
<P>
   Turning and looking out the window, Ryan says her life had
always been a violent one. She recounts a childhood memory.
</P>
<P>
   She is 4 years old and in the kitchen of her Brooklyn home,
clinging to the front of her mother's legs. Her mother has her arms
wrapped around her, trying to block the blows to the child's back.
</P>
<P>
   Still, her father continues to beat her until she slides down
her mother's apron, catches her two front teeth on it and they rip
out.
</P>
<P>
   ``They were loose already,'' Ryan said. ``See, even to this day
I tend to minimalize it.''
</P>
<P>
   Minimalizing and rationalizing was how Ryan says she made it
through life.
</P>
<P>
   First, she did it for her father. Later, it was for her first
and second husbands.
</P>
<P>
   Her first husband also had been abusive. Ryan says he was very
controlling and criticized everything she did. By the time she
divorced him in 1963, after 11 years of marriage and the birth of
two daughters, she says, she had little self-esteem left and fell
victim to a physically abusive second husband.
</P>
<P>
   ``That was all I knew,'' confesses Ryan, who divorced her second
husband after 3{ years. ``I didn't know there was any other way.''
</P>
<P>
   Al-Anon, Ryan says, helped her realize she had choices. It also
got her started in the domestic violence field. From her Al-Anon
meetings, Ryan had met other women who were being beaten by their
hus bands. She began offering them and their children shelter in
her home.
</P>
<P>
   ``I would wake up in the morn ing and see these women and
children asleep in our living room,'' recalls Lisa Gebhardt, Ryan's
38-year-old daughter. ``At first, I really resented it. I wanted
nothing to do with it.''
</P>
<P>
   Today, Lisa and her sister, Robin Burke, are part of the Faith
House team. Robin runs the Prescott shel ter and Lisa manages the
alternative programs in Phoenix.
</P>
<P>
   After two years of taking domes tic violence victims into her
home, Ryan decided to convert her resi dence officially into the
first do mestic abuse shelter.
</P>
<P>
   For five years, the shelter ran only with volunteers and
donations. Later, bingo games helped fund the programs and build
the Prescott facility.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's been a constant struggle for funding. We've had to work
so hard for every dollar we get,'' Ryan says. ``I remember going to
the food bank to put meals on the table for the women. We still
have to do that.''
</P>
<P>
   At first, Ryan would do practi cally everything. Her right-hand
assistant was _ and still is _ Flo Mills, another domestic abuse
survi vor. The two women would take the victims to Al-Anon meetings
and counseling sessions and wipe away their tears.
</P>
<P>
   ``Actually, we would cry with them,'' says Ryan, who today
mostly handles chief executive duties, such as securing funding,
and lobbies for stricter laws.
</P>
<P>
   Reflecting on how her life has changed, Ryan wants to provide
hope to other women.
</P>
<P>
   ``Look at me. People told me it couldn't be done. They told me
what I had was a dream and they couldn't invest in a dream,'' Ryan
says. ``That's why we call it Faith House, because it was built on
faith.'' &QL; 
 &UR; Julie Amparano can be reached at
 &UR; 444-8394 or at julie.amparano &LR; pni.com via
 &UR; e-mail. &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
