<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-NY-BUDGET-ASSESS-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
ANALYSIS: BUDGET FEUD SEEMS HEADED FOR COURT 
</HEADLINE>
  (mk) 
 By DAN BARRY   
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ The nasty skirmish that Mayor Rudolph Giuliani and
the speaker of the City Council, Peter Vallone, are engaged in
along the margins of a $34 billion budget will most likely end up
in court.
</P>
<P>
   Until then, those on both sides say, the public will witness the
stuff that suffices for high drama in City Hall: The rare execution
of mayoral vetoes. The equally rare override of those
budget-related vetoes by a Council not known for inviting
confrontation. The eventual freezing of city funds. And the
possibility that the tensions between the city's two most powerful
leaders will have repercussions for years to come.
</P>
<P>
   All this will play out with a touch of the politically absurd,
given that the city enjoys a $2 billion surplus, more than enough
under normal circumstances to strike friendships among enemies.
</P>
<P>
   ``Now it's tit-for-tat stuff,'' said Thomas McMahon, the
Council's budget director. ``And it's definitely unfortunate.''
</P>
<P>
   For those joining ``Budget: The Movie'' in midshowing, here is a
brief synopsis:
</P>
<P>
   Budget negotiations ended about two weeks ago, virtually before
they began, and the two sides cannot even agree on why. Council
leaders say Giuliani demanded that Vallone drop plans for a
referendum on whether city money should be used to build a
Manhattan stadium for the New York Yankees. The mayor's aides
counter that the Council was intransigent on negotiating various
tax-cut proposals _ although they acknowledge that, yes, Giuliani
has a thing about the referendum.
</P>
<P>
   Vallone quickly seized the opportunity created by the impasse.
For the first time since the city charter's revision in 1989, the
Council on Friday adopted its own budget _ one that was $49 million
less than the budget proposed by the mayor. This act of
independence presented Giuliani with the City Hall equivalent to a
schoolyard double dare: What are you going do about it?
</P>
<P>
   Vallone recently asserted that ``there is no politics in
adopting the budget,'' and that he wanted the City Council to be
seen as something more than a stable of amusing mayoral sidekicks.
But he is running for governor, his referendum plan would bring out
the vote, and he sorely needed to shed his image as a compliant
speaker who has acquiesced to the mayor's budgetary desires in the
past.
</P>
<P>
   The mayor and his aides argued that politics obviously motivated
Vallone; they also demonstrated that they were up to the
double-dare challenge. After some thrusts and parries over revenue
estimates and property tax rates, the mayor issued a line-item veto
Monday that would cut $4.6 million from the Council's allocation
for itself _ a warning of things to come.
</P>
<P>
   Now for the rest of the movie, one not written to have a happy
ending.
</P>
<P>
   Wednesday, Vallone will push his knife just a tad deeper by
introducing a bill to hold the stadium referendum.
</P>
<P>
   Coincidentally, Giuliani will use his own knife, in the form of
his veto power, to cut tens of millions of dollars from the
Council's budget.
</P>
<P>
   The mayor declined Tuesday to say where he would cut, although
some possible places are libraries and cultural institutions, the
recycling program and parks. Tuesday night the Council issued a
helpful pre-emptive response to what the mayor might cut, warning
that they could be programs ``helping working families'' or
``helping vulnerable children.''
</P>
<P>
   Once the mayor vetoes those spending items that offend him, the
Council has 10 days to summon a two-thirds' majority from its 51
members to override the veto. Vallone should have no trouble
achieving that in the overwhelmingly Democratic Council. And his
aides said that they planned to put the vetoes to a vote as soon as
possible, to contain the mayor's opportunity to gloat.
</P>
<P>
   Giuliani said he was aware of the probable outcome. ``I'm
realistic enough to understand that whatever I do with the vetoes,
they're going to override,'' he said. ``It's largely symbolic.''
</P>
<P>
   Although most people follow the Gregorian calendar, those in
City Hall follow the fiscal calendar, and fiscal year 1998 _ the
Year of the Surplus _ will end on June 30. Like partners in a
marriage of necessity, both the Council and the mayor's offices are
required by city law to come together one more time for ``the
Close.''
</P>
<P>
   This means that the two sides must agree to budget modifications
that will balance the books for the fiscal year that has just
ended.
</P>
<P>
   But that brief moment of consensus does not mean that fiscal
year 1999 will bring peace to City Hall. Once his vetoes are
rejected, the mayor is required by the City Charter to begin the
new fiscal year by executing the budget given to him by the
Council. But the charter also requires him to be fiscally prudent,
and to keep the city's books balanced. And these are the
responsibilities he is likely to use to keep the Council's bravado
in check.
</P>
<P>
   The charter ``gives the mayor the power of impoundment,'' he
said. ``And it gives the mayor the power to set up accounts in each
one of the agencies and to hold back the spending of money until
we're sure that we're not going to have a shortfall in some part of
the budget, or the entire budget.
</P>
<P>
   ``And you know I'll use those powers aggressively.''
</P>
<P>
   How the mayor uses his powers to impound _ to freeze funds
selectively _ will be closely watched by the Council's leaders.
They say those drastic powers were meant for times of fiscal
crisis, and not for the mayor's political whims; the mayor's
advisers say that the charter language makes no specific
constraints.
</P>
<P>
   ``The Council could say it's a misuse of the power, and even
though that may have been the intention, the charter doesn't spell
that out,'' said Frank Mauro, who was the director of research for
the commission that amended the Charter in 1989. ``Whether or not a
court would say that's a proper exercise of his power remains to be
seen.''
</P>
<P>
   It appears that Mauro identified the only language on which both
the Council and the mayor agree: See you in court. &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
