<SLUG> BC-JENNIFER-RESTITUTION-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
JENNIFER CONVERTIBLES ORDERED TO COMPENSATE 780 PATRONS 
</HEADLINE>
  (mk) 
 By THOMAS J. LUECK   
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   Jennifer Convertibles Inc., one of the largest chains of
furniture stores in the New York region, has been ordered to
compensate more than 700 customers following what Attorney General
Dennis Vacco said was a flood of customer complaints since 1995.
</P>
<P>
   The chain, which operates 200 stores across the nation _ 50 of
them are in New York City and on Long Island _ ``took money from
consumers but failed to deliver the furniture they ordered as
promised,'' Vacco said Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
   He said Jennifer had signed a consent order in which it agreed
to make full restitution to 780 customers who had complained of a
variety of improper business practices, including delivering
damaged furniture and refusing to honor warranties on its products.
</P>
<P>
   Vacco said the company agreed to provide refunds to other
customers who make complaints to his office and to have those
complaints substantiated by his staff, within 180 days. Under the
consent order, handed down last week by the New York state Supreme
Court in Albany, Jennifer was also assessed a $70,000 fine and
ordered to pay $2,000 to defray part of the state's costs for its
investigation, he said.
</P>
<P>
   ``My office was flooded with horror stories from consumers who
said that their pleas to Jennifer about damaged couches, and
defective chairs _ even the delivery of sofas that did not conform
to the model they selected _ were met with deafening silence,'' he
said.
</P>
<P>
   Executives of Jennifer, based in Woodbury, N.Y., did not return
phone calls Tuesday. Bernard Wincig, a Manhattan lawyer who is a
director of Jennifer and who represented the company in
negotiations with Vacco's staff, and before the state Surpreme
Court in Albany, declined to comment.
</P>
<P>
   According to Vacco's staff, the complaints against Jennifer and
the order for compensation involve customers of its stores across
the nation. Because the company is based in New York, Vacco has
jurisdiction over its business practices in all states, they said.
</P>
<P>
   But while only 25 percent of Jennifer's stores are in New York
City and on Long Island, lawyers involved in the investigation said
700 of the 780 complaints that had been received were from
customers in those areas.
</P>
<P>
   ``It was an incredible amount of complaints to be coming from a
quarter of the company's stores, and it signaled to us that
something was very much awry,'' said Mollie Conkey, a spokeswoman
for Vacco.
</P>
<P>
   Among the customers' complaints were that Jennifer had failed to
give timely refunds on defective or damaged furniture, failed to
make repairs, refused to let customers inspect furniture when it
was being delivered and failed to disclose estimated delivery dates
in its customer contracts.
</P>
<P>
   Ms. Conkey said the investigation of Jennifer began in September
1995 when the attorney general's Consumer Protection Bureau noticed
an unusually high number of complaints coming in from New York City
and Long Island customers.
</P>
<P>
   Then, working with the state's Better Business Bureau, which
sent inquiries to its counterparts across the nation, she said
lawyers for the state documented the high number of complaints
across the nation and their concentration in the New York City
metropolitan area.
</P>
<P>
   She said a smaller number of complaints had been received from
customers in New Jersey, Connecticut and other cities in New York,
including Scarsdale and Albany.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
