A1960 &Cx1f; taf-z
u k &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-EDIT-NIGERIA-NYT &LR;      06-09 0378
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-EDIT-NIGERIA-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
EDITORIAL: NIGERIA'S OPPORTUNITY 
</HEADLINE>
  (sw) 
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   The New York Times said in an editorial on Wednesday, June 10:
</P>
<P>
   The death this week of Sani Abacha, the corrupt and abusive
Nigerian military dictator, is an opportunity for an African giant
to begin to lift itself from poverty, fear and decay. Abacha so
discredited military rule that in recent months even many officers
began to join ordinary Nigerians in clamoring for a civilian
government. Gen. Abdulsalam Abubakar, who has taken over the
government, was one of those officers. He should put those ideas
into practice.
</P>
<P>
   Nigeria, the most populous nation in Africa, should also be the
most prosperous. Oil revenues alone, if not depleted by corruption
and mismanagement, should provide the basis for sustainable
economic growth. It is also a diverse, culturally rich land stunted
by years of tyranny.
</P>
<P>
   Ideally, Abubakar should turn the government over to Moshood
Abiola, a civilian who apparently won Nigeria's last democratic
elections, five years ago this week. The military annulled the
election, and Abiola was imprisoned in 1994 and has suffered there
since.
</P>
<P>
   The military seems to have another plan in mind. A spokesman for
the government said on Tuesday that it would turn power over to
elected civilians by October. If the military holds free and open
elections, this would be acceptable as well. But military leaders
have repeatedly failed to deliver promised transitions to civilian
rule. Even though people who know Abubakar call him the least
corrupt and power-hungry of Nigeria's top generals, Nigerians are
right to be skeptical. His first task should be to release all
political prisoners and end the persecution of critics.
</P>
<P>
   Outsiders can help with a clear call for democratic, civilian
rule. A high-level American delegation bearing such an unambiguous
message would be useful. Companies like Mobil, Chevron and Shell,
which profit from Nigerian oil, have done little in the past to
promote democratic rule. Abacha's death offers them a chance to use
their considerable influence to discourage continued dictatorship.
The one favor that Abacha may have done his country is to clarify
that military rule is misrule.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
