</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-NY-KILLINGS-APOLOGY-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
FATHER IS CONFUSED OVER APOLOGY IN RACIAL KILLING OF SON 
</HEADLINE>
  (mk) 
 By BARBARA STEWART   
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ The father of Yusuf Hawkins, the 16-year-old killed
in Brooklyn nine years ago because he was black, said Tuesday that
he felt conflicting emotions over a letter of apology he had
received from a man convicted in the attack.
</P>
<P>
   ``This letter has really not quite sunken in,'' said Moses
Stewart, speaking at a news conference in Harlem.
</P>
<P>
   The letter _ three pages, penned by hand on notebook paper,
expressing ``deepest sorrow and regret for the tragic death of your
son'' _ was signed by Keith Mondello, who was released from Attica
state prison last week after serving 8 years of his 12-year
sentence for his part in the attack.
</P>
<P>
   Stewart expressed confusion over the apology: ``My feelings are
crazy _ one minute I'm feeling this way, another minute, I'm
feeling that way.''
</P>
<P>
   Beside him at the news conference was Al Sharpton, who said of
the apology: ``It raises real questions. But clearly, it took him
nine years to write the letter.''
</P>
<P>
   The letter, Mondello's first apology to Hawkins' family, was
reported Tuesday in The Daily News.
</P>
<P>
   A reply to it _ the reactions of Stewart and Diane Hawkins, the
mother of Yusuf, and Sharpton, the family's adviser _ are to appear
in The Amsterdam News, Sharpton said.
</P>
<P>
   The letter of apology was dated June 6, the day that Sharpton,
Stewart and about 100 supporters marched through Bensonhurst, in an
echo of the many impassioned marches there following the murder.
</P>
<P>
   The authorities said Mondello, who was convicted of rioting,
unlawful imprisonment, menacing and possession of a weapon, had
organized and led a crowd of white teen-agers who attacked and
killed Hawkins on Aug. 23, 1989. Hawkins was in the Bensonhurst
neighborhood with some friends to answer an ad for a used car.
</P>
<P>
   In the months afterward, eight of the 30 to 40 teen-agers who
had threatened Hawkins, who was shot twice in the chest, were
arrested. One, Joseph Fama, was convicted of the murder.
</P>
<P>
   Mondello's three requests for parole were rejected because he
was judged to be unrepentant and likely to commit more crimes, said
Tom Grant, a spokesman for the New York State Division of Parole.
</P>
<P>
   The apology letter was passed, unsealed and unaddressed, from
the writer to Frank Macchiarola, the former schools chancellor who
is Mondello's mentor, Sharpton said.
</P>
<P>
   Sal Albanese, a former City Council member, said he took it from
Macchiarola and delivered it to Sharpton.
</P>
<P>
   The only public purpose to the apology letter, Sharpton said,
was that it ``removes all doubt'' that Mondello was the ringleader
of the attackers.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
