<DOCNO> NYT19980609.0472 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-06-09 23:52 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A1967 &Cx1f; ttj-z
u s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-rockets-HNS &LR;      06-09 1154
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-rockets-HNS </SLUG>
  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
Rockets deal Willis for Rogers, picks
<TEXT>
<P>
   &UR; By EDDIE SEFKO &LR;  &QL; 
 &UR; c. 1998, Houston Chronicle &LR;  &QL; 
The Rockets' makeover has begun.
</P>
<P>
   In a deal designed to reverse the aging process that had turned
them into one of the NBA's oldest teams, the Rockets on Tuesday
traded Kevin Willis to the Toronto Raptors for two 1998 first-round
draft choices and forward Roy Rogers, who missed virtually the
entire season with knee problems but was the 22nd pick of the '96
draft.
</P>
<P>
   The move means the Rockets have three selections in the middle
of the first round of the June 24 draft. Toronto conveyed the 16th
and 18th picks to the Rockets, whose own pick is No. 14.
</P>
<P>
   One Rockets insider said the possibility exists of more movement
before the draft.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're still working,'' the source said. ``You can't rule out
the possibility of packaging some of the picks and moving up in the
draft.''
</P>
<P>
   Willis' departure is not particularly surprising. On the day
after the Rockets' season ended, coach Rudy Tomjanovich promised
changes. Willis improved his stock around the NBA with his play
this season, when he averaged 16.1 points and 8.4 rebounds. The
7-footer did a solid job as a starter at center and power forward
when Hakeem Olajuwon and Charles Barkley were injured.
</P>
<P>
   Willis, 35, joined the Rockets as a free agent before the
1996-97 season and is scheduled to earn $2.1 million next season.
</P>
<P>
   Speculation grew Monday that the Rockets were working on a deal
to garner draft picks. One source in Chicago at the NBA Finals said
some sort of trade was imminent. Tuesday, Willis was dealt.
</P>
<P>
   ``It was a situation that was presented to us that we couldn't
pass up,'' Tomjanovich said. ``It was a tough decision, as these
things always are. But Kevin played so well this season that there
was a lot of interest.''
</P>
<P>
   Tomjanovich said he could envision the Rockets doing something
with the three picks they possess in this year's draft.
</P>
<P>
   ``That's something we're looking at,'' he said. ``Obviously,
this is the first move (of revamping the roster). We don't know
what else might be coming.''
</P>
<P>
   But the Rockets have started the process of transforming from an
elderly team by NBA standards to a younger, athletic team. Whether
Rogers will be part of that metamorphosis remains to be seen.
</P>
<P>
   Rogers, 24, attended Alabama, the same school that produced
former Rocket Robert Horry. Like Horry, Rogers is 6-10, although he
is slightly bigger at 235 pounds. Rogers was drafted by Vancouver
in '96.
</P>
<P>
   Rogers also comes off a serious injury to his right knee that
kept him out of all but 15 games this season. As a rookie with the
Grizzlies, he averaged 6.6 points and 4.7 rebounds in 82 games.
</P>
<P>
   ``We think he could have a big future,'' Tomjanovich said. ``He
has a knee problem, but we liked him before when he was with
Vancouver. He could be a big, big plus, if he gets healthy.''
</P>
<P>
   Rogers recently had surgery on his knee, and sources in Toronto
believe that procedure could allow him to resume his NBA career
next season, although it's unknown for how long.
</P>
<P>
   ``We've looked at him,'' Rockets executive vice president of
basketball Carroll Dawson said of Rogers. ``He used to come in when
we had Robert Horry here. He's always been around; we've known him
for a long time.''
</P>
<P>
   The Rockets and Raptors came together on the trade quickly.
Willis' agent, Steve Woods, said the subject was brought up by
Toronto general manager Glen Grunwald, who also toyed with the idea
of trading for Willis in January.
</P>
<P>
   A proposed deal that would have brought Damon Stoudamire to the
Rockets for Willis, Mario Elie and others fell through after weeks
of talks.
</P>
<P>
   But the Raptors liked Willis enough to rekindle the talks in the
past week.
</P>
<P>
   Tomjanovich spoke to Willis shortly after the trade was
completed.
</P>
<P>
   ``I did most of the talking,'' Tomjanovich said. ``There wasn't
much to say, except to tell him how difficult it was. I appreciate
all the things he's done for our organization and the city of
Houston.
</P>
<P>
   ``Kevin came in here with a very solid attitude and work ethic.
He had to make adjustments, and he handled them well in going from
one role to the next. And you don't find a lot of people who can do
that. What made this difficult is that I like him as a person and a
player. But the bottom line is to look at where we're at.''
</P>
<P>
   And the Rockets' situation is at the other end of the spectrum
from the Raptors' plight.
</P>
<P>
   ``We've been interested in Kevin for some time,'' said Grunwald.
``Even though he's 35, we feel he has at least a couple of years of
good basketball left in him because he is such a fitness nut. We're
very happy we got this done.
</P>
<P>
   ``He's a leader who I think will help us. I think Kevin sees
this as an opportunity where he can finish his career on a positive
note.''
</P>
<P>
   Grunwald added the trade makes sense from Toronto's side because
the Raptors have a young team, need a veteran leader and don't
believe they could get better players at the 16th and 18th picks.
</P>
<P>
   ``With the other players that might be available as free agents
or through trades, we felt for the next two years they were no
better than Kevin,'' Grunwald said. ``I think there are some good
players in the draft. But that's the one thing we couldn't predict.
</P>
<P>
   ``There were some players we liked in this draft, some players
that might be there at 16 and 18. But that was beyond our control
as to who actually fell to those spots. And we weren't prepared to
face that uncertainty. To us, Kevin is more valuable.
</P>
<P>
   ``The Rockets have been very good (in the draft). It reflects
more where the teams are. They're getting older and looking at
replenishing their roster.''
</P>
<P>
   For Willis, Toronto will be his fifth team since the start of
the 1994-95 season, having been traded from Atlanta to Miami to
Golden State and then signed as a free agent by the Rockets before
the 1996-97 season.
</P>
<P>
   Willis could not be reached for comment Tuesday. But Woods said
his client would have no aversion to reporting to Toronto for camp
next season. Numerous players have said they would not play for the
Raptors or the Vancouver Grizzlies because of Canada's higher taxes
and lower temperatures, as well as the other inconveniences of
living in a foreign country.
</P>
<P>
   ``Kevin's really disappointed,'' Woods said. ``But he's handling
it professionally. I think too many athletes react with righteous
indignation when they get traded. And that's flawed. Players
receive exorbitant compensation, and it's merely a component of
that compensation that they may be inconvenienced to fulfill their
contracts. If that means relocating, that's part of it.''
</P>
<P>
   On the other hand, Woods said he knows the Raptors ``really,
really want Kevin. And they're eager to get Kevin up to Toronto.''
</P>
<P>
   Staff writer W.H. Stickney Jr. contributed to this report.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
