<HEADER>
A1968 &Cx1f; taf-z
u k &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-EDIT-BANK-MERGER-NYT &LR;      06-09 0452
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-EDIT-BANK-MERGER-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
EDITORIAL: A BIG BANK MERGER, AGAIN 
</HEADLINE>
  (sw) 
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   The New York Times said in an editorial on Wednesday, June 10:
</P>
<P>
   The wave of giant bank mergers, which continued this week with
the Norwest Corp.'s planned $34 billion takeover of Wells Fargo,
has mixed implications for the nation's financial system and the
civic well-being of many communities.
</P>
<P>
   The mergers reflect pressures on banks to gain competitive
strength in an era when they have been losing market share to
investment banks in corporate lending and to mutual funds in the
attraction of consumer savings. Mergers have also become more
feasible because a presence on the local corner is less and less
necessary as transactions by computer and ATM become easier and
less costly.
</P>
<P>
   It is argued that larger banks are safer because they are more
diversified. Wells Fargo was once tied closely to the California
economy, and thus vulnerable to that state's downturn earlier in
this decade. Now, as part of a banking operation stretching across
most of the West and Midwest, it will be less dependent on the
fortunes of any one region.
</P>
<P>
   But it is also true that as big banks get bigger and merge with
each other, there are fewer players. That makes it more likely that
a large financial blunder that affects most big banks _ such as the
widespread lending in the 1970s to less-developed countries that
ended up unable to pay their bills _ may affect a much larger
proportion of the financial system than would have been true in the
past.
</P>
<P>
   The effectiveness of banking regulation thus becomes more
important than ever. Financial engineers have made it possible,
through a wide variety of derivative securities, for banks to take
on widely varying levels of risks. It is difficult for bank
managers to monitor the risks and even harder for bank regulators
to do so.
</P>
<P>
   The newly merged bank will take the Wells Fargo name, and be
based in San Francisco. That spares California the indignity of no
longer having any major banks based in the state. That can be
important because a bank's bosses are more likely to be sensitive
to the needs of the regions where they live, and they are more
likely to have their banks support such local institutions as
symphonies, museums and boys' clubs.
</P>
<P>
   If mergers are well executed, they hold little threat to banking
customers, who might even benefit from the combined institution
being able to offer more services. But the threat _ amply
illustrated by some previous mergers _ is that efforts to save
money by making the combined company more efficient can backfire,
causing service to suffer and customers to flee to competitors.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-06-09-98 2352EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19980609.0474 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-06-09 23:52 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A1970 &Cx1f; ttj-z
u s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-NHL0610NHL-HNS &LR;      06-09 0882
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-NHL0610 </SLUG>
 NHL -HNS  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
<TEXT>
<P>
   Wings skate away with opener 2-1
</P>
<P>
   Caps give defending Stanley Cup champs something to think about
</P>
<P>
   &UR; By NEIL HOHLFELD &LR;
</P>
<P>
   &UR; c. 1998, Houston Chronicle &LR;  &QL; 
DETROIT _ For 35 minutes in Game 1 of the Stanley Cup finals
Tuesday night, the Washington Capitals skated as if they were
wearing ankle weights. Slow. Uninspired. Laboring.
</P>
<P>
   Maybe they were merely lulling the Detroit Red Wings to sleep.
They had just about everyone else at Joe Louis Arena feeling
drowsy. Even Ron Wilson, their coach, wondered where the spark was
early in the second period.
</P>
<P>
   Wilson, who was wired for sound by Fox Sports, barked: ``Let's
have a little more enthusiasm, boys. This is the final.''
</P>
<P>
   After falling behind 2-0 in the opening period, the Capitals
came to life with a goal late in the second period. They dominated
play in the third period, so much so Wilson had changed his patter
midway through that period.
</P>
<P>
   ``If we dig in, this is a game we can win,'' Wilson shouted to
his team.
</P>
<P>
   The Caps did not win, falling short 2-1. But as Wilson predicted
before the game, a lot of people who were predicting an easy road
for Detroit to its second straight Stanley Cup were going to be
surprised. Indeed, the Caps put a scare into the Red Wings.
</P>
<P>
   After goaltender Olaf Kolzig allowed two goals in just more than
two minutes in the first period, he regrouped and showed why he has
been the best goalie throughout the playoff run. The Caps were
outshot 31-17, but they swarmed the Detroit net in the final
minutes and only excellent goaltending by Chris Osgood allowed the
Red Wings to avoid the upset in the first game of the best-of-seven
series.
</P>
<P>
   ``You can talk all you want, now we see what it's all about,''
said Red Wings coach Scotty Bowman. ``I thought Washington played a
really good game. We started out pretty good, played OK in the
third, but we can play a lot better than we did in the second. We
seemed to be a little mixed up.''
</P>
<P>
   Usually, when the Red Wings get a two-goal lead, you might as
well warm up the bus. They normally are the masters of protecting a
lead, especially against a young team like the Capitals that, for
the most part, has players getting their first taste of the finals.
</P>
<P>
   But the Capitals got a goal from rookie Richard Zednik at 15:57
of the second period to make it 2-1, changing the complexion of the
game. Zednik took a pass from Andrei Nikolishin and blasted a shot
that bounced off Osgood's pad, hit the post and went into the net.
</P>
<P>
   That was all the Caps could get behind Osgood, but their play in
the final period will give the hockey world plenty to chew on
before Game 2 on Thursday night.
</P>
<P>
   ``We lost 2-1 and they outshot us by a large margin, but I don't
think our players feel they were dominated by any stretch of the
imagination,'' Wilson said. ``We read the papers and see where we
are supposed to get blasted out of here 5-0 or 6-0. Now we know we
can play. I know we can play better. We'll take a lot out of this
game.''
</P>
<P>
   Though the Caps came close, the Red Wings hung on to get a win
in a game that didn't figure to be this difficult after they went
ahead 2-0 in the first period.
</P>
<P>
   Before the game, the Caps convinced themselves they were not
going to be intimidated by the Wings or their raucous, chanting
crowd at Joe Louis Arena. But after a brief spurt at the start of
in the first period, everything the Caps didn't want to happen did
happen.
</P>
<P>
   One key to Detroit's game plan, according to associate coach
Dave Lewis, was to control play for the first 10 minutes of the
game and put the Capitals on their heels. Instead, Washington
carried play in the early going and had the first good scoring
chance three minutes into the game but the puck bounced off
Zednik's stick as he attempted a backhand shot.
</P>
<P>
   The Caps took the first three shots of the game and had Detroit
on the run for the first five minutes. But that changed quickly.
The Red Wings picked up their pace and, almost at the same time,
the Capitals lost their spark. By period's end, Detroit had a 2-0
lead and indeed had Washington on the run.
</P>
<P>
   For the Red Wings, the last was indeed first. Detroit's fourth
line of Tomas Holmstrom, Doug Brown and Joey Kocur connected for
the first goal of the series, surprising Kolzig at 14:04.
</P>
<P>
   Holmstrom did the bulk of the work, pushing the puck into the
Caps' zone just as he was checked at the blue line. Brown caught
sight of Kocur streaking to the net and hit him with a backhand
pass. Kocur, who did not dress for four of the six games in the
Dallas series, tipped the puck behind Kolzig to make it 1-0.
</P>
<P>
   The Red Wings continued to pressure Washington, winning nearly
every battle along the boards and delivering the majority of hard
checks. Their second goal in a 2-minute, 14-second span was the
result of hard work by Darren McCarty and Holmstrom.
</P>
<P>
   McCarty stayed with the puck on the boards behind the net and
survived a hit from Washington defenseman Mark Tinordi. McCarty
pushed the puck to Holmstrom, who passed to Steve Yzerman and
headed to the front of the net.
</P>
<P>
   With Holmstrom screening Kolzig, Nicklas Lidstrom's slap shot
zipped past Kolzig, putting Detroit ahead 2-0 at 16:18.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
