u a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-NJ-POLICE-SUSPENDED-N     06-09 0628
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-NJ-POLICE-SUSPENDED-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
5 OFFICERS ACCUSED IN GUN BUY-BACK PROGRAM 
</HEADLINE>
  (mk) 
 By DAVID M. HERSZENHORN   
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEWARK, N.J. _ In seeking safer streets, police departments
across the country have increasingly asked citizens to turn in guns
in exchange for cash or gift certificates, no questions asked. But
in Newark, officials said Tuesday, the city's gun buy-back program
earlier this year took an unfortunate twist: Fancy weapons were
pocketed by some officers in the Police Department's East District.
</P>
<P>
   Four veteran police supervisors and an officer have been
suspended without pay amid allegations that they mishandled money
and stole two guns, the Newark police director, Joseph Santiago,
announced Tuesday. His face flushed with anger, Santiago clutched
the gold and silver badges that had belonged to the officer, three
lieutenants and a sergeant, and vowed to have them smelted _ just
like the 636 guns turned in to the program. ``These will never be
used again,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   At a news conference at police headquarters, Santiago described
a sting in which undercover investigators turned in a German
9-millimeter Luger pistol as part of the buy-back program, which
ran from Feb. 9 to March 9. The Luger was never logged into
inventory, and an ordinary .32-caliber handgun was recorded in its
place, he said. In another instance, internal affairs investigators
determined that a Marlin shotgun surrendered by an unidentified
citizen had also been replaced with an ordinary .32-caliber
handgun, he said. Both the Luger and the shotgun are still missing.
</P>
<P>
   Santiago identified the suspended officers as Lt. Robert Russo,
40, a 17-year veteran; Sgt. John Zajkowski, 43, a 24-year veteran;
Lt. John Lavook, 55, a 33-year veteran; Lt. Milton Medina, 46, a
21-year veteran, and Police Officer Jose DaSilva, 33, who has been
on the force for three years. The officers have not been arrested,
but police said they had each committed several crimes, including
theft, official misconduct and conspiracy.
</P>
<P>
   The case has been turned over to the Essex County prosecutor,
Patricia Hurt, who will determine whether to ask a grand jury for a
criminal indictment.
</P>
<P>
   Paul Bergrin, a lawyer representing Russo and DaSilva, said each
of his clients ``unequivocally and categorically denies any guilt
whatsoever in this case.'' Bergrin added: ``The Police Director and
the mayor drew conclusions without knowing all the facts and having
the benefit of a complete and impartial investigation.''
</P>
<P>
   Lawyers for the other suspended officers either declined to
comment or could not be reached by telephone.
</P>
<P>
   Mayor Sharpe James, who stood next to Santiago throughout the
news conference, said the suspensions ``send a message to the city
of Newark that no one is above the law.'' James reiterated his
support of the gun buy-back program and said it would be offered
again, adding, ``We can't legislate morality but whenever we find
wrongdoing we try to eliminate it from government.''
</P>
<P>
   Officials said the sting operation was part of a new effort by
the Newark Police Department to conduct periodic ``integrity and
compliance'' tests. The undercover officers surrendered guns in all
four of the department's districts but only found misconduct in the
East District, Santiago said. The Luger was used twice in the sting
operation and stolen the second time that it was surrendered, he
said. The Newark buy-back program paid citizens $75 for each
handgun, $100 for each automatic weapon and $150 for each assault
weapon.
</P>
<P>
   Santiago also said money was mishandled, but would not give
details, saying only that there were financial ``improprieties''
surrounding the surrender of four different weapons in the East
District.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
