<DATE_TIME> 1998-06-09 23:55 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A1974 &Cx1f; ttj-z
u s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-astroslede-HNS &LR;      06-09 0805
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-astros </SLUG>
 lede-HNS  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
Astros 
win with 
nifty 9th
<TEXT>
<P>
   Biggio homer caps &QL; 
taming of Tigers
</P>
<P>
   Twins solve Wood, end Cubs' winning streak at 10: Page 3B.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; By JOSEPH DUARTE &LR;  &QL; 
 &UR; c. 1998, Houston Chronicle &LR;  &QL; 
DETROIT _ Now playing at Tiger Stadium: Nightmare on Jones Street.
</P>
<P>
   Part II.
</P>
<P>
   ``I can't believe we're having this same conversation again,''
said Detroit closer Todd Jones, who blew a ninth-inning lead for
the second consecutive night as the Astros pulled off a 5-3 victory
over the Tigers on Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
   The script could hardly have been more identical for the Astros,
who on Monday had rallied from a one-run deficit to a 9-5 win with
five ninth-inning runs off Jones.
</P>
<P>
   This time, a little patience, a ball in the dirt, a clutch hit
from a catcher batting .212, and two home runs paved the way for
the Astros' fourth consecutive victory and sixth in their last
eight games.
</P>
<P>
   Moises Alou's club-leading 13th home run of the season to lead
off the ninth against Detroit's Brian Moehler sliced the Tigers'
lead to 3-2.
</P>
<P>
   Jones, an Astros reliever from 1993-96, then entered the game
and retired the first two batters he faced before walking pinch
hitter J.R. Phillips. Phillips advanced to second base on a wild
pitch, but Jones (0-3) was still one strike away from redemption
before Ausmus sent a 1-2 pitch into right field for a game-tying
single.
</P>
<P>
   Craig Biggio then sent a two-run homer into the upper deck in
right field to give the Astros their fourth ninth-inning comeback
of the year.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's just killing me right now,'' said Jones, who had
converted 32 of his last 35 save opportunities dating to last
season. ``I could puke.''
</P>
<P>
   Astros closer Billy Wagner made things interesting in the bottom
of the ninth by starting it with consecutive walks to Bill Ripken
and Deivi Cruz. But Wagner fanned the final three batters,
including former Astro Brian Hunter on a failed third-strike bunt,
to earn his 16th save.
</P>
<P>
   With their fourth win in five interleague games this season, the
Astros moved back into sole possession of first place in the
National League Central, one game ahead of the Chicago Cubs.
</P>
<P>
   ``It doesn't happen very often that you are going to get to a
closer two nights in a row,'' Ausmus said. ``That's why there are
27 outs.''
</P>
<P>
   The Astros needed every single one of them against Moehler. The
righthander, who entered with a 5-0 record and 1.87 earned run
average in his last six home starts, held the Astros to one run and
seven hits through eight innings and had seven strikeouts before
Alou's home run to lead off the ninth.
</P>
<P>
   Before that, seemingly everything the Astros hit landed in a
Tiger glove. Everything Detroit hit found a hole or bounce.
</P>
<P>
   ``Moehler pitched a great game. He completely neutralized our
right-handed hitters,'' manager Larry Dierker said. ``We did hit
some balls sharply that went to a lot of their infielders I was
noticing a lot of their balls went through and our went right
straight to the second baseman, short stop or third baseman. Until
Alou none of our righthanders were getting hits.''
</P>
<P>
   Mike Hampton (8-3) kept the Astros in the game just long enough
for his sixth road victory of the season. Hampton shook off a
three-run fifth inning by Detroit that saw the Tigers hit five
consecutive two-out singles to take a 3-1 lead. But Hampton showed
the mettle that has enabled him to compile a 20-6 record since last
July. He worked out of jams in the sixth and eighth inning that
left three Tigers stranded on base.
</P>
<P>
   ``A lot of times it's better to be lucky than good,'' Hampton
said. ``I was lucky to be in there and get the win.''
</P>
<P>
   With two outs in their final at-bat, Dierker said he inserted
Phillips to pinch hit for Ricky Gutierrez, ``hoping he hit a home
run.''
</P>
<P>
   Phillips, who had struck out 13 of his previous 28 at bats since
being recalled from Class AAA New Orleans, drew the walk off Jones
before advancing to second to put the tying run in scoring
position. He was replaced for pinch runner Tim Bogar.
</P>
<P>
   ``I was getting myself in a bad hitting position,'' Phillips
said of his recent inability to lay off pitches. ``I've been trying
to hit the ball too hard. That's why I'm striking out a lot.''
</P>
<P>
   Dierker thought about another gamble in the ninth when he almost
had backup catcher Tony Eusebio bat for Ausmus. With Eusebio having
sat out the entire game, Dierker went with the game-ready Ausmus,
who drove in Bogar for the tying run.
</P>
<P>
   ``I love to win, and it's exciting, but this could take a
toll,'' said Dierker, whose club is 4-18 when trailing after the
eighth inning this season. I had a feeling Brad would have a chance
and luckily it paid off. It gets to the point where you never feel
you are going to lose until the last out is made.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
